## Chapter 1: Oil on the Brain — The Beginning (p14-25, continued next batch)

### *The Missing $526.08*

The chapter opens with the story of Benjamin Silliman, Jr., son of a great American chemist and himself a distinguished professor of chemistry at Yale University. In the 1850s, a professor's salary was hardly generous, and Silliman had taken on an outside research project for a fee totaling $526.08. He had been retained in 1854 by a group of promoters and businessmen, but though he completed the project, the promised fee was not forthcoming. His anger was aimed at the leaders of the investor group — George Bissell, a New York lawyer, and James Townsend, president of a bank in New Haven. Townsend had sought to keep a low profile, fearing it would look inappropriate to his depositors if they learned he was involved in so speculative a venture.

What Bissell, Townsend, and the group had in mind was a grandiose vision for "rock oil" — so called to distinguish it from vegetable oils and animal fats. Rock oil bubbled up in springs or seeped into salt wells around Oil Creek, in the isolated wooded hills of northwestern Pennsylvania. A few barrels of this dark, smelly substance were gathered by primitive means — skimming off surfaces of springs and creeks, or wringing out rags or blankets soaked in oily waters. The bulk of this tiny supply was used to make medicine. The group believed rock oil could be exploited in far larger quantities and processed into a fluid burned as an illuminant in lamps — competitive with the "coal-oils" winning markets in the 1850s. They were convinced they could light up towns and farms of North America and Europe, use rock oil to lubricate the moving parts of the dawning mechanical age, and grow very rich. Many scoffed, but they would succeed in laying the basis for an entirely new era — the age of oil.

### *To "Assuage Our Woes"*

George Bissell, more than anybody else, was responsible for the creation of the oil industry. With his long, towering face and broad forehead, he conveyed intellectual force but was also shrewd and open to business opportunity. Self-supporting from age twelve, Bissell worked his way through Dartmouth College by teaching and writing articles. After graduation he was a professor of Latin and Greek, then a journalist in Washington, D.C., then ended up in New Orleans as principal of a high school and then superintendent of public schools. In his spare time he studied law and taught himself several more languages — altogether fluent in French, Irish, Portuguese and could read Hebrew, Sanskrit, ancient and modern Greek, Latin, and German.

Ill health forced Bissell north in 1853, and passing through western Pennsylvania, he saw the primitive oil-gathering industry with its skimmings and oil-soaked rags. Soon after, visiting his alma mater Dartmouth, he spied in a professor's office a bottle of Pennsylvania rock oil brought by another Dartmouth graduate, a physician practicing in western Pennsylvania. Bissell knew rock oil was being used as patent medicine — called "Seneca Oil" after the local Indians and their chief Red Jacket. One purveyor advertised its "wonderful curative powers" in a poem: "The Healthful balm, from Nature's secret spring, / The bloom of health, and life, to man will bring."

Seeing the sample at Dartmouth, Bissell conceived in a flash that rock oil could be used not as medicine but as an illuminant. That intuition became his guiding principle and faith, sorely tested during the next six years as "disappointment consistently overwhelmed hope."

### *The Disappearing Professor*

Bissell aroused investor interest, and in late 1854 the group engaged Yale's Professor Silliman to analyze the oil's properties as illuminant and lubricant. They also wanted his distinguished imprimatur to sell stock and raise capital. Heavyset and vigorous, with a "good, jolly face," Silliman was one of the greatest and most respected names in nineteenth-century science — son of the founder of American chemistry, author of the leading textbooks in physics and chemistry. Yale was the scientific capital of mid-nineteenth-century America.

Silliman was less interested in the abstract than in the practical world of business. Academic salaries were low and he had a growing family; he habitually took on outside consulting jobs. His taste for the practical drew him into speculative business ventures. A brother-in-law was skeptical: "Benjamin Silliman, Jr., he said, is on the constant go in behalf of one thing or another, and alas for Science."

Silliman's analysis promised the result would "meet your expectations." Three months later, nearing the end, he reported "unexpected success in the use of the distillate product of Rock Oil as an illuminator." But the investors owed him $526.08 (equivalent of about $5,000 today) and had insisted on a $100 deposit they never made. Silliman's bill was much higher than expected. The professor was upset and angry — he withheld the study, secretly handed the report to a friend for safekeeping, and took himself off on a tour of the South where he could not be easily reached.

The investors grew desperate. Finally, one of Bissell's partners put up the money "on his own security," complaining "these are the hardest times I ever heard of." The report, dated April 16, 1855, was released and hurried to the printers. Silliman's study was "a turning point in the establishment of the petroleum business." He banished doubts about potential new uses for rock oil — it could be distilled into several fractions, all composed of carbon and hydrogen, one of which was a very high-quality illuminating oil. "Gentlemen, it appears to me that there is much ground for encouragement," Silliman wrote.

Armed with Silliman's report, the group raised funds. Silliman himself took two hundred shares. The enterprise became the Pennsylvania Rock Oil Company. But it took another year and a half before they were ready for the next hazardous step.

### *Price and Innovation*

The hopes pinned on oil arose from pure necessity. Burgeoning populations and the spreading industrial revolution had increased demand for artificial illumination beyond the simple wick dipped into animal grease or vegetable fat. For those with money, sperm whale oil had set the standard for high-quality illumination for hundreds of years; but whale schools of the Atlantic had been decimated, whaling ships forced to sail farther and farther — around Cape Horn and into the distant Pacific. Prices were rising: $2.50 a gallon, a price that seemed sure to go even higher. Cheaper lighting fluids had been developed but were inferior. The most popular was camphene, a derivative of turpentine, which produced a good light but had the drawback of being highly flammable, "compounded by an even more unattractive tendency to explode in people's houses." There was also "town gas" distilled from coal, piped into street lamps and homes of middle-and upper-class families — but it was expensive. There was a sharply growing need for a reliable, relatively cheap illuminant. There was also a second need — lubrication for the advances in mechanical production (power looms, steam printing presses) that created too much friction for common lubricants like lard.

Entrepreneurial innovation had already begun responding in the late 1840s and early 1850s. A court-martialed British admiral, Thomas Cochrane — said to have provided the model for Lord Byron's *Don Juan* — became obsessed with asphalt potential and acquired a huge tar pit in Trinidad. Cochrane collaborated with a Canadian, Dr. Abraham Gesner, who had attempted to start a business exporting horses to the West Indies, was shipwrecked twice, went to Guy's Hospital in London to study medicine, returned to Canada to become provincial geologist of New Brunswick. Gesner developed a process for extracting illuminating oil from asphalt, which he called "kerosene" — from the Greek *Keros* (wax) and *elaion* (oil), altering *elaion* to *ene* to sound like the familiar camphene. In 1854 he applied for a US patent for "a new liquid hydrocarbon, which I denominate Kerosene." By 1859, Gesner's kerosene works in New York City was producing 5,000 gallons a day. The Scottish chemist James Young had pioneered a parallel refining industry in Britain based on cannel coal. By 1859, an estimated thirty-four companies in the US were producing $5 million a year worth of kerosene or "coal-oils."

Oil was hardly unfamiliar to mankind. In the Middle East, bitumen had seeped to the surface through cracks since antiquity — tapped in Mesopotamia back to 3000 B.C. The most famous source was at Hit, on the Euphrates, near Babylon. Bitumen was a traded commodity in the ancient Middle East — used as building mortar, binding walls of Jericho and Babylon, probably caulking Noah's ark and Moses' basket. It was used for road making and lighting. Bitumen served as medicine — Pliny described it checking bleeding, healing wounds, treating cataracts, curing gout, relieving shortness of breath, and being "useful for straightening out eyelashes which inconvenience the eyes."

Oil seepages set aflame also played a role in warfare. Homer recorded Trojans casting unwearied fire upon Greek ships. The Persian King Cyrus used pitch and tow to take Babylon. From the seventh century onward, the Byzantines used *oleum incendiarum* — Greek fire — a mixture of petroleum and lime that, touched with moisture, would catch fire. The recipe was a closely guarded state secret. For centuries it was considered more terrible than gunpowder.

Knowledge of petroleum was lost to the West for many centuries, perhaps because the known major sources lay beyond the Roman empire's boundaries. But oil seepages were observed across Europe — Bavaria, Sicily, the Po Valley, Alsace, Hannover, Galicia. Refining technology was transmitted via the Arabs. Petroleum was mostly used as an all-purpose medicinal remedy. A small oil industry had developed in Eastern Europe — first in Galicia (variously part of Poland, Austria, and Russia) and then in Rumania. Peasants dug shafts by hand. A pharmacist from Lvov, with help from a plumber, invented a cheap lamp suited to burning kerosene. By 1854 kerosene was a staple of commerce in Vienna; by 1859 Galicia had a thriving business with over 150 villages involved in mining for oil. European crude production in 1859 was estimated at thirty-six thousand barrels, primarily from Galicia and Rumania. What the Eastern European industry lacked was the technology for drilling.

In the 1850s, kerosene spread in the US faced two barriers: no substantial supply source, and no cheap lamp suited to burning it. Then a kerosene sales agent in New York learned of a lamp with a glass chimney being produced in Vienna to burn Galician kerosene — based on the pharmacist and plumber's design from Lvov. It overcame problems of smoke and smell. The New York salesman imported it, and though improved many times over, that Vienna lamp became the basis of the kerosene lamp trade in the United States and was later re-exported around the world.

By the time Bissell was launching his venture, cheaper, better-quality kerosene had already been introduced into some homes. The refining techniques required were already commercialized with coal-oils, and an inexpensive lamp had been developed. What Bissell and the Pennsylvania Rock Oil Company needed was to discover a new, cheaper source for the raw material. If they could find rock oil in sufficient abundance, it could be sold cheaply, capturing the illuminating oils market. But how to get it in quantity?

Salt "boring" or drilling had been developed more than 1,500 years earlier in China, with wells going down 3,000 feet. Around 1830 the Chinese method was imported into Europe and copied, stimulating salt well drilling in the United States. In 1856, on a hot day in New York, Bissell took refuge under a druggist's awning on Broadway and spotted an advertisement for a rock oil patent medicine showing several drilling derricks — the kind used to bore for salt. The rock oil for the patent medicine was obtained as a byproduct of salt drilling. With that coincidental glimpse — following his earlier ones in western Pennsylvania and at Dartmouth — the last piece fell into place. Could drilling be applied to the recovery of oil? If yes, here was the means for achieving his fortune.

The essential insight of Bissell and his fellow investors was to adapt the salt-boring technique directly to oil. They were not alone — others in the US and Ontario, Canada, were experimenting. But Bissell's group was ready to move: they had Silliman's report and the capital it attracted. Still, people thought them crazy. When Townsend discussed drilling for oil in New Haven, people derided it: "Oh Townsend, oil coming out of the ground, pumping oil out of the earth as you pump water? Nonsense! You're crazy."

### *The "Colonel"*

Their candidate to carry out the project was Edwin L. Drake, chosen mainly by coincidence. He brought no outstanding qualifications — a jack-of-all-trades and sometime railroad conductor, laid up by bad health, living with his daughter in the old Tontine Hotel in New Haven. James Townsend, the banker, happened to live in the same hotel — a place where men gathered to exchange news and shoot the breeze. The thirty-eight-year-old Drake was friendly, jovial, loquacious, and had nothing else to do. He passed evenings entertaining companions with dramatic, exaggerated tales in which he played the heroic role. Townsend talked frequently about the rock oil venture, persuaded Drake to buy stock, then recruited him to go to Pennsylvania — he was out of work, had a railroad pass and could travel free, and was very tenacious.

Dispatching Drake to Pennsylvania, Townsend gave him a valuable send-off: concerned about the need to impress the "backwoodsmen," the banker sent ahead letters addressed to "Colonel" E. L. Drake. Thus was "Colonel" Drake invented — though a colonel he certainly was not. The stratagem worked. Drake arrived in December 1857 in the tiny, impoverished village of Titusville, population 125, tucked into the hills of northwestern Pennsylvania — a lumber town deeply in debt to the local lumber company's store.

Drake's first job was to perfect the title to the prospective oil land. He returned to New Haven, intent on drilling. "I had made up my mind," he later said, "that oil could be obtained in large quantities by Boreing as for Salt Water. I also determined that I should be the one to do it. But I found that no one with whom I conversed upon the subject agreed with me, all maintaining that oil was the drippings of an extensive Coal field or bed."

Drake was back in Titusville in the spring of 1858. The investors had established the Seneca Oil Company with Drake as general agent. He set up operations about two miles down Oil Creek from Titusville, on a farm with an oil spring producing three to six gallons a day by traditional methods. After several months, he wrote Townsend: "I shall not try to dig by hand any more, as I am satisfied that boring is the cheapest." He begged for more funds: "Money we must have if we are to make anything ... Please let me know at once. Money is very scarce here." Townsend managed to send a thousand dollars, and Drake tried to hire "salt borers" — drillers — needed to proceed. But salt drillers had a reputation for "extreme partiality to whiskey and frequent drunkenness," and he wanted to be careful. He tied compensation to successful completion at one dollar per foot drilled. The first couple of drillers simply disappeared or begged off — they thought he was insane. Drake had nothing to show for his first year in Titusville.

So he devoted himself to erecting the steam engine that would power the drill bit, while the investors back in New Haven fretted and waited.

Finally, in the spring of 1859, Drake found his driller — a blacksmith named William A. Smith, "Uncle Billy" Smith, who came with his two sons. Smith knew something about what was needed, for he made the tools for the salt water drillers. The little team built the derrick and assembled equipment. They assumed they would have to go several hundred feet. The work was slow, and the New Haven investors were becoming more and more restive. Drake stuck to his plan. He would not give up. Eventually, Townsend was the only promoter who still believed in the project. When the venture ran out of money, Townsend began paying bills from his own pocket. In despair, he at last sent Drake a money order as a final remittance, instructing him to pay his bills, close up the operation, and return to New Haven. That was toward the end of August 1859.

Drake had not yet received the letter when, on Saturday afternoon, August 27, 1859, at sixty-nine feet, the drill dropped into a crevice and slid another six inches. Work was called off for the weekend. The next day, Sunday, Uncle Billy came out to see the well. He peered down into the pipe and saw a dark fluid floating on top of the water. He used a tin rain spout to draw up a sample. He was overcome by excitement. On Monday, when Drake arrived, he found Uncle Billy and his boys standing guard over tubs, washbasins, and barrels, all filled with oil. Drake attached a common hand pump and began to do exactly what the scoffers had ridiculed — pump up the liquid. That same day he received the money order from Townsend and the command to close up shop. A week earlier, with the last funds in hand, he would have done so. But not anymore. Drake's single-mindedness had paid off. Just in time.

Farmers along Oil Creek rushed into Titusville shouting, "The Yankee has struck oil." The news spread like wildfire and started a mad rush to acquire sites and drill for oil. The population of tiny Titusville multiplied overnight, and land prices shot up instantaneously.

Success with the drill did not guarantee financial success. What were Drake and Uncle Billy to do with the flow of oil? They got hold of every whiskey barrel they could scrounge in the area. Unfortunately, one night a lantern's flame ignited the petroleum gases, causing the entire storage area to explode and go up in fierce flames. Meanwhile, other wells were drilled, supply far outran demand, and the price plummeted. With the advent of drilling, there was no shortage of rock oil. The only shortage was of whiskey barrels, and they soon cost almost twice as much as the oil inside them.

### *"The Light of the Age"*

Pennsylvania rock oil quickly found its way to market refined as kerosene. Its virtues were immediately clear. "As an illuminator the oil is without a figure: It is the light of the age," wrote the author of America's very first handbook on oil, less than a year after Drake's discovery. "Those that have not seen it burn, may rest assured its light is no moonshine; but something nearer the clear, strong, brilliant light of day, to which darkness is no party ... rock oil emits a dainty light; the brightest and yet the cheapest in the world; a light fit for Kings and Royalists and not unsuitable for Republicans and Democrats."

George Bissell wasted no time getting to Titusville, spending hundreds of thousands of dollars leasing and buying farms around Oil Creek. "We find here an unparalleled excitement," he wrote his wife. "The whole population are crazy almost ... I never saw such excitement. The whole western country are thronging here and fabulous prices are offered for lands in the vicinity where there is a prospect of getting oil." After six years of struggle, he reflected: "I am quite well, but very much worn down. We have had a hard time of it, very. Our prospects are most brilliant that's certain. ... We ought to make an immense fortune."

Bissell did indeed become very wealthy. Among his philanthropies, he donated a gymnasium to Dartmouth with six bowling alleys "in remembrance of disciplinary troubles into which he had fallen as an undergraduate because of his indulgence in this sinful sport." It was said in his later years "that his name and fame is a 'household word' among oil men from end to end of the continent." James Townsend, who had taken the greatest financial risk, was denied the credit he thought he deserved. "The whole plan was suggested by me, and my suggestions were carried out," he later wrote bitterly.

As for Drake, things did not go well at all. He became an oil buyer, then a partner in a Wall Street firm specializing in oil shares. He was improvident, not a good businessman, indeed a gambler. By 1866 he had lost all his money, became a semi-invalid, racked with pain, living in poverty. "If you have any of the milk of human kindness left in your bosom for me or my family, send me some money," he wrote. Finally, in 1873, Pennsylvania granted him a small lifetime pension for his service. Toward the end of his life, Drake sought to stake out his place in history: "I claim that I did invent the driving Pipe and drive it and without that they could not bore on bottom lands when the earth is full of water. And I claim to have bored the first well that ever was bored for Petroleum in America and can show the well."

### *The First Boom*

Drake proved, through drilling, the final requirement for a new industry — the availability of supply. Man was suddenly given the ability to push back the night. But Drake's discovery would also bequeath mobility and power to the world's population, play a central role in the rise and fall of nations and empires, and become a major element in the transformation of human society.

What followed was like a gold rush. The flats in the narrow valley of Oil Creek were quickly leased, and by November 1860, fifteen months after Drake's discovery, about seventy-five wells were producing, with many more dry holes scarring the earth. Titusville became "the rendezvous of strangers eager for speculation." "They barter prices in claims and shares; buy and sell sites, and report the depth, show, or yield of wells, etc. etc. ... Never was a hive of bees in time of swarming more astir, or making a greater buzz."

Down at the bottom of Oil Creek, where it flowed into the Allegheny River, a small town called Cornplanter, named after a Seneca Indian chief, was renamed Oil City and became the major center for what was now known as the Oil Regions. Refineries to turn crude into kerosene were cheap to build — by 1860 at least fifteen were operating in the Oil Regions, with another five in Pittsburgh. A coal-oil refiner visited the fields in 1860 and said, "If this business succeeds, mine is ruined." He was right — by end of 1860, coal-oil refiners were either out of business or had converted to crude-oil refining.

Yet all wells thus far were modest producers and had to be pumped. That changed in April 1861, when drillers struck the first flowing well, which gushed at three thousand barrels per day. When the oil shot into the air, something ignited the escaping gases, setting off a great explosion and wall of fire that killed nineteen people and blazed for three days. Though temporarily lost in the news of Fort Sumter — the opening shots of the Civil War — the explosion announced that ample supplies for the new industry would be available.

Production rose rapidly — from about 450,000 barrels in 1860 to 3 million barrels in 1862. The market could not absorb the swelling volume. Prices, which had been $10 a barrel in January 1861, fell to 50 cents by June and were down to 10 cents by the end of 1861. Many producers were ruined. But cheap prices gave Pennsylvania oil a quick and decisive victory in the marketplace, driving out coal-oils and other illuminants. Demand caught up with supply, and by end of 1862 prices rose to $4 a barrel, then to $7.25 by September 1863. Despite wild price fluctuations, stories of instant wealth continued to draw throngs. One memorable well generated $15,000 of profit for every dollar invested in less than two years.

The Civil War hardly disrupted the boom — it actually gave a major stimulus. The war cut off the shipment of turpentine from the South, creating an acute shortage of camphene, the cheap illuminating oil derived from turpentine. Kerosene from Pennsylvania oil quickly filled the gap. The war had an even more significant impact: when the South seceded, the North lost foreign revenues from cotton, one of America's major exports. The rapid growth of oil exports to Europe compensated for that loss and provided a significant new source of foreign earnings.

After the war, thousands of veterans poured into the Oil Regions seeking their fortunes in a new speculative boom, fueled by prices as high as $13.75 a barrel. The effects of the frenzy were felt up and down the East Coast — hundreds of new oil companies were floated. Office space ran short in the financial district of New York. Shares were sold so rapidly that one new company disposed of its entire issue in just four hours. Washington, D.C., was no more immune — Congressman James Garfield became a substantial investor in oil lands.

Nothing revealed the feverish pitch of speculation better than the story of Pithole, fifteen miles from Titusville. A first well was struck in dense forest in January 1865; by June, four flowing wells were producing two thousand barrels per day — one third of the Oil Regions' total output. People fought their way in on roads already clogged with barrel-laden wagons. "The whole place smells like a corps of soldiers when they have the diarrhea." The land speculation knew no bounds — one farm virtually worthless a few months earlier was sold for $1.3 million in July 1868 and resold for two million dollars in September. By that September, what had once been an unidentifiable spot in the wilderness had become a town of fifteen thousand people, with two banks, two telegraph offices, a newspaper, a waterworks, more than fifty hotels — at least three up to elegant metropolitan standards — and a post office handling more than five thousand letters a day.

But then, a couple of months later, oil production abruptly gave out — just as quickly as it had begun. By January 1866, only a year from the first discovery, thousands had fled. The town was totally deserted. Fires ravaged the buildings. A parcel of land that sold for $2 million in 1868 was auctioned for $4.37 in 1878.

Even as Pithole died, the speculative boom was engulfing neighboring areas. Production in the Oil Regions jumped to 3.6 million barrels in 1866. Oil became part of popular culture — Americans danced to the "American Petroleum Polka" and the "Oil Fever Gallop," and sang songs like "Famous Oil Firms" and "Oil on the Brain."

### *Boom and Bust*

The race to find oil was swiftly followed by another race to produce it as quickly and in as much volume as possible. The drive for "flush production" often damaged the reservoirs, leading to premature exhaustion of gas pressure and less recovery than would otherwise have been the case. Several reasons drove this: lack of geological knowledge, the large and quick rewards to be attained, the nature of leasing terms which put a premium on producing quickly.

But most important in shaping the legal context was the **"rule of capture,"** a doctrine based on English common law. If a game animal or bird migrated from one estate to another, the owner of the latter estate could kill the game on his land. Similarly, owners of land had the right to draw out whatever wealth lay beneath. As applied to oil production, the rule meant that surface owners atop a common pool could take all the oil they could get, even if they disproportionately drained the pool or reduced output of neighboring wells. The owners of adjacent wells were in heated competition to produce as much as they could as swiftly as possible, to avoid having the pool drained by another. The rule of capture contributed to the instability of both production and prices, and led to considerable waste and damage. But it also created room for many more people to enter the industry and helped make possible a wider market.

Fueled by the rule of capture and the race for riches, the Oil Regions became a chaotic scene of shacks, derricks, storage tanks, everyone energized by hope and rumor and the acrid scent of oil. And everywhere — the perennial mud. "Mud, deep, and indescribably disgusting, covered all the main and by-roads in wet weather." A local editor in 1865 captured the scene: "The oil and land excitement in this section has already become a sort of epidemic. It embraces all classes and ages and conditions of men. They neither talk, nor look, nor act as they did six months ago. Land, leases, contracts, refusals, deeds, agreements, interests, and all that sort of talk is all they can comprehend. ... The court is at a standstill; the bar is demoralized; the social circle is broken; the sanctuary is forsaken; and all our habits, and notions, and associations for half a century are turned topsy-turvy in the headlong rush for riches." The editor had a final thought: "The big bubble will burst sooner or later."

The bubble did burst — depression engulfed the industry in 1866-67; the price of oil dropped as low as $2.40 a barrel. Yet while many stopped drilling, new fields were opened beyond Oil Creek. Innovation and organization were being imposed upon the industry.

From the first discoveries, teamsters had clogged the roads with their loads of barrels. They were more than a physical bottleneck — holding a monopoly position, they charged exorbitant rates; it cost more to move a barrel over a few miles of muddy road to a railway stop than to transport it by rail from western Pennsylvania to New York. The teamsters' stranglehold led to the development of pipelines. Between 1863 and 1865, despite much scoffing and ridicule, wooden pipelines proved they could carry oil much more efficiently and cheaply. The teamsters responded with threats, armed attacks, arson, and sabotage. But by 1866, pipelines were hooked up to most wells, feeding into a larger gathering system connected with the railroads.

The refiners needed to acquire oil, and that too was initially chaotic — buyers on horseback rode from well to well. As the industry grew, informal oil exchanges emerged where buyers and sellers could meet and agree on prices — in a hotel in Titusville and at a curbside exchange near the railway tracks in Oil City. Beginning in the early 1870s, more formal oil exchanges emerged. Oil was bought and sold on three bases: "Spot" sales for immediate delivery and payment; "regular" sales completed within ten days; and "futures" — a certain quantity sold at a certain price within a specified future time. Futures prices became the focus for speculation, and oil became "the favorite speculative commodity of the time." Buyers could make a handsome profit — or suffer a devastating loss — without ever taking possession of the oil.

By the time the Titusville Oil Exchange opened in 1871, oil was already on its way to becoming a very big business. The decade of the 1860s had been one of dizzy advance from Drake's lunatic experiment — "the impetuous energy with which the American mind takes up any branch of industry that promises to pay well." Bissell's intuition and Drake's perseverance had opened a turbulent era of ingenuity and innovation, of deals and frauds, of fortunes made, fortunes lost, fortunes never made, of grueling hard work and bitter disappointments, and of astonishing growth.

And what might be expected of oil's future? There were those who saw much greater opportunities ahead, who envisioned the industry on a scale few in the Oil Regions could begin to imagine. Yet at the same time they were repelled and disgusted by the chaos and disorder. They had their own very strong ideas about how the oil business ought to be organized and proceed. And they were already at work, according to their own plans.

---

## Chapter 2: "Our Plan" — John D. Rockefeller and the Combination of American Oil (p40-45, continued next batch)

A curious auction took place one February day in 1865 in Cleveland, Ohio — then a bustling city that had profited from both the Civil War and the oil boom and now stood to prosper from America's industrial expansion. The two senior partners in one of the city's most successful oil refineries had fallen into yet another of their chronic disputes over the speed of expansion. Maurice Clark, the more cautious partner, threatened dissolution. This time, John D. Rockefeller surprised him by accepting. They agreed on a private auction — the highest bidder would get the company, held right there in the office.

The bidding began at $500, climbed quickly. Maurice Clark was soon at $72,000. Rockefeller calmly went to $72,500. Clark threw up his hands: "I'll go no higher, John. The business is yours." On a handshake they parted.

"I ever point to that day," Rockefeller said a half century later, "as the beginning of the success I have made in my life." That handshake also signaled the beginning of the modern oil industry, which would bring order out of the chaos of the wild Pennsylvania boom. The order would take the form of Standard Oil, which, as it sought total dominance and mastery over the world oil trade, grew into a complex global enterprise carrying the "new light" to the farthest corners of the earth — operating according to the merciless methods and unbridled lust of late-nineteenth-century capitalism, yet opening a new era as one of the world's first and biggest multinational corporations.

### *"Methodical to an Extreme"*

The mastermind of Standard Oil was the young man who won that auction in Cleveland in 1865. Even then, at twenty-six, John D. Rockefeller already made a forbidding impression. Tall and thin, he struck others as solitary, taciturn, remote, and ascetic. His unbending quietness — combined with cold, piercing blue eyes set in an angular face with a sharp chin — made people uneasy and fearful. Somehow, they felt, he could look right through them.

Rockefeller was the single most important figure in shaping the oil industry. The same might arguably be said for his place in the history of America's industrial development and the rise of the modern corporation. Admired by some as a genius of management and organization, he also came to rank as the most hated and reviled American businessman — in part because he was so ruthless and in part because he was so successful.

Rockefeller was born in 1839 in rural New York State and lived almost a full century, until 1937. His father, William Rockefeller, traded in lumber and salt, then turned himself into "Dr. William Rockefeller" who sold herbal remedies and patent medicines. The father was often away on long absences; the reason, some suggested, was that he maintained another wife and family in Canada. "I trade with the boys," the father boasted, "and skin 'em and I just beat 'em every time I can. I want to make 'em sharp."

The son's character was already set at a young age — pious, single-minded, persistent, thorough, attentive to detail, with a gift and fascination for numbers, especially those involving money. At age seven he launched his first successful venture — selling turkeys. Mathematics was his best subject in high school, which stressed mental arithmetic — the ability to do calculations quickly in one's head.

Intent on achieving "something big," Rockefeller went to work at age sixteen in Cleveland for a produce-shipping firm. In 1859 he formed his own partnership with Maurice Clark to trade produce. The firm prospered from demand generated by the Civil War and the opening of the West. Clark would later testify that Rockefeller was "methodical to an extreme." As the firm grew, Rockefeller stuck to his habit of holding "intimate conversations" with himself, counseling himself, repeating homilies, warning himself to beware of pitfalls. The firm dealt in Ohio wheat, Michigan salt, and Illinois pork. Within a couple of years of Drake's discovery, Clark and Rockefeller were also dealing in Pennsylvania oil.

Oil had already captured the imagination of entrepreneurial men in Cleveland, when, in 1863, a new railroad link placed Cleveland in a position to compete. Refinery after refinery sprang into existence along the railway tracks. Many were desperately undercapitalized, but this was never true of the one owned by Rockefeller and Clark. Rockefeller initially thought refining would merely be a sideline to the produce business, but within a year, as the refinery became quite profitable, he became convinced otherwise. Now, in 1865, with the auction and Clark out of the way, Rockefeller was master of his own business — the largest of Cleveland's thirty refineries.

### *The Great Game*

Rockefeller won his first victory in refining at a perfect time. The end of the Civil War in 1865 inaugurated an era of massive economic expansion, fierce speculation and competition, and combination and monopoly. Large-scale enterprises rose with technological advances in steel, meat packing, and communication. Heavy immigration and the opening of the West made for rapidly growing markets. Indeed, in the last three and a half decades of the nineteenth century, the business of America was truly business. Young men were irresistibly drawn to what Rockefeller called "the Great Game" — the struggle to accomplish and build, and the drive to make money.

As the oil boom progressed, Rockefeller threw himself wholeheartedly into the Great Game, pouring both profits and borrowed money into his refinery. He built a second one. He needed new markets for his growing capacity, and in 1866 organized another firm in New York to manage both the Atlantic Coast trade and the export of kerosene, putting his brother William in charge. In that year, his sales exceeded two million dollars.

Yet markets for kerosene and lubricants were not growing fast enough to match refinery capacity growth. Too many companies were competing for the same customers. It didn't take much to set oneself up as a refiner. As Rockefeller recalled, "All sorts of people went into it: the butcher, the baker, and the candlestick-maker began to refine oil." Rockefeller and his associates became quite concerned when they learned that a German baker they liked had foolishly traded his bakery for a low-quality refinery. They bought him out in order to get him back to baking.

Rockefeller devoted himself to strengthening his business — expanding facilities, improving quality, and always controlling costs. He took the first steps toward **integration** — bringing supply and distribution inside the organization. His firm acquired its own tracts of land for white oak timber to make barrels; bought its own tank cars, warehouses in New York, and boats on the Hudson River. Rockefeller also established another principle he religiously stuck to — to build up and maintain a strong cash position. Already, before the end of the 1860s, he had built up sufficient financial resources so that his company would not have to depend upon bankers, financiers, and speculators. The cash not only insulated the company from violent busts and depressions, but enabled it to take advantage of such downturns.

One of Rockefeller's great talents was already discernible: he had a vision of where his company and the overall industry were going, and yet at the same time persisted in commanding the critical daily details. "As I began my business life as a bookkeeper, I learned to have great respect for figures and facts, no matter how small they were." He kept an old suit that he would wear to tramp around in the muddy Oil Regions fields, buying oil. By the latter part of the 1860s, Rockefeller owned what was probably the largest refinery in the world.

In 1867, Rockefeller was joined by Henry Flagler, whose influence in the creation of Standard Oil was almost as great as Rockefeller's. Going to work at age fourteen as a clerk in a general store, Flagler had succeeded, by his mid-twenties, in making a small fortune distilling whiskey in Ohio. He sold out in 1858 because of moral scruples about alcohol. He then threw himself into salt manufacturing in Michigan but in circumstances of chaotic competition and over-supply, he went broke — a sobering experience for a man to whom making money had initially come so easily.

Still, Flagler was an eternally buoyant man, determined to rebound, now matured by hard-won lessons. His bankruptcy left him with a deep-seated belief in the value of "cooperation" among producers and a no less deep-seated aversion to "unbridled competition." He had also learned another lesson: "Keep your head above water and bet on the growth of your country."

Flagler became the closest colleague Rockefeller ever had, and one of his closest friends. Their relationship led Flagler to another adage: "A friendship founded on business is better than a business founded on friendship." Energetic and striving, Flagler was well matched to the dour, careful Rockefeller, who was delighted to acquire a partner so "full of vim and push." To a critic, however, Flagler looked somewhat different — "a bold, unscrupulous self-seeker [who] made no bones about conscience. He did whatever was necessary to success." Many years later, after making one great fortune with Rockefeller, Flagler set off on a second conquest — the development of the state of Florida. He would build the railways down the east coast all the way to the Keys, opening up what he called the "American Riviera," and was to found both Miami and West Palm Beach.

In these building years, Rockefeller and Flagler worked in close harness, sitting in the same office with desks back to back, passing drafts of letters to customers and suppliers back and forth until they said exactly what they wanted. "On those walks," Rockefeller said, "when we were away from the office interruptions, we did our thinking, talking, and planning together."

Flagler devised and ran the transportation arrangements, which would prove central to the success of Standard Oil — for they gave the company a decisive power against all competitors. Without Flagler's expertise and aggressiveness in this realm, there might well have been no Standard Oil as the world came to know it.

The size, efficiency, and economies of scale of Rockefeller's organization enabled it to extract **rebates** — discounts on railway freight rates — which lowered its transportation costs below what competitors paid, providing a potent advantage in pricing and profit. These rebates would later be a source of great controversy. Many charged that Standard forced the rebates to undercut competitors unfairly. But competition among railroads for freight was so intense that rebates and discounts of one kind or another became common practice across the nation, especially for anyone who could guarantee large, regular shipments. Flagler was very good at driving the best deal possible.

Standard did not stop with rebates. It also used its prowess to win **"drawbacks."** A competing shipper might pay a dollar a barrel to send his oil by rail to New York. The railroad would turn around and pay twenty-five cents of that dollar back, not to the shipper, but to the shipper's rival — Standard Oil. What this practice really meant was that competitors were, unknowingly, subsidizing Standard Oil. Few business practices did as much to rouse public antipathy toward Standard Oil as these drawbacks.

### *"Now Try Our Plan"*

While the market for oil was growing at an extraordinary rate, the amount of oil seeking markets was growing even more rapidly, resulting in wild price fluctuations and frequent collapses. Toward the end of the 1860s, overproduction caused prices to plummet again, and the new industry went into a depression. Between 1865 and 1870, the retail price of kerosene fell by more than half. It was estimated that refining capacity was three times greater than the market's needs.

The costs of overcapacity were obvious to Rockefeller, and it was in these circumstances that he launched his effort to consolidate the industry in his own grasp. He and Flagler wanted to bring in more capital without jeopardizing control. The technique they used was to turn their partnership into a joint stock company. On **January 10, 1870**, five men, led by Rockefeller and Flagler, established the **Standard Oil Company**. The name was chosen to indicate a "standard quality of product" on which the consumer could depend. At that time, kerosene of widely varying quality was sold — if it contained too much flammable gasoline or naphtha, lighting it could be your last act on earth. Rockefeller held a quarter of the stock, which at that time already controlled a tenth of the American refining industry. "Who would ever have thought it would grow to such a size?"

Newly constituted with more capital, Standard pursued even more vigorously the railroad rebates. But overall business conditions continued to deteriorate, and by 1871 the refining industry was in a complete panic. Profit margins were disappearing, and most refiners were losing money. Rockefeller had married Laura Celestia Spelman in 1864. In her high school graduation essay, "I Can Paddle My Own Canoe," she had written, "The independence of woman in thought, deed, or will is one of the problems of the age." While giving up her dream of paddling her own canoe, she became his closest confidante. Now, in 1872, in the midst of the refinery depression, he reassured her: "You know, we are independently rich outside of investments in oil."

It was at this anxious time that Rockefeller conceived his bold vision of consolidating nearly all oil refining into one giant combination. "It was desirable to do something to save the business," he later said. An actual combination would do what a mere pool or association could not: eliminate excess capacity, suppress wild fluctuations of price — and, indeed, save the business. That was what Rockefeller and his colleagues meant when they talked of **"our plan."** "The idea was mine," he said much later. "The idea was persisted in, too, in spite of the opposition of some who became faint-hearted at the magnitude of the undertaking, as it constantly assumed larger proportions."

Standard geared up for the campaign, increasing its capitalization to facilitate takeovers. But events were moving in another direction as well. In February 1872, a local railway official in Pennsylvania became confused and abruptly doubled the cost of carrying crude from the Oil Regions to New York. Word leaked that the increase was the doing of an unknown entity called the **South Improvement Company**. The independent producers and refiners in the Oil Regions were aroused and alarmed.

The South Improvement Company was the embodiment of another scheme for stabilization of the oil industry and would become the symbol of the effort to achieve monopoly control. Though the idea actually belonged to the railroads, trying to find a way out of bitter rate wars, Rockefeller's name was to be ever more associated with it. Under the scheme, railroads and refiners would band together in cartels and divide markets. The refiners would not only get rebates on their shipments, but also receive those drawbacks — rebates from the full rates paid by nonmember refiners. "Of all the devices for the extinction of competition," one biographer has written, "this was the cruelest and most deadly yet conceived by any group of American industrialists."

Though still cloaked in mystery, the South Improvement Company enraged the Oil Regions. A Pittsburgh newspaper warned it would create "but one buyer of oil in the whole oil region." Three thousand angry men trooped with banners into the Titusville Opera House to denounce it. Thus was launched what became known as the **Oil War**. Producers marched from town to town to denounce "the Monster" and "the Forty Thieves." United against monopoly, they launched a boycott of the refiners and railroads so effective that Standard refineries in Cleveland had only enough crude to occupy seventy of their twelve hundred men. But Rockefeller had absolutely no doubts: "It is easy to write newspaper articles but we have other business," he told his wife. "We will do right and not be nervous or troubled by what the papers say." And: "It is not the business of the public to change our private contracts."

By April 1872, both the railroads and the refiners, including Rockefeller, had decided to disown and scuttle the South Improvement Company. The Oil War was over, apparently won by the producers. Later, Rockefeller would say he had always expected the South Improvement Company to fail, but went along for his own purposes. "When it failed, we would be in a position to say, 'Now try our plan.'" But Rockefeller had not even waited for it to fail. By the spring of 1872, he had already won control over most of Cleveland's refining and some of the most important refiners in New York City — making him the master of the largest refinery group in the world. He was ready to take on the entire oil industry.

The 1870s were marked by ever-rising production. Producers repeatedly tried to restrict production, but to no avail. Storage tanks overflowed. Crude oil was run out into streams and onto farms. At one point, the price dropped to forty-eight cents a barrel — three cents less than housewives in the Oil Regions were paying for drinking water. Efforts to organize shutdown movements always failed. There were far too many producers — estimates ranged as high as sixteen thousand firms. Many were speculators, farmers, highly individualistic and unlikely to take "a long view." Rockefeller, with his passion for order, looked with revulsion at the chaos. "The Oil Regions," he said with acid disdain, "was a mining camp." His target was the refiners.

### *"War or Peace"*

The objective of Rockefeller's audacious battle plan was, in his words, to end "that cut-throat policy of making no profits" and "make the oil business safe and profitable" — under his control. Rockefeller was both strategist and supreme commander, directing his lieutenants to move with stealth and speed. His brother William categorized relations with other refiners in terms of "war or peace."

Standard began, in each area, by attempting to buy out the leading refiners, the dominant firms. Rockefeller and his associates would approach their targets with deference, politeness, and flattery. They would demonstrate how profitable Standard Oil was compared with other refiners struggling through hard times. If all that failed, Standard would bring a tough competitor to heel by making him "feel sick" or giving him "a good sweating." Standard would cut prices in that particular market, forcing the competitor to operate at a loss. At one point, Standard orchestrated a "barrel famine" to put pressure on recalcitrant refiners. In another battle, Henry Flagler instructed: "If you think the perspiration don't roll off freely enough, pile the blankets on him. I would rather lose a great deal of money than to yield a pint to him at this time."

The Standard men, moving in great secrecy, operated through firms that appeared independent to the outside world but had in fact become part of the Standard Group. Many refiners never knew that their local competitors cutting prices were actually part of Rockefeller's growing empire. Through all phases of the campaign, the Standard men communicated in code — Standard Oil itself was "Morose." Rockefeller never wavered in his defense of secrecy. "But I wonder what General of the Allies ever sends out a brass band in advance with orders to notify the enemy that on a certain day he will begin an attack?"

By **1879**, the war was virtually over. Standard Oil was triumphant. It **controlled 90 percent of America's refining capacity.** It also controlled the pipelines and gathering system of the Oil Regions and dominated transportation. Rockefeller was unemotional in victory, bearing no grudge. Some of the conquered were brought into Standard's inner councils to become devoted allies.

### *New Threats*

At the very end of the 1870s, just when Rockefeller thought he had everything tied up, Pennsylvania producers made one last effort to break out of Standard's suffocating embrace — the world's first attempt at a **long-distance pipeline**. The project, named the **Tidewater Pipeline**, had no precedent. The oil would travel eastward from the Oil Regions to a connection with the Pennsylvania and Reading Railroad. Its construction was carried out with both deception and dispatch — fake surveys were taken to throw Standard off. By May 1879, oil was flowing in the pipeline. It was a major technological achievement, comparable to the Brooklyn Bridge four years later, and introduced a new stage in the history of oil — the pipeline would become a major competitor with the railroad for long-distance transportation.

The clear success of Tidewater caught Standard by surprise and meant that its control of the industry was suddenly in jeopardy. Standard sprang into action, building four long-distance pipelines from the Oil Regions to Cleveland, New York, Philadelphia, and Buffalo. Within two years, Standard was a minority stockholder in Tidewater itself and had an arrangement to pool shipments. With the partial exception of Tidewater, Standard controlled almost every inch of pipeline into and out of the Oil Regions.

There remained only one way to hold this giant in check — through the political system and the courts. At the end of the 1870s, producers from the Oil Regions launched a series of legal assaults in Pennsylvania against discriminatory rates. They denounced "the overweening control of the oil business by the Standard Oil Company," castigated it as an "Autocrat" and "this gang of thieves." Legislative hearings in New York focused on Standard Oil's rebate system. The investigations and legal proceedings in the two states marked the first public revelation of the activities of Standard Oil. A Pennsylvania grand jury indicted Rockefeller, Flagler, and several associates for conspiracy to create a monopoly and injure competitors. A vigorous effort was made to extradite Rockefeller to Pennsylvania. He was alarmed enough to exact a promise from the Governor of New York not to approve any extradition order, and the attempt eventually failed.

Still, the cumulative effect on public opinion was devastating and lasting. The charges against Standard were brought together for the first time by **Henry Demarest Lloyd**, in editorials for the *Chicago Tribune* and then in an article entitled "The Story of a Great Monopoly," published in the *Atlantic Monthly* in 1881 — so great was the attention that the issue went through seven printings. Lloyd declared that the Standard Oil Company had done everything to the Pennsylvania State Legislature except refine it. Yet the article had little immediate impact on Standard's business. In the Oil Regions, mothers would warn their children, "Rockefeller will get you if you don't mind."

### *The Trust*

While the courts and public opinion had to be kept at bay, an ingenious internal order and control was created in the vast empire Rockefeller had conquered. There was no clear legal basis for the association of these various refineries around the country. Thus, Rockefeller could say with a straight face and without perjuring himself that Standard Oil itself did not own or control a host of companies that it manifestly did control. The real clue was that it was the *stockholders* of Standard Oil, not Standard Oil itself, who owned shares in the other firms. At that time, corporations themselves could not own stock in other corporations. The shares were held "in trust," not for the Standard Oil Company of Ohio, but on behalf of the stockholders of that corporation.

The legal concept of the "trust" was refined and formalized in the **Standard Oil Trust Agreement**, signed on **January 2, 1882**. It was also a response to judicial and political attacks. There was also a personal reason — Rockefeller and his partners had begun to think about mortality and inheritance, and they concluded that the death of one of them would lead to confusion, controversy, and litigation under the existing system. A trust would get the ownership organized.

In preparing the trust, "every foot of pipeline was measured, every particle of brickwork was estimated." A board of trustees was set up, and the stock of all entities controlled by Standard Oil was placed in the trust. Out of 700,000 total shares, Rockefeller held 191,700 and Flagler, next, had 60,000. The trustees held shares on behalf of the forty-one shareowners and were charged with "general supervision" of fourteen wholly owned and twenty-six partly owned companies. It was the first great "trust," and it was perfectly legal. But this was also why "trust," formerly a device for protecting widows and orphans, became a term of derogation and hatred.

The trust agreement made possible a central office to coordinate and rationalize the activities of the various operating entities. The trust gave Rockefeller and his associates "the shield of legality and the administrative flexibility they needed to operate effectively what had become virtually global properties."

What evolved was a system of management and coordination by committee. There was a Domestic Trade Committee, an Export Trade Committee, a Manufacturing Committee, a Staves and Heading Committee, a Pipe Line Committee, a Case Committee, a Lubricating Committee, and later a Production Committee. Daily reports flowed in from around the country. On top of it all was the **Executive Committee**, composed of the top managers, which set overall policies and directions. The Executive Committee did not issue orders so much as requests, suggestions, and recommendations — but no one doubted its authority or control. "You gentlemen on the ground can judge better than we about the matter, but let us not drift into arrangements where we cannot control the policy."

A basic strategy that had governed Standard in the 1870s became even more explicit in the 1880s — to be the **low-cost producer**. This required efficiency in operations, mastery of costs, a drive for scale and volume, constant attention to technology, and ceaseless striving for ever-larger markets. Refining operations were consolidated; by the middle 1880s, just three Standard refineries — in Cleveland, Philadelphia, and Bayonne, New Jersey — produced upward of a quarter of the world's total supply of kerosene. The focus on costs never wavered. "It has always been my rule in business to make everything count," Rockefeller said. The company also used an extraordinary system of corporate intelligence and espionage to track market conditions and competitors — maintaining a card catalog of practically every buyer of oil in the country, showing where virtually every barrel shipped by independent dealers went.

A central theme underlay Rockefeller's management: he *believed* in oil, and his faith never wavered. Any drop in the price of crude was not a reason for anxiety, but an opportunity to buy. "Hope if crude oil goes down again ... our Executive Committee will not allow any amount of statistics or information ... to prevent their buying," he instructed in 1884. "We must try and not lose our nerve when the market gets to the bottom as some people almost always do." Shortly after, he added, *"We will surely make a great mistake if we do not buy."*

The senior management included Rockefeller, his brother William, Henry Flagler, and two others who altogether controlled four-sevenths of the stock. But it also extended to perhaps a dozen others, virtually all willful, assertive individuals who had been successful entrepreneurs — and, originally, competitors of Rockefeller. "It is not always the easiest of tasks to induce strong, forceful men to agree." The only way such a grouping could work was by consensus. "It is always, I presume, a question in every business just how fast it is wise to go, and we went pretty rapidly on those days, building and expanding in all directions."

The senior managers were frequently found shuttling between Cleveland, New York, Pittsburgh, Buffalo, Baltimore, and Philadelphia. In 1885, the trust moved into new headquarters, a nine-story office building at **26 Broadway**, in lower Manhattan, which soon became a landmark. The senior executives lunched together daily in a private dining room at the top of the building. Over the meal, vital information was exchanged, ideas examined, consensus built. "These men are smarter than I am a great deal," William Vanderbilt of the New York Central Railroad told the legislature. "They are very enterprising and smart men. I never came into contact with any class of men so smart and able as they are in their business."

### *"The Wise Old Owl"*

But the smartest was certainly John D. Rockefeller. At the time the trust was formed, he was in his early forties, already one of the half-dozen richest men in America. He was also strangely, deliberately, inaccessible. Later in life, he recited a little rhyme: "A wise old owl lived in an oak, / The more he saw the less he spoke, / The less he spoke, the more he heard, / Why aren't we all like that old bird?"

He had resolved from the beginning to "expose as little surface as possible." His remoteness and icy, penetrating stare were unnerving. On one occasion, Rockefeller met in Pittsburgh with a group of refiners. Afterward, the talk centered on the taciturn, ungregarious, menacing man from Cleveland. "I've been watching him," one finally said. "He lets everybody else talk, while he sits back and says nothing. But he seems to remember everything, and when he does begin he puts everything in its proper place ... I guess he's 140 years old — for he must have been 100 years old when he was born."

Many years later, one who worked for Rockefeller described him as "the most unemotional man I have ever known." Yet behind the mask, there was a man. The 1870s and 1880s were years when "our plan" reached its fruition, but those years of consolidation and integration, of unexpected political and press attacks, were also years of great strain and tension. "All the fortune that I have made has not served to compensate me for the anxiety of that period," Rockefeller once said. His wife remembered "days of worry," and he himself recalled he "seldom got an unbroken night's sleep."

He sought relaxation in different ways. Late in the day, during business meetings, he would lie down on a couch and participate from there. He kept a primitive muscle extender in his office. He had a special love for horses, fast horses, and would take them out for a carriage ride at the end of the day — "trot, pace, gallop, everything" — after which he would rejuvenate and "take up the evening's mail and get ten letters off."

Outside of business, his life centered on his Baptist church, where he was superintendent of the Sunday school. His Forest Hill estate outside Cleveland absorbed him with the same obsessive attention to detail he brought to business — the building of fireplaces, planting trees, cutting roads through woods. He moved later to a vast estate in the Pocantico hills, north of New York City, where he directed landscaping, constructed views, and worked at laying out new roads himself with stakes and flags.

Even while becoming the richest man in America, he maintained a curious frugality. He wore the same old suits until they became so shiny they had to be replaced. One favorite dish remained bread and milk. Once in Cleveland, he invited a prominent local businessman and his wife to stay at Forest Hill for the summer. They spent a pleasant six weeks — then were surprised to receive a bill of six hundred dollars from Rockefeller for board.

He was not without a sense of humor, though he displayed it only in restricted circles. "Have been in the dentist's chair," he once reported to Flagler. "Think would have preferred to write you, or even read your letters, but could not help myself!" He would entertain his family by singing at dinner, or by putting a cracker on his nose and catching it in his mouth, or balancing a plate on his nose. He loved to sit with his children and play a game called "Buzz" — counting numbers and saying "Buzz" instead of any number with a seven. Somehow, despite his gift for mathematics, he could never get beyond 71. The children found this hilarious.

Rockefeller had begun making small donations to his church as soon as he started earning money. Over time, he devoted increasing efforts to giving away a significant part of his wealth, applying the same methodical investigation he brought to business. Eventually his donations would extend through the sciences, medicine, and education. In the nineteenth century, much of his philanthropy was oriented to the Baptist church.

At the end of the 1880s, he committed himself to the creation of a great Baptist university — providing the endowment and the organizational focus for the establishment of the **University of Chicago**. He continued as by far its largest donor. Though he paid keen attention to its development, he did not interfere in its academic workings, save to insist it stay within its budget. He refused to allow buildings to be named after him. By 1910, he had given to the university $35 million, compared to $7 million from all other sources. Altogether, he was to give away some $550 million.

He carried over his habits of business to his private life. In the Gilded Age of "robber barons," his New York townhouse and Pocantico estate were opulent, but Rockefeller and his family stood apart from the garishness and ostentation of the age. He sought to inculcate values of probity in his children and avoid having them ruined by inherited riches — the children shared only one tricycle so they might learn to share. Young John D. Rockefeller, Jr., in New York City, was made to walk to and from school even as other children of the rich were carried back and forth in rigs accompanied by grooms, and he earned pocket money working on his father's estates for the same wages as the laborers.

In 1888, Rockefeller took his family and two Baptist ministers to Europe for three months. Though he did not know French, he would scrutinize each item on every bill. "Poulets!" he would exclaim. "What are poulets?" Told they were chickens, he would go on to the next item. "Father," John Junior would later recall, "was never willing to pay a bill which he did not know to be correct in all its items. Such care in small things might seem penurious to some people, yet to him it was the working out of a life principle."

### *A Marvel to the Eye*

The company Rockefeller founded continued to expand during the 1880s and into the 1890s. Scientific research was incorporated into the business. Great attention was devoted to quality of product and neatness of operations. The growth of the marketing system — down to the final consumer — was an imperative of the business. "We needed volume." And it surely and steadily moved to ever-higher volumes. The growth in the use of oil, largely as kerosene, was stupendous.

Oil and the kerosene lamp were changing American life — and the clock by which Americans lived. Whether in towns and cities of the East or farms of the Midwest, consumers usually bought their kerosene from their grocer or druggist, supplied by a wholesaler, most of whom were supplied by Standard Oil. As early as 1864, a New York chemist described the impact: "Kerosene has, in one sense, increased the length of life among the agricultural population. Those who, on account of the dearness or inefficiency of whale oil, were accustomed to go to bed soon after the sunset and spend almost half their time in sleep, now occupy a portion of the night in reading and other amusements."

Practical advice on kerosene — showing its quick acceptance — was provided in 1869 by Harriet Beecher Stowe, who assisted her sister with *American Woman's Home or Principles of Domestic Science*. "Good kerosene gives a light which leaves little to be desired," they wrote, but warned against poor quality and impure oils responsible for "those terrible explosions." In the mid-1870s, five to six thousand deaths a year were attributed to such accidents. This was why Rockefeller insisted on consistency and quality control, and why he had chosen the name Standard.

Kerosene was by far the most important product coming out of refineries, but not the only one. Other products included naphtha, used as a solvent or turned into a gas for illuminating buildings; gasoline; fuel oil; lubricants for train engines, railway cars, agricultural implements, cotton spindles, and later bicycles. Other products were petroleum jelly, trademarked as "Vaseline," paraffin for candle making and food preservation, and "paraffin chewing gum," which was "highly recommended for constant use in ladies in sewing circles."

In its effort to reach the consumer, Standard Oil moved to gain control over the marketing side of the business. By the mid-1880s, its control of marketing must have been almost equivalent to its control of refining — in the 80 percent range. Its tactics in acquiring that huge market share were just as ruthless. Its salesmen would "make a fist" and seek to intimidate rivals and retailers who dared to carry competing products. Standard pushed innovations to make marketing more efficient and lower costs. One innovation was the railway tank car, replacing the need to pile barrels into boxcars. Standard also replaced barrels on the streets with horse-drawn tank cars that could disburse anything from a pint to five gallons of kerosene.

### *"Buy All We Can Get"*

But Standard had stayed out of one critical part of the business — the production of oil. It was too risky, too volatile, too speculative. As one Executive Committee member wrote Rockefeller in 1885, "Our business is that of manufacturers, and it is in my judgment, an unfortunate thing for any manufacturer or merchant to allow his mind to have the care and friction which attends speculative ventures."

But a sense of precariousness underlay Standard's great globe-girdling system. There was always the fear that the oil would run out. Flush production quickly exhausted wells. Pennsylvania was the only game, and perhaps what had happened at Pithole could happen to the entire Oil Regions. In 1885, the State Geologist of Pennsylvania warned that "the amazing exhibition of oil" was only "a temporary and vanishing phenomenon — one which young men will live to see come to its natural end."

That same year, John Archbold, a top Standard executive, was told by a company specialist that decline in American production was almost inevitable and chances of finding another large field were "at least one hundred to one against it." These warnings were so persuasive that Archbold sold some of his Standard shares at seventy-five to eighty cents on the dollar. When also told about signs of oil in Oklahoma, he replied, "Are you crazy? Why, I'll drink every gallon produced west of the Mississippi!"

But just at that moment, the industry was about to break out of Pennsylvania — with dramatic suddenness. The scene was northwestern Ohio, where flammable gas springs in the vicinity of Findlay had been known since the earliest settlements. In the mid-1880s, oil was discovered there, igniting a great boom in the region that straddled the border with Indiana — the **Lima-Indiana fields**. By 1890, they accounted for a third of United States oil production.

Rockefeller was poised to make his last great strategic decision — to go directly into oil production. No less than his colleagues, he had great antipathy for oil producers — speculators, unreliable, behaving like greedy miners in a gold rush. Yet here, in Lima, was an opportunity for Standard to gain control of its raw materials on a very large scale. In short, Standard would be able to insulate itself against the fluctuations and volatility of the oil market — and against the disorder of the "mining camp." And that was the direction in which Rockefeller very definitely wanted to go.

But there were two major obstacles. One was the quality of the petroleum — it had very different properties from Pennsylvania crude, including a most unappealing sulfuric odor, like rotten eggs. Some called the Lima crude "skunk juice." There was no known way to remove the odor, and until one was found, the Ohio oil had only a very limited market.

The second obstacle was located at 26 Broadway — the obstinacy of Rockefeller's more cautious colleagues. They thought the risk much too great. Rockefeller argued the company should buy up all the oil and store it in tanks. The oil was flowing in such huge volumes that the price dropped from forty cents a barrel in 1886 to fifteen cents in 1887. But many of Rockefeller's colleagues strongly opposed buying oil for which there was not yet any good use. "Our conservative brethren on the Board," as Rockefeller called them, "held up their hands in holy terror and desperately fought a few of us." Eventually, however, Rockefeller prevailed, and Standard Oil put more than 40 million barrels of Lima oil in storage. Then, in 1888 and 1889, **Herman Frasch**, a German chemist employed by Standard, figured out that if the crude oil were refined in the presence of copper oxide, the sulfur could be removed, eliminating the rotten-eggs smell and making Lima oil an acceptable source of kerosene. Rockefeller's Lima gamble proved well worth it — after Frasch's breakthrough, the price of Lima oil immediately doubled from the fifteen cents a barrel at which Standard had acquired it to thirty cents, and continued to climb.

Rockefeller pushed the company toward the final step of buying up producing properties. His colleagues were reluctant, even opposed. Rockefeller was insistent. He carried the day. Of the leases available for purchase he simply ordered **"Buy all we can get."** By 1891, though virtually absent from production a few years earlier, Standard was itself responsible for a quarter of America's total output of crude oil.

Standard committed itself to building the world's largest refinery at a place called **Whiting**, amidst desolate sand dunes on the shore of Lake Michigan in Indiana, to process the Lima crude. There, as everywhere, Standard's cult of secrecy was at work. A reporter from the *Chicago Tribune* found it impossible to get information from Mr. Marshall, the close-mouthed manager: "They might be erecting a $5 million dollar oil refinery or they might be putting up a pork packing establishment. He didn't think it was a pork packing establishment, but he wasn't sure."

Then there was the matter of the price itself. For many years, prices had reflected trading on oil exchanges. Through the 1880s, the **Joseph Seep Agency**, the buying arm of Standard Oil, bought oil on the open market by acquiring "certificates" on these exchanges. When the Seep Agency bought directly at the wellhead, it averaged the day's highest and lowest prices from the exchanges. Increasingly, Seep bought directly from producers, and transactions on the exchanges fell steadily.

Finally, in January 1895, Joseph Seep closed down the era of the oil exchanges with a historic "Notice to Oil Producers." He announced that "dealing" on the exchanges was "no longer a reliable indication of the value of the product." From then on, "the price paid will be as high as the markets of the world will justify." As either purchaser or owner of between 85 and 90 percent of the oil in Pennsylvania and Lima-Indiana, Seep and Standard Oil now effectively determined the purchase price for American crude oil, though always bound by supply and demand.

### *The Upbuilder*

In every dimension, the scale of Standard's operations was awesome, overwhelming competitors. Yet it was not a complete monopoly — somewhere around 15 to 20 percent of oil was sold by competitors, and Standard's directors were willing to live with that. Control of upwards of 85 percent of the market was sufficient to maintain stability. Reflecting upon his landscaping and tree growing, Rockefeller observed in old age, "In nursery stock, as in other things, the advantage of doing things on a large scale reveals itself."

Rockefeller created the **vertically integrated petroleum company**. Many years later, one of his successors at Standard Oil of Ohio mused: "He instinctively realized that orderliness would only proceed from a centralized control of large aggregations of plant and capital, with the one aim of an orderly flow of products from the producer to the consumer. That orderly, economical, efficient flow was what we now, many years later, call 'vertical integration.' I do not know whether Mr. Rockefeller ever used the word 'integration.' I only know he conceived the idea."

The US government's *Mineral Resources* declared in 1882: "There seems to be little doubt that the company has done a great work, and that through its instrumentality oil refining has been reduced to a business, and transportation has been greatly simplified; but as to how much evil has been mixed with this good, it is not practicable to make a definite statement."

For others — Standard's competitors and a good part of the public — the judgment was completely negative. To many producers and independent refiners, Standard Oil was the **Octopus**, out to grasp all competitors, "body and soul." To those who suffered from Rockefeller's machinations, he was a bloodless monster who hypocritically invoked the Lord as he methodically set about destroying people's livelihoods.

Some colleagues were grieved by the criticism. "We have met with a success unparalleled in commercial history, our name is known all over the world, and our public character is not one to be envied," one wrote Rockefeller in 1887. "We are quoted as the representative of all that is evil, hard hearted, oppressive, cruel (we think unjustly)." Rockefeller himself was not so troubled. He even sought to enlist Protestant evangelists and Social Gospel clergy in defense of Standard Oil. He remained confident that Standard Oil was an instrument for human betterment, replacing chaos and volatility with stability, delivering the gift of the "new light" to the world of darkness. "Give the poor man his cheap light, gentlemen," he would tell the Executive Committee. "The day of combination is here to stay," Rockefeller said after he had stepped aside from active management. "Individualism has gone, never to return." Standard Oil was one of the greatest, perhaps even the greatest, of "upbuilders we ever had in this country."

Mark Twain and Charles Dudley Warner, in *The Gilded Age*, grasped the character of the decades after the Civil War — "the manufacture of giant schemes, of speculations of all sorts ... [and of] inflamed desire for sudden wealth." Rockefeller was in some ways the true embodiment of his age. Standard Oil was a merciless competitor that would "cut to kill," and he became the wealthiest of all. Yet, whereas many other robber barons amassed their wealth by speculation, stock and financial manipulation, and outright fraud — cheating their stockholders — Rockefeller built his fortune by taking on a youthful, wild, unpredictable, and unreliable industry, and relentlessly transforming it according to his own logic into a highly organized, far-flung business that satisfied the basic hunger for light around the world.

"Our plan" was to succeed even beyond Rockefeller's boldest visions, but it would ultimately fail. In the United States, public opinion and the political process would revolt against combination and monopoly. At the same time, new individuals and new companies — operating beyond Rockefeller's reach in the US and in faraway places like Baku, Sumatra, Burma, and later Persia — would rise up to prove themselves hardy and persistent competitors. And some would do more than survive; they would flourish.

---

## Chapter 3: Competitive Commerce (p75-85, continued next batch)

Though the rest of the world was waiting for the "new light" from America, it had been no easy thing to get the first shipment of oil off to Europe. Sailors were terrified about explosions and fires. Finally, in 1861, a Philadelphia shipper obtained a crew by getting the potential recruits drunk and virtually shanghai-ing them aboard. That cargo made its way safely to London. The door to global trade was opened, and American oil quickly won markets throughout the world. Virtually from the very beginning, petroleum was an international business. The American oil industry could not have grown to the size it did without its foreign markets. In Europe, rapid demand increase was stimulated by industrialization, economic growth, urbanization, and a shortage of fats and oils. The development of various markets was speeded by United States consuls eager to push "this new Yankee invention," sometimes purchasing oil out of their own pockets to distribute to potential customers.

Consider what the global demand meant: the substance for the popular form of lighting worldwide was provided not merely by one country, but, for the most part, by one state — Pennsylvania. Never again would any single region have such a grasp on supply of the raw material. Almost overnight, the export business became immensely important. In the 1870s and 1880s, kerosene exports accounted for over half of total American oil output. Kerosene was the fourth-largest US export in value; the first among manufactured goods. And Europe was by far the largest market.

By the end of the 1870s, not only was one state dominant, but so was one company — Standard Oil. Eventually, at least 90 percent of exported kerosene passed through Standard's hands. Standard was satisfied with a system in which its role ended in an American port. Rockefeller, indeed, intended to impose "our plan" on the entire world. Petroleum, said Standard Oil's chief foreign representative, had "forced its way into more nooks and corners of civilized and uncivilized countries than any other product in business history emanating from a single source."

There was, of course, a danger — the potential of foreign competition. But the men at 26 Broadway discounted that possibility. The Pennsylvania Geological Report of 1874 proudly commented on how thoroughly the state's oil dominated world markets. It mentioned in passing "the drill in other countries ... would find oil" — but "this was only an issue that some day may interest us." They were already in error.

### *"The Walnut Money"*

Among the most promising markets for the "new light" was the vast Russian empire, which was beginning to industrialize and for which artificial light had special importance. As early as 1862, American kerosene reached Russia and St. Petersburg, quickly winning wide acceptance, with kerosene lamps swiftly replacing the tallow on which the populace had almost entirely depended. But future developments in a distant part of the empire would not only foreclose the Russian market to American oil but spell the undoing of Rockefeller's global plans.

For many centuries, oil seepages had been noted on the arid **Aspheron Peninsula**, an outgrowth of the Caucasus Mountains projecting into the landlocked Caspian Sea. In the thirteenth century, Marco Polo reported hearing of a spring around Baku that produced oil, "good to burn" and useful for cleaning the mange of camels. Baku was the territory of the "eternal pillars of fire" worshiped by the Zoroastrians — the result of flammable gas, associated with petroleum deposits, escaping from fissures in porous limestone.

Baku was part of an independent duchy annexed to the Russian empire early in the nineteenth century. By 1829 there were eighty-two hand-dug oil pits, but output was tiny. The industry was severely restricted by the region's backwardness and remoteness and by the corrupt, heavy-handed, incompetent Czarist administration, which ran the oil industry as a state monopoly. Finally, at the beginning of the 1870s, the Russian government abolished the monopoly system and opened the area to competitive private enterprise. The result was an explosion of entrepreneurship. The first wells were drilled in 1871-72; by 1873, more than twenty small refineries were at work.

Shortly after, a chemist named **Robert Nobel** arrived in Baku. He was the eldest son of Immanuel Nobel, a clever Swedish inventor who had emigrated in 1837 to Russia, where the military establishment excitedly took up his invention of the underwater mine. Immanuel built up a considerable industrial company, only to have it fail when the Russian government swung from domestic to foreign procurement. One son, **Ludwig**, built upon the ruins of his father's business a new company — a great armaments concern; he also developed the "Nobel wheel," uniquely suited to wretched Russian roads. Another son, **Alfred**, gifted in both chemistry and finance, created a worldwide dynamite empire from Paris. But the eldest son, Robert, was unsuccessful in various businesses and finally returned to St. Petersburg to work grudgingly for Ludwig.

Ludwig obtained a huge contract to manufacture rifles for the Russian government. He needed wood for the rifle stocks, and dispatched Robert south to the Caucasus to search for Russian walnut. In March 1873, Robert's journey took him to Baku. Though very much a part of Asia — with minarets and the old mosque of the Persian shahs, populated by Tatars, Persians, and Armenians — the recent oil development had begun to bring great change. Robert was immediately caught up in the fever. Without consulting his brother, he took the twenty-five thousand rubles Ludwig had entrusted to him for buying wood — **"the walnut money"** — and instead bought a small refinery. The Nobels were in the oil business.

### *The Rise of Russian Oil*

Robert quickly set about modernizing the refinery he had bought with Ludwig's money. With additional funds from his brother, he established himself as the most competent refiner in Baku. In October 1876, the first shipment of Nobel's illuminating oil arrived in St. Petersburg. In that same year, Ludwig came to Baku to see for himself. Skilled in dealing with the imperial system, Ludwig won the blessing of the Grand Duke, brother of the Czar and viceroy of the Caucasus. But Ludwig was also a great industrial leader, capable of conceiving a plan on the scale of Rockefeller. He set about analyzing every phase of the oil business, learned everything about the American oil experience, and harnessed science, innovation, and business planning to efficiency and profitability. In a very few years, Russian oil was to take on and even surpass American oil, and Ludwig Nobel would become **"the Oil King of Baku."**

Long-distance transit was a critical problem. Oil was shipped in wooden barrels over an inefficient and lengthy route — by boat on the Caspian Sea to Astrakhan, then transferred to barges for the journey up the Volga River, eventually reaching a rail line. Handling costs were enormous. Even the barrels were costly — no local wood, so wood was imported from America or secondhand American barrels were bought in Western Europe. Ludwig conceived a solution with far-reaching implications: ship the oil in **"bulk"** — in large tanks built into ships.

The idea faced considerable ballast and safety problems. Ludwig figured out the ballast problem and commissioned the first successful **bulk tanker**, the *Zoroaster*, which was put into service in 1878 on the Caspian. By the middle 1880s, Ludwig's concept had proved itself on the Atlantic, launching a major revolution in oil transport. Meanwhile Ludwig was constantly pushing his Baku refinery to be among the most scientifically advanced in the world. His was the first company anywhere in the world to have a permanent staff position for a **professional petroleum geologist**.

The great, highly integrated oil combine built by Ludwig soon dominated the Russian oil trade. The **Nobel Brothers Petroleum Producing Company** had wells, pipelines, refineries, tankers, barges, storage depots, its own railroad, a retail distribution network — and a multinational workforce that was treated better than virtually any other working group in Russia, proudly calling themselves "Nobelites." The rapid development of Ludwig's empire was described as "one of the greatest triumphs of business enterprise in the entire nineteenth century."

Russian crude production, less than 600,000 barrels in 1874, reached **10.8 million** a decade later — equivalent to almost a third of American production. By the early 1880s, almost two hundred refineries were at work in the new industrial suburb of Baku known as **Black Town** — so dense a cloud of dark, smelly oil smoke that life there was compared to "confinement in a chimney-pot." Nobel's company was producing half of all Russian kerosene, triumphantly telling stockholders that "American kerosene has now been completely forced out of the Russian market."

But the company suffered from discord among the Nobel brothers. Robert resented Ludwig's intrusion. Ludwig was a builder, constantly seeking to expand, continuously hungry for new capital. Alfred, remembering how their father had failed through overexpansion, was much more cautious. "The main point of criticism," Alfred scolded Ludwig, "is that you build first and then look around for the wherewithal." Despite their disagreements, Alfred provided crucial assistance — his own money and help arranging loans, including a major borrowing from the Credit Lyonnais. That transaction set a significant precedent: it may have been the first loan for which future petroleum production was used as collateral.

Nobel Brothers dominated distribution of oil within the Russian Empire. Beyond those borders, Russian oil was hardly a factor — geography locked the oil into the empire. To reach a Baltic port meant "2,000 miles, intermittent water and rail transportation through western Russia." Severe winter weather precluded shipping kerosene on the Caspian between October and March, with the result that many refiners shut down for half the year. Even parts of the empire were inaccessible — in the city of Tiflis, it was cheaper to import kerosene from America, 8,000 miles away, than from Baku, 341 miles to the west.

There were also limits to the market within the Russian empire — illumination was far from a necessity for the vast peasantry. Ever-growing production forced the producers of Baku to look hungrily beyond the borders of the empire. Seeking an alternative to the northern route dominated by Nobel, two other producers — Bunge and Palashkovsky — won government approval to begin building a railroad from Baku west over the Caucasus to **Batum**, a port on the Black Sea incorporated into Russia in 1877. But in the midst of construction, the price of oil dropped, and they ran out of money.

Their rescue came from the French branch of a family that had financed many of Europe's wars, governments, and new railroads. They owned a refinery at Fiume on the Adriatic and were interested in acquiring lower-priced Russian crude. They loaned the money to complete the railroad, acquiring mortgages on Russian oil facilities. They also arranged guaranteed shipments of Russian oil to Europe at attractive prices. They were the **Rothschilds**.

This was a time of fervent anti-Semitism in Russia. An 1882 Imperial Decree had forbidden Jews to own or rent any more land within the empire. But in the Rothschilds' case, the decree did not seem to matter. Russian oil was a project of the Paris Rothschilds — that meant **Baron Alphonse**, who had organized France's reparations payments after its defeat by Prussia in 1871, was considered one of the best-informed men in Europe, and was said to own the best pair of moustaches on the Continent — and of his younger brother **Baron Edmond**, who sponsored Jewish settlement in Palestine. The Rothschild loan allowed the railroad from Baku to be completed in 1883, turning Batum almost overnight into one of the world's most important oil ports. In 1886, the Rothschilds formed the **Caspian and Black Sea Petroleum Company**, known ever after by its Russian initials — **"Bnito."** The Baku-Batum railroad opened a door to the West for Russian oil; it also initiated a fierce, thirty-year struggle for the oil markets of the world.

### *The Challenge to Standard Oil*

With the Rothschilds on the scene, the Nobels suddenly faced a major competitor — soon to become the second-largest Russian oil group. Though the two competitive groups discussed amalgamation, they could find no common ground, and their rivalry remained intense. Standard Oil could not afford to ignore the Russian oil industry. Russian kerosene was now competing with American illuminating oils in many countries in Europe. In response, Standard Oil stepped up its intelligence-gathering effort. Reports began to flow into 26 Broadway from all over the world, including some from American consuls who were also on the Standard payroll. The intelligence was disturbing — no longer could Standard complacently count on its overwhelming dominance.

Standard's management figured the Czarist government would never allow it to buy out Ludwig Nobel altogether. But it could try to acquire a substantial number of Nobel shares and retain the invaluable Ludwig in management. In 1885, W. H. Libby, Standard's top business-diplomat, opened talks with the Nobels in St. Petersburg. Ludwig Nobel was not interested. Instead he concentrated on strengthening his own marketing network and building up his sales in Europe. The spectacular increase of Russian oil production forced Nobel and the other Russian oil men to seek new markets beyond the empire. Baku was characterized by astonishing oil "fountains" or gushers, with such names as "Kormilitza" (the Wet Nurse) and Golden Bazaar and Devil's Bazaar. One called "Droozba" (Friendship) gushed for five months at forty-three thousand barrels per day, most of it wasted. By 1886 there were eleven fountains. Altogether Russian oil production rose tenfold between 1879 and 1888, reaching **23 million barrels** — equivalent to more than four-fifths of American production. As the flood of oil rapidly rose in the 1880s, it needed to find its way to markets.

Faced with Nobel's aggressive new sales campaign in Europe and the growing production from Baku, Standard concluded it had to take actions beyond mere discussions. In November 1885, it dropped its prices in Europe — just as it would when attacking a competitor in the US. Its local agents started rumor campaigns in various European countries about the quality and safety of Russian kerosenes. They also resorted to sabotage and bribery. Despite the ferocity of the Standard assault, Nobel and the Rothschilds fought back fiercely and successfully, and Standard's executives watched with dismay as the region of "Russian competition" broadened across the map.

In 1888, the Rothschilds took a new step — establishing their own importing and distributing companies in Britain. Nobel Brothers did likewise. Finally galvanized into action, Standard set up its first foreign "affiliate," the **Anglo-American Oil Company**, just twenty-four days after the official organization of the Rothschilds' new enterprise in Britain. It also established new affiliates on the Continent — joint ventures with leading local distributors. Standard Oil had become a true multinational enterprise.

Still its competitors could not be stayed. The Rothschilds lent money to smaller Russian producers, tying up rights to their production at advantageous prices. The Baku-Batum railroad suffered from a great bottleneck — the seventy-eight-mile stretch over a three-thousand-foot peak was so difficult that only half a dozen cars could be hauled over at any given time. In 1889, the Nobel Brothers completed a forty-two-mile pipeline through the mountain, using four hundred tons of Alfred's dynamite. In this new era of what Libby, Standard's roving ambassador, called **"competitive commerce,"** America's share of the world export trade in illuminating oil fell from 78 percent in 1888 to 71 percent in 1891, while the Russian share rose from 22 percent to 29 percent.

The prolific Baku fields continued to throw up new petroleum fountains and ever more oil. But there had been one dramatic change in the Russian oil industry. While Ludwig Nobel's patience and determination did not abate, physically he was worn out. In 1888 at the age of fifty-seven, the Oil King of Baku **died of a heart attack** while vacationing on the French Riviera.

Some of the European newspapers confused the Nobel brothers and instead reported the death of Alfred. Reading his own premature obituaries, Alfred was distressed to find himself condemned as a munitions maker, the "dynamite king," a merchant of death who had made a huge fortune by finding new ways to maim and kill. He brooded over these obituaries, and eventually rewrote his will, leaving his money for the establishment of the prizes that would perpetuate his name — the **Nobel Prizes** — in a way that would seem to honor the best in human endeavor.

### *The Son of the Shell Merchant*

Still, there was Russian kerosene flowing out of Batum in ever-increasing quantities, in search of markets. The Nobels had a firm grip on the internal Russian market. But for the others, especially the Rothschilds, the problem of "disposal" was growing each year. Somehow, the Rothschilds had to find their way around Standard Oil and into the world market. They looked with special interest to the East, to Asia, where they saw hundreds of millions of potential customers for the "new light." But how to get the oil to them?

The Rothschilds in Paris knew a shipping broker in London named **Fred Lane**, who watched out for their oil interests. Though always a backstage figure, Lane was to be one of the important oil pioneers. He was a big, burly man of great intelligence, a "go-between *par excellence*" eventually known as **"Shady Lane"** — not because he was crooked, but because he sometimes appeared to be representing so many different interested parties simultaneously that it was hard to know for whom he was really working.

Lane was truly expert in shipping, and he had a solution to offer the Rothschilds. He knew a certain merchant of rising prominence — **Marcus Samuel**. He put the Rothschilds in touch with Samuel. The result would be an audacious scheme that might not only solve the problem of Russian oil, but also take the form of a veritable worldwide coup that, if successful, would loosen the iron grip of Rockefeller and Standard Oil on the kerosene trade of the world.

By the end of the 1880s, Marcus Samuel had already gained some prominence in the City of London — no mean achievement for a Jew, and a Jew not from one of the old Sephardic families but from the East End of London, a descendant of immigrants who had come to Britain in 1750 from Holland and Bavaria. Samuel had the same name as his father, Marcus Samuel, most unusual for a professing Jew. The elder Marcus Samuel had begun his business career trading on the East London docks, buying curios from returning sailors. In the census of 1851, he was listed as a "shell merchant"; among his most popular products were little knickknack boxes covered with seashells, known as a "Gift from Brighton," sold to girls and young ladies at English seaside resorts. By the 1860s, the elder Marcus had accumulated some wealth and was importing everything from ostrich feathers to partridge canes to bags of pepper and slabs of tin. He was also exporting manufactures, including the first mechanical looms sent to Japan. Importantly for his son, the elder Samuel had built up a network of trusted relationships with some of the great British trading houses — run mainly by expatriate Scots — in Calcutta, Singapore, Bangkok, Manila, Hong Kong, and other parts of the Far East.

The younger Marcus was born in 1853. In 1869, at age sixteen, he went to work on his father's ledgers. At that very moment, John Rockefeller, fourteen years older, was about to begin his decade-long campaign to consolidate the oil industry. New technology was radically transforming trading and international commerce. In 1869, the Suez Canal was opened, knocking four thousand miles off the journey to the Far East. Steamships were taking over from sail. In 1870, the direct telegraph cable from England to Bombay was completed, and shortly after, Japan, China, Singapore, and Australia were all brought into the telegraph network. These were tools the younger Marcus Samuel would use to build his wealth.

After his father's death, Marcus, in partnership with his brother Samuel Samuel, developed a considerable trading operation. Samuel Samuel was resident in Japan for several years, and the brothers had two firms — M. Samuel & Co. in London and Samuel Samuel & Co. in Yokohama, later Kobe. The brothers played an important role in the industrialization of Japan, and before he was thirty, Marcus had made his first fortune out of the trade with Japan. At the time, Marcus and Samuel Samuel were the only British Jews prominent in the trade with the Orient.

Marcus Samuel was always the trader, the idea man, and Samuel Samuel, always the loyal adherent and sidekick. Marcus was the more complicated — short and stout, with heavy eyebrows, totally unprepossessing in appearance. But he was capable of bold vision, adventurous, ingenious, quick to act, and single-minded when he chose to be. He talked in a very soft voice, sometimes hardly audible, making people strain to hear him and perhaps making himself all the more persuasive. He instilled trust in people, so much so that for two decades he depended for his credit not on bankers but on those Scottish merchants in the Far East. Marcus had more on his agenda than simply accumulating wealth — he had a craving for position. As an outsider, a Jew born in the East End, he would put his energies into seeking acceptance for the name Samuel at the highest levels of British society.

Marcus did not believe in overhead — he profoundly disbelieved in it. He operated out of a small office in Houndsditch in the East End, behind which was his warehouse crammed to the ceiling with Japanese vases, imported furniture and silks, seashells and feathers, and every other kind of knickknack. His operating staff was lean — he had virtually no staff at all. He had little capital, depending on the credit extended by the Far Eastern trading houses. He also used the trading houses as his foreign agents. To charter ships, he used the shipping brokerage firm of Lane and Macandrew, whose senior partner, Fred Lane, could frequently be found in the cramped offices off a narrow alley.

### *The Coup of 1892*

Marcus Samuel's entire business experience had conditioned him to be swift in grasping an opportunity, and here with the Rothschilds was an astonishing one. He moved quickly to lay the groundwork with Lane. The two men made a prospecting trip to the Caucasus in 1890. Samuel observed a primitive bulk tanker and saw in a flash that bulk tankers — the ship as a floating bottle — would be much more efficient. Samuel then traveled out to Japan and back through the Far East, seeking to persuade the Scottish trading houses to sign on with his new venture. Without them, he could not go ahead — he needed their cooperation and they would finance the enterprise. They all agreed.

Samuel carried out a study of the opportunity with a meticulous care uncharacteristic of the normally fast-moving trader. But he knew how large the risks were — and the stakes. He recognized there was no point in trying to break into the market unless he and his partners could undersell Standard Oil — or at least avoid being undersold. The campaign would have to be waged in all markets simultaneously; otherwise, Standard Oil would slash prices in markets where Samuel was competing and subsidize the price cuts by raising prices elsewhere. Speed and secrecy were essential.

But exactly how was Samuel to fight? He needed tankers so kerosene could be shipped in tanks rather than cases — greatly reducing shipping costs per gallon. Like Rockefeller with the railroads, Samuel understood the need to master transportation costs. The type of tanker then in operation simply would not do. Samuel needed a new, larger, technologically more advanced tanker — capable of being steam-cleaned and then filled for the return trip with goods from the Orient. He needed guaranteed supplies of kerosene from Batum in sufficient volume and at prices reflecting savings from not having to tin the kerosene. He needed access to the **Suez Canal**, which would cut the voyage by four thousand miles, increasing his competitive advantage against Standard, whose oil traveled to the Far East on sailing ships around the Cape of Good Hope. But the Suez Canal was closed to tankers on safety grounds — Standard's tankers had already been refused. Samuel also required large storage tanks in all major Asian ports, tank cars or wagons to carry kerosene into the hinterlands, and inland depots where bulk shipments could be broken down into receptacles for local wholesale and retail trade. This demanding enterprise, involving detailed long-distance coordination of markets, engineering, and politics, had to be kept as secret as possible.

Samuel found it difficult to work out the actual deal with the Rothschilds and Bnito — they were of two minds: never quite sure whether they wanted to compete with Standard or reach an accommodation. To M. Aron, the Rothschilds' chief oil man, Standard was always "cette puissante compagnie" ("this powerful company") — not to be trifled with.

But finally, in 1891, after long negotiations and in the face of falling prices, Samuel won his contract with the Rothschilds: exclusive rights for nine years, until 1900, to sell Bnito's kerosene east of Suez. That was what he had always been sure he would get, and he had been proceeding at full speed on the other fronts.

Samuel's tankers represented a significant technological advance — capable of being steam-cleaned and filled with food for the return trip, and designed with new safety features for expansion and contraction of kerosene at different temperatures. Opposition quickly arose to allowing Samuel's tankers into the Suez Canal. By the summer of 1891, the press was darkly reporting rumors of a "powerful group of financiers and merchants" under "Hebrew influence" who were trying to take tankers through the Suez Canal. Then, one of the most eminent firms of solicitors in the City of London, **Russell and Arnholz**, launched a strong lobbying campaign against granting permission — including lengthy correspondence with the Foreign Secretary. They refused to reveal their client, but there was hardly any question that the client was **Standard Oil**. Soon, Russell and Arnholz was hastily alerting the British government that if British merchants were permitted to put tankers into the canal, Russian shipping concerns would also win the same right, and if Russian naval officers and seamen got into the canal, they would "undertake all kinds of mischief," including seeking "to block the navigation of the Canal" and "destroy all the shipping in it."

But Samuel had powerful allies in the Rothschild family, whose English branch had financed Benjamin Disraeli's purchase of the Suez Canal shares in 1875, and in the influential French Banque Worms. Moreover, the Foreign Secretary saw the passage of British tankers through the canal as very much in Britain's interest. Lloyds of London rated Samuel's new tanker design safe.

Meanwhile, M. Samuel & Co. had embarked upon a campaign to build storage tanks throughout Asia. The Samuel brothers sent out their nephews, Mark and Joseph Abrahams, to find sites and supervise construction. Joseph had India and Mark the Far East. Mark was paid five pounds a week and was further rewarded by constant long-range interference, carping, criticism, and insults from his uncles. They hammered at him about keeping costs down and speeding up — two quite contrary objectives. When Mark purchased his own secondhand rickshaw, he could not win his uncles' approval. Yet, through it all, Mark was buying sites and building storage tanks throughout the Far East, including one on Freshwater Island, off Singapore, outside the jurisdiction of an obstructionist harbormaster.

On January 5, 1892, the Suez Canal gave its official approval to passage for tankers built to Samuel's new design. "The new scheme is one of singular boldness and great magnitude," the *Economist* commented four days later.

The first tanker was nearing completion at West Hartlespool. It was called the ***Murex*** — named for a type of seashell, as were all of Samuel's subsequent tankers, a memorial to the elder Marcus, the shell merchant. On July 22, 1892, the *Murex* sailed from West Hartlespool for Batum, where it filled its tanks with Bnito's kerosene. On **August 23**, it passed through the Suez Canal, headed for the East. It discharged part of its cargo at Freshwater Island, Singapore; then sailed on to Mark's new installation in Bangkok. **The coup was launched.**

Taken by surprise, Standard's shocked representatives rushed to assess the dangers. The implications were enormous — as the *Economist* noted, "If the sanguine anticipations of the promoters are realized, the Eastern case-oil trade must needs become obsolete." Standard Oil's agents were too late — Samuel's kerosene was everywhere. Standard could not cut prices in one market and subsidize them by raising prices elsewhere.

The coup was indeed brilliant and the execution superb — with one exception. Samuel and the Far Eastern trading houses had committed a small oversight that almost destroyed their venture. They had assumed that eager customers would line up with their own receptacles to be filled. The customers were expected to use old Standard Oil tin cans. But they did not — throughout the Far East, Standard's blue oil tins had become a prized mainstay of local economies, used to construct everything from roofing to birdcages to opium cups, hibachis, tea strainers, and egg beaters. They were not about to give up such a valuable product. A local crisis was created in each port, as the kerosene went unsold, and despairing telegrams began to flow into Houndsditch.

Marcus proved his entrepreneurial genius. He sent out a chartered ship, filled with tinplate, to the Far East, and simply instructed his partners in Asia to begin manufacturing tin receptacles for the kerosene. "How do *you* stick on the wire handles?" the agent in Singapore wrote to Samuel's representative in Japan. Instructions were sent. "What color do you suggest?" cabled the agent in Shanghai. Mark gave the answer — "Red!" All the trading houses quickly established local factories, and throughout Asia, Samuel's bright and shiny **red** receptacles were soon competing with Standard's blue ones, battered and chipped after the long voyage. Perhaps some customers were buying Samuel's kerosene more for the useful red can than for its contents. Red roofs and red birdcages, as well as red opium cups, hibachis, tea strainers, and egg beaters, began to replace the blue.

And so the day was saved. By end of 1893, Samuel had launched ten more ships, all named for seashells — the *Conch*, the *Clam*, the *Elax*, the *Cowrie*, and so on. By 1895, sixty-nine tanker passages had been made through the Suez Canal, all but four in ships owned or chartered by Samuel. By 1902, of all the oil passing through the Suez Canal, 90 percent belonged to Samuel and his group.

### *The Alderman*

Marcus Samuel was not only on the edge of a great success in business; he was also beginning to achieve some station in British life. In 1891, he had taken time off to stand for and win election as an alderman of the City of London. But then in 1893, all seemed for naught — Samuel became seriously ill; his physician diagnosed cancer and gave him no more than six months to live. The prediction proved slightly off — by some thirty-four years. Still, the threat of imminent death motivated Samuel to create a new entity, the **Tank Syndicate**, composed of the Samuel brothers, Fred Lane, and the trading houses of the Far East, sharing all profits and losses on a global basis — necessary if they were to fight Standard Oil in whatever market it chose.

Samuel's fortune accumulated rapidly, from oil and tankers and from the longer-standing trade with the Far East, principally Japan. The Samuel brothers made money as principal provisioners of weapons and supplies to Japan during its 1894-95 war with China. Within a few years of the *Murex*'s first passage through the Suez Canal, Marcus Samuel had become a very rich man, one who went riding every morning in Hyde Park, who owned a splendid country house in Kent called the Mote, with its own five-hundred-acre deer park.

Samuel had, however, one serious fault as a businessman. Unlike his rival, Rockefeller, he **lacked talent for organization and administration**. Where Rockefeller had an instinct for order, Samuel had an addiction to improvisation. Organization was an afterthought; he ran everything out of his hat. He was operating a large steamship line as part of his oil enterprise, yet had no one in his office with any knowledge or experience of managing such an organization. He simply depended upon Fred Lane. The fleet was run out of a small room in Houndsditch with nothing but a table, two chairs, a small wall map of the world, and two clerks.

Compare Rockefeller's owl-like unfathomability, his masklike face, his quiet deliberation, his drawing out of judgment and consensus from the gentlemen in Room 1400, to the violent quarrels — the combat, anger, and recriminations — by which Marcus and Samuel arrived at decisions. Sometimes a clerk would be summoned and while he waited, "the two brothers would always go to the window, their backs to the room, huddled together close, their arms around each other's shoulders, heads bent, talking in low voices, until suddenly they would burst apart in yet another dispute, Mr. Sam with loud and furious cries, Mr. Marcus speaking softly, but both calling each other fool, idiot, imbecile, until suddenly, for no apparent reason, they were in agreement again."

### *"This Struggle to the Death"*

The rapid rise of Russian production, the towering position of Standard Oil, the struggle for established and new markets at a time of increasing supplies — all were factors in what became known as the **Oil Wars**. In the 1890s, there was a continuing struggle involving four rivals: Standard, the Rothschilds, the Nobels, and the other Russian producers. At one moment they would be battling fiercely for markets, cutting prices; at the next, courting one another, trying to apportion the world's markets among themselves; at still the next, exploring mergers and acquisitions. On many occasions, they would be doing all three at the same time, in an atmosphere of great suspicion and mistrust.

In 1892-93, the Nobels, Rothschilds, and Standard came close to bringing virtually all oil production into one system, dividing the world among them. "In my opinion," noted M. Aron of the Rothschilds, "the crisis has reached its end, for everybody, in America and Russia, is exhausted by this struggle to the death that has gone on so long." Baron Alphonse was keen to get matters settled but mortally afraid of publicity. Finally, Libby of Standard Oil assured Baron Alphonse that with so many foreigners visiting America for the Chicago World's Fair, his arrival would not be much noted. After the meeting at 26 Broadway, a Standard executive reported that the Baron was "very courteous and remarkably fluent in English," adding that the Rothschilds would "immediately begin the steps toward control in Russia." But the Baron insisted that Standard bring the American independents into the contract. Despite great effort, slowed by rivalries and a cholera epidemic in Baku, the Rothschilds, joined by the Nobels, did succeed in getting all Russian producers to agree to a common front as a prelude to a grand negotiation with Standard. But despite its 85 to 90 percent control of American oil, Standard could not deliver the critical missing element — the independent American refiners and producers — and the proposed agreement collapsed.

In autumn 1894, Standard launched another worldwide price-cutting campaign. The Rothschilds regarded Samuel as a tool with which to improve their bargaining position with Standard and were very tough in their interpretation of their contract with him. Suspecting that the dissatisfied Samuel could be the weak link, Standard opened negotiations with him, presenting a proposal to buy him out on a far grander scale than usual — his enterprise would become part of Standard Oil, and he would become a director, though free to pursue his civic interests. Altogether, it was a very attractive offer. But Samuel rejected it. He wanted to keep the independent identity of his enterprise and his fleet, flying the flag of M. Samuel and Company, and he wanted it all to remain British.

Standard Oil immediately returned again to the Russian producers, and on **March 14, 1895**, signed the long-sought grand alliance with the Rothschilds and Nobels "on behalf of the petroleum industry of the U.S." and "on behalf of the petroleum industry of Russia." The Americans were to get 75 percent of world export sales, the Russians 25 percent. But the agreement never came into force — apparently because of opposition of the Russian government. Once again, the would-be grand alliance had collapsed. Standard responded with new price-cutting campaigns.

If Standard Oil could not regain control through a grand alliance, there was an alternative — to beat the Russians at their own game by acquiring access to crude much closer to the Asian market, or indeed in Asia itself. Standard's attention turned to **Sumatra**, in the Dutch East Indies, from which the steaming time to Singapore could be measured in hours. And its eyes fell on a Dutch company that, after years of struggle, had successfully carved out a profitable business from the jungles of Sumatra, now beginning to make a sizeable impact on markets throughout Asia with its own brand, **Crown Oil**, opening up the world's third major producing province. It was called **Royal Dutch**.

### *Royal Dutch*

Seepages had been commented upon in the Dutch East Indies for hundreds of years, and small amounts of "earth oil" had been used for relief of "stiffness in the limbs" and other medicinal purposes. By 1865, no fewer than fifty-two oil seepages had been identified through the archipelago. But matters languished.

One day in 1880, **Aeilko Jans Zijlker**, a manager of the East Sumatra Tobacco Company, happened to be visiting a plantation in the marshy coastal strip of Sumatra. While traipsing around during a powerful storm, he took refuge in a darkened, unused tobacco shed. With him was a *mandur*, or native overseer, who lit a torch. Its bright flame caught Zijlker's attention — he thought it must be unusually resinous wood. How had the *mandur* acquired the torch? He replied the torch had been daubed with a mineral wax. For longer than anyone could remember, the locals had been skimming this wax from the surface of small ponds and putting it to many uses, including caulking boats.

The next morning, Zijlker had the *mandur* take him to one of the ponds. He recognized the smell — imported kerosene had been introduced into the islands. He collected a sample and sent it to Batavia for analysis, which yielded between 59 and 62 percent kerosene. Zijlker threw himself wholeheartedly into the venture. His first step was to win a concession from the local Sultan of Langkat — the concession known as **Telaga Said**, in northeast Sumatra, six miles of jungle from the Balaban River. It was not until 1885 that the first successful well was drilled. Progress was slow and Zijlker was continually strapped for cash. But he finally gained prestigious sponsorship from the former head of the central bank of the East Indies and the former governor general. The Dutch king himself, William III, granted use of the title "Royal" in the company name. The **Royal Dutch** company was launched in 1890, and its first stock flotation was oversubscribed four and a half times.

Zijlker was triumphant: "What won't bend must break." But returning to the Far East in autumn 1890, he stopped at Singapore and there he died suddenly. His grave was marked with an inconspicuous monument.

Leadership of the enterprise passed to **Jean Baptiste August Kessler**, born in 1853. Kessler had been a successful trader in the Dutch East Indies, but business reverses sent him back to Holland, broken and in poor health. Royal Dutch offered him a chance to begin again. When he arrived at the drilling site in 1891, he found total chaos — "I do not feel very cheerful about this business. An enormous amount of money has been lost by precipitate action." Working conditions were awful — men labored in water up to their waists, the site ran out of rice, and Chinese workmen had to swim fifteen miles to a village for provisions. Somehow, working both day and night, often racked with fever, the obsessed Kessler forced the pace.

In 1892, a six-mile pipeline linking the wells in the jungle to the refinery on the Balaban River was completed. On February 28, the entire crew gathered nervously to wait for the oil. They counted the minutes. The moment came and went — there was no oil. Depression settled. Kessler, fearing defeat, turned away. But then suddenly they all froze. A "roar as of a mighty storm" announced the arrival of the oil, and it quickly poured "with incredible driving force" into the first still of the Royal Dutch refinery. The crowd burst into cheers, the Dutch flag was raised, and Kessler and the crew toasted the future prosperity of Royal Dutch.

By April 1892 — while Marcus Samuel was preparing to send the *Murex* through the Suez Canal — Kessler had delivered the first few cases of kerosene, christened **Crown Oil**. But financial resources were quickly strained. Kessler managed to secure capital, returned to Telaga Said in 1893 to find the operation in a deplorable state — "Half-heartedness, ignorance, indifference, dilapidation, disorder, and vexation are everywhere apparent." He pushed the operation hard, summing up the danger: **"To stagnate means to liquidate."**

All sorts of obstacles had to be overcome, including the arrival of almost three hundred marauding pirates from another part of Sumatra. Yet Kessler kept pushing: "If things go wrong, my job and my name are gone and perhaps my sacrifices and my extraordinary exertions will be repaid with censure into the bargain. Heaven preserve me from all that misery."

Kessler persevered and succeeded. Within two years, he had increased production sixfold, and Royal Dutch had finally become profitable, even able to pay a dividend. If Royal Dutch were to survive, it needed to establish its own marketing organization throughout the Far East, independent of middlemen. Royal Dutch also began to use tankers and build its own storage tanks. The immediate danger was that Samuel's Tank Syndicate would move too swiftly ahead and gain a hammerlock on the business. But the Dutch government excluded the Tank Syndicate from the ports of the East Indies, telling its own producers that the Tank Syndicate thus "need not be for the time being an object of terror" to the local industry.

Royal Dutch's business was growing at an astonishing pace; between 1895 and 1897, production increased fivefold. Yet Kessler warned that until Royal Dutch could obtain additional concessions, "we must pretend to be poor." He did not want to draw other European and American interests to the East Indies, or to Royal Dutch. His principal worry was Standard Oil, which if too aroused, would wield its potent weapon — price cutting — and push Royal Dutch to the wall.

### *"Dutch Obstacles"*

Royal Dutch could hardly remain invisible. Its rapid growth, along with other producers in Asia, created new distress for Standard Oil, matching that already created by the Russian producers. Standard investigated all options. Early on, it began negotiating for a concession in Sumatra, but gave that up in the wake of a native revolt. It searched for production from China and Sakhalin to California.

In 1897, Standard dispatched two representatives to Asia to assess what could be done. They met Royal Dutch's local manager, visited installations, called on Dutch government officials, gathered intelligence from homesick American drillers. The representatives warned 26 Broadway against a "promiscuous search through such an enormous expanse" of steaming jungle. Much better to buy existing production and establish a partnership with an authentic Dutch enterprise. Standard's objective, they insisted, should be to "assimilate" the successful companies — and that meant, above all, Royal Dutch.

Standard's agents were impressed by everything about Royal Dutch — Kessler's leadership, the favorable economics, the new marketing system. "In the whole history of the oil business, there has never been anything more phenomenal than the success and rapid growth of the R. D. Co." When the Standard Oil men said good-bye to the Royal Dutch managers in Sumatra, there was something almost wistful: "Would not it be a pity that two such big concerns as you and we own should not go together."

Samuel's syndicate was also hungrily eyeing Royal Dutch. In late 1896 and early 1897, intense discussions took place between the two groups. But their objectives were quite different — Royal Dutch wanted a joint marketing arrangement; Marcus and Samuel Samuel wanted to buy out Royal Dutch. After one visit to the Dutch directors in The Hague, Sam wrote to Marcus: "A Dutchman sits and says nothing till he gets what he wants but of course in this case he won't." Yet Marcus and Kessler maintained a friendly relationship despite their competition.

Standard Oil knew such discussions were going on, and could not be confident that they would not lead to some kind of powerful combination arrayed against it. "Every day makes the situation more serious and dangerous to handle. If we don't get control of the situation soon, the Russians, Rothschilds, or some other party may." In summer 1897, W. H. Libby presented Kessler and Royal Dutch with a formal proposal: the capital would be quadrupled, with Standard taking all additional shares. Standard, Libby stressed, had no intention of getting Royal Dutch "into its power" — it was "only seeking a favorable capital investment." Kessler could hardly believe Libby or the sincerity of his pledge. On Kessler's strong recommendation, Royal Dutch's board rejected the offer.

Standard, disappointed, began discussions about acquiring another concession, but both Dutch government officials and Royal Dutch successfully intervened. "Dutch obstacles are about the most difficult in the World for Americans to remove," a Standard Oil official declared, "for Americans are always in a hurry and Dutchmen never." Still, Royal Dutch did not feel secure. Its directors knew how Standard operated — buying up shares quietly and then putting competitors out of action. To forestall this, the directors of Royal Dutch created a special class of preference stock, the holders of which controlled the board. Admission to this exclusive rank was by invitation only. One of Standard's agents unhappily reported that Royal Dutch would never merge with the American company. It was not merely a "sentimental barrier" on the part of the Dutch; the managers of Royal Dutch greatly enjoyed receiving 15 percent of the company's profits.

### *Samuel as Lord Mayor — Distracted from Oil*

Marcus Samuel achieved his great ambition in November 1902, becoming Lord Mayor of London — the first Jewish Lord Mayor since the 1870s. Deterding attended the inauguration but distanced himself from the event, derisively writing to a colleague: "I certainly should not think it worth a white tie to attend a second time. The Lord Mayor's show was very fine, according to the view here, but in Dutch eyes it was more like the ceremonial parade of [a] circus."

Samuel was consumed by ceremonial duties — receptions, speeches, official trips, interviewing every lunatic to be certified insane at the Mansion House. He spent almost a month before turning back to oil business, and even then was continually pulled away. The strain was immense: ill health, constant headaches, and he had to have all his teeth removed.

On the last Saturday of December 1902, after a whirlwind of funerals, plays, military displays, and city business, Samuel finally turned to private business — only to find a devastating letter from Fred Lane, his old friend and partner, resigning from Shell's board. Lane launched a bitter critique of how Marcus Samuel ran his company: "You are, and have always been, too much occupied to be at the head of such a business. There seems only one idea: sink capital, create a great bluster, and trust to providence. Such a happy-go-lucky frame of mind in business I have never seen before. ... Business like this cannot be conducted by an occasional glance in one's spare time, or by some brilliant *coup* from time to time. It is steady, treadmill work." Unless "some very radical change is made," Lane prophesied, "the bubble will burst." The breach could not be healed; Lane left the board with lasting bitterness on both sides.

### *Asiatic Petroleum — Deterding Triumphs*

Meanwhile, the Asiatic Petroleum Company was still being constructed. Disputes over control and policy continued. Deterding was so intent on getting his way that he was driven into "a state of unreasonable rage and unreasoning venom" that was "close to dementia." He was unwilling to compromise: "I am feeling entirely fit and able to withstand ten Lord Mayors."

By May 1903, ten contracts established Asiatic, owned equally in thirds by Royal Dutch, Shell, and the Rothschilds. It would regulate East Indies production, carry out Far East sales, and control East Indies gasoline and kerosene sales in Europe. The greatest achievement for Deterding: Royal Dutch emerged paramount in every part of the agreement. The managing director of Asiatic would also be the managing director of Royal Dutch — Henri Deterding. Samuel wanted the term limited to three years; Deterding insisted on "Twenty-one years and not a day less," which was another way of saying permanent. He won on that too.

The first Asiatic board meeting took place in July 1903, with Samuel in the chairman's seat. Deterding, speaking without notes, seemed to know where every ship was, its destination, its cargo, and the prices awaiting it in each port. Samuel was much impressed.

### *"The Group" — Samuel Surrenders*

Deterding threw himself into the new enterprise with irrepressible energy. "It so happens that in the oil business one has to seize one's opportunities quickly; otherwise, they escape." He was a calculated risk taker, not a gambler. Royal Dutch quickly assimilated most independent producers in the East Indies, where the oil was particularly suited to gasoline manufacture. Under Deterding's bullwhip, Asiatic won an important share of the growing European gasoline market as automobiles became familiar sights on roads.

Things were getting progressively worse for Shell. Texas supplies from Spindletop had given out. The British Admiralty refused to take seriously Samuel's vision for fuel oil for the Royal Navy. Royal Dutch discovered Borneo crudes suitable for fuel oil, shattering Samuel's hoped monopoly. Standard's price wars continued. Fred Lane, now deputy managing director of Asiatic, used his position to settle scores against Shell. Shell could barely pay 5 percent dividends, while Royal Dutch's were at 65 percent, then 50 percent, then an immensely satisfying 73 percent in 1905.

In winter 1906, Robert Waley Cohen, Samuel's most talented employee, told him the truth: a consolidated marketing company was insufficient — the only way Shell could survive was to amalgamate completely with Royal Dutch on the best terms available. The idea devastated Samuel. He raised the issue with Deterding. On what basis? "Fifty-fifty," said Samuel. "Absolutely not," said Deterding. The days of "British Dutch" were past; the ratio would have to be sixty for Royal Dutch and forty for Shell. "The property and interests of Shell would henceforth be managed by a foreigner!" Samuel protested.

After several months with no improvement in Shell's position, Samuel was forced to return. Deterding offered only one guarantee: Royal Dutch would buy a quarter of Shell's shares, giving it a shareholder's interest in Shell's welfare. Samuel asked for time. Deterding refused: "I am at present in a generous mood. I have made you this offer, but if you leave this room without accepting it, the offer is off." Samuel accepted. His struggle with Deterding had gone on for half a decade. It was over. Deterding had won.

The union was cemented in 1907, creating the **Royal Dutch/Shell Group**, sometimes simply known as "the Group." All oil production and refining assets were lodged in a Dutch company, Bataafsche Petroleum Maatschappij; all transport and storage in an English company, Anglo-Saxon Petroleum Company. Royal Dutch held 60 percent of the stock in operating subsidiaries and Shell 40 percent. There was no Royal Dutch/Shell board and no legal entity called Royal Dutch/Shell. The "Committee of Managing Directors" had no specific legal status but was composed of active members of the boards of the two holding companies.

### *The Three Leaders of Royal Dutch/Shell*

Three men ran all parts of the business. **Henri Deterding** was first — the business side, constantly traveling and negotiating. **Hugo Loudon**, the Dutch engineer who had rescued Royal Dutch with new discoveries when initial wells gave out, focused on the technical side. **Robert Waley Cohen**, young Cambridge chemistry graduate who had gone to work for Marcus Samuel in 1901, was Deterding's de facto commercial deputy — making decisions in Deterding's absences, bucking Deterding when the Dutchman had misgivings.

Samuel initially regarded himself as a failure. "I am a disappointed man," he told newspaper reporters. He treated himself to a 650-ton yacht. But the humiliation healed quickly. Deterding consulted Samuel, made him much richer, and spoke of him as "our chairman." By 1908, Samuel was telling Shell stockholders that Deterding was "nothing less than a genius." Samuel presided for over a decade as chairman, grew even more wealthy, became an engaged philanthropist, and promoted fuel oil for shipping. But there was never any question: Deterding was the boss.

### *"To America!"*

The 1907 amalgamation meant the world oil market was now dominated by two giants: Standard Oil and the Royal Dutch/Shell Group. "If the Standard had tried to wipe us out three years ago, they'd have succeeded," Deterding said in 1910, "Now things are different." He made a pilgrimage to 26 Broadway seeking conciliation, but encountered only an offer to buy Royal Dutch/Shell for $100 million. "I am sorry to have to place on record that my visit to this city ... has been so useless," was his acid response.

Standard replied with a new price-cutting campaign and established a Dutch subsidiary to seek oil concessions in southern Sumatra. The Group had no choice but to counterattack: **"To America!"** became the slogan between 1910 and 1914. If not active in America, the Group would always be vulnerable to Standard's price cutting — Standard could sell surplus at cut-rate prices in Europe while maintaining higher domestic prices.

Deterding moved in two directions: the West Coast (marketing Sumatra gasoline in 1912, then California production in 1913) and the mid-continent. He sent **Mark Abrahams** — Marcus Samuel's nephew, fresh from launching an oil exploration company in Egypt — to Tulsa in July 1912. Abrahams arrived with his own typewriter (in case there were none) and $2,500 in a money belt (in case there were no reputable banks) in the boom town already proclaiming itself "the Oil Capital of the World." He acquired several small oil companies and incorporated them into **Roxana Petroleum**. Deterding sent a jubilant letter to Loudon: "At last we *are* in America!"

### *Russia in Turmoil*

Events soon proved the Royal Dutch/Shell amalgamation wise, given Shell's dependence on Russian oil. Russia's economy had grown under **Count Sergei Witte**, the powerful finance minister from 1892 to 1903, who oversaw rapid industrialization fueled by foreign capital. Conservative critics attacked his program; the Minister of War complained of "too hurried development" by "foreign capitalists, foreign capital, and Jews."

**Czar Nicholas II** was highly vulnerable to flattery, and he and his court descended into mysticism, "imported mediums and home-bred 'idiots' passing as saints." Witte prophetically noted the Czar could "not relinquish his 'Byzantine' habits" and "inasmuch as he does not possess the talents of either Metternich or Talleyrand, he usually lands in a mud puddle — or in a pool of blood."

Nicholas II was contemptuous of non-Russian minorities and sanctioned repression that turned them into rebels. By the early 1900s, the empire was in turmoil. The Caucasus — home of the Russian oil industry — was one of the worst-run parts. Workers in Baku had no families, working fourteen hours with two hours compulsory overtime.

Baku became the "revolutionary hotbed on the Caspian." A secret printing operation called **"Nina"** — hidden in a large cellar under the Tatar quarter — printed Lenin's revolutionary paper *Iskra*, smuggled from Europe via Persia. The oil industry's distribution system provided a perfect vehicle for clandestinely distributing propaganda. Baku's oil fields also provided training ground for future Bolshevik leaders: future Soviet President **Mikhail Kalinin**, future marshal **Klementi Voroshilov**, and most importantly, a young Georgian seminarian, son of a shoemaker, named **Joseph Djugashvili** — who operated underground as "Koba" (Turkish for "Indomitable") and later became **Joseph Stalin**.

In 1901-1902, Stalin became the chief socialist organizer in Batum, masterminding strikes against the Rothschilds' interests. He was arrested eight times, repeatedly escaping exile. In 1903, Baku oil workers went on strike, setting off a wave culminating in the first general strike in the empire. Marcus Samuel, the Rothschilds, and others worried about their dependence on Russia.

### *Russo-Japanese War and Revolution of 1905*

The Czarist regime sought diversion through foreign adventure, choosing war with Japan over Manchuria and Korea. "Russia's internal situation required something drastic," said the Minister of Interior. "We need a little victorious war to stem the tide of revolution."

The Russo-Japanese War began in January 1904 with Japan's surprise attack at Port Arthur. Russia lurched from one disaster to the next, culminating in the burial at sea of the entire fleet at the Battle of Tsushima. In December 1904, Baku oil workers struck again and won their first collective labor agreement. Days later, revolutionaries proclaimed "Workers of the Caucasus, the hour of revenge has struck" — authored by Stalin. The next day, Bloody Sunday: police fired on workers marching to the Winter Palace. This was the beginning of the Revolution of 1905 — what Lenin called the Great Rehearsal.

Government officials, fearful of revolution, provided arms to the Moslem Tatars, who rose up to massacre Christian Armenians, including leaders of the oil industry. One wealthy Armenian, Adamoff, stationed himself on his balcony with his son, held off a siege for three days, until killed when the house was set on fire. In September-October 1905, Tatars attacked the oil industry throughout Baku, setting fire to buildings, pillaging. "The flames from the burning derricks and oil wells leaped up into the awful pall of smoke which hung over the inferno." At two in the afternoon, the smoke was so thick the sun could not be seen. Then, an earthquake shook the entire region.

The impact was profound: for the first time, violent upheaval had interrupted the flow of oil, threatening to make vast investments worthless. Standard Oil quickly recaptured Far East markets formerly lost to Russian kerosene. **Two-thirds of all Russian oil wells had been destroyed** and exports collapsed.

By end of 1905, the revolution was spent. The Russo-Japanese War was mediated by Theodore Roosevelt at Portsmouth. In October 1905, the Czar grudgingly granted a constitutional government with a Parliament (the Duma). The oil region remained in turmoil — Baku elected Bolshevik deputies; Nobel's chief in Batum was murdered. The Bolsheviks sent Stalin back to Baku in 1907, where he fomented "unlimited distrust of the oil industrialists" among workers. In 1910, he was arrested again and exiled. "It was in Baku that he had honed the revolutionary and conspiratorial skills — and the ambition and cynicism — that would help make his future."

### *Return to Russia — Rothschilds Sell Out*

Chaotic drilling and political instability had led to deterioration in Russian production capacity. Operating costs rose sharply. The government unwisely raised transport tariffs, making Russian oil even less competitive. Its price advantage had turned into a disadvantage. Russian oil was increasingly a residual, bought only when other petroleum was unavailable.

A new source emerged in Europe: **Rumania**, where hand-dug pits on the Carpathian slopes had long produced minuscule supply. In the 1890s, Hungarian and Austrian bank investment combined with modern technology dramatically increased production. Standard Oil, the Deutsche Bank, and Royal Dutch entered Rumania, and output grew sevenfold in the first decade of the twentieth century. Deutsche Bank, with its Rumanian production, joined the Nobels and Rothschilds in 1906 to form the **European Petroleum Union (EPU)**, which negotiated market division agreements with Standard Oil — the EPU getting 20-25 percent of various European markets, Standard getting the rest.

The **Rothschilds wanted out** of Russia. Anti-Semitism, political instability, strikes, arson, murder — and profits were now low or nonexistent. All their oil assets depended on Russian production with no international diversification. In 1911, they began negotiating with Royal Dutch/Shell. Fred Lane represented the Rothschilds: "I can assure you to get Deterding to do something is not an easy task. His habit is to allow things to remain as open as possible and he sits like an owl upon it thinking it over." By 1912, the deal was done — the Group paid the Rothschilds in stock of both Royal Dutch and Shell, making them among the largest shareholders. The Rothschilds transformed uncertain Russian assets into substantial holdings in a diversified international company.

Deterding's motive was pure: "his intention was to make money." Overnight, the Group became a major force in Russia, controlling at least a fifth of entire Russian production. The acquisition gave the Group a globally balanced portfolio: **53 percent from the East Indies, 17 percent from Rumania, and 29 percent from Russia.** Between 1904 and 1913, Russia's share of world petroleum exports dropped from 31 to 9 percent. Stalin later reflected: "Three years of revolutionary work among the workers of the oil industry tempered me as a practical fighter... There in Baku I received, thus, my second baptism in revolutionary combat. There I became a journeyman for the revolution."

## Chapter 7: "Beer and Skittles" in Persia

A dapper gentleman from Persia, **Antoine Kitabgi**, carrying the title of general, arrived in Paris toward the end of 1900. Variously said to be of Armenian or Georgian origin, Kitabgi had held several positions in the Persian government, including director general of customs. He was, said a British diplomat, "well versed in Western matters — being able to draw up a concession and initiate commercial movements." The ostensible reason for his visit was the opening of a Persian Exhibition in Paris, but his real purpose was to find an investor willing to assume a petroleum concession in Persia. The Persian government desperately needed money; the reason was "the Shah's prodigality."

### *"A Capitalist of the Highest Order"*

In Paris, Kitabgi sought the aid of a retired British diplomat, who reported back: "Concerning the oil, I have spoken to a capitalist of the highest order, who declares himself disposed to examine the affair." The capitalist was **William Knox D'Arcy**. Born in Devon, England, in 1849, D'Arcy had emigrated to Australia, became a solicitor, developed a passion for horse racing, and took a flyer on an old gold mine. The mine turned out to be very rich in gold, making D'Arcy extremely wealthy. He returned to England, married a prominent actress named Nina Boucicault who entertained lavishly (Enrico Caruso came to sing at their dinner parties), maintained two estates, and had the only private box at the Epsom racing track aside from the royal box. He was an investor and speculator, not a manager, and was looking for a new investment.

Oil seepages had been noted for centuries in Persia. In 1872 and 1889, **Baron Julius de Reuter**, founder of the Reuters news agency, had obtained Persian concessions for oil development, but both ended in failure — generating great protest within Persia and opposition from Imperial Russia. In the 1890s, a French geologist published reports pointing to considerable oil potential. Kitabgi, eager to ensnare D'Arcy, promised "the presence of a source of riches incalculable as to extension."

On March 25, 1901, D'Arcy's representative left Paris, arriving in Tehran via Baku on April 16. Negotiations proceeded slowly; D'Arcy's man passed the time buying rugs and embroidery. Kitabgi "secured in a very thorough manner the support of all the Shah's principal Ministers and courtiers, not even forgetting the personal servant who brings His Majesty his pipe and morning coffee."

### *Russia Versus Britain*

Persia could claim a national identity stretching to the ancient empire of Cyrus the Great and Darius I, which by the fifth century B.C. stretched from India to modern Greece and Libya. The Parthian empire became the redoubtable eastern rival of the Roman empire. Wave after wave of armies — Alexander the Great from the West, Genghis Khan and the Mongols from the East — passed through. At the end of the eighteenth century, the Qajar dynasty won control over a fragmented country of contending principalities and tribal confederacies. The Qajar shahs ruled uneasily for a century and a half, subject to diplomatic and commercial competition between Russia and Britain for dominance.

Lord Curzon, Viceroy of India, described Persia as one of "the pieces on a chessboard upon which is being played out a game for the domination of the world." Beginning in the 1860s, Russia had embarked on a relentless drive of expansion in Central Asia. To Britain, Russia's expansion was a direct threat to India and routes thereto. In 1885, Russia attacked neighboring Afghanistan, nearly precipitating war with Britain.

Russia renewed its pressure on Persia around 1900. The British sought to keep Persia intact as a buffer between Russia and India. The Shah, **Muzaffar al-Din**, was "merely an elderly child" and "the Persian monarchy itself was an old, long-mismanaged estate, ready to be knocked down at once to whatever Foreign Power bid highest." Hardinge feared "the Shah and his ministers were in a state of complete vassalage to Russia, owing to their own reckless extravagance and folly." The Russians wanted political dominion, not trade: "What interest do we have in trading with seven or eight million lazy ragamuffins?"

A British oil concession would assist in righting the balance against Russia. Britain gave its support to D'Arcy's venture. When the Russian minister found out, he angrily sought to block negotiations. But D'Arcy's man threw another five thousand pounds onto the table — "the Shah wanted some ready money and stood out for some on signing the concession." On **May 28, 1901**, Shah Muzaffar al-Din signed the historic agreement: twenty thousand pounds in cash, another twenty thousand pounds' worth of shares, and 16 percent of "annual net profits." D'Arcy received a concession for sixty years covering three-quarters of the country.

D'Arcy had deliberately excluded the five northern provinces, closest to Russia, to "give no umbrage to Russia." But the Russians sought to build a pipeline from Baku to the Persian Gulf to expand kerosene exports and project strategic influence. Hardinge warned the "preposterous" concession for a pipeline, even if never built, would "afford an excuse for covering Southern Persia with surveyors, engineers and protecting detachments of Cossacks, preparing a veiled military occupation." The British opposition succeeded; the pipeline was not built.

### *The D'Arcy Concession — "Wild-Catting on a Colossal Scale"*

What drew D'Arcy to such a risky enterprise — "wild-catting on a colossal scale in a distant unsettled land"? The irresistible lure of immense wealth, the chance to become another Rockefeller. He had gambled before on the Australian gold mine with tremendous success. But this was a vast gamble on a much grander scale, with many more players and a political/social dimension absent in Australia. D'Arcy had been advised it would cost ten thousand pounds to drill two wells. Within four years, he was out of pocket in excess of two hundred thousand pounds.

### *The First Go*

D'Arcy had no organization, only a secretary. He hired **George Reynolds**, a graduate of the Royal Indian Engineering College with drilling experience in Sumatra. The first site was **Chiah Surkh**, an inaccessible plateau in the mountains of northwestern Persia, near what would later become the Iran-Iraq border, three hundred miles from the Persian Gulf. The entire country had barely eight hundred miles of road. Large parts were ruled by warring tribes that hardly recognized Tehran's authority. Persian Army commanders would rent out their soldiers as gardeners to local landowners and pocket the wages.

The population lacked technical skills, and the culture was hostile toward Western ideas. In his memoirs, Hardinge discussed the dominant Shia sect's religious zeal, resistance to political authority, and fierce antagonism toward all outsiders. "The hatred of the Shiahs for the first four Caliphs was, and is still, so strong" that some sought to "hasten their own entrance into Paradise by defiling the tombs of these usurpers." He discussed the doctrine of 'Ketman' or pious dissimulation "which renders it lawful for a good Moslem to appear to dissemble or even lie, for a really pious purpose."

Each piece of equipment had to be shipped to Basra on the Persian Gulf, transshipped three hundred miles up the Tigris to Baghdad, then carried by man and mule over the Mesopotamian plain and through the mountains. Reynolds and his motley crew of Poles, Canadians, and Azeris from Baku struggled to assemble the machinery. To the Azeris, even the introduction of the wheelbarrow was a startling innovation.

D'Arcy telegraphed from London: "Delay serious. Pray expedite." Actual drilling commenced at end of 1902. Equipment kept breaking, insects were incessant, food and parts supply was a constant problem. The "infernal heat" in workers' quarters reached 120 degrees. The work camp had a separate "Mohamedan Kitchen" for local dignitaries who all seemed "very keen on receiving a substantial present from us, especially in the shape of some shares of our Company." Reynolds had to be a diplomat dealing with petty feuds and open warfare between tribes. "The Mullahs in the North are exciting the population as much as they can against the foreigners. The real fight is now between the Shah and the Mullahs for the control of the public affairs."

### *"Every Purse Has Its Limits"*

In October 1903, eleven months after drilling began, there were the first shows of oil. But D'Arcy discovered this was far more difficult and expensive than imagined: "Every purse has its limit, and I can see the limits of my own." He needed to be bailed out or the concession would be lost.

D'Arcy applied to the British Admiralty for a loan, inspired by **Thomas Boverton Redwood**, the "*eminence grise* of British oil policy before the First World War." Immaculately dressed with an orchid in his buttonhole, often mistaken for a leading actor, Redwood was Britain's premier oil expert — his consulting firm was used by almost every British oil company. He published *A Treatise on Petroleum* (1896), the standard work for the next two decades. He saw the advantages of burning fuel oil rather than coal in the Royal Navy and wanted oil reserves under British control.

Redwood brought D'Arcy's plight to the Admiralty's Fuel Oil Committee. D'Arcy had spent £160,000 on exploration with at least another £120,000 to be expected. He was told to expect in return an Admiralty contract for fuel oil. Both the Admiralty and Foreign Office supported the loan, but the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Austen Chamberlain, thought the House of Commons would never approve it. He turned it down.

D'Arcy was desperate: "It is all I can do to keep the bank quiet and something *must* be done." By end of 1903, he was overdrawn £177,000 at Lloyds Bank and had to put up shares in his Australian gold mine as collateral. In mid-January 1904, the second well at Chiah Surkh turned into a producer. "Glorious news from Persia — the greatest relief to me." But discovery alone was not enough; tens of thousands of pounds more would be required.

D'Arcy tried Joseph Lyons and Company, Standard Oil, and visited Baron Alphonse de Rothschild in Cannes — but the Rothschilds had enough to do with their new links to Shell and Royal Dutch. The flow at Chiah Surkh shrank to a trickle. By April 1904, D'Arcy's overdraft had increased further, Lloyds was demanding the concession itself as security. Less than three years after its inception, the Persian venture was on the verge of collapse.

### *The "Syndicate of Patriots"*

The Treasury's rejection alarmed the Foreign Office. Lord Lansdowne expressed concern that "there is danger of whole petroleum concession in Persia falling thus under Russian control." Hardinge concurred — the Russians might gain control and use it to expand their reach. British majority control should be maintained at all costs.

D'Arcy's visit to the Rothschilds, with the threat the concession might pass under French control, galvanized the Admiralty. The chairman of the Fuel Oil Committee wrote D'Arcy asking that before making any foreign deals, he allow the Admiralty to arrange acquisition by a British syndicate. Lord Lansdowne had risen in the House of Lords in May 1903 to declare: "The British government would regard the establishment of a naval base or of a fortified port in the Persian Gulf by any other power as a very grave menace to British interests, and we should certainly resist it with all the means at our disposal." Lord Curzon called this "our Monroe Doctrine in the Middle East."

**Lord Strathcona**, an eighty-four-year-old self-made millionaire, was asked to become head of a "syndicate of patriots." He agreed not for commercial reasons "but really from an imperial point of view." The partner was **Burmah Oil**, founded by Scottish merchants in 1886 in Glasgow, which had transformed primitive oil gathering by Burmese villagers into a commercial industry with a refinery in Rangoon. The cautious Scottish merchants had very practical questions — could Persia be considered under British protection? The impatient D'Arcy invited Burmah's vice-chairman to watch the Epsom Derby from his private box near the winning post. The rich food and drink so upset the vice-chairman's liver that he was sick four times in the next few weeks and never again accepted an invitation from D'Arcy.

Finally, in 1905, almost exactly four years after the concession was initialed, D'Arcy and Burmah agreed. The **Concession Syndicate** was established; D'Arcy's operation became a subsidiary and D'Arcy became a director. Burmah provided new capital and management expertise. As the historian of Burmah Oil put it, D'Arcy's needs "coincided exactly with those of the Foreign Office, anxious about the route to India, and of the Admiralty, seeking reliable fuel oil supplies." Henceforth profit and politics would be inextricably linked in Persia.

### *To the Fire Temple: Masjid-i-Suleiman*

The Concession Syndicate shifted exploration to southwestern Persia. Under Reynolds's direction, wells at Chiah Surkh were plugged, the camp closed, and some forty tons of equipment dismantled, carried back to Baghdad, shipped down the Tigris to Basra, then transshipped to the Iranian port of Mohammerah. Eventually it would be shipped by river, wagon, and mules (as many as nine hundred) to new sites. Drilling first commenced at Shardin.

But there was another potential site: **Maidan-i-Naftan**, "the Plain of Oil." The specific spot, **Masjid-i-Suleiman**, was named for a nearby fire temple. Reynolds had first visited this roadless spot in late November 1903, feeling dispirited and ready to pack it all in, when he encountered a British official, **Louis Dane**, in Kuwait. Dane was traveling with Lord Curzon to celebrate the Lansdowne Declaration and was compiling a gazetteer of the Gulf. He had come across several references to Maidan-i-Naftan that reminded him of Baku. At Dane's strong urging — "it seems a thousand pities to turn up what may be an immense national benefit" — Reynolds set off for Maidan-i-Naftan. In February 1904, he reported rocks saturated with oil. In 1906, he returned and found even more extensive indications. Boverton Redwood called it the most important and promising information to date.

The operation at Masjid-i-Suleiman was "not all beer and skittles," Reynolds informed Burmah managers in Glasgow. Drinking water was "best described as water with dung in suspension." The nearest dentist was fifteen hundred miles away in Karachi. Workers could find relief closer to home at what was euphemistically called the "dentist" — a mere 150 miles away in Basra.

**George Reynolds** was the man who held it all together. Around fifty when he arrived in Persia in September 1901, he was at one and the same time engineer, geologist, manager, diplomat, linguist, and anthropologist. He had a knack for jerry-rigging machinery when parts broke. He was taciturn, tough, and tenacious. Arnold Wilson described him as "dignified in negotiation, quick in action, and completely single-minded in his determination to find oil. In short, Reynolds was 'solid British oak.'" But his true bane was not the desert nor the tribesmen — it was Burmah Oil in Glasgow, which constantly second-guessed him. Reynolds responded with "searing and impolitic sarcasm": "You really amuse me by instructing me how to run a contumacious Parsee and an alcoholic driller, both suffering from swelled heads."

### *Revolution in Tehran*

The Shah's government was in advanced decay, and foreigners' concessions were a major political sore. Conservative religious opponents led the attack on despotism, joining merchants seeking liberal reforms. In July 1906, riots erupted when the government attempted to arrest a prominent preacher. As many as fourteen thousand Persians took to the streets and sought refuge in the garden of the British legation. The result was a new constitution and a Majlis (Parliament), which put investigation of the concession at the top of its agenda. But the new political system proved unstable.

The new drilling site was in the winter grazing pasture of the **Bakhtiari**, the most powerful tribal confederacy. They were nomads, driving flocks of sheep and goats, living in goat-hair tents. In 1905, Reynolds made an arrangement with some Bakhtiari — in exchange for a fee and profit share, they would provide "guards" for the concession. But among the main things to be guarded against were the Bakhtiaris themselves. Reynolds described one Bakhtiari leader as "a man as full of intrigue as the egg of a nightingale is pregnant with music." D'Arcy could only complain, "Of course Baksheesh is at the root of it all."

The Foreign Office dispatched a guard force — a total of two British officers and twenty Indian cavalry. In 1907, the Anglo-Russian Convention partitioned Persia into spheres of influence: northern Persia under Russian sway, the southeast under British, and the middle a neutral zone — which happened to be the location of the new drilling sites.

### *Racing the Clock*

Masjid-i-Suleiman was "the last throw of the concessionary dice." There was no road; one had to be carved from the desert. A torrential rain wiped out most of a half-year's effort. Finally, in January 1908, drilling began at this last site.

Burmah Oil was most unhappy. Its vice-chairman suggested "the whole thing" might "go smash." In April 1908, the Burmah board told D'Arcy the money was exhausted and unless he put up half of additional funds, work would stop. "Of course, I cannot find £20,000 or anything," D'Arcy complained. But he shrewdly concluded Burmah was too committed to back out, and simply ignored their April 30 deadline.

On May 14, 1908, Burmah sent a letter to Reynolds saying the project was over and he should be prepared to pack up. The letter instructed Reynolds to carry the two wells down to no more than sixteen hundred feet. If no oil was found, he was to "abandon operations, close down, and bring as much of the plant as is possible down to Mohammerah." The end of the Concession Syndicate seemed near. But the letter was not received in Persia for several weeks — just the delay Reynolds needed.

Excitement at the drilling site was mounting. A smell of natural gas could be detected. Then a drill bit came unscrewed and was lost in the hole; several days were spent fishing for it in temperatures reaching no degrees in the shade. Vaporous gas could clearly be seen rising from the hole. On the night of **May 25, 1908**, Arnold Wilson went to sleep outside his tent because of the heat. Shortly after 4:00 a.m. on the twenty-sixth, he was awakened by shouting. A gusher of petroleum, rising perhaps fifty feet above the top of the drilling rig, was smothering the drillers. The accompanying gas was threatening to suffocate the workers.

**Oil had, at last, been struck in Persia.** It was just two days short of seven years since the Shah had signed the concession. According to legend, Wilson sent the news in code: "See Psalm 104 verse 15 third sentence." The Bible reads: "that he may bring out of the earth oil to make a cheerful countenance." D'Arcy was delighted but kept his enthusiasm in check: "I am telling no one about it until I get the news confirmed." Three weeks later, the first well continued to gush, and oil was struck in the second well. Around this time, Reynolds received the May 14 letter from Burmah ordering him to wind down — a striking echo of the letter half a century earlier that had told Colonel Drake to quit at Titusville. Reynolds had already sent a cable back: "The instructions you say you are sending me may be modified by the fact that oil has been struck, so on receipt of them I can hardly act on them."

Reynolds remained in Persia a couple more years but was unceremoniously fired in January 1911 despite D'Arcy trying to protect him. Arnold Wilson offered an epitaph: "He was able to endure heat and cold, disappointment and success, and to get the best out of every Persian, Indian, and European with whom he came in contact, except his Scottish employers, whose short-sighted parsimony had so nearly wrecked a great enterprise."

### *The "Big Company": Anglo-Persian*

On April 19, 1909, the Glasgow branch of the Bank of Scotland was mobbed by fevered investors. The newly incorporated **Anglo-Persian Oil Company** was going public. The public stood ten deep at the counter, clutching application forms. The Admiralty objected to the draft prospectus's "making public" its encouragement of Burmah's stake: "As the Admiralty is our prospective good customer, we cannot afford to stamp on their corns." Mrs. D'Arcy, with theatrical flair, protested the omission of her husband's name from the company's title: "This, I think, a great mistake as far and wide his name is associated with this Persian business. I am making a last bid for fame to you."

D'Arcy came out well — he received shares worth £895,000 (£30 million or $55 million today). But he lamented: "I feel like signing away a child." D'Arcy became a director but his influence faded. He died in 1917; the company merely kept "D'Arcy" for an exploration subsidiary.

Anglo-Persian quickly became a significant company — by end of 1910, it already employed 2,500 people. Arnold Wilson, acting consul in the region, became the de facto adviser on local affairs: "I have spent a fortnight upon Oil Company business, mediating between Englishmen who cannot always say what they mean and Persians who do not always mean what they say."

A 138-mile pipeline, crossing two ranges of hills and a desert plain — its route initially marked by sticks and calico flags — was built in a year and a half using six thousand mules. The refinery site was **Abadan**, a long narrow island of mud flats and palm trees in the Shatt-al-Arab estuary. The laborers were mainly Indians from Burmah's Rangoon refinery, and the construction was badly done. On its first test in July 1912, the refinery immediately broke down, thereafter operating far below capacity with poor-quality kerosene that had a "yellowish tinge and filmed up lamps."

In October 1912, Anglo-Persian made a deal with Asiatic (Royal Dutch/Shell's trading arm) — Anglo-Persian would sell crude, gasoline, and kerosene through Asiatic but reserved the rights to its fuel oil, on which it was basing its strategy for future growth. Shell wanted to contain any new threats: "the situation of these people, apparently with very large supplies, made them rather a serious menace in the East."

But Anglo-Persian was in deep financial trouble again. By end of 1912, working capital was exhausted. John Cargill, chairman of Burmah Oil: "What a hell of a mess Persian things are in. It's all very well to say 'don't worry,' but my name and business reputation are too closely associated with the Anglo-Persian Oil Company to admit of my not being terribly anxious." Millions of pounds were needed, with no obvious way to get new capital. Without an infusion, the effort might grind to a stop or be swallowed by Royal Dutch/Shell. A new savior would have to be found.

## Chapter 8: The Fateful Plunge

In July 1903, during one of his many moments of despair, D'Arcy had taken himself to the spa at Marienbad, in Bohemia. His spirits were lifted by an acquaintance he made — **Admiral John Fisher**, then the Second Sea Lord, already known as the "oil maniac." That chance meeting would eventually push oil to the center of national strategies.

### *"The God-father of Oil"*

**John Arbuthnot Fisher**, memorialized by Marcus Samuel as "the God-father of oil," became First Sea Lord in 1904. For the next six years, "Jacky" Fisher would dominate the Royal Navy as no other man had ever done. Born in Ceylon in 1854 to an impoverished planter family, he went to sea at thirteen as a naval cadet. He had advantages of neither birth nor rank, advancing by sheer intelligence, tenacity, and force of will — "a mixture of Machiavelli and a child." He was "a tornado of energy, enthusiasm, and persuasive power." King Edward VII himself told Fisher, "I wish you would stop shaking your fist in my face."

Fisher had only one consuming passion — the Royal Navy. He dedicated himself to modernizing it, shaking it free of "its ingrained habits, its complacency, its cobwebbed traditions." An officer who served under him said "'Jacky' was never satisfied with anything but 'Full Speed!'" His "Golden rule" was never "to allow ourselves to be out 'classed.'" He championed the submarine, the destroyer, Kelvin's compass, advances in firepower, naval aviation — and petroleum. "Oil fuel," he wrote as early as 1901, "will absolutely revolutionize naval strategy. It's a case of 'Wake up England!'" He wanted to convert the fleet from coal to oil for faster speed and greater efficiency.

While First Sea Lord, Fisher provided much of the impetus for the Admiralty's support of the Persian concession and the pressure on Burmah Oil to rescue D'Arcy. His principal objective was always the same — to bring the Royal Navy into the industrial age and have it prepared for when war came. He was convinced Britain's enemy would be imperial Germany.

### *"Made in Germany"*

The burgeoning naval race between Britain and Germany was the single factor that counted most in their growing antagonism. Germany's *Weltpolitik* — the drive for global political, strategic, and economic prominence — was heavy-handed and aggressive. Kaiser Wilhelm was temperamental, erratic, prejudiced, and mercurial. Germany's aim was to break "England's world domination so as to lay free the necessary colonial possessions for the central European states who need to expand." The Kaiser declared, "Only when we can hold out our mailed fist against his face will the British lion draw back." The Germans launched their naval challenge in 1897.

Naval supremacy was central to England's conception of its world role and to the security of the British Empire. Industrial leadership was slipping to the United States and to Germany. In 1896, *Made in Germany* became a best seller. Britain, moaned a Cabinet minister, was "the weary Titan."

Fisher had no doubt Germany was the future enemy and feared a bolt out of the blue on a long holiday weekend — so his aides were always kept on special duty. By 1904, the naval race was "a runaway technological revolution" in battleship size, speed, firepower, and new weapons.

Britain's ruling Liberal party was torn between "navalists" (big Navy + expanded construction) and "economists" (contain naval spending, fund social welfare). The debate was bitter: "Is Britain going to surrender her maritime supremacy to provide old-age pensions?" The "economists" were led by **David Lloyd George**, Chancellor of the Exchequer, and for a time by **Winston Spencer-Churchill**, "the young man in a hurry."

### *Enter Churchill*

**Winston Churchill** was nephew of the Duke of Marlborough, son of the brilliant but erratic Lord Randolph Churchill and his beautiful American wife, Jennie Jerome. He entered Parliament as a Conservative in 1901 at twenty-six, then bolted to the Liberals over free trade. He became President of the Board of Trade and by 1910, Home Secretary. He lived for politics and grand strategy — on the day of his marriage, waiting in the vestry, he talked and gossiped of politics.

Churchill threw himself into the "economists" campaign against Fisher's expanded naval program, championing an Anglo-German naval agreement to reduce the Navy's budget. He declared belief in the inevitability of war with Germany was "all nonsense."

But in July 1911, the German gunboat *Panther* sailed into the Moroccan port of Agadir. The episode backfired, consolidating anti-German feeling. Churchill's views were instantaneously transformed. Germany meant to make war. At end of September 1911, after the crisis passed, Asquith asked Churchill during a golf game if he would like to become First Lord of the Admiralty. "Indeed I would," Churchill replied.

"The whole fortunes of our race and Empire," Churchill said, "the whole treasure accumulated during so many centuries of sacrifice and achievement, would perish and be swept utterly away if our naval supremacy were to be impaired." His guiding precept: "I intended to prepare for an attack by Germany as if it might come the next day."

### *Fisher and Churchill — Speed!*

Fisher, recently retired, had been entranced by Churchill since their first meeting at Biarritz in 1907. Fisher became Churchill's "dry nurse" — the dominating unofficial adviser. Churchill regarded Fisher as the source of "all the most important steps taken to enlarge, improve, or modernize the Navy." Fisher bombarded him with memos — "a veritable volcano of knowledge and of inspiration."

Fisher set out to educate Churchill about petroleum's importance to naval strategy. To speed Churchill's education, Fisher conspired with Marcus Samuel. Fisher arranged for Samuel to make the case for oil, but Churchill was not impressed with the Shell chairman. Fisher apologized: "He is not as good at exposition but he began as a pedlar selling 'sea' shells! (Hence the name of his Company) and now he has six million sterling of his own private money. 'He's a good teapot though he may be a bad pourer'!"

Fisher lectured Churchill on oil's advantages: "Remember oil like coal don't deteriorate and you can accumulate vast stores of it in submerged tanks so as to be free from destruction by fire or bombardment or incendiaries and *east of Suez oil is cheaper than coal.*" He added: "When a cargo steamer can save 78 percent in fuel and gain 30 percent in cargo space by the adoption of internal combustion propulsion and practically get rid of stokers and engineers — it is obvious what a prodigious change is at our doors with oil!" He warned Churchill about delays: "Your old women will have a nice time of it when the new American Battleships are at sea burning oil alone and a German Motor Battleship is cocking a snook at our 'Tortoises'!"

When Churchill arrived at the Admiralty, the Navy already had fifty-six destroyers and seventy-four submarines solely dependent on oil. But the battleships — the backbone of the Navy — burned coal. Churchill and the Navy wanted a new breed of battleships with bigger guns, stronger armor, and greater speed. Fisher reminded him: "The first of all necessities is SPEED, so as to be able to fight — *When* you like, *Where* you like, and *How* you like." The War College estimated that a "Fast Division" at twenty-five knots could get the better of the emerging German fleet. The Royal Navy wanted an extra four knots — and there was no way to get it without oil.

Churchill's education was complete. Oil offered not only higher speeds but greater rapidity in getting up to speed, a greater radius of action, refueling at sea, reduced stoker manpower by more than half, and less stress and exhaustion from coaling. "As a coal ship used up her coal," Churchill wrote, "increasingly large numbers of men had to be taken, if necessary from the guns, to shovel the coal from remote and inconvenient bunkers... The use of oil made it possible in every type of vessel to have more gun-power and more speed for less size or less cost."

The three naval programs of 1912, 1913, and 1914 constituted the greatest addition in the history of the Royal Navy — all based on oil, not a coal-burning ship among them. The key decision came in April 1912: the **Queen Elizabeth class** — five oil-fired battleships for the Fast Division. With this **"fateful plunge,"** Churchill wrote, "the supreme ships of the Navy, on which our life depended, were fed by oil and could only be fed by oil."

The commitment raised a grave problem — where to find the oil, and would it be militarily secure? Churchill's great gamble was pushing for conversion *before* the supply problem was solved. "To commit the Navy irrevocably to oil was indeed 'to take arms against a sea of troubles.'" Yet "if the difficulties and risks could be surmounted, we should be able to raise the whole power and efficiency of the Navy to a definitely higher level — in a word, 'mastery itself was the prize of the venture.'"

### *The Admiral Cracks the Nut*

Churchill established a committee to study the conversion, then recommended a royal commission headed by the retired Admiral Fisher. Fisher was furious with Churchill over promotions: "You have betrayed the Navy. This must be the last communication with you in any matter at all." Churchill wrote a most forceful letter of cajolery: "This liquid fuel problem has got to be solved... I want you for this, *viz*, to crack the nut. No one else can do it so well. Perhaps no one else can do it at all... You have got to find the oil; to show how it can be stored cheaply... When you have solved the riddle, you will find a vy hushed attentive audience. But the riddle will not be solved unless you are willing — for the glory of God — to expend yourself upon its toils."

Fisher accepted. He sold his Shell shares to avoid conflict of interest. He threw himself into the job, working as hard as he ever had. His urgency increased when he learned the German Navy was going forward with oil propulsion. "*They have killed* 15 *men in experiments with oil engines and we have not killed one!*"

The commission's report (November 1912 and two further sections in 1913) stressed the "overwhelming advantages in favour of oil fuel" over coal for the Royal Navy. It called for much-expanded storage because "Oil don't grow in England."

### *The Shell Menace*

Though Anglo-Persian's creation was the result of D'Arcy, Reynolds, and Burmah Oil, **Charles Greenway** was the man who really fashioned the company. Starting as manager of a Scottish trading house in Bombay, he became managing director and dominated Anglo-Persian for the next two decades. Known later as "Champagne Charlie" and "Old Spats and Monocle," Greenway was tenacious and always ready for a brawl. His central objectives: build Anglo-Persian into a major force in world oil, make it the national champion of Great Britain, resist Royal Dutch/Shell's "unwelcome and suffocating embrace," and ensure his own unquestioned control.

Greenway offered the Admiralty a twenty-year fuel contract and campaigned for a special relationship. His recurrent theme: without government aid, Anglo-Persian would disappear into Shell. If that happened, Shell would have a monopoly and extract monopoly prices from a hapless Royal Navy. He stressed Samuel's "Jewishness" and Deterding's "Dutchness" — Shell was controlled by Royal Dutch and the Dutch government was susceptible to German pressure. Control by Shell would eventually place Anglo-Persian "under the control of the German Government itself."

Greenway said all he and his fellow patriotic Englishmen asked was "some small consideration from the British government — just a guarantee or contract that will at any rate give us a moderate return on our capital." The Foreign Office supported him: the Anglo-Persian concession "embracing as it did the entire oil fields of Persia ... should not pass under the control of a foreign syndicate." Sir Edward Grey, the Foreign Secretary: "what we must do is to secure under British control a sufficient oil field for the British Navy."

Fisher privately insisted: "We must do our d-----st to get control of the Anglo-Persian Company and to keep it for all times as an absolutely 'all-British' Company."

### *Aid for Anglo-Persian*

Initially, the Admiralty feared becoming involved in a "speculative risk." But three factors changed the outlook: (1) growing doubts about reliability of petroleum supplies from other sources; (2) the price of fuel oil doubling between January and July 1913 in response to rising maritime demand; (3) Churchill pushing decisions and forcing analysis.

In June 1913, Churchill presented the Cabinet with a key memorandum on "Oil Fuel Supply for His Majesty's Navy," calling for long-term contracts, "keeping alive independent competitive sources of supplies," and frustrating "the formation of a universal oil monopoly." The Cabinet agreed the government should "acquire a controlling interest in trustworthy sources of supply." The idea emerged that the government itself become a shareholder in Anglo-Persian.

On **July 17, 1913**, Churchill made a landmark statement to Parliament. "If we cannot get oil," he warned, "we cannot get corn, we cannot get cotton and we cannot get a thousand and one commodities necessary for the preservation of the economic energies of Great Britain." The Admiralty should become "the owners or, at any rate, the controllers at the source" of a substantial part of the oil it required. "On no one quality, on no one process, on no one country, on no one route and on no one field must we be dependent. Safety and certainty in oil lie in variety and variety alone."

The Cabinet sent a commission to Persia led by **Admiral Edmond Slade**, former Director of Naval Intelligence. The company hastily introduced cosmetic improvements at Abadan, rushing in a new refinery manager from Rangoon. Slade privately informed Churchill: "It seems to be a thoroughly sound concession, which may be developed to a gigantic extent with a large expenditure of capital. It would put us into a perfectly safe position as regards the supply of oil for naval purposes *if we had the control of the company.*" In his official report (January 1914), he added it would be "a national disaster if the concession were allowed to pass into foreign hands."

### *A Victory for Oil*

On **May 20, 1914**, the deal was signed: the British government would invest **£2.2 million** in Anglo-Persian, acquiring 51 percent of the stock and placing two directors on the board with a veto on Admiralty fuel contracts and major political matters, but not commercial activities. A separate secret contract gave the Admiralty a twenty-year fuel oil supply with a rebate from profits.

On **June 17, 1914**, Churchill rose in the House of Commons to introduce the historic bill. Charles Greenway sat in the official box. Also present was Samuel Samuel (Marcus's brother), who became increasingly fidgety as Churchill spoke. Churchill described the world oil landscape: "Two gigantic corporations — one in either hemisphere — stand out predominantly. In the New World there is the Standard Oil. ... In the Old World the great combination of the Shell and the Royal Dutch... has practically covered the whole ground."

Samuel Samuel popped up three times to object to Churchill's characterizations of Royal Dutch/Shell and was ruled out of order. "He had better hear the case for the prosecution," Churchill acidly said, "before he offers an argument for the defense."

Churchill's oratory was full of sarcasm. If the bill failed, Anglo-Persian would become part of Shell. "We have no quarrel with the 'Shell.' We have always found them courteous, considerate, ready to oblige, anxious to serve the Admiralty... The only difficulty has been price." With the leverage of Persian oil, "we do not think we shall be treated with less courtesy, or less consideration."

Samuel finally got his chance: "I do protest most strongly on behalf of one of the greatest British commercial industrial companies, that the attacks that have been made are wholly unjustifiable." Another M.P., Watson Rutherford, criticized Churchill for raising the specter of monopoly and for "Jew-baiting," declaring rising fuel oil prices resulted not from a trust but from the recent emergence of an international fuel oil market.

Churchill's proposal for government ownership was unprecedented, save for Disraeli's purchase of shares in the Suez Canal half a century earlier. Despite strong criticism, the oil bill passed by an overwhelming vote — **254 to 18**. After the vote, Greenway asked Churchill, "How did you manage to carry the House with you so successfully?" "It was," Churchill replied, "the attack on monopolies and trusts that did it."

Churchill had been more than a little cynical. There was no evidence Shell had ever served the Admiralty poorly — indeed, years before, Marcus Samuel had actually asked the government to place a director on Shell's board. And while Churchill had taken a dislike to Samuel, he had developed a most favorable opinion of Deterding — the foreigner. Fisher wrote to Churchill that Deterding "is Napoleon and Cromwell rolled into one. *He is the greatest man I ever met.* ... Napoleonic in his audacity: Cromwellian in his thoroughness! ... Placate him, don't threaten him! Make a contract with him for his fleet of 64 oil tankers in case of war. Don't abuse the Shell Company. ... [Deterding] has a son at Rugby or Eton and has bought a big property in Norfolk and [is] building a castle! Bind him to the land of his adoption!" Churchill did exactly that.

Deterding was practical and understood the rationale for the Anglo-Persian arrangement. Fisher wrote on July 31, 1914: "I have just received a most patriotic letter from Deterding... to say he means you shan't want for oil or tankers in case of war — *Good Old Deterding!* How these Dutchmen do hate the Germans! Knight him when you get the chance."

### *The Coming of War*

Critics were perplexed by the government's purchase. The Viceroy of India declared it "altogether unwise to become dependent upon a most insecure foreign source of oil when Britain was blessed with an abundance of secure coal." The Secretary of State for India likened it to "the owners of the *premier cru* vineyards in the Gironde went about preaching the virtues of Scotch whisky as a beverage."

But the decision was driven by the technological imperatives of the Anglo-German naval race. Oil offered a vital edge in speed and flexibility. The deal assured the British government a large supply of oil, provided Anglo-Persian with desperately needed capital, and spoke to the survival of the empire. **By the summer of 1914, the British Navy was fully committed to oil and the British government had assumed the role of Anglo-Persian's majority stockholder. Oil, for the first time, but certainly not the last, had become an instrument of national policy, a strategic commodity second to none.**

During the weeks leading up to the June 17 debate, Europe had seemed more at peace than in years. British naval units were making courtesy visits to German ports. Many would later look back on the early summer of 1914 with nostalgia, as the dusk of an era. On June 28, 1914, eleven days after Parliament approved Churchill's bill, Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria was assassinated at Sarajevo. It was not until August 10 that the Anglo-Persian Oil Convention received its Royal Assent. By then, Russia had mobilized, Germany had declared war, and at 11:00 p.m. on August 4, Churchill flashed a message to all of His Majesty's ships: "commence hostilities against Germany." The First World War had begun.

## Chapter 9: The Blood of Victory — World War I

It was supposed to be a short war, over in a few weeks or months. Instead, it sank into stalemate and dragged on. An estimated 13 million people died, many millions more were wounded and displaced. It was a catastrophe for the political systems of much of Europe. One of the great historians of international relations would recall the war as "the well-spring of our discontents."

It was a war fought between men and machines — and these machines were powered by oil, just as Admiral Fisher and Winston Churchill had foreseen, but to a much greater extent than even they expected. Oil and the internal combustion engine changed every dimension of warfare, even the very meaning of mobility on land, sea, and in the air.

### *The Taxi Armada*

The French government had already evacuated Paris with 100,000 civilians. The fall of the capital seemed imminent. General Joffre, Commander in Chief, considered ordering his troops to drop back. But the military governor of Paris, **General Joseph Gallieni**, had other ideas. Aerial reconnaissance convinced him an opportunity existed to hit the German lines. The British Army would not take him seriously — "No British officer would be seen speaking to such a comedian." But in an emotional angry nighttime phone call — what Gallieni called his "*coups de telephone*" — he finally persuaded General Joffre to launch a counterattack.

On September 6, 1914, the French went on the offensive. But when the Germans brought up reinforcements, the French were in a precarious position. Desperately needed reinforcements were in Paris but could not be moved — railway was disrupted, marching would be too slow.

Gallieni had his inspiration at 8:00 p.m., sitting at a lycee on the boulevard des Invalides: an armada of Paris taxicabs. He ordered every one of the three thousand available taxis commandeered. Policemen stopped cabs, demanded passengers disgorge, and directed them to the Invalides. "How will we be paid?" one driver asked the lieutenant who flagged him down. "By the meter or on a flat rate?" "By the meter," the lieutenant said. "All right, let's go," replied the driver, making sure to put down his flag before starting off.

Within two hours, scores of taxis were converging. They took off in great convoys up the Champs-Elysees, along the rue Royale and the rue Lafayette. "Today destiny will deliver a great decision," Helmuth von Moltke wrote to his wife. "What torrents of blood have flowed!" Once night fell, each taxi crammed with soldiers, their meter flags down, set off in convoys of twenty-five to fifty toward the battlefield — "this forerunner of the future motorized column."

Thousands of troops were rushed to the critical point. They made the difference. On September 9, the Germans fell back. "Things are going badly, the battles east of Paris will not be decided in our favor," Moltke wrote. "Our campaign is a cruel disillusion." The taxicab drivers returned to Paris after two days without sleep, were paid their fares, and were besieged by the curious. They had helped save Paris and demonstrated what motorized transport would mean in the future.

### *Internal Combustion at War*

The First Battle of the Marne (September 6-8, 1914) was the turning point, ending the much-planned German offensive. When the Germans halted their retreat, both sides dug trenches, settling into a long, bloody, senseless war of attrition — the static war of defense. For more than two years, the lines on the western front moved no more than ten miles in either direction. The machine gun, combined with trenches and barbed wire, gave primacy to defense. Lord Kitchener, British War Secretary: "I don't know what is to be done. This isn't war."

The only way to break the stalemate was mechanical innovation. The first military man to diagnose the disease and conceive the antidote was British colonel **Ernest Swinton**, who, as an "official eyewitness" in France, came up with the idea of an armored vehicle powered by the internal combustion engine, impervious to machine gun bullets and barbed wire. The high command did not take the idea seriously. It might have died altogether had it not been championed by Churchill, who told the PM in January 1915: "The present war has revolutionized all military theories about the field of fire." Churchill doled out Navy funds for development. The new machine was known as the "land cruiser" or "landship" — Churchill called it the "caterpillar." For secrecy, it needed a code name; various names including "cistern" and "reservoir" were considered. But finally it became known as the **"tank."**

The tank was first used prematurely at the Battle of the Somme (1916), played a more important role at Cambrai (November 1917), but had its most decisive impact on **August 8, 1918**, at the **Battle of Amiens**, when 456 tanks broke through the German line, resulting in what General Erich Ludendorff called the "black day of the German Army in the history of the war." The "primacy of the defense" was over. When the German High Command declared in October 1918 that victory was no longer possible, the first reason was the introduction of the tank.

Another oil-powered revolution was mechanized transport. The British Expeditionary Force in August 1914 had just 827 motor cars (747 requisitioned) and 15 motorcycles. By the last months of the war, British Army vehicles included **56,000 trucks, 23,000 motorcars, and 34,000 motorcycles**. The U.S., entering in April 1917, brought another 50,000 gasoline-driven vehicles. The victory of the Allies over Germany was "in some ways the victory of the truck over the locomotive."

### *The War in the Air and at Sea*

The airplane had an even more dramatic impact. The Wright brothers flew in 1903, but General Foch dismissed aviation as "good sport, but for the Army the aeroplane is worthless." At the outbreak of war, the British aviation industry barely numbered a thousand people and had produced just 250 planes (sixty experimental). Yet by July 1915, every machine in the air at the war's outbreak had become obsolete. Air combat evolved from pilots shooting with handguns to machine guns synchronized with propellers. By 1916, planes flew in formation with developed tactics. Tactical bombing and strategic bombing emerged — Germany launched zeppelin and bomber assaults against England in what became "the first Battle of Britain." By the war's last months, aircraft speeds had more than doubled to over 120 mph, with a ceiling of 27,000 feet. Wartime production: Britain 55,000 planes; France 68,000; Italy 20,000; Germany 48,000; U.S. (in a year and a half) 15,000.

The prewar naval race produced a stalemate. Britain's Grand Fleet was superior but the two fleets met only once in major engagement — the **Battle of Jutland** (May 31, 1916). The German fleet was tactically victorious but strategically the British won, dominating the North Sea for the rest of the war. Events proved Churchill and Fisher right: the conversion to oil gave the British fleet greater range, speed, and faster refueling. The German High Seas Fleet was primarily coal-burning with no stations outside Germany — its reliance on coal made its name a misnomer.

### *Anglo-Persian Versus Shell*

Anglo-Persian in 1914 accounted for just under one percent of total world oil output. Churchill himself, less than a month after war began, despaired of Britain's ability to defend the Persian oil fields: "There is little likelihood of any troops being available for this purpose. We shall have to buy our oil from elsewhere."

The forces of the **Ottoman Empire** were the chief threat. Immediately after Turkey entered the war on Germany's side in autumn 1914, its troops threatened the Abadan refinery. British soldiers repulsed them and went on to capture **Basra** — critical because it guarded approaches to Persian oil. The British extended their line toward Baghdad; one of the major considerations was to secure oil fields and counteract German subversion. In 1917, after a degrading defeat, the British finally captured Baghdad. Oil production in Persia grew more than **tenfold between 1912 and 1918 — from 1,600 barrels per day to 18,000**. By late 1916, Anglo-Persian was meeting a fifth of the British Navy's entire oil needs.

**Charles Greenway** pursued a clear strategy to transform Anglo-Persian from a crude producer into an integrated oil company — "to build up an absolutely self-contained organization." His most important step was purchasing **British Petroleum**, one of the largest petroleum distribution networks in the UK. Despite its name, it had belonged to the Deutsche Bank for its Rumanian oil; the British government had seized it at the outbreak of war. Anglo-Persian acquired not only a major marketing system but a most useful name. Up until 1916-17, over 80 percent of Anglo-Persian's fixed assets were in Persia; the very next year, only half were, with the rest in tankers and distribution. It had become an integrated company.

Greenway revived the "Shell menace," attacking "the schemes of Sir Marcus and his associates for securing a worldwide monopoly of the oil trade." But these charges were unfair. Deterding had naturalized himself British and spent the war years in London, identifying with the Allies. Marcus Samuel was simply a fierce British patriot — one of his two sons was killed in France leading his platoon. Of his two sons-in-law, one was killed in action, the other died after the war from trench warfare effects.

Samuel himself masterminded an audacious scheme of critical importance: extracting **toluol** — the essential ingredient for the explosive TNT — from Shell's Borneo crude. By end of 1914, coal-based toluol production was inadequate and Britain was perilously close to running out of explosives. Shell's toluol-extracting factory had been built in Rotterdam by the Dutch arm of the Group, and German companies were using its output to make TNT. In the middle of the night at the end of January 1915, the plant was disassembled, each piece numbered and camouflaged, loaded onto a Dutch freighter that rendezvoused at sea with British destroyers. A cover story leaked to Germans said the evacuation would occur a day later — that following night, a similar Dutch freighter was torpedoed at the mouth of Rotterdam's harbor. The plant was re-erected in Somerset within weeks and, along with a second plant Shell built, **provided 80 percent of the British military's TNT**. Samuel was awarded a peerage for this achievement.

Shell acted as the **quartermaster general for oil**, acquiring and organizing supplies around the world for the British forces — delivering products from Borneo, Sumatra, and the United States to the railheads and airfields in France. Government officials, concerned about alienating Shell when it was most needed, began to react negatively to Greenway's continuing attacks. Greenway so overplayed his hand that he eventually turned many in the government against Anglo-Persian.

### *"A Dearth of Petrol"*

As late as 1915, oil supply raised little anxiety. But by early 1916, the *Times* of London reported "a dearth of petrol." The following May, the *Times* called for a sharp definition of where "joy-riding" ended and war demands began. The reasons were twofold: (1) the growing shortage of shipping tonnage owing to the **German submarine campaign**, which constricted oil along with all other raw materials; (2) the rapidly growing demand for oil on the battlefield and home front. The government instituted rationing.

Pressure returned at the beginning of 1917 when Germany unleashed **unrestricted submarine warfare** against Allied shipping — a blunder of immense proportions that led the United States to enter the war. Tonnage lost in the first half of 1917 was twice that in the comparable period of 1916. Standard Oil of New Jersey lost six tankers, including the brand new *John D. Archbold*. Among Shell's losses was the *Murex* — the first vessel Marcus Samuel had dispatched through the Suez Canal a quarter century earlier.

By end of May 1917, Admiralty oil stocks were less than half the six-month target, and it was even suggested the Royal Navy stop building oil-driven ships and go back to coal. "Desperate" telegrams were dispatched to America declaring the Royal Navy would be immobilized, "fleet out of action," unless more tonnage was available. "The Germans are succeeding," the American ambassador in London despairingly wrote in July 1917. "They have lately sunk so many fuel oil ships, that this country may very soon be in a perilous condition — even the Grand Fleet may not have enough fuel." In October, Walter Long, Secretary of State for the Colonies, warned the House of Commons: "You may have men, munitions, and money, but if you do not have oil, which is today the greatest motive power that you use, all your other advantages would be of comparatively little value." Pleasure driving in Britain was summarily and completely banned.

France's oil position was also degenerating. In December 1917, Senator Berenger warned Clemenceau that France would run out of oil by March 1918. Clemenceau urgently appealed to President Wilson on December 15, 1917, that an additional hundred thousand tons of tanker capacity be made immediately available, declaring that gasoline was "as vital as blood in the coming battles" and "a failure in the supply of gasoline would cause the immediate paralysis of our armies." He ominously added that a shortage might even "compel us to a peace unfavorable to the Allies." Wilson responded quickly with the necessary tonnage.

An **Inter-Allied Petroleum Conference** was established in February 1918 to pool, coordinate, and control all oil supplies and tanker shipping — members were the U.S., Britain, France, and Italy. Standard Oil of New Jersey and Royal Dutch/Shell really made the system work, though they continually argued about who was making the larger contribution. That joint system — along with the introduction of convoys as an antidote to U-boats — solved the Allies' oil supply problems for the rest of the war.

### *The Energy Czar*

American oil had become essential to the European war. In 1914, the U.S. had produced **266 million barrels — 65 percent of total world output**. By 1917, output had risen to 335 million barrels — 67 percent. Exports accounted for a quarter of total U.S. production, with the bulk going to Europe. With access to Russian oil closed off by war and revolution, the U.S. was to **satisfy 80 percent of the Allies' wartime requirement for petroleum**.

America's entry into the war complicated the picture — supplies needed for the American military, the Allies, American war industries, and normal civilian use. The **Fuel Administration**, established by President Wilson in August 1917, was part of overall economic mobilization. The head of the Oil Division was **Mark Requa**, a California petroleum engineer who became America's first energy czar. His Oil Division worked with the **National Petroleum War Service Committee**, chaired by **Alfred Bedford**, president of Standard Oil of New Jersey. It was this committee that organized the supply of American oil for the war in Europe. This new pattern of close cooperation between business and government stood in marked contrast to the battle between government and Standard Oil just a decade earlier. Trust busting seemed far away, as the industry was now pushed to run itself as a single body, under the leadership of the once-hated Standard Oil of New Jersey.

In 1917, surging demand hit the limit of available supplies. The bitterly cold winter of 1917-18 created a severe coal shortage. In January 1918, the Fuel Administration ordered almost all industrial plants east of the Mississippi to close for a week to free fuel for Europe-bound ships immobilized in East Coast harbors. Factories were ordered to remain closed on Mondays. "Bedlam broke loose," observed Colonel Edward House, Wilson's political confidant.

The coal shortage stimulated demand for oil; by early 1918, average crude prices were double 1914 levels. On May 17, 1918, Requa warned there was "no justification" for further price advances and called for "voluntary" price controls. Standard Oil of New Jersey agreed; but when independent producers did not, Requa bluntly told them in Tulsa there would be direct government controls. In August 1918, maximum prices were set. An appeal was made for **"Gasolineless Sundays"** — the only exemptions were for freight, doctors, police, emergency vehicles, and hearses. "I suppose," declared President Wilson, "I must walk to church."

### *The Man with the Sledgehammer*

Despite periodic alarms, the Allies never suffered a protracted oil crunch. **Germany did.** The Allied blockade succeeded in choking off supplies from overseas, leaving only one source — **Rumania**. Germany was heavily dependent on it. For the first two years, Rumania remained neutral, waiting to see which side was winning. In August 1916, Rumania declared war against Austria-Hungary. Victory in this Eastern theater was essential for Germany. "As I now saw quite clearly, we should not have been able to exist, much less to carry on the war, without Rumania's corn and oil," said Ludendorff.

German and Austrian troops advanced on Rumania in September 1916. They captured a vast amount of petroleum products, including a large cache of Allied gasoline on the Black Sea. The British Cabinet War Committee discussed the matter urgently on October 31, 1916: "No efforts should be spared to ensure, in case of necessity, the destruction of the supplies of grain and oil, as well as of the oil wells." But the Rumanian government was reluctant to destroy its national treasure.

The British recruited **Colonel John Norton-Griffiths, M.P.**, to organize the destruction. A larger-than-life figure known as "Hell-fire Jack," "the Monkey Man" (for having eaten a monkey in Africa), and most treasured, **"Empire Jack"** — handsome, physically imposing, a charming swashbuckler. His first great engineering feat in WWI had been adapting Manchester sewer-tunneling techniques to mine beneath German trenches. He arrived in Bucharest on November 18, 1916, via Russia, accompanied only by his manservant. As the Germans continued their advance, the Rumanian government finally agreed to the policy of destruction.

The destruction teams swung into action with "Empire Jack" at the forefront. Fields went up in flames on November 26-27. Explosives were placed in refineries, petroleum products in storage were allowed to flow in, creating lakes of oil several inches deep, then everything was set afire. Those who challenged Norton-Griffiths were overwhelmed by sheer force of personality — or he would deliver a powerful kick or pull out his revolver shouting, "I don't speak your blasted language." Apparatus was smashed; derricks dynamited; wells plugged with stone, spikes, mud, broken chains, drillbits. The last field was Ploesti itself. On December 5, only a few hours after the facilities went up in flames, the Germans entered the town. Norton-Griffiths barely escaped by car, just ahead of the German cavalry.

After the war, Ludendorff admitted Norton-Griffiths's efforts "did materially reduce the oil supplies of our army and the home country. We must attribute our shortages in part to him." Altogether, some **seventy refineries and an estimated eight hundred thousand tons of crude oil and petroleum products** had been destroyed. It took the Germans five months to restart production, and for all of 1917, production was only a third of 1914 levels. By 1918, they had pushed it back to 80 percent. Germany's timely capture of the Rumanian oil, along with Rumanian grain, "made just the difference between shortage and collapse" for the German side — but only for a time.

### *Baku*

Even as the Germans were getting Rumanian fields back, Ludendorff set his sights on a greater prize — **Baku**, on the Caspian Sea. The collapse of the Czarist regime in early 1917, the rise of the Bolsheviks, and the fragmentation of the Russian empire held out hope. Germany sought access to Baku petroleum in March 1918 with the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk. But the Turks, Germany's ally, had already begun advancing toward Baku. Fearing their ally would destroy the oil fields, the Germans promised the Bolsheviks they would try to restrain the Turks in exchange for oil. "Of course, we agreed," said Lenin. Stalin telegraphed the Bolshevik Baku Commune ordering it to comply. But the local Bolsheviks refused: "Neither in victory nor in defeat will we give the German plunderers one drop of oil produced by our labor."

The Turks continued their advance. By end of July, they were laying siege to the city. In mid-August 1918, the British intervened with a small force through Persia, charged with saving Baku and keeping oil from the enemy. If need be, they were to follow the Rumanian plan and "destroy the Baku pumping plant, pipeline and oil reservoirs." The British stayed only a month — but long enough to deny Baku oil to the Germans at the critical moment. "A serious blow for us," Ludendorff said. Then the Turks captured the city, and the local Moslems, abetted by the Turks, began again to pillage and destroy, killing every Armenian they could find. Twenty-six Bolshevik commissars were taken to the desert, 140 miles east of the Caspian, and executed. One of the few to escape was a young Armenian named **Anastas Mikoyan**, who eventually got to Moscow to tell Lenin what had happened. But by the time the Turks took Baku, it was too late for the Germans.

### *Floating to Victory*

The denial of Baku was a decisive blow for Germany. By October 1918, the picture was grim. The German Army had all but exhausted its reserves. The German High Command was anticipating a grave petroleum crisis. **Air and mechanized land warfare would cease absolutely within two months.** War industries operating on oil would run out in two months; lubricants exhausted in six months. Limited land operations could continue on a strictly rationed basis.

The estimates were never tested. Within a month, Germany surrendered. The armistice was signed at five in the morning, November 11, 1918, in Marshal Foch's railway car in the Forest of Compiegne. Six hours later, the war was over.

Ten days after the Armistice, the British government hosted a dinner for the Inter-Allied Petroleum Conference at Lancaster House, with **Lord Curzon** as chairman. He had been the great Persian expert, Viceroy of India, member of the War Cabinet, and was shortly to become Foreign Secretary. He told the guests that "one of the most astonishing things" he had seen in France and Flanders "was the tremendous army of motor lorries." Then he resoundingly declared, **"The Allied cause had floated to victory upon a wave of oil."**

Senator Berenger was even more eloquent, declaring oil was **"the blood of the earth — the blood of victory."** Germany had boasted of its superiority in iron and coal, "but it had not taken sufficient account of our superiority of oil." He prophesied: "As oil had been the blood of war, so it would be the blood of the peace. At this hour, at the beginning of the peace, our civilian populations, our industries, our commerce, our farmers are all calling for more oil, always more oil, for more gasoline, always more gasoline." Then he broke into English: **"More oil, ever more oil!"**

## Chapter 10: Opening the Door on the Middle East — The Turkish Petroleum Company

Ten days after the "blood of victory" toasts, French Premier **Georges Clemenceau** visited British Prime Minister **David Lloyd George** in London. Oil was now inextricably linked to postwar politics. Britain wanted to assert influence over Mesopotamia (later Iraq), thought to be highly prospective of oil. France had a claim to one part — Mosul, northwest of Baghdad.

What did Britain want? Clemenceau asked. Would France give up its claim to Mosul, Lloyd George responded, in exchange for British recognition of French control over neighboring Syria? France would, Clemenceau replied — so long as it received a share of the oil production from Mosul. Lloyd George assented. Neither Prime Minister bothered to inform his respective foreign minister. Their casual verbal agreement was not a settlement — it was the beginning of the great postwar struggle for new oil sources that would pit French against English and draw in the Americans.

The Great War had made abundantly clear that petroleum had become an essential element in the strategy of nations. Politicians and bureaucrats would now rush headlong into the competition, drawn by the common perception that the postwar world would require ever-greater quantities of oil for economic prosperity and national power.

### *Mr. Five Percent*

**Calouste Gulbenkian** was the second generation of his family in the oil business. His father was a wealthy Armenian oil man and banker who had built his fortune importing Russian kerosene into the Ottoman Empire and had been rewarded by the Sultan with the governorship of a Black Sea port. The family lived in Constantinople. At age seven, Calouste's first recorded transaction: he took a Turkish silver piece to the bazaar, not to buy candy, but to exchange it for an antique coin. (He later created one of the world's great collections of gold coins, acquiring J. P. Morgan's superb collection of Greek gold coins.) Unpopular as a schoolboy, the young Calouste spent after-school hours in the bazaar, listening to deals and learning the arts of Oriental negotiation.

He studied mining engineering at King's College, London, graduating in 1887 at nineteen with a first-class degree. He wrote a thesis on petroleum. His father sent him to Baku, where the young man was fascinated by the oil industry and was drenched by a gusher — "fine and consistent" oil, though he found the experience unpleasant and never visited oil country again. He published highly regarded articles on Russian oil in a leading French magazine in 1889 and turned them into a book in 1891, making himself a world oil expert at twenty-one.

Turkish officials immediately asked him to investigate Mesopotamian oil possibilities. He put together a competent report based on others' writings and talks with German railway engineers — the region had very great petroleum potential. Thus began his lifelong devotion to Mesopotamian oil, pursued with extraordinary dedication and tenacity over six decades.

In Constantinople, Gulbenkian tried several commercial ventures, mastering the bazaar arts: trading, dealing, intrigue, baksheesh, and information-gathering. He developed his lifelong passion for hard work, his capacity for vision, and his great skills as a negotiator. His favorite Arab proverb: "The hand you dare not bite, kiss it." He was not prone to budge: "It would have been easier to squeeze granite than Mr. Gulbenkian." He was totally and completely untrusting — Sir Kenneth Clark of the National Gallery said, "I have never known anybody so suspicious. He always had people spying for him." He employed two different sets of doctors so he could check one against the other.

In 1896, during one of the periodic Turkish massacres of Armenians, Gulbenkian fled to Egypt. He made himself invaluable to two powerful Armenians — an oil millionaire from Baku and Nubar Pasha, who helped rule Egypt. These connections opened the doors of both oil and international finance. In London, he allied with the Samuel brothers and Henri Deterding. His son Nubar later wrote that Gulbenkian "and Deterding were very close for over twenty years. One never knows whether in the end it was Deterding who used my father or my father who used Deterding." To Shell, Gulbenkian brought deals, especially acquisitions, and arranged financing.

One of his earliest transactions was the Persian concession that went to D'Arcy. Gulbenkian and Deterding had looked at the prospectus but rejected it: "a very wild cat, and it looked so speculative that we thought it was a business for a gambler." Thereafter, he framed a motto — **"Never give up an oil concession"** — that would be his guiding principle for life. In 1907, he persuaded the Samuels to open a Constantinople office. He was financial adviser to the Turkish government and a major stockholder in the **Turkish National Bank** — from this base he brought the rival British and German interests, and then Royal Dutch/Shell, into the **Turkish Petroleum Company** (TPC). The Deutsche Bank and Royal Dutch/Shell each held a quarter, the Turkish National Bank held half (of which Gulbenkian was the silent owner of 30 percent, giving him a 15 percent stake in TPC).

### *The Foreign Office Agreement and the Self-Denying Clause*

From 1912 onward, the British government forced the TPC to amalgamate with D'Arcy's Anglo-Persian syndicate and jointly pursue a concession. Under the **Foreign Office Agreement of March 19, 1914**, British interests predominated: Anglo-Persian held 50 percent, Deutsche Bank and Shell each 25 percent. Gulbenkian was still to contend with: Anglo-Persian and Shell each gave up "beneficiary interests" of 2.5 percent to the Armenian. He could not vote the shares but would enjoy all financial benefits. Thus **Mr. Five Percent** was born.

The signatories agreed to the **"self-denying clause"**: none would be involved in oil production anywhere in the Ottoman Empire save jointly through the Turkish Petroleum Company. The only exceptions were Egypt, Kuwait, and "transferred territories" on the Turco-Persian border. That clause would establish the foundation for oil development in the Middle East — and for titanic struggles — for many years.

On June 28, 1914 — the very day the Grand Vizier promised the concession would be formally granted — Archduke Franz Ferdinand was assassinated. Had the concession actually been granted, or only promised? The answer would hang much argument. The war interred the TPC — apparently.

### *"A First-Class War Aim"*

The **Sykes-Picot Agreement** (1915-16) casually assigned Mosul — one of the most promising oil regions — to a future French sphere. This "surrender" outraged many British officials. The issue became more urgent when British forces captured Baghdad in 1917. Sir Maurice Hankey, secretary of the War Cabinet, wrote to Foreign Secretary Balfour that "oil in the next war will occupy the place of coal in the present war. The only big potential supply that we can get under British control is the Persian and Mesopotamian supply." Therefore, Hankey said, **"control over these oil supplies becomes a first-class British war aim."**

Wilson's Fourteen Points and the call for self-determination complicated British designs. Balfour worried that explicitly pronouncing Mesopotamia a war aim would seem "too old-fashionably imperialistic." Instead, in August 1918, he told the Prime Ministers of the Dominions that Britain must be the "guiding spirit" in Mesopotamia. "I do not care under what system we keep the oil," he said, "but I am quite clear it is all-important for us that this oil should be available." British forces captured Mosul after the armistice with Turkey.

### *Clemenceau and His Grocer*

Before WWI, Clemenceau had supposedly said, "When I want some oil, I'll find it at my grocer's." The war changed his mind. On December 1, 1918, following his drive through London's cheering crowds with Lloyd George, Clemenceau apparently surrendered France's claim to Mosul in exchange for British support for France in Syria, plus a guarantee of a share of any Mosul oil.

But the exchange settled nothing. It initiated protracted, acrimonious negotiations. During the Paris Peace Conference in spring 1919, the two leaders rancorously disagreed and accused each other of bad faith. The discussion nearly became an actual fistfight.

Finally, in April 1920, Lloyd George and France's new premier, Alexandre Millerand, hammered out the **San Remo Agreement**: France would get 25 percent of the oil from Mesopotamia (which would become a British mandate under the League of Nations). The vehicle remained the Turkish Petroleum Company; the French acquired the former German share. France gave up its territorial claim to Mosul. Britain ensured any private company developing Mesopotamian oil would be under its control.

The French also created their own national oil champion: the **Compagnie Francaise des Petroles (CFP)**, established in 1924 under **Colonel Ernest Mercier**, a *Polytechnicien*, war hero, and technocrat devoted to modernizing France. He had already built a modern electric industry. French companies and banks were reluctant to invest — Mesopotamia looked "so full of international difficulties." "None of the initial investors begged for the favor of being admitted into the CFP." Mercier found ninety banks and companies. By 1928, France established a new "constitution" for oil: a quota system to curtail "Anglo-Saxon oil trusts," build a domestic refining industry, and develop France's Mesopotamian share. The state acquired 25 percent ownership of CFP.

### *Amalgamation? — Shell vs. Anglo-Persian*

Britain continued efforts to upset the 60-40 Dutch-British split in Royal Dutch/Shell and bring the Group under British control. Deterding and Shell were interested in amalgamating with Anglo-Persian to gain control before it became a fearsome competitor. But Deterding would not accept British government interference in commercial operations. He also saw disadvantages in too close an association with the British government — Latin American countries were banning concessions to government-controlled companies, specifically targeting Anglo-Persian.

The strongest opposition to amalgamation came from the Admiralty, which was antagonistic to Shell and deeply attached to its right to obtain fuel oil from Anglo-Persian at a substantial discount. Anglo-Persian itself vehemently opposed: Charles Greenway had not fought so hard to turn it into an integrated oil company just to become "merely an addendum to the hated Shell."

### *Reenter Churchill*

Robert Waley Cohen had a brain wave: at a carefully orchestrated dinner, he approached **Winston Churchill** — then out of a job, defeated at Dundee East and writing at Chartwell — with a proposition. Would Churchill lobby for Shell's amalgamation with Anglo-Persian, whereby Shell might purchase the government's shares? Churchill wanted ten thousand pounds if the deal didn't go through and fifty thousand if it did. "We couldn't very well haggle or bargain with Churchill," Burmah's chairman remarked. The sum was split between Shell and Burmah via a secret account.

Churchill, the same man who as First Lord had castigated Shell's voraciousness and insisted the government buy shares to guarantee Anglo-Persian's independence, was now prepared to undo all that. In August 1923, he called on PM Stanley Baldwin, who was "thoroughly in favor of the Oil settlement" and mentioned twenty million pounds as "a very good price" for the government's shares — almost ten times what the government had paid.

But Baldwin called a snap election; Churchill returned his fee and charged back into politics. Britain's first Labour government rejected the amalgamation. In autumn 1924, the Conservatives returned — and the minister now responsible for the government's shares was none other than the new Chancellor of the Exchequer, Winston Churchill, who now opposed selling.

### *Oil Shortage and the Open Door*

American companies were embarking on a worldwide campaign for new oil. A fear of imminent depletion — a virtual obsession — gripped the American oil industry and government at the end of WWI and into the early 1920s. President Wilson agreed: "There seemed to be no method by which we could assure ourselves of the necessary supply at home and abroad." American oil consumption had increased 90 percent between 1911 and 1918. Registered motor vehicles in the U.S. jumped from **1.8 to 9.2 million between 1914 and 1920**. One Senator called on the Navy to reconvert from oil to coal.

The Bureau of Mines director predicted American oil fields would reach maximum production in two to five years. George Otis Smith of the U.S. Geological Survey warned of a possible **"gasoline famine"** and said known American reserves would be exhausted in exactly nine years and three months. There was much discussion of shale oil in Colorado, Utah, and Nevada — *National Geographic* declared "no man who owns a motor-car will fail to rejoice" — but development costs were woefully underestimated. Britain was even cultivating Jerusalem artichokes in Dorset hoping to produce automobile fuel.

Crude prices jumped 50 percent between 1918 and 1920. Both the oil industry and the American government firmly believed Britain was pressing an aggressive policy to preempt the rest of the world's oil. Washington rallied to support American companies' quest for foreign supplies under the principle of the **"Open Door"** — equal access for American capital and business.

The news of the **San Remo Agreement** stunned Washington. Standard Oil of New Jersey protested to the State Department; the American press denounced it as old-fashioned imperialism violating the Open Door. Congress passed the **Mineral Leasing Act of 1920**, denying drilling rights on public lands to foreign interests whose governments denied similar access to Americans — aimed specifically at the Dutch in the East Indies and the British in Mesopotamia.

The Wilson Administration, once the embodiment of progressivism, now gave full support to the oil companies — particularly Jersey Standard, the most prominent heir to the dragon slain by the Supreme Court a decade earlier. The British ambassador marveled at the "rapprochement between the Wilson Administration and the Standard Oil interest" that "completely reversed the prewar relationships." The Harding Administration, which came in 1921, proved even stronger in defending American oil interests.

### *"The Boss": Walter Teagle*

Commerce Secretary **Herbert Hoover** suggested a syndicate of American companies for Mesopotamia. At a meeting in May 1921, Hoover and Secretary of State Hughes explained the U.S. could not swing the door open on behalf of one company alone. Jersey Standard's **Walter Teagle** put together a consortium of several leading companies — what would recently have been attacked as restraint of trade was now supported as a national champion for the Open Door.

**Teagle** was second-generation oil — on his mother's side, actually third: his maternal grandfather was **Maurice Clark**, the partner Rockefeller had bought out at the critical 1865 auction. Teagle's father was a successful independent Cleveland refiner who had resisted Standard Oil for years, was one of Ida Tarbell's heroes, and eventually sold out to Standard. Young Teagle went to Cornell, wrote a thesis on de-sulfurization of crude scoring a perfect one hundred, and was told by his professor to study for an advanced degree. His father responded with a terse telegram: "Come home at once." At nineteen cents an hour, Teagle fired a still in the family refinery, then proved himself a formidable salesman on the road — "He haggled over everything. He'd trade and trade. If it was company money, he'd think he was paying too much for a five cent cigar and try to get it for four."

By 1908, he was head of Standard Oil's Foreign Export Committee. He promoted conciliation with Deterding — once settling a Far East competitive dispute by spending two days shooting grouse in Scotland with Deterding (both excellent wing shots), two days playing poker, then working out the matter. Yet their mutual respect could not overcome fundamental suspicion. Deterding, Teagle once said, "frequently changes his mind and usually forgets to tell you that such is the case."

In **1917**, at thirty-nine, Teagle became president of Standard Oil of New Jersey. He was a new style leader — a professional manager, not a substantial stockholder. He installed Rockefeller's old rolltop desk — number 44 — in his office and set about reinvigorating the moribund company. He created an in-house magazine, *The Lamp*, instituted an "open door" for the press, and was apparently candid and forthright with reporters (though carefully controlled).

Teagle's big problem was crude supply — Standard Oil's production was only 16 percent of its refinery output. At the company's fiftieth anniversary in 1920, he declared: "The present policy of the Standard Oil Company is to be interested in every producing area no matter in what country it is situated." Wherever oil might be found, Standard Oil of New Jersey intended to be there.

### *The Crowded Table — Negotiations for Iraq*

In summer 1922, Teagle went to London to begin negotiations on American participation in the Turkish Petroleum Company. The discussions were fruitless. Arrayed against him were Deterding, Greenway, Mercier of CFP, and hovering nearby, Gulbenkian. The participants argued over shares, whether to maintain the self-denying clause, and the acrimonious matter of revenues. Teagle and Greenway wanted oil sold to stockholders at cost (avoiding Iraqi taxes); this did not please Iraq, which wanted a direct share of earnings, nor Gulbenkian, who was "most interested in receiving his dividends in money — not oil."

The new Turkey was challenging the border with Iraq and trying to undermine the TPC's legal basis. The British government, using its League of Nations mandate, put pressure on Iraq to grant a new concession.

### *Faisal of Iraq*

During the war, London had encouraged **Hussein**, Sharif of Mecca, to raise an Arab revolt against Turkey, aided by **T. E. Lawrence** ("Lawrence of Arabia"). Hussein's sons were to become rulers of the new Arab states. **Faisal**, the third son, was considered the most able — Lawrence described him as "an absolute ripper." Faisal cut a romantic figure at the Versailles Conference; Secretary of State Lansing wrote that Faisal's "voice seemed to breathe the perfume of frankincense."

The British put Faisal on the throne of Syria. But when France took control under the postwar understandings, Faisal was abruptly deposed and turned out of Damascus. He showed up at a railway station in Palestine, sat on his luggage, and waited for his connection. But his career as a king was not over. The British needed a monarch for Iraq — a new state formed from three former Ottoman provinces. Political stability was needed for oil, for defense of the Persian Gulf, and for the imperial air route to India, Singapore, and Australia.

Churchill, then head of the Colonial Office, chose the out-of-work Faisal as his candidate. Summoned from exile, he was crowned King of Iraq in Baghdad in August 1921. His brother Abdullah was installed as king "of the vacant lot which the British christened the Amirate of Transjordan." Faisal had not inherited a well-defined nation but rather a collection of diverse groups — Shia Arabs, Sunni Arabs, Jews, Kurds, and Yazidis. The minority Sunni Arabs held political power while the Shia were most numerous. The Jews were the largest single group in Baghdad.

Oil exploration could not begin without a new, sounder concession. Washington consistently refused to recognize the validity of the 1914 grant. **Allen Dulles**, chief of Near Eastern Affairs at the State Department, told Teagle the TPC's claim was "invalid." Iraqi cabinets — fearful of nationalistic sentiments and assassination — were reluctant to sign. But finally, on **March 14, 1925**, a new concession agreement was signed. Gulbenkian later noted the Open Door was mere "eyewash."

### *The Architect — Gulbenkian's Triumph*

Everything seemed settled except for one stumbling block — Gulbenkian and his 5 percent. Throughout the negotiations, he had remained strange and solitary, going to great lengths to avoid meetings but scrutinizing every word of memoranda. "Oil friendships are very slippery," he once said. His formerly close relationship with Deterding had ruptured in the mid-1920s — partly over a dispute about a Venezuelan oil company Gulbenkian had brought to Royal Dutch/Shell, partly over the affections of a White Russian lady, **Lydia Pavlova**, former wife of a Czarist general. When Deterding couldn't pay $300,000 for emeralds from Cartier's, Gulbenkian arranged a bridging credit. But Lydia became the second Mrs. Deterding, leading to bad blood between the two men. Deterding resented Gulbenkian's "persnickety interference"; Gulbenkian could not stand Deterding's "overbearing grandeur."

Gulbenkian insisted on his 5 percent of the TPC to be paid in cash, which the Americans opposed. His break with Deterding only strengthened his obstinacy. Teagle was driven to say Gulbenkian was "most difficult in a difficult situation." Gulbenkian was convinced "the oil groups headed by the American had only one aim, that is, by hook or by crook to wipe out his rights."

At a famous luncheon at the Carlton Hotel, Teagle tried an appealing line: "Surely, Mr. Gulbenkian, you're too good an oil merchant not to know that the property won't stand any such rate as that." Gulbenkian's face went red: "Young man! Don't you ever call me an oil merchant! I'm not an oil merchant and I'll have you distinctly understand that!" Teagle apologized. "I'll tell you how I classify myself," the Armenian replied hotly. **"I classify myself as a business architect. I design this company and that company. I designed this Turkish Petroleum Company and I made a room for Deterding and I made a room for the French and I made a room for you. Now, the three of you are trying to throw me out on my ass."**

### *Toward the Red Line — Baba Gurgur*

In 1925, a joint geological expedition from Anglo-Persian, Royal Dutch, and the American companies arrived in Iraq and reported with rising excitement. One American reported back that he knew of no other region where the promise of drilling was greater.

Drilling began in April 1927. At 3:00 a.m. on **October 15, 1927**, from a well at **Baba Gurgur** — about six miles northwest of Kirkuk, where for thousands of years two dozen holes had been venting natural gas (always alight, thought to be the "burning fiery furnace" into which Nebuchadnezzar had cast the Jews) — the drill bit had barely passed fifteen hundred feet when a great roar was heard reverberating across the desert. A powerful gusher reached fifty feet above the derrick, carrying rocks from the bottom. The countryside was drenched with oil, hollows filled with poisonous gas. Whole villages were threatened. Seven hundred tribesmen were recruited to build dikes. After eight and a half days, the well was brought under control. It had flowed at **ninety-five thousand barrels per day**.

The leading question had been answered — there *were* petroleum resources in Iraq, potentially bountiful. On **July 31, 1928**, nine months after the discovery and almost six years since Teagle had first sailed for London, the full contract was signed. Royal Dutch/Shell, Anglo-Persian, and the French each received **23.75 percent**, as did the **Near East Development Company** (the American consortium). Gulbenkian received his **5 percent interest in oil**, which he could immediately sell to the French at market prices, transmuting crude into his beloved cash.

The critical **self-denying clause** was reborn. Gulbenkian called for a large map of the Middle East, took a thick red pencil, and drew a line along the boundaries of the old Ottoman Empire. **"That was the old Ottoman Empire which I knew in 1914. And I ought to know. I was born in it, lived in it, and served in it."** This far-reaching oil settlement was thereafter called **"The Red Line Agreement."** Within the red line were eventually to be found all the major oil-producing fields of the Middle East, save those of Persia and Kuwait. The partners were bound not to engage in any oil operations within that vast territory except in cooperation with the other members of the Turkish Petroleum Company. It set the framework for future Middle Eastern oil development — and became the focus for decades of bitter conflict.

Teagle later looked back: "It was a damn bad move! Should have gone in by ourselves three years earlier." But for Gulbenkian, it was a great victory — the culmination of thirty-seven years of perseverance and tenacity. To mark the event, he chartered a boat for a Mediterranean cruise with his daughter Rita. Off the coast of Morocco, he caught sight of a strange ship with its funnel jutting up at the extreme stern. He asked what it was. An oil tanker, Rita told him. He was fifty-nine years old, had just made one of the greatest oil deals of the century, and **he had never before seen an oil tanker**.

## Chapter 11: From Shortage to Surplus — The Age of Gasoline

In 1919, U.S. Army Captain **Dwight D. Eisenhower**, depressed by the tedium of peacetime military life, volunteered for a cross-country motor caravan organized to demonstrate motor transportation's potential and the need for better highways. "A coast-to-coast convoy," he said, "was, under the circumstances of the time, a genuine adventure." He called it "Through Darkest America with Truck and Tank."

The journey started on July 7, 1919, from just south of the White House, with forty-two trucks, staff cars, ambulances, tank trucks, mobile field kitchens, and repair shops. The drivers seemed more familiar with teams of horses than the internal combustion engine. The first three days, they managed five and two-thirds miles an hour — "not quite so good as even the slowest troop train." Roads varied "from average to nonexistent." In some places, trucks broke through the road surface and had to be towed out one by one. Some days when they had counted on sixty or seventy miles, they would do three or four. They left Washington July 7 and did not arrive in San Francisco until September 6. "The old convoy had started me thinking about good, two lane highways." Three and a half decades later, as President, Eisenhower championed the interstate highway system. But in 1919, his mission "Through Darkest America" signified the dawn of a new era — **the motorization of the American people**.

### *"A Century of Travel"*

Deterding had written in 1916: "This is a century of travel, and the restlessness which has been created by the war will make the desire for travel still greater." By 1929, **23.1 million** autos were registered in the United States, up from 3.4 million in 1916. Each was being driven farther — from 4,500 miles per car in 1919 to 7,500 in 1929. Frederick Lewis Allen captured the transformation in *Only Yesterday*: villages on the railroad languished while villages on Route 61 "bloomed with garages, filling stations, hot-dog stands, chicken-dinner restaurants." The interurban trolley perished. Railroad after railroad gave up branch lines. "The age of steam was yielding to the gasoline age."

By 1929, **78 percent of the world's autos were in America** — five people per motor vehicle, compared to 30 in England, 33 in France, 102 in Germany, 702 in Japan, and 6,130 in the Soviet Union. Total U.S. oil demand rose from 1.03 million barrels a day in 1919 to 2.58 million in 1929. Oil's share of total energy consumption rose from 10 to 25 percent. Gasoline and fuel oil together accounted for 85 percent of total oil consumption in 1929. As for kerosene, it was negligible. **The "new light" had given way to the "new fuel."**

### *"The Magic of Gasoline"*

The transformation was accompanied by the emergence of the drive-in gasoline station. Before the 1920s, most gasoline was sold by storekeepers in cans under the counter, often adulterated with cheaper naphtha or kerosene. The first drive-in station is attributed to the Automobile Gasoline Company in St. Louis in 1907 — a small tin shack with a couple of barrels and two old hot-water tanks on high brackets with garden hoses to drain gasoline by gravity. By 1920, no more than 100,000 establishments sold gasoline (half were grocery and hardware stores). By 1929, the number had grown to **300,000**, almost all gas stations or garages. Drive-in stations specifically grew from about 12,000 in 1921 to **143,000** in 1929.

California, specifically Los Angeles, was the true incubator of the modern service station — standard structures with huge signs, restroom facilities, canopies, landscaped grounds, and paved entrances. Shell pioneered the standardized "cracker box" station. Stations made money not only from gasoline but from "TBA" — tires, batteries, and accessories. Standard of Indiana turned stations into grand emporiums selling everything from motor oil to furniture polishes to oil for sewing machines. A glass bowl atop the pump, where gasoline was forced up to be seen by the customer, reassured him of the product's purity.

Competition heated up, and the stations hoisted the signs and symbols of the new age: Texaco's star, Shell's scallop shell, Sun's radiant diamond, Union's "76," Phillips's "66" (suggested by Heinz's "57 Varieties"), Socony's flying horse, Gulf's orange disc, Standard of Indiana's red crown, Sinclair's brontosaurus, and Jersey Standard's patriotic red, white, and blue. Oil companies also made "uniquely American contributions to cartography" — the oil company road map. Gulf started the practice in 1914, handing out free maps at its first Pittsburgh station.

Shell of California required free uniforms for attendants, forbade magazine reading on duty, and insisted "Air and water service is a gratuity which you are expected to render the public, showing no distinction as to whether the individual is a Shell customer or not." By 1927, "service station salesmen" were expected to ask, "Can I check the tires for you?" and told: "Salesmen should be careful in their attendance upon Oriental and Latin classes of customers and refrain from using broken English in conversation with them."

**Bruce Barton**, the advertising man who had written *The Man Nobody Knows* (proving Jesus was "the greatest advertiser of his day"), called upon oil men in 1928 to reflect upon "the magic of gasoline": "My friends, it is the juice of the fountain of eternal youth that you are selling. It is health. It is comfort. It is success. And you have sold merely a bad smelling liquid at so many cents per gallon."

### *The Tempest in the Teapot*

Gasoline prices had become a political issue by the 1920s — whenever they rose, it was reported by press, discussed by governors, senators, and even presidents, and investigated by government branches. In 1923, Senator **Robert "Fighting Bob" La Follette** of Wisconsin conducted highly charged hearings on gasoline prices, warning that "if a few great oil companies" continued to manipulate prices, Americans would soon pay $1 a gallon. His warning lost punch as surplus mounted and prices plummeted — by April 1927, retail gasoline fell to **13 cents a gallon** in San Francisco and 10.5 cents in Los Angeles.

But La Follette was on target in another drama — he led the Senate crusade that uncovered one of America's most famous scandals: **Teapot Dome**. The field in Wyoming, named for the shape of a geological structure, was one of three oil fields (two others in California) set aside as "naval oil reserves" by the Taft and Wilson administrations. These reserves were meant to be "a supply laid up for some unexpected emergency" in time of war. A long battle had raged in Washington over whether private interests could lease them.

When **Warren G. Harding** won the presidency in 1920, he appointed Senator **Albert B. Fall** of New Mexico as Secretary of the Interior — a rough-and-ready rancher, lawyer, and miner described as "the frontiersman, the rough and ready, two-fisted fighter" who looked like "an old-time Texas sheriff." Fall's "belief in the unrestrained disposition of the public lands was as typically Western as his black, broad-brimmed Stetson hat and his love of fine horses." Conservationists called him a member of the "exploitation gang."

Fall wrested control of the naval oil reserves from the Navy Department and placed them in Interior. In spring 1922, just before leases were signed, **Walter Teagle** of Standard Oil visited advertising man **Albert Lasker** (who had directed Harding's campaign publicity) and warned: "the Interior Department is about to close a contract to lease Teapot Dome, and all through the industry it smells." Lasker reluctantly told the President, who paced behind his desk: "This isn't the first time that this rumor has come to me, but if Albert Fall isn't an honest man, I'm not fit to be President of the United States."

Fall leased Teapot Dome to **Harry Sinclair** and the more bountiful California reserve, Elk Hill, to **Edward Doheny**. Both were "new men" who had risen outside the Standard Oil inheritance. Doheny was a legendary prospector who once fought off a mountain lion with a knife; by the 1920s his company Pan American was a larger crude producer than any Standard Oil successor. Sinclair, son of a small-town Kansas druggist, had lost the family drugstore at age twenty, then built tiny oil companies one per lease in southeast Kansas and Osage Indian territory of Oklahoma. "Where he sat, there was the head of the table." By WWI he was the largest independent producer in the midcontinent; in 1916 he raised $50 million and assembled one of the ten largest integrated oil companies.

The Interior Department signed contracts with Doheny and Sinclair in April 1922 amid swirling rumors about Fall's friendships with "interests of an oleaginous nature." La Follette investigated and found naval officers who opposed the transfer had been reassigned to distant posts. In March 1923, Fall resigned, still respected but increasingly controversial.

The Harding Administration was sinking in scandal. Harding himself lamented: "I have no trouble with my enemies... It is my friends that are giving me my trouble." He died suddenly in San Francisco — "an embolism" said a doctor, but a newspaper editor called it "an illness that was part terror, part shame, and part utter confusion." **Calvin Coolidge** succeeded him.

The Senate's Public Lands Committee took up Teapot Dome. Fall had made expensive renovations to his New Mexico ranch and bought a neighboring ranch with hundred-dollar bills lifted from a small tin box. He claimed a $100,000 loan from **Ned McLean**, publisher of the *Washington Post*, who initially confirmed but then said Fall had returned the checks uncashed. On January 24, 1924, **Doheny** testified he had provided the $100,000, carried "in a little black bag" by his son to Fall's office — "just a loan to an old friend." He produced a mutilated promissory note with the signature ripped off (his wife held it "so as not to embarrass Fall").

By 1924, *The New Republic* said all of Washington was "wading shoulder-deep in oil... the sole subject of discussion is oil. Congress has abandoned all other business." Coolidge distanced himself through a "campaign of silence" and won the 1924 election handily. In 1928, it emerged that Sinclair had channeled several hundred thousand dollars more through a bogus company, Continental Trading Company — Fall had received at least **$409,000** total. In 1931, Fall became **the first Cabinet officer convicted and imprisoned for a felony committed while in office**. Sinclair got six and a half months for contempt. On his way to jail, Sinclair stopped at a Sinclair Consolidated board meeting where directors gave him "a public vote of confidence." Doheny was judged innocent, leading one Senator to complain, "You can't convict a million dollars in the United States."

### *The Colonel and the Liberty Bonds*

The scandal widened when investigators discovered the Continental Trading Company was really a kickback mechanism — prominent oil men received Liberty Bonds on oil purchases by their own companies. Sinclair had used part of his kickback to pay Fall and gave some bonds to the Republican National Committee. Among the recipients was **Colonel Robert Stewart**, chairman of Standard of Indiana — a broad-faced, bulky man who had ridden with Teddy Roosevelt's Rough Riders and risen through the company as a lawyer, not an oil man. Autocratic and commanding, he made Standard of Indiana the nation's number-one gasoline marketer. After years of evasion, Stewart admitted receiving about **$760,000** in bonds.

**John D. Rockefeller, Jr.** — the largest stockholder in Standard of Indiana — was appalled. Short, shy, serious, and reclusive, "Junior" had been schooled in "duty" and "responsibility." At Brown University he had hemmed his own dish towels. His vocation was philanthropy, not oil. He had even courted **Ida Tarbell**, his father's nemesis, delivering materials to her Gramercy Park apartment for review of his father's interviews. After Tarbell judged the elder Rockefeller's comments "self-serving," Junior abandoned the biography project.

Now Junior launched a proxy fight to oust Stewart. The colonel counterattacked: "If the Rockefellers want to fight, I'll show them how to fight." He had quadrupled the company's net assets, declared an extra dividend and stock split. Some saw it as East vs. West for control of oil. But the Rockefeller forces organized relentlessly, and in March 1929, with **60 percent** of stockholder votes, Stewart was out. Junior had intervened "not for mere profits but in the name of decency and high standards." A college professor wrote that "no endowment of a college nor support of a piece of research could have done more... to educate the public toward honest business." But the whole Teapot Dome scandal — from Fall, Doheny, and Sinclair to Stewart — had "picked up where the Standard Oil Trust had left off in ingraining in the public mind a nefarious image of the power and corruption of 'oil money.'"

### *Geophysics and Luck*

At the dawn of the automotive age, many worried supplies of the "new fuel" were running out. The years 1917-20 had been disappointing for discoveries. Leading geologists prophesied U.S. production limits were near. Some refineries ran at only 50 percent capacity for lack of crude. Walter Teagle remarked that "pessimism over crude supplies had become a chronic malady in the oil business." Oklahoma crude rose from $1.20/barrel in 1916 to **$3.36** by 1920; a record number of wells were drilled.

The technology for finding oil was about to transform. By 1920, "surface geology" — mapping visible landscapes — had gone as far as it could. The emerging science of **geophysics** provided new ways to "see" underground. Key innovations adapted from WWI military technology included:
- **Torsion balance** — measured gravity changes point to point, revealing subsurface structures. Developed by a Hungarian physicist, used by Germans in WWI to restore Rumanian fields.
- **Magnetometer** — measured vertical components of Earth's magnetic field.
- **Seismograph** — most powerful of all. Originally developed mid-19th century for earthquakes, Germans used it in WWI to locate enemy artillery. Refraction seismology was introduced to U.S. oil ~1923-24 by a German company: dynamite charges sent energy waves through underground structures, picked up by "geophones" on the surface, identifying salt domes where oil might be found. The reflection seismograph soon supplanted it, recording waves bouncing off rock interfaces to plot underground structures at all depths.
- **Aerial surveillance** — adapted from wartime troop spotting. Union Oil hired two former Army lieutenants in 1919 to photograph California terrain.
- **Micropaleontology** — analysis of microscopic fossils from drilling depths provided clues to sediment ages.
- Drilling itself improved: deepest wells went from 6,000 feet in 1918 to **10,000 feet** by 1930.

And always, luck. One of the most dramatic discoveries was at **Signal Hill**, rising 365 feet behind Long Beach, south of Los Angeles. Once used by local Indians to signal brethren on Catalina Island, later coveted by real estate developers. In June 1921, during subdivision into residential lots, Shell's **Alamitos Number 1** blew in, creating a stampede. Parcels were so small that wooden derricks' legs interlaced. Property owners got 50 percent royalties. Even the next-of-kin of persons buried in Sunnyside Cemetery received royalty checks for oil drawn from beneath grave plots. Signal Hill made California the **number-one producing state in 1923**, source of one quarter of the world's oil output. Yet that same year, the Federal Trade Commission still warned crude was "being rapidly depleted." In fact, American crude production exceeded domestic demand for the first time in a decade.

## Chapter 12: The Fight for New Production

### *The Tycoon*

**Harry Doherty** was an anomaly in oil — with oversized glasses and Van Dyke beard, he looked like "the professor" rather than a businessman. But he was among the great entrepreneurs of the 1920s, controlling a host of companies including **Cities Service**, earning the title "the nearest approach on Wall Street to Ned the Newsboy of the Horatio Alger stories." He began working at age nine selling newspapers in Columbus, Ohio, dropped out of school at twelve ("I had not been in school more than ten days before I grew to hate school worse than Satan"), rose through night school and engineering training to become director of 150 companies — gas and electric utilities composing "Cities Service." When one company struck oil in Kansas drilling for gas, Doherty became an oil man too. Eccentric and prolific with epigrams: "Never give orders — give instructions... Make a game out of your work... The greatest dividend in human life is happiness." His favorite relaxation was driving through New York City traffic.

Doherty was an intellectual gadfly of oil, insistent on one theme: the **"rule of capture"** had to be eliminated. This doctrine, sanctioned by English common law regarding migratory wild beasts, meant every operator drilled as fast as possible, draining oil from under neighbors' property. The courts offered "scant solace": "Only go and do likewise." The result was chaotic flush production and wildly fluctuating prices with every discovery.

Doherty argued the multiplication of wells and rapid production from the rule of capture exhausted underground pressure prematurely. Oil that might otherwise be produced was left underground, unrecoverable — gas and water pressure provided the "lift" to bring oil to the surface. His solution: fields should be **"unitized"** — tapped as single units with output apportioned among owners, producing at controlled rates to maintain underground pressure and maximize ultimate recovery. "Conservation" meant measured production for the largest recoverable resource, not reduced consumption.

The radical part: Doherty insisted the **Federal government** would have to lead, or at least sanction industry cooperation, with public enforcement of superior production practices. Most of the industry was hostile. Larger companies would discuss voluntary cooperation but no more. Independents wanted nothing to do with unitization — "They wanted their chance to get rich too." Doherty was a "diabolical needier" — barred three times from the API board and three times from presenting at API meetings, he hired his own hall. Others called him "that crazy man" and "an oil man is a barbarian with a suit on."

But Doherty had a friend in **President Coolidge**. In August 1924, he wrote: "If the public some day in the near future awakens to the fact that we have become a bankrupt nation as far as oil is concerned... they will blame both the men of the oil industry and the men who held public offices." Coolidge established the **Federal Oil Conservation Board** after winning the 1924 election, declaring: "The supremacy of nations may be determined by the possession of available petroleum and its products." The board stimulated research showing natural gas was not just "a commodity of smaller commercial value" but provided the essential underground pressure — dissipating it through helter-skelter production left vast amounts of petroleum unrecoverable.

**William Farish**, president of Humble (Jersey's Texas affiliate), who had scorned Doherty in 1925, was thanking him by 1928 for "making the industry see the virtues of better production methods." Farish became a strong advocate of unitization. But Doherty grossly underestimated the possibilities for finding new oil. **J. Howard Pew** of Sun Oil, a bitter opponent of government involvement, sarcastically predicted that "the nitrates in the soil would disappear, timber reserves be depleted, and the rivers of the world change their course before petroleum reserves were exhausted."

### *The Rising Tide*

It was Pew, not Doherty, who proved the more accurate prophet. Spring 1926 saw the first major discoveries in what became the **Greater Seminole field** in Oklahoma — one of the most rapid developments the world had seen. A breakneck, wasteful drilling competition driven by the rule of capture, with traditional boomtown chaos — "streets clogged with equipment, workers, gamblers, hucksters, and drunks; hastily built wooden structures; the stifling odor of escaping gas and the acrid smell of burning oil." By July 30, 1927, just sixteen months after the first major finds, the single field produced **527,000 barrels per day**. Other major discoveries followed in Oklahoma. In Texas, the late 1920s established the **Permian Basin** — the vast, sun-scorched region of West Texas and New Mexico — as one of the world's great oil concentrations.

Technology also altered the demand side. **Cracking** techniques increased gasoline yield per barrel — one barrel of cracked oil produced as much gasoline as two barrels uncracked, and cracked gasoline had superior antiknock properties. So though gasoline demand grew, crude demand didn't grow at the same rate, adding to surplus.

By decade's end, the gloomy predictions of the early 1920s had been washed away by floods of oil. Flush production — "too many straws in a tub" — damaged reservoirs and reduced ultimate recoverable resources. The massive oversupply disrupted markets and caused sudden price collapses. Yet as glut mounted, opinion shifted toward Doherty's conservation and production control ideas — not to forestall shortage (proof of surplus was everywhere) but to prevent ruinous flush production that shook pricing structures.

The debate over who should control production — voluntarily or under government aegis, Federal or state — was fierce. Within Jersey Standard, **Teagle** favored voluntary control while **Farish** at Humble insisted: "The industry is powerless to help itself... We must have government help, permission to do things we cannot do today." Farish added: "I have come to the conclusion that there are more individual fools in the petroleum industry than in any other business." Independent producers opposed government regulation: "No state corporation commission will tell me how to run my business," thundered **Tom Slick** to cheering Oklahoma producers. The independents formed the **Independent Petroleum Association of America** and campaigned for a tariff on imported oil (mainly Venezuelan oil imported by majors), but failed to get it into the Smoot-Hawley Act of 1930.

### *Emerging Competition*

The oil industry had always confronted chronic supply-demand imbalances, responding with consolidation and integration. In the 1920s, the same strategies reemerged among Standard Oil successor companies and others, turning them into vigorous competitors. A new dimension appeared: oil companies were becoming **marketers**, selling automotive fuel directly to motorists at brand-name stations springing up across America. Oil wars were being fought not only for foreign supply and markets but also on America's main streets. In its drive toward consolidation and integration, the American oil industry began to take on its modern and familiar outline.

The 1911 dissolution had left **Standard Oil of New Jersey** a huge refining company with virtually no oil of its own, highly dependent on other companies. Walter Teagle sought secure crude sources both domestic and foreign. As early as 1919, Jersey bought just over half of **Humble Oil**, a leading Texas producer that badly needed capital. By 1921 Humble was the largest producer in Texas. **Standard of Indiana** moved aggressively to assure its own crude supply from the Southwest and Wyoming, and also purchased **Pan American Petroleum** (Doheny's company), one of the leading American companies in Mexico. Meanwhile, major crude producers went downstream to assure markets: **Ohio Oil Company** (later Marathon) had been the largest Standard Oil producing company before dissolution; now it moved into refining and marketing, eventually controlling half of the immensely prolific Yates field in Texas.

**Phillips Petroleum** was created by **Frank Phillips**, an ex-barber and ex-bond salesman with considerable flair for oil deals. Also a banker, he was adept at overcoming investor skepticism and raising money in New York, Chicago, and other cities. By the mid-1920s, Phillips and his brother had built the company into one of the major independents, in the same league as Gulf and the Texas Company. In November 1927, Phillips opened its first refinery in the Texas Panhandle and its first service station in Wichita, Kansas. To start things off, officials planned to offer coupons for ten free gallons of gas. "Sure, go ahead," Phillips replied. "It isn't worth as much as water anyway. Give 'em all you want to." By 1930, within three years of its first station, Phillips had built or acquired **6,750 retail outlets** in twelve states.

Competitive pressures pushed other companies to break through the wholesale wall into retail by acquiring gas stations and marketing facilities. Between 1926 and 1928, **Gulf** expanded retail rapidly into the North Central states. The Texas Company and Shell were marketing in all **forty-eight states** by decade's end. Established retailers had to expand into new areas to protect profitability as new competitors invaded their territories.

These invasions finished the work of the Supreme Court. A kind of shadow Standard Oil Trust had persisted for a decade after dissolution — successor companies remained tied by contracts, habits, personal relationships, old loyalties, and shared dominant stockholders. Each successor refining company had been based in a specific geographical region, and for a decade they more or less respected one another's borders. But in the 1920s, they began invading one another's territories. **Atlantic Refining** entered the markets of both Standard of New Jersey and Standard of New York — "as a matter of protection, rather than of desire." Jersey and other Eastern successors got into a bitter, highly publicized price war with Midwestern successors including Standard of Indiana. **Ida Tarbell** wrote with astonishment: "It certainly looks very much as if the Standard Oil Company might be crumbling — crumbling within."

By the mid-1920s, the concept of the "Standard Oil Group" exerting total control was obsolete. The successor companies were turning into large, fully integrated companies that, along with "independents" like the Texas Company and Gulf, dominated the industry. A 1927 FTC study found the separated Standard companies controlled **45 percent** of refined products output, down from 80 percent two decades earlier. The cozy relationship had dissipated: "There is no longer unity of control of these companies through community of interest," the FTC found. On price control, the FTC was skeptical that Standard companies could manipulate prices: "The price movements for the longer periods are substantially controlled by supply and demand conditions."

### *"Those Sunkist Sons of Bitches"*

The breakup of the Standard Oil Trust into aggressive competitors, combined with the appearance of new companies based on crude discoveries or gasoline refining and marketing, spurred a powerful wave of **mergers**. Rockefeller's impulse toward acquisition and consolidation lived on — not to exert total control (no longer possible) but to protect and improve competitive position. Standard of New York bought a major California producer and refiner, then merged with the Vacuum Oil Company to form **Socony-Vacuum** and develop the brand name **Mobil**. Standard of California acquired one of the other major California producers.

**Shell** grew rapidly through aggressive acquisition, but continued to involve American investors per Deterding's 1916 dictum: "It is, of course, always galling (apart from political considerations) in any country to see an enterprise doing well without local people being interested." Deterding was put off by American investment bankers: "Of all the grasping individuals I have ever met... the American bankers absolutely take the cake." In 1924, Shell came close to buying a production company called **Belridge** near Bakersfield, California for $8 million but decided it was too expensive. Fifty-five years later, in 1979, Shell finally bought Belridge — for **$3.6 billion**. Shell also acquired a quarter of **Union Oil of California**, but California stockholders invoked patriotism against "parties foreign to California and entirely unknown to us," embroiling the Senate and FTC, and eventually forced Shell to sell its holdings (though Shell made a 50 percent return on a two-year investment).

The Texas Company and Phillips came close to merging. So did Gulf and Standard of Indiana. Between 1929 and 1933, **Standard of New Jersey and Standard of California** devoted much managerial time to merger negotiations. To keep conversations secret, Walter Teagle traveled to one Lake Tahoe rendezvous in a private railroad car under an assumed name. Talks collapsed partly because of Standard of California's tough negotiating stance — its president **Kenneth Kingsbury** and associates were known to Jersey people as **"King Rex" and "those sunkist sons of bitches."** A more important reason for failure was Jersey's accounting system, which could not satisfactorily establish either book value or true profitability.

One thing united virtually the whole industry by decade's end: though scientific understanding of oil production had advanced, opposition to direct Federal regulation was overwhelming. Harry Doherty, outraged, predicted: "The oil industry is in for a long period of trouble... I do not know how long it will take, but I will stake the last shred of my reputation that the day will come when every oil man will wish we had sought Federal legislation." His own health broken from the strain, he wrote in 1929: "If a man has ever gotten a dirtier deal from an Industry than I have gotten from the Oil Industry, I would certainly like to meet him. I often wish to God I had never gone into the oil business."

No one paid attention to his prophecy. The new corporate giants were preoccupied with sorting out competitive positions, and the prospects for stabilization without government intervention looked reasonable. But then the stock market crashed in October 1929, heralding the Great Depression. And in autumn 1930, a throw of the dice led to the discovery of the largest oil field ever found in the forty-eight states — **the Black Giant** — one that could have met a very substantial part of the entire American demand. Harry Doherty would turn out to have been right on the mark.

## Chapter 12: "The Fight for New Production" (continued — foreign oil)

The equation — oil equals power — had already been proven on WWI battlefields, and from that conflict emerged a new era in relations between oil companies and nation-states. If oil was power, it was also a symbol of sovereignty. That inevitably meant a collision between oil companies' objectives and nation-states' interests — a clash that would become a lasting characteristic of international politics.

### *Mexico's Golden Lane*

In the early twentieth century, Western Hemisphere exploration outside the U.S. centered on **Mexico**. The two dominating companies were **Pan American Petroleum** (led by Edward Doheny) and **Mexican Eagle** (led by Englishman **Sir Weetman Pearson**, later Lord Cowdray). Doheny, already successful in California, had gone to Mexico in 1900 at the invitation of the head of Mexican State Railways, who needed fuel.

Pearson's interests were far more sweeping — he was one of the greatest nineteenth-century engineer contractors. Talented, innovative, and a daring entrepreneur, "born to engineering" with gifts in mathematics — "slow, steady, meticulous, and persevering." The "**Pearson touch**" — his knack for grand-scale success — was much admired. To his daughter: "Dame Fortune is very elusive; the only way is to sketch a fortune which you think you can realize and then go for it baldheaded." To his son: "Do not hesitate for one second to be in opposition to your colleagues or in overriding their decisions. *No business can be a permanent success unless its head is an autocrat.*" He built Blackwall Tunnel under the Thames, four tunnels under the East River in New York for the Pennsylvania Railroad, and Dover Harbor. His eventual empire included the *Financial Times*, the *Economist*, Penguin Books, and the investment bank Lazard's in London.

President **Porfirio Diaz**, Mexico's dictator, invited Pearson to undertake major projects — the Grand Canal draining Mexico City, Vera Cruz Harbor, and the Tehuantepec Railway connecting Atlantic and Pacific. Pearson cultivated Diaz with European objets d'art and £100,000 to found a hospital. "Poor Mexico," Diaz supposedly remarked, "so far from God and so close to the United States" — he invited a world-famous British engineer to balance American dominance.

In 1901, Pearson missed a rail connection in the Texas border town of Laredo, discovered the town was "wild with the oil craze" from Spindletop three months earlier. He examined every oil prospectus, then cabled his manager to "move sharply" to acquire Mexican oil lands — all accomplished during a nine-hour stopover. He hired **Captain Anthony Lucas** (of Spindletop fame) to assist in Mexico. After a full decade of large expenditures with little to show, Pearson was despondent: "I entered lightly on this enterprise, not realizing its many problems." To his wife: "I cannot help but think what a craven adventurer I am compared to men of old... I am slothful and horribly afraid of two things — first that my pride in my judgment and administration should be scattered to the winds and secondly that I should have to begin life again."

Finally in 1910, Pearson (now **Lord Cowdray**) made major strikes, beginning with the fabulous **Potrero del Llano 4**, which flowed at **110,000 barrels per day** — considered the biggest oil well in the world. Production centered along the "**Golden Lane**" near Tampico, where 70,000-100,000-barrel wells were not uncommon. By 1913, Mexican oil was even used on Russian railroads. During WWI, Mexico became critical for the U.S., meeting **20 percent** of domestic American demand by 1920. By 1921, Mexico was the **second-largest oil producer in the world** with annual output of **193 million barrels**.

But the political environment had changed dramatically. In 1911, the 81-year-old Diaz was overthrown ("distracted by a toothache that had gone septic"), inaugurating the **Mexican Revolution**. Violence reduced foreign investment appetite. E. J. Sadler, head of Jersey's Mexican operations, was captured by bandits, beaten savagely, and left for dead — thereafter he never carried more than $25 in cash and always wore a cheap gold watch. Oil camps belonging to Mexican Eagle were overrun by rebels and employees killed.

In October 1918, Cowdray was approached by **Calouste Gulbenkian** on behalf of Deterding — Royal Dutch/Shell wanted to buy a substantial part of Mexican Eagle. Cowdray, weary and wary of further risk, accepted. Shell's acquisition proved well-timed: almost immediately, salt water intruded into the big producing wells, beginning Mexico's decline.

The emerging conflict established a lasting battle line between governments and oil companies. In Mexico, the issue was sovereignty and ownership — to whom did the benefits of oil belong? Until 1884, subsoil resources had belonged to the crown/nation. Diaz altered this, giving subsoil ownership to surface landowners who welcomed foreign capital (which eventually controlled 90 percent of all oil properties). The revolution's **Article 27 of the 1917 Constitution** restored national ownership of subsoil resources, becoming the center of battle. Mexico had recaptured the oil but couldn't develop it without foreign capital. Various Mexican regimes imposed regulations and tax hikes, fueling continuous conflicts. Doheny and other American oil men whipped up sentiment in Washington for military intervention to protect "vital" American-owned reserves.

Relations between Mexico and the U.S. became continually turbulent — Washington withheld diplomatic recognition, and the countries seemed close to war more than once. When Washington looked south, it saw "instability, insecurity, banditry, anarchy, a dangerous threat to the flow of a strategic resource, and welching on contracts." When Mexico looked north, it saw "foreign exploitation, humiliation, the violation of sovereignty, and the enormous weight, pressure, and power of 'Yankee imperialism.'" Oil company investment declined, output plummeted, and Mexico soon ceased being a world oil power.

### *General Gomez's Venezuelan "Hacienda"*

The fear of shortage, oil's new role in national power, and the profits to be made fueled what Royal Dutch/Shell called "the fight for new production" in its 1920 annual report: "We must not be outstripped in this struggle to obtain new territory... our geologists are everywhere where any chance of success exists." **Venezuela** was at the top of the list. The political turmoil in Mexico was stimulating a wholesale migration of oil men to Venezuela, where early Spanish explorers had observed Indians using oil seepages to caulk canoes.

Venezuela offered a friendly political climate — the handiwork of **General Juan Vicente Gomez**, the cruel, cunning, and avaricious dictator who ruled for twenty-seven years for his personal enrichment. Venezuela was an underpopulated, impoverished agricultural nation. Of 184 legislature members in the mid-1890s, at least **112 managed to claim the rank of general**. Gomez seized power in 1908, turning the country into a personal hacienda. Barely literate, he fathered **97 illegitimate children** (by one count), installed his brother as vice-president (until the brother was murdered by Gomez's son), affected Teddy Roosevelt big game hunter garb, was pro-German during WWI (dressing up in imitation of the Kaiser), and was called "scoundrel" by Woodrow Wilson. The British minister described Gomez as "an 'Absolute Monarch' in the most medieval sense of the word."

Gomez shrewdly recognized that luring foreign investment required political predictability and fiscal stability — in sharp contrast to Mexico. His government even sought help from the American minister in Caracas and American companies in drafting the **Petroleum Law**, setting terms for concessions, taxes, and royalties. By 1913, Royal Dutch/Shell was already at work near **Lake Maracaibo**, with minor commercial production beginning in 1914.

In 1919, Jersey Standard sent scouts to Venezuela, including a geologist who recommended skipping the Maracaibo Basin altogether: "Anyone who stays there a few weeks is almost certain to become infected with malaria or liver and intestinal disorders." But a Jersey manager disagreed — what counted was Royal Dutch/Shell's commitment there: "The fact that they have spent millions there leads us to suspect that there is considerable oil in this country. Failure to develop production in Latin America could endanger Standard Oil's ability to remain predominant."

Getting concessions on Gomez's "hacienda" wasn't easy. Standard's representative arranged to see the general directly, but on the same day, a concession was bid on by **Julio Mendez** — Gomez's son-in-law — who won and immediately flipped it to another company. Eventually, Jersey acquired acreage including **4,200 acres under Lake Maracaibo** — considered a joke. A Jersey official suggested buying a boat so that "if the 4,200 underwater acres proved valueless as an oil concession, the company could go into the fishing business."

Exploration was difficult and hazardous — virtually no roads passable by auto, geologists traveled by canoe or mule, rivers on maps didn't exist or were tributaries of different systems. "Mosquitoes were the worst and largest of any place I ever saw." One Jersey driller was killed by an arrow from hostile Indians; Shell protected tractor cabins with special cloth dense enough to stop arrows.

In December 1922, despite skepticism, Shell's **Barroso well** in the **La Rosa field** (Maracaibo Basin) blew out with an uncontrolled flow estimated at **100,000 barrels per day**. The field had been selected and staked by **George Reynolds** — the same "solid British oak" who had guided Anglo-Persian to its first discoveries in Persia a decade and a half earlier, then been let go with only a minuscule bonus. Now his persistence had opened Venezuela.

The Barroso blowout announced Venezuela to the world. The scramble intensified — Jersey, Shell, Gulf, and others competed fiercely for concessions. Gomez played them against each other, extracting maximum personal benefit. His family members and cronies served as intermediaries, taking cuts on every deal. Standard Oil of Indiana also entered Venezuela, buying concessions from the **Creole Syndicate** — a group of Venezuelan insiders close to Gomez. Indiana Standard paid $33 million for its Venezuelan properties, one of the largest foreign investments of the era.

### *The Russian Question*

While the fight for new production raged in Venezuela and elsewhere, the question of Russian oil loomed large. The **Bolshevik Revolution** of 1917 had nationalized all oil properties, wiping out the investments of the Nobels, the Rothschilds, and Royal Dutch/Shell. The question was whether to deal with the Soviets or boycott them. Anglo-Soviet discussions proceeded with great difficulty. Lenin passed a secret message to **Leonid Krasin** in London: "That swine Lloyd George has no scruples or shame in the way he deceives; don't believe a word he says and gull him three times as much." Krasin proved singularly adept at stimulating British businessmen eager for trade.

The Soviet Union was headed toward economic disaster — industrial underproduction, inflation, severe capital shortage, and widespread famine. It desperately needed foreign capital. In November 1920, Moscow announced a new policy of offering concessions to foreign investors. In March 1921, Lenin went further with the **New Economic Policy (NEP)** — expanded domestic markets, return of private enterprise, broadened foreign trade concessions. "We cannot by our own strength restore our shattered economy without equipment and technical assistance from abroad," Lenin declared. His first two examples of concessions were oil — "a quarter of Baku, a quarter of Grozny." A Bolshevik newspaper called petroleum "liquid gold."

Lenin's rapprochement with the West met opposition from comrades including **Stalin**, who warned the businessmen would include "the best spies of the world bourgeoisie." Nevertheless, Krasin signed the **Anglo-Soviet Trade Agreement** in London, then proceeded to dangle oil concessions to companies while playing them off against each other.

Deterding claimed not to be disappointed about the Nobel deal. He believed Standard Oil's entrance into Russia brought insurance to all foreign investors. "We have already several good seats and a very great part of the food on the Russian table," he lectured Gulbenkian. "Dining is very much better in company with other people who have also got a very big interest in the dinner." But Deterding had no intention of accepting the Bolsheviks' sell-off of what he regarded as his properties. Nor did Walter Teagle.

### *In Search of a United Front*

In 1922, Jersey, Royal Dutch/Shell, and the Nobels formed the **Front Uni** — a common bloc against the Soviet threat. A dozen other companies joined, pledging to fight the Soviet Union together and not be picked off individually. They agreed to seek compensation for nationalized property and refrain from dealing with Russia independently. But "the brethren of oil merchants" hardly trusted one another, let alone the Soviets. The Front Uni stood on unsteady legs, and Krasin continued to play the companies off against each other "with a master's skill."

The Soviet oil industry, virtually dormant 1920-1923, revived quickly with Western technology imports, and the USSR reentered the world market as an exporter. Jersey executives faced a dilemma — buy cheaper Russian oil or stand back on moral/business grounds? Teagle regretted the Nobel investment: "I am convinced that instead of sitting up with a sick child of this character and nursing it along for years, we could have taken the same amount of money and invested it elsewhere in the oil business in such a way that the investment would have immediately become productive."

**Heinrich Riedemann**, head of Standard's German operations, saw it differently — private companies could not easily defend their rights against confiscation and nationalization. "The participation of a government in industrial and business enterprise as in Russia is new and unheard of in the history of business." Other Western groups were already seeking concessions across the Soviet Union — from Baku to the Caucasus to Sakhalin off Siberia. The Soviets were selling oil from those properties as if they were their own.

Teagle reluctantly agreed to form a joint Jersey-Shell buying organization in November 1924 to explore options with the Soviets. "I know I am old fashioned in feeling this way," he said, "but somehow or other the idea of trying to be on friendly terms with the man who burglarizes your house or steals your property has never appealed to me." He wrote to Riedemann lamenting the hasty handling of the matter. Cooperation with Royal Dutch/Shell was one thing, but cooperation with the Soviets remained repugnant. "Affording the Soviet a market for petroleum not only is actually becoming a receiver of stolen goods, but operates to encourage the thief to persist in his evil courses by making theft readily profitable."

A Jersey-Shell agreement for joint Soviet purchase seemed imminent — even providing that 5% of the purchase price would compensate former owners. But both Teagle and Deterding remained personally skeptical. When the agreement fell apart in early 1927, Deterding was "almost gleeful": "I am so glad that nothing came of these Soviet deals... I feel that everybody will regret at some time that he had anything to do with these robbers, whose only aim is the destruction of all civilization and the re-establishment of brute force."

Deterding's anti-communism had intensified after his marriage to **Lydia Pavlova**, a White Russian emigre. He even telegraphed John D. Rockefeller Jr., beseeching him to block Standard companies from buying Russian oil, calling the Soviet regime "anti-Christ" and begging "for humanity's sake" that "all decent people" abstain from helping the Soviets.

### *Price War*

Despite Deterding's entreaties, **Standard Oil of New York (Socony)** and **Vacuum** went their own way, dealing directly with the Soviets. Socony built a kerosene plant for the Russians at Batum and leased it back. Both companies contracted to buy large amounts of Russian kerosene, particularly for India and Asian markets. Socony needed Russian oil for India; Shell had other sources to substitute, but Socony did not.

Deterding went into "an awful rage," denouncing Socony's president **C. F. Meyer** as "a man who has neither honor nor intelligence." In 1927, in retaliation, Deterding launched a **brutal price war** in India that spread to other markets worldwide. Socony counterattacked, cutting prices elsewhere. Deterding orchestrated a press campaign against Standard of New York for buying "communist" oil. Jersey was dragged in too — accused of buying communist oil. Deterding expected Jersey to bring Socony "sharply to heel," saying "the minor New York Cy. should be made to understand that she is the servant of the Jersey Cy., and not her boss."

Jersey's executives suspected Deterding had withdrawn from the joint Soviet deal due to British government pressure, but a senior British official denied this: "Sir Henri Deterding always got himself into hot water because of his tactlessness." When Russians questioned the compensation arrangement, "Sir Henri completely lost his head and told them that he would prevent any one from buying Soviet oil.... This was an utterly stupid and at the same time thoroughly characteristic thing for him to do."

Vacuum's president countered accusations of betraying American principles by noting American farmers were busily selling cotton and other products to Russia: "Is it more unrighteous to buy from Russia than to sell to it?" By the late 1920s, the major companies were weary of the whole Russian matter. The gusher at **Baba Gurgur in Iraq** turned attention to new Middle East sources. Jersey adopted a neutral stance — neither seeking Soviet contracts nor boycotting. Riedemann summed up in autumn 1927: "Personally, I have buried Russia." But Soviet oil proved "a lively corpse," as growing volumes entered the world market, and Deterding's price war had far larger consequences for all players in international oil.

## Chapter 13: The Flood

### *Dad Joiner and the East Texas Discovery*

**Columbus "Dad" Joiner** was seventy years old in 1930, walked bent from rheumatic fever, and was the caricature of a down-on-his-luck wildcat promoter — always optimistic, silver-tongued, ever-persuasive. He had a silky-smooth complexion (attributed to eating carrots), only seven weeks of formal schooling, had been tutored at home with the Bible as his text, and learned to write by copying the Book of Genesis. He absorbed the King James language and could spin an enticing web of promised wealth. He also wrote love letters to widows whose names he found in newspaper obituaries — "his interest, to be sure, was not in their lonely hearts; it was in their purses."

Joiner was one of many in the big oil promotion frenzy of the 1920s. Oil stocks and deals were madly enticing in the speculative climate. One promoter, **Dr. Frederick Cook** (who claimed to have beaten Admiral Perry to the North Pole), mailed up to 300,000 letters a month, pulling in some $2 million in one year before being apprehended. The **General Lee Development Company** found a Robert A. Lee, descendant of the Confederate general, and had him tell investors "I would rather lead you and a thousand others to financial independence than to have won Fredericksburg or Chancellorsville."

Dad Joiner was a small-time operator who actually wanted to wildcat for oil, not just fleece the gullible. He worked out of Dallas, hanging around the Adolphus Hotel lobby. His eyes eventually fell on **East Texas** — drought-ridden, dirt-poor, piney woods, sandy soil, still mired in agricultural depression. Neither Overton nor Henderson had one paved road. Joiner told the locals that under their barren soil lay "an ocean of oil, a treasure trove all the kings of earth might covet."

Geologists scoffed — there was no oil in East Texas. But Joiner was convinced by **"Doc Lloyd"** — a mysterious, 300-pound, self-proclaimed geologist who wore sombreros and riding boots, was variously said to be a veterinarian, pharmacist, and patent medicine showman. Lloyd's geology description was totally fabricated — he was a "trendologist" who drew trend lines from all major U.S. oil fields intersecting in East Texas. But he did one memorable thing: he told Joiner exactly where to drill.

Joiner mailed prospectuses with Doc Lloyd's fictitious geology to his "sucker list" and scraped together money to drill on **Daisy Bradford's** farm in Rusk County. He paid workers in "royalty rights" and "certificates" against possibilities of discovery — sold at deep discounts, they became local currency. A Texaco geologist visited and uttered the famous taunt: "I'll drink every barrel of oil you get out of that hole." For three years (1927-1930), Joiner and his motley crew drilled with rusted, third-hand equipment amid constant breakdowns.

In early September 1930, **Daisy Bradford Number 3** tested positively. A shantytown called **"Joinerville"** sprang up overnight on the road to the well. Thousands gathered for the vigil — it felt like a religious event. Hamburgers cost a quarter (vs. sixteen cents elsewhere). On **October 3, 1930**, at 8 PM, a gurgling was heard, the driller shouted "Put out the fires! Put out your cigarettes! *Quick!*" The earth trembled, oil and water shot high above the derrick. The crowd went mad. A crewman pulled a pistol and fired into the oil spray — three men tackled him and wrestled the gun away, as one spark could have caused the well to explode.

### *The Black Giant*

"Joiner's Wildcat a Gusher" headlined the *Henderson Daily News*. Industry leaders initially responded with skepticism. But over the next three months, two other wildcat wells blew in. The **East Texas reservoir** proved to be **forty-five miles long, five to ten miles wide, 140,000 acres** — the **Black Giant**, the largest oil field ever discovered in America. The boom dwarfed everything before it — Spindletop, Cushing, Greater Seminole, Oklahoma City, Signal Hill.

In early 1931, while the Great Depression gripped the nation, East Texas was exuberant and going crazy. People poured in, crowding into tent cities and shanty towns. This fundamentalist region of stern values suddenly became home to honky-tonk districts catering to every vice. By end of April 1931, the area produced **340,000 barrels per day**, with a new well spudded every hour.

Prices collapsed catastrophically. From **$1.85/barrel in Texas in 1926**, to about a dollar in 1930, to as low as **fifteen cents** by end of May 1931 — some oil sold for **six cents**, even **two cents** a barrel. By early June 1931, one thousand wells had been completed and East Texas was producing **500,000 barrels per day**. Cheap, pint-sized "teakettle" refineries sprang up producing "Eastex gasoline" sold at discount stations offering premiums — a crate of tomatoes or a free chicken dinner with each fill-up.

### *Dad Joiner's Deal with H. L. Hunt*

Dad Joiner had been "very cavalier" in his promotion — selling more "interests" than actually existed, some leases sold multiple times (one at least eleven times). Of his 5,000 acres of leases, he had clear title to just two. A local newspaper editor cast him as "the second Moses to be led to the Promised Land, permitted to gaze upon its 'milk and honey,' and then denied the privilege of entering."

**Haroldson Lafayette "H. L." Hunt** — stout, wearing a straw boater and string tie, called "Boy" by Joiner — was a failed cotton farmer with two formidable talents: gambling and complex mental arithmetic (like Rockefeller and Deterding). He had opened a gambling hall in El Dorado, Arkansas, switched to oil when the Ku Klux Klan threatened to burn it down, and was already maintaining **two wives, each with a growing family**.

Hunt befriended Joiner before the well blew in. After the discovery, Hunt holed up with Joiner in **Room 1553 at the Baker Hotel** for an interminable negotiation. Crucially, Hunt was being fed secret reports on the nearby **Deep Rock well** — showing a second major discovery. After 36+ nonstop hours, between midnight and 2 AM on **Thanksgiving, November 27, 1930**, Joiner signed all rights to "Boy." Hunt ordered cheese and crackers to celebrate.

Hunt paid Joiner **$1.33 million** ($30,000 up front, rest from production). When Joiner later learned Hunt had paid $20,000 to the Deep Rock driller for secret advance information, he sued for fraud but then withdrew. Hunt became the largest independent in East Texas and went on to amass an immense fortune. He later achieved notoriety as a right-wing patron, health food promoter, and enemy of white flour and sugar. Dad Joiner spent the money wildcatting and romancing his "secretary" — died at 87, still wildcatting, net worth barely more than his car and house.

### *Anarchy in the Oil Field*

The East Texas flood brought prices down nationwide, threatening ruin for even the largest producers. The rush of competitive production meant "competitive suicide" for the entire industry. Controlling the East Texas field was complicated by fragmented ownership — independents owned much of it and resisted any surrender of freedom that might reduce their advantage over the hated big companies.

The **Texas Railroad Commission** — originally created in 1891 by Governor Jim Hogg for railroad regulation — had been given some mandate over oil. However, it was specifically forbidden from "economic waste" regulation (market proration). It could only prevent "physical waste." The commission argued that flush production would cause stripper wells to shut down (physical waste), but federal courts repeatedly blocked its proration efforts. The commission was even held in contempt of court.

**Frederick Godber**, a Shell director from London, visited the U.S. in spring 1931 and found "unmitigated gloom." The chairman of Standard of Indiana was "very depressed, almost panicky." Teagle at Jersey was "very pessimistic, feels there is nothing to do but sit back and rely on lowering prices." Godber reported: "much of the industry's troubles are due to known causes over which individuals have little or no control and which cannot be remedied until laws are passed in the various producing states."

In Oklahoma, Governor **"Alfalfa Bill" Murray** proclaimed a state of emergency, declared martial law, and ordered the state militia to take control of major oil fields, keeping them closed until "price hits one dollar." **"A dollar a barrel"** became the rallying cry throughout the oil states.

By August 1931, both East Texas and the petroleum market were in total anarchy. Production exceeded **one million barrels per day** — almost half of total American demand. Crude prices had plunged to **thirteen cents a barrel**. Texas oil was even underselling Russian petroleum in Europe. Production costs averaged around eighty cents. Violence was in the air — talk of dynamiting wells and pipelines. The Texas economy was on the verge of collapse.

**Texas Governor Ross Sterling** — a founder and former chairman of Humble Oil — declared war on East Texas. On **August 17, 1931**, he announced a "state of insurrection" and "open rebellion," sending in several thousand **National Guardsmen** and **Texas Rangers** (arriving on horseback because rains made roads impassable). They set up on **"Proration Hill"** and shut down production within days. An eerie quiet settled over East Texas. Even the chickens, which had feasted on insects drawn by gas flares, were forced to "return to the prosaic ante-petroleum practice of scratching for worms."

The National Guard commander banned "beach pajamas" — a garb favored by the busy prostitutes — and ancillary businesses went into a sharp slump. The shutdown actually worked: prices rose from thirteen cents. The Railroad Commission continued issuing proration orders enforced by state troopers. By **April 1932**, prices were nearly back to the magic dollar — **ninety-eight cents**. In 1932, the commission issued **nineteen separate proration orders**, each declared invalid by the judiciary. But the market held firm, and stronger prices finally persuaded many independents of the value of prorationing.

In November, Governor Sterling gave the commission the specific power to counter "economic waste" — calling a special legislative session and ramming through a bill allowing **market prorationing**. The new law was facilitated by understanding that the East Texas reservoir was driven by **"water drive"** (not gas pressure as elsewhere) — rapid, chaotic production would damage the water drive and prematurely stunt overall output.

### *Hot Oil and the Crisis of 1933*

Despite the Railroad Commission's new powers, spring 1933 looked as bad as or worse than summer 1931. The commission had set the East Texas quota far too high — twice what "bottom hole" pressure engineering suggested. Hundreds of thousands of barrels were being illegally produced above quotas. This excess became known as **"hot oil"** — a term coined in East Texas. Origin story: a state militiaman shivering on a chilly night was told by a suspected operator to lean against a tank of the suspect oil. "It's hot enough," said the operator, "to keep you warm."

Hot oil was being smuggled out of Texas and across state borders. The Texas Company slashed its posted price from seventy-five cents to **ten cents a barrel**. So vast was the flood that "hot oil runners" had trouble finding markets at even **two cents a barrel**. Pipelines were mysteriously dynamited. **William Farish**, president of Humble, wrote to Teagle that only the shock and pain of very low prices could convince independents their long-term interests lay in production control and unitization. "The law of the tooth and claw" was the only recourse. Some Texas producers urgently petitioned for Federal supervision.

### *The Reformer: Harold Ickes*

**Franklin Roosevelt's New Deal** brought a new activist administration willing to intervene. Roosevelt appointed **Harold L. Ickes** as Secretary of the Interior — a post still tainted by memories of Albert B. Fall and the Teapot Dome scandal. Ickes was described as "a plump, blond, bespectacled gentleman" — a Chicago lawyer who had been a leading figure in progressive Republican politics. He had managed Theodore Roosevelt's Chicago campaign in 1912 and chaired the Western Committee of the National Progressive League for FDR. He was a man of "powerful liberal convictions, strong passions, stinging polemics, pervasive suspicions, oversensitivity to any slight (real or imagined), immense self-righteousness, great dedication to duty, and a deeply ingrained moral conscience."

Ickes had been raised in a poor household by a stern Calvinist mother — not even permitted to whistle on Sunday. He was so good in high school that when the Latin teacher fell ill, he took over. As class president, he first practiced what became an art: the impulsive resignation on grounds of high principle, only to have it rejected. Decades later, Roosevelt would respond to one of his several resignations: "You are needed.... Resignation *not* accepted!"

As a young attorney with "restless reforming energy," Ickes joined campaigns against corruption, monopoly, and social injustice in Chicago — civil rights, women's trade unions, the ten-hour day. He joked about his "uncanny ability to pick losers!" In addition to Interior, Ickes assumed the role of **Oil Administrator** and held the key New Deal position of **Public Works Administrator**.

Ickes threw himself into intricate administrative details, haunted by Teapot Dome. "With the spotty record of Interior always in mind," he wrote, "I slaved away over endless mountains of documents, contracts, and letters, refusing to sign anything that I had not personally read." After Harry Sinclair (one of Fall's paymasters) visited in 1933, Ickes wrote in his diary: "I kept wondering whether the ghost of Albert B. Fall, carrying a little black satchel, might not emerge from one of the gloomy corners of this office." He set up an internal investigating unit using wiretaps as standard operating technique.

Ickes learned quickly how "thorny" the petroleum situation was. On **May 1, 1933**, he wrote Roosevelt about "utter demoralization" and "impending collapse" of the oil industry. On **May 5**, entering a Cabinet meeting, he received a telegram: East Texas prices had fallen to **four cents a barrel**. The Governor of Texas wired that "the situation is beyond the control of the state authorities." Ickes warned: "the oil business has broken down and... to continue to do nothing will result in the utter collapse of the industry."

### *The Government Acts*

Ickes started with prices — too low, like other raw materials during the Depression. Ten cents a barrel would prolong the Depression. For prices to rise, production had to be controlled. Ickes launched an all-out campaign against the "hot oiler" with "sly animal cunning." **Hot oil** production in 1933 was estimated at up to **half a million barrels per day**. This bootleg oil was secretly siphoned from pipelines, hidden in camouflaged tanks covered with weeds, moved through secret pipeline networks and by trucks, smuggled across state borders at night — every step smoothed by graft and payoffs. Any firming of prices only incentivized more hot oil production.

The Federal government's power to regulate interstate commerce provided the answer. Legislation in 1933 gave the President explicit power to ban **"hot oil" — petroleum produced in excess of state-mandated levels — from interstate commerce**. Roosevelt was appalled by "the wretched conditions" in the oil industry. On **July 14, 1933**, he signed an executive order. Ickes wrote in his diary: "stop the carrying into interstate or foreign commerce of any petroleum... produced in violation of the law of the state of their origin." Ickes dispatched Federal investigators to East Texas to examine refinery records, test oil gauges, inspect tanks, even dig up pipelines. Federal **"certificates of clearance"** were required to move any oil out of East Texas.

The **Oil Code** under the National Industrial Recovery Act gave Ickes extraordinary power to set **monthly quotas for each state**. On **September 2, 1933**, aiming to reduce production by 300,000 barrels per day, Ickes sent telegrams to governors telling them their state quotas. It was a historic act — the days of flush production were over. With prorationing, **the rule of capture was overturned**. "What had made sense for deer and game birds on estates in medieval England would no longer do when the very structure of the American oil industry seemed likely to be washed away."

Some in the industry wanted the government to go further and fix prices directly. "If you do not give us price regulations," said a Standard of California representative, "you can make codes from now to doomsday and you will get nowhere." But others feared government price-setting would make oil a public utility with regulated profits. Regulation of production — not prices — was chosen as the preferred method, with the actual job kept at the state level where it was less controversial and closer to actual production.

### *The System Stabilizes*

By end of 1934, the Federal-state partnership was gaining headway. But in **January 1935**, the Supreme Court struck down the NIRA subsection banning hot oil — a potential death blow. Without hot oil controls, the whole system would collapse. New legislation was speedily drafted and passed: the **Connally Hot Oil Act** (named for Senator Tom Connally of Texas). Then in **June 1935**, the Supreme Court declared much of the NIRA unconstitutional (the "sick chickens" case — a poultry jobber in New York). The voiding of the NIRA stripped Ickes of his power to set mandatory state quotas.

Yet the system survived. By this time, a framework for regulation was in place and a consensus established. The **Connally Hot Oil Act** provided police powers against contraband oil. The **Bureau of Mines** prepared demand estimates and "assigned" each state a suggested voluntary "quota." States were not required to accept these quotas — but they essentially did, adopting Federal estimates and prorating to fill their share of projected demand. The memory of ten cents a barrel was powerful motivation.

A state that greatly exceeded its quota would risk reprisal from the Federal government and other states, plus the peril of another glut and price collapse. The **Interstate Oil Compact** was established in 1935, formalizing cooperation among oil-producing states — a forum for exchanging information, standardizing legislation, and coordinating prorationing and conservation. Oklahoma wanted it to be an enforceable cartel; Texas refused to surrender sovereignty. Texas won, and the Compact became much less than a cartel but still useful.

The system also required an **oil tariff** to check cheap foreign imports. In 1932, a duty of **twenty-one cents a barrel** on crude and fuel oil and **$1.05 on gasoline** was passed. This tariff provided the protective barrier behind which the prorationing system could work. The duties were supported by a voluntary agreement on import volumes between Ickes and the main importing companies. Imports fell from **9-12% of domestic demand** in the late 1920s and early 1930s to **only 5%** after the tariff. Venezuela was hardest hit — it had supplied over half of U.S. crude imports, with 55% of production going to the U.S. Ships filled with expatriate oil men sailed home. Venezuelan companies reoriented exports toward Europe.

### *Stability*

The regulatory system emerged incrementally, in nasty and disordered circumstances — bitter debates, rancorous and desperate. It took East Texas and ten cents a barrel to shock the industry. It was devised by an unlikely alliance of Texas and Oklahoma oil men, patronage politicians in Austin and Oklahoma City, and Ickes and New Deal liberals in Washington. Though innately suspicious, they worked together to bring stability to an industry prone to boom and bust.

The system possessed a powerful underlying logic: it rewrote the book on production and "ownership" of oil reserves. Two working assumptions were central: (1) demand for oil was not particularly responsive to price movements — oil at ten cents would not mean far greater demand than at a dollar; (2) each state had its "natural" share of the market. When discoveries in **Illinois** in the late 1930s made it the nation's fourth-largest producer (and it didn't belong to the Interstate Oil Compact), Texas and Oklahoma cut back to make way. There were recriminations and calls to scrap the system, but it withstood even this challenge.

Prices were not fixed by the government — its advocates insisted on this point. But setting production to match demand did establish a level of crude that could be marketed at a stable price. From **1934 through 1940**, the average price of oil in the U.S. varied between **$1.00 and $1.18 per barrel**. The magical "dollar a barrel" rallying cry had been realized. The flood had been stayed, and the relationship between oil companies and the government had been forever changed.

## Chapter 14: "Friends" — and Enemies

### *Achnacarry Castle and the "As Is" Agreement*

**Malcolm and Hillcart**, a real estate agency in Fort William on the west coast of Scotland, had prepared "particulars" for a property called **Achna-carry Castle** — a dozen miles away in Inverness-shire, with fifty thousand acres of shooting, fishing for 90 stags, 160 brace of grouse, and 2,000 fish. In August 1928, **Henri Deterding** rented the property for the month. Joining him were **Walter Teagle** (Jersey), **Heinrich Riedemann** (Jersey's German chief), **Sir John Cadman** (Anglo-Persian), **William Mellon** (Gulf), and **Colonel Robert Stewart** (Standard of Indiana). Their holiday entourage included secretaries, typists, and advisers housed in a secured cottage seven miles away.

Despite great efforts at secrecy, the London press galloped northward, only to be told the oil men had gathered merely for grouse shooting and fishing. "The grouse were to have no warning," the *Daily Express* hypothesized. Deterding's two teenage nieces — "hellions" in Teagle's phrase — poured molasses into Riedemann's bed and tied his pajamas in knots. As for the shooting, "it was lousy," Teagle later said. But it did not matter — they were not after grouse. They were searching for a solution to overproduction and overcapacity. More than a truce to the oil wars, they wanted **a formal treaty for Europe and Asia** — one that would bring order, divide markets, stabilize the industry, and defend profitability. Achnacarry was a **peace conference**.

This was a year before the 1929 crash and two years before East Texas. But oil was already surging from the U.S., Venezuela, Romania, and the Soviet Union, weakening prices and threatening "ruinous competition." The flow of Russian oil, and the vicious price war Deterding launched in retaliation, had carried the oil men to Achnacarry. The battle had spread to many markets worldwide — bitter global warfare with collapsing prices.

Achnacarry reflected the temper of the times: industrial rationalization, efficiency, elimination of duplication were values celebrated by businessmen and government officials alike. Mergers, cartels, marketing agreements, and associations were the pattern. As in Rockefeller and Flagler's day, "unbridled competition" was the danger. But total monopoly was no longer possible — no one firm was powerful enough, and political realities would not allow it. A **concordat, rather than conquest**, was the objective.

### *The Hand of the British Government*

The meeting was not only the oil companies' work. Behind the scenes, the **British government** was prodding and pushing the companies toward collaboration. At the juncture stood **Sir John Cadman**, successor to Greenway as chairman of Anglo-Persian. By 1928, Cadman was operating on the same plane as Deterding and Teagle, but with unparalleled credibility with the British government. He grew up in a mining family, began as a coal mine manager (winning awards for saving miners during disasters), became professor of mining at Birmingham University, where he introduced "petroleum engineering" — so novel that an academic opponent denounced it as "flagrantly advertised" and "a blind alley" with "a freak title." During WWI, as head of the Petroleum Executive, Cadman demonstrated considerable political and managerial skills. In 1921 he became Anglo-Persian's technical adviser; six years later, the government's candidate, he became chairman.

Anglo-Persian's output from Persia and Iraq was poised to increase **fourfold**. "It was essential that new markets should be found," Cadman said. The choice: fight into new markets with large investment and unavoidable competition, or set up joint ventures with established companies and divide markets. Cadman chose the second path — pooling markets and facilities in India with Shell and Burmah, then proposing an "alliance" with Royal Dutch/Shell in **Africa**, splitting markets fifty-fifty.

For this African venture, Anglo-Persian needed permission from its majority stockholder — the British government. The Admiralty feared Anglo-Persian might be absorbed by Shell, violating basic government policy. The Foreign Office and Treasury worried about alienating the United States — that such a combination might be seen as " 'war' on American interests represented by the Standard Oil Company," extending blame to the British government through its Anglo-Persian ownership. **Winston Churchill**, now Chancellor of the Exchequer, initially doubted the combination: "The moment when Sir Henri Deterding is at 'war' with the Standard seems a singularly inopportune one for the British government to be drawn into the quarrel." But upon reflection, Churchill concluded combination was the best and cheapest policy.

The alternative, Churchill told the Committee on Imperial Defense, was for Anglo-Persian to fight for the African market alone — requiring much more money and possibly requiring him to approach Parliament again for funds (as in 1914). The government gave firm support to Cadman's African alliance with Shell. A joint Treasury-Admiralty memorandum in February 1928 declared: "Such a policy will in the long run be more in the interest of the consumer than cutthroat competition." The memorandum went further — it might promote "similar alliances elsewhere — especially with Standard Oil of New Jersey."

This was the most important outcome: the government had given Anglo-Persian a **mandate to talk with Standard Oil** and seek similar market arrangements with the Americans "to allay their jealousies and show that we are not out to quarrel." Unhindered by American antitrust tradition, the British government was partial to combination. "Our experience has broadly been that the amalgamation of oil interests has not resulted in the consumer suffering." Cadman, now representing government policy as well as Anglo-Persian, pursued a concordat with the Americans. He wrote to Teagle proposing "a small 'clearinghouse' for matters of the very highest policy." These developments were among the major influences leading to Deterding's invitation to Achnacarry.

### *"The Problem of the Oil Industry"*

The two weeks of discussion on the banks of the River Arkaig resulted in a seventeen-page document, agreed to but not signed, called the **"Pool Association"** — better known as the **Achnacarry or "As-Is" Agreement**. The document summarized "the problem of the oil industry" — overproduction, "the effect of which has been destructive rather than constructive competition, resulting in much higher operating costs.... Recognizing this, economies must be effected, waste must be eliminated, the expensive duplication of facilities curtailed."

The heart of the "As-Is" understanding: **each company was allocated a quota — a percentage share of total sales in various markets, based upon its 1928 share**. A company could only increase actual volumes as total demand grew, but always keeping the same percentage share. Beyond this, companies would share facilities, be cautious about building new refineries, and increase efficiency by supplying markets from the nearest geographical source. The sales price would be based on the traditional formula — **American Gulf Coast price plus freight** — even if the oil came from a closer location. This established a uniform selling price and eliminated price competition among adherents.

A few months later, the leaders agreed to control production as well. Excess production above market quotas would be sold to other pool members. An **"Association"** with a representative from each company would handle statistical analysis and allocate quotas.

The **Soviet Union** was notably absent. By 1928, **Russian Oil Products** was the fourth-largest importer into the UK. In **February 1929**, despite Deterding's and Teagle's distaste, the major companies reached an understanding giving the Soviet Union a guaranteed share of the British market. With Russia roped in, there was only one major exception to this amicable division: the **domestic U.S. market was explicitly excluded** to avoid violating American antitrust laws.

The Achnacarry Agreement harked back to Rockefeller and Archbold, Deterding and Samuel, the Nobels and the Rothschilds — all had sought a grand concord and failed. This time was no more successful. While the "As-Is" companies were by far dominant, **"fringe" players** who did not belong could price just below the majors and win market share. When forced out of one market, they moved to another.

It was critical to control **American oil exports** (about a third of all oil consumed outside the U.S.). Seventeen American companies formed the **Export Petroleum Association** under the **Webb-Pomerene Act of 1918** (which allowed U.S. companies to do abroad what antitrust banned at home). But negotiations with the "European Group" fell apart over allocation, and the association never controlled more than **45% of American exports** — far too few companies to agree on prices and quotas. This failure further undermined Achnacarry.

**J. B. Kessler**, a Royal Dutch/Shell director, warned Teagle: "the figures we had before us showed that, of the potential world production, a large part is controlled by companies which are not controlled either by you or us or any of the few other large oil companies." Discoveries and output were building toward the great crescendo of East Texas. In the surge of uncontrollable production, the Achnacarry Agreement was washed away.

### *Discord Within "Private Walls"*

The Big Three — Jersey, Shell, and Anglo-Persian — tried to reformulate an alliance in 1930, less grandiose this time. They revised the "As-Is" into a new **Memorandum for European Markets**, with operating companies making "local arrangements" and dividing shares with "Outsiders." Yet again, the system proved ineffective against rising American, Russian, and Romanian oil. The Soviets never hesitated to cut prices to earn more foreign currency for Russia's industrialization drive.

By 1931, Jersey had grown disenchanted. **E. J. Sadler**, Jersey's head of production, advocated junking cooperation and making war on Shell: "Now is the best time to fight the Royal Dutch, as they are most vulnerable in the Far East.... In this region we have never made any profit, and a price war would cost us almost nothing." In March 1932, **M. Weill**, overseeing the Rothschilds' large interest in Royal Dutch/Shell, reported to Baron Rothschild: "Prices are bad everywhere, and except for a few rare places, money is not being made."

In November 1932, **Sir John Cadman** addressed the American Petroleum Institute, extolling "cooperation" — "strictly, of course, within the laws of every country." He publicly declared that "the principle of 'As-Is' has become the keystone of cooperation in international petroleum trading outside the United States." He warned: "It is still raining outside," and the companies could not give up seeking shelter from the storm.

The companies came up with a new version: the **Heads of Agreement for Distribution (December 1932)**, a guide for drawing up local cartels and agreements. Adherents included Royal Dutch/Shell, Jersey, Anglo-Persian, Socony, Gulf, Atlantic, Texas, and Sinclair. Two "As-Is" committees (New York and London) managed the arrangement, with a central secretariat in London. Internal "As-Is" departments were established at some companies. But friction persisted — chronic cheating and disputes over **"virginal markets"** (markets where participants had not previously traded but now sought to enter).

The **1934 Draft Memorandum of Principles** called for "economy in competitive expenditure" — reducing road signs, billboards, newspaper advertising, "premiums to racing drivers," promotional gifts (cigarette lighters, pens, calendars). Even the number and type of gas station signs were to be standardized.

Within each company, management referred to other companies as **"friends"**: "Friends in London say..." or "Friends not yet made up mind." But it was not friendship — it was desperation in a depressed world economy. They were aggressive competitors who never forgot it. Collaboration was paralleled by pervasive distrust and deep-seated rivalry. Just months after Achnacarry, Shell entered the U.S. East Coast market and expanded rapidly. Jersey was infuriated. In 1936, when Deterding learned Jersey was discussing selling its entire Mexican operation to **William Davis** (a "fringe" player), he wrote angrily: "We are engaged together in resistance to Davis' activities... and surely it is hopelessly inconsistent with sound warfare to sell the enemy a complete set of much needed munitions."

A Standard-Vacuum executive objected to outside auditors reviewing trade numbers: "Not only is the thought of having outside auditors go over our books objectionable for obvious reasons, but it seems to us that the As-Is would be on a very weak foundation if the parties concerned cannot trust each other." In December 1934, Shell director Godber in the Far East reported: "Figures trade clearly show Texas Co. unnecessarily aggressive and will end year with larger share of trade than that to which they are entitled." He wanted "sterner measures" against Texas Company.

The "As-Is" agreements became much more effective from 1934 onward due to three factors: (1) in the U.S., Ickes finally brought production under control; (2) in the Soviet Union, quickening industrialization consumed domestic oil, constricting exports; (3) large companies gained some control over Romanian output. But in **early 1938**, Jersey gave verbal notice of termination. Any surviving "As-Is" activities came to an end in **September 1939** with the outbreak of World War II.

### *Nationalism*

The "As-Is" agreements were meant to defend against both the oil glut and the Depression, and against **powerful political forces** in Europe and elsewhere. "Throughout the European continent, government policies confronted those of private foreign oil companies — and the scope of the confrontation was unprecedented." During the 1930s, governments imposed import quotas, set prices, placed restrictions on foreign exchange, forced companies to blend alcohol from surplus crops into motor fuel, levied new taxes, and controlled export/import trade to match bilateral agreements. They blocked profit remittances, forced investment in domestic facilities, and insisted companies maintain extra inventories.

It became standard practice for European governments to compel foreign companies to participate in **national cartels** and divide markets between foreign and local companies. In France, under 1928 legislation, the government allocated specific market shares to each company. A Jersey executive warned: "failure to cooperate with a national commercial endeavor — whatever the sacrifice in dollars or in principles — invariably provoked retaliatory legislation which was more costly." In **Nazi Germany**, regulations and manipulations of all kinds mounted as that government geared up for war.

**Orville Harden**, Jersey vice-president, summed up in 1935: "We are now confronted with nationalistic policies in almost all foreign countries, as well as decidedly socialistic tendencies in many.... These problems are between the Government, on the one hand, and industry as a unit, on the other." An observer of the oil industry that same year noted: "Operations in the oil business in Europe are **90 percent political and 10 percent oil**."

### *The Shah's New Terms*

At the very bottom of the Depression, **Shah Reza Pahlavi** of Persia was infuriated to discover that "oil is not gold in these days." Petroleum royalties from Anglo-Persian provided **two-thirds** of Persia's export earnings and a substantial part of government revenues. But with the Depression, royalties had plummeted to the lowest level since 1917. On **November 16, 1932**, the Shah abruptly announced at a Cabinet meeting that he was **unilaterally canceling Anglo-Persian's concession**. It was a thunderbolt that threatened the company's very existence.

The cancellation culminated four years of negotiation. In 1928, Cadman had observed "that concessionaries can regard their future as safeguarded against the rising tide of economic nationalism in proportion to the extent in which the national interests and their own approach identity." In 1929, Cadman thought he had worked out a deal with the Shah's Minister of Court, **Abdul Husayn Timurtash** — higher payments, 25% of the company's shares, board representation, and a share of global profits. But the deal could never be closed. The Shah's greatest fault, said Timurtash, was "his suspicion of everybody and everyone. There was really nobody in the whole country whom His Majesty trusted."

**Reza Shah** — formerly Reza Khan — was tough, domineering, brutal, and blunt. He had used his command of the Cossack Brigade to become War Minister in 1921, then Prime Minister in 1923, then crowned himself Reza Shah Pahlavi in 1925, founding the new Pahlavi dynasty. He told visitors the Persian people were "bigoted and ignorant." He was bent on consolidating power and reducing all competing centers — including the mullahs (religious clerics). He personally beat an ayatollah who questioned his family's dress at a shrine. "It has often been said that the Shah's greatest achievement is his victory over the Mullahs."

In the Shah's opinion, Anglo-Persian was like the mullahs — an independent power center to be reduced. The local press, responding to the Shah, attacked everything from D'Arcy's original concession to the refrigeration of food at the Abadan refinery (considered irreligious). The Shah was also angry with Britain over Bahrain (which Persia claimed) and the British recognition of Iraq. Anglo-Persian's claim to operate independently of the British government was never believed: Persians "could only imagine that duplicity was being compounded with complicity."

The cancellation was a direct challenge to the British government, whose military security had been tied to Persian oil since Churchill in 1914. The issue was sent to the **League of Nations**, which put it into abeyance. Five months later, in **April 1933**, Cadman flew to Tehran himself. He noted: "There is no doubt that H.M. [His Majesty] is after money." Negotiations deadlocked. Cadman, frustrated, returned to the Shah's palace and to emphasize that a breakdown was imminent and his patience at an end, **instructed his pilot to carry out a trial flight and taxi the plane visibly from the windows of the Shah's palace** during the meeting.

The Shah retreated. By end of April 1933, a new agreement was forged: the concession area was **reduced by three-quarters**; Persia was guaranteed a fixed royalty of **four shillings per ton** (protecting against price fluctuations); it would receive **20% of worldwide profits** distributed to shareholders above a minimum; a minimum annual payment of **£750,000** was guaranteed; royalties for 1931-32 were recalculated; and the "Persianization" of the workforce was to be accelerated. The concession was extended from **1961 to 1993**. "I felt that we had been pretty well plucked," Cadman noted afterward. But Anglo-Persian's essential position was preserved.

### *The Mexican Battle*

Of all the nationalistic challenges, the greatest came in **Mexico** — the focal point being **paragraph 4 of Article 27** of the 1917 Constitution, which declared subsoil resources belonged to the Mexican state, not the surface property owner. The companies fought hard against Article 27, invoking U.S. and British government support, maintaining that property rights acquired before the revolution could not be retroactively seized. Mexico insisted it had owned the subsoil all along. The result was a standoff — an agreement to disagree.

The modus vivendi was hardly easy — punctuated by sharp acrimony. In 1927, tensions rose so high that a rupture seemed imminent, with possible U.S. military intervention. President **Plutarco Elias Calles** ordered **General Lazaro Cardenas** (then military commander in the oil zone) to prepare to **set the oil fields on fire** in the event of a U.S. invasion. From 1927 onward, greater stability emerged, but by the mid-1930s, the detente was unraveling. Mexico was losing competitiveness — higher production costs, increasing taxation, field exhaustion. Venezuelan oil was being landed at Tampico for refining because it was cheaper than Mexican oil. Mexican production had fallen from **499,000 barrels per day to 104,000** — an 80% drop in a decade.

**General Lazaro Cardenas** became President at the end of 1934. A man of "striking appearance" — "the long, mask-like face and inscrutable, obsidian eyes of the Indian" — son of an herbalist, educated only to age eleven but a voracious reader of history. By age eighteen he had been a tax collector, printer's devil, and jailkeeper before enlisting in the revolution. A general by twenty-five, protege of Calles, he was sober, puritanical, a supporter of prohibition and opponent of casinos. As president, he packed Calles into exile and demonstrated independence. He aggressively pushed land reform, education, and public works. Labor unions became powerful under his presidency.

Cardenas viewed the foreign oil industry as a painful presence — he resented what he saw as their arrogant treatment of Mexico as "conquered territory." Mexican Eagle was caught between local management trying to adjust to radicalism and Deterding in London, who "was incapable of conceiving of Mexico as anything but a Colonial Government to which you simply dictated orders." The local manager tried to "disillusion" Deterding but failed and was accused of being "half a Bolshevik."

**Everette DeGolyer**, the prominent American geologist, privately urged Jersey's **Eugene Holman** to "work out a partnership deal with the Mexican Government which would satisfy their national aspirations." Holman adamantly rejected: "The matter was so important as a precedent in other areas that the company would prefer to lose everything that it had in Mexico rather than acquiesce in a partnership which might be regarded as a partial expropriation."

In 1937, **Bolivia** confiscated Standard Oil's local subsidiary, winning great applause throughout Latin America. In Mexico, wages had supplanted taxes and concessions as the main point of contention. The oil workers' union struck in **May 1937**. Cardenas set up a review commission under **Professor Jesus Silva Herzog**, who described company officials as "men without respect who were unaccustomed to speaking the truth." The commission declared the companies had been "making lucrative profits while raping the Mexican economy" and recommended much higher wages totaling **26 million pesos** annually, plus a forty-hour week, six weeks' vacation, and retirement pensions at 85% of wages at age fifty.

The companies claimed their total combined profit 1935-37 was only **23 million pesos** — less than the demanded wage increase. They said compliance would force them to close down, gambling Mexico would not take that chance. The government confirmed the commission's recommendations and added retroactive penalties. Mexican Eagle evacuated wives and children.

On **March 8, 1938**, Cardenas met privately with oil company representatives — a further stalemate on wages. That same night, he made up his mind to expropriate if needed. On **March 16**, the companies were declared "in rebellion." They finally accepted the 26 million peso wage hike but refused to transfer management decision-making and administrative control to the unions.

On the night of **March 18, 1938**, Cardenas met with his Cabinet and told them he intended to take over the oil industry. It was better to destroy the oil fields, he said, than let them be an obstacle to national development. At **9:45 PM**, he signed the **expropriation order** and broadcast it from the Yellow Room. His words were greeted with a **six-hour parade** through Mexico City. For Mexico, it was a great symbolic act of resistance to foreign control. For the companies, it was absolutely illegitimate — a violation of clear agreements and formal commitments.

The companies joined in a united front to negotiate — not about compensation (in which they had no confidence) but to get their properties back. One Shell director warned: "a precedent is established throughout the world, particularly in Latin America, which would jeopardize the whole structure of international trade and the security of foreign investment." Companies organized embargoes against Mexican oil around the world. The company hardest hit was **Mexican Eagle** (Shell-controlled, largely British stockholders). The British government took a very strong stand against Mexico.

Britain insisted the properties be returned; Mexico instead severed diplomatic relations. A break with the United States was barely averted. Washington tried to exert economic pressure, but half-heartedly. In the era of Roosevelt's **Good Neighbor Policy** and criticism of "economic royalists," the American government could hardly act harshly against Mexico or oppose the sovereign right of expropriation so long as "fair compensation" was offered. With the rapidly deteriorating international situation, Roosevelt did not want to aggravate relations with any hemispheric country, as that could benefit the Axis powers.

The British-led embargo had unsettling effects: **Nazi Germany** became Mexico's number-one petroleum customer (at discount or barter terms), with Fascist Italy next and Japan a major customer as well. Japanese companies were exploring for oil in Mexico and discussing a pipeline to the Pacific. The Roosevelt Administration concluded that additional American pressure would only enable the Axis powers to strengthen their footholds. The British position was driven by strategic concerns: just eight countries accounted for 94% of world production, and U.S. neutrality legislation might foreclose American petroleum to Britain in a crisis. Latin American oil was essential — "defense requirements" and access to wartime oil were "the paramount consideration."

### *"As Dead as Julius Caesar"*

After war broke out in September 1939, national security trumped restitution for the Roosevelt Administration. Washington did not want Nazi submarines refueling in Mexican ports or German "geologists" wandering near the U.S. border and Panama Canal. U.S. Ambassador **Josephus Daniels** told Roosevelt in 1941 there was no sense defending a status "as dead as Julius Caesar."

By autumn 1941, Washington pushed for settlement — compensation, not restoration. Valuations ranged wildly: Mexico said **$7 million**, the companies claimed **$408 million**. A joint U.S.-Mexican commission found a creative solution: it judged that **90% of all subsoil reserves** had already been produced by the time of expropriation. Under this formulation, there was no point arguing about ownership of the reserves. The commission proposed **$30 million** in compensation, spread over several years. The companies reacted with bitter outrage, arguing they had sought foreign oil partly at the U.S. government's behest. **Secretary of State Cordell Hull** made clear the companies had no obligation to accept but should expect no further government support. In **October 1943**, the American companies took the deal.

There was a price for Mexico too. **Petroleos Mexicanos (Pemex)** was established as the national oil company. But the oil business was no longer export-oriented; it shifted to cheap domestic fuel for Mexico's own development. Mexican exports became a small factor. The industry was hamstrung by shortage of capital and lack of technology and skills. The promised 26-million-peso wage hike — the *casus belli* of the expropriation — was not only indefinitely postponed but in fact cut. Britain did not settle with Mexico until **1947** — Mexican Eagle/Shell won **$130 million**, proportionately much better than the Americans.

Both British and American companies agreed: the Mexican expropriation was the biggest trauma since the Bolshevik Revolution, perhaps since the 1911 Standard Oil dissolution. For Mexico, the 1938 nationalization was one of the greatest triumphs of the revolution. **Pemex** would emerge as one of the first and most important state-owned oil companies in the world. Mexico had established a model for the future.

## Chapter 15: The Arabian Concessions — The World That Frank Holmes Made

### *Major Frank Holmes*

Among the millions displaced by World War I was **Major Frank Holmes** — born on a New Zealand farm in 1874, he had worked in South African gold mines and then spent two decades as an itinerant mining engineer specializing in gold and tin, from Australia and Malaya to Mexico, Uruguay, Russia, and Nigeria. He was "robust and sturdy in stature, assertive and headstrong in manner." A competitor described him as "a man of considerable personal charm, with a bluff, breezy, blustering, buccaneering way about him."

During WWI, as a quartermaster in the British Army on a **beef-buying expedition to Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, in 1918**, Holmes first heard from an Arab trader about **oil seepages on the Arabian coast of the Persian Gulf**. Later, stationed in Basra, he took further interest in Anglo-Persian's activities across the border and reports of petroleum seepages along the Arabian coast.

After the war, Holmes helped set up the **Eastern and General Syndicate** to develop business opportunities in the Middle East. Its first venture was a drugstore in Aden. But Holmes's passion was oil — he was convinced the Arabian coast would be a fabulous source. He traveled up and down the Gulf, from one impoverished ruler to the next, spinning his vision, "promising them wealth where they saw only poverty, seeking always to put another concession into his kit."

British officials regarded Holmes with suspicion — an unscrupulous troublemaker with "a capacity for mischief," trying to undermine British influence. One official called him "nothing more than a rover in the world of oil." But to the Arabs, Holmes was something altogether different — **"Abu al-Naft," the "Father of Oil."**

Holmes set up headquarters on **Bahrain**, attracted by reports of oil seepages. The Sheikh had no interest in oil but desperately wanted fresh water. Holmes drilled for water, struck it, and made a nice profit. In exchange, the grateful ruler rewarded him with an **oil concession in 1925**. Holmes also won options to concessions in **al-Hasa** (eastern Saudi Arabia) in 1923, the **Neutral Zone** between Saudi Arabia and Kuwait in 1924, and tried for Kuwait proper.

Anglo-Persian was alarmed — it did not want anyone else operating within its "sphere of influence." The company was convinced there was no oil in Arabia. Cadman said geological reports "leave little room for optimism," and one director declared in 1926 that Saudi Arabia was "devoid of all prospects" for oil. (Albania, the director added, was the promising play.) A Swiss geologist retained by the syndicate produced a damning report declaring the region did "*not present any decided promise for drilling on oil*" and exploration "would have to be classified as pure gamble." This report leaked to the City of London, making it impossible to raise money.

By 1926, the syndicate was in deep financial trouble. Holmes tried to sell all concessions to Anglo-Persian, which said no. In the City of London, he got a frigid reception. "Holmes was the worst nuisance in London," one businessman recalled. "People ran when they saw him coming."

### *Bahrain and the New York Sheikhs*

With no luck in Britain, Holmes sailed for New York, hoping for better luck with "the really big New York Sheikhs." Jersey turned him down — Bahrain was "too far away and too small" (no larger than a pencil point on the map). Other companies were focused on the Turkish Petroleum Company. But **Gulf Oil** showed a flicker of interest — committed to diversified global production as a hedge. Holmes provided Gulf with rock samples and a "greasy substance" along with reports of oil traces in Bahrain water wells. In **November 1927**, Gulf took overall rights claimed by Eastern and General to Arabian concessions and agreed to work with Holmes's group to secure a Kuwait concession.

But a problem arose: in **1928**, Gulf joined the Turkish Petroleum Company and became bound by the **Red Line Agreement**, which precluded independent operations within the Red Line — clearly ruling out Saudi Arabia and Bahrain. The TPC board would not take up Holmes's entire Arabian package. So while Gulf could pursue Kuwait (outside the Red Line), it had to surrender its Bahrain interest.

Gulf brought the Bahrain concession to **Standard of California (Socal)**, which was aggressively committed to developing foreign oil but had nothing to show for very large expenditures. Unlike Gulf, Socal was not part of the TPC and not bound by the Red Line. Socal set up a Canadian subsidiary, the **Bahrain Petroleum Company**, to hold the concession.

Both Socal (in Bahrain) and Gulf (in Kuwait) then ran into **British government opposition** — the "British nationality clause" in Gulf concession agreements required that oil development be carried out by "British interests" only, excluding Americans. A nasty series of negotiations followed, backed by the U.S. government on one side and Britain on the other. The Americans saw it as a cunningly constructed barrier; the British felt harried and defensive before greater American power. In **1929**, Britain reconsidered — American capital would encourage rapid development, benefiting local rulers (who might otherwise need British subsidies) and the Royal Navy. Britain backed off on Bahrain, allowing Socal to exercise its option under conditions guaranteeing British political primacy (e.g., all company communications to the Amir had to pass through the British political agent).

The Bahrain Petroleum Company began drilling in **October 1931**. On **May 31, 1932**, it hit oil — petroleum had been discovered in the Arab world. Though only modest in production, the discovery had far wider implications. Over the course of a decade, Major Holmes with his oil obsession had been a figure of condescension and ridicule. Now his instincts had been vindicated. Was he to be proved right on a much grander scale? After all, Bahrain was only twenty miles from the Arabian mainland, where the geology was exactly the same.

### *Ibn Saud*

Britain's political agent in Kuwait spoke of the ruler of neighboring Saudi Arabia as "the astute Bin Saud, who always takes the 'long view.'" But **Ibn Saud** did not have the luxury of a long view — he needed money for his treasury urgently. He was skeptical about oil prospects and uneasy about what foreign oil development would mean — foreign capital and technicians could disturb traditional values. But granting a concession to *explore* was another matter, so long as it came with appropriate financial considerations.

**Abdul Aziz bin Abdul Rahman bin Faisal al Saud** was just over fifty years old. At six feet three inches with a barrel chest, he had an imposing physical presence. He combined "his qualities as a soldier that grasp of statecraft which is yet more highly prized by the tribesmen." His later amassing of immense wealth was remarkable for a ruler who, in his early days, could carry his entire national treasury in the saddlebags of a camel.

The **Saudi dynasty** had been established by **Muhammad bin Saud**, emir of Dariya in the Nejd, in the early 1700s. He allied with **Muhammad bin Abdul Wahab**, who espoused a stern puritanical version of Islam — the **Wahabi** branch that would become the religious mortar of the dynasty and state. The Saudis' rapid expansion alarmed the Ottoman Turks, who defeated them in 1818. Muhammad's great-grandson Abdullah was beheaded in Constantinople. The family eventually reestablished itself in Riyadh, but fell apart due to power struggles. By 1891, Abdul Rahman (Ibn Saud's father) fled into exile — the future Ibn Saud made part of the journey in a bag hung from a camel saddle. The family eventually settled in Kuwait under the protection of the Sabah family.

**Mubarak**, the Amir of Kuwait, gave the young prince an education in *realpolitik*. When the Turks incited the Rashids (the Saudis' enemies) to attack Kuwait, Mubarak dispatched Ibn Saud, then just twenty years old, to retake Riyadh. He led a small band across the desert, was repulsed, then on a second attempt entered the city by night and at dawn slew the Rashids' governor. In **January 1902**, his father proclaimed him Governor of Nejd and Imam of the Wahabis — the second al-Saud restoration had begun.

Over the next years, Ibn Saud made himself the acknowledged ruler of central Arabia. He became leader of the **Ikhwan (Brotherhood)** — intensely religious warriors. During 1913-14, he brought eastern Arabia including the Shia-populated **al-Hasa** under his control. By December 1925, the Ikhwan had captured the **Hejaz** (the holy land of Islam with Mecca and Medina). In **January 1926**, at the Great Mosque of Mecca, Ibn Saud was proclaimed King of the Hejaz, keeper of the holy places. By age forty-five, he had reestablished Saudi ascendancy over nine-tenths of the Arabian Peninsula.

But then the Ikhwan began criticizing Ibn Saud for backsliding from Wahabism — the telephone, telegraph, radio, and motorcar were "tools of the devil." In 1927 they rose in rebellion. By 1930 he had destroyed the Ikhwan movement. In **1932**, the realm was renamed **Saudi Arabia**.

Just as Ibn Saud had consolidated power, the **Great Depression** hit. The flow of **pilgrims to Mecca** — the kingdom's major revenue source — slowed to a trickle. Finances fell into desperate straits; civil servants were six to eight months in arrears. Ibn Saud tried to collect taxes a year in advance, sent his son **Faisal** to Europe to seek aid (unsuccessfully). As his financial problems grew, the King did not know where to turn.

### *The Sorcerer's Apprentice: Jack Philby*

Perhaps valuable resources were hidden under the soil. This idea was suggested to Ibn Saud during an automobile ride, probably autumn 1930, by his companion — an Englishman, former Indian Civil Service official turned Jidda merchant, who had recently converted to Islam. The King had given him the Islamic name Abdullah. His real name was **Harry St. John Bridger Philby** — known as Jack. He is now remembered best as the eccentric father of **Harold "Kim" Philby**, the notorious double agent who headed anti-Soviet counterespionage in British intelligence while spying for the Soviets. On reading Kim's memoir, Ibn Saud's retired court interpreter marveled that Kim was "a true replica of his father."

Jack Philby was a relentless contrarian, an inveterate rebel against authority. In Jidda he once paraded his pet baboons to demonstrate he could do without the European community. Raised in Ceylon, a Trinity College Cambridge graduate, he began in the Indian Civil Service and was posted to Baghdad and Basra during WWI, where he became a gifted Arabist. He first met Ibn Saud on a mission to Riyadh in 1917 — thirty-four hours of personal interviews that set the course of the rest of Philby's life.

In 1925, angered by British policy, Philby quit the civil service and returned to Saudi Arabia to establish a trading company in Jidda. He became an informal adviser to the King, joining his traveling party and evening Privy Council deliberations. On the eve of his conversion to Islam in 1930, the King told him "how nice it would be for me when I became a Muslim and could have four wives." The conversion enabled Philby to pursue his famous explorations — the Rub al-Khali (Empty Quarter), northwestern Arabia — for which he received the Founder's Medal of the Royal Geographical Society. He kept up five o'clock tea and cricket scores from Lord's even in the desert, yet remained at odds with Britain, which he saw as exercising "traditional western dominance."

The British found Philby "most troublesome" — "His methods have been as unscrupulous as they have been violent. He is a public nuisance." Another official denounced him as "an arch-humbug." But Philby knew very well Ibn Saud's severe financial problems. During the automobile ride in autumn 1930, noting the King was particularly despondent, Philby said cheerfully that the King and his government were "like folk asleep on buried treasure." Development required prospecting, foreign expertise, and foreign capital. "Oh, Philby," the King replied, "if anyone would offer me a million pounds, I would give him all the concessions he wanted."

Philby suggested **Charles Crane** — an American plumbing tycoon and philanthropist with a special interest in the Arab world. Crane arrived on **February 25, 1931**, was received with great pomp, mesmerizing sword dances, and gifts of rugs, daggers, swords, and two pedigreed Arabian horses. At his own expense, Crane made available an American mining engineer named **Karl Twitchell** to investigate the kingdom's water potential. After a 1,500-mile journey, Twitchell arrived in Jidda in April 1931 with bad news: no prospects of artesian wells.

In **March 1932**, the Amir of Kuwait, **Sheikh Ahmad**, visited Ibn Saud in Riyadh — traveling 300 miles by motorcar. He was struck by the King's ill health and strain. Sheikh Ahmad urged Ibn Saud to reduce his cars by three-quarters and "standardize by concentrating on Fords and Chevrolets." Having delivered this advice, he drove back across the desert in a gift from Ibn Saud — a large eight-cylinder Cadillac limousine.

The two rulers discussed oil exploration. Ibn Saud was "not anxious in the least to grant concessions to foreigners," but given his financial difficulties, did he have a choice? Twitchell had found some promising oil prospects in **al-Hasa**. Then, on **May 31, 1932**, Socal's discovery on Bahrain significantly increased the attractiveness of al-Hasa. Twitchell agreed at the King's behest to try to locate interest and capital in the United States.

### *The Negotiation*

Socal was delighted and retained Twitchell as a negotiator. He returned to Saudi Arabia in **February 1933** with **Lloyd Hamilton**, a Socal lawyer, to negotiate with Ibn Saud's minister of finance, **Abdullah Suleiman** — "a cunning and masterly opponent." The brother of the King's private secretary, a Nadji by birth (most senior administrators were Syrians, Egyptians, or Libyans), Suleiman had been an assistant to an Arab merchant in Bombay. The King called him "my support." Ibn Saud's interpreter considered him "the ultimate eminence grise" with "power and influence so monumental that I often thought of him as the uncrowned King of Arabia."

Suleiman knew exactly what he wanted — a very large sum of money, as soon as possible. Whether oil was there could be left to later. The **Iraq Petroleum Company** (IPC) dispatched **Stephen Longrigg** as its representative — also in effect representing Anglo-Persian. But IPC's efforts were more "prophylactic than prospective" — they wanted to keep out competitors, not make a large commitment. Longrigg's brief was "certainly not to buy a pig in a poke by paying big money at this stage for the right of extracting problematic oil."

Philby was glorying in his multiple roles — paid agent for Socal, adviser to the Saudis, coaching IPC through his contact with Longrigg (who regarded him as a confidant), and casually dropping in conversation what the King had said. Socal paid Philby **$1,000 a month for six months** plus bonuses on signing and on discovery of oil — money he used to pay his son Kim's Cambridge University fees, where Kim was taking "the first steps on the way to becoming a Soviet spy."

Socal was offering only about a fifth of what the Saudis wanted. IPC/Anglo-Persian continued to be skeptical — they didn't need more oil and were unwilling to pay much. Finally Philby advised Longrigg: "You might just as well pack up; the Americans are far and away higher than that." Longrigg departed abruptly, leaving the field to Socal. Philby coaxed Socal and Suleiman toward what he called "this detente" — a much higher Socal offer.

By May 1933, the final draft was ready. Ibn Saud told Suleiman: "Put your trust in God, and sign." The agreement provided for **£35,000 ($175,000)** in gold up front (£30,000 as a loan, £5,000 as the first year's royalty in advance). After eighteen months, a second loan of **£20,000 ($100,000)**. An additional loan of **£100,000 ($500,000)** in gold on discovery of oil. The concession was good for **sixty years** and covered about **360,000 square miles**. On **May 29, 1933**, the agreement was signed.

Getting the gold proved tricky — America had just gone off the gold standard. Socal's effort to dispatch gold directly was turned down by Assistant Secretary of the Treasury **Dean Acheson**. The Guaranty Trust's London office obtained **35,000 gold sovereigns** from the Royal Mint, transported in seven boxes on a P&O ship to Saudi Arabia. Care was taken that all coins bore the likeness of a **male English monarch, not Queen Victoria** — feared to be devalued in Saudi Arabia's male-dominated society.

When Philby told **Sir Andrew Ryan**, the British minister, that Socal had won the concession, Ryan was "thunderstruck, and his face darkened with anger and disappointment" — which delighted Philby no end. Washington was slow to realize the significance; the Roosevelt Administration refused to establish diplomatic representation, repeating there was no need. Not until **1939** was the U.S. minister to Egypt also accredited to Saudi Arabia, and only in **1942** did the U.S. establish a permanent one-man legation.

Anglo-Persian and the IPC realized they had blundered — "too timid and too miserly." In **1936**, the IPC group obtained a concession for the **Hejaz** (western Saudi Arabia, extending to Yemen) on much higher terms. The only drawback: the IPC never found oil in its concession.

### *Kuwait*

**Sheikh Ahmad** of Kuwait had been courting concessionaires for a decade. The Bahrain exploration "was a stab to my heart," he told Holmes in 1931, "when I observed the oil work at Bahrein and nothing here." The jovial, thickset Sheikh (Amir since 1921) prided himself on modernity — dress slacks and patent leather shoes beneath his robes, an enthusiast of the British Navy with photographs of officers and war sloops on his drawing room walls. He played a dangerous balancing act — "trying to play His Majesty's Government, the Iraqi government and King Ibn Saud off against each other."

Both **Anglo-Persian** and **Gulf** courted Sheikh Ahmad. Gulf was working through Holmes and his Eastern and General Syndicate (which the Foreign Office called Gulf's "jackal"). Anglo-Persian was skeptical about Kuwait oil prospects and mainly interested defensively — to prevent anyone from moving in on its "flank" and threatening its position in Persia and Iraq. Kuwait's economy had been devastated by **Japanese cultured pearls** — **Kokichi Mikimoto**, a Japanese noodle vendor turned pearl cultivator, had developed artificial pearl cultivation, and by 1930 large volumes were destroying the natural pearl market. Kuwait's export earnings plummeted; merchants went bankrupt; boats were laid up and divers returned to the desert.

Sheikh Ahmad believed American oil company entry would bring American political interest, bolstering his position against regional rivals. Yet he could not alienate Britain, on which Kuwait depended for security against Saudi Arabia, Iraq, and Persia (which did not even acknowledge Kuwait's existence). Britain insisted on the **"British nationality clause"** for Kuwait even after dropping it for Bahrain. The Admiralty worried about "American warships intervening in Gulf affairs." But by **April 1932**, key British departments — Foreign Office, Colonial Office, Petroleum Department — were prepared to jettison the clause. "The last thing we want," said one Foreign Office official, "is an oil war with the United States." Cadman told the Foreign Office any Kuwait oil would not "be of interest to the Anglo-Persian Oil Company. The Americans are welcome to what they can find there!"

Holmes attributed the "wonderful victory" partly to Ambassador **Andrew Mellon** — former Treasury Secretary, patriarch of the family that controlled Gulf Oil. He arrived in London in 1932 at seventy-seven, under a cloud (allegations of special treatment for Mellon companies during his Treasury tenure). He personally intervened to facilitate State Department help for Gulf in Kuwait, referring to Gulf as "my company." The State Department had to delicately manage the appearance of acting "merely for the personal benefit of Mr. Mellon."

After Socal's Bahrain discovery in May 1932, **Anglo-Persian abruptly changed its mind** — Cadman hurriedly disavowed his "no interest" statement and declared Anglo-Persian now very much wanted to bid for Kuwait. The Sheikh was delighted: "Yes, I have now two bidders, and from the point of view of a seller that is all to the good." A bidding war ensued — each company impressed by the other's determination. **Cadman** raised the possibility of amalgamation with Mellon. But both sides concluded that a **fifty-fifty joint venture** was the only way to prevent being played off against each other.

In **December 1933**, they came to final terms: the **Kuwait Oil Company** — fifty-fifty Anglo-Persian and Gulf. Holmes and **Archibald Chisholm** (for Anglo-Persian) were the "heavenly twins" sent to negotiate with the Sheikh. At a tiny church service in Kuwait, when the lesson on "blessed are the pure of heart" was read, Holmes jabbed Chisholm: "At last, you and I are pure in heart about each other."

The Sheikh proved a tough negotiator, well-informed about concession terms in Iraq, Persia, and Saudi Arabia. On **December 23, 1934**, Sheikh Ahmad signed a **seventy-five-year concession** with the Kuwait Oil Company. He received an upfront payment of **£35,700 ($179,000)**, minimum annual payments of **£7,150 ($36,000)** before oil discovery, and **£18,800 ($94,000)** or more after discovery. The Sheikh appointed Major Frank Holmes as his representative to the Kuwait Oil Company — a position Holmes held until his death in 1947.

### *The "Sure Shot"? — Saudi Exploration*

Socal had set up **Casoc** (California-Arabian Standard Oil Company) to hold the Saudi concession. Administrative headquarters were established in Jidda — in a building owned by Jack Philby. In **September 1933**, the first two American geologists arrived at Jubail on a motor launch. They had grown beards and donned Arab headdresses and robes. A few days later, they identified a promising geological structure — the **Dammam Dome** — a desolate expanse of sand and naked rock, only twenty-five miles from the Bahrain discovery. It was a "sure shot," they believed.

Drilling commenced in summer 1934, but the first half-dozen wells were all failures. More geologists arrived, traveling by camel with escorts of ten guards. Conditions were extreme — 115-degree daytime temperatures, bitter cold nights. Distances were measured in "camel days." Three weeks from Jubail, they hunted gazelle and Qatar birds, or bought sheep from passing Bedouin. They used seismography and aerial surveys (a Fairchild 71 with a hole cut in the bottom, using specially heat-resistant Kodak film).

Socal's management in San Francisco grew increasingly anxious — "sometimes there was an open question whether the venture should be abandoned and the approximately $10 million spent written off as a total loss." There was also the alarming possibility that Socal might find oil where it had no distribution facilities in a depressed world market.

### *The Blue Line Agreement — Caltex*

Socal was already facing this problem with Bahrain (capacity 13,000 barrels/day, potential 30,000). In early 1935, it choked production to just 2,500 barrels/day for lack of markets. A proposed deal with Jersey, Shell, and Anglo-Persian fell apart. In early 1936, discouraged **K. R. Kingsbury**, Socal's president, went to New York. **James Forrestal** of investment bank Dillon, Read brought Kingsbury together with **Texaco**'s management. Forrestal (assisted by vice-president **Paul Nitze**) worked out a scheme: Socal and Texaco would pool all assets **"East of Suez"** in a fifty-fifty joint venture. Socal threw in its Bahrain and Saudi concessions plus an East Indies concession; the joint venture took over Texaco's widespread marketing system in Africa and Asia. They delineated their territory with what they called the **"Blue Line"** — and the joint venture became known as **Caltex** (California-Texas company). The established companies were relieved — the merger meant Bahrain and any Saudi oil would be managed and would not destroy prices.

### *Discovery*

Exploration in Kuwait began in 1935; seismic work in 1936 pinpointed the **Burgan field** in southeastern Kuwait. On **February 23, 1938**, petroleum was struck with a surprisingly large flow. To gauge the discovery, crude was allowed to flow into an adjoining sand reservoir, then ignited — the heat was so intense that the sand walls were transformed into **sheets of glass**. Anglo-Persian and Gulf directors heaved a sigh of relief. Holmes was jubilant; Sheikh Ahmad needed no longer worry about cultured pearls.

In Saudi Arabia, Socal's board grew increasingly restive. In **November 1937**, Socal's foreign production manager cabled Arabia with a firm order: no more projects without detailed proposals first. Then, in **March 1938** — a few weeks after the Kuwait discovery — stunning news: at **4,727 feet**, large quantities of oil were tapped in **Well Number 7** in the Dammam Zone. Discovery at last — almost three years after drilling began on Dammam Number 1.

The Saudi discovery set off fevered efforts by the IPC and, more ominously, by **German, Japanese, and Italian interests** seeking drilling rights. The Japanese established diplomatic representation in Saudi Arabia, offered "astronomical" sums for concessions, and presented Ibn Saud with a gift of classic samurai military armor (too small for the large monarch). The Germans accredited their Baghdad minister and pursued an arms deal. But Casoc had a secret annex to the 1933 agreement giving it preference rights to Saudi territory. On **May 31, 1939**, Casoc expanded its exclusive concession to **440,000 square miles** — about one-sixth the size of the continental United States. Socal repeatedly made loans totaling several million dollars to the kingdom.

The Well Number 7 discovery had opened a new era. Work sped up at **Dhahran** — which would become an American middle-class suburb in the desert. A pipeline linked the oil field to **Ras Tanura**, a coastal marine terminal. In **April 1939**, a great procession of **four hundred cars** carrying the King and his huge retinue crossed the desert to Dhahran, where they encamped in 350 tents.

The occasion was the arrival of the Socal tanker ***D. G. Scofield*** at Ras Tanura to pick up the first cargo of oil. With appropriate pomp, **King Ibn Saud himself turned the valve** through which the first trickle of oil flowed out of Saudi Arabia.

### *War Intrudes and the Fates of Philby and Holmes*

Socal hastened to spread exploration. A wildcat well drilled to ten thousand feet indicated very large deposits. Production in 1940 reached **twenty thousand barrels per day**. But then World War II intruded. In **October 1940**, the Italians bombed Dhahran (apparently aiming at Bahrain). A small refinery started at Ras Tanura in January 1941 was closed down the following June. In neighboring Kuwait, on orders of the Allied governments, all wells were **plugged with cement** for fear they would fall into German hands.

In Saudi Arabia, operations were mostly shut down — a skeleton crew kept production of 12,000-15,000 barrels per day going as feedstock for the Bahrain refinery. Further development was postponed; the enterprise entered "a state of suspended animation." But elsewhere, people were beginning to assimilate what Saudi Arabia's oil potential might mean — the country's petroleum reserves would become "the object of political power plays more intricate and intense than anything that might have been imagined."

**Jack Philby** prospered in Saudi Arabia through the 1930s with his explorations and trading. After WWII began, he tried to broker a deal between Ibn Saud and **Chaim Weizmann** (Zionist leader) for a partition of Palestine — it came to nothing. His anti-British sentiments did not abate. He was arrested on a trip to India, sent back to Britain, and **jailed for half a year**. He spent the war writing pamphlets, poetry, and unpublishable books. Returning to Saudi Arabia after the war, he again became adviser to the King. With a young woman presented to him by the King, he became a father again at sixty-five. After Ibn Saud's death, he criticized the spendthrift ways of King Saud and was expelled, though later allowed to return. On a trip to Beirut in 1960 to visit his son Kim, he fell ill and was rushed to the hospital. The man "whose life had been so eventful and panoramic, so daring and theatrical, now lay unconscious." He awoke briefly, murmured to his son "I am so bored," and expired. His gravestone in a Moslem cemetery in Lebanon bore the simple inscription: **"Greatest of Arabian Explorers."**

And **Major Frank Holmes** — **"Abu al-Naft," the Father of Oil**? He was the one who imagined, conceived, and promoted the entire Arabian oil venture. In the mid-1940s, as the extent of Arabian oil riches became clear, Holmes — by then Kuwait's oil representative in London — was asked an obvious question. What made him so certain of Arabian oil prospects, in the face of the virtually unanimous verdict of the world's leading geologists that Arabia would be "oil dry"? His practical experience as a mining engineer had taught him that theoretical advice, however expert, could be quite wrong. But Holmes offered a simpler answer. He tapped his finger to his nose. **"This," he said, "was my geologist."**

## Chapter 16: Japan's Road to War

### *The Manchurian Affair*

On the night of **September 18, 1931**, soldiers of the Japanese Imperial Army in the semi-autonomous Chinese province of Manchuria carried out a bomb attack against the **South Manchurian Railway**. The actual damage was scant — about thirty-one inches of track, so negligible that a speeding express train passed over the spot minutes later. But this was by intention: the Japanese controlled the railroad and wanted to keep damage minimal while blaming the Chinese. The Japanese Army now had its desired pretext to launch an attack on Chinese forces, which it did without delay. The **Manchurian Affair** had begun, marking the entry into what the Japanese would call **the Valley of Darkness**.

Japan had gained economic and political prerogatives in Manchuria through its victories over China (1895) and Russia (1905). By the late 1920s, there was strong support to take complete control — Manchuria was "Japan's life line," as one Prime Minister described it. It would supply raw materials and "living space." Moreover, the Japanese Army feared the dual threats of Soviet communism and Chinese nationalism.

### *"Shall We Trust Japan?"*

In 1923, **Franklin Roosevelt** (then a private citizen, formerly Assistant Navy Secretary) wrote an article entitled **"Shall We Trust Japan?"** He observed that "long before the events of 1914 centered attention elsewhere, an American-Japanese war was the best bet of prophets." Yet Roosevelt answered affirmatively — Japan had changed. Through the 1920s, his analysis proved correct. The 1921 **Washington Naval Conference** defused a potential naval race. Japan based its security on cooperation with Anglo-American powers.

But this cooperation did not survive the decade. The Japanese military, particularly the Army, came to dominate the government. The Great Depression brought economic hardship, heightening vulnerability from lack of raw materials and shrinking international markets. The Army and segments of society were gripped by extreme nationalism, arrogance, and a mystical belief in "The Imperial Way." Prime Minister **Osachi Hamaguchi**, who favored naval treaty cooperation, was **shot at a railway station** by an enraged youth in 1930 and died in 1931. A cult of ultranationalism — "government by assassination" — took hold. Japan organized the puppet state of **Manchukuo** with the deposed Chinese emperor **Pu Yi** as figurehead. When the League of Nations condemned Japan, it stalked out of the League.

### *The New Order in Asia*

Japanese politics seethed with conspiracies, ideological movements, and secret societies rejecting liberalism, capitalism, and democracy. By the mid-1930s, elements of the military focused on total war doctrine — a **"national defense state"** harnessing all industrial and military resources. Officers who studied Germany's WWI failure attributed it to economic vulnerability — lack of raw materials and inability to withstand naval blockade. Japan, they recognized, was far less well-endowed. It was **almost bare of oil**. While petroleum was only about **7% of total energy consumption**, its strategic importance was paramount — most was consumed by the military and shipping. By the late 1930s, Japan produced only about **7% of the oil it consumed**. The rest was imported — **80% from the United States**, another 10% from the Dutch East Indies.

An acrimonious split between **Army** and **Navy** shaped policy. The Army focused on Manchuria, North China, Inner Mongolia, and the Soviet threat. The Navy, under the doctrine of ***hokushu nanshin*** — "defend in the north, advance to the south" — set its sights on the **Dutch East Indies, Malaya, Indochina**, and Pacific islands to secure access to natural resources, especially oil.

In the early 1930s, the Japanese government asserted domination over the oil industry. **60%** of the internal market was held by two Western companies — **Rising Sun** (Shell's Japanese affiliate) and **Standard-Vacuum (Stanvac)** (the Jersey/Socony amalgam for the Far East). In 1934, the **Petroleum Industry Law** gave the government power to control imports, set quotas, fix prices, and make compulsory purchases. Foreign companies were required to maintain **six months of inventories** beyond normal levels — to build up the Japanese-owned refining industry, reduce foreign companies' role, and prepare for war. Japan also established a petroleum monopoly in Manchukuo.

In **August 1934**, Deterding and Teagle went to Washington to suggest "frightening" Japan into moderation by hinting at an embargo. In **November 1934**, the British Cabinet endorsed "the stiffest possible resistance" to Japanese oil policies, including government support for a privately organized embargo. But **Secretary of State Cordell Hull** refused, and the embargo talk died.

### *"Quarantine"*

On the night of **July 7-8, 1937**, clashes between Japanese and Chinese troops at the **Marco Polo Bridge** near Beijing escalated into full-scale war. **Chiang Kai-shek** declared: "If we allow one more inch of our territory to be lost, we shall be guilty of an unpardonable crime against our race." Japan decided the Chinese needed "a thoroughgoing blow" and went to war with China.

Japan accelerated its war economy. A special session of the Diet passed the **Synthetic Oil Industry Law** — a seven-year plan to produce synthetic fuels from coal by 1943, in volumes equivalent to half of Japan's 1937 consumption. The goal was extremely unrealistic. Roosevelt, frustrated by isolationist constraints, obliquely broached a **"quarantine"** in an October 1937 speech to check the "epidemic of world lawlessness." After a Japanese air attack on four American ships in the Yangtze, he privately told his Cabinet he meant "such a thing as using economic sanctions without declaring war." But prevailing isolationism prevented action.

In 1938, after Japanese bombing of Canton, polls found a **large majority** of the American public opposed continued export of military materiel to Japan. "Japan furnishes the pilot, America furnishes the airplane, gasoline, oil, and bombs for the ravaging of undefended Chinese cities." A **Gallup Poll in June 1939** reported **72%** favored an embargo on war materials to Japan. But the Roosevelt Administration feared undermining Japanese moderates and provoking worse aggression.

**Joseph Grew**, American ambassador to Japan, warned of the consequences of sanctions. The Japanese would submit "to any deprivation rather than see their nation humbled by Western powers — and lose face." In autumn 1939, he met twice with Roosevelt and wrote: "I brought out clearly my view that if we once start sanctions against Japan we must see them through to the end, and the end may conceivably be war. I also said that if we cut off Japanese supplies of oil and if Japan then finds that she cannot obtain sufficient oil from other commercial sources to ensure her national security, she will in all probability send her fleets down to take the Dutch East Indies." **"Then we could easily intercept her fleet,"** the President replied.

In **September 1938**, during the Munich crisis, **George Walden** (head of Stanvac) and **Lloyd "Shorty" Elliott** (president of Stanvac's producing arm in the Dutch East Indies) listened to radio reports in The Hague. They were sure that when war came to Asia, Japan would attack the East Indies — "it was just a question of when and how." That night they began planning for that eventuality. They dismissed German, Dutch, and Japanese employees of doubtful loyalty. Plans were prepared for the **destruction of Stanvac's refinery and oil wells** — not secretly, but openly, as a deterrent. By early 1940, Walden indicated that if the U.S. placed an embargo, Stanvac "would cooperate fully" and "stop all shipments from all properties under its control all over the world."

### *Japanese Advance and American Restrictions — The First Round*

Japan sought industrial self-sufficiency and elimination of dependence on the U.S. The Japanese public was bombarded with propaganda about the **"ABCD" powers** — America, Britain, China, and the Dutch — conspiring to deny resources. After the **fall of France and the Low Countries** in May-June 1940, the colonial powers in the Far East looked vulnerable. Japan demanded oil from the Dutch East Indies. Washington made a fateful decision: it transferred the American fleet from Southern California to **Pearl Harbor** on Oahu — as a deterrent to Tokyo and a stiffening of British resolve.

Summer 1940 was a major turning point. Japan demanded a military mission to French Indochina, war materials from the East Indies, and the closing of the Burma supply route into China. Roosevelt brought **Henry Stimson** (a longtime Japan critic) into the Cabinet as Secretary of War. On **July 2, 1940**, Roosevelt signed the **National Defense Act**, whose **Section VI** gave the President power to control exports — the lever to regulate oil supplies to Japan.

In Tokyo, leaders favoring accommodation were losing ground. A secret police plot to kill those favoring settlement with the U.S. and Britain — including the Prime Minister — was aborted in July. The Cabinet was reconstructed under **Prince Konoye**; the militant **General Hideki Tojo** — known as ***"Kamisori,"*** the "Razor" — became War Minister.

On **July 19, 1940**, Roosevelt told senior advisers he had concluded "the only way out of the difficulties of the world" was "by cutting off supplies to the aggressor countries, particularly in regard to their supply of fuel to carry on the war." But on Japan specifically, there was "no consensus about whether that would make things better or worse." Treasury Secretary **Morgenthau** and War Secretary **Stimson** pushed for a complete embargo. But the State Department, fearful of provoking rupture, succeeded in limiting the ban to **aviation gasoline of 87 octane or higher**, plus some iron ore and steel scrap. American planes used 100-octane fuel; Japanese planes could operate on fuels below 87 octane. Japan bought **550% more** 86-octane gasoline from the U.S. in the five months after the proclamation than before. Despite appearances, an embargo had not gone into effect — only a licensing system.

On **September 26, 1940**, Washington banned export of all iron and steel scrap — but not oil. The next day, Japan signed the **Tripartite Pact** with Hitler and Mussolini. Roosevelt, committed to a "Europe first" strategy, husbanded resources for Europe and resisted a full oil embargo — the Presidential election was a month away. Meanwhile, Japan was buying up all petroleum supplies, drilling equipment, and storage tanks it could obtain. Britain now wanted to halt the oil flow, fearing Japanese stockpiling would make sanctions immune. Still, Roosevelt and Hull resisted.

### *Quiet Conversations — Hull and Nomura*

**Secretary of State Cordell Hull** — a tall, silver-haired backwoodsman turned statesman from a Tennessee log cabin — began secret nighttime talks with the new Japanese ambassador, **Admiral Kichisaburo Nomura**, usually at Hull's apartment at the Wardman Park Hotel. Hull had devoted himself since 1933 to breaking down trade barriers for world peace. Now he could see those labors going for naught.

Admiral Nomura was a political moderate, widely respected in Japanese circles. At six feet, he stood out. He had lost an eye in a bomb attack by a Korean nationalist in Shanghai in 1932, which also left him with a limp and more than a hundred metal fragments in his body. He had served as naval attache in Washington during WWI and known the young FDR. Upon his return in February 1941, Roosevelt greeted him as "friend" and insisted on calling him "Admiral" rather than "Ambassador." Nomura told the U.S. Chief of Naval Operations that "his lips and his heart" were "at variance." Later, trying to explain the tense days, he said simply: **"When a big house falls, one pillar can not stop it."**

Beginning March 1941, Hull and Nomura met perhaps **forty or fifty times**, plowing through discouraging soil. Hull had a startling advantage: thanks to the code-breaking operation **"Magic,"** the U.S. and Britain had cracked **"Purple,"** the top-secret Japanese diplomatic code. Hull could read, before meetings, Tokyo's instructions to Nomura. He played his part adroitly, never revealing his knowledge. In early May 1941, the Germans informed Tokyo that the Americans had broken their codes — **the Japanese simply did not believe it**, convinced Americans were not capable of such a feat.

Yet despite "Magic," Washington did not know of the Japanese Navy's concern that the American fleet at Pearl Harbor, if left unattended during an invasion of the East Indies, could launch a dangerous flank attack. The Japanese Navy had begun planning a high-risk project — a **surprise attack on Pearl Harbor**.

### *Yamamoto's Gamble — "Doubtless I Will Die"*

As early as spring 1940, **Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto**, Commander in Chief of Japan's Combined Fleets, had begun to outline this wild gamble. He was the most daring, original, and controversial of the Japanese admirals — short, broadly constructed, widely respected for physical courage. He had spent more than four years in the U.S. (Harvard, then naval representative and attache), read four or five biographies of Lincoln, regularly received *Life* magazine, and recognized that America was rich in resources while Japan was poor, with productive capacity far outstripping Japan's.

Even while developing the Pearl Harbor plan, Yamamoto continued to challenge the whole idea of war with the United States — "at best, very risky and, most probably, a losing proposition." He scoffed at ultranationalists with their "armchair arguments about war and their mystical fantasies." He called complaints about "America's economic pressure" the "aimless action of a schoolboy."

The oil factor weighed heavily on Yamamoto. He grew up in the **Niigata district**, one of Japan's small domestic oil-producing regions; his hometown of Nagaoka was populated by hundreds of tiny factories producing oil for lamps. His time in America convinced him the industrial world was moving from coal to oil and that air power was the future. Acutely conscious of Japan's oil vulnerability, he restricted the Navy (the world's third-largest) to training only in waters immediately off Japan — **to conserve petroleum**. He even sponsored experiments by a "scientist" who claimed he could change water into oil.

Yet Yamamoto was a fervent nationalist devoted to Emperor and country. "It's out of the question!" he exclaimed. "To fight the United States is like fighting the whole world. But it has been decided. So I will do my best. Doubtless I will die." If Japan had to go to war, he believed in the **"decisive blow"** — knock the United States off balance, incapacitate it, while Japan secured Southeast Asia. "The lesson which impressed me most deeply when I studied the Russo-Japanese War was the fact that our Navy launched a night assault against Port Arthur at the very beginning. This was the most excellent strategical initiative ever envisaged during the war." His plan was decided in late 1940 and early 1941 — "to decide the fate of the war on the very first day" by knocking out the U.S. fleet, and also to destroy the morale of the American people.

"Operation Hawaii" required secrecy, first-rate intelligence, superb coordination, high technical skills, new aerial torpedoes, new refueling-at-sea techniques, absolute devotion, and the cooperation of weather and waves. Early in 1941, Ambassador Grew heard a rumor about the planned attack from Peru's minister to Tokyo. Grew reported it to Washington, where it was immediately discounted. **American officials simply could not believe — then or in the months following — that such an audacious assault was even possible.**

### *Embargo*

From April through June 1941, arguments raged in the U.S. government over whether to cut off oil exports to Japan and freeze Japanese funds. The Axis powers and America were moving closer to direct confrontation. On **May 27, 1941**, Roosevelt declared an **"unlimited national emergency"** — aiming to "scare the daylights out of everyone" about Axis dangers. **Harold Ickes**, just appointed Petroleum Coordinator, immediately prohibited oil shipments to Japan from the East Coast — but the order did not cover the Gulf or West Coasts. Ickes was pushing for a general embargo on all oil exports to Japan.

An angry Roosevelt **countermanded Ickes's order**, leading to a bitter exchange. **"There will never be so good a time to stop the shipment of oil to Japan as we now have,"** Ickes argued, noting Japan was preoccupied with Russia and Siberia. Roosevelt shot back sarcastically: "Please let me know if this would continue to be your judgment if this were to tip the delicate scales and cause Japan to decide either to attack Russia or to attack the Dutch East Indies." He told Ickes the question of Japanese exports was "a matter not of oil conservation, but of foreign policy."

Ickes, as was his wont, proffered his resignation — though not as Interior Secretary. Roosevelt refused to accept it: **"There you go again!"** He explained: "the Japs are having a real drag-down and knock-out fight among themselves... trying to figure out which way they are going to jump." He added: **"As you know, it is terribly important for the control of the Atlantic for us to help to keep peace in the Pacific. I simply have not got enough Navy to go around."**

The "knock-out fight" Roosevelt referred to had been precipitated by **Germany's surprise attack on the Soviet Union in June 1941**, which forced a major strategic choice for Tokyo: continue southward or join the attack on Russia from the east. Between **June 25 and July 2, 1941**, senior officials in Tokyo grappled with and argued fervently over the choices. They made the **fateful decision**: put off doing anything about the Soviet Union, concentrate on the **southern strategy** — secure control of all of Indochina, deemed necessary to go for the East Indies. They did so knowing the occupation of southern Indochina could provoke an all-out American oil embargo, which would be **"a matter of life or death to the empire,"** in the words of the Navy General Staff. But Japan would not be deterred by the threat of war with Britain and the United States.

Through **"Magic" intercepts**, Washington knew of the momentous debate and its outcome. "After the occupation of French Indochina," said one intercepted message, **"next on our schedule is... the Netherlands East Indies."** At Roosevelt's Cabinet meeting on July 18, it was reported that the Japanese were virtually certain to advance into southern Indochina within days.

**"What are you going to do on the economic front against Japan if she makes this move?"** Treasury Secretary **Morgenthau** asked the President. **"If we stopped all oil,"** Roosevelt replied, **"it would simply drive the Japanese down to the Dutch East Indies, and it would mean war in the Pacific."** But he indicated he would support freezing Japanese financial assets in the United States.

Roosevelt himself did not want a full embargo. He wanted to tighten controls but keep them **"day to day," a flexible tool** that could be adjusted. He thought he could use oil as an instrument for diplomacy, not as the trigger for war. Undersecretary of State **Sumner Welles** proposed a program holding petroleum exports to the 1935-36 level but prohibiting export of any grades convertible into aviation gasoline. Export licenses would be required for *all* oil exports.

On the evening of **July 25**, the U.S. government ordered all Japanese financial assets in the United States frozen. Licenses — government approval — would be required for each use of frozen funds, including oil purchases. On **July 28**, Japan began its anticipated invasion of southern Indochina.

### *Dean Acheson's De Facto Embargo*

The new American policy was not meant to cut off oil entirely, at least not explicitly, but **a virtually total embargo was the actual result**. A key role was played by **Dean Acheson**, Assistant Secretary of State for Economic Affairs, one of the few senior State Department officials to favor an out-and-out embargo. He turned the July 25 order into an embargo, in consultation with the Treasury Department, by completely preventing the release of frozen funds necessary for the Japanese to buy oil. **"Whether or not we had a policy, we had a state of affairs,"** Acheson later said. **"Until further notice it would continue."** From the beginning of August, no more oil was exported to Japan. Two Japanese tankers were left sitting empty in the harbor at San Pedro, near Los Angeles.

Britain followed with its own freeze and embargo, cutting off supplies from Borneo, as did the Dutch East Indies.

By the end of July 1941, Japan had secured its occupation of southern Indochina. **"Today I knew from the hard looks on their faces that they meant business,"** Ambassador Nomura reported to the Foreign Ministry in Tokyo on July 31. He urged appeasement measures. The Foreign Ministry scathingly dismissed his concerns. With the Japanese thrust into Indochina and the consequent American freeze on Japanese funds — which in practice meant an embargo on oil — **the countdown had begun**.

The embargo did not create the impending confrontation — it was virtually the only way left for the U.S., Britain, and the Dutch to respond to Japanese aggression short of military action. For the Japanese, however, it was the final link in their **"encirclement"** by hostile powers. Tokyo refused to recognize it was creating a self-fulfilling prophecy. The embargo was the result of four years of Japanese military aggression in Asia. The only oil securely available to Japan was what it held in its own inventories. If it were to maintain its capability to wage war, it would inevitably have to risk — or make — war.

### *"We Cannot Endure It"*

The leaders of the Japanese Navy — previously more cautious than the Army about confrontation with the United States — were no longer restrained in the light of the complete embargo. **"If there were no supply of oil, battleships and any other warships would be nothing more than scarecrows,"** a leading Japanese admiral said. **Admiral Osami Nagano**, chief of the Naval General Staff, stressed to the Emperor that Japan's petroleum reserves would, without replenishment, **last no more than two years**.

The new Japanese foreign minister, **Teijiro Toyoda**, expressed the paranoia in secret messages to ambassadors in Berlin and Washington: **"Commercial and economic relations between Japan and third countries, led by England and the United States, are gradually becoming so horribly strained that we cannot endure it much longer."** He wrote on July 31, 1941: "Consequently, our Empire, to save its very life, must take measures to secure the raw materials of the South Seas... break asunder this ever-strengthening chain of encirclement."

How different it looked to **Cordell Hull**, ill and exhausted at White Sulphur Springs: "The Japanese are seeking to dominate militarily practically one-half the world. ... Nothing will stop them except force." Still he sought to postpone the inevitable: "The point is how long we can maneuver the situation until the military matter in Europe is brought to a conclusion."

Ambassador **Grew** in Tokyo saw the situation clearly: **"The vicious circle of reprisals and counter reprisals is one,"** he wrote in his diary. ***"Facilis descensus Averno est."*** By that time, power shovels were already digging shelters around the Imperial Palace in Tokyo.

### *Last-Ditch Diplomacy — Konoye's Gamble*

There were last-minute diplomatic efforts. **Prince Konoye**, the Prime Minister, with some support from the Navy, raised the possibility of a summit meeting with Roosevelt. He was even willing to jettison the Axis alliance with Hitler to reach an understanding with the Americans. Palace officials endorsed Konoye's idea. **"The whole problem facing Japan had been reduced to a very simple factor, and that was oil,"** **Koichi Kido**, the Lord Privy Seal, told the premier in private, adding, "Japan could not possibly fight a war of certain victory against the United States."

The Emperor himself gave Konoye's idea his blessing, noting intelligence from the Navy about the general oil embargo. Konoye suggested Roosevelt meet in, of all places, **Honolulu**. The President was initially quite interested — taken enough to counter-propose Juneau, Alaska. But **Hull and the State Department strenuously opposed** this breach in diplomatic due process. They did not understand this was Konoye's last gamble. Nor did they trust Japan. Moreover, Roosevelt did not want "Juneau" to join the vocabulary along with "Munich." Magic intercepts indicated the Japanese were intent on further conquest. So Roosevelt, with his talent for ambiguity, neither agreed to nor rejected such a meeting.

### *"Dwindling Day by Day"*

In Tokyo, on **September 5 and 6**, the most senior Japanese officials met with the Emperor to assume a war posture, even while diplomatic alternatives were explored. Oil was their central concern: **"At present oil is the weak point of our Empire's national strength and fighting power... As time passes, our capacity to carry on war will decline, and our Empire will become powerless militarily."** The Navy Chief of Staff told the Emperor: **"Vital military supplies, including oil, are dwindling day by day."**

The Emperor asked how long hostilities would last. "Operations in the South Pacific could be disposed of in about three months," the Army Chief of Staff answered. The Emperor retorted sharply: the General had been Minister of War at the outbreak of the China Incident and had then promised it would be disposed of in about one month — **"Despite the General's assurance, the incident was not yet concluded after four long years of fighting."** "If the Chinese hinterland was extensive," the Emperor shot back, raising his voice, **"the Pacific was boundless."** How could the general be certain of his three-month calculation? The Chief of Staff hung his head, with no reply.

**Admiral Nagano** stepped in: "Japan was like a patient suffering from a serious illness. A quick decision had to be made one way or the other." The Emperor tried to ascertain whether the senior advisers favored diplomacy or war first — he could not get a clear answer. The next day, when the question was raised again, the Chiefs of Army and Navy General Staff remained silent. The Emperor expressed regret, drew a paper from his robe, and read a poem by his grandfather, **Emperor Meiji**: *"Since all are brothers in this world, Why is there such constant turmoil?"* The hall was silent. "Everyone present was struck with awe." Admiral Nagano rose and said military force would be used only when all else had failed. The meeting adjourned **"in an atmosphere of unprecedented tenseness."**

After the conference, the Cabinet took up whether **synthetic oil production** could be greatly increased. Konoye said it was better to spend vast sums on such a program than on war. But the head of the Planning Board said it would require up to four years, many billions of yen, vast amounts of steel, pipes, machinery, and upward of **four hundred thousand coal miners**. Konoye's proposal was put aside. In late September, four men armed with daggers and short swords attacked Konoye's car — they were repulsed, but the Prime Minister was badly shaken.

On **October 2**, the United States officially rejected a meeting between Konoye and Roosevelt. Shortly after, Konoye fell from office. He was replaced on **October 18** by **Hideki Tojo**, the bellicose war minister nicknamed **"the Razor"**, who had consistently dismissed diplomacy as useless. Ambassador Nomura futilely described himself as **"the bones of a dead horse."** Roosevelt pleaded with Nomura that between their two countries, there be "no last words."

The two Japanese tankers that had sat in the harbor near Los Angeles since midsummer, waiting for contracted oil, finally weighed anchor in the first part of November and sailed away with no oil aboard. Now no one could doubt the absoluteness of the oil embargo. With winter almost at hand in Tokyo, the Japanese retaliated by cutting off all supplies of heating oil to the American and British embassies.

Through October and November, Japan's military and political leaders debated the final commitment to war in small rooms in the Imperial Palace. Again and again, the discussion came back to oil. Japanese oil imports had fallen drastically in 1941. Inventories were declining. **"From the records available it is clear that this time-oil factor hovered over the conference table like a demon,"** one historian wrote. **"A decision for war was considered the most readily available means of exorcising it."**

### *The Imperial Conference — November 5*

On **November 5**, an Imperial Conference of the most senior leaders convened before the Emperor. **Tojo** summarized the majority position: "The United States has from the beginning believed that Japan would give up because of economic pressure... If we enter into a protracted war, there will be difficulties... We have some uneasiness about a protracted war. But how can we let the United States continue as she pleases, even though there is some uneasiness? **Two years from now we will have no petroleum for military use. Ships will stop moving.** When I think about the strengthening of American defenses in the Southwest Pacific, the expansion of the American fleet, the unfinished China Incident, and so on, I see no end to difficulties. ... **I fear that we would become a third-class nation after two or three years if we just sat tight.**"

The proposal called for stiff last-ditch demands to the United States. If rejected, Japan would go to war. Tojo asked for objections; hearing none, the proposal was approved.

A Japanese diplomat arrived in Washington the third week of November to present the demands to Hull — they read like an ultimatum. There was also an intercepted "Magic" message of **November 22**, informing Nomura that American agreement to Tokyo's proposals had to be received by **November 29** at the very latest, for **"reasons beyond your ability to guess."** For, **"after that, things are automatically going to happen."**

On **November 25**, Roosevelt warned his senior military advisers that war could come very soon, even within a week. On November 26, Hull presented a note proposing Japanese withdrawal from Indochina and China in exchange for resumed trade. Tokyo regarded this as an American ultimatum. On **that same day, November 26**, a Japanese naval task force that had gathered in the **Kurile Islands** was ordered to set sail, under radio silence. **Its destination was Hawaii.**

Secretary of War **Stimson** brought Roosevelt an intelligence report showing a large Japanese expeditionary force moving south from Shanghai toward Southeast Asia. "He fairly blew up, jumped into the air, so to speak, and said he hadn't seen it," commented Stimson. That changed the whole situation — evidence of bad faith while negotiating for a truce. On **November 27**, Hull told Stimson he had completely given up on negotiations: **"I have washed my hands of it."** Washington sent off "a final alert" to American commanders in the Pacific, including **Admiral Husband Kimmel**, commander of the Pacific Fleet in Hawaii. The message began: **"This dispatch is to be considered a war warning."**

Up to the very end, there were those in Tokyo who saw nothing but disaster ahead. On **November 29**, the Senior Statesmen met with the Cabinet and the Emperor to plead that Japan seek a diplomatic solution. Tojo railed that broken economic relations would mean progressive weakening of Japan. The Japanese leaders, in all their studies, had recognized that a long war would increasingly favor the United States because of its resources, capabilities, and endurance — **but so strongly were the militarists gripped in the trance of their own making that those committed to war simply waved that consideration aside.** War was on a speeding track.

### *Pearl Harbor*

On **December 1**, the special Japanese task force, still undetected, crossed the international dateline. "Everything is decided," a flight commander wrote on December 2. "There is neither here nor there, neither sorrow nor rejoicing." Tokyo gave orders to its embassies and consulates to destroy codes. An American military officer, sent to reconnoiter the Japanese embassy in Washington, found that **papers were being burned in the backyard**.

On **Saturday, December 6**, Roosevelt decided to send a personal note directly to the Emperor, seeking to dispel "the dark clouds." The message did not go off until nine o'clock that evening. Shortly after sending it, Roosevelt told some visitors, **"This son of man has just sent his final message to the Son of God."**

At **12:30 in the afternoon of December 7**, Washington time, Roosevelt received the Chinese ambassador and said he expected "foul play" in Asia. He had a feeling the Japanese might do something "nasty" within forty-eight hours. At **1:00 p.m. Washington time** — it was **3:00 a.m., December 8, in Tokyo** — Roosevelt's message was finally delivered to the Emperor. In the middle of the Pacific, it was the early morning hours of December 7, and the Japanese fleet was coming upon the Hawaiian Islands. Aloft above the flagship was the flag that had flown on a Japanese battleship in 1905, when the fleet had destroyed the Russian Navy in the Tsushima Strait. Planes were leaving the decks of the aircraft carriers. Their crews had been told they were going to **destroy the ability of the United States to cheat Japan out of its deserved place on earth**.

**The bombs began to fall on the American fleet in Pearl Harbor at 7:55 a.m., Hawaiian time.**

An hour after the attack began, Ambassador Nomura arrived at the State Department. Hull took an urgent call from the President: **"There's a report that the Japanese have attacked Pearl Harbor."** "Has the report been confirmed?" Hull asked. "No," the President replied. Hull made a pretense of reading Tokyo's justification. He could not control his rage: **"In all my fifty years of public service I have never seen such a document more crowded with falsehoods and distortions — infamous falsehoods and distortions on a scale so huge that I never imagined until today that any Government on this planet was capable of uttering them."** To Hull, the backwoodsman turned statesman, the two diplomats looked to him **"like a pair of sheep-killing dogs."**

Neither Japanese offered any further comment. The meeting ended, but no one came forward to open the door for them, for they were now enemies. They opened the door themselves and rode down in an empty elevator, and let themselves out to the street.

All that day, the reports flowed into Washington from Pearl Harbor — disjointed, fragmentary, and finally, dismal. "The news coming from Hawaii is very bad," Stimson noted. **"It has been staggering to see our people there, who have been warned long ago and were standing on the alert, should have been so caught by surprise."** Senior American officials had fully expected a Japanese attack — but in Southeast Asia. Virtually no one seriously considered that Japan could launch a surprise assault against the American fleet at its home base. They believed Pearl Harbor was "the strongest fortress in the world." Most American officials seemed to have forgotten that Japan's great victory in the Russo-Japanese War had begun with a surprise attack on the Russian fleet at Port Arthur.

Each side had fundamentally underestimated the other. Just as the Japanese did not think the Americans were technically capable of cracking their most secret codes, the Americans could not conceive that the Japanese would be able to mount so technically complex an operation. The Japanese counted on Pearl Harbor to shatter American morale — instead, the attack **revivified national morale and swiftly united the country**. That was a much greater error.

After the fact, Japanese intentions could be clearly discerned in the mass of information available. But in those tense months, the clear signals were lost in "the noise" — the maze of complex, confusing, contradictory, competing, and ambiguous pieces of information. The dissemination of "Magic" itself was sometimes bungled, in critical ways. The breakdown of critical communication among key actors on the American side may have been the **second most important cause** of the tragedy at Pearl Harbor, following only the failure to believe that such an attack could take place at all.

### *The One Mistake*

Pearl Harbor was not the main Japanese target — Hawaii was but one piece of a massive, far-flung military onslaught. In the same hours, the Japanese were bombing and blockading Hong Kong, bombing Singapore, bombing the Philippines, bombarding Wake and Guam, taking over Thailand, invading Malaya — **and preparing to invade the East Indies**. The operation against Pearl Harbor was meant to protect the flank — to safeguard the Japanese invasion of the Indies and the rest of Southeast Asia by incapacitating the American fleet, and to protect the tanker routes from Sumatra and Borneo to the home islands. **The primary target of this huge campaign remained the oil fields of the East Indies.**

A critical element of success — **luck** — had been with the Japanese attackers right up to the last moment. They far exceeded their own ambitions. Two waves of Japanese aircraft succeeded in sinking, capsizing, or severely damaging **eight battleships**, three light cruisers, three destroyers, and four auxiliary craft. Hundreds of American planes were destroyed or damaged. **2,335 American servicemen and 68 civilians were killed.** The American aircraft carriers survived only because they happened to be out on missions at sea. The Japanese lost only **twenty-nine planes**. Admiral Yamamoto's gamble had paid off, handsomely.

Yet the commander of the Hawaiian task force, **Chuichi Nagumo**, was far more cautious — indeed, he had actually opposed the entire operation. Despite the entreaties of his emboldened officers, he did not want to send planes back to Hawaii for **a third wave** to attack the repair facilities and the oil tanks at Pearl. His luck had been so enormous that he did not want to take more risks. And that, along with the sparing of the aircraft carriers, was **America's only piece of good fortune on that day of devastation**.

Yamamoto had observed that the great mistake in Japan's surprise attack against the Russians at Port Arthur in 1904 was in not being **"thoroughgoing"** enough. The same mistake was made once again at Pearl Harbor. Oil had been central to Japan's decision to go to war — **yet the Japanese forgot about oil when it came to planning Operation Hawaii**.

Yamamoto and his colleagues, who had endlessly reviewed America's preponderant position in oil, all failed to grasp the significance of the oil supplies on Oahu. An assault on those supplies was not included in their plans.

It was a **strategic error with momentous reverberations**. Every barrel of oil in Hawaii had been transported from the mainland. If the Japanese planes had knocked out the Pacific Fleet's fuel reserves and the tanks in which they were stored, they would have immobilized every ship of the American Pacific Fleet, and not just those they actually destroyed. New petroleum supplies would only have been available from California, thousands of miles away. **"All of the oil for the Fleet was in surface tanks at the time of Pearl Harbor,"** **Admiral Chester Nimitz**, who became Commander in Chief of the Pacific Fleet, was later to say. **"We had about 4.5 million barrels of oil out there and all of it was vulnerable to .50 caliber bullets. Had the Japanese destroyed the oil, it would have prolonged the war another two years."**

---

## Chapter 17: Germany's Formula for War

### *I.G. Farben Meets Hitler*

One afternoon in **June 1932**, an open car appeared at a Munich hotel to pick up two officials of **I.G. Farben**, the huge German chemical combine — one a chemist, the other a public relations man — and drive them to the private apartment of **Adolf Hitler** at *Prinzregentenplatz*. Hitler had not yet come to power as Chancellor, but he was the leader of the National Socialist party, which held almost 20 percent of the seats in the Reichstag and looked likely to increase significantly in the upcoming election.

The men from I.G. Farben had sought out the would-be Fuhrer to try to end the continuing Nazi press campaign against their company. The Nazis railed against I.G. Farben as an exploitative tool of **"international financial lords"** and **"money-mighty Jews,"** and attacked the company for the fact that Jews occupied some senior positions. They even caricatured the company as **"Isadore G. Farben."** The Nazis also criticized I.G. Farben for pursuing its expensive project to manufacture liquid fuels from coal — otherwise known as **synthetic fuels** — and for the tariff protection it had obtained from the government. I.G. Farben had made a very large financial commitment to synthetic fuels, but it appeared by 1932 that the project could never be profitable without continued government tariff protection and other support. The company's main argument was that a synthetic fuels industry would cut Germany's dependence on foreign oil and thus reduce the acute pressure on foreign exchange.

Hitler himself was late for the meeting, having just returned from an electoral campaign trip. He intended to give the two I.G. Farben officials only a half hour, but he became so engrossed in the discussion that he spent **two and a half hours** with them. Mesmerized by his own visions, Hitler did much of the talking, lecturing and declaiming on his plans to motorize Germany and build new highways. But he also asked technical questions about synthetic fuels and assured the two men that such fuels fit perfectly with his overall plans for a new Germany. **"Today, an economy without oil is inconceivable in a Germany which wishes to remain politically independent. Therefore, German motor fuel must become a reality, even if this entails sacrifices. Therefore, it is urgently necessary that the hydrogenation of coal be continued."** He strongly endorsed the synthetic fuels effort and promised to halt the press campaign against I.G. Farben and to keep tariff protection in place once the Nazis came to power. For its part, I.G. Farben — then or later — promised to deliver what the Nazis wanted: **campaign contributions**. When the I.G. Farben officials reported back, the chairman of the company said, "Well, this man seems to be more reasonable than I had thought."

Hitler had good cause to appear reasonable. A successful synthetic fuels program could prove essential to his overall objectives for a resurgent and dominant Germany. One of the major obstacles was Germany's dependence on imported raw materials — and oil in particular. Domestic petroleum production was tiny; imports, correspondingly high, and much of the imported oil came from the Western Hemisphere.

Germany's remarkable economic growth over the preceding half century had been based largely on its own plentiful energy source — **coal**. In the late 1930s, coal supplied **90 percent of Germany's energy** — while oil accounted for only about 5 percent. But already in 1932, Hitler was planning for the future, and oil would be essential to his ambitions. He became Chancellor in January 1933 and over the next year and a half seized complete power. He wasted no time in launching a motorcar campaign — autobahns, limited-access highways without speed limits, were to span the country, and in 1934, planning began for a new type of vehicle called **"the people's car," the Volkswagen**.

But these were pieces of his grand plan to subordinate all of Europe to the Nazi Reich — and to himself. He quickly regimented the economy, harnessed big business to the state, and built the Nazi war machine — bombers, fighter planes, tanks, and trucks, all of which required oil. And the synthetic fuels on which I.G. Farben was working were to be of decisive importance.

### *The Chemical Solution*

Pioneering work on the extraction of synthetic fuels from coal had begun in Germany before the First World War. Germany was already acknowledged as the world's leader in chemistry. In **1913**, the German chemist **Friedrich Bergius** first succeeded in extracting a liquid from coal in a process that became known as **hydrogenation**. Large amounts of hydrogen were added to coal under high temperatures and high pressure in the presence of a catalyst. The end product was a high-grade liquid fuel. A competing German process, **Fischer-Tropsch**, was detailed a decade later, in the mid-1920s. Here, coal molecules were broken down under steam into hydrogen and carbon monoxide, which were made to react together, resulting in synthetic oil. The **Bergius hydrogenation process** was deemed the better of the two — it could produce aviation fuel, which Fischer-Tropsch could not. In addition, I.G. Farben, which acquired the patent rights in 1926 to the Bergius process, was politically more powerful than the sponsors of Fischer-Tropsch.

I.G. Farben became interested in synthetic fuels in the 1920s because of the same predictions of imminent exhaustion of conventional petroleum supplies that were stimulating exploration around the world. A pilot plant was built at I.G.'s **Leuna works**, with initial production beginning in **1927**. At the same time, I.G. Farben was busy seeking potential partners in other countries. After negotiations with a leading British chemical group fell through, I.G. Farben found a much more important potential partner — **Standard Oil of New Jersey**.

### *Standard Oil and I.G. Farben*

Standard was midway in its strategic transformation from refiner to integrated oil company. It had also been exploring alternatives to crude oil as a source of liquid fuels — as early as 1921, it had purchased twenty-two thousand acres in Colorado with the hope of finding a commercially successful method for extracting oil from shale. But Standard had been dissatisfied with the results; one barrel of synthetic oil from shale required a ton of rock, and the economics were extremely unattractive.

**Frank Howard**, the head of research at Standard, visited I.G.'s Leuna works in **1926**. He was so impressed that he fired off a telegram to Standard's president, **Walter Teagle**, in Paris: **"Based upon observations and discussions today, I think that this matter is the most important which has ever faced the company since the dissolution... This means absolutely the independence of Europe in the matter of gasoline supply."** Teagle himself, alarmed about the possibility of losing European markets, hurried to Leuna. "I had not known what research meant until I saw it," he later said. **"We were babies compared to the work I saw."**

Teagle, Howard, and other Standard executives hurriedly gathered at a hotel room in Heidelberg, ten miles from the I.G. Farben works. They concluded that the hydrogenation process might be **"more significant than any technical factor ever introduced into the oil industry up to this time."** It was a clear threat to Standard's business. "Although hydrogenation of coal probably could never compete on an economic basis with crude oil," said Howard, "the nationalistic factor would lead to hydrogenation's being made the foundation of a protected manufacturing industry in many countries willing to pay the price." Markets could be closed to imported crude oil and refined products; Standard could hardly afford not to become involved.

An initial agreement was reached with I.G. Farben, allowing Standard to build a hydrogenation plant in Louisiana. But the world oil shortage was beginning to turn into a surplus, and Standard's interest shifted — hydrogenation could be used on crude oil, to increase the gasoline yield. In **1929**, the two companies struck a broader agreement: Standard would have the patent rights to hydrogenation outside Germany; I.G. Farben received 2 percent of Standard's stock — **546,000 shares — valued at $35 million**. Each company agreed to stay out of the other's main fields. "The I.G. are going to stay out of the oil business — and we are going to stay out of the chemical business." The next step came in 1930, with the establishment of a joint company to share developments in the "oil-chemical" field.

In **1931**, German science and hydrogenation received the highest accolade: **Bergius**, the inventor, and **Carl Bosch**, the chairman of I.G. Farben, shared the **Nobel Prize in chemistry**. Yet the project at Leuna was by then producing at a rate of two thousand barrels per day but floundering badly in deep financial trouble. Development was proving more difficult and much more expensive than anticipated. The oil surplus, with new discoveries in East Texas, had turned into an overwhelming global glut. The resulting collapse in world oil prices made the synthetic fuel effort at Leuna decidedly uneconomical. The cost of producing a liter of *Leunabenzin* was **up to ten times the price per gallon** at which gasoline was put onto tankers in the Gulf of Mexico bound for Germany. Some I.G. Farben executives said the whole project should be abandoned. The sole reason to keep it going was that the costs of shutting it down would be greater than the costs of continuing.

### *Nazi Patronage and the Four-Year Plan*

The only real hope for keeping the synthetic fuels project alive, in the midst of the Great Depression, was state support or bail-out. The new Nazi regime was willing to go much further — guarantee prices and markets to I.G. Farben — so long as the company promised to increase substantially its production of synthetic fuels. Even that was not enough, for hydrogenation was still an infant technology. I.G. Farben won support from the Air Force, the **Luftwaffe**, by proving it could develop a high-quality aviation gasoline. The German Army, the **Wehrmacht**, also lobbied for an expanded commitment to a domestic synthetic fuels industry, arguing that Germany's own current supplies would be woefully inadequate for the new type of warfare it was planning.

Two further developments demonstrated to Hitler the dangers of depending upon foreign oil. First, in **October 1935**, Italy invaded **Ethiopia** (Abyssinia). The **League of Nations** condemned the invasion and considered placing an embargo on oil exports to Italy. **Mussolini** well knew that a shut-off of petroleum supplies would paralyze the Italian military. He resorted to every form of bluff and bluster. A leading proponent of oil sanctions was **Anthony Eden**. But Mussolini found a willing ally in French Prime Minister **Pierre Laval**, who cleverly subverted the oil sanctions movement at the moment when it was closest to success.

By spring 1936, Mussolini's forces had conquered Ethiopia, and the sanctions movement had collapsed. The oil embargo was never tested, never applied. **Mussolini himself later confided to Hitler: "If the League of Nations had followed Eden's advice on the Abyssinian dispute, and had extended economic sanctions to oil, I would have had to withdraw from Abyssinia within a week. That would have been an incalculable disaster for me!"** Hitler took the lesson of dependence most seriously.

The second lesson: the Nazi regime was committed to "recovering" the domestic German market from Standard Oil, Shell, and other foreign companies. The hated Bolsheviks owned a large chain of gasoline stations through which they sold oil products. The Nazi government pushed a German gasoline marketer to acquire the Soviet chain in **1935**. But in **February 1936**, the Soviets abruptly stopped deliveries due to "difficulties with foreign payments." The deliveries did not resume — another warning to Hitler about the dangers of dependence.

Just at this time — February 1936 — as the League still debated oil sanctions, the annual German motor show in Berlin was opened by Hitler. He took the occasion to announce that Germany **"had effectively solved the problem of producing synthetic gasoline."** This achievement, he pointedly declared, "possessed political significance." The question of foreign supplies and sanctions was very much on Hitler's mind. The next month, **March 1936**, he boldly remilitarized the **Rhineland** in violation of treaty agreements — his gravest risk, **"the most nerve-racking in my life."** The Western powers did nothing.

Later in **1936**, Hitler took decisive steps to gird the German state for war by the target date of **1940**. He inaugurated his **Four-Year Plan**, aimed to reduce dependence on foreign oil through new technology and chemistry. **"German fuel production must now be developed with the utmost speed,"** he said. **"This task must be handled and executed with the same determination as the waging of a war, since on its solution depends the future conduct of the war."** He added that "the production cost of these raw materials" was of **"no importance."**

The synthetic fuels industry was supposed to expand output almost **sixfold**. The program received major financial support, and vast amounts of steel and labor were requisitioned. Each plant was a huge engineering undertaking, spread over acres. I.G. Farben led the way, adapting itself to Nazi ideology. By **1937-38**, it was no longer an independent company but rather an industrial arm of the German state, fully Nazified. All Jewish officials had been removed, including a third of the supervisory board who were Jews. The anti-Nazi chairman of the managing board, **Carl Bosch**, the man who had made the deal with Standard Oil, was pushed aside, while most other managing board members who did not already belong to the Nazi party fell all over each other in their rush to sign up.

By **September 1, 1939**, when Germany invaded Poland, **fourteen hydrogenation plants** were in full operation, with six more under construction. By **1940**, synthetic fuel output had increased drastically — **72,000 barrels per day**, accounting for **46 percent of total oil supply**. But the synthetic fuels were even more significant when viewed in terms of military needs. Hydrogenation, the Bergius process, provided some **95 percent of Germany's total aviation gasoline**. Without those synthetic fuels, the Luftwaffe could not have taken to the air.

### *Blitzkrieg and the Russian Campaign*

Despite the strength of his military machine and a growing supply of synthetic fuels, oil was never far from Hitler's mind. That concern had helped shape his basic strategic approach to war — the ***blitzkrieg***, or "lightning war" — fierce but short battles with concentrated mechanized forces that would lead to decisive victory before petroleum supply problems could develop. Initially, the strategy worked astonishingly well — in Poland in 1939, and also in spring 1940, as Hitler's forces overran Norway, the Low Countries, and France with surprising ease. The campaign in the West actually improved Germany's oil position, for German troops captured oil stocks considerably in excess of the fuel they had expended in the invasions.

### *The Russian Campaign: "My Generals Know Nothing About the Economic Aspects of War"*

Many factors shaped Germany's decision to go to war with the Soviet Union: Hitler's deep-seated hatred of Bolshevism ("its eradication, he said, was his 'life's mission'"); his personal enmity for Stalin; his contempt for the Slavs, whom he regarded as "little worms"; his desire to dominate completely the Eurasian land mass; and his drive for glory. He saw ***lebensraum*** ("living space") for the Thousand-Year Reich. Moreover, despite Stalin's pathetic eagerness to live up to the Nazi-Soviet Pact, Hitler suspected a secret deal between Britain and the Soviet Union. Amid all else, there was also the issue of oil.

From the very start, the **capture of Baku** and the other Caucasian oil fields was central to Hitler's concept of his Russian campaign. **"In the economic field,"** one historian has written, **"Hitler's obsession was oil."** To Hitler, it was *the* vital commodity of the industrial age. He read about it, talked about it, knew the history of the world's oil fields. If the oil of the Caucasus — along with the "black earth" farmlands of the Ukraine — could be brought into the German empire, then Hitler's New Order would have the resources to make it invulnerable. **Albert Speer**, the German Minister for Armaments and War Production, said at his interrogation in May 1945, **"the need for oil certainly was a prime motive" in the decision to invade Russia**.

Hitler also saw the Soviet Union as a permanent threat to the **Ploesti oil fields** of **Rumania**, Europe's largest source of petroleum production outside the Soviet Union. Rumania was a German ally, and Germany had become heavily dependent upon Ploesti, which provided **58 percent of Germany's total imports in 1940**. Oil shipments from the Soviet Union had resumed with the signing of the Nazi-Soviet Pact, and in 1940 they accounted for another third of Germany's oil imports. In **June 1940**, the Soviet Union used the terms of the Nazi-Soviet Pact to seize a significant part of northeastern Rumania, putting Russian troops all too close to the Ploesti oil fields. **"The life of the Axis depends on those oilfields,"** Hitler told Mussolini. An attack on Russia would guarantee Ploesti's security — and make available the far grander prize of the Caucasus oil.

In **December 1940**, Hitler issued **Directive Number 21 — Operation Barbarossa** — ordering preparations for an invasion of the Soviet Union. The Germans engaged in an elaborate charade of deception to lull Stalin. Warnings came from many sources — Americans, British, his own spies — but **Stalin resolutely refused to believe them**. Scarcely hours before the invasion, a dedicated German communist defected with word of what was about to happen. Stalin suspected a trick and ordered the man shot.

In the early morning hours of **June 22, 1941**, Russian freight trains were still lumbering westward carrying oil and other raw materials for Germany. Just after 3:00 a.m., the German Army, **three million men strong**, with **600,000 motor vehicles and 625,000 horses**, struck along a wide front. The onslaught caught the Soviet Union completely off guard and put Stalin into a nervous collapse. The Germans thought the attack would be over **in six or eight weeks, or ten at the most**.

Hitler's boast — **"we'll kick the door in and the house will fall down"** — seemed amply borne out at first. The Germans moved even faster than expected. Yet there were soon preliminary signs that they were stretching themselves. They had seriously miscalculated their supply needs, including the need for fuel. On the bad Russian roads and difficult terrain, vehicles burned considerably more fuel than anticipated, sometimes twice as much. The larger vehicles sank into unsurfaced roads and had to be replaced with small Russian wagons drawn by horses.

In **August**, German generals sought Hitler's permission to make Moscow the prime target. Hitler refused. **"The most important aim to be achieved before the onset of winter is not to capture Moscow,"** said his directive of August 21, **"but to seize the Crimea and the industrial and coal region on the Donets, and to cut off the Russian oil supply from the Caucasus area."** The Wehrmacht had to reach Baku. To the arguments of his generals, he responded with one of his favorite maxims: **"My generals know nothing about the economic aspects of war."** Intoxicated by conquest, Hitler was already dreaming aloud about the vast autobahn from Trondheim, Norway, to the Crimea, which would become Germany's Riviera. And, he said, **"the Volga will be our Mississippi."**

Later, Hitler changed his mind and put Moscow back at the top of his objectives. But critical time had been lost. The Germans reached the outskirts of Moscow, just twenty miles from the Kremlin, only at the end of autumn 1941. There they bogged down in mud and snow of fast-approaching winter. The shortages of oil and other supplies finally caught up with them. **"We have reached the end of our resources of personnel and material,"** the Quartermaster General said on November 27. Then on **December 5 and 6**, General **Yuri Zhukov** launched the first successful Soviet counterattack, tying the Germans down for the winter.

The six to eight weeks had turned into months. The Germans were stalemated by winter. They had vastly underestimated the space over which their supply lines would stretch and the reserves of Soviet manpower — **six to eight million Soviet soldiers were killed or captured in the first year of war**, and still new men were thrown into battle. Japan's decision to attack Pearl Harbor rather than the Soviet Union allowed Stalin to transfer his crack **Siberian divisions** westward to the German front.

### *Operation Blau*

In early **1942**, Berlin was making plans for another great offensive — **Operation Blau**. The oil of the Caucasus was its main objective, and from there, on to the oil fields in Iran and Iraq and then on to India. Hitler's economic experts had told him that Germany could not continue the war effort without access to Russian oil, and Hitler fully agreed. At the same time, he wanted to strike at the heart of the Russian war economy. Deprived of fuel, Russia would not be able to stay in the war. Germany assembled a **Technical Oil Brigade**, eventually **fifteen thousand men** strong, with the charge of rehabilitating and running the Russian oil industry. The only thing standing in the way was the requirement to capture it.

By late July 1942, the German armies seemed well on the way — with the conquest of the city of **Rostov** and the cutting of the oil pipeline from the Caucasus. On **August 9**, they reached **Maikop**, the most westerly of the Caucasian oil centers — but a small one, with an output equivalent to only a tenth of Baku. Moreover, before withdrawing, the Russians had so thoroughly destroyed the oil fields and equipment, right down to the small tools in the workshops, that by January 1943 the Germans were able to eke out **no more than seventy barrels per day**.

In mid-August, German mountain troops planted the swastika at the summit of **Mount Elbrus**, the highest point in the Caucasus and in Europe. But the German war machine was stopped before it could reach its objectives — blocked by mountain passes that could be defended, and stymied by **their own shortage of fuel**. The irony of Operation Blau was that the Germans **ran short of oil in their quest for oil**.

The Germans had captured Russian oil supplies, but to no avail — Russian tanks ran on diesel, which was useless to German panzer units, which ran on gasoline. Panzer divisions were sometimes at a standstill for several days in the Caucasus while they waited for fresh supplies. Trucks carrying oil could not catch up because they too had run short of fuel. In desperation, the Germans took to **transporting oil supplies on the backs of camels**. By November 1942, the last German effort to break through the mountain passes toward Grozny and Baku had definitively been repulsed.

### *Stalingrad*

The city of **Stalingrad**, to the northwest of the Caucasus, was meant to be a sideshow, a secondary German objective. But from the very beginning, its name made its fate pregnant with symbolism for both sides. It became the scene of a titanic, decisive struggle fought in the winter of **1942-43**. Again and again, the German Army was crippled by supply shortages, of which fuel loomed largest. General **Heinz Guderian**, the legendary panzer commander, wrote from the Stalingrad front: **"The icy cold, the lack of shelter, the shortage of clothing, the heavy losses of men and equipment, the wretched state of our fuel supplies, all this makes the duties of a commander a misery."**

After more than eighteen months, the tide of battle turned, and the Germans were finally on the defensive in Russia. **Field Marshal Erich von Manstein** begged Hitler in a midnight phone call to transfer the German forces in the Caucasus to help the embattled Sixth Army at Stalingrad. Hitler refused. **"It's a question of the possession of Baku, Field Marshal,"** the dictator said. **"Unless we get the Baku oil, the war is lost."** He proceeded to deliver a lesson on the central importance oil had assumed in warfare, repeating himself over and over. **"If I can no longer get you the oil for your operations, Field Marshal, you will be unable to do anything."**

Manstein tried to argue about the immediate strategic issue — the survival of the Sixth Army. Hitler would not listen. Instead he described how German armies would meet up in the Middle East. **"Then we shall march with our assembled forces to India, where we shall seal our final victory over England. Goodnight, Heil, Field Marshal!"** "Heil, mein Fuhrer!" was all Manstein could say.

Despite Hitler's rapture, the order to retreat was given in January 1943. But it was too late for the Sixth Army at Stalingrad. Surrounded by Soviet forces, it was trapped, unable to risk a breakout. Its tanks only had enough fuel to move **twenty miles**, but to escape they would have had to bridge a gap of thirty miles. It simply could not be done. At the end of January and beginning of February 1943, the encircled German forces at Stalingrad — **ground down and incapacitated, frozen, hungry, and with their essential element of mobility gone** — surrendered.

Stalingrad was Germany's first major defeat in Europe. It sent Hitler into an uncontrollable rage. The ***blitzkrieg*** phase was over. Instead of lightning attacks, the critical factors from here on would be military manpower and economic resources — including oil. The Soviets would press relentlessly forward, pushing the Germans out of all captured Russian territory and moving inexorably toward Berlin itself.

### *Rommel and the Revenge of the Quartermaster*

North Africa was, in the words of General **Erwin Rommel**, the one theater of World War II where the military struggle took place almost totally on the new **"principle of complete mobility."** That mobility was provided by Germany's Panzer Army in North Africa and its most important element, the **Afrika Korps**, both the creation of Rommel. He was a brilliant, innovative, imaginative master of tank warfare and the mobile campaign, as well as a consummate risk taker. Small, silent, and cold, Rommel had established his reputation as a battlefield leader in the First World War. Hitler was impressed by a book he wrote on infantry tactics and in 1938 appointed him, though not a Nazi party member, to head the battalion responsible for the personal safety of the Fuhrer. In 1940, he commanded a panzer division that moved with astonishing speed across France — **"We never imagined war in the West would be like this,"** he wrote to his wife. The campaign had "turned into a lightning tour of France."

In **February 1941**, Rommel was dispatched to North Africa to shore up an Italian Army on the brink of being defeated by British forces. The battle zone would stretch a thousand miles in length, from Tripoli in Libya to **El Alamein** in Egypt, though only seventy miles in width. Rommel was committed to a war of movement and boldness. He was scathing about the commander who halted at the urging of the quartermaster: **"It has become the habit for quartermaster staffs to complain at every difficulty... When, after a great victory... the pursuit is abandoned on the quartermaster's advice, history almost invariably finds the decision to be wrong."**

At first, Rommel won stunning victories against British forces, often with only slender resources and captured booty. At one point, **85 percent of his transport** was provided by captured British and American vehicles. He also ordered "dummy tanks" built at workshops in Tripoli, mounted on Volkswagens. But there was one thing even he could not fake — mobile warfare was absolutely dependent on ample supplies of fuel, delivered along very long lines. Oil proved to be one of Rommel's most persistent problems. As early as June 1941 he wrote: **"Unfortunately, our petrol stocks were badly depleted, and it was with some anxiety that we contemplated the coming British attack, for we knew that our moves would be decided more by the petrol gauge than by tactical requirements."**

In late May 1942, Rommel launched a major assault against the British. It went very well. In one week, his forces traveled three hundred miles. Rather than stop at the frontier between Libya and Egypt as planned, Rommel pushed on until his advance was finally halted, late in June, near **El Alamein** — now less than sixty miles from Alexandria; Cairo and the Suez Canal were not far beyond.

The Axis powers thought they were on the verge of famous victory. **Mussolini flew over to North Africa**, accompanied in another airplane by a white charger, on which he planned to make a triumphant entry into Cairo. Rommel's goals were far more expansive: Cairo would only be a way station for a campaign through Palestine, Iraq, and Iran whose final objective would be **Baku and its oil fields**. Their capture, in concert with the German forces then battling in the Caucasus, would **"shatter the Russian colossus."** Hitler wrote to Mussolini: **"Destiny has offered us a chance which will never occur twice in the same theater of war."**

Both Rommel and Hitler spoke too soon. While the Soviets held on in the Caucasus, the Allies had succeeded in retaining the Mediterranean island of **Malta**, off the coast of Libya, which gave them a base from which to attack the Axis shipping that supplied Rommel's forces. The Allies were further aided by their intercepts of German and Italian codes. The supply aircraft of the Luftwaffe were running short of fuel. Italian supply ships were no longer getting through to North Africa. And Rommel's very success — the incredible distance the Afrika Korps had traveled — created a dangerous vulnerability. His own supply lines were very long, and the fuel trucks from Tripoli used more gasoline to get to the front and back than they were able to carry. By driving so far and so fast, Rommel had called up **the quartermaster's nightmare**. On June 28, 1942, he wrote his wife to plan on a July vacation together in Italy. **"Get passports!"**

On the other side of the line, panic was building in Cairo. The British were burning documents, Allied personnel were being squeezed into cattle trains for a hasty evacuation, and Cairo merchants were hurriedly replacing photographs of Churchill and Roosevelt in their shop windows with those of Hitler and Mussolini. But the British did not give way in late June and July 1942, and Rommel was too short of gasoline to regain his momentum. The two exhausted armies had fought to a stalemate — the **First Battle of El Alamein**. And there in the desert they waited.

### *Montgomery*

In mid-August, Rommel gained a new and formidable adversary — **General Bernard Montgomery**, austere, ascetic, self-righteous, sometimes insubordinate, but invariably patient. A cousin of **H. St. John B. Philby**, the sorcerer's apprentice of Saudi oil, Montgomery had been the best man when Philby was married in India. Early on in life, Montgomery had learned to depend on his own resources, and not much else. After the death of his wife, he seemed to have been left with virtually no emotional attachments. "Everything I possessed had been destroyed by enemy bombing in Portsmouth in January 1941," he later wrote. **"I was now going to be given the opportunity to get my own back on the Germans."** In his first address to officers of the Eighth Army at Ruweisat Ridge near El Alamein, he felt the need to say: "I assure you I am quite sane. I understand there are people who often think I am slightly mad; so often that I now regard it as rather a compliment."

Montgomery was also a methodical, pedagogic, and deeply analytical military strategist. He would sometimes spend hours a day by himself — in his own **"mental oases"** — thinking through problems, searching for key principles. He hung a drawing of Rommel in his desert trailer, to help him think how Rommel would think. He knew that in facing Rommel, he was taking on a modern legend. He had one clear aim: turn the tables on the master of mobile warfare and decisively defeat Rommel. For, said Montgomery, Rommel **"had never been beaten before though he had often had to 'nip back to get more petrol.'"** He was "the only Field-Marshal in this war who won all his battles."

Montgomery sought to work out a strategy using the Eighth Army, now equipped with Sherman tanks, as a unified whole, capitalizing on the fact that its own supply line was short and Rommel's very long — and highly vulnerable.

### *The Battle of Alam Haifa and El Alamein*

Rommel himself was of two minds — acutely conscious of fuel shortages but also wanting to get on with the drive to Cairo and beyond. He was convinced time was running short and that the spirit of the Afrika Korps would win the day. He gave the order to attack. This round, still in the environs of El Alamein, became known as the **Battle of Alam Haifa**.

Again and again, during that week-long battle, the Afrika Korps was hampered by its fuel shortage. On **August 31**: "Due to the heavy going, the Afrika Korps' petrol stocks were soon badly depleted and at 16:00 hours we called off the attack on Hill 132." On **September 1**, "the promised petrol had still not arrived in Africa." It never came. Most of the fuel due by ship had either been sunk or was still waiting to be loaded in Italy. A small railway that might have transported gasoline had been flooded. By **September 7, 1942**, the battle of Alam Haifa was over. Rommel's latest offensive had been stopped dead in its tracks, and **a legend of invincibility was toppling**.

In the weeks that followed, Rommel begged for more supplies, including fuel sufficient for two thousand miles per vehicle. On **September 23**, Rommel left North Africa to see Mussolini in Rome, then Hitler at his headquarters on the Russian front. Again he pleaded for supplies; instead, he received the baton of **Field Marshal**, personally bestowed upon him by his Fuhrer. Hitler made generous promises, which he would not keep.

On **October 23**, after weeks of careful preparation and resupply, Montgomery opened his counterattack — the **Second Battle of El Alamein** — with a powerful artillery barrage. The Germans were stunned. On the first day, General Georg Stumme, Rommel's replacement, fell out of his car under British aerial bombardment and died of a heart attack. Hitler telephoned Rommel, who was in the Austrian Alps on sick leave, and ordered him to return immediately. By the evening of October 25, he was back in Egypt — this time commanding the beginning of a long retreat.

German hopes for new supplies were pinned on aircraft and ships that were being methodically destroyed by the Royal Navy and the RAF. When Rommel learned that four ships carrying desperately needed petroleum had been sunk by the RAF at Tobruk, he lay awake all night, eyes wide open, unable to sleep. He knew what the sinkings meant: **"In attacking our petrol transport, the British were able to hit us in a part of our machine on whose proper functioning the whole of the rest depended."**

During the ensuing weeks, all Rommel could do was fall back. At times, he believed he could have turned around and delivered devastating blows, but **he simply did not have the fuel to dare it**. To Hitler he repeatedly described the fuel situation as "catastrophic." An even greater catastrophe loomed when Allied forces invaded Morocco and Algeria — in the path of his retreat. On **Christmas Eve, 1942**, Rommel joined his headquarters Christmas party. That day, he had shot a gazelle from his car, which he contributed to the dinner table. In turn, he received a present: a couple of pounds of captured coffee, presented in a **miniature oil barrel**. "Thus proper homage," he said, "was paid to our most serious problem even on that day."

Soon all that Rommel's forces had left was a toehold between the forces advancing from both east and west. The legend had fallen. In **March 1943**, Rommel, now regarded by Hitler as defeatist, was removed from command of the Afrika Korps. By May, the last German and Italian troops in North Africa had surrendered.

### *Rommel's Death and Epitaph*

Rommel was called to serve the Fuhrer again, first in Italy, and then in France, where he was badly wounded shortly after the Normandy invasion. Three days later, a group of army officers tried to assassinate Hitler but failed. Rommel was suspected of involvement in the conspiracy. In **October 1944**, two SS generals appeared at his home with an ultimatum: commit a suicide that could be disguised as a natural death, or his entire family would be in danger. Rommel, holding the Field Marshal's baton, drove off with the two SS men. A few hundred yards from the house, the car pulled over into the woods — the area had been sealed off by the Gestapo. Rommel was given a poison pill; he swallowed it and fell forward in the seat, dropping the Field Marshal's baton. A state funeral was organized, and Hitler sent his condolences. Rommel's **"heart,"** said the official funeral oration, **"belonged to the Fuhrer."**

In Rommel's papers, he left a hard-earned epitaph for the role of supply and of oil in the age of mobile warfare. **"The battle is fought and decided by the Quartermasters before the shooting begins,"** he wrote, looking back on El Alamein. He himself had derisively rejected such a thought a few years earlier. But he had learned a bitter lesson: **"The bravest men can do nothing without guns, the guns nothing without plenty of ammunition, and neither guns nor ammunition are of much use in mobile warfare unless there are vehicles with sufficient petrol to haul them around."** Two weeks after the Second Battle of El Alamein, retreating before Montgomery's forces, Rommel wrote to his wife: **"Shortage of petrol! It's enough to make one weep."**

### *Autarchy and Catastrophe*

By mid-1943, the Axis had been defeated both in Russia and in North Africa, and the dream of German armies converging at Baku or on the oil fields of the Middle East had been relegated to fantasy. Germany had to turn back to its own resources. Synthetic fuels would be at the heart of the frantic effort to sustain the machines of war — and in that effort, Hitler's Reich would display its technological ingenuity as well as its total moral bankruptcy.

The man in charge was **Albert Speer**, Hitler's personal architect, intensely ambitious and one of Hitler's favorites. He had caught Hitler's attention with his designs for grand panoramas of flags, hundred-foot-high eagles, and spotlights for the 1933 Nazi party rally in Nuremberg. In **1942**, the Fuhrer appointed Speer Minister of Armaments and War Production. In early 1943, as the magnitude of the failures in Russia and North Africa became clear, Speer was given sweeping powers over the entire German economy. The architect proved remarkably adept at industrial mobilization. Over two and a half years, Speer drove a more than **threefold increase** in the production of aircraft, weapons, and ammunition, and a nearly **sixfold increase in tanks** — even while the Allies carried out an extensive strategic bombing campaign against German targets. German industrial production registered its highest level of the entire war in **June 1944**. **"Oil, which was Germany's weakest point,"** wrote the British military historian **Basil Liddell Hart**, **"was scarcely touched."**

The synthetic fuels industry was headed on the same upward trend. Between 1940 and 1943, synthetic fuel production almost doubled, from 72,000 to **124,000 barrels per day**. In the first quarter of 1944, synthetic fuels provided **57 percent of total supply** — and **92 percent of aviation gasoline**. Altogether, during the Second World War, synthetic fuels would account for half of Germany's total oil production.

### *Slave Labor at Auschwitz*

It could not have happened without immense effort and all the normal tools and techniques of the Nazi war economy, including **slave labor**. The concentration camps were the mechanisms for achieving the **"Final Solution,"** decided upon at the **Wannsee Conference in January 1942**. Until the "Final Solution" could be completed, those Jews who were fit — along with Slavs and other prisoners — were to be put to work to further the objectives of the Reich. A continuing supply of concentration camp prisoners was drafted into I.G. Farben's hydrogenation plants, as well as into its synthetic rubber plants. The company was building synthetic fuel and rubber plants **adjacent to the Auschwitz concentration camp** in Poland. Auschwitz was the largest of the Nazi mass murder factories; upwards of **two million people**, mostly Jews, were put to death there with gas manufactured by an I.G. Farben subsidiary. The I.G. Farben officials described the Auschwitz site, with its ample supplies of coal and labor, as **"very favorably located."** The synthetic fuels plant was under the directorship of the same chemist who had met with Hitler in Munich in June 1932.

I.G. Farben paid a per diem for each slave laborer — **three or four marks for an adult**, depending upon skills, and half price for children. The money went into the coffers of the SS. The slave laborers subsisted on a thousand calories a day and slept on wooden racks. They would work for a few months, then die from the horrible conditions or be killed in the death camp, and be replaced by others from newly arrived trains packed like cattle cars.

One of those was **Prisoner Number 174,517**, a young Italian named **Primo Levi**, who managed to survive only because he could recall enough organic chemistry to be put to work in a lab. "This huge entanglement of iron, concrete, mud and smoke is the negation of beauty," he said of I.G.'s industrial complex. **"Within its bounds not a blade of grass grows, and the soil is impregnated with the poisonous saps of coal and petroleum, and the only thing alive are machines and slaves — and the former are more alive than the latter."** Monowitz — the company's own private "branch" concentration camp — was a death factory. The records indicate that **three hundred thousand prisoners** passed through I.G. Farben's portals at Auschwitz. The plants were so large they used **more electricity than the entire city of Berlin**.

By 1944, according to one estimate, **a third of the total work force** in the German synthetic fuels industry throughout the Reich was slave labor.

### *"The Primary Strategic Aim"*

Following the haphazard Allied strategic bombing campaign against Germany, General **Carl Spaatz**, commander of the United States Strategic Air Force in Europe, decided a change was needed. On **March 5, 1944**, he proposed to General **Dwight Eisenhower** that a new priority target be set — **the German synthetic fuels industry**. Its output, he promised, could be cut by half within six months. The British opposed Spaatz's plan, insisting on targeting the French railway system. But Spaatz received a tacit go-ahead from Eisenhower.

On **May 12, 1944**, a combat wing involving **935 bombers** plus fighter escorts bombed a number of synthetic fuels factories, including the giant **I.G. Farben plant at Leuna**. As soon as Speer realized what had happened, he rushed by plane to Leuna to see the damage for himself. **"I shall never forget the date May 12,"** he later wrote. **"On that day the technological war was decided."** The results of the attack, and the broken, twisted pipe systems, made real **"what had been a nightmare to us for more than two years."** A week after the attack, Speer flew to report personally to Hitler: **"The enemy has struck us at one of our weakest points. If they persist at it this time, we will soon no longer have any fuel production worth mentioning."** He added: **"Our one hope is that the other side has an Air Force General Staff as scatterbrained as ours!"**

Yet this initial attack was not so troublesome as it first appeared. The Germans had seized Italy's oil stocks, providing a cushion. And feverish repair activity returned damaged plants to production within weeks. But on **May 28-29**, the Allies hit the oil facilities again. Other Allied bombers attacked **Ploesti** in Rumania. On **June 6**, D-Day, the Allies invaded Normandy. On **June 8**, General Spaatz gave the formal directive: **"the 'primary strategic aim' of the United States Strategic Air Forces is now to deny oil to enemy armed forces."** Regular bombing attacks on the synthetic fuels industry followed.

Speer ordered synthetic fuels plants be rebuilt quickly, or dispersed into smaller, better-protected, hidden sites — some in quarries, some underground. Even **breweries were converted to making fuel**. Upward of **350,000 workers** — many of them slave laborers — were engaged in this frantic undertaking. But as time went on, the plants became more fragile and vulnerable to further air attacks, and more difficult to get back into operation. Before the attacks began in May 1944, synthetic fuel production by hydrogenation was averaging **92,000 barrels per day**; by September, output had fallen to **5,000 barrels per day**. Aviation gasoline production that month was just **3,000 barrels per day** — only **6 percent** of the average production in the first four months of 1944. Meanwhile, the Russians had captured the **Ploesti oil fields**, depriving Hitler of his major source of crude oil.

The output of German planes was still at peak level — but they sat on the ground without fuel. **Jet fighters**, a new German innovation that would have given the Luftwaffe a significant advantage, were being introduced into operational squadrons in autumn 1944. But **there was no fuel to train the pilots**, or even to get the planes into the air. The Luftwaffe was operating on just **one-tenth of the minimum** required gasoline. In-air training for new pilots was cut to **only an hour a week**. **"This was actually the fatal blow for the Luftwaffe!"** General **Adolph Galland**, commander of German fighter forces, said after the war. **"From September on, the shortage of fuel was unbearable. Air operations were thereby made virtually impossible."**

In the autumn of 1944, bad weather temporarily curtailed the Allied attacks, and in November, the Germans managed to increase synthetic fuel output. But production fell again in December. **"We must realize that the men on the enemy side who are directing the economic air raids know something about German economic life,"** Speer told an armaments conference. **"Fortunately for us the enemy began following this strategy only in the last half or three-quarters of a year. ... Before that he was, at least from his standpoint, committing absurdities."**

### *The Battle of the Bulge: Europe's Biggest Gas Station*

By the fall of 1944, the D-Day invasion had widened to drive the Germans out of France. Soviet forces were pushing in from the east. But to Hitler, the war could not be coming to an end. On **December 16**, he launched a huge counteroffensive in the hilly, wooded **Ardennes forest** in eastern Belgium and Luxembourg — the **Battle of the Bulge**, Germany's last great concentrated attack, the final *blitzkrieg*. The plan was Hitler's own, and everything was thrown into it, including every bit of fuel that could be scrounged from other units. The objective was to throw back the Allies, isolate their armies, and buy time for the development of new, more devastating weapons.

The Germans had the advantage of surprise, but they had undertaken the assault with vastly insufficient resources. The reserves of manpower that might have been decisive **could not reach the front lines**. "They could not be moved," a German commander later said. **"They were at a standstill for lack of petrol — stranded over a stretch of a hundred miles — just when they were needed."**

The German fuel plan depended on capturing Allied fuel dumps. Near **Stavelot** in eastern Belgium was the Allies' largest fuel dump — the biggest filling station in Europe. There the Allies had stored **2.5 million gallons of fuel** for their troops, along with two million road maps of Europe. The roads were lined with hundreds of thousands of five-gallon jerry cans.

On **December 17**, the second day, a panzer unit led by the butcherous colonel **Jochem Peiper** overran a small fuel dump nearby. Peiper forced fifty captured American soldiers to fill his vehicles and then coldly ordered them killed. A large number of American prisoners were also gunned down in the **Malmedy Massacre**. By that evening, Peiper's forces were within a thousand feet of the forward edge of the **Stavelot dump** — fifty times larger than the one he had captured. The Allied defenses were light and disorganized. Peiper's forces moved into Stavelot. In a desperate effort to improvise, a small group of Allied defenders poured the contents of jerry cans into a round ditch and set it ablaze, creating **a wall of fire**. Peiper examined his maps carefully, but they were out of date and failed to show the correct location or magnitude of the dump. **He did not know about the bounty that lay at hand.** Instead of sending his forces through the thin wall of fire, he ordered them to go back across the bridge and head west. Ironically, Peiper's unit soon ran out of fuel; his tanks got only half a mile to the gallon. Resupply efforts by the Luftwaffe failed, and the unit was captured.

Peiper's U-turn was one of those small battle incidents with momentous consequences. **The Stavelot fuel supply was equivalent to the requirements of the first ten days of Germany's entire Ardennes offensive**; its capture would have given the Germans the fuel to push on to Antwerp and the English Channel. Even so, it was not until **Christmas Day 1944**, ten days after the Germans began, that they were finally stopped and pushed back.

### *"Twilight of the Gods"*

With the failure of the Ardennes offensive, Germany's war effort was over from a strategic point of view. In **February 1945**, German production of aviation gasoline amounted to just **a thousand tons** — one-half of one percent of the level of the first four months of 1944. None was produced thereafter. But the delusions of victory lived on. Those around Hitler, Speer would recall, "would listen to him in silence when, in the long since hopeless situation, he continued to commit nonexistent divisions or to order units supplied by planes that could no longer fly for lack of fuel."

Still the months of bloody fighting went on. Hitler and his immediate entourage retreated ever more into fantasy, with the Fuhrer calling for a scorched earth policy and issuing "the last crazy orders." Even as the end approached, he remained in the grip of his insane, violent visions, for which at least **35 million people** paid with their lives. He listened to Wagner's ***Gotterdammerung*** — "Twilight of the Gods" — on the gramophone, and avidly read horoscopes that promised a sudden improvement. Only when Russian soldiers were almost directly above his underground bunker, on the doorstep of the now-ruined Chancellery that Speer had designed for him, did Hitler commit suicide. **He left orders that his body be doused in gasoline and burned** so that it would not fall into the hands of the hated Slavs. There was enough gasoline at hand to carry out that final order.

On a night journey to the struggling remnants of Germany's Tenth Army in Italy, Albert Speer had seen a clear vision of why the Reich that was to last for a thousand years had, in fact, only weeks to go. He had encountered **150 German Army trucks**. To each were hitched **four oxen**, which were dragging the trucks forward. **It was the only way the vehicles could move. They had no fuel.**

**German Oil Supply, 1938-1945 (barrels per day):**
| Year | Synthetic | Other | Total |
|------|-----------|-------|-------|
| 1939 | 47,574 | 121,973 | 169,547 |
| 1941 | 89,007 | 119,614 | 208,621 |
| 1943 | 124,299 | 112,865 | 237,164 |
| 1944 | 330,499 | 244,344 | 574,843 |
| 1945 (Q1) | 5,437 | 17,726 | 23,163 |

