# The Prize — Part 2 Notes

## Chapter 20: The New Center of Gravity

### DeGolyer's Mission to the Middle East

- Everette DeGolyer was one of the most respected figures in the oil industry — a geologist who had discovered Mexico's great Golden Lane field as a young man. He put together the independent company Amerada on behalf of the Cowdray interests, then in the late 1930s established DeGolyer and McNaughton, the world's leading petroleum engineering consulting firm — an innovation that met the new need for independent appraisal of reserves for bank financing.
- DeGolyer was already a millionaire several times over by his mid-forties, earning $2 million a year. His interests ranged far beyond oil — he was a founder of what became Texas Instruments, a considerable historian of chili, built an extraordinary book collection, and bailed out the Saturday Review of Literature when it was about to go bust.
- As a self-made man, DeGolyer had little use for the New Deal. But when WWII broke out, he was called to Washington as a chief deputy to Harold Ickes in the Petroleum Administration for War. In 1943, he was given a special foreign mission: appraise the oil potential of Saudi Arabia and the Persian Gulf countries — the center of a contentious debate.
- In a 1940 speech, DeGolyer had prophesied: "No such galaxy of fields of the first magnitude over such a wide area has been developed previously in the history of the oil industry... I will be rash enough to prophesy that the area we have been considering will be the most important oil producing region in the world within the next score of years."
- Getting to the Middle East was arduous in wartime — military planes via Miami, Caribbean, Brazil, Africa, then the Persian Gulf. DeGolyer toured oil fields in Iraq, Iran, Kuwait, Bahrain, and Saudi Arabia. He wrote his wife: "We haven't seen anything but a pretty barren land on this whole trip... In fact Texas is a garden in comparison."
- DeGolyer mastered the art of eating sheep's eyes when ceremoniously offered. But it was the geology that captured his imagination — three structures already tapped in Saudi Arabia with reserves estimated at 750 million barrels, but similar structures suggested reserves would be far larger. For DeGolyer, the Arabian Peninsula was "an El Dorado, the stuff of legend." He had discovered a well flowing 110,000 barrels per day and had never seen anything on so vast a scale in half a century in the business.
- Upon returning to Washington in early 1944, DeGolyer reported proven and probable reserves of Iran, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, and Qatar at about 25 billion barrels. Saudi Arabia accounted for about 20% — perhaps 5 billion barrels. He was conservative, applying the same "proven" and "probable" standards he'd use for bank appraisals. He suspected reserves would be much larger — estimates sounding like lunacy, up to 300 billion barrels for the region and 100 billion for Saudi Arabia alone.
- One mission member told State Department officials: "The oil in this region is the greatest single prize in all history."
- DeGolyer's key judgment: "The center of gravity of world oil production is shifting from the Gulf-Caribbean area to the Middle East — to the Persian Gulf area, and is likely to continue to shift until it is firmly established in that area." This constituted a eulogy for America's receding place in world oil. The US had produced almost 90% of oil used by the Allies in WWII — the high-water mark. Its remaining days as an exporter would soon disappear.

### "The Allies Have the Money"

- In 1940, the Middle East (Iran, Iraq, entire Arabian Peninsula) produced less than 5% of world oil, compared to 63% for the United States. But James Terry Duce, a vice-president of Casoc (California-Arabian Standard Oil Company), wrote to DeGolyer in 1941 about "fields such as we have in that area are a totally different experience to anything in the United States — even East Texas."
- While the Axis powers were on the offensive in Russia and North Africa, the dwindling Americans in Saudi Arabia ("the hundred men") planned how to protect the wells by filling them with cement, and how to destroy them to deny them to advancing German armies. Wells in Kuwait and Iran were also plugged in coordination with British and American military authorities.
- By 1941, Ibn Saud faced a stark financial crisis — war interrupted pilgrim flow to Mecca, drought caused crop failure, traditional industries (sword and knife making, leather working) couldn't make up the losses. As he explained in 1942: "The Arabs have the religion, but the Allies have the money."
- Ibn Saud appealed to the British, to Casoc, and to its parents Standard of California and Texaco. The companies didn't want more loans but didn't want to risk losing the concession. Lend Lease was suggested, but Saudi Arabia was a kingdom, not a democracy — Ibn Saud was no constitutional monarch. Roosevelt initially decided against American assistance: "Will you tell the British... I hope they can take care of the King of Saudi Arabia. This is a little far afield for us" (July 1941).
- The British provided about $2 million in newly minted coins, and British subsidies continued. American oil men worked to convince Ibn Saud that this British aid was really American — since Britain was a Lend Lease recipient, the aid "actually came from the United States. It just came indirectly."

### "We're Running Out of Oil!"

- America's entry into the war brought a wholesale redefinition of the Middle East's importance. Oil was the critical strategic commodity — shaping the Axis military strategy, and the resource that could defeat them. The US almost single-handedly fueled the entire Allied war effort.
- From the mid-1930s onward, the discovery rate of new US oil fields fell sharply. The director of reserves for the Petroleum Administration for War warned in 1943: "The law of diminishing returns is becoming operative... the bonanza days of oil discovery, for the most part, belong to history."
- Harold Ickes published "We're Running Out of Oil!" in December 1943, warning that if there were a WWIII, "it would have to be fought with someone else's petroleum, because the United States wouldn't have it... America's crown, symbolizing supremacy as the oil empire of the world, is sliding down over one eye."
- This pessimism gave rise to the "conservation theory" — that the US government had to control and develop foreign ("extraterritorial") oil reserves to reduce the drain on domestic supplies. Even Republican Senator Henry Cabot Lodge declared "history does not give us confidence that private interest alone would adequately safeguard the national interest."
- Herbert Feis, the State Department's Economic Adviser: "In all surveys of the situation, the pencil came to an awed pause at one point and place — the Middle East."

### Anglo-American Suspicions and Rivalry

- American policymakers arrived at the same conclusion that had directed British oil policy since WWI — the centrality of the Middle East. But the two Allies viewed each other with considerable suspicion. The British feared Americans would eject them from the Middle East; the Americans feared the British would "diddle" them out of the Saudi concession.
- Navy Undersecretary William Bullitt warned that London would "diddle" the American companies "out of the concession and the British into it." When the British sent a locust-control mission to Saudi Arabia, Casoc was certain it was a cover for secret oil geology exploration.
- In truth, the Americans woefully exaggerated British designs on Saudi Arabia — Britain was hardly in a position to dislodge the Americans, on whom they depended heavily. Three alternatives emerged: acquire direct ownership (like Anglo-Persian), negotiate a settlement with the British, or leave the matter in private hands.

### The Policy of "Solidification"

- Socal and Texaco feared the British would gain a dominant position over Ibn Saud's finances. Saudi Arabia was only two decades old as a unified country — would the kingdom and the concession survive the King himself? Mexico's recent nationalization of foreign oil companies was a cautionary tale.
- Direct US government involvement became the policy of "solidification." In February 1943, the presidents of Socal, Texaco, and Casoc went to Washington seeking government aid to keep the British at bay.
- On February 16, 1943, Ickes lobbied Roosevelt over lunch: Saudi Arabia was "probably the greatest and richest oil field in the world," the British were "trying to edge their way into it." On February 18, Roosevelt reversed his earlier position and authorized Lend Lease assistance to King Ibn Saud.
- The Army Navy Petroleum Board projected a serious oil shortage for 1944, threatening military operations — pushing the US government further toward Saudi Arabia.

### The Petroleum Reserves Corporation

- Ickes created the Petroleum Reserves Corporation, backed by the Army and Navy, aiming to acquire actual ownership of foreign oil reserves. Secretary of State Hull objected, fearing "intense new disputes" — "In many conferences after the last war the atmosphere and smell of oil was almost stifling."
- In June 1943, Ickes met at the White House with War Secretary Stimson, Navy Secretary Knox, and James Byrnes (Director of the Office of War Mobilization). They agreed on the need to acquire "an interest in the highly important Saudi Arabia fields." Roosevelt confirmed the decision — the government's "interest" should be 100%.
- In August 1943, the presidents of Texaco (W.S.S. Rodgers) and Socal (Harry C. Collier) were summoned to Ickes's office. They expected to discuss aid for an option on Saudi oil. Instead, Ickes proposed the government buy the whole of Casoc. The oilmen "literally took their breath away." As one participant noted: "They had gone fishing for a cod and had caught a whale."
- Ickes eventually whittled his proposal to a 51% share, modeled on Anglo-Iranian. He even suggested naming it the "American-Arabian Oil Company."
- Then a deal was struck: the US government would acquire one-third of Casoc for $40 million to finance a new refinery at Ras Tanura, with the right to buy 51% of production in peacetime and 100% in wartime.

### Industry Opposition Kills Government Ownership

- The rest of the American oil industry rose up in "righteous and fiery indignation." Other companies feared government competition — it might champion foreign over domestic oil, be the first step toward federal control or nationalization. Opposition came from independents, Standard of New Jersey, and Socony-Vacuum (Mobil), which themselves wanted into Saudi oil.
- Ickes abruptly retreated in late 1943, repudiating the plan and blaming Texaco and Socal for being "too greedy and recalcitrant." That was the end of the US government's move into direct ownership of foreign oil.

### The Government Pipeline Plan

- In early 1944, Ickes championed a new plan: through the Petroleum Reserves Corporation, the US government would spend up to $120 million to build a pipeline carrying Saudi and Kuwaiti oil across the desert to the Mediterranean. In exchange, companies would establish a one-billion-barrel reserve for the American military at a 25% discount.
- Massive opposition mobilized. Congressmen called for abolishing the Petroleum Reserves Corporation. Independent oil men called it "a threat to our national security" and "a move towards fascism." Liberals opposed it for helping big business; isolationists for digging into Middle East sand. After D-Day, the Joint Chiefs withdrew their endorsement. The pipeline project withered and disappeared.

### "A Wrangle About Oil" — The Anglo-American Petroleum Agreement

- A partnership with Britain to manage world oil was the remaining avenue. Fears of a postwar glut of cheap Persian Gulf oil — as destabilizing as East Texas in the 1930s — drove both sides. The British feared a competitive production race that would create a glut, depress prices, deprive producing governments of royalty income, and threaten concession stability.
- The British wanted American help defending the area against "Russian pressure." The British Chiefs added: "American continental resources constitute our most secure supply in war and therefore it is in our interest to take any steps that may assist in their conservation."
- In April 1943, Basil Jackson of Anglo-Persian warned James Terry Duce: "It is the first time in history that there have been such enormous quantities of oil overhanging the markets of the world." Without agreement, there would be "a fierce competitive battle."
- Lord Beaverbrook told Churchill: "Oil is the single greatest post-war asset remaining to us. We should refuse to divide our last asset with the Americans."
- Roosevelt showed British Ambassador Lord Halifax a hand-drawn map of the Middle East: "Persian oil is yours. We share the oil of Iraq and Kuwait. As for Saudi Arabian oil, it's ours."
- Churchill fired back at Roosevelt: "A wrangle about oil would be a poor prelude for the tremendous joint enterprise and sacrifice to which we have bound ourselves." Roosevelt replied about Britain "eyeing" and trying to "horn in" on Saudi Arabia. Churchill's acid response: Britain "will not be deprived of anything which rightly belongs to her."
- The Anglo-American Petroleum Agreement was signed August 8, 1944, creating an eight-member International Petroleum Commission to estimate global demand and allocate production quotas — fundamentally a link to the market management of Achnacarry and the "As-Is" system.
- Independent American oil men bitterly opposed it, fearing international regulation of domestic production and cheap Middle Eastern oil flooding into the US. The majors feared antitrust liability. The agreement was submitted to the Senate as a treaty but was heading for "an inglorious defeat." In January 1945, the Roosevelt Administration withdrew it. Efforts to revise it were shelved as Roosevelt headed to Yalta.

### The "Twins" — Roosevelt Meets Ibn Saud

- After Yalta in February 1945, Roosevelt's plane (the Sacred Cow) flew to the Suez Canal Zone. He boarded the USS Quincy in the Great Bitter Lake. The USS Murphy brought Ibn Saud — perhaps only his second trip outside his kingdom in 45 years.
- Ibn Saud traveled with a party of 48 (originally to include 100 live sheep, reduced to 7). He spurned the commodore's cabin and slept in an improvised tent on the forecastle, furnished with Oriental carpets and his own chairs.
- Roosevelt, the chain-smoker, did not light up out of deference to the King's religious precepts. On the way to lunch, Roosevelt was taken in his wheelchair into a separate elevator — the President pushed the red emergency button to smoke two cigarettes before meeting the King again.
- The two men spent more than five intense hours together. Roosevelt's interests: a Jewish homeland in Palestine, oil, the postwar Middle East. Ibn Saud wanted continuing American interest to counterbalance British influence. On Palestine, the anti-Zionist Ibn Saud suggested displaced Jews be given a national homeland in Germany.
- Roosevelt and Ibn Saud bonded personally — the King declared himself the President's "twin" due to their close ages, national responsibilities, farming interests, and physical infirmities (Roosevelt's polio wheelchair vs. Ibn Saud's war-wounded legs). "You are luckier than I because you can still walk on your legs and I have to be wheeled wherever I go," said Roosevelt. "No, my friend, you are more fortunate," replied the King. "Your chair will take you wherever you want to go and you know you will get there. My legs are less reliable and are getting weaker every day."
- Roosevelt gave Ibn Saud one of his two wheelchairs. It was kept in the King's private apartment in Riyadh as a most valued memento, though too small for a man of the King's large stature.
- NYT correspondent C.L. Sulzberger wrote: "The immense oil deposits in Saudi Arabia alone make that country more important to American diplomacy than almost any other smaller nation." Churchill was not pleased — he "burned up the wires to all his diplomats in the area, breathing out threatening and slaughter unless appointments with him were made with the same potentates." Three days after Roosevelt, Churchill drove into the Egyptian desert to meet Ibn Saud at an oasis hotel.
- Churchill's meeting with Ibn Saud included a clash of customs: Churchill was told the King "could not allow smoking or drinking alcohol in his presence." Churchill would not be as accommodating as Roosevelt: "I was the host and I said if it was his religion that made him say such things, my religion prescribed as an absolute sacred rite smoking cigars and drinking alcohol before, after, and if need be during, all meals and the intervals between them."
- Churchill's high-handedness did little to reassure Ibn Saud about British intentions. A gift exchange went badly — Churchill gave Ibn Saud perfumes worth about 100 pounds, but the King presented Churchill and Anthony Eden with diamond-hilted jeweled swords, robes, and about 3,000 pounds' worth of diamonds and pearls "for your womanfolk." Embarrassed, Churchill promised "the finest motor car in the world" — a Rolls-Royce costing the British Treasury upwards of 6,000 pounds. The jewels were eventually sold secretly so as not to offend Ibn Saud.

### "What Do We Do Now?"

- On Roosevelt's return, his advisers were still battling over the Petroleum Agreement and antitrust issues. Roosevelt planned to meet with Ickes and Secretary of State Stettinius after resting at Warm Springs. "I shall be delighted to have the meeting that Harold proposes just as soon as I get back from Warm Springs," he told Stettinius on March 27, 1945. "Will you remind me of it?"
- Stettinius did not have the opportunity. Roosevelt died at Warm Springs on April 12, 1945.
- Under Truman, Ickes renegotiated the Petroleum Agreement in London in September 1945, but its teeth were extracted — the International Petroleum Commission was effectively precluded from touching domestic American production (which was two-thirds of world production). The British Minister of Fuel and Power told the Chancellor: "On balance, it is better that we should accept the Agreement rather than reject it."
- Meanwhile, the gloom about oil reserves was receding. J. Edgar Pew, vice-president of Sun Oil, lambasted the prospect of shortage as "a psychological rather than a geological condition." He assured Senators that domestic production would meet American needs for two decades: "Of that I am as sure as I am that the sun shall rise and set tomorrow. I am an optimist."
- With WWII victory, the crushing demand on American oil reserves eased, removing the impetus for the British agreement. In February 1946, Ickes got into a bitter scrap with Truman over the appointment of Edwin Pauley, a California oil man, as Undersecretary of the Navy. Ickes submitted a resignation letter of more than six pages, single-spaced. "It was the kind of letter sent by a man who is sure that he can have his way if he threatens to quit," Truman later said.
- But Truman was not Roosevelt — he accepted Ickes's resignation "tersely and with alacrity and delight." Ickes requested six weeks to wind up; Truman gave him two days. The Oil Czar of the New Deal and WWII left office, denouncing Truman for "lack of adherence to the strict truth" — "neither an absolute monarch nor a descendant of a putative Sun Goddess." He became a newspaper columnist.

### Forrestal Champions Middle East Oil

- Navy Secretary James Forrestal, a driving, ambitious former Dillon Read investment banker, was one of the first senior policymakers to conclude the US must organize for a protracted confrontation with the Soviet Union. Oil held a central place in his security strategy: "The Navy cannot err on the side of optimism in its estimates for what supplies might be available."
- Forrestal declared: "The prestige and hence the influence of the United States is in part related to the wealth of the Government and its nationals in terms of oil resources, foreign as well as domestic. The active expansion of such holdings is very much to be desired." The State Department should work to "substitute Middle Eastern oil for American oil" and "promote the expansion of United States oil holdings abroad."
- At Potsdam, Forrestal lectured the new Secretary of State, James Byrnes, on Saudi Arabia as "a matter of first importance." He was influenced by DeGolyer's assessment: "If we ever got into another World War it is quite possible that we would not have access to reserves held in the Middle East but in the meantime the use of those reserves would prevent the depletion of our own, a depletion which may be serious within the next fifteen years."
- But Forrestal was a minority. State Department official Claire Wilcox wrote a memo, "Oil: What Do We Do Now?" declaring the Agreement "either dangerous or useless. If employed as a cover to set up a cartel to allot quotas and fix minimum prices, it is dangerous. If not so employed, it is useless." Even local schoolteachers in Texas were mobilized against it. In 1947, the Truman Administration gave up. The Anglo-American Petroleum Agreement was dead.
- The process of "solidification" would proceed through private companies, not government action. As an Anglo-Iranian executive put it, the oil companies were working out their own "salvation" in the Middle East.

## Chapter 21: The Postwar Petroleum Order

### The Postwar Oil Boom

- Gasoline rationing was lifted in August 1945, within 24 hours of Japan's capitulation. The voice of the motorist, silenced for years, rose in a "single, deafening crescendo — 'Fill 'er up!'" Drivers tossed away rationing books and took to the streets and highways. America was in love with the automobile again.
- In 1945, 26 million cars were in service; by 1950, 40 million. Gasoline sales were 42% higher in 1950 than in 1945. By 1950, oil was meeting more of America's total energy needs than coal.
- The pessimistic predictions about postwar supplies were eviscerated. Price, after controls were lifted, proved a powerful stimulus to exploration. In 1947, Imperial (a Jersey affiliate) drilled a successful discovery well near Edmonton, Alberta, igniting the first frenetic oil boom of the postwar years. Despite growing demand, proven US reserves were 21% higher in 1950 than in 1946. The United States was not running out of oil in the ground.
- But there was a shortage of available oil in 1947-48. Crude prices more than doubled from 1945 levels. Politicians declared an energy crisis; more than twenty Congressional investigations were launched. Consumption rose with "unexpected rapidity — astonishingly," said Shell. Refineries needed redesign for civilian products (gasoline, home heating oil) rather than 100-octane aviation fuel. Steel was in short supply worldwide, slowing refinery and tanker construction. The tanker shortage worsened in early 1948 after ships broke in half at sea, and the Coast Guard ordered 288 tankers laid up for emergency reinforcing.
- Oil companies became advocates of conservation — Standard of Indiana urged motorists to avoid "jackrabbit" starts and keep tires inflated. Sun promoted "Helpful Hints" for conserving oil on newscaster Lowell Thomas's broadcasts.
- Up through 1947, American exports exceeded imports. In 1948, imports of crude oil and products exceeded exports for the first time. The US was now dependent on other countries for the marginal barrel, and "foreign oil" entered the American vocabulary.

### The Great Oil Deals: Aramco and the "Arabian Risk"

- In the developing Cold War, oil was central to American, British, and Western European security. The Middle East was the focus where foreign policy, economics, national security, and corporate interests converged.
- Aramco (the Arabian-American Oil Company, renamed from Casoc in 1944) was the joint venture of Socal and Texaco in Saudi Arabia. It was troubled — an embarrassment of riches. The enormous scale of the Saudi fields required massive capital and, above all, markets. Texaco was a famous American company (Spindletop origins, Metropolitan Opera sponsor, "the man who wears the star" ads); Socal was a regional company that had spent millions searching for oil worldwide since WWI with little to show except minor East Indies/Bahrain production and Saudi Arabia's massive potential.
- By 1946, Standard of California's investment in Aramco totaled $80 million, with tens of millions more needed. The Trans-Arabian Pipeline (Tapline) from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean would cost $100 million. Building a European refining and marketing system would be prohibitively expensive against established competitors. Political conditions were unstable — large communist parties in Italy and France, occupied Germany's uncertain future, Britain's Labour government nationalizing the "commanding heights."
- Saudi Arabia was only two decades old. Ibn Saud was now in his mid-sixties, blind in one eye, failing in health. He had sired upwards of 45 sons, 37 thought to be living — would they bring stability or conflict? The concession would always be in jeopardy if Aramco couldn't satisfy the Saudi government's rising expectations. The answer: spread the risk. Bring in other oil companies with capital, expertise, and especially markets. Ibn Saud insisted Aramco remain 100% American — only Standard Oil of New Jersey and Socony-Vacuum qualified.
- State Department and Navy officials had encouraged broader participation. Navy Secretary Forrestal said in 1945 he "did not care which American company or companies developed the Arabian reserves" as long as they were "American." Socal opened talks with Standard Oil of New Jersey in spring 1946.

### Internal Rebellion at Socal

- Jersey was very receptive — facing oil shortage, Europe its most vulnerable market, and getting only 9,300 barrels/day from its IPC share of Iraqi production. Socal and Texaco thrusting into European markets with cheap Arabian oil was a feared threat.
- But Socal's own people rebelled. The production department in San Francisco — "the men on the ground" who had made the barren desert bloom — didn't want to lose control to larger partners. For 13 years, there had been no return to stockholders; only now in 1946 was the concession becoming profitable. James MacPherson, a Socal engineer in charge of Saudi field operations, called the concession "a gold mine" and was intent on building Aramco into "the greatest oil company in the world." He scathingly said Aramco was about to turn itself into "an annex to Jersey's production department."
- Harry Collier, Socal's chairman (one of the "Terrible Tycoons"), was the boss. He believed Aramco would sell far more oil through Jersey's system, ending up with "much more gold." The deal would let Socal recoup all its direct investment. Collier overruled the opposition. Argument ended.

### Erasing the Red Line

- Jersey and Socony faced a massive obstacle: the Red Line Agreement from their IPC membership. Saudi Arabia was inside the red line Gulbenkian had drawn in 1928. The "self-denying" clause 10 of the IPC agreement effectively prohibited Jersey and Socony from going into Aramco unless they brought Shell, Anglo-Iranian, CFP, and Gulbenkian along.
- Jersey and Socony had wanted out of the Red Line Agreement — they were "straitjacketed in the most prolific oil basin in the world for a mere 11.875 percent each of an enterprise they did not control." The US government had helped them get into the deal in the 1920s, but Washington would not help them get out.
- The "bombshell" solution: the doctrine of "supervening illegality." During WWII, the British government had seized IPC shares held by CFP and Gulbenkian (who had gone to Vichy France) as "enemy aliens." Under this doctrine, the entire IPC agreement was "frustrated" — null and void.
- At war's end, shares reverted to CFP and Gulbenkian. But in late 1946, Jersey and Socony invoked "supervening illegality" with enthusiasm, declaring the whole IPC agreement no longer in effect. They went to London to tell the European members: the old agreement was dissolved, Red Line and all.
- Anglo-Persian and Shell indicated they could work things out on the basis of "mutual interest." The French were furious — they rejected the American contention completely. The IPC was their sole key to Middle Eastern oil, and they would not relinquish it. De Gaulle had reportedly "exploded in rage" when he discovered what small volumes CFP actually produced.
- Gulbenkian, now in residence in Lisbon, defiantly replied: "We do not acquiesce." The IPC had been his life's work, "his great personal monument." He would fight through lawyers and agents to resist efforts to overturn the Red Line Agreement. The new generation of American negotiators dismissed him: "We have no reason to buy Gulbenkian's signature," Harold Sheets of Socony said optimistically.

### Antitrust Worries and the State Department's Alternative

- The danger of litigation over the Red Line was not Jersey and Socony's only worry — would the quadripartite Aramco violate American antitrust laws? Three of the four companies had been spun out of the original Rockefeller Trust. Lawyers concluded the combination would not violate antitrust or the 1911 dissolution decree. Socony's chief counsel worried that seven companies holding "such overwhelming control of crude reserves in the Eastern Hemisphere as well as in the Western Hemisphere" couldn't go on "for any great length of time without some sort of regulation."
- The State Department, under Paul Nitze (head of Office of International Trade Policy), proposed an alternative: have Jersey sell its IPC shares to Socony, then go it alone into Aramco, creating two distinct groups with no overlapping membership. Jersey and Socony rejected this as "not a practicable plan." Undersecretary Dean Acheson scotched Nitze's idea.
- By December 1946, the four companies agreed in general principle to expand Aramco. In January 1947, the French launched a public counterattack — protests at the State Department, commercial pressure on Jersey in France, and CFP's solicitors brought suit in London charging breach of contract.
- Ibn Saud had to be consulted — told the "marriage" of four companies was "a natural" meaning more royalties. He was interested in only one point: that neither Jersey nor Socony were "British-controlled." Reassured of their purely American character, the King approved.
- The final arrangement had to account for the contingency that the French might win in court and demand Aramco participation, which Ibn Saud had made clear he would not tolerate.

### The Aramco Deal Closes

- Jersey and Socony guaranteed a loan of $102 million, convertible to equity once legally safe. They could start taking oil immediately. Jersey and Socony also became partners in Tapline. Socal and Texaco received overriding payments on every barrel for a number of years — altogether about $470 million over several years for selling 40% of Aramco, getting all their original investment back and a good deal more. As Gwin Follis of Socal observed, the sale "took the enormous investment required for Tapline off our shoulders."
- Initially Jersey and Socony planned a 50-50 split of the 40%. But Socony's president, fretful that Middle Eastern oil "was not absolutely safe" and worried about markets, argued the company "ought to put more money in Venezuela." Socony took only 10%, Jersey 30%. "It would not be very long before Socony came to regret its parsimony."
- The US Attorney General gave reassurance: "Off-hand, no legal objections to the deal. It should be a good thing for the country." But political troubles in the eastern Mediterranean threatened — communist insurrection in Greece, Soviet threat to Turkey. On March 11, 1947, Socony's directors discussed "the problems affecting the Middle East." Optimism prevailed, and the next day, March 12, 1947, officials of the four companies signed the historic documents. The concession had been "solidified."
- March 12 was also the day Truman delivered his "all-out speech" to Congress proposing aid to Greece and Turkey — the Truman Doctrine — a landmark of the Cold War. The Truman Doctrine and the sealing of the four-company Aramco deal now assured a substantial American presence stretching from the Mediterranean to the Persian Gulf.

### Gulbenkian Again

- By May 1947, a deal improved the French position in IPC, and CFP withdrew its suit. But Gulbenkian, installed in a first-floor suite at Lisbon's venerable Hotel Aviz, kept to his flint-nosed habits. He no longer kept a car and chauffeur — he hired a driver, carefully checking the odometer to make sure he wasn't being charged for someone else's trips.
- "Gulbenkian may be regarded as a man of his word once this has been given," observed a British official. "The difficulty lies in obtaining it. The ability to compromise is not one of his attributes." He escaped income taxes in France and Portugal by maintaining an appointment with the Iranian legation. To avoid property tax on his Paris mansion, he turned part of it into a picture gallery. When he sold the Ritz Hotel in Paris, he insisted on terms providing a suite permanently reserved for him so he could claim to be "in transit" and avoid French taxation.
- Though the French had dropped their suit, Gulbenkian filed suit in a British court, willing to "wash every last piece of dirty linen in public." Jersey and Socony responded with countersuits. The case received wide publicity — Gulbenkian became a tourist attraction in Lisbon, "one of the tourist 'musts' of Lisbon, along with the bullfights." Owing to his short stature, he had ordered a special platform built in the Hotel Aviz restaurant so he could eat lunch and survey the scene at the same time.
- Gulbenkian's son Nubar described his father's negotiating tactic: "It was my father's practice never to press any claim to a breakdown, but, very able negotiator that he was, to make his demands step by step, so that having obtained satisfaction on one point he would raise another and yet another, thus achieving all he wanted or, at least, much more of what he wanted than he would have obtained if he had started by putting forward all his demands at once."
- Gulbenkian had four separate representatives at negotiations, each reporting to him separately in writing, without collaborating — so he could double-check and second-guess everyone. He told a Socony director he "could not respect himself unless he drove as good a bargain as possible." To an art-loving American, he explained: money itself "did not count for very much" — he thought of himself as "an architect, even as an artist, creating beautiful structures, balancing interests, harmonizing economic forces." His art collection was the greatest ever assembled by a single person. He called the artworks his "children" and seemed to care more for them than for his actual son. But his masterpiece was the Iraq Petroleum Company — "as architecturally designed, as faultlessly composed, as Raphael's The School of Athens." He regarded the Jersey and Socony executives as "Giroloma Genga, a third-rate, mediocre, obscure imitator of the masters of the Renaissance."
- At the last minute in November 1948, with the signing in Lisbon about to take place and a celebratory dinner prepared, Gulbenkian announced at five minutes to seven that he had found "one more point." Consternation gripped the room. Telegrams went to London; a "stunned and depressing silence" descended. The dinner was somber and funereal — "only one bottle of champagne was drunk among twelve people." Around midnight, London telegraphed that Gulbenkian's final demand was acceded to. He signed at 1:30 AM. The documents were sent by chartered plane to London.
- The Group Agreement of November 1948 reconstituted the IPC. Gulbenkian got higher overall production and an extra allocation of oil. "Mr. Five Percent was no more; he was now something greater." An Anglo-Iranian executive declared: "We have now succeeded in making the Agreement completely unintelligible to anybody." One of Gulbenkian's lawyers noted: "No one will ever be able to litigate about these documents because no one will be able to understand them."
- With the Red Line Agreement dissolved, the legal threat to Jersey and Socony's participation in Aramco was removed. "If you laid all the conversations that went into this deal end to end, they would reach to the moon." In December 1948, Aramco was finalized — owned by Jersey, Socony, Socal, and Texaco. 100% American.
- Gulbenkian preserved his IPC and his position. His last display of artistry earned hundreds of millions more for the Gulbenkian interests. He lived on six more years in Lisbon, ceaselessly arguing with IPC partners and rewriting his will. When he died in 1955 at 85, he left three legacies: a vast fortune, a splendid art collection, and — most fittingly — endless litigation over his will and estate.

### Kuwait

- Gulf Oil, half owner of the Kuwait Oil Company, was constrained by its partner Anglo-Iranian from competing in India and the Middle East. Gulf needed outlets for the rapidly rising tide of Kuwaiti oil. Colonel J.F. Drake, Gulf's president, found the answer in Royal Dutch/Shell — one of the two largest marketing organizations in the Eastern Hemisphere, but with little Middle Eastern oil.
- Drake explained to the State Department: "a deal between Gulf, which is long on crude oil and short on markets, and Shell, which is long on markets and short on crude oil, made excellent sense."
- The two companies developed a unique purchase-and-sale agreement — "shadow integration" allowing Kuwaiti oil to flow into Shell's system. Initially a ten-year agreement (later extended 13 more years), it would account for a quarter of Gulf's proven Kuwaiti reserves, providing Shell with 30% of its Eastern Hemisphere needs. They innovated "netback pricing" — a 50-50 profit split defined as "final selling price" minus all costs. The profit-calculation schedules filled over half of the 170-page contract.
- The Kuwaiti Amir would insist on production increases as he saw neighbors' production rising. Shell was about the only system that could absorb so much oil. As the Foreign Office put it, Shell was "to all intents and purposes a partner in the Concession."

### Iran and the Soviet Threat

- The third great postwar oil deal involved Iran. Jersey and Socony privately raised the possibility of a long-term contract for Iranian crude with Sir William Fraser, chairman of Anglo-Iranian. "Willie" was receptive — AIOC feared being shut out of Europe by cheap Aramco oil.
- Political considerations also drove the deal: Iran was under continuing Soviet pressure. During WWII, the USSR had demanded an Iranian oil concession and occupied Azerbaijan in northern Iran. Soviet troops didn't withdraw until spring 1946 under intense US/British pressure. The Iranian Crisis of 1946 was the first major East-West confrontation of the Cold War.
- The American ambassador asked Stalin in April 1946: "What does the Soviet Union want, and how far is Russia going to go?" Stalin's reply: "We're not going much farther." He described Soviet interest in Iran as defensive — "The Baku oil fields are our major source of supply. They are close to the Iranian border and they are very vulnerable." Stalin, the former "journeyman of the Revolution" in Baku, warned that "saboteurs — even a man with a box of matches — might cause us serious damage. We are not going to risk our oil supply."
- Soviet oil production in 1945 was only 60% of 1941. Fields were seriously damaged and depleted. Stalin interrogated his petroleum minister Nikolai Baibakov (who would run the Soviet economy for two decades until Gorbachev replaced him). Stalin demanded to know what to do about the "very bad oil position." Efforts would have to be redoubled.
- In 1940, Soviet Foreign Minister Molotov had declared "the area south of Batum and Baku in the general direction of the Persian Gulf be recognized as the center of the aspirations of the Soviet Union." That area was Iran.
- After Soviet withdrawal, the communist-led Tudeh party conducted demonstrations and strikes at Anglo-Iranian's Abadan refinery, where people were killed. Iran was unstable, with the grave possibility of civil war or absorption into the Soviet bloc.
- Both American and British governments sought to preserve Iranian independence. London was categoric: Anglo-Iranian's oil position "was the company's crown jewels, and it had to be preserved at all costs." Having American companies take a direct interest in Iranian oil would help "solidify" the position. In September 1947, Anglo-Iranian, Jersey, and Socony signed a twenty-year contract.

### Europe's Energy Crisis and the Marshall Plan

- Europe in 1946 was devastated — Germany barely functioning, food and raw materials in short supply, trading patterns broken, inflation rampant, severe shortage of American dollars. By 1946, Europe was gripped by a terrible coal shortage. The winter of 1946-47 was the longest and coldest of the century — the Thames froze at Windsor, power stations shut down, electricity was cut to industry, unemployment increased six times over, and British industrial production halted for three weeks — "something German bombing had never been able to accomplish."
- This crisis drove home Britain's impoverishment. In February 1947, the Labour government referred Palestine to the UN, announced Indian independence, and told the US it could no longer afford to prop up Greece. Britain asked the US to take over broader responsibilities in the Near and Middle East.
- In June 1947 at Harvard, Secretary of State George Marshall introduced the European Recovery Program (Marshall Plan), which became central to containment of Soviet power. "Without petroleum the Marshall Plan could not have functioned," said a US government report. About 20% of total Marshall Plan aid went to oil and oil equipment imports. Oil was the largest single item in European dollar budgets.
- The "dollar oil" vs. "sterling oil" debate erupted — British Foreign Secretary Ernest Bevin told the American ambassador that "while the Americans were voting money to help Europe, the rise in oil prices nullified their efforts to a considerable extent." Middle Eastern oil prices were eventually pushed below the US Gulf Coast benchmark — ending the Achnacarry pricing convention. The last vestige of the "As-Is" system was gone.
- The Marshall Plan drove Europe's transition from coal to imported oil. Coal shortages, labor strife in mines, and communist influence in miners' unions made oil essential. "It is not a joyful thing, but it is a national necessity to import more oil," Britain's Chancellor Hugh Dalton told Marshall. Oil could effectively compete against coal in price. Central heating was the revolutionary innovation — "The Englishman began to realize that there was no value in being cold."
- In 1946, 77% of Europe's oil came from the Western Hemisphere; by 1951, 80% was expected from the Middle East.

### Tapline and the Palestine/Israel Problem

- Aramco's four parents continued to battle to build Tapline to carry Saudi oil to the Mediterranean. Steel was in short supply under US government controls. Independent oil men tried to block the steel allocation to prevent cheap foreign oil flooding America. The Truman Administration supported Tapline as essential to the Marshall Plan: "the European recovery program will be seriously handicapped" without it.
- Syria and other transit countries demanded exorbitant fees. The partition of Palestine and creation of Israel complicated everything. Ibn Saud was bitterly anti-Zionist — he said Jews "had been the enemies of Arabs since the seventh century." He told Truman that American support for a Jewish state "would be a death blow to American interests in the Arab world" and that the Arabs "will lay siege to it until it dies of famine."
- When Ibn Saud visited Aramco's Dhahran headquarters in 1947, he praised the oranges served but pointedly asked if they were from Palestine (a kibbutz). He was reassured they were from California. In opposing a Jewish state, Ibn Saud held a "trump card": he could cancel the Aramco concession.
- On May 14, 1948, Israel declared statehood, recognized almost instantly by the Soviet Union and the US. The Arab League launched a full-scale attack — the first Arab-Israeli war. James Terry Duce of Aramco warned Secretary Marshall that Ibn Saud "may be compelled, in certain circumstances, to apply sanctions against the American oil concessions." But a State Department study found the Middle East provided only 6% of free world oil supplies and "such a cut in consumption could be achieved without substantial hardship."
- Ibn Saud could have canceled the concession but at considerable risk — Aramco was his sole source of rapidly rising wealth, and the US relationship guaranteed Saudi territorial integrity. He feared the British might sponsor the Hashemites (whom he had driven from Mecca) to recapture western Saudi Arabia. He pressed for a tripartite US-British-Saudi defensive treaty. He found he could "distinguish between Aramco, a purely commercial enterprise owned by four private companies, and the policy of the U.S. government elsewhere in the region." When other Arab countries pressed him to cancel the concession, he replied that oil royalties helped make Saudi Arabia "a stronger and more powerful nation, better to assist her neighboring Arab states in resisting Jewish pretensions."
- Tapline was finished in September 1950 — 1,040 miles, with oil arriving at Sidon, Lebanon in November. It replaced 7,200 miles of sea journey via the Suez Canal, equivalent to sixty tankers in continuous operation.

### No Longer "Far Afield": The New Dimension of Security

- The British, even withdrawing from empire, could not turn their backs on the Middle East. Iran, Kuwait, and Iraq were major oil sources. Anglo-Iranian dividends were a major revenue generator. Foreign Secretary Bevin told the Cabinet Defense Committee: "Without the Middle East and its oil, I see no hope of our being able to achieve the standard of living at which we are aiming in Great Britain."
- The US shift was even more dramatic. No longer would any American President say Saudi Arabia was "a little far afield." The US was becoming an ever more petroleum-based society that could no longer supply its own needs. Soviet expansionism brought the Middle East to center stage — the oil resources were "no less vital, in its own way, than the independence of Western Europe."
- Saudi Arabia became the dominant focus. "Here was what is probably the richest economic prize in the world in the field of foreign investment," said one American official in 1948. In October 1950, Truman wrote Ibn Saud: "No threat to your Kingdom could occur which would not be a matter of immediate concern to the United States." It sounded like a guarantee.
- The special US-Saudi relationship was "an unlikely union — Bedouin Arabs and Texas oil men, a traditional Islamic autocracy allied with modern American capitalism. Yet it was one that was destined to endure."

### The End of Energy Independence

- Middle Eastern oil in wartime was "very susceptible to enemy interference" (Joint Chiefs of Staff). Some argued for importing more oil in peacetime to preserve domestic reserves for wartime. Eugene V. Rostow's book A National Policy for the Oil Industry made this case. The National Security Resources Board argued in 1948 that importing Middle Eastern oil would allow a million barrels/day of Western Hemisphere production to be shut in — "the ideal storage place for petroleum."
- Synthetic fuels were promoted as an alternative. The New York Times declared in 1948 that "The United States is on the threshold of a profound chemical revolution... gasoline will be produced from coal, air, and water." The Interior Department claimed gasoline from coal or shale could cost eleven cents a gallon (wholesale was twelve cents). But cost projections kept rising — by 1951, synthetic gasoline from coal would cost 3.5 times the market price. Cheap foreign oil killed synthetic fuels. "Imported petroleum killed synthetic fuels. And they would remain dead for three decades."
- Technology opened new domestic frontiers — greater drilling depth and offshore production. Drilling off piers near Santa Barbara dated to the mid-1890s (1-2 barrels/day). In the 1930s, drillers walked into shallow waters off Texas and Louisiana.
- Going truly offshore into the Gulf of Mexico required creating a new industry. Kerr-McGee, an Oklahoma independent, took the gamble. Technology for building platforms, drilling into the ocean floor, or servicing offshore operations barely existed. Knowledge of weather (hurricanes), tides, and currents was rudimentary.
- Kerr-McGee reasoned it couldn't compete for "real class-one" onshore acreage against majors, but offshore had hardly any competition — most companies thought it impossible. On a clear Sunday morning in October 1947, on Block 32, ten and a half miles off the Louisiana coast, Kerr-McGee struck oil. A landmark event. But offshore wells cost five times onshore wells of similar depth, and a struggle between the federal government and states over continental shelf ownership (and tax revenues) wasn't resolved until 1953.
- Natural gas was "the orphan of the oil industry" — considered a useless, inconvenient byproduct, burned off ("flared") because there was nothing else to do with it. Only a fraction was used, mostly in the Southwest. It sold for one-fifth the energy-equivalent cost of oil. The problem was transmission — pipelines had meant 150 miles maximum. But the House Armed Services Committee declared natural gas "the quickest and cheapest method immediately available to reduce domestic consumption of petroleum."
- In 1947, the Big Inch and Little Inch wartime oil pipelines were converted to natural gas. Los Angeles was connected to New Mexico and West Texas gas fields via the "Biggest Inch" pipeline (El Paso Natural Gas). By 1950, interstate natural gas movement reached 2.5 trillion cubic feet — 2.5 times the 1946 level. Without the additional natural gas, American oil demand would have been 700,000 barrels per day higher.
- By 1950, the postwar petroleum order was established, centered on the Middle East. US oil consumption jumped 12% in 1950 over 1949. A July 1950 Jersey analysis warned: "Mid-East crudes available to Jersey may exceed requirements substantially." The massive surplus would confront the industry. Bitter battles over profit division were already erupting.

## Chapter 22: Fifty-Fifty: The New Deal in Oil

### The Fight Over Rents

- In 1950, US Treasury representatives conferring with British officials mentioned "certain developments regarding Saudi Arabian oil policies, the effects of which would surely be felt throughout the Middle East." The Saudi government had made "startling demands on Aramco... They covered all possible points ever thought up by a concessionary government." All the demands came down to one thing: the Saudis wanted more money.
- In the late 1940s and early 1950s, oil companies and governments grappled continually over financial terms. The central issue was the division of "rents" — "that uneasy and important term in the economics of natural resources." The objective of producing countries was to shift revenues from oil companies and the treasuries of consuming countries to themselves. But it was not just about money — it was also about power.

### Landlord and Tenant — Ricardo's Framework

- The intellectual framework came from David Ricardo, the fantastically successful late-18th/early-19th century English stockbroker (who made a killing on Wellington's defeat of Napoleon at Waterloo). A Jew who became a Quaker, then a House of Commons member, Ricardo was one of the founding fathers of modern economics, the successor generation (with Thomas Malthus) to Adam Smith.
- Ricardo developed the concept of "rents" — the difference between the market price and the cost of production (including allowances for transport, processing, distribution, and some return on capital). Two landlords with fields of different fertility sell grain at the same price; the one with more fertile land gets not just profit but also rents — rewards from "nature's bountiful legacy," not from ingenuity or hard work.
- Applied to oil: in the late 1940s, oil sold for about $2.50/barrel. A Texas stripper-well operator might make 10 cents profit. In the Middle East, production cost only 25 cents/barrel. Deducting 50 cents for other costs and 10 cents "profit," that left $1.65 per barrel of rents on every barrel of Middle Eastern oil. The question: who — the host country, the producing company, or the consuming country — would get those rents?
- The host country had sovereignty over the oil. But the oil had no value until the foreign company risked its capital and expertise. The host country was the landlord; the company was the tenant. "A rich discovery means a dissatisfied landlord," said oil economist M.A. Adelman. "He knows that the tenant's profit is far greater than is necessary to keep him producing, and he wants some of the rent. If he gets some, he wants more."
- The battle was also political — producing countries saw foreign companies as "exploiting" the country, draining the "irreplaceable heritage," acting as the "all-too-visible embodiment of colonialism" in a "haughty, arrogant, and superior manner." The companies saw it differently: they had taken risks, invested capital, created value where none existed. Their plaintive cry was "We wuz robbed."
- For consuming countries, oil was a strategic prize vital to their economies and national strategy — and also a significant source of tax revenues. For producing countries, oil meant "power, influence, significance, and status — all of which were previously lacking." Money signified both power and pride.

### Venezuela's Ritual Cleansing — The Origin of Fifty-Fifty

- General Gomez's tyrannical dictatorship ended with his death in 1935. He had treated Venezuela as "a sole proprietorship, a personal hacienda." Much of the population was impoverished while the oil industry dominated the economy. The democratic opposition centered on the "Generation of '28" — students at the Universidad Central in Caracas who had rebelled against Gomez. They were crushed: some got sixty-pound leg irons, others were exiled or sent to road crews in disease-ridden jungles. Many perished. The survivors became the nucleus of reformers.
- With oil accounting for over 90% of Venezuela's total export value by the late 1930s, Gomez's successors reformed the oil industry's regulation and reallocated rents. The US government was the catalyst — conscious of the Mexican nationalization disaster, Washington wanted to protect access to Venezuela, the most important foreign oil source. The Roosevelt Administration made clear that Jersey could not count on US support if it failed to adapt.
- Jersey was sharply divided. Traditionalists (some Gomez cronies) wanted to stand firm. Wallace Pratt, the former chief geologist turned senior executive, argued that adaptation was "not only inevitable but essential." Better to help create the new order than be a victim. Jersey under political attack in Washington (I.G. Farben scandal, new antitrust campaign) could not risk losing Venezuela.
- Jersey installed Arthur Proudfit as top man in Venezuela — he had been part of the 1920s migration from Mexico and brought lasting memories of the disaster of government-company relations and bitter labor strife there. All sides wanted to work things out. U.S. Undersecretary of State Sumner Welles took the unprecedented step of recommending independent consultants to Venezuela, including Herbert Hoover Jr. (son of the former president, a well-known geologist).
- A settlement was hammered out based on "fifty-fifty" — a landmark. Royalties and taxes would be raised to the point where the government's take would about equal the companies' net profits in Venezuela. In exchange, the validity of concessions would be confirmed, their life extended, and new exploration opportunities opened.
- The proposed law was criticized by Accion Democratica (the liberal/socialist party of the Generation of '28 survivors). Juan Pablo Perez Alfonzo declared: "The total purification of the Venezuelan oil industry, its ritual cleansing, will remain impossible until the companies have paid adequate financial compensation to our country." Despite Accion Democratica's abstention, the Venezuelan Congress passed the new petroleum law in March 1943.
- Shell director Frederick Godber's reaction: "What they are after is money. Unless they are prompted to do so by our friends across the water, they are not likely yet to reject good money from wherever it comes." Some smaller companies were outraged — William F. Buckley (Pantepec Oil) called it "burdensome" and accepted "under compulsion."
- In 1945, Romulo Betancourt and Accion Democratica came to power via a coup. Minister of Development Juan Pablo Perez Alfonzo found the promised 50-50 split had actually worked out to about 60-40 in companies' favor. He instituted tax revisions to ensure a true 50-50. By 1948, the government's total income was six times that of 1942.
- Perez Alfonzo broke another precedent: he insisted Venezuela take some royalties in kind (in oil rather than money), then sold the royalty oil directly on the world market. "The veil of mystery over the marketing of oil — behind which the Anglo-Saxons had maintained a monopoly of rights and secrets — was removed forever," declared President Betancourt.
- Creole (Jersey's subsidiary) adapted successfully — workforce became 90% Venezuelan; Arthur Proudfit even lobbied on behalf of the Venezuelan government with the US State Department. Betancourt recognized realities: "It would have been a suicidal leap into space to nationalize the industry by decree." Venezuela received 7% more per barrel than Mexico got from its nationalized industry. Venezuelan production was six times Mexico's.
- But in November 1948, the Accion Democratica government was overthrown by the same military clique from the 1945 coup. Some operators applauded; Buckley claimed AD had "used the vast dollar resources of the country to further Russian Communistic interests." But the major companies found the coup "disheartening and disappointing" — it threatened three years of stable relationship-building. Betancourt had invited Nelson A. Rockefeller (grandson of John D.) to establish the International Basic Economy Corporation for development projects in Venezuela.

### The Neutral Zone — Precedent-Shattering Terms

- The Neutral Zone was about 2,000 square miles of desert between Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, carved out by the British in 1922 with shared sovereignty. If every system has the seeds of its own destruction, it was in the Neutral Zone that the erosion of the postwar petroleum order began.
- The State Department encouraged "new companies" to participate in Middle Eastern oil development to counterbalance the majors. Washington circularized American companies about Kuwait putting its Neutral Zone rights up for bid. Major companies feared that bidding would force them to offer terms far better than their current concessions.
- Ralph Davies, former Socal marketing executive and Ickes's wartime deputy, organized a consortium of independents (Phillips, Ashland, Sinclair) called "Aminoil" (American Independent Oil Company). Davies warned partners they were "bucking the big, big, big time."
- Aminoil had a unique entree: Jim Brooks, a Texas oil field welder returning from Saudi Arabia, had stopped at Shepheard's Hotel in Cairo. The secretary to the Amir of Kuwait was also there, tasked with finding a Texas oil man unconnected to the majors. Brooks's cowboy hat caught his attention. Brooks ended up at the Dasman Palace, where he earned lasting gratitude by adjusting the plumbing to cut water use by 90%.
- Aminoil won with a bid that stunned the industry: $7.5 million cash, $625,000 minimum annual royalty, 15% of profits, and a million-dollar yacht for the Amir.

### "The Best Hotel in Town" — J. Paul Getty

- The Saudi Arabian rights in the Neutral Zone were also up for grabs. Within eight years of winning the concession, Jean Paul Getty (or "J. Paul Getty" as he styled himself) would become the richest man in America.
- Getty was "inward, vain, and insecure" but driven by "a powerful need to make money, matched by an extraordinary talent for doing so." His philosophy: "There's always the best hotel in town and the best room in the best hotel in town, and there's always somebody in it." He was no more trusting than Gulbenkian: "One is very nearly always let down by underlings... They may be all right for 80 percent of the time, but for 20 percent, they do something quite incredible."
- Getty could not stand to lose a contest or share authority. "I had a perfect record with J. Paul Getty," said a business partner. "I had a thousand fights with him, and never won a single one." He was a gambler, but cautious: "If I wanted to gamble on typical gambling games, I'd buy a casino and have the percentages for me, rather than play."
- Getty's father was a Minnesota insurance company lawyer who went to Oklahoma to collect a bad debt and became a millionaire oil man. The father's word was his bond; the son engaged in "sharp practices" and turned them into an art. Getty was "well built, pugnacious by nature, and quick," said boxer Jack Dempsey, who had sparred with him. "I've never met anybody with such intense concentration and willpower — perhaps more than is good for him."
- Getty married five times, with "a special predilection for teenage girls." He traveled in Europe under the alias "Mr. Paul" because it was "less noticed" that he was "in transit flagrante with two or three women at a time." The only true love of his life may have been a French woman, Madame Marguerite Tallasou, with whom he had a passionate affair in Constantinople in 1913 — he lost contact with her in the turmoil of war and revolution.
- Getty wrote at least seven books (including one for Playboy on how to be rich), launched a major art collection, but never let outside interests interfere with his quest for money through oil. "A man is a business failure if he lets his family life interfere with his business record." Or: "When I'm thinking about oil, I'm not thinking about girls."
- Getty was "obsessed with value. If he thought something had value, he bought it and never sold it." In the 1920s, he decided it was cheaper to drill for oil than buy oil company shares. After the 1929 crash, he reversed — oil shares at great discounts became his target, leading to an extended takeover battle for Tidewater Oil against Standard of New Jersey. Those Depression-era stock purchases were the basis of his fortune.
- Getty was ruthless in pursuit of bargains. During the Depression, he fired all employees and rehired them at lower salaries. In 1938, he bought the Pierre Hotel in New York for $2.4 million (less than a quarter of construction cost). That same year in Vienna, after the Nazi seizure of Austria, he got himself into Baron Louis de Rothschild's home (the Baron was held prisoner by the Nazis) to look at furniture that would "soon be available." He went to Berlin to check what the SS planned, and ended up buying Rothschild pieces at a great discount.
- Getty had extensive social connections with Nazi leaders and perhaps sympathized with the Nazis. The FBI and military intelligence suspected him. His application for a naval commission "was rejected because of suspected espionage activities." He remained fascinated by dictators for life.
- During WWII, Getty managed an airplane factory in Tulsa from a concrete bunker (fearing Luftwaffe bombing). He chewed each mouthful 33 times, washed his own underwear nightly due to antipathy toward commercial detergents, and by age 55 had his second facelift and was dyeing his hair a "funny kind of reddish-brown" giving him a "wizened, embalmed look."

### Getty Wins the Saudi Neutral Zone Concession

- Getty was certain he wanted the Saudi Neutral Zone concession: "If one is to be anybody in the world oil business, one must have a footing in the Middle East." He sent Paul Walton, a young MIT-trained geologist who had worked for Socal in Saudi Arabia in the 1930s, as his point man. At the Pierre Hotel, Getty briefed Walton, who remembered Getty's "half-mad expression on his face — a sort of angry, disagreeable scowl" designed to keep people at a distance from him and his money.
- Walton went to Jidda and negotiated with Abdullah Suleiman (the same finance minister who had handled the original Socal concession in 1933). Suleiman arranged for Walton to fly low over the Neutral Zone in a DC-3. Walton saw a small mound rising from the flat expanse — it looked almost exactly like the mound in Kuwait's Burgan field, then the largest known oil field in the world. He was elated.
- Walton was extremely cautious about security — no locks on hotel rooms in Jidda, so he left no papers and sent a handwritten letter by airmail rather than wireless. He told Getty the odds of a major oil play were fifty-fifty — better than the one-in-ten or one-in-twenty odds in the Rockies.
- Negotiations were conducted mostly on Suleiman's porch. The deal: $9.5 million up front, $1 million/year guaranteed even with no oil found, and a royalty of 55 cents a barrel — far higher than anywhere else. Getty also agreed to build housing, schools, a mosque, provide free gasoline for the Saudi Army, and establish training programs. Suleiman even insisted Getty pay for a Saudi Army unit to defend the concession area. A telegram from Secretary of State Dean Acheson was required to take that demand off the table (American companies were legally prohibited from funding foreign armies).
- Getty had authorized Walton to go up to $10.5 million, but Suleiman stopped at $9.5 million. Suleiman also told Aminoil and a Wall Street firm that if they topped Getty's offer, the concession was theirs — but neither would match the price. Pacific Western was paying an unprecedentedly high price to wildcat in an unknown desert.

### The Unhappy Marriage and Five Dry Holes

- Kuwait and Saudi Arabia each held an "undivided half interest" in the Neutral Zone, so Aminoil and Getty's Pacific Western had to amalgamate operations. The result was "a totally unhappy marriage" — Getty and Ralph Davies of Aminoil could not stand each other.
- Aminoil led exploration. By early 1953, half a decade in, they had spent over $30 million and had nothing to show but five dry holes. Getty was disgusted. He wandered Europe, spent weeks researching a Rembrandt he owned, totted up his income and expenses each evening (income in thousands/millions; expenses included "newspaper — 10 centimes" and "bus fare — 5 centimes"). He bought a rare Louis XV lacquer table and enrolled in a $178 course at Arthur Murray's School of Dancing (samba, jitterbug, and leading).
- Getty insisted the sixth hole be drilled at the little mound Walton had spotted from the airplane, which the Aminoil team had resolutely ignored. Sunk costs were sunk costs — if the sixth was dry, he was pulling out. In March 1953, the Aminoil team struck oil where Walton had always thought it would be found. Fortune described it as "somewhere between colossal and history-making."

### Billionaire

- Getty made his first visit to the region only afterward, listening to a "Teach Yourself Arabic" course on records. Ralph Davies of Aminoil never made it to the Neutral Zone — he had "a pathological fear of dust, dirt and germs."
- Getty used his Neutral Zone production, especially the cheap, heavier "garbage oil," to build vast integrated oil operations in the US, Western Europe, and Japan. He reorganized all holdings under Getty Oil, making himself sole commander. By the late 1950s, he was the seventh-largest marketer of gasoline in the United States. Fortune announced in 1957 that he was America's richest man and sole billionaire. His reaction: "My bankers kept telling me that it was so, but I was hoping I wouldn't be found out." He added: "If you can count your money, you don't have a billion dollars."
- Getty became the Billionaire Miser. At his 72-room Tudor manor house, Sutton Place, in Surrey, amid his priceless art and antiques collection, he installed a pay phone for guests.
- Paul Walton, who had spotted the mound and negotiated the deal, came down with amebic dysentery in Saudi Arabia in 1948. It took three years to recover. Getty gave him a $1,200 bonus. Walton returned to Salt Lake City to work as an independent geologist. The Neutral Zone had more than a billion barrels of recoverable reserves — making Getty not only the richest American but the richest private citizen in the world. Walton continued putting together ordinary drilling deals.
- When Getty died in 1976 at 83, the Duke of Bedford eulogized: "When I think of Paul, I think of money." For Getty, "there surely could have been no higher compliment."

### Impact of Getty's Terms — Gulbenkian's Warning

- Getty's 55-cent royalty to the Saudis loomed over Aminoil's 35 cents to Kuwait, Aramco's roughly 33 cents, Anglo-Iranian's and IPC's 16.5 cents to Iran and Iraq, and the Kuwait Oil Company's 15 cents. The IPC general manager called the 55-cent royalty "completely insane, uncalled for, and responsible for the difficulties being encountered in Iran and Iraq." A British diplomat angrily denounced "the notorious Pacific Western concession."
- Gulbenkian, the veteran negotiator, prophesied: "These new groups lack the experience of developing oil concessions in the Middle East. They offer fantastic terms to the local governments who expect similar fantasies from us. The result is trouble all around." He warned: "I feel confident that the local governments, although by no means cordially disposed with each other, will come together on this question of petroleum concessions, and do their best to squeeze us. I fear that the wind of nationalization and other complications may spread to us also. I would not be tranquil."

### "Retreat Is Inevitable" — The Saudi Fifty-Fifty Deal

- In 1949, world demand for Saudi oil flattened (American recession, British economic problems). Saudi revenues fell, but the King's financial commitments kept growing. Soldiers went unpaid, tribal subsidies were withheld, debt piled up — reminiscent of the crises of the 1930s and early 1940s.
- Finance Minister Abdullah Suleiman regularly threatened to "close down the entire oil operation" unless Saudi Arabia got a greater share of "large company profits." Demands were endless: construction projects, a "welfare fund," new loans. Aramco's general counsel: "Each time the company agreed to one thing, there was always just one more."
- A Venezuelan delegation had traveled to the Middle East, promulgating the fifty-fifty concept and translating documents into Arabic. Betancourt explained their motive: "competition from low-cost, high-volume production from the Middle East was a grave threat to Venezuela." Better to get Middle Eastern costs up. The Venezuelans "decided to spread the benefits of the fifty-fifty principle to the area which was taking business away from them — the Middle East."
- The Venezuelan delegation got only as close to Saudi Arabia as Basra, Iraq (the Saudis wouldn't let them in because Venezuela had voted for Israel at the UN). But the concept crossed the border. The Saudis saw that in 1949, Aramco's profits were almost three times Saudi Arabia's own earnings from the concession. Even more striking: the US government's tax take from Aramco ($43 million) was $4 million higher than Aramco's royalty payments to Riyadh. The Saudis "weren't a darn bit happy about that."

### The Foreign Tax Credit — The Mechanism

- The Saudis, unbeknownst to Aramco, retained their own adviser on American tax law and discovered the "foreign tax credit." Under legislation dating to 1918, an American company overseas could deduct foreign income taxes (not royalties) from its US tax bill. If Saudi Arabia collected $39 million in royalties AND $39 million in taxes, that $39 million tax bill could be deducted from Aramco's $43 million US tax obligation — leaving only $4 million to the US Treasury. Saudi Arabia's take would double from $39 million to $78 million. The overall tax bite on Aramco would stay the same, but most would be collected in Riyadh, not Washington.
- In August 1950, Aramco authorized negotiations for a fundamental revision. The State Department was a strong proponent — the Korean War had begun in June 1950, and Washington worried about communist influence and Soviet expansion in the Middle East. Anti-Western nationalists had to be kept at bay. "Since company retreat is inevitable," concluded a State Department policy paper, "it would seem useful to make the retreat as beneficial and orderly as possible to all concerned."
- George McGhee, Assistant Secretary of State for Near Eastern Affairs: "The Saudis knew the Venezuelans were getting 50/50. Why wouldn't they want it too?" At a State Department meeting on September 18, 1950, McGhee told oil company representatives the time was for "rolling with the punch." He bluntly told the parent companies there was no alternative — long-term contracts created "the practical necessity of horsetrading."
- On December 30, 1950, after a month of complex negotiations, Aramco and Saudi Arabia signed the new fifty-fifty agreement.

### The Tax Credit Confirmed — Revenue Shift

- The IRS did not confirm the tax credit's eligibility until 1955 when auditing Aramco's 1950 return. In 1957, the Joint Congressional Committee on Internal Revenue Taxation approved, finding the ruling consistent with tax laws and IRS precedent.
- The revenue shift was dramatic: in 1949, the US Treasury collected $43 million from Aramco vs. $39 million in royalties to Saudi Arabia. By 1951, Saudi Arabia collected $110 million from Aramco, while Aramco paid only $6 million to the US Treasury.
- The impact spread swiftly. Kuwait insisted on fifty-fifty; Gulf overcame Anglo-Iranian chairman Sir William Fraser's "obdurate objections." Iraq followed by early 1952. Britain's Inland Revenue eventually accepted the tax credit mechanism.

### Jersey's Internal Assessment

- Inside Jersey, a working paper analyzed the significance: "We now know that the safety of our position in any country depends not alone on compliance with laws and contracts, or on the rate or amount of our payments to the government, but on whether our whole relationship is accepted at any given moment by the government and public opinion of the country — and by our own government and public opinion — as 'fair.'" Unfortunately, "'fairness' and 'unfairness' are essentially concepts of the emotions rather than fixed and measurable standards."
- The paper warned: "If we ever admit in any country that an equal division is less than 'fair,' the ground will be cut out from under our feet in every country." Fifty-fifty was where Jersey should make its stand: "'50/50' is a good position which needs no defense and is hard to attack; '55/45' or '60/40' would have no such appeal, and could be only rear-guard defense positions in an unlimited retreat."

### The Watershed

- The Saudi-Aramco agreement was described by a historian of the British empire's decline as "an economic and political watershed no less significant for the Middle East than the transfer of power for India and Pakistan." For the American government, it satisfied the urgent need to increase income to Saudi Arabia and other producing countries to maintain the postwar petroleum order and keep "friendly" regimes in power.
- Taxing oil company profits was more efficient than getting foreign aid through Congress. The fifty-fifty principle had the right psychological feel. George McGhee, quizzed at a 1974 Senate hearing about whether the tax credit was "a very ingenious way of transferring many millions by executive decision out of the public treasury and into the hands of a foreign government treasury," disagreed: "The ownership of this oil concession was a valuable asset for our country. The risk of not doing something along these lines was much too great. In essence, the threat was the loss of the concession."
- But within six months of the Saudi deal (December 1950), events in neighboring Iran would prove that the landlord-tenant relationship had by no means been satisfactorily resolved.

## Chapter 23: "Old Mossy" and the Struggle for Iran

### The Young Shah

- When Reza Pahlavi, the former Shah, died in exile in South Africa in 1944, his son Mohammed Reza Pahlavi was devastated. "My grief was immense." He had worshipped his father — the resolute, towering commander of the Persian Cossack brigade who had seized power and crowned himself Shah in the 1920s. Reza Shah had brought order, begun modernization, and subjugated the powerful mullahs.
- The son's grief was compounded by guilt — he had been part of his father's downfall. In August 1941, after Germany invaded the Soviet Union, Britain and Russia moved forces into Iran to protect the Abadan refinery and the supply line to the USSR. Alarmed by German advances in Russia and North Africa, the Allies feared a pincer converging on Iran. They deposed Reza Shah (who had shown friendliness toward the Nazis) and replaced him with his 21-year-old son.
- Mohammed Reza Pahlavi was forever haunted by his father's memory, striving to be worthy of Reza Shah. His sister Ashraf once asked "whether I was a man or a mouse." He had been entrusted to a French governess at six, sent to school in Switzerland at twelve. The American ambassador mused in 1950 that "he is a little too Westernized for an Oriental country."
- The young Shah faced treacherous circumstances that would challenge the most experienced politicians. His dynasty's legitimacy was problematic. He contended with chronic foreign intervention, direct Soviet pressure, and a highly visible British economic presence. Iran's political system was riven by every division — class, regional, religious, modern vs. traditional.
- On one side were Islamic fundamentalists led by the fiery Ayatollah Seyed Kashani, outraged by every intrusion of the modern world. On the other were the communists and the Tudeh party, a well-organized leftist party tied to Moscow. In between were reformers, nationalists, republicans, and military officers.
- Iran's political culture was "chaotic and phantasmagoric, given to wild exaggeration and violent emotion. Graft and corruption were a way of life." The British charge d'affaires summed up Majlis (parliament) rules: "Deputies expect to be bribed." Tribes and clans in the countryside hated subordination to Tehran. Virtually no part of the Shah's domain was immune to secessionist drives.
- The nation was gripped by grinding poverty and economic collapse, with pervasive hopelessness. Only one thing united the country: hatred of foreigners, especially the British. The English were regarded as "almost supernatural devils, controlling and manipulating the entire nation." Every politician was "virtually obliged to accuse his enemies and opponents of being British agents." Even droughts, crop failures, and locust plagues were blamed on "those clever Englishmen."
- The detestation centered on Anglo-Iranian Oil Company — the largest industrial employer in Iran, the major source of foreign earnings, and "the all-too-tangible symbol of the intrusion of the modern foreign world." Between 1945 and 1950, AIOC registered £250 million profit vs. £90 million in royalties to Iran. The British government received more in taxes from Anglo-Iranian than Iran did in royalties. Dividends went to the majority owner, the British government, and it was rumored AIOC sold oil to the British Navy at a substantial discount.

### The Last Chance

- Through WWII, Iran was seen as primarily a "British show." But the Cold War shoved Iran to the fore of American foreign policy concerns. By 1949, Americans feared Iran was so decayed economically and politically that it would be easy prey for the Soviet Union.
- In February 1949, a Muslim fanatic posing as a photographer tried to kill the Shah at Tehran University, firing a half-dozen shots at point-blank range but only slightly wounding him. The Shah used the assassination attempt to impose martial law, assert authority, and exhume his father's body from South Africa (now posthumously "the Great") for a state funeral. Huge equestrian statues of Reza Shah would rise across the country.
- George McGhee, the American point man (age 37 in 1949, called "that infant prodigy" by the British), pushed the British government and Anglo-Iranian to increase royalties to Iran. McGhee was actually an Anglophile — a Rhodes Scholar who had known John Cadman's daughters at Oxford and been offered a job as a geophysicist in Iran by Anglo-Iranian. He married the daughter of Everette DeGolyer. But he thought the British needed saving from their "nineteenth-century attitude toward oil." Secretary of State Dean Acheson criticized "the unusual and persistent stupidity of the company and the British Government" on Iran.
- Despite being a 51% owner, the British government had no great affection for Anglo-Iranian. There was suspicion and rancor — "a classic case of what has been called the 'battle between Minister and Manager.'" Foreign Secretary Bevin complained in 1946 that Anglo-Iranian "is virtually a private company with state capital and anything it does reacts upon the relationships between the British Government and Persia. As Foreign Secretary, I have no power or influence, in spite of this great holding by the Government, to do anything at all."
- Anglo-Iranian, the third-largest crude producer in the world, thought Iran got a pretty good deal — not only a royalty but 20% of worldwide profits, better than any other producer received. The company saw itself as a private firm trying to carry on a complex global business. Its senior executives resented the intrusions of politicians and civil servants — "West End gentlemen" who "simply did not understand the oil business."

### Sir William Fraser's Obstinacy

- Fraser was a tough, implacable autocrat who ran Anglo-Iranian one way — his way. Dissent was not tolerated. The Gulf chairman observed that Fraser's domination was so total that Anglo-Iranian's other directors "did not dare call their souls their own." He was "a Scotsman to his fingertips" — his father had founded the leading Scottish shale oil company and then sold it to Anglo-Iranian, hence "Willie came with the shale." A Foreign Office minister said Fraser had "all the contempt of a Glasgow accountant for anything which can not be shown on a balance sheet." Another British official: "obstinate, narrow old skinflint."
- Fraser implacably resisted entreaties to negotiate with Iran and ignored the Americans. But in autumn 1950, he had an abrupt change of heart — learning about the "McGhee Bombshell" (the imminent Saudi fifty-fifty deal), he knew time had run out. He offered substantially more money, subsidies for Iranian development, and support for education. But it was too late. In December, the Saudi fifty-fifty deal was announced, forcing Premier Razmara to withdraw support for the Supplemental Agreement. Anglo-Iranian then offered its own fifty-fifty deal — but it was no longer enough.

### Mossadegh and Nationalization

- The entire opposition now focused on Anglo-Iranian. Mohammed Mossadegh, chairman of the Majlis oil committee, declared: "The source of all the misfortunes of this tortured nation is only the oil company." Another deputy thundered it would be better for the Iranian oil industry "to be destroyed by an atomic bomb than remain in the hands of Anglo-Iranian."
- Prime Minister Razmara, a lean young "soldier's soldier" (St. Cyr graduate, known for having once returned a bribe), came out against nationalization in a speech to Parliament in March 1951. Four days later, as he was about to enter Tehran's central mosque, he was assassinated by a young carpenter entrusted by Islamic terrorists with the "sacred mission" of killing "the British stooge." A week later, the minister of education was also assassinated.
- The Majlis passed a resolution nationalizing the oil industry. On April 28, 1951, the Majlis chose Mossadegh as Prime Minister with the mandate to execute the nationalization law. The Shah signed it; it went into effect May 1. In the nationalization decree, Anglo-Iranian was designated the "Former Company." As the British ambassador reported, Anglo-Iranian "has been legally abolished" and Tehran "has taken the line it has no further existence."
- Mossadegh dispatched the governor of Khuzistan to Anglo-Iranian's headquarters at Khorramshahr. The governor sacrificed a sheep in front of the building, then announced the concession was voided. Directors of the new state oil company appeared at Abadan refinery carrying stationery, rubber stamps, and a sign reading "Iranian National Oil Company." Scores more sheep were sacrificed. But though the sheep had been sacrificed, "the deed was not yet done" — for five months, the status of Anglo-Iranian's facilities remained in uncertainty.

### "Old Mossy"

- Mohammed Mossadegh was about seventy, frail, completely bald with a very long nose and bright, buttonlike eyes. He was a man of contradictions — cosmopolitan (educated in France and Switzerland), yet fiercely nationalistic and antiforeigner. Son of a high bureaucrat, great-grandson of a Shah from the preceding dynasty, he was an aristocrat with extensive landholdings including a 150-family village. Yet he took on the mantle of reform, republicanism, and rabble-rousing.
- One of the first professors at the Persian School of Political Science, he had been caught up in Iran's 1906 constitutional revolution, which remained his lodestar. He went to the Versailles Peace Conference after WWI with a rubber stamp reading "Comite resistance des nations" to plead Persia's case against the British — received no hearing and returned embittered.
- In the 1920s, he opposed Reza Shah's moves toward dictatorship and was rewarded with jail and detention on his estate, where he busied himself with "amateur medical studies and the investigation of homeopathic remedies." The 1941 expulsion of Reza Shah was the signal for Mossadegh to burst back onto the political scene. His long years of dedicated opposition established him as the "pure" man, devoted to Iran and to cleansing it of foreign domination.
- Mossadegh was "unpretentious and eccentric" — he frequently received Iranians and foreign dignitaries in pajamas, lying on his bed. He lived in perpetual fear of assassination. His bodyguards were always nearby; two doors were blocked with wardrobes to prevent access by assassins.
- Mossadegh would say whatever suited his needs, "no matter how exaggerated or fanciful. But in the next moment, there was no assertion, no matter how strongly expressed, that could not be remolded or changed or, with a joke or only a giggle, repudiated altogether." He was a master of merging theatricality with politics — bursting into tears, moaning, fainting at the climax of speeches. Once he collapsed on the floor of the Majlis; a deputy who was a medical doctor rushed up to check his pulse. "As he did so, Mossadegh opened one eye and winked at him."
- Anthony Eden dubbed him "Old Mossy" — "with his pajamas and iron bedstead, was the first real bit of meat to come the way of the cartoonists since the war." Dean Acheson: "Mossadegh was a great actor and a great gambler." Truman called Sir William Fraser "a typical nineteenth-century colonial exploiter."
- Americans initially saw Mossadegh as a rational nationalist and potential bulwark against communism. Cold War considerations shaped American policy more than British. Mossadegh's real problem centered on keeping at bay those who were "more nationalistic, more extreme, more fundamentalist, and more antiforeigner than he."
- The British saw things differently: "Mossadegh was a Moslem, and in 1951 he would not have turned to the Russians," said Peter Ramsbotham. Some British officials regarded him as "lunatic." British Ambassador Sir Francis Shepherd described him as "cunning and slippery and completely unscrupulous" — the PM "looked rather like a cab horse and diffused a slight reek of opium."

### Plan Y — Military Intervention Debate

- The British Cabinet considered Plan Y — military intervention to seize the island of Abadan and its refinery. The inland oil fields were too remote, but Abadan could be taken with surprise. The US pressed hard against armed intervention, fearing it would legitimize a Russian move into northern Iran. India had just become independent, so there was no Indian Army to call upon. Britain could expect to be "castigated all over the world for old-fashioned imperialism." Defense Minister Emmanuel Shinwell worried that if Persia got away with nationalization, "the next thing might be an attempt to nationalize the Suez Canal."
- Churchill (then Leader of the Opposition) told Attlee he was "rather shocked at the attitude of the United States" — the area from the Caspian to the Persian Gulf "was more important than Korea." Parachutists were moved to Cyprus. But Attlee's government decided against using force. Some saw this as "the real beginning of the end of Britain's credibility and position in the Middle East."

### Averell Harriman's Mission

- Washington feared British military action would push Iran into Soviet arms. Acheson arranged for his friend Averell Harriman to mediate. Harriman was a multimillionaire who had given up business for public service — FDR's Special Representative, ambassador to Moscow and London, Secretary of Commerce, Marshall Plan representative.
- In Tehran, Harriman stayed in a Shah's palace with walls covered in thousands of tiny mirrors. He found Mossadegh lying on his bed, hands crossed below his neck, two doors blocked by wardrobes. "You do not know how crafty they are," Mossadegh told Harriman of the British. "You do not know how evil they are. You do not know how they sully everything they touch." Harriman: "I assure you they are good and bad and most of all in between."
- Mossadegh mentioned his grandson was away at school. "Where?" asked Harriman. "Why, in England, of course," Mossadegh replied. "Where else?"
- Colonel Vernon Walters ordered a copy of Alice in Wonderland from Washington "to serve as a kind of unofficial guidebook." Day after day, Harriman and Walter Levy tried to educate Mossadegh about oil realities. "In his dream world," Harriman cabled Truman, "the simple passage of legislation nationalizing the oil industry creates profitable business and everyone is expected to help Iran on terms that he lays down." At one point, Mossadegh seemed to demand more revenue per barrel than the total selling price of all products derived from it. "Dr. Mossadegh, if we are going to talk intelligently about these things, we have to agree on certain principles." "Such as what?" "Such as: nothing can be larger than the sum of its parts." Mossadegh replied in French: "That is false." "Consider the fox. His tail is often much longer than he is." He put the pillow over his head and rolled back and forth, laughing uproariously.
- Mossadegh would seem to agree to a framework by evening, but by morning would say he couldn't carry through — "He would not survive." His real concern was domestic politics and the threat from Muslim extremists.
- Harriman visited Ayatollah Kashani, the religious right leader (imprisoned in WWII for Axis sympathies). Kashani declared the British "the most evil people in the world," told the story of an American in Iran who had been shot and then butchered by a mob on the operating table. "Do you understand?" asked the ayatollah. Harriman, lips tightening: "Your Eminence, you must understand that I have been in many dangerous situations in my life and I do not frighten easily." "Well," shrugged Kashani, "there was no harm in trying." Kashani accused Mossadegh of being pro-British: "If Mossadegh yields, his blood will flow like Razmara's."
- Harriman recommended the British send a special negotiator — the socialist millionaire Richard Stokes. Accompanying Stokes was Sir Donald Fergusson, the influential Permanent Undersecretary at the Ministry of Fuel and Power, a consistent critic of Fraser. But Fergusson feared any deal would threaten every other British foreign investment: "It was British enterprise, skill and effort which discovered oil under the soil of Persia, which has got the oil out, which has built the refinery, which has developed markets for Persian oil in 30 or 40 countries." He called the fifty-fifty principle "bunk."
- Fergusson recognized that Mossadegh's real objective was "not better financial terms but to get rid of this foreign Company with its predominating influence out of Persia." The negotiations failed. "Mossadegh's stock-in-trade was fighting with the British. Any settlement of the dispute would end his political power." Harriman: "I am simply not used to failure. But then he had never before tried to do business with anybody like Old Mossy."

### "Stand Firm, You Cads!" — The Farewell to Abadan

- Operations at the oil fields and refinery ground to a halt. Britain mounted an embargo, threatening tanker owners with legal action for "stolen oil." Britain also embargoed goods to Iran and the Bank of England suspended financial and trade facilities. The Majlis passed a law making "sabotage or inattention" punishable by death. Eric Drake, Anglo-Iranian's general manager in Iran, was accused of such — he fled the country in a small plane and ran operations from Basra, then from a ship in the Gulf.
- Drake was summoned to Attlee's Cabinet (entering 10 Downing Street through a secret back passage). He told the Cabinet that if Britain did nothing about Abadan, "it would eventually lose much more, including the Suez Canal." Churchill, meeting Drake privately, growled: "You've got a pistol, Drake?" Drake had turned his in. "Drake, you can finish a man with a pistol. I know because I have."
- Secret military preparations were advanced — by September 1951, Abadan could have been seized in under twelve hours. But Attlee's government decided against force. "It would be humiliating to this country if the remaining British staff at Abadan were expelled."
- On September 25, 1951, Mossadegh gave the remaining British at Abadan one week to clear out. Ayatollah Kashani declared "a day of hatred against the British Government." At the refinery, British oil men and nurses put on a farewell revue called "Stand Firm, You Cads!"
- On October 4, the oil men and families gathered at the Gymkhana Club with fishing rods, tennis rackets, golf clubs, and dogs. The guest house lady had interdicted an Iranian tank commander three days earlier using only her umbrella. The parson locked the church that held records of births, baptisms, marriages, and deaths in Abadan.
- The British cruiser Mauritius carried them upriver to Basra. In a bizarre display of protocol, the ship's band played the Iranian national anthem. As the Mauritius steamed toward Basra, the band played "Colonel Bogey" and the passengers broke into a great chorus singing unpublished and obscene versions of the venerable military march. "With this musical burst of defiance, Britain bade good-bye to its largest single overseas enterprise, and the world's largest refinery, which now had virtually ceased to operate." The first of the great Middle Eastern oil concessions was the first to be summarily canceled.

### "A Splutter of Musketry" — Churchill Returns

- The British embargo removed a substantial amount of petroleum from world commerce during the Korean War. Rationing was imposed in parts of Asia; the US Petroleum Administration for Defense estimated that without Iran, world oil demand would exceed supply by end of 1951. But the momentum of postwar oil development supported the embargo — other countries (Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Iraq) increased production. By 1952, Iranian production had plummeted to just 20,000 barrels/day (from 666,000 in 1950), while total world production rose from 10.9 million to 13.0 million barrels/day — an increase more than three times Iran's total 1950 output.
- In October 1951, the Labour government fell. Churchill returned as PM at age seventy-seven, complaining "'my old brain' not working as it used to do." But he had firm ideas about Iran: the Labour government had been "too indecisive and too weak." Had he been in office, "there might have been a splutter of musketry but Britain would not have been kicked out of Iran." There was a grand irony — thirty-seven years earlier, as First Lord of the Admiralty, Churchill had purchased the government's stake in Anglo-Persian. Now he had lived long enough to head the government at the time of the company's greatest crisis.
- Foreign Secretary Anthony Eden had a special affinity with Iran — he had studied Oriental languages at Oxford, been a star student of Persian, and played a key role in solving the 1933 Reza Shah crisis over Anglo-Persian. He had kept up his Persian connections throughout.

### The Eisenhower Administration and the Coup — Operation Ajax

- Eden's personal connections to Iran made him keen to resolve the crisis. But Churchill's new government also considered force — Churchill told Truman that "if I had been in office it would not have come to this." The Americans counseled restraint but grew increasingly alarmed about communist infiltration. The Truman Administration tried one more diplomatic push in 1952, but Mossadegh rejected all proposals.
- The Eisenhower Administration took office in January 1953 with a harder line toward communism. The Dulles brothers — John Foster as Secretary of State and Allen as CIA Director — were receptive to British arguments that Mossadegh was leading Iran toward Soviet control. The British had developed Operation Boot; the Americans created a parallel plan, Operation Ajax, led by Kermit Roosevelt (grandson of Theodore Roosevelt), the CIA's top Middle East operative.
- The plan aimed to orchestrate a coup by rallying military officers, tribal leaders, and street mobs loyal to the Shah to topple Mossadegh. The Shah was reluctant and vacillating — his nerve had to be stiffened repeatedly. Kermit Roosevelt arrived in Tehran in mid-July 1953 under cover. The Shah finally signed two firmans (royal decrees) dismissing Mossadegh and appointing General Fazlollah Zahedi as Prime Minister.
- The first attempt at the coup on the night of August 15-16, 1953 went badly wrong. The officer sent to deliver the Shah's dismissal order to Mossadegh was himself arrested. Mossadegh's supporters and the Tudeh party took to the streets. They smashed and tore down statues of the Shah's father. The Shah himself took flight, first to Baghdad. He told the American ambassador there that "he would be looking for work shortly as he had a large family and very small means outside of Iran."
- The Shah's next stop was Rome, where he and his wife took up residence in a borrowed suite at the Excelsior Hotel. They had virtually no clothes, no retainers, and no money. The Queen wandered through shops without cash. The Royal Couple ate their meals in the hotel's public dining rooms and got their news secondhand from reporters. "Altogether, it was an excruciatingly anxious and nervous time at the Excelsior."
- On August 18, Undersecretary of State Walter Bedell Smith told Eisenhower that Operation Ajax had failed: "We now have to take a whole new look at the Iranian situation and probably have to snuggle up to Mossadeq if we're going to save anything there." But the next morning, the tide turned in Tehran. General Zahedi held a press conference distributing photostats of the Shah's dismissal order. A small pro-Shah demonstration grew into a vast, shouting crowd — "led by tumblers doing handsprings and wrestlers showing off their biceps and giant weightlifters twirling iron bars." The crowd swarmed out of the bazaars proclaiming hatred of Mossadegh and support for the Shah. Cars turned on headlights to show support.
- Key elements of the military rallied to the Shah. Soldiers and police sent to quell pro-Shah demonstrators joined them instead. Mossadegh fled over the back wall of his garden. Tehran now belonged to the Shah's supporters.
- At the Excelsior in Rome, a wire service reporter rushed up to the Shah: "Teheran: Mossadeq overthrown. Imperial troops control Teheran." The Queen burst into tears. The Shah turned white, then spoke: "I knew that they loved me." He returned in triumph. By the end of August 1953, the Shah was back on his throne, Mossadegh was under arrest, and the statues of the Shah's father were being re-erected.
- In the years following, debate continued over the real significance of Operation Ajax. Did it cost less than $100,000 or millions? Did the Western powers create the countercoup, or did they only lubricate it? Mossadegh's time was certainly running out; his base of support had greatly narrowed. What the CIA and MI6 did was play "the facilitating role, providing the financial and logistical aid, emboldening the opposition and making the critical connections, during uncertain and fluid times." Operation Ajax succeeded because it accorded with increasing popular support for the Shah and growing disillusionment with Mossadegh.
- Kermit Roosevelt reported directly to Eisenhower, who noted admiringly in his diary that Operation Ajax "seemed more like a dime novel than an historical fact."

### "A Group of Companies" — The Iranian Consortium

- With the Shah back in power, Iranian oil had to be brought back to market. Anglo-Iranian was hamstrung — taking the lead would only reignite nationalist fires. The British government was, as a Ministry of Fuel and Power official put it, "completely stumped."
- Washington would have to lead. The State Department retained Herbert Hoover Jr. as special representative to see if a new consortium of companies could take up Anglo-Iranian's interests. Hoover was the former President's son, an oil consultant who had helped devise the original fifty-fifty arrangement with Venezuela. He disliked the British, and the solution he pursued was the common American prescription: a consortium in which Anglo-Iranian was "camouflaged in the midst of a number of companies, several of them American."
- The American majors were far from enthusiastic. Their production elsewhere in the Middle East was building up rapidly. The Arab producers did not want their output reduced to make room for Iranian oil. The four Aramco partners had more than enough Saudi petroleum. A Jersey official recalled: "There was no assurance whatever that we wouldn't lose the whole thing within a few months again... It was touch and go as to whether or not the country would last." A Standard of California representative called it an "ouchy" situation.
- American officials found oil company executives difficult: "it is of critical importance to the success of any approach that oil men be handled most carefully and diplomatically. Oil officials seem overly sensitive to any indication that the industry isn't perfect... Emotion, pride, loyalty, suspicion make it difficult to penetrate to reason."
- Considerable diplomacy — and brute persuasion from Washington backed by London — went into getting the American oil men to go into Iran. Howard Page of Jersey later said: "If the U.S. and British governments hadn't really beat us on the head, we wouldn't have gone back." The State Department harped on one theme: if Iranian oil did not move, the country would collapse and fall into the Soviet camp, threatening the rest of the Middle East and all the concessions therein.
- Herbert Hoover Jr. told Sir William Fraser there was no alternative: "He who pays the fiddler gets to invite the guests to the ball." Fraser then wrote to the chairmen of the American majors, inviting them to London to discuss a consortium — a humiliating admission of defeat. A Jersey vice-president wrote to Secretary Dulles: "From the strictly commercial viewpoint, our Company has no particular interest in entering such a group but we are very conscious of the large national security interests involved."

### The Oil Cartel Case — Antitrust vs. Foreign Policy

- A massive obstacle loomed: the US government was bringing a giant antitrust case against the major oil companies — the very same companies it was seeking to push into the Iranian consortium. The Justice Department was busily gearing up a criminal suit against those companies for belonging to an "international petroleum cartel."
- Two contradictory strands of US public policy had collided: Washington would champion the companies to promote strategic and economic interests, but would also subject them to populist assaults against "big oil" for being greedy, monopolistic, and secretive. Never before had these two policies come into "such sharp and potentially paralyzing collision."
- The Federal Trade Commission had subpoenaed company documents in 1949, producing the most extensive analysis of international oil company relationships ever seen — titled The International Petroleum Cartel. One State Department specialist noted "its highly slanted and non-objective approach." It showed a fundamental blind spot: in the world of The International Petroleum Cartel, oil companies did not have to adapt to the will of governments.
- The State Department, Defense Department, and CIA were appalled by the FTC report. The White House Intelligence Advisory Committee warned it would "greatly assist Soviet propaganda." The Truman Administration classified it secret, but political pressure forced release to a Senate subcommittee. It became a subject of commentary on Radio Baku broadcasts to the Middle East.
- The Justice Department launched a criminal antitrust suit — the "As-Is conspiracy." The British government was outraged, calling it "stale bread" and the work of "witch-hunters." Britain ordered Anglo-Iranian and Shell not to cooperate. Foreign Secretary Eden called the FTC disclosures "extremely prejudicial to the national interest."
- The contradictions were stark: the State Department was trying to persuade the companies into an Iranian consortium while the Justice Department was preparing criminal conspiracy charges for exactly the kind of cooperation the State Department was promoting.
- Dean Acheson tried to call off Justice, flanked by Defense Secretary Lovett and General Omar Bradley. But Attorney General McGranery would not back off. The decision fell to President Truman, who knew something about oil — as a young man, he had been a partner in a wildcatting company that failed. A group that bought some of Truman's leases later struck a huge field; Truman sometimes mused he might have been an oil millionaire instead of President.
- Truman put his finger on Iran on a globe during a discussion about the Korean War: "Here is where they will start trouble if we aren't careful... If we just stand by, they'll move into Iran and they'll take over the whole Middle East." "They" were the Soviets. On January 12, 1953, Truman called off the criminal investigation, replacing it with a civil action.
- The Eisenhower Administration filed the civil case in April 1953. The National Security Council issued a directive that "the enforcement of the Antitrust laws of the United States against the Western oil companies operating in the Near East may be deemed secondary to the national security interest." In January 1954, both the Attorney General and the NSC provided explicit guarantees that the Iranian consortium "would not violate the anti-trust laws of the United States."

### Building the Consortium

- The consortium included Anglo-Iranian, the four Aramco partners (Jersey, Socony, Socal, Texaco), plus Gulf (Anglo-Iranian's Kuwait partner), Shell, and CFP. All seven were members of joint ventures producing oil elsewhere in the Middle East. During Iran's absence, production in neighboring countries had surged dramatically — output in the region would have to be "reined in" to make room for Iranian exports. Only by giving all seven companies a stake could their acquiescence be assured.
- Even before addressing Iran, the other producing countries had to be placated. The Aramco partners visited the aged King Ibn Saud just before his death, explaining they were joining the Iranian consortium "solely on the basis that there might be chaos out in the area if we didn't... as a political matter at the request of our government." Ibn Saud understood but warned: "In no case should you lift more than you are obligated to lift to satisfy the requirements of doing that job."
- Negotiations in Tehran were interminable — "issues and definitions and objectives were forever shifting." The Iranians could not be seen as compromising sovereignty. They feared another uprising and expulsion. At one point, the companies' team prepared to leave, though they left some members behind as "hostages."
- Howard Page of Jersey led a final push in June 1954. On September 17, 1954, Page and the Iranian Finance Minister initialed the agreement. The Shah signed it October 29, 1954 — three years after the British departure to "Colonel Bogey." Oil began flowing to waiting tankers. The first to pull away was the British Advocate, owned by Anglo-Iranian. Iran was back in the oil business.
- The consortium marked a great turning point: for the first time, the concept of foreign-owned concessions was replaced by negotiation and mutual agreement. Iran's National Iranian Oil Company would own all oil resources and facilities. But in practice, the consortium managed the industry, buying all output and marketing through their own systems.
- Anglo-Iranian held 40% of the consortium. Shell had 14%, each of the five American majors 8% initially, and CFP 6%. Soon after, each American company surrendered 1% to a new entity called "Iricon" — a "little consortium" of nine independent American companies (Phillips, Richfield, Standard of Ohio, Ashland, others). Their entry was insisted upon by the US government for political and antitrust reasons. Howard Page joked: "because people were always yacking about it, we had better put some independents in there." The British were furious: "We didn't know who the independents were... We didn't think they were reputable marketers."

### Loy Henderson's Prophecy and Anglo-Iranian's Compensation

- With the Iranian consortium established, the United States was now the major player in the volatile politics of Middle Eastern oil. Loy Henderson, American ambassador to Tehran, predicted in 1953: "It seems almost inevitable that at some time in the future... the Middle Eastern countries... will come together and decide upon unified policies which might have disastrous effects upon the operations of the companies." He warned: "Continuation and enhancement of the dependence which the West now places upon Middle Eastern oil might eventually place European consumers at their mercy."
- Anglo-Iranian came out surprisingly well from the turmoil. Fraser tenaciously pursued compensation, infuriating all other participants. The other companies paid Anglo-Iranian about $90 million up front for the 60% rights it was giving up, plus a ten-cent-a-barrel royalty on all consortium production until another $500 million had been paid. "It was a wonderful deal for Fraser, the best deal Willie Fraser ever made," said John Loudon of Shell. "After all, Anglo-Iranian actually had nothing to sell. It had already been nationalized."
- Mossadegh was put on trial, delivered impassioned speeches, spent three years in prison, then lived under house arrest for the rest of his days — "continuing his experiments with homeopathic medicines, much as he had done, three decades earlier, when the Shah's father put him under house arrest." Meanwhile, swelling oil revenues were transforming the insecurities of the young Shah into the pretensions of an assertive monarch with global aspirations.
- The antitrust case against the oil companies continued to grind on. The Attorney General's approval of the Iranian consortium had the effect of insulating joint production arrangements (like Aramco) from antitrust attack. The case was narrowed to downstream — marketing and distribution — resulting in the early 1960s breakup of Stanvac (Jersey and Socony's joint company in the Far East). Caltex (Socal and Texaco's joint European system) was dissolved for commercial reasons. It was not until 1968 that the American government finally folded its tent on the case — by then the consortium had been in business for almost a decade and a half.

## Chapter 24: The Suez Crisis

### The Canal and Its Strategic Importance

- The Suez Canal — a narrow waterway a hundred miles long, dug through the Egyptian desert to link the Red Sea to the Mediterranean — was one of the grandest achievements of the nineteenth century. It was the handiwork of Ferdinand de Lesseps, a Frenchman celebrated as "the Great Engineer." He was in fact no engineer at all, but a diplomat, entrepreneur, and promoter. At age sixty-four, he married a woman of twenty and fathered twelve children.
- Construction began in 1859; the canal was completed in 1869. The British were quick to recognize its value — it substantially reduced travel time to India, "the jewel of the empire." The Prince of Wales dubbed it "our highway to India." In 1875, Egypt's 44% ownership came on the market owing to the insolvency of the Khedive. With lightning speed and the timely financial assistance of the English branch of the Rothschilds, Prime Minister Benjamin Disraeli engineered the acquisition. He capped his efforts with a note to Queen Victoria: "You have it, Madam."
- The canal's greatest significance was strategic — the main highway and lifeline of the British Empire, linking England to India and the Far East. "Defense of the communications with India" became the fundamental rationale for Britain's security strategy. British forces were stationed permanently in the Canal Zone. At El Alamein in WWII, the British mounted their stand to defend the canal against Rommel.
- In 1948, the canal abruptly lost its traditional rationale when India became independent. But at the same moment, the canal was gaining a new role — as the highway not of empire, but of oil. The Suez Canal was the way most Persian Gulf oil got to Europe, cutting the 11,000-mile journey around the Cape of Good Hope to 6,500 miles. By 1955, petroleum accounted for two-thirds of the canal's traffic, and two-thirds of Europe's oil passed through it. Flanked by Tapline and the IPC pipelines, the canal was the critical link in the postwar oil industry.

### The Nationalist: Nasser

- Britain had exercised control over Egypt and the canal for three-quarters of a century. In 1952, a group of military officers carried out a coup, dispatching the sybaritic King Farouk to exile on the Riviera (where he acquired new renown for his many girlfriends and for being enormously fat). By 1954, Colonel Gamal Abdel Nasser had toppled General Naguib and emerged as undisputed dictator of Egypt.
- Son of a post office clerk and a born plotter, Nasser had begun anti-British maneuverings during WWII. A secret CIA profile concluded: "He gets boyish pleasure out of conspiratorial doings." He was a gifted student of Mohammed Mossadegh — he mastered the use of rhetoric and radio to inflame and mobilize the masses. He became the model for the military officer turned fiery nationalist leader in the emerging Third World.
- Nasser wanted to reach far beyond Egypt — across the entire Arab world. "The Voice of the Arabs" was his powerful radio station, beaming impassioned speeches calling for rejection of the West and threatening other Arab regimes. His program included pan-Arabism, elimination of the Israeli wedge, and the righting of what he called "the greatest international crime" — the creation of Israel.
- The Suez Canal — with ships guided by mostly foreign pilots in impeccable knee socks, shorts, and captain's hats — was an embarrassing symbol of nineteenth-century colonialism in the middle of Nasser's new Egypt. Most of the canal company's earnings from tolls went to European shareholders, including the British government. If Egypt could seize control, the tolls would open a major new source of income for a desperately poor country.
- The canal concession was due to expire in 1968, and British influence was already in retreat. In 1954, Eden negotiated the withdrawal of British troops within twenty months. In early 1955, Eden visited Cairo and startled Nasser by speaking — and telling Arabic proverbs — in Arabic.
- Nasser was viewed more tolerantly in Washington, where the Administration adopted an attitude of moral superiority toward European colonial powers. The Americans believed the relics of colonialism were an enormous handicap in the struggle with communism. The canal company chairman observed bitterly that to Americans, "the company had a certain musty, nineteenth century odor derived from that lamentable colonial period."

### The Aswan Dam and the Break

- Alarm about Nasser mounted in London and Washington in autumn 1955 when Nasser turned to the Soviet bloc for weapons. As early as February 1956, the State Department raised with oil companies the question of revising the Voluntary Agreement — originally used to manage the loss of Iranian oil — to allow cooperation in case the canal was closed. But companies found joint action unworkable because of the continuing antitrust threat. In April 1956, Standard Oil of New Jersey commissioned its own study of alternatives to the canal.
- British Foreign Secretary Selwyn Lloyd visited Nasser, who declared the Suez Canal was "an integral part of the Middle East oil complex, which was vital to Britain." Nasser replied that oil-producing countries received 50% of profits, but Egypt did not get 50% from the canal. If the canal was part of the oil complex, Egypt should have the same fifty-fifty terms as oil producers.
- At the end of 1955, the Americans, British, and World Bank had begun considering a loan to build the Aswan Dam on the Nile. But Nasser's Soviet arms deals had alienated Washington. American senators from the South were hostile (the dam would produce a competing cotton crop), and Congressmen friendly to Israel opposed aid to an antagonistic regime. Nasser had recognized "Red China." The coup de grace came when Senate Republicans told Dulles foreign aid could be approved for only one "neutralist" leader — Tito of Yugoslavia or Nasser. Dulles chose Tito. On July 19, 1956, Dulles canceled the Aswan Dam loan, taking Nasser and the World Bank by surprise.

### Code Word "de Lesseps" — Nasser Nationalizes the Canal

- Nasser was angry, humiliated, and eager for revenge. On July 26, 1956, he gave a speech in Alexandria where he had, as a boy, first demonstrated against the British. He repeatedly heaped calumny on the name of de Lesseps. "De Lesseps" was the code word to the Egyptian military to move; by the time the speech was completed, the army had seized control of the Canal Zone. The Suez Canal had been expropriated.
- Tension rose swiftly. Harold Macmillan, Chancellor of the Exchequer, wrote apprehensively: "There was last night and through today, the most violent gale I ever remember." In Cairo, Nasser slipped off to the Metro movie theater to see Cyd Charisse in Meet Me in Las Vegas.
- Three months of diplomatic circus followed. In mid-September, the British and French pilots who had guided ships through the canal were withdrawn. London and Paris assumed the Egyptians would not be able to run the canal. And indeed, considerable skill was required. But the Egyptian government had insisted for several years that Egyptians be trained as pilots, and a considerable cadre was ready. Assisted by Soviet bloc pilots, the nationalized canal continued to function more or less normally.
- The American position was confusing to the British and French. Eden and Dulles clashed in style and substance. Eden's principal private secretary wrote: "Foster talks so slowly that Master [Eden] does not want to hear what he has to say, while our man talks in so roundabout and elusive a style that the other, being a lawyer, goes away having failed to make the right guesses." Eisenhower found Dulles "not particularly persuasive in presentation and, at times, seems to have a curious lack of understanding as to how his words and manner may affect another personality."

### Eisenhower's Opposition to Force

- US policy was determined by Eisenhower. Force was neither warranted nor justified; the essence of policy was to prevent the British and French from intervening militarily. Eisenhower believed the two European countries could not establish a pliable government in Egypt that would survive. Any such attempt would arouse the entire developing world against the West and play into Soviet hands. He told Eden: "Nasser thrives on drama, and the best thing to do was to let the drama seep out of the situation." He told his own advisers that British thinking was "out of date," and that a military assault would surely turn Nasser into a hero.
- It was paramount to Eisenhower that the US not appear associated with sponsoring a return to colonial domination. After hearing one Eisenhower statement, Nasser joked to an aide: "Which side is he on?"
- Eisenhower was also up for reelection in November 1956 — he was running as a man of peace, and the last thing he wanted was a military crisis. In an appalling blunder, the British and French never really factored the American Presidential election into their calculations.

### "We Had No Intention of Being Strangled to Death"

- Both London and Paris were strongly motivated toward military intervention. The French saw Nasser as a threat to their position in North Africa — he was egging on and supplying Algerian rebels. They had already opened a military dialogue with Israel, which had its own reasons for striking at Nasser (arms buildup, guerrilla raids, blockade of Eilat).
- For Britain, oil was the jugular. Just before the canal's expropriation, Eden had told Soviet leaders Bulganin and Khrushchev: "I must be absolutely blunt about the oil... because we would fight for it." He added: "We could not live without oil and... we had no intention of being strangled to death."
- Britain's international finances were precarious — it had gone from the world's greatest creditor to greatest debtor. Gold and dollar reserves covered only three months of imports. Middle East oil holdings contributed mightily to total foreign earnings. A Nasser victory might have the same repercussions as a Mossadegh victory in Iran. Eden warned Eisenhower: "Nasser can deny oil to Western Europe and we shall all be at his mercy."
- Harold Macmillan thought exactly as Eden — convinced Britain was in a very dangerous position. In the first two weeks of the crisis, he managed to read through thousands of pages of novels (Jane Austen, Dickens, George Eliot, Thackeray, and more). "If he had not done all this reading, Macmillan later said, 'I'd have gone barmy!'" But he was as forceful as anyone in supporting action: "The truth is that we are caught in a terrible dilemma... 'If we take strong action against Egypt, and as a result the Canal is closed, the pipelines to the Levant are cut, the Persian Gulf revolts and oil production is stopped — then U.K. and Western Europe have 'had it.' Yet 'if we suffer a diplomatic defeat; if Nasser gets away with it' — and the Middle East countries 'nationalize oil'... we have equally 'had it.'"

### At the "Rhineland" Again — The 1930s Analogy

- Eden, Macmillan, French Premier Guy Mollet, and their colleagues were haunted by the 1930s. To all of them, Nasser was a resurrected Mussolini, even a nascent Hitler. Eden saw Nasser's Philosophy of Revolution as reading like Hitler's Mein Kampf — Nasser wished to carve out a great empire using the power of petroleum, "the vital nerve of civilization." Without petroleum, Nasser proclaimed, machines and tools of the industrial world are "mere pieces of iron, rusty, motionless, and lifeless."
- Eden had courageously resigned as Foreign Secretary in 1938 to protest appeasement of Mussolini and Hitler. The failure to act in time — the Rhineland in 1936, Munich in 1938 — haunted him. "We are all marked to some extent by the stamp of our generation, mine is that of the assassination of Sarajevo and all that flowed from it... Always a lap behind, the fatal lap."
- Mollet had been imprisoned at Buchenwald. Belgian Foreign Minister Paul Henri Spaak wrote to the British Foreign Secretary: "I do not wish to hide from you that I am haunted by the memory of the mistakes which were committed at the outset of the Hitler period."
- The analogies were less compelling in Washington. But contingency planning was underway — Eisenhower authorized a Middle East Emergency Committee to figure out how to supply Western Europe if the canal was blocked. The Justice Department granted limited antitrust immunity but not enough for a full joint supply operation.
- Standard Oil of New Jersey's study, commissioned in April, recommended a large-diameter pipeline from the Persian Gulf through Iraq and Turkey to the Mediterranean — cost half a billion dollars, four years to build.
- In September, Eisenhower warned Eden against "making of Nasser a much more important figure than he is." Sir Ivone Kirkpatrick, Permanent Undersecretary of the Foreign Office, sharply rejoined: "I wish the President were right. But I am convinced that he is wrong.... If we sit back while Nasser consolidates his position and gradually acquires control of the oil-bearing countries, he can, and is, according to our information, resolved to wreck us. If Middle East oil is denied to us for a year or two our gold reserves will disappear... And a country that cannot provide for its defense is finished."
- Robert Anderson, a wealthy Texas oil man and Eisenhower's personal emissary, made a secret trip to Saudi Arabia to pressure the Saudis to compromise. He warned King Saud and Prince Faisal that the US had made advances in energy "much cheaper and more efficient than oil, potentially rendering Saudi and all Middle Eastern petroleum reserves worthless." What might this substitute be? "Nuclear energy," replied Anderson. Neither King Saud nor Prince Faisal seemed impressed; they dismissed the warning.

### Force Applied — The Secret Plan at Sevres

- On October 24, 1956, senior British and French officials met secretly at a villa in Sevres, outside Paris, with top Israelis including David Ben-Gurion, Moshe Dayan, and Shimon Peres. The three nations agreed: Israel would launch a military strike across the Sinai toward the Suez Canal. Britain and France would issue an ultimatum about protecting the canal, and then invade the Canal Zone to "protect" it — with the ultimate objective of toppling Nasser.
- There was much closer understanding between Israel and France than between Israel and Britain. Eden himself, who had a fondness for Arabs, had said during WWII: "Let me murmur in your ear that I prefer Arabs to Jews." Macmillan, by contrast, thought Jews "had character." At Sevres, British Foreign Secretary Selwyn Lloyd treated the Israelis with what seemed like disdain. Britain had been considering coming to Jordan's aid against Israel — one reason the French took the lead at Sevres.
- The day before Sevres, Egypt and Syria set up a joint military command under Egyptian control. Jordan acceded the next day. On October 24 — the same day as the Sevres meeting — Red Army troops entered Budapest to put down the Hungarian revolution.
- Eden's medical condition was also a factor. In 1953, a careless surgeon had damaged his bile duct during a gall bladder operation, leaving Eden "with a largely artificial inside" and a tendency to become ill under pressure. He was on drugs for stomach pain and stimulants (apparently amphetamines) to counter the painkillers. In early October, he collapsed with a 106-degree fever. A British intelligence official confided to an American counterpart: "Chums in Downing Street tell me our old boy is feeling queer and is all nerves." Sometimes Eden would seek solace by gazing at a Degas bronze of a girl in a bath that film producer Sir Alexander Korda had given him.

### The Attack and Eisenhower's Fury

- Eisenhower had suffered a heart attack in 1955 and ileitis surgery in June 1956 — two of the three principal actors on both sides of the Atlantic were in poor health. A third would soon join them.
- On October 29, Israel launched its attack into the Sinai. On October 30, London and Paris issued their ultimatum and announced their intention to occupy the Canal Zone. The same day, Russian troops were withdrawn from Budapest with a promise of nonintervention. The next day, October 31, the British bombed Egyptian air fields, and the Egyptian Army began its retreat across the Sinai.
- The entire Suez operation came as a surprise to the Americans. Eisenhower first learned about the Israeli attack while on a campaign swing through the South. He was absolutely furious — Eden had betrayed him, his allies had deliberately deceived him. "They might inadvertently set off a far wider international crisis, involving a direct clash with the Soviet Union." And they had done so while America was preoccupied with the Presidential election, only a week away. Eisenhower was so angry that he called 10 Downing Street and personally gave Eden "unshirted hell" — or at least that is what he thought. In fact, he was in such a rage that he mistook one of Eden's aides for the Prime Minister himself, "and without waiting for the answerer to identify himself, the President dumped the diatribe on the hapless aide and then hung up before Eden could be summoned to the phone."
- On November 3, Dulles was rushed to the hospital with acute stomach cancer. With Dulles out, day-to-day control of US foreign policy rested with Undersecretary Herbert Hoover Jr. — regarded in London as antipathetic to the British.

### Nasser Blocks the Canal — Oil as Weapon

- There was a gap of several days before British and French troops could follow up their ultimatum — logistical problems, poor planning, and Eden's vacillation. Meanwhile, Nasser acted quickly: he scuttled dozens of ships filled with rocks, cement, and old beer bottles, effectively blocking the waterway and thus choking off the supply of oil — the very reason for the attack. Syrian engineers, on instructions from Nasser, sabotaged the pumping stations along the Iraq Petroleum Company pipeline, further reducing supplies.
- During months of planning, the British had always assumed the United States would step into any breach with American supplies. That assumption proved to be "a large and decisive mistake, no less a miscalculation than their inattention to the date of the Presidential election." Eisenhower refused to permit any emergency supply arrangements: "I'm inclined to think that those who began this operation should be left to work out their own oil problems — to boil in their own oil, so to speak." Petroleum would provide the way for Washington to punish and pressure its allies.

### Purgatory — The Ceasefire and Oil Crisis

- On November 6, Eisenhower won a landslide victory. That same day, the British and French agreed to a cease-fire; they had achieved only a foothold along the canal. Washington made clear that a cease-fire was not enough — they would have to withdraw, or face economic reprisals.
- Without American aid, all of Western Europe would soon be short of oil. Winter was coming, stock levels were only enough for several weeks. The normal route for three-quarters of Western Europe's oil was now interrupted by the combined loss of the canal and the Middle Eastern pipelines. Saudi Arabia instituted an embargo against Britain and France. In Kuwait, acts of sabotage shut down the supply system. When Harold Macmillan heard the US was considering oil sanctions, he threw his arms up: "Oil sanctions! That finishes it." On November 7, the British government announced consumption would have to be cut by 10%. Critics in Parliament declared that if ration coupons were issued, they should bear a portrait of Sir Anthony Eden.
- Eisenhower told the NSC on November 9 he would provide antitrust protection for a cooperative oil supply program — "Despite my stiff-necked Attorney General," he said with a smile. But he made emphatically clear that absolutely no emergency oil supply program would be put into effect until the British and French had actually begun to withdraw from Egypt. Europeans bitterly complained the US was "keeping them in purgatory."
- Britain was also economically vulnerable — an immense run on the pound started. The British strongly believed the run was carried out with the acquiescence, perhaps even instigation, of the Eisenhower Administration. The IMF, under American prodding, refused London's pleas for emergency financial aid. The British economics minister reported meeting a "brick wall at every turn" in Washington. The Americans, he added, "seem determined to treat us as naughty boys who have got to be taught that they cannot go off and act on their own without asking Nanny's permission first."
- Finally, at the end of November, London and Paris pledged swift withdrawal. Only then did Eisenhower authorize the Middle East Emergency Committee. The Americans "had earned the day." They had also added to the burden of defeat and humiliation the British and French had already suffered. Nasser was the only clear winner.
- Selwyn Lloyd visited the hospitalized Dulles at Walter Reed. A puzzling conversation ensued: "Selwyn, why did you stop? Why didn't you go through with it and get Nasser down?" Lloyd was flabbergasted — this was the same Secretary of State who had tried to head off Anglo-French action. "Well, Foster, if you had so much as winked at us we might have gone on." "He couldn't have done that," Dulles replied.

### The Oil Lift and the "Sugar Bowl"

- In December, the emergency Oil Lift finally swung into operation — a cooperative venture of governments and oil companies. Middle East oil production had not been interrupted; the problem was transportation. Tankers could transport twice as much oil from the Western Hemisphere as from the Persian Gulf via the Cape of Good Hope. The main focus was wholesale redeployment of tankers so that the Western Hemisphere would once again be the main supply source for Europe, as it had been up to the end of the 1940s.
- In Europe, the emergency supplies — known as "the sugar bowl" — were distributed equitably by the Organization for European Economic Cooperation (subsequently the OECD), which created a Petroleum Emergency Group. Belgium banned private driving on Sundays. France limited oil company sales to 70% of pre-Suez levels. Britain slapped new taxes on oil, leading to higher gasoline and fuel oil prices and a hike in London taxi fares immortalized as the "Suez sixpence." By the end of December, Britain was rationing gasoline.
- Western Hemisphere production had to increase substantially. The international companies scoured US crude markets for extra supplies. But the Texas Railroad Commission, to almost everyone's consternation, barely allowed any increase in production — basically keeping shut-in production shut in. The commission reflected the independent producers in Texas, "whose interests normally are wholly domestic." They feared a buildup of crude inventories would depress prices. Eric Drake of British Petroleum called it "nothing less than a calamity for Europe."
- Both Eden and Macmillan personally protested the Texas Railroad Commission's policies. The Daily Express declared: "No Extra Oil — Say Texas Wise Men." Commissioner Colonel E. O. Thompson replied: "We have already shipped her many barrels of crude, but we only get criticism for not going all out at her bidding. England apparently still looks on us as a province or dominion."
- Eventually, Humble (Jersey's Texas affiliate) raised the price it paid for oil by thirty-five cents a barrel. Additional crude became available and the Oil Lift surged. But soon the companies were accused of collusion to raise prices. The price increases led to Congressional hearings (2,800 pages) and a new antitrust prosecution of twenty-nine oil companies by the Justice Department. The case was eventually thrown out in 1960 — a Federal judge ruled there was "economic justification" for the price increases.
- The Oil Lift involved tremendous coordination and logistical dexterity, drawing on experience from the Allies' WWII Atlantic oil supply system. One oil company executive tried to explain how misleading it was to believe that "all you had to do is push a button and everything is all right. It was an admonition that should have been kept in mind for future crises."

### The Crisis Resolved

- By spring 1957, the oil crisis was ending. Almost 90% of lost supplies had been compensated for. Conservation measures and warm weather made up much of the rest. Overall, the European economy was not as vulnerable as it would later become — in 1956, oil was only about 20% of total energy consumption; Europe was still primarily a coal economy.
- In March 1957, the Iraq Petroleum pipelines were partly reopened. By April, the Suez Canal had been sufficiently cleared. Nasser had won — the canal now unequivocally belonged to and was operated by Egypt. The Egyptian Suez Canal pilots, while they did not dress as crisply as their British and French predecessors, were quite adequate to the navigational task. Kuwait's production had dropped by half owing to the inability to transport oil. In April, the American government suspended the Oil Lift. In mid-May, Britain terminated gasoline rationing. The Suez crisis was really over.

### The Exit of "Sir Eden"

- One American participant remembered the crisis as "a curious time, those Suez months. There was high comedy, low conspiracy, and deep tragedy — for individuals and for nations." It constituted a huge personal tragedy for Anthony Eden — whom Nasser called "Sir Eden" — who had until then amassed an extraordinary record of prescience, courage, and diplomatic skill, but whose reputation was "to be ignominiously scuttled with the ships that Nasser sent to the bottom of the canal."
- In November, while the crisis still raged, Eden's ill health forced him to take a long vacation in Jamaica, in a house loaned to him by Ian Fleming, the creator of James Bond. On his return, doctors told him his health would not allow him to function as Prime Minister. He described himself as "so unrepentant... I find it strange that so few, if any, have compared these events to 1936 — yet it is so like." In January 1957, he resigned.
- Macmillan was summoned to succeed him. Macmillan wrote in his diary of seeing Eden on that sad winter afternoon, "still looking so youthful, so gay, so debonair — the representative of all that was best of the youth that had served in the 1914-1918 War." Stunned, Macmillan walked back to the Chancellor's residence. The next morning, he sat under a portrait of Gladstone, reading Pride and Prejudice to soothe his soul, until interrupted by a phone call asking him to come to the Palace to be invested as Prime Minister.
- Suez was a watershed for Britain. It did not presage Britain's decline; rather, it made obvious what had already come to pass. Britain no longer belonged to the top echelon of world powers. Years later, the Times of London said of Eden: "He was the last prime minister to believe Britain was a great power and the first to confront a crisis which proved she was not. It was as much an epitaph for an empire and a state of mind as for a man."

### Pipelines Versus Tankers — The Supertanker Solution

- After Suez, the oil companies were no longer confident they could rely on the canal. Pipelines were also vulnerable — Syria had shown that during the crisis. The safer alternative was the route around the Cape of Good Hope, but that required much larger tankers.
- The general view in 1956 was that such tankers could not be constructed. But Japanese shipyards, taking advantage of advances in diesel engines and better steels, were soon proving otherwise. John Loudon of Shell recalled: "In 1956, the tanker people were saying larger ships would be too expensive, their fuel costs too high. The amazing thing to me was how quickly these tankers were being manufactured by the Japanese." Supertankers, along with the decline of British influence and the ascendancy of Nasser, were among the consequences of the Suez Crisis. "Tankers clearly were less subject to political risk."

### Healing the Suez Schism — The Bermuda Conference

- Much bitterness remained between the Americans and the British/French. The British ambassador in Washington described Eisenhower as having "the American boy scout views about colonialism, the United Nations and the effectiveness of phrases as act of policy." But both sides recognized the need to heal the rift.
- The new Prime Minister Harold Macmillan, known for his "unflappability" (though internally he "suffered from agonies of nervous apprehension"), had worked with Eisenhower during WWII and maintained friendship. Macmillan was a realist: after Suez, it was the "rulers in Washington, in whose hands all our destinies largely lay."
- At the Bermuda Conference in March 1957, oil and Middle Eastern security were major subjects. Macmillan called Middle Eastern oil "the biggest prize in the world" and urged cooperation for long-term peace. They discussed promoting supertankers. The British emphasized maintaining the independence of Kuwait and the Gulf states, all vulnerable to Nasserite coups.
- The Bermuda Conference helped close the schism. Eisenhower and Macmillan agreed to write privately to each other weekly. But as Suez had demonstrated, in the years ahead it would be America, not Britain, whose power would predominate.
- In 1970, fourteen years after the Suez Crisis, Edward Heath became PM and arranged a dinner at 10 Downing Street for Lord Avon (as Anthony Eden had become). Eden rose to respond impromptu and offered a special prayer for the British people — "that they might discover 'a lake of oil' under the North Sea. That was exactly what they were just beginning to do in 1970." How different things might have been in 1956 had the British known of, or even suspected, the existence of such a lake.

## Chapter 25: The Elephants

### The Era of Giant Discoveries

- In the parlance of the oil industry, a giant oil field is called an "elephant." By the early 1950s, the tally of elephants in the Middle East was lengthening rapidly. In 1953, Everette DeGolyer wrote to F. E. Wellings, IPC's chief geologist, that his company had just found three elephants in three successive months. "The Middle East is rapidly getting into a condition which has been almost chronic in the United States since the earliest days of the industry, that is, the problem becomes market rather than production." DeGolyer's firm was finishing a secret study for the Saudi government; he knew reserves would far dwarf earlier estimates. "They are so great that adding a billion barrels or so makes no real difference in the oil available."
- From the early 1950s to the end of the 1960s, the world oil market was dominated by extraordinarily rapid growth — "a tremendous surge that, like a powerful and somewhat frightening undertow, swept everyone in the industry forward with its seemingly irresistible force." Free world crude oil production increased from 8.7 million barrels/day in 1948 to 42 million barrels/day in 1972. US production grew from 5.5 to 9.5 million, but America's share slipped from 64% to 22%. The Middle East grew from 1.1 million to 18.2 million barrels/day — a 1,500% increase.
- Proven world oil reserves increased from 62 billion barrels in 1948 to 534 billion in 1972 — almost a ninefold rise. American reserves grew from 21 billion to 38 billion, but their statistical significance shrank from 34% to a mere 7% of world reserves. The Middle East had increased from 28 billion to 367 billion barrels. Out of every ten barrels added to free world reserves between 1948 and 1972, more than seven were found in the Middle East.
- In 1950, the industry estimated proven reserves at current production rates would last nineteen years. By 1972, after all the years of rapid consumption growth, the estimated reserve life was thirty-five years — reserves were being found even faster than oil was being consumed.

### The Postwar Petroleum Order — Two Foundations

- The postwar petroleum order rested on two foundations. One was the great oil deals of the 1940s, establishing relationships among companies in the Middle East — mobilizing resources for rapid development, tying production to refining and marketing systems. The second was the concessional and contractual relationships between companies and governments, at the heart of which was the fifty-fifty profit-sharing arrangement.
- Neither the major companies nor the consuming country governments wanted to budge from fifty-fifty. The British Middle East Oil Committee said in late 1954: "A reasonable basis has now been reached for a partnership between the oil companies and the Middle East Governments.... Any further encroachment... would seriously damage our oil supply system." But producing countries saw it differently — why not increase revenues if they could?

### The Shah's Ambition and the Search for an Interlocutor

- By the mid-1950s, the Shah of Iran had moved past his earlier insecurities, declaring in private that "It was Iran's destiny to become a great power." He wanted more oil income and greater independence from the consortium. But he could not afford to upset basic foreign relations. He needed an interlocutor from outside the ranks of the majors and the American independents in the consortium. The answer: a European, an Italian — Enrico Mattei.

### A New Napoleon — Enrico Mattei and ENI

- Enrico Mattei was determined to create a new major — Italy's state-owned AGIP — cast in his own image. He was a bold swashbuckler, a condottiere. The stocky hawk-featured Mattei had the look of a fervent but worldly Jesuit of the sixteenth century — dark somber eyes under high arching eyebrows, thin hair combed straight back. He was willful, ingenious, manipulative, and suspicious, with a talent for improvisation and a propensity for gambling and taking risks.
- The unruly son of a policeman from northern Italy, Mattei left school at fourteen to work in a furniture factory. By his early thirties, he ran his own chemical plant in Milan. During WWII, he became a partisan leader (Christian Democrats). After the war, his skills led to his being entrusted with AGIP — Azienda Generali Italiana Petroli — which Italy had created in the 1920s (following France's example) as a state-owned refining company. AGIP had attained a market share in Italy roughly commensurate with Esso and Shell, but outside Italy it counted not at all.
- Mattei set about transforming AGIP with "a great burst of energy and a masterly grasp of politics, Italian-style." The requisite money came from the Po Valley, where discovery and development of significant natural gas reserves generated high earnings funding both AGIP's expansion and its overseas ambitions.
- In 1953, the various state hydrocarbon companies were gathered into ENI — Ente Nazionale Idrocarburi — a sprawling conglomerate with thirty-six subsidiaries ranging from crude oil and tankers to gasoline stations, real estate, hotels, toll highways, and soaps. The US embassy in Rome reported with wonder in 1954 that ENI "has found itself in the unique position of being financially solvent, capably led, and responsible to no one other than its leader." ENI's future would be "profoundly shaped by the limitless ambition evidenced in the person of Enrico Mattei."
- Mattei became a popular hero, the most visible man in Italy — embodying antifascism, national resurrection, and the self-made "new man." He also became the most powerful man in Italy. ENI owned the newspaper Il Giorno, subsidized politicians from far left to right, and financed the Christian Democrats. "To deal with a government," Mattei would complain, "is like sucking needles." One aide recalled: "Anybody who worked with him would go into the fire for him, although you couldn't really explain why."
- Mattei came to London for a lunch with John Loudon, the senior managing director of Royal Dutch/Shell. Loudon, with apparent innocence, asked Mattei how he had gotten into oil. Mattei, flattered to be taken seriously at the heart of the major, talked nonstop through the entire lunch telling his whole life story. "Finally, when we went to dessert, he asked us for something. We couldn't do it, and that was the end of the conversation." It was not the last they would hear from Mattei.

### Mattei's Greatest Battle — Breaking the Fifty-Fifty

- Mattei's overriding objective was to ensure ENI had its own international petroleum supply, independent of the "Anglo-Saxon" companies. He loudly attacked the "cartel" — the major companies — and was credited with coining the term "Sette Sorrelle" (the Seven Sisters): Jersey (Exxon), Socony-Vacuum (Mobil), Socal (Chevron), Texaco, Gulf, Royal Dutch/Shell, and British Petroleum. Actually there was an eighth sister — CFP — but since CFP didn't fit the "Anglo-Saxon" rubric, Mattei conveniently dropped it.
- Mattei had tried to win membership in the Iranian consortium. He believed his cooperation with the embargo after Mossadegh's nationalization had earned him a place. But Italy was excluded. He was furious and looked for opportunity — and revenge.
- The 1956 Suez Crisis put the established companies on the defensive and showed the retreat of British power in the Middle East. Mattei would step forward to fill the vacuum. His anticolonial rhetoric matched the nationalistic fervor of the exporting countries.
- Mattei began talking to the Shah. If the majors used corporate intermarriages through joint ventures, Mattei would go one better — thinking dynastically, he floated the idea of marrying off an Italian princess to the Shah, who was in urgent need of a male heir. One legacy of Mossadegh's nationalization gave the Shah flexibility: the Iranian government owned all oil resources in the ground, unlike other Middle Eastern countries where the concessionaires still owned the reserves.
- Over the spring and summer of 1957, Mattei hammered out a wholly unprecedented arrangement. Under the deal, Iran's National Iranian Oil Company would be ENI's partner as well as its landlord — in practice, Iran would get 75% of profits to ENI's 25%, breaking the treasured fifty-fifty arrangement. "As J. Paul Getty and others had already found, it cost more to get into the game when you were a latecomer."
- The companies were appalled. The Americans and British protested to the Shah, warning that upsetting fifty-fifty would "seriously prejudice the stability of the Middle East" and threaten oil supplies. The Italian Foreign Ministry's own Secretary General, resentful of Mattei's power, secretly advised the British to take a tough line — any accommodation with Mattei would be seen "as a sign of weakness."
- All objections were to no avail. By August 1957, Mattei had signed the deal. The British ambassador in Tehran, who rode his horse over to the Italian summer embassy and came upon Mattei "sitting under a tree, relaxing with a whiskey and soda, happily celebrating his victory," reported that Mattei "certainly uses bold strokes and a big brush on a wide canvas."
- To his inner circle, Mattei expressed perplexity: "They've given us two tiny places in Iran, and everybody makes a great noise." The ENI-Iran partnership did not work out commercially — no significant oil was found. But Mattei achieved his larger purpose: "the fifty-fifty principle had been pierced, much weakening the foundation on which, he believed, the power of the 'Seven Sisters' had rested." The British embassy in Tehran reported: "But in fact we all know that 50/50 is about as dead as the four minute mile. And as inevitably."

### Japan Enters the Middle East

- Japan was acutely oil-sensitive, beginning its extraordinary economic climb with almost total dependence on imports. The Suez Crisis made Japan even more nervous. In spring 1957, a consortium of Japanese companies pursued a concession for the area offshore from the Saudi-Kuwaiti Neutral Zone.
- The idea had emerged by chance on a train ride in Italy, where a Japan Development Bank employee met a Japanese businessman with Middle Eastern oil contacts. Back in Japan, Taro Yamashita — an entrepreneur who had made a fortune building rental homes in Manchuria before WWII — seized on the idea, assembled the Arabian Oil Company, and won the Japanese government's backing. None of the participating companies had any significant oil industry experience.
- The Japanese agreed to take only 44% of profits, leaving the Saudis with 56%. The Saudis also had the right to acquire equity. The Kuwaitis then insisted on 57%. Arabian Oil started drilling offshore in July 1959 and made its first discovery in January 1960. Japan's MITI made refiners take the oil proportionally. By the mid-1960s, Arabian Oil was providing almost 15% of Japan's total supply.

### "Even the Americans..." — Standard of Indiana in Iran

- Others wanting to enter the Middle East would have to pay a higher price and observe the new precedents — even American companies. Standard Oil of Indiana had long regretted selling its Venezuelan production to Jersey during the Great Depression. In the late 1950s, Indiana went overseas, telling stockholders to seek "opportunities for profitable operations wherever they may exist."
- An agreement was swiftly made with Iran in 1958, along Mattei's seventy-five-twenty-five lines, plus a very large up-front bonus. The Shah opened their first meeting with a surprising lecture: "You know — we are not Arabs. We are Aryans, and we are the same race as you are, and we have a great history. We have great pride." "Oh, yes," replied Indiana's chairman, "we know, Your Majesty."
- Unlike ENI, Indiana found a great deal of oil — beginning with a great offshore field south of Kharg Island named Darius (for the ancient Persian King), to flatter the Shah. The Shah remarried soon after and had a male heir. His "continuity" now seemed assured.

### Nasser Ascendant and the Iraqi Revolution

- Nationalism was building to a crescendo across the Middle East, with Nasser as its driving force. Suez had proven a Middle Eastern country could triumph not only against "imperialistic" companies but also against the might of Western governments. A notable technological innovation — the cheap transistor radio — was carrying his rousing Voice of the Arabs to the poor masses everywhere.
- In 1958, the Soviet Union provided funding for the Aswan Dam. Syria joined Egypt to form the United Arab Republic. The apparent merger brought together the Suez Canal and the Syrian pipelines — Nasser was theoretically in a position to choke off most Middle Eastern oil transit.
- In July 1958, Nasser's propaganda war against Iraq's British-backed Hashemite monarchy came to its terrible culmination. Officers plotting a coup told their troops the far-fetched story that they had been ordered to march to Israel and surrender their weapons. The coup set off an explosion of violence and savagery. Crowds surged through the streets holding aloft huge photographs of Nasser and live squirming dogs representing the Iraqi Royal Family. King Faisal II was beheaded by troops who stormed the palace. The Crown Prince was shot, his hands and feet hacked off and carried on spikes through the streets. The pro-Western PM Nuri es-Said was recognized trying to flee disguised as a woman, was lynched, and a car was driven back and forth over his body "until it was flattened almost beyond recognition."
- The new Baghdad government demanded vast revisions in the IPC concession. The grisly coup sent shudders through every government in the region; Nasserism seemed destined to reign supreme.

### Arab Oil Experts and the Road to Organization

- Oil was a central focus of rising Arab nationalism. Since the early 1950s, meetings among "Arab Oil Experts" had been taking place. Initially the dominant subject was the oil blockade against Israel. Over time, the agenda broadened — Nasser used these meetings to shape public opinion on sovereignty, "colonialism," and his influence over Gulf oil. It was a case of a "have not" (Egypt had no oil exports) seeking to better his position with the "haves." Abdullah Tariki of Saudi Arabia declared: "Oil is the strongest of weapons the Arabs wield."
- At a 1957 conclave in Egypt, delegates proposed building domestic refining capacity, an Arab tanker fleet and pipeline, and creating an "international body" or "international consortium" to manage Middle Eastern oil production and counterbalance the power of the petroleum companies. Talk of a producers' organization remained inchoate — it needed participation from non-Arab producers, particularly Venezuela and Iran. And it would require the catalytic role of one man: Juan Pablo Perez Alfonzo.

### Juan Pablo Perez Alfonzo — The Prophet of OPEC

- In 1948, shortly after codifying fifty-fifty, the democratic government in Venezuela was overthrown. Control passed to Colonel Marcos Perez Jimenez's brutal dictatorship. Under Jimenez, oil production doubled by 1957. When the dictatorship collapsed in January 1958, Romulo Betancourt returned as President. He had been an eloquent critic of the oil companies, whose "close identification with the dictatorship" had turned Venezuela into "a petroleum factory that represented a throwback to the dark days of the Gomez dictatorship."
- Betancourt and his colleagues had learned from 1948: the need for broad democratic coalitions. They had to contend with assaults from both right and left, including communist guerrillas, and much anti-American sentiment. In 1958, VP Richard Nixon nearly was hurt or killed when an enraged mob attacked his motorcade entering Caracas. In 1960, Betancourt's own car was bombed in an assassination attempt. Despite grievances, Betancourt and his colleagues were "not impractical romantics." The man to whom Betancourt turned on oil was Juan Pablo Perez Alfonzo.
- Perez Alfonzo was "a man of iron determination... and yet soft-spoken and almost monastic." Born to a well-to-do Caracas family, he studied medicine at Johns Hopkins then law in Caracas. When the family lost its money, he became responsible for his 10 brothers — an experience that made conservation and planning central to his character.
- Working with Betancourt, Perez Alfonzo became the opposition's expert on oil. As Minister of Development from 1945, he repaired the 1943 law to ensure Venezuela truly got 50% of profits. After the 1948 coup, he was jailed (later joking to his family that "jail was like a holiday"). In exile in Washington, D.C., he and his family scraped by on rents from their Caracas house. He became a regular at the Library of Congress, studying everything about the oil industry — from Forbes and Fortune to Oil and Gas Journal. He devoted particular time to the Texas Railroad Commission, which fascinated him as the institution that had stabilized oil production in the US.
- After several years in Washington, he moved to Mexico City (fearing his children would become too Americanized). When the dictatorship fell in 1958, Betancourt insisted Perez Alfonzo return as Minister of Mines and Hydrocarbons. He was struck by how much more affluent Caracas looked — and his response was not altogether favorable. Oil wealth, he believed, was "the gift of nature and politics, and not of hard work," with pernicious consequences.
- While in exile, the family had bought a 1950 Singer motorcar. When Perez Alfonzo returned to Venezuela, the car was shipped to him but sat at the docks rusting for two months because nobody told him. A mechanic drove it up to Caracas, but the engine burned out because nobody checked the oil. The corroded car was delivered to his villa. Perez Alfonzo viewed it all as a sign from heaven — "he had the car installed near a ping-pong table in his garden, as a corroded, overgrown shrine and symbol of what he saw as the dangers of oil wealth — laziness, the spirit of not caring, the commitment to buying and consuming and wasting."
- Once back in office, Perez Alfonzo kept a simple, parsimonious life — carrying sardine sandwiches for lunch. His objectives were clear: increase the government's share of rents, and transfer power and authority over production from the oil companies to sovereign governments. Oil was a national heritage belonging to future generations; selling it too cheaply was bad for consumers (premature exhaustion of a nonrenewable resource) and producers (discouragement of new development). "Human nature should not be allowed to squander the potential of this precious resource."
- Perez Alfonzo was also motivated by shrewd commercial judgment. Venezuela was a relatively high-cost producer at about 80 cents/barrel vs. 20 cents for Persian Gulf producers. In an out-and-out production race, Venezuela would inevitably lose market share. Venezuela thus had a very good reason to persuade Middle Eastern producers to raise their taxes — and to establish a global alliance modeled on the Texas Railroad Commission. A common front, by regulating production and allocation, would prevent Venezuela from being swamped by millions of barrels of cheap Middle Eastern oil.

### US Import Quotas and Venezuela's Fury

- The Eisenhower Administration's reluctant decision in early 1959 to impose quotas on foreign oil hit Venezuela harder than any other country — the US was the destination of 40% of its total exports. To placate neighbors, the US exempted overland oil from Canada and Mexico on "national security" grounds. To the Venezuelans, this was a convenient fiction — "The Americans are throwing us the bones," Perez Alfonzo acidly said.
- Bitterly complaining, Perez Alfonzo flew to Washington proposing a Western Hemisphere oil system run by governments, not companies — with Venezuela guaranteed a quota share of the US market (modeled on the American sugar quota system). The US was not interested; the government in Caracas was insulted. Perez Alfonzo would seek a more attentive hearing elsewhere — in Cairo.

### The "Red Sheikh" — Abdullah Tariki

- Abdullah Tariki, a Saudi Arabian, was the son of a camel owner. His intelligence was noted early; he was sent to school in Kuwait, then spent a dozen years studying in Cairo (where he imbibed Nasserism). A scholarship carried him to the University of Texas, where he studied chemistry and geology and worked as a trainee geologist with Texaco. His view of America was shaped in Texas, where on several occasions he was excluded from bars and facilities because he was taken for a Mexican.
- In 1948, he returned to Saudi Arabia — virtually the first American-educated Saudi technocrat, the first Saudi trained in geology and chemistry. He also had an American wife. In 1955, at age thirty-five, Tariki was appointed to head a newly created Directorate of Oil and Mining Affairs. He created a team of experts — including an American lawyer and a young Saudi technocrat, Hisham Nazir — and prepared to challenge not only Aramco but the Western oil companies themselves.
- Tariki was an odd combination — an ardent Nasser supporter and fervent Arab nationalist critical of the Saudi Royal Family, yet a servant of that same family in the single most important economic position in the kingdom. Known as the "Red Sheikh," Tariki's position resulted from a power struggle between King Saud (erratic, weak, spendthrift) and his younger brother Faisal (shrewd, coldly calculating). With so much energy focused on this struggle, Tariki was able to shape oil policy with considerable autonomy.
- At first, Tariki concentrated on gaining control over refining and marketing — wanting to create a Saudi company integrated "right down to the service station." He would even raise the idea of outright nationalization of Aramco. But in early 1959, his strategy abruptly changed — control over prices and production became more important than nationalization and integration. The reason: a sudden cut in the price of oil.

### Competitive Pressures — The Posted Price Gap

- While world oil demand was growing during the 1950s, production capacity was growing still more rapidly. More oil was in search of markets than there were markets for oil. Companies were forced to offer bigger and bigger discounts on the prices at which they sold their Middle Eastern oil.
- A crucial divergence was emerging between the "posted" or official price (held constant, against which the producing country's taxes and royalties were computed) and the actual market price (which was dropping). The posted price was supposed to match the market price, but as discounting spread, a gap appeared. The producing countries continued to take 50% of profits based on the posted price — meaning the companies absorbed all the effects of discounting. By the late 1950s, the posted price was a fictional price. The producing countries were actually taking 60 or 70% of the profit realized from the actual price, while Middle Eastern governments were being kept whole.
- The problem of discounting became more acute from 1958 onward. US import quotas closed off the largest oil market in the world to rapidly rising production outside the US. Those additional barrels had to fight their way into a less-than-global market.

### The Soviet Oil Offensive

- An even more important reason for discounting was the arrival of the Soviet Union as a major new entrant in the world oil market. Between 1955 and 1960, Soviet oil output actually doubled. By the end of the 1950s, the USSR had displaced Venezuela as the second-largest oil producer in the world, with output equal to about three-fifths of total Middle Eastern production.
- From 1958 onward, Soviet exports surged, becoming "a force to be reckoned with in the international petroleum field," said the CIA. The Soviets wanted whatever buyers they could obtain, cutting prices as part of what became known in Washington as the "Soviet Economic Offensive." Allen Dulles, CIA director, warned in 1958: "The free world faces a quite dangerous situation in the Soviet capacity to dislocate established markets."
- Russian oil could be picked up in Black Sea ports at about half the posted price of Middle Eastern oil. The most prominent buyer of Russian oil was none other than Enrico Mattei of ENI — the companies' number-one bete noire.
- The companies' competitive response was price cuts. But could they dare cut the posted price as well, so that producing countries would share the burden? In early 1959, British Petroleum made the first cut — eighteen cents a barrel, about a 10% reduction. It instantly set off a torrent of denunciation. Perez Alfonzo was outraged. Tariki was furious. "With a stroke of the pen, a major oil company had unilaterally slashed the national revenues of the oil producers."

### The Arab Oil Congress and the Maadi Yacht Club — The Gentlemen's Agreement

- An Arab Oil Congress had been scheduled for Cairo in April 1959. Four hundred people attended, including Tariki. Perez Alfonzo — angry about BP's price cut, the American import quotas, and Washington's rejection of his Western Hemisphere scheme — came as an "observer," with a Venezuelan delegation carrying texts of oil legislation translated into Arabic.
- Iraq notably boycotted the conference (the new Baghdad regime did not want to subordinate itself to Nasser). BP sent observers who reported the conference was "remarkably friendly" and could be "marked off as a 'plus' for the oil industry's future relations with the Arab host countries."
- But BP also tried private diplomacy through "Miss Wanda Jablonski of Petroleum Week," who arranged a meeting with Tariki. Unfortunately, BP's representative was "subjected to a diatribe on the inequity of oil production in Kuwait with its population of a few hundred thousand growing more rapidly than production in Saudi Arabia with its many millions of under-privileged."
- Wanda Jablonski was the most influential oil journalist of her time — correspondent of Petroleum Week and later editor of Petroleum Intelligence Weekly. Blonde and stylish, she was born in Czechoslovakia, daughter of a prominent botanist turned geologist. She had traveled by camel from Cairo to Jerusalem and been schooled in New Zealand, Egypt, England, Morocco, Germany, Austria, and Texas. "I have a different attitude towards the world. I can't fit in any one spot, except New York."
- In 1956, Jablonski even wrangled an invitation to interview King Saud in Riyadh — and spent an evening in the King's harem ("drinking tea with rose water, eating dinner, and having a perfectly gay 'hen party'"). She met Abdullah Tariki, whom she described as "the No. 1 man to watch in the Middle East." At a second meeting years later, she also passed him a critical piece of information: "There's another guy who's just as nuts as you — Juan Pablo Perez Alfonzo." She promised to bring them together.
- At the 1959 Arab Oil Congress in Cairo, Jablonski kept her word. She invited Perez Alfonzo to her room at the Cairo Hilton for a Coke and introduced Abdullah Tariki. "You're the one I've been hearing so many things about," said Perez Alfonzo. The two men agreed to talk secretly with representatives from other major exporters. They reconvened at an off-season, virtually deserted yacht club in Maadi, a suburb of Cairo.
- The discussions were conducted in great secrecy — "We met in a James Bond atmosphere," the Iranian participant later said. Those involved: Perez Alfonzo, Tariki, a Kuwaiti, an Iranian (who kept insisting he had no mandate and was only an observer), and an Iraqi (there as an Arab League official, since Iraq was boycotting the conference). The Iranian was so frightened of acting without authorization from the Shah that he disappeared, and the Cairo police had to be called to find him so he could sign.
- The Gentlemen's Agreement reflected Perez Alfonzo's ideas: their governments should establish an Oil Consultative Commission, defend the price structure, and establish national oil companies. They urged jettisoning fifty-fifty and moving to at least sixty-forty in their favor. They should build up domestic refining, move downstream, and become more integrated. "In all its dimensions, the Gentlemen's Agreement, though secret, was a milestone in the changing dynamics of the petroleum industry." As for Wanda Jablonski — "she had just been the matchmaker for an alliance that would develop into the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries — OPEC."

## Chapter 26: OPEC and the Surge Pot

### The Soviet Threat and the Second Price Cut

- The surplus of oil continued to mount. Further discounts off the posted price followed, driven by aggressive Soviet marketing — slashing prices and making barter deals. Many in the West believed the Soviet petroleum campaign was not just commercial but "also a political assault, the purpose of which was to create dependence in Western Europe, weaken the unity of NATO, and subvert the Western oil position in the Middle East." Senator Kenneth Keating said: "Khrushchev has threatened to bury us on more than one occasion. It is now becoming increasingly evident that he would also like to drown us in a sea of oil."
- Russian oil could be picked up at about half the posted price of Middle Eastern oil. The most prominent buyer was Enrico Mattei's ENI.

### T Square Versus Slide Rule — The Jersey Board Debate

- In July 1960, fifteen months after the first price cut, the board of Standard Oil of New Jersey met to consider the vexing question of the posted price. The new chairman, Monroe Rathbone ("Jack"), was a no-nonsense man whose life was practically a textbook of the American oil industry. Both his father and uncle had been Jersey refiners in West Virginia. Rathbone studied chemical engineering and worked at Jersey's Baton Rouge refinery, where he developed political skills fending off Huey Long. "He was self-confident, decisive, unemotional, and uninterested in small talk. A colleague described him as 'an engineer with a T Square.'" The great drawback was that his entire career had been domestic — he did not intuitively grasp the changing mentality of foreign oil producers. "Money is heady wine for some of these poor countries, and some of these poor people," he once said.
- Jersey was managed by a committee system — the "Standard Committee Company of New Jersey" — intended to forestall precipitous decisions. But Rathbone had "the kind of determination that takes an awful lot of evidence to break down." Preoccupied with gaining markets amid the glut, Rathbone was determined to overwhelm the committee system and force a cut in the posted price.
- Howard Page, Jersey's expert Middle East negotiator and the man who had put together the Iranian consortium, vigorously disagreed. "He was a very tough man... He always had a slide rule on his lap, so that he could calculate down to the last half cent on a barrel. But he was also a man of some vision, and was very well able to understand other people's vision." Page grasped the explosive force of nationalism and feared his colleagues did not.
- Page arranged for Wanda Jablonski to brief the Jersey board. She told them there was "almost universal adulation for Nasser among all classes, and a hostility towards the west that had deepened markedly." She warned the existing structure of IPC and Aramco might prove to be "short-lived." At a separate meeting, Rathbone vehemently disagreed with her disquisition on nationalism. "You never got beneath the surface," Jablonski replied tartly. "Jack, do yourself a favor. You got the red carpet treatment, you were there only a few days. You'd be wiser if you didn't make those statements."
- Page argued against cutting the posted price — it would be cutting the countries' national revenues. He made a motion that any cut be effected only after consultation and agreement with the governments. The other directors backed the motion. But Rathbone was the chairman. He privately dismissed Page as "a know-it-all" and decided Jersey would go ahead unilaterally.
- On August 9, 1960, with no direct warning to the exporters, Jersey announced cuts of up to fourteen cents a barrel in posted prices of Middle Eastern crudes — about a 7% reduction. The other companies followed suit. John Loudon of Shell called it "the fatal move. You can't just be guided by market forces in an industry so essential to various governments. You had to be so terribly careful." BP, which had learned its lesson from its 1959 cut, complained it "heard the news with regret."
- The reactions went far beyond "regret." The producing countries were outraged. "All hell broke loose," recalled Howard Page. Another Jersey executive, in Baghdad when the cut was announced, was "glad to get out alive."

### "We've Done It!" — The Founding of OPEC

- Within hours of Jersey's August 1960 price cut, Abdullah Tariki telegraphed Perez Alfonzo, then hurriedly departed to Beirut. When asked what would happen, he replied: "Just wait." Tariki and Perez Alfonzo wanted to bring the signatories of the Cairo Gentlemen's Agreement together as quickly as possible.
- In the maelstrom of anger, the Iraqis recognized a political opportunity. The revolutionary government of Abdul Karim Kassem had no wish to subordinate itself to Nasser. By using the price cut as catalyst to establish a new organization of oil exporters (including non-Arab countries, Iran and Venezuela), they could isolate oil policy from Nasser. They also hoped such a grouping would bolster them in their confrontation with IPC. Iraq quickly dispatched invitations to meet in Baghdad.
- When the telegram from Baghdad reached Perez Alfonzo's office in Caracas, "he was exultant. Here were the makings of the international 'Texas association' that he so ardently advocated. 'We've done it!' he declared excitedly to his aides as he held the telegram aloft. 'We've achieved it!'"
- Shell tried to offer an olive branch on September 8, 1960, raising posted prices by two to four cents. Too little, too late. By September 10, representatives of Saudi Arabia, Venezuela, Kuwait, Iraq, and Iran had arrived in Baghdad. Qatar attended as an observer. The omens were not good — Perez Alfonzo had to delay his departure from Caracas owing to an attempted coup. Baghdad was filled with tanks and armed soldiers; armed guards were posted behind each delegate during discussions.
- Yet by September 14, the group had completed its work. A new entity was established: the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries — OPEC. It made its intention clear: to defend the price of oil (more precisely, to restore it to its precut level). Member countries would insist the companies consult them on pricing matters. They also called for "regulation of production" — Tariki's and Perez Alfonzo's dream of a worldwide Texas Railroad Commission. And they committed to solidarity in case the companies sought to impose "sanctions" on any one of them.
- OPEC's five founding members were the source of over 80% of the world's crude oil exports. OPEC's creation represented "the first collective act of sovereignty on the part of the oil exporters," in the words of Fadhil al-Chalabi, later OPEC Deputy Secretary General — "the first turning point in the international economic relations towards the states' control over natural resources."

### The Companies Dismiss OPEC

- Yet despite the rhetoric, the newly created OPEC did not seem very threatening or imposing. The companies did not take it seriously. "We attached little importance to it," said Howard Page. "We believed it would not work." Fuad Rouhani, the Iranian delegate to the founding conference and OPEC's first Secretary General, observed that the companies "initially pretended that 'OPEC did not exist.'" Western governments paid scant attention. In a secret forty-three-page CIA report on "Middle East Oil" in November 1960, two months after OPEC's founding, the CIA devoted a mere four lines to the new organization.

### OPEC in the 1960s — Limited Achievements

- OPEC could claim only two achievements in its early years. First, the companies would not dare cut the posted price again — they became cautious about any unilateral step without consultation. Second, OPEC had so little to show for its first decade because in all member countries (except Iran), the oil reserves actually belonged by contract to the concessionaires. The world oil market was overwhelmed with surplus, and the exporting countries were competitors who had to worry about holding on to markets.
- The 1960s saw decolonization and "Third World" questions. But sovereignty issues in oil subsided as companies met exporter demands for higher revenues by pushing up production. Broader political factors helped: in Saudi Arabia, King Faisal was now firmly in charge, oriented toward the West. Saudi Arabia and Egypt were engaged in a proxy war in Yemen. Venezuela was pursuing a stable relationship with the US through the Alliance for Progress.
- Political rivalries within OPEC were considerable. In 1961, when Kuwait became independent, Iraq claimed ownership and threatened invasion — backing off only after Britain dispatched a military squadron. Iraq temporarily suspended its OPEC membership. Iran and Saudi Arabia, the two major producers, looked upon each other with apprehension and envy — one was Arab, the other not; one Sunni, the other Shia. Each wanted to be the regional leader and the top oil producer. The Shah wanted revenues increased as fast as possible through selling more oil, not through holding back production and raising prices. He called international prorationing "nice in theory but unrealistic in practice."
- Abdullah Tariki had aligned himself with King Saud. When Faisal won the power struggle, Tariki was fired in 1962 and replaced by the young legal adviser Ahmed Zaki Yamani — who had no particular attachment to the idea of an international Texas Railroad Commission. Tariki spent the next decade and a half in itinerant exile, advising other petroleum countries and denouncing the oil companies as a journalist and polemicist.
- Perez Alfonzo, OPEC's other father, grew disillusioned with politics and with OPEC itself. He resigned in 1963, saying his mission had been to bring the oil producers together. He retreated to his villa in Caracas to read and study philosophy, managing his gardens. He no longer talked about "sowing the oil" — instead calling petroleum "the excrement of the devil." He kept the rusted Singer automobile in his garden as monument to the waste of oil wealth. "I am an ecologist first of all," he said shortly before his death in 1979. "Now I am not interested in oil any more. I live for my flowers. OPEC, as an ecological group, has really disappeared."
- The oil companies strenuously sought to avoid direct negotiations with OPEC. "Our position was that we owned the concessions, and we would deal with the countries in which the concessions were located," recalled a major company executive. OPEC continued through the 1960s to be, as another executive put it, a sideshow: "The reality of the oil world was U.S. import quotas, Russian oil exports, and competition." What loomed was the dizzying growth in demand and even dizzier growth in supply. "It seemed that OPEC's moment to mount an effective challenge to the power of the major oil companies had passed — or would never come."

### "The New Frontier" — Africa and More Elephants

- Almost as soon as OPEC was established, its member countries lost their near-total grip on world oil exports. New oil provinces were found and opened up in the 1960s, adding to supplies and swamping the market.
- Africa was the "new frontier." France took a lead, drawing on Clemenceau's WWI declaration that oil was "the blood of the earth." De Gaulle ordered a maximum drive to develop oil within the French empire. A new group of state companies, under the Bureau de Recherches Petroliers (BRP), explored in the empire. Oil was discovered in Gabon in West Africa.
- In North Africa, despite much skepticism (the Sorbonne's most prominent geology professor announced he was so sure there was no oil in the Sahara "that he would happily drink any drops of oil that happened to be found there"), Regie Autonome des Petroles (RAP) began exploration and in 1956 discovered oil in Algeria. The "Sahara" became a magical word in France — "France's answer to Germany's Ruhr." De Gaulle himself visited the Saharan oil fields in 1957: "Here is the great opportunity for our country that you have brought into the world. In our destiny, this can change everything."
- Getting the oil out was very difficult — fields deep in the desert, the simplest things trucked hundreds of miles across roadless wastelands. By 1958, oil was flowing from the Sahara. But Algeria was caught in a bloody war for independence (begun 1954). When Algeria won independence in 1962, the Evian Agreement guaranteed France's position in Saharan oil. By 1961, French state companies were producing oil equivalent to 94% of French demand. RAP and BRP merged in 1965, eventually becoming Elf-ERAP (later simply Elf) — one of the largest oil companies and one of the biggest industrial groups in the world.
- Shell and BP had begun exploration in Nigeria in 1937, finally hitting oil in the swampy Niger delta in 1956. But nothing anywhere would compare to the phenomenon that unfolded in Libya.

### The Libyan Jack-Pot

- During WWII, Rommel's forces had fought in Libya, chronically short of fuel — neither side knowing they were fighting at times only a hundred miles from one of the world's great reserves of oil.
- Libya after WWII was a very poor country whose leading exports were esparto (a grass for making currency paper) and scrap metal scavenged from rusting WWII tanks and weaponry. At the top of its rickety political system sat old King Idris, who "did not really like being king" — he actually wrote a resignation letter once. By the mid-1950s, growing geological suspicion led to the Libyan Petroleum Law of 1955, which provided for many smaller concessions (instead of the vast concession areas of the Persian Gulf). "I did not want Libya to begin as Iraq or as Saudi Arabia or as Kuwait... I didn't want my country to be in the hands of one oil company," explained the Libyan petroleum minister. Libya gave many concessions to independent companies that had no other oil production to protect, so they would explore and produce as fast as possible.
- Working conditions were primitive — no telephones to the outside world, and an estimated three million unexploded WWII land mines. Geologists and oil field workers were "not infrequently injured or killed." Some of the Germans who had laid the mines for Rommel were recruited to remove them.
- Early exploration results were disappointing. BP was beginning to dispose of its supplies and villas in preparation to exit. Then, in April 1959, at a spot called Zelten about a hundred miles south of the Mediterranean coast, Standard Oil of New Jersey made a big strike. The State Department summed it up: "Libya has hit the jack-pot." Ironically, Jersey had nearly given Libya a pass — it already owned 30% of Aramco, was in IPC, the Iranian consortium, and was the largest producer in Venezuela.
- By 1961, ten good fields had been discovered. Libyan crude was very high quality — "sweet" (low-sulfur), refining into a high proportion of gasoline and other light, "clean" products, perfect for Europe's growing automobile fleets and the dawning age of environmentalism. Libya was perfectly located — a quick, secure jaunt across the Mediterranean to European refineries, no need for the Suez Canal or the Horn of Africa route. By 1965, Libya was the world's sixth-largest oil exporter (10% of all petroleum exports). By the end of the 1960s, it was producing over three million barrels per day, and in 1969 its output exceeded Saudi Arabia's.
- Corruption pervaded the Libyan business environment — "nickeled and dimed to death," said one executive. "The pressures came from all kinds of places." The family running the royal household was "particularly well known for its interest in extremely large gratuities."
- The vast surge of Libyan oil dramatically affected world prices. In Libya, more than half the production was in the hands of independent companies that had no other outlets and no reason for restraint. Shut out of the American market by import quotas, they sold aggressively into Europe at whatever price they could get. Between 1960 and 1969, the market price of oil fell by 36 cents a barrel — a 22% drop (correcting for inflation, a 40% decline). "Oil was available for anybody, anytime, any place and always at a price as low as you were charging for it," recalled Howard Page. "I have never seen such a competitive market. The market was just falling on its face."

### Mattei's Last Flight

- As Mattei turned ENI into a world force — taking on the established companies, the US government, and NATO — he intended to link his Mediterranean-based pipeline system to the westward-marching Soviet system, bartering Italian pipe for Russian oil. But he was also working toward a compromise with Jersey and other majors, and preparing to meet President Kennedy.
- On October 27, 1962, Mattei took off from Sicily in his private jet. The only other passenger was Time magazine's Rome bureau chief, researching a cover story. They never made it to Milan — the plane crashed in a terrible thunderstorm, about seven miles short of the runway at Linate Airport.
- Much speculation followed — had Western intelligence services sabotaged his jet? The French Secret Army Organization? It is more likely his death was an accident — Mattei was always in a rush, his impatient personality "would not permit a storm to deter him from landing." He had often pushed his reluctant pilot through Milanese weather.
- At the time of his death, Mattei was fifty-six and at the height of his empire. The NYT foreign affairs columnist called him "the most important individual in Italy, more important than either the premier in Rome or the Pope in the Vatican." It was said he was more responsible than any other man for "the Italian Miracle." ENI's headquarters in Rome was named "Piazza Enrico Mattei." ENI and AGIP continued to grow — but without Mattei, "ENI's buccaneer days as the world's number-one maverick oil company were over."

### The New Competitors — Proliferation of Players

- Though Mattei was gone, he had instigated a revolution that would eventually overthrow the majors' global dominance. The history of international oil was one in which "newcomers" continually broke in on the established order. But up until the 1950s, newcomers could usually be accommodated. That possibility ended in 1957 with Mattei's deal, the Japanese Neutral Zone venture, and the frenetic activity in Libya.
- The explosion in the number of players was remarkable: in the Middle East, 9 oil companies operated in 1946; by 1956, 19; by 1970, 81. Between 1953 and 1972, more than 350 companies entered or significantly expanded their foreign oil activities. Among them: 15 large American oil companies, 20 medium-sized American companies, 10 large American natural gas/chemical/steel companies, and 25 non-American firms. By 1972, at least thirteen "new internationals" each owned more than 2 billion barrels of foreign reserves. Altogether, they owned 112 billion barrels — a quarter of the free world total — with daily output of 5.2 million barrels.
- One obvious result was a decline in profitability. Through the mid-1950s, foreign oil investment had earned above 20%. After the reopening of Suez in 1957, intense competition forced both prices and profits down. Through the 1960s, investment in foreign oil yielded 11 to 13% returns — about the same as manufacturing industries.

### Walking the Tightrope — Iran Versus Saudi Arabia (The "Surge Pot")

- The global battle of production intensified the Iran-Saudi Arabia rivalry. The major companies were in a political quandary — they had to balance supply against demand while newcomers kept adding production, which meant restraining output in the Persian Gulf. The Gulf became the stabilizer, the "swing area" or "surge pot," the control mechanism for balancing global supply and demand. Allocating growth between Iran and Saudi Arabia was hardly easy — "This is like a balloon... Push it in one place, it comes out in another, and so if we acceded to all those demands, we would get it in the neck," said Howard Page.
- The rivalry created enormous problems for the major companies, who were partners in both countries. Jersey, Mobil, Socal, and Texaco were the four Aramco partners — nothing should jeopardize the Saudi concession. But Iran was potentially the dominant power, and the Shah had to be placated. "Nobody could have lifted enough crude to satisfy all the governments in the Persian Gulf during this period," said George Parkhurst of Socal. The tightrope-walk meant allocating growth so neither government felt the other was getting a better deal.
- Between 1957 and 1970, Iranian production grew by 387%, compared to Saudi Arabia's 258%. But because Saudi Arabia had started from a larger base, the two countries' absolute outputs were within 5% of each other in 1970. The high-wire balancing act had, despite running controversies, succeeded.
- The Shah told LBJ at a 1964 White House luncheon that oil companies would give preferential treatment to Arab producers. OPEC, the Shah added, had become "an instrument of Arab imperialism." He told his old friend Kermit Roosevelt that he was "tired of being treated like a schoolboy" by the US. The special relationship between Iran and America, he warned, "is coming to an end." He made a gas deal with Moscow and threatened to reorient Iranian imports toward the Soviet Union. The Shah's tactics worked — both governments urged the oil companies to "do their best" to meet Iranian demands.
- For this achievement, the companies owed a considerable debt to radical Iraq. At the beginning of the 1960s, Iraq revoked 99.5% of the IPC concession, leaving it only the region where it was actually producing. IPC ceased investing in new exploration, and Iraqi output — which could have surged along with Iran's and Saudi Arabia's — only edged up gradually.
- Jersey's Howard Page recommended against entering Oman because he could imagine what Yamani would say if Aramco had to restrain Saudi output to make room for a new neighboring concession. Jersey stayed out; Shell took the lead. Oman became a significant producer. "I am absolutely sure we don't want to go into it," Page had said. "I might put some money in if I was sure we weren't going to get oil, but not if we are going to get oil because we are liable to lose the Aramco concession."

### "Us Independent Oil Suckers" — The Import Quota Fight

- Consumers worldwide welcomed cheap oil from Venezuela and the Middle East — except in the United States, where independent American producers saw the flood of imported oil as a dangerous threat. As early as 1949, an irate Texas geologist named "Tex" Willis wrote to his Senator Lyndon B. Johnson asking if he was "going to be able to do anything for us independent oil suckers on that foreign oil that has destroyed the market for two billion dollars worth of Texas independent oil this year?"
- Oil state representatives sought to raise tariffs tenfold and limit imports to 5% of domestic consumption. Truman opposed: "Something must be radically wrong with the reasoning of the people who would like to cut off our foreign trade for the benefit of the oil crowd." After the Korean War, petroleum imports made further inroads. Coal-producing and oil-producing states formed an unlikely coalition to limit imports.
- Eisenhower first tried "voluntary" restrictions, then a more formal system of voluntary controls in 1957. But companies with large foreign commitments were uncooperative — including Getty, who had embarked on a $600 million expansion program based on Neutral Zone oil. Eventually, in early 1959, Eisenhower reluctantly imposed mandatory import quotas through the Mandatory Oil Import Program (MOIP), the protectionist system that would endure for fourteen years.
- The program was defended as essential to national security — protecting domestic production capacity. Its critics called it a subsidy to domestic producers that cost consumers billions per year. Eisenhower himself had suggested an alternative: a government stockpile of cheap foreign oil in exhausted wells. Nobody supported the idea — the special committee he appointed rejected it as "simply too impractical." (This was essentially the concept of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, which would be created nearly two decades later.)

### "A Very Healthy Domestic Industry" — The Import Quotas in Practice

- The quotas lasted for fourteen years. Under Eisenhower, imported oil could not exceed 9% of total consumption. The Kennedy Administration tightened them slightly in 1962. The Johnson Administration made some effort to relax them to counteract Vietnam War inflation. But essentially, the quota system remained intact.
- Oil import quotas sounded simple but became increasingly Byzantine — fights over allocations, searches for loopholes, and ever-more-intense hunts for exceptions and exemptions. A brisk market developed not in oil itself but in "tickets" or rights to bring in oil. One notorious loophole was the "Mexican Merry-Go-Round" or "Brownsville U-Turn": since "overland" oil from Mexico qualified for exemption, Mexican oil was shipped by tanker to Brownsville, Texas, put into trucks, driven across the bridge into Mexico, around a traffic circle, and back across the bridge into Brownsville — where it was reloaded onto tankers. Thus shipped "overland," it perfectly legally qualified for an exemption.
- The program made domestic US oil prices higher than they would have been without protection. The average wellhead price in 1959 was $2.90/barrel; a decade later, $2.94 — stable, but 60-70% above Middle Eastern crude in East Coast markets. Conversely, by closing off the American market, mandatory controls resulted in lower prices outside the US.
- Despite the complications, the quotas achieved their fundamental goal: ample protection for domestic production against cheaper foreign oil. By 1968, US crude output was 29% higher than in 1959. Without that protection, American production would surely have plateaued or declined. The majors, despite initial opposition, eventually came to see merit in a program that protected domestic profitability.
- The mandatory program taught the international companies a lesson about political power. Senator Russell Long of Louisiana delivered a homily to oil company executives: "We would like you fellows that produce oil overseas to realize this, that when problems come up with regard to your tax credit overseas or even your depletion allowance overseas, or the special tax treatment to your employees that you have overseas, the fellows you are going to rely upon to protect your activities in that respect are the same people who are interested in the domestic production of oil." In short: "It is very much to your advantage to have a very healthy domestic industry and do everything within your power to cooperate to that end." The international companies grudgingly absorbed the lesson.

## Chapter 27: Hydrocarbon Man

### The Explosion of Oil Consumption

- Whatever the twists of global politics, one trend following WWII progressed in a straight and rapidly ascending line — the consumption of oil. "If it can be said, in the abstract, that the sun energized the planet, it was oil that now powered its human population, both in its familiar forms as fuel and in the proliferation of new petrochemical products. Oil emerged triumphant, the undisputed King, a monarch garbed in a dazzling array of plastics." It was the Age of Hydrocarbon Man.
- Total world energy consumption more than tripled between 1949 and 1972. But oil demand increased more than five and a half times over. Between 1948 and 1972: US consumption tripled (5.8 to 16.4 million barrels/day); Western Europe increased fifteen times over (970,000 to 14.1 million barrels/day); Japan increased 137 times over (32,000 to 4.4 million barrels/day).
- The drivers: rapid economic growth and rising incomes. By the end of the 1960s, populations enjoyed a standard of living far beyond imagining just twenty years before. People bought houses, electrical appliances, central heating, air conditioning. Motor vehicles in the US increased from 45 million in 1949 to 119 million in 1972. Outside the US, the increase was even more monumental — from 18.9 million to 161 million vehicles.
- The petrochemical industry transformed oil and natural gas into plastics and a host of chemicals. In the 1967 film The Graduate, an older man confided the secret of success to a young man: "Plastics." The secret was already everywhere evident.
- Oil prices fell through the 1950s and 1960s, becoming very cheap, which encouraged consumption. Governments promoted oil use for economic growth and modernization. Exporting countries wanting higher revenues pushed production up, giving companies impetus to find new markets.
- The industry became elephantine in every aspect. New refineries were built ever larger for economies of scale. New technologies increased the yield of high-value products — gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, heating oil — from less than 50% to 90% of a barrel of crude. Tanker fleets multiplied; conventional tankers gave way to supertankers. Gasoline stations popped up everywhere. American automobiles, powered by huge engines and bedecked with chrome and extravagant tail fins, grew longer and wider, getting all of eight miles to a gallon of gas.

### Old King Coal Deposed

- In the buoyant decades after WWII, a war was being fought — buried in the day-to-day trade press — between coal and oil for the hearts, minds, and pocketbooks of the consumer. Paul Frankel called it "a war of movement." It was a great historical transformation.
- Coal had powered the Industrial Revolution. Economist W. S. Jevons wrote in the nineteenth century that coal "stands not beside but entirely above all other commodities. It is the material energy of the country, the universal aid, the factor in everything we do." King Coal held on through the first half of the twentieth century — but could not withstand the great tidal wave of petroleum.
- Oil was environmentally more attractive, easier to handle, and became cheaper than coal. In the US, the coal industry's own cost structure made it a sitting duck. There was also a compelling reason: labor strife. Strikes by coal miners, led by John L. Lewis's combative United Mine Workers, were virtually an annual ritual. Lewis's fiery rhetoric and militancy constituted "a powerful invitation to find a substitute for coal." A Venezuelan oil man mused: "We ought to take up a public subscription throughout Venezuela to erect a statue of John L. Lewis in the central square in Caracas — to honor him as one of the greatest benefactors and heroes to the Venezuelan oil industry."
- In Britain, the first postwar energy crisis (1947) was a severe coal shortfall. The government encouraged power plants to switch to oil as a stopgap — but oil was hardly a stopgap; it was a relentless competitor. After Suez, Britain pushed ahead with nuclear energy and discussed emergency oil stockpiles, but security concerns dissipated quickly. Part of oil's victory over coal in Britain was environmental — London's "Killer Fogs" from coal burning were so thick motorists could not find their streets. "Smokeless zones" were established; the 1957 Clean Air Act favored oil. From 1958 onward, oil was cheaper than coal as an industrial fuel. The coal industry responded with an advertising campaign around the "Living Fire" — but when it came to heating homes, "coal was a dying ember."
- By the mid-1960s, the British government concluded that rapid oil growth was needed for international competitiveness. "Oil has become the lifeblood of the economy, as of all other industrialized countries, and it affects every part of it."
- The pattern repeated across Western Europe. By 1960, France committed to rationalization and contraction of its coal industry and a wholesale switch to oil. Keynes had once said "the German empire was built more truly on coal and iron, than on blood and iron." But Germany too converted. In 1955, coal provided 75% of total energy in Western Europe, petroleum just 23%. By 1972, coal had shrunk to 22%, while oil had risen to 60% — almost a complete flip-flop.

### Japan: No Longer Poor

- Japan was somewhat slower to shift to oil. Coal was its traditional energy source. Refineries and oil infrastructure had been devastated in WWII. Not until 1949 did the American Occupation permit reestablishment of oil refining, under the tutelage of Western companies. In 1956, Japan made an epochal declaration: "We are no longer living in the days of postwar reconstruction."
- At the beginning of the 1950s, coal provided more than half of Japan's total energy, and oil only 7% — less than firewood. But oil prices kept falling. By the beginning of the 1960s, the government and industry bet on oil. MITI restructured the petroleum industry to ensure independent Japanese refiners gained substantial market share against Western majors. A 1962 oil law gave MITI authority over import permits and sales allocation.
- In the second half of the 1960s, while the Japanese economy grew at an extraordinary 11% per year, oil demand was growing at an even more extraordinary 18% per year. By the end of the 1960s, oil provided 70% of Japan's total energy, compared to 7% at the beginning of the 1950s.
- The Japanese automotive revolution also drove demand. In 1955, Japan produced only 69,000 cars; by 1968, 4.1 million — 85% bought and used domestically. The great auto export boom, which would establish Japan as a formidable global economic power, had yet to begin.
- The economic historian Alfred Chandler summed up the recipe for the postwar German and Japanese miracles: "improved institutional arrangements and cheap oil." On a global basis, coal had provided two-thirds of world energy in 1949. By 1971, oil, along with natural gas, was providing two-thirds. What Jevons had said in the nineteenth century about coal was now true for oil: "It stood above all other commodities; it was the universal aid, the factor in almost everything we did."

### The Struggle for Europe

- Because of rapid economic growth, the switch from coal to oil, and the advent of the popularly priced automobile, Europe was the most competitive oil market in the world in the 1950s and 1960s. With US protectionist quotas limiting imports, all American companies that had gone overseas to discover oil had to find other markets — which meant Europe. Producing nations kept up pressure to increase volume. "Each year our people made an annual pilgrimage to Kuwait City," said Gulf executive William King. "It was universally the same. It would be a difficult meeting, with lots of threats and blandishments on both sides."
- Companies could not simply buy land and put up a gasoline station in Europe — governments exerted tight controls on allocating locations. "Competition was horrendously intense in Europe because the amounts of money involved were so great," said King. "The people from the different companies would speak politely to each other and act friendly, and then we'd all go out and try to steal each other's markets."
- Shell, the leading European marketer, was on the defensive. Deutsche Shell trained 220 young salesmen in "American-style aggressive selling." Jersey tried to build its relative position; in Britain, stations would often carry pumps for six different brands — Jersey wanted Esso-only stations.
- Among the agile Davids was Continental Oil (later Conoco). Its president Leonard McCollum had been Jersey's worldwide production coordinator. He went overseas in the 1950s, drilled dry holes in Egypt and Africa, but struck it big in Libya with the Oasis Group (a partnership with Marathon and Amerada). Import quotas precluded bringing cheap Libyan oil into the US, so Continental built its own downstream refining and distribution system in Western Europe and Britain under the "Jet" brand name. By 1964, Continental was producing more overseas than in the US.
- The multiplication of such companies, each more or less autonomous, increased competitive pressures and pushed oil prices further down. Their success would also stir up nationalist sentiment in the countries that supplied their oil. "In short, the companies were most vulnerable at the extreme ends of the production chain, the wellhead and the pump."

### Courting the Consumer — Gasoline Wars and Gimmicks

- The American gasoline consumer was riding high in the 1950s and 1960s. Gasoline stations sprouted on every corner, and frequent "price wars" broke out — operators rushing hand-lettered signs to the edge of the property proclaiming prices half a cent less than across the street. The majors did not particularly like price wars — they adopted a "we were forced" attitude — but would sometimes initiate them when breaking into new markets.
- Never had motorists been better served. Tires and oil were checked, windows washed, drinking glasses and sweepstakes entry forms handed out — all for free. Credit cards were introduced in the early 1950s to tie customers to particular companies. Television provided a whole new medium for advertising. Texaco reached beyond its Metropolitan Opera radio fans with the Texaco Star Theater and Milton Berle, urging millions of viewers to "Trust Your Car to the Man Who Wears the Star." Texaco also proudly assured patrons it had gone so far as to "register" all its restrooms throughout the forty-eight states.
- There was the great hullabaloo over gasoline additives. In the mid-1950s, thirteen of the top fourteen marketers began selling new "premium" gasolines with extravagant claims. Richfield proclaimed its gasoline "uses hydrogen for peace" — technically true since all hydrocarbons contain hydrogen. Shell claimed its TCP (tricresyl phosphate), meant to reduce engine deposits, was such a wonder fuel that the Air Force had classified it a military secret — forcing Shell to offer its additive to all comers. Socony countered that TCP was actually harmful and would damage engines. An FTC investigation was launched. The "additives war" was not quite as serious as an oil war, but was a fair reflection of the intensity of competition.

## Chapter 28: The Hinge Years: Countries Versus Companies

### The Persepolis Celebration

- In October 1971, the Shah of Iran staged what Time magazine called "one of the biggest bashes in all history" at Persepolis, the ancient Persian capital sacked by Alexander the Great in 330 B.C. Three huge tents and fifty-nine smaller ones were erected on the desolate site. Assembled dignitaries included the President of the Soviet Union, the Vice-President of the United States, Marshal Tito of Yugoslavia, twenty kings and sheikhs, five queens, twenty-one princes and princesses, fourteen other presidents, three other vice-presidents, three premiers, and two foreign ministers.
- The Shah publicly communed with the ghost of Cyrus the Great, the empire's founder, and promised to continue his tradition. The jeweled guests were taken up the hill for a stunning son et lumiere under the stars — dramatizing, strangely enough, Alexander's destruction of Persepolis.
- The Iranian government urgently sought top-secret advice from Britain on seating protocol — the Foreign Office in London designed a specially constructed table with undulating curves so no one would be too far from a Pahlavi family member.
- The Shah invited Queen Elizabeth II, but she was committed to a state visit in neighboring Turkey, which infuriated him. He asked for Prince Charles — unavailable, on naval duty. London offered Prince Philip and Princess Anne. The Shah accepted but was not placated. He was, after all, ordering several hundred British-built Chieftain tanks, critically important to Britain's balance of payments.
- The event was catered by Maxim's of Paris — 165 chefs, bakers, and waiters flown in from Paris, along with twenty-five thousand bottles of wine. France's President Georges Pompidou was notably absent: "If I did go," he explained privately, "they would probably make me the head-waiter." Cost was estimated at $100-$200 million. The Shah dismissed criticism: "So what are people complaining about? That we are giving a couple of banquets for some 50 Heads of State? We can hardly offer them bread and radishes, can we?"
- After Persepolis, the British invited the Shah to spend Ascot Royal Weekend at Windsor Castle to reduce tensions. The visit was a great success, marred only by a near-diplomatic incident: the Shah, as an Iranian male, would not ride a mare or gelding, only a stallion. None was available until the Queen remembered Princess Anne had a stallion — named Cossack, a potentially offensive name since the Shah's father had been an officer of the Cossack Brigade. The Shah did ride Cossack, though the horse's name was kept from him. Thereafter the Shah wrote to the Queen as "My Dear Sovereign Cousin."
- The overall aim of the Persepolis celebration was to establish the Shah firmly in the line of Cyrus the Great, the Appointed One of God. He was no longer a puppet or pawn — he was a man of enormous wealth, power, and pride, stepping into pivotal new roles in the Middle East and on the international stage.

### The Anglo-American Retreat

- The postwar petroleum order in the Middle East had been developed under American-British ascendancy. By the latter half of the 1960s, the power of both nations was in political recession. The US was mired in Vietnam — costly, unpopular, and ultimately unsuccessful. Anti-Americanism had become a great fashion worldwide, organized around denunciations of imperialism, neocolonialism, and economic exploitation.
- For some in the developing world, the "lessons of Vietnam" were quite different from American interpretations: the dangers and costs of challenging the United States were less than in the past (not as high as for Mossadegh), while the gains could be considerable.
- Britain had been involved in the Persian Gulf since the early 1800s, establishing truces among the sheikhs and guaranteeing the independence of "trucial" states (Bahrain, Kuwait, Qatar). But Britain in the 1960s was preoccupied with economic decline, liquidating its empire. It bowed out of Aden (which became the Marxist-Leninist state of South Yemen), and in January 1968 Prime Minister Harold Wilson announced Britain would end defense commitments east of Suez and completely withdraw its military presence from the Persian Gulf by 1971, eliminating the last major remnant of Pax Britannica.
- Gulf rulers were dumbfounded — only three months earlier the Foreign Office had assured them Britain had no intention of leaving. "Who asked them to leave?" asked the Ruler of Dubai. The Amir of Bahrain said, "Britain could do with another Winston Churchill. Britain is weak now where she was once so strong."
- The British position actually involved only about six thousand ground troops plus air support, costing 12 million pounds a year — a small insurance premium given the vast British oil investments. Some sheikhs offered to pay the 12 million pounds themselves. Defense Secretary Denis Healey angrily rejected this, deriding "mercenaries for people who like to have British troops around." But similar offset payments were accepted for garrisoning troops in West Germany and Hong Kong.
- The British helped set up the United Arab Emirates to bind the small states together, then packed up and left in November 1971. Their departure marked the most fundamental change in the Gulf since World War II — the end of a century-old security system. It left a dangerous power vacuum in a region supplying 32 percent of the free world's petroleum and holding 58 percent of proven oil reserves.
- The Shah of Iran was eager to fill the vacuum: "The safety of the Persian Gulf had to be guaranteed, and who but Iran could fulfill this function?" This was the era of the Nixon Doctrine — depending on strong, friendly local powers as regional policemen. Nixon had developed a high regard for the Shah, whom he first met in 1953. When Nixon lost the 1962 California gubernatorial election, the Shah was one of the few heads of state to receive him cordially on a world trip — Nixon never forgot. Soviet arms were flowing into neighboring Iraq, which had its own ambitions for Gulf hegemony.

### The End of the Twenty-Year Surplus: To a Seller's Market

- The 1970s saw a dramatic shift in world oil. Demand was catching up with supply; the twenty-year surplus was over. The world was rapidly becoming more dependent on the Middle East and North Africa. Free world petroleum demand rose from almost 19 million barrels per day in 1960 to more than 44 million bpd in 1972. Cars were getting heavier, carrying more "extras" like air-conditioning. The cheap price of oil meant no incentive for fuel-efficient automobiles.
- The domestic US oil industry hit a watershed. For decades, the Texas Railroad Commission, Oklahoma Corporations Commission, and Louisiana Conservation Commission had prorationed output, keeping production below capacity. This inadvertently provided the entire Western world with a security reserve — surge capacity callable in crises (WWII, 1951, 1956, 1967).
- Rising demand, low investment, low discovery rates, and the end of import quotas erased the need to restrain production. American oil production reached 11.3 million barrels per day in 1970 — the peak, the highest level it would ever reach. From then on, it began its decline. In March 1971, for the first time in a quarter century, the Texas Railroad Commission allowed all-out production at 100 percent of capacity. "We feel this to be an historic occasion," declared the chairman. "Damned historic, and a sad one. Texas oil fields have been like a reliable old warrior that could rise to the task when needed. That old warrior can't rise anymore."
- US net imports rose rapidly from 2.2 million bpd in 1967 to six million bpd by 1973. Imports as a share of total consumption rose from 19 percent to 36 percent. The disappearance of surplus capacity meant the "security margin" upon which the Western world had depended was gone. In November 1968, the State Department warned European governments at an OECD meeting that American production would soon reach limits — there would be no security cushion. The other participants were taken by surprise.
- Between 1960 and 1970, free world oil demand had grown by 21 million bpd. Production in the Middle East (including North Africa) had grown by 13 million bpd — two-thirds of the huge increase was satisfied by Middle Eastern wells.

### Environmental Impact

- Beginning in the mid-1960s, environmental issues entered politics. Air pollution prompted utilities to shift from coal to less-polluting oil, adding stimulus to demand. In 1965, New York's mayor pledged to banish coal; after a smog crisis on Thanksgiving Day 1966, Consolidated Edison switched to oil. In 1967, a clean air bill passed the Senate 88-3. In 1970, federal environmental impact statements were enacted, and 100,000 people marched down Fifth Avenue for Earth Day.
- The Limits to Growth (1972), a Club of Rome report, argued that if trends in population, industrialization, pollution, food production, energy consumption, and resource depletion continued, industrial civilization would become unsustainable "sometime within the next hundred years." It warned of resource depletion, environmental consequences of hydrocarbon burning, CO2 buildup, and global warming. It became a lodestar in energy/environment debates, fueling fear and pessimism about impending shortages.
- The environmental movement had a paradoxical effect — both increasing demand for oil (as a cleaner-burning substitute for coal) and restricting its supply (blocking new exploration). In January 1969, an offshore well in the Santa Barbara Channel encountered an unexpected geological anomaly; an estimated six thousand barrels seeped out, washing crude oil onto thirty miles of beaches. The Nixon Administration imposed a moratorium on California offshore development. The Santa Barbara spill also increased opposition to development in other environmentally sensitive areas, including Alaska — the most promising area to stem the decline in American production.

### The Alaskan Elephant

- As early as 1923, President Harding had created a naval petroleum reserve on the Arctic coast of Alaska. Following the 1956 Suez Crisis, Shell and Standard Oil of New Jersey began exploring but drilled the most expensive dry hole to that date in 1959 and suspended operations. Sinclair Oil and BP drilled six expensive dry holes in succession on the North Slope and also suspended.
- Gulf Oil showed interest but top management refused: "It would cost $5 a barrel, and oil will never get to $5 a barrel in our lifetime."
- Richfield, a California-based independent attracted by thick marine sediments on the North Slope, partnered with Jersey's Humble subsidiary in 1964. In 1965, this joint venture won about two-thirds of the exploration leases on the Prudhoe Bay structure. The BP-Sinclair combination won the rest. That same year, Richfield merged with Atlantic Refining to form ARCO, headed by Robert O. Anderson.
- Anderson was one of the last great wildcatters and oil tycoons of the twentieth century — son of a Chicago banker who lent to Texas and Oklahoma independents in the 1930s. He grew up around the University of Chicago, considered becoming a philosophy professor, but was captured by the oil men who were his father's clients. In 1942, he took over a 1,500-barrel-per-day refinery in New Mexico and became one of the better-known independents. He had quick mental arithmetic rivaling Rockefeller and Deterding, and believed fervently in crude oil and reserves as "the absolute heart of the industry." "90 percent of what you drill are failures. You really have to take defeat regularly." The other 10 percent made him the largest individual landowner in the United States.
- In winter 1966, ARCO drilled a costly dry well sixty miles south of Alaska's north coast. One more wildcat was on the schedule at Prudhoe Bay. Anderson gave the okay reluctantly — it was more a decision not to cancel a well already scheduled than an enthusiastic go-ahead.
- In spring 1967, the ARCO-Humble venture began drilling Prudhoe Bay State Number 1. On December 26, 1967, a loud, vibrating sound drew about forty men in heavy clothes (thirty degrees below zero, thirty-knot wind). The roar of natural gas sounded like four jumbo jets. A gas flare shot thirty feet straight up. They had struck oil. In mid-1968, a "step-out well" seven miles away confirmed a world-class field. DeGolyer and McNaughton estimated Prudhoe Bay held as much as 10 billion barrels of recoverable reserves — the largest oil field ever discovered in North America, one-and-a-half times larger than Dad Joiner's East Texas field.
- ARCO acquired Sinclair, and the Big Three on the North Slope were ARCO, Jersey, and BP. The physical environment was fiercely hostile — "a mean, nasty, unforgiving place to work." Temperatures fell to sixty-five below zero, tundra thawed into spongy prairie in summer, no roads existed, permafrost extended a thousand feet deep. Normal steel piling crumbled in the permafrost.
- Transport options considered included icebreaker tankers through the Arctic, a monorail, an eight-lane highway of trucks across Alaska, nuclear-powered submarine tankers under the polar ice cap to a Greenland port created by nuclear explosion, and jumbo jet oil tankers. The decision was a pipeline — either an 800-mile trans-Alaskan pipeline south to Valdez, or an overland pipeline east through Canada to Chicago. The trans-Alaskan route was chosen because it was "all-American," more secure, and could be built more quickly.
- The pipeline group (ARCO, Jersey, BP) hurriedly bought 500,000 tons of forty-eight-inch pipe from a Japanese manufacturer and brought $75 million worth of Caterpillar trucks and trailers to the Yukon River. But a Federal court injunction won by environmentalists in 1970 — energized by the Santa Barbara spill — completely stopped the project. The trucks and tractors sat for five years, companies spending millions just keeping engines warm. The oil expected from Alaska in 1972 did not flow; American imports of foreign oil rose instead.
- North Sea oil was another promising alternative but highly uncertain — enormous scale, very expensive, harsh and treacherous environment requiring an entirely new generation of technology. Alaska and the North Sea shared a common bond: physically difficult but politically stable. Even so, neither could provide imminent relief for the tightening global supply-demand balance.

### The Doctor

- Just before dawn in late August 1970, a chartered French Falcon jet entered Libyan air space carrying Dr. Armand Hammer, chairman of Occidental Petroleum, age seventy-two. He feared losing his "shining star" — Occidental's richly prolific oil concession in Libya.
- Hammer was born in 1898 in New York City to an immigrant Jewish family with roots in Odessa on the Black Sea. His father, Dr. Julius Hammer, was a practicing physician, drug manufacturer, and partisan of the left who had met Lenin in 1907 and was one of the founders of the American Communist party. Armand did not share his father's socialist tendencies — he was interested in making money and doing deals.
- In 1921, having just graduated from medical school, Hammer went to Russia carrying relief medical supplies and aiming to collect $150,000 owed to the family drug business. Through his father's connections, he became known to Lenin, who was allowing some competition in the ruined Russian economy. Lenin commended Hammer to Stalin as "a little path leading to the American 'business' world." Hammer stayed in Russia doing business under Lenin's New Economic Policy — an asbestos concession, a Ford agency, the national concession for pencils, even fur stations in Siberia. When Stalin came to power, Hammer correctly read the portents, packed up, and carried out a load of Russian art, sold through department stores in the US. He went on to make millions in businesses from beer barrels and bourbon whiskey to bull semen.
- In 1956, at age fifty-eight, Hammer came to Los Angeles as a wealthy art gallery owner and collector, seeking a tax shelter. He made some oil investments, then bought a small, nearly bankrupt company called Occidental. By 1961, Occidental made its first significant discovery in California. By 1966, annual sales were almost $700 million. His political connections were unparalleled; his personal fortune vast. "The Doctor is one of the greatest actors in the world," was the acid comment of one who had mistakenly thought himself Hammer's heir apparent.
- Hammer renewed contacts with the Soviet Union under Khrushchev and became a go-between for five Soviet General Secretaries and seven US Presidents. As late as 1990, at age ninety-two, he was still the active chairman. He was in the line of the great buccaneer-creators of oil: Rockefeller, Samuel, Deterding, Gulbenkian, Getty, and Mattei.
- In 1965, Occidental won concessions in the second round of Libyan bidding. Oxy's thick bid stood out — done on sheepskin manuscripts wrapped in red, black, and green ribbons (the Libyan flag colors). As sweeteners, Oxy promised to establish an agricultural experimental farm at King Idris's childhood home and gave the King a gold chess set, plus the expected overrides and commissions to those who could help.
- Occidental's blocks (Numbers 102 and 103) covered almost two thousand square miles of desert in the Sirte Basin, more than a hundred miles from the Mediterranean coast. Initial drilling was dry and costly — Occidental's board grumbled about "Hammer's Folly." But in autumn 1966, Occidental struck oil on Number 102, and then spectacularly on Number 103 (the Idris field) — drilled right under the site of Mobil's former base camp, which Mobil had relinquished. The first well came in at 43,000 bpd; another at a phenomenal 75,000 bpd. It was newly developed seismic technology that enabled this "puny California producer to find what giant Mobil had missed." "All hell broke loose. We became one of the Big Boys."
- By another stroke of luck, the 1967 Six-Day War closed the Suez Canal, making Libyan oil (close to Europe) even more valuable. DeGolyer and McNaughton estimated Occidental alone held three billion barrels of recoverable reserves — almost a third of the reserves discovered on Alaska's North Slope. A 130-mile pipeline across the desert was force-built in less than a year. Occidental was soon producing upwards of 800,000 barrels per day in Libya, becoming the sixth-largest oil-producing company in the world.
- Yet Occidental was very vulnerable, owing to its lopsided dependence on Libya. Elderly King Idris could not last. Hammer sought to diversify by acquiring Island Creek Coal. Before agreeing, Island Creek's president William Bollano checked with the State Department, Chase Manhattan Bank, and Citibank — all assured him political stability in Libya for five or six years and an "orderly transfer of power when the King died." The merger went ahead in 1968. The experts were all dead wrong.

### The Libyan Squeeze

- On the night of August 31-September 1, 1969, a senior Libyan military officer was awakened in his bedroom by a junior officer telling him the coup was early — the senior officer's own coup was scheduled for a few days later. The whole Libyan military had been seething with conspiracies. A group of radical young officers led by the charismatic Muammar al-Qaddafi beat all others to the punch, staging their coup on September 1. Many military men participated without knowing who was in charge or even which coup it was.
- Qaddafi and his associates had begun conspiring a full decade earlier as teenagers in secondary school, inspired by Nasser, his Philosophy of Revolution, and the Voice of the Arabs radio station. They modeled their lives on Nasser and took the same route to power — through the military academy. In Qaddafi's mind, the revolutionary doctrines of Nasser were amalgamated "to the ideas of Islam at the time of Mohammed." He was a born conspirator, but also eccentric and erratic, with the mood swings of a manic-depressive. Equipped with huge oil revenues, he would become banker, sponsor, and paymaster for many terrorist groups around the world.
- Among Qaddafi's first acts: shutting down British and American military bases, expelling the large Italian population, closing all Catholic churches and ordering their crosses removed and contents auctioned off. After a December 1969 countercoup was aborted, Qaddafi was ready to deal with oil. In January 1970, officers of the Revolutionary Command Council demanded an increase in the posted price. Qaddafi warned the twenty-one oil companies he would shut down production if necessary: "People who have lived without oil for 5,000 years can live without it again for a few years in order to attain their legitimate rights."
- Initially, Libya pressured Esso-Libya, demanding a 43-cent-a-barrel increase. "43 cents in those days — Good God! That was out of the world," recalled Esso-Libya's head. Esso offered five cents. Stymied by the majors (which had alternative sources), Libya turned to the one company without alternatives — Occidental. "It had all its eggs in one basket." In late spring 1970, Occidental was ordered to cut production from 800,000 to around 500,000 bpd. Libyan policemen began to stop, search, and harass Occidental executives.
- Libya had chosen a propitious time. Libya was supplying 30 percent of Europe's oil. The Suez Canal was still closed. In May 1970, a tractor ruptured the Tapline inside Syria, cutting 500,000 bpd of Saudi oil to the Mediterranean. Tanker rates immediately tripled. There was no shortage of oil, but a shortage of transportation — putting Libya and Qaddafi, sitting directly across the Mediterranean from European markets, in a central position. Between the Tapline closure and the Libyan cutbacks, 1.3 million bpd had been abruptly taken off the market. Abdullah Tariki, the radical former Saudi oil minister fired eight years earlier, was now in Tripoli advising the revolutionary government.
- Hammer became agitated. He went to Egypt to ask Nasser to intercede with his "disciple." Concerned about Libya's subsidies to the Egyptian Army, Nasser advised Qaddafi to go easy and not to repeat Egypt's mistakes with nationalization and expulsion of foreign technicians. The advice was not heeded.
- Hammer tried to find other companies that would provide replacement oil at cost if Occidental stood firm against Qaddafi. He was unsuccessful. Even a visit to Kenneth Jamieson, chairman of Exxon, did not produce the oil Hammer wanted. Hammer was very bitter. "Here the President of Exxon, the world's largest corporation, was confronted with an art dealer, a non-fraternity type, coming out of the cold with a worldwide scheme."
- Desperate, Hammer tried a barter deal over dinner at Lyndon Johnson's ranch in Texas — he would be middleman trading McDonnell Douglas warplanes for Iranian oil. That too failed. Then in late August 1970, his Libya manager George Williamson warned that nationalization was imminent — sending Hammer streaking through the night skies to Tripoli.
- On the Libyan side, negotiations were led by Deputy Prime Minister Abdel Salaam Ahmed Jalloud — more fun-loving than the puritanical Qaddafi but a relentless negotiator. He once rolled up a Texaco/Standard of California proposal into a paper ball and threw it back in their faces. On another occasion, he charged into a room of oil executives with a submachine gun slung over his shoulder. At his first session with Hammer, after offering hot rolls and coffee, Jalloud unbuckled his belt and set his .45 revolver directly in front of Hammer. Hammer smiled but was disconcerted — he had never before negotiated across a gun barrel.
- Hammer commuted daily between Tripoli and Paris (flying back by 2 a.m., off again by 6 a.m.), telephoning his board from the Ritz Hotel. He worried about being "detained" and initially used a chartered French jet rather than his own Gulfstream II, fearing the Libyans might seize his private plane.
- Finally, Hammer and Jalloud reached agreement. The Libyans got a 20 percent increase in royalties and taxes — a thirty-cent posted price increase and a hike in Libya's profit share from 50 to 55 percent. By the end of September, virtually all other companies in Libya had given in with immense reluctance. The Libyans solemnly promised to stick to these new agreements for five years.
- The significance went far beyond the thirty-cent increase. The Libyan agreements decisively changed the balance of power between producing countries and oil companies. For the exporters, it was emboldening — it not only reversed the decline in the real price of oil but reopened the campaign for sovereignty and control over their resources. "The oil industry as we had known it would not exist much longer," said the Jersey director for Libya. George Williamson of Occidental had a premonition: "Everybody who drives a tractor, truck, or car in the Western world will be affected by this."

### Leapfrogging Prices

- The Shah of Iran would not be outdone by young Libyan military officers. In November 1970, he broke through the fifty-fifty profit-sharing barrier, winning 55 percent of consortium profits. The companies then offered 55 percent to all Gulf countries, triggering a leapfrog game. Venezuela introduced legislation raising its share to 60 percent with unilateral price-setting power. An OPEC conference endorsed 55 percent as the minimum and threatened a supply cutoff. At the beginning of 1971, Libya jumped over Iran with new demands.
- David Barran, chairman of Shell Transport and Trading, became the foremost advocate of a common company front: "Our Shell view was that the avalanche had begun. Without a united front, the companies would be picked off one by one." The companies formed a "Front Uni" of two dozen companies (American and non-American) representing about four-fifths of free world oil production, with an antitrust waiver from the US Justice Department. They also created the "Libyan Safety Net" — a secret understanding that if any company's production was cut back for standing up to Qaddafi, the others would provide replacement oil. This institutionalized the deal Hammer had tried and failed to get from Exxon six months earlier.
- On January 15, 1971, the companies sent a "Letter to OPEC" calling for an "all-embracing" settlement — negotiate with OPEC as a whole, not individual exporters or subgroups. But the Shah resolutely opposed this, saying "moderates" could not restrain the "radicals" (Libya and Venezuela). He promised a stable five-year agreement if the companies dealt with Gulf countries separately. "If the companies tried any tricks, the entire Gulf would be shut down and no oil would flow."
- The Front Uni negotiators — George Piercy of Exxon and Lord Strathalmond of BP — arrived in Tehran to find that Washington had acquiesced to the Shah's position, undercutting them. "It made the whole exercise look silly as hell," Piercy said. The OPEC Gulf committee (Iranian Finance Minister Jamshid Amouzegar, Saudi Oil Minister Zaki Yamani, Iraqi Oil Minister Saadoun Hammadi) was unbending. The Shah himself denounced the companies and brandished the possibility of an embargo, summoning the ghost of Mossadegh: "The conditions of the year 1951 do not exist anymore."
- Yamani privately warned Piercy that there was real talk of an embargo among exporting countries, and that the Saudis and the Shah supported it. "I don't think you realize the problem in OPEC. I must go along."
- The companies capitulated. On February 14, 1971, the Tehran Agreement was signed. The hallowed fifty-fifty principle was dead — 55 percent was the new minimum government take. The price of oil was raised by thirty-five cents a barrel, with further annual hikes. The exporters pledged no increases for five years. "It was the real turning point for OPEC," said one OPEC official. "After the Tehran Agreement, OPEC got muscles." David Barran of Shell was a better prophet: "There is no doubt that the buyer's market for oil is over."
- Negotiations then shifted to the Mediterranean committee (Libya, Algeria, Saudi Arabia, Iraq). Major Jalloud used all his now-familiar tactics — bluster, intimidation, revolutionary sermons, threats of embargo and nationalization. On April 2, 1971, agreement was announced: the posted price was raised by ninety cents — well beyond the Tehran Agreement's implications. Libya's oil revenues increased by almost 50 percent. The Shah was beside himself with rage — he had been leapfrogged again.

### Participation: "Indissoluble, like a Catholic Marriage"

- The five-year stability pledged in the Tehran and Tripoli agreements proved illusory. OPEC soon sought further increases to compensate for dollar devaluation. But a more momentous conflict was over "participation" — the acquisition by exporting countries of partial ownership of oil resources within their borders. If exporters won this battle, it would mean a radical restructuring of the industry.
- The concession system, dating back to William Knox D'Arcy's 1901 venture in Persia, was now seen by exporters as a holdover from the defunct age of colonialism, wholly inappropriate to the new age of decolonization, self-determination, and nationalism. Countries did not want to be mere tax collectors — the greater question was sovereignty over their own natural resources.
- "Participation" was consciously devised as an alternative to outright nationalization. Outright nationalization would disrupt relations with international companies and put producing countries directly into the business of selling oil — leading to a battle royal among exporters for markets, a dramatic collapse of the price structure, and financial/political instability. Yamani insisted participation — joint ownership with the majors — was the way to meet exporters' objectives while maintaining the system that held up the price. It would create "a bond that would be indissoluble, like a Catholic marriage."
- Participation fit Saudi Arabia's situation — gradual change rather than radical overturning. But for other exporters, gradual participation was insufficient. Algeria took 51 percent of French oil operations outright. Venezuela passed legislation under which all concessions would revert to the government upon expiration in the early 1980s. Libya nationalized BP's holdings (punishing Britain for Iran's seizure of islands near the Strait of Hormuz). Iraq nationalized the Iraq Petroleum Company's last remnant — the Kirkuk concession, the great producing field discovered in the 1920s. "There is a worldwide trend toward nationalization and Saudis cannot stand against it alone," Yamani warned.
- In October 1972, a "participation agreement" was reached between the Gulf states and the companies: an immediate 25 percent participation share, rising to 51 percent by 1983. But the agreement was less popular than Yamani hoped — Algeria, Libya, and Iran all stood outside it. Kuwait's parliament rejected it, so Kuwait was also out.
- At a New York meeting of oil executives chaired by John McCloy, Aramco announced its decision to accept participation. Ed Guinn of Bunker Hunt was upset — concessions in the Gulf would only goad Libya into greater demands. The Aramco plan reminded him of "two skeletons hanging in a closet. One skeleton said to the other, 'How did we get here?' The other replied, 'I don't know, but if we had any guts we'd get out.'" "Meeting adjourned!" McCloy shouted.
- After Yamani's deal with Aramco, Libya took over 50 percent of ENI's operations, then expropriated Bunker Hunt entirely. Qaddafi proudly announced — standing with Uganda's Idi Amin Dada — that by taking over Bunker Hunt, he had given the United States "a big hard blow on its cold insolent face." He then nationalized 51 percent of all other companies in Libya, including Occidental.
- The Shah insisted on a better deal than Saudi Arabia. Owing to the 1951 nationalization, Iran already owned the oil and facilities, but the consortium — not NIOC — actually operated the industry. The Shah demanded NIOC become not only owner but also operator; the 1954 consortium companies would set up a new company to act as a service contractor to NIOC. He got what he wanted. "Finally I won out," the Shah declared. "Seventy-two years of foreign control of the operations of our industry was ended."

### The Hinge Years

- In gaining greater control over oil companies, the exporting countries also gained greater control over prices. Where they had previously sought income by emphasizing volume (pushing prices down), they now sought higher prices, supported by the tight supply-demand balance. The companies had been unable to put up a new Front Uni, nor had their governments backed them. Western governments were distracted by other matters and some thought price increases were justified and would stimulate conservation and new energy development.
- Both Britain and the US had powerful incentives to cooperate with rather than confront Iran and Saudi Arabia — by the early 1970s, both were heeding the Sultan of Oman's appeal to put down a radical rebellion and were taking up roles as regional policemen. Arms purchases were increasing rapidly, calibrating the interaction of rising oil prices with the new security calculus for the Gulf.
- The supply-demand balance was sending a critical message: cheap oil had been a tremendous boon to economic growth, but it could not be sustained. New supplies were needed. As late as 1970, there were still about 3 million bpd of excess capacity outside the US, mostly in the Middle East. By 1973, this had been cut in half to about 1.5 million bpd (~3 percent of total demand). Middle Eastern countries had been instituting cutbacks; by 1973, surplus "available" production capacity was just 500,000 bpd — one percent of free world consumption. A 99 percent utilization rate with a one percent security margin was extraordinarily precarious. Politics was adding to the dangers.
- James Placke, an American diplomat in Tripoli who had watched the Libyan squeeze unfold from his broom-closet office overlooking an Occidental building, wrote a prescient dispatch to the State Department in late November 1970. He argued that the international petroleum order had been irrevocably changed. The producing countries "will be able to overcome their divisions to cooperate in controlling production and raising prices." The extent of Western dependence on oil as a source of energy had been exposed, and the "rationale of those who call for the use of Arab oil as a weapon in Middle East conflict has also been strengthened." He added: "Control of the flow of resources has been of strategic concern throughout history. Asserting control over a vital source of energy would permit Middle Eastern states to regain the power position vis-a-vis the West, which this area lost long ago." The greatest sin was inattention.
- The US ambassador was so impressed he sent the dispatch over his own name to give it added weight. But to Placke's knowledge, no one in Washington paid any serious attention. He certainly never heard a word back on it.

## Chapter 29: The Oil Weapon

- Just moments before 2:00 p.m. on October 6, 1973 — Yom Kippur, the holiest of Jewish holidays — 222 Egyptian jets roared into the sky targeting Israeli command posts and positions on the eastern bank of the Suez Canal and in the Sinai. Minutes later, 3,000 field guns opened fire along the entire front. Simultaneously, Syrian aircraft attacked Israel's northern border, followed by a barrage from 700 pieces of artillery. This began the October War (Yom Kippur War), the fourth Arab-Israeli war — the most destructive, intense, and with the most far-reaching consequences. One of the most potent weapons was unique to the Middle East: the oil weapon, wielded as an embargo, production cutbacks, and export restrictions that, in Henry Kissinger's words, "altered irrevocably the world as it had grown up in the postwar period."
- By 1973, oil had become the lifeblood of the world's industrial economies, pumped and circulated with very little to spare. Never before had the supply-demand equation been so tight while the relationships between oil-exporting countries and oil companies continued to unravel.

### The United States Joins the World Market

- Under the Nixon Administration, oil and energy were rising on the political agenda. The Mandatory Oil Import Program (Eisenhower's quotas) was laboring under mounting strain. Nixon established a Cabinet Task Force on Oil Import Control, headed by Labor Secretary George Shultz, to review the quota program. Shultz's committee recommended scrapping the quotas and replacing them with a tariff. The political response was overwhelmingly negative — a hundred Congressmen signed a letter denouncing it as a threat to the domestic industry. Nixon shelved the report and kept the quotas.
- The Shah of Iran wrote to Nixon, arguing Iran's security required surmounting quota barriers. The Administration was sympathetic to the "power vacuum in the Persian Gulf" but would not tear down restrictions to please the Shah. Nixon apologized in a letter: "Your disappointment that it has not been possible to find a way to provide for increased sales of Iranian oil in the United States is understandable."
- Signs of stress were multiplying in the US energy supply system. During the 1969-70 winter (the coldest in thirty years), both oil and natural gas were in short supply. Electric utilities switched from coal to oil. The following summer, capacity constraints led to brownouts up and down the Atlantic Coast. Surplus oil production capacity in the US had disappeared. Price controls on oil, imposed by Nixon in 1971 as part of his anti-inflation program, were discouraging domestic production while stimulating consumption. Natural gas supplies were tightening due to a regulatory system that controlled prices. Utilities were ordering new nuclear power plants.
- In April 1973, Nixon delivered the first-ever Presidential address on energy, announcing he was abolishing the quota system. Domestic production could no longer keep up with America's voracious appetite. The Administration immediately followed with a "voluntary" allocation system to distribute whatever supplies were available. The shift perfectly symbolized how circumstances had changed: quotas managed surplus; allocations distributed shortage.

### "The Wolf Is Here"

- James Akins, a tall, somber Foreign Service officer and State Department oil expert detailed to the White House, had directed a secret study concluding the world petroleum industry was passing through "the last gasp in the buyers market." By 1975, "we will have entered a permanent sellers' market, with any one of several major suppliers being able to create a supply crisis by cutting off oil supplies." He called for reducing consumption, raising domestic production, and importing from "secure sources." These actions "will be as unpopular as they will be costly." None were taken.
- In April 1973, Akins prepared a secret report from his White House post with proposals including expanded coal use, synthetic fuels, a stiff gasoline tax, and much-increased research and development. His ideas were met with incredulity. "Conservation is not the Republican ethic," Nixon's chief domestic adviser John Ehrlichman told him flatly. That same month, Akins published an article in Foreign Affairs: "The Oil Crisis: This Time the Wolf Is Here." It was widely read but controversial. Foreign Policy magazine simultaneously published "Is the Oil Shortage Real?" emphatically answering no and suggesting Akins was part of a State Department/oil exporter/company cabal.
- Without import barriers, the US was now a full-fledged, very thirsty member of the world oil market. Companies were buying any oil they could find. Petroleum Intelligence Weekly reported in August 1973 "near-panic buying by U.S. and European independents as well as the Japanese" sending "oil prices sky-rocketing." By summer 1973, US imports were 6.2 million bpd, compared to 3.2 million in 1970.
- As demand exceeded supply, market prices exceeded official posted prices for the first time — a decisive change marking the end of the twenty-year surplus. The exporters did not want to see the growing gap between posted price and market price going to the companies. On September 1, 1973, Libya nationalized 51 percent of those company operations not already taken over. Nixon warned: "Oil without a market, as Mr. Mossadegh learned many, many years ago, does not do a country much good." But the stern admonition fell flat — in 1973, there was no spare capacity; the market was hungry. Libya had no trouble selling its oil.
- The radicals in OPEC — Iraq, Algeria, Libya — pushed for revision of the Tehran and Tripoli agreements. By September, Yamani told Aramco's president the Tehran Agreement was "now out of whack," "either dead or dying." If the companies did not cooperate in framing a new price agreement, the exporters would "exercise our rights on our own."

### The Secret: Sadat's Gamble

- Upon coming to power after Nasser's death in 1970, Anwar Sadat had been regarded as a nonentity, judged likely to last only a few months. He was much underestimated. "The legacy Nasser left me was in a pitiable condition," he later said. Egypt was pouring over 20 percent of its GNP into military expenditures (Israel was close behind at 18 percent). Sadat wanted to break out of the cycle of conflict with Israel and out of stalemated diplomacy, but concluded this could not occur while Israel sat on the eastern bank of the Suez Canal and held the entire Sinai.
- He purged the pro-Soviet Egyptians and in July 1972 threw out twenty thousand arrogant Soviet military advisers, though he continued receiving Soviet military supplies. Still, he did not get the response he expected from the West. In late 1972 and early 1973, Sadat came to his fateful decision: war was the only way to obtain his political objectives. "What literally no one understood beforehand was the mind of the man," Kissinger later said. "Sadat aimed not so much for territorial gain but for a crisis that would alter the attitudes into which the parties were then frozen — and thereby open the way to negotiations." His purpose was "psychological and diplomatic, much more than military."
- Sadat's decision was calculated — he was operating on Clausewitz's dictum that war was the continuation of politics by other means. By April 1973, he had begun formulating joint Egyptian-Syrian attack plans with Syria's President Hafez al-Assad. His secret was tightly kept. One of the few people outside the high commands with whom he shared it was King Faisal of Saudi Arabia — meaning oil would be central to the coming conflict.

### The Oil Weapon Unsheathed: Faisal Changes His Mind

- Ever since the 1950s, the Arab world had talked about using the "oil weapon." But it had always been deflected by the fact that Arab oil was not the supply of last resort — Texas, Louisiana, Oklahoma could always put additional oil into the world market. Once the US hit 100 percent production rates, that old warrior could not rise again to defend against the oil weapon.
- King Faisal had gone out of his way to reject use of the oil weapon. In summer 1972, when Sadat called for manipulation of oil supplies, Faisal disagreed strongly: "It was not only useless, but dangerous even to think of that. Politics and oil should not be mixed." Saudi Arabia had discovered during the 1967 war that cutting exports availed nothing except loss of revenues and markets. Faisal believed the US would not need Arab Gulf oil before 1985. "Therefore my opinion is that this proposal should be ruled out."
- But by early 1973, Faisal was changing his mind. Saudi Arabia had become the marginal supplier for the entire world, graduating to the position once held by Texas — the swing producer. Saudi Arabia's share of world exports had risen from 13 percent in 1970 to 21 percent in 1973. Its average output in July 1973 was 8.4 million bpd, 62 percent higher than July 1972. Aramco was producing at capacity. There was also a growing view that Saudi Arabia was earning revenues in excess of what it could spend, while two devaluations of the dollar had abruptly cut the worth of its financial holdings. "What is the point of producing more oil and selling it for an unguaranteed paper currency?" the Kuwaiti oil minister asked.
- The changing marketplace coincided with significant political developments. Faisal had been estranged from Nasser but was sympathetic to Sadat, who was seeking to dismantle Nasser's legacy. Without Saudi support, Sadat might revert to the Soviet connection. By spring 1973, Sadat was pressing Faisal to use the oil weapon. Faisal also felt growing pressure from within his kingdom and the Arab world — guerrillas attacked the Tapline terminal at Sidon, destroying one tank.
- In early May 1973, Faisal met with Aramco executives. Yes, he was a staunch friend of the US, but it was "absolutely mandatory" that the US "do something to change the direction that events were taking in the Middle East today." Aramco's president reported the King's warning: it was "most unsafe for American interests in the Middle East." "A simple disavowal of Israeli policies and actions" would "go a long way toward overcoming the current anti-American feeling." There was "extreme urgency."
- A few weeks later at the Geneva Intercontinental Hotel, Yamani mentioned to Aramco executives that the King had just had a "bad time" in Cairo; Sadat had put intense pressure on him. "Time is running out with respect to U.S. interest in Middle East," the King told the oil men. "Saudi Arabia is in danger of being isolated among its Arab friends, because of failure of the U.S. Government to give Saudi Arabia positive support." Faisal was emphatic: "You will lose everything."
- The company executives went to Washington. "Action must be taken urgently; otherwise, everything will be lost." US government officials expressed "a large degree of disbelief that any drastic action was imminent." "Some believe" the King "is calling wolf when no wolf exists except in his imagination," the oil men were told. Three of the companies — Texaco, Chevron, and Mobil — publicly called for a change in American Middle East policy. Faisal himself gave interviews to the Washington Post, Christian Science Monitor, Newsweek, and NBC Television: "We have no wish to restrict our oil exports to the United States in any way, but America's complete support for Zionism and against the Arabs makes it extremely difficult for us to continue to supply the United States with oil, or even to remain friends with the United States."

### Nervous Leaders

- In June 1973, at a summit meeting at San Clemente, an agitated Brezhnev, unable to sleep, suddenly demanded an unscheduled late-night meeting with Nixon. For three hours, in front of a little fire overlooking the dark Pacific, Brezhnev argued in rough and emotional terms that the Middle East was explosive and a war might soon start. He insisted the only way to avoid war was a new Soviet diplomatic initiative. Nixon and Kissinger thought it was a heavy-handed ploy and dismissed it.
- On August 23, 1973, Sadat made an unannounced trip to Riyadh and told King Faisal he was considering war against Israel. It would begin with a surprise attack. Faisal allegedly promised half a billion dollars for Sadat's war chest and pledged to use the oil weapon. "But give us time. We don't want to use our oil as a weapon in a battle which only goes on for two or three days, and then stops. We want to see a battle which goes on for long enough time for world opinion to be mobilized."
- Less than a week later, on August 27, Yamani told an Aramco executive that the King had suddenly taken to asking for detailed reports on Aramco's production, expansion plans, and the consequences of curtailment on consuming countries, especially the US. "This is a completely new phenomenon," Yamani explained. Yamani warned that elements led by Kissinger "are misleading Nixon as to the seriousness of Saudi Arabia's intentions." The King was "one hundred percent determined to effect a change in U.S. policy and to use oil for that purpose." He was "additionally under constant pressure from Arab public opinion and Arab leaders, particularly Sadat. He is losing patience."

### September 1973: "Pressure All Around"

- By September 1973, talk of an impending energy crisis was widespread. The Middle East Economic Survey headlined: "The Oil Scene: Pressure All Around." The administration decided to impose mandatory allocations for some oil products in tight domestic supply. Joseph Sisco, American Assistant Secretary of State, told Israeli television: "While our interests are parallel to the interests of Israel, they are not synonymous with the state of Israel."
- Nixon at a press conference acknowledged the possibility of Arabs using oil as a club: "We are all in the same bag when you really come down to it. Both sides need to start negotiating." In Germany, the Bonn government unveiled its first energy program focused on security of supply — Ulf Lantzke had needed five years to overcome "the deep-seated political belief that energy supplies were no problem."
- In Japan, MITI released a September 1973 White Paper: "The oil-supply management system, until now run by the international oil companies, has crumbled." Japan pursued "resource diplomacy" — MITI Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone called for Japan to follow "her own independent direction." On September 26, Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka told a television interviewer, "Regarding the energy crisis, an oil crisis ten years from now is clearly seen." It was more like ten days. Sadat was beginning his countdown to war.

### Nothing Further to Negotiate

- At a mid-September Vienna meeting, OPEC called for a new deal with oil companies. The Tehran and Tripoli agreements were dead. Oil company representatives were summoned to meet in Vienna on October 8 with Yamani's team. The companies' joint lawyer John McCloy requested an antitrust waiver from the Justice Department on September 21. Justice Department attorneys, citing a book by an MIT professor, insisted oil prices were going up because of the machinations of large integrated companies, not OPEC. Kenneth Jamieson of Exxon stared in disbelief. Finally, on October 5, three days before the Vienna meeting, the Antitrust Division reluctantly gave clearance.
- American intelligence had been dismissing the likelihood of war for months. It seemed irrational for the Arabs to start a war they would badly lose. A CIA analysis on October 5: "The military preparations that have occurred do not indicate that any party intends to initiate hostilities." At 5:30 p.m. on October 5, the latest Israeli estimate: "We consider the opening of military operations against Israel by the two armies as of low probability." The Watch Committee representing the entire American intelligence community agreed. War, it said, was unlikely.
- On that same day, as Yom Kippur began, the Saudi delegation to OPEC boarded their jet for Vienna. Only when they arrived on October 6 did they learn that Egypt and Syria had launched surprise attacks against Israel. Senior American officials awoke to find the Middle East at war.

### Sadat's Surprise

- The choice of Yom Kippur was designed to catch Israel when it was least prepared — the entire defense strategy depended on rapid mobilization, impossible on the day of meditation and prayer. Sadat had feinted at least twice before, causing costly Israeli mobilizations that bred skepticism and complacency. Assad had also joined in the deception. A Syrian source had provided the US with astonishingly exact intelligence, including Syria's order of battle, but it was lost among hundreds of other pieces of information. On October 3, Assad ordered preparation of large graveyards. Egyptian hospital beds were suddenly emptied. A young Israeli lieutenant submitted reports on October 1 and October 3 pointing to imminent war — they were ignored. The Israeli military was in thrall to "the conception" — a particular view that by definition precluded an Egyptian attack under current circumstances.
- A key Israeli source in Egypt sent an urgent signal in the first days of October — he was hurriedly extricated and debriefed in Europe. There could be no doubt about what he said. But inexplicably, there was a delay of a day in transmitting his warning to Tel Aviv. By then it was too late.
- The Americans made the same fundamental error — not thinking the way Sadat thought, not putting themselves in his shoes, and not taking him seriously. Until October 1973, Kissinger admitted, he thought of Sadat as "more actor than statesman." The surprise of the Arab attack was for the Israelis what Pearl Harbor had been for Americans thirty-two years earlier.
- When finally, nine and a half hours before the attack, the Israelis got confirmation, they were still hamstrung — they could not go first, could not take preemptive action. They thought the war would start four hours later than it actually did. In the initial days, the Israelis fell back, disordered, while the Egyptians and Syrians scored massive victories.

### "The Third Temple Is Going Under"

- America's initial objective was to arrange a truce with a pullback to prehostilities lines, then pursue a diplomatic solution. The US wanted to keep a low profile — to avoid supplying the Israelis against Soviet-supplied Arabs, believing Israel would quickly win. The best outcome, in the words of one senior official, was one in which "Israel won, but had its nose bloodied in the process," making it more amenable to negotiation.
- But Israel's second big miscalculation (after assuming there would be no war) was that it had enough supplies for three weeks of war, based on the 1967 experience. Now, immediately thrown on the defensive against two richly Soviet-equipped enemies, the Israelis were devouring materiel at an alarming pace. A distraught Moshe Dayan told Premier Golda Meir that "the Third Temple is going under," and Meir herself prepared a secret letter to Nixon warning Israel might be destroyed.
- On October 9, the US realized the Israelis were in deep trouble and desperately short of supplies. On October 10, the Soviet Union began a massive resupply to Syria and then Egypt, put airborne troops on alert, and encouraged other Arab states to join. The US started discussions about more unmarked El Al planes and pressed commercial carriers for charters. Kissinger wanted a low profile. But on Thursday, October 11, the Americans realized Israel could lose the war without resupply. The US could not allow an American ally to be defeated by Soviet arms.
- On Friday, October 12, two private letters went to Nixon. One from the four Aramco chairmen (Exxon, Mobil, Texaco, Standard of California) via John McCloy, warning that the OPEC 100 percent price increase demand was "unacceptable" but that increased US military support for Israel could produce a "snowballing effect" retaliation and a "major petroleum supply crisis." "The whole position of the United States in the Middle East is on the way to being seriously impaired." The second letter was from Golda Meir — her nation's survival hung in the balance. Israel might run out of critical munitions within days.
- Kissinger learned from Defense Secretary Schlesinger that all efforts to arrange commercial charters had failed — airlines feared an Arab embargo or terrorist attacks. "If you want supplies there, we are going to have to use U.S. airlift all the way. There's no alternative." Kissinger asked Schlesinger to have the Israelis promise that Air Force planes could land under cover of darkness and be gone by daybreak. Before daylight Saturday, October 13, the Military Airlift Command began moving supplies.
- But powerful crosswinds at Lajes airfield in the Azores (the C-5As needed a refueling stop) delayed the transports half a day. Instead of arriving Saturday night, they came lumbering out of the sky Sunday during the day, October 14, their immense white stars visible for all to see. The US, instead of keeping a low profile as honest broker, was now portrayed as an active ally of Israel.
- The Israelis stopped the Egyptian offensive and on October 15 launched successful counteroffensives. Meanwhile, in Vienna on October 14, OPEC announced the failure of negotiations with the companies. The Gulf OPEC countries scheduled a meeting in Kuwait City. Most delegates were stranded in Vienna due to war-cancelled flights until they discovered one Air India flight through Geneva with a stop at Kuwait City — many delegations rushed to the airport on October 15.

### The October 16 Price Decision and the Oil Weapon

- On October 16, Gulf state delegates (five Arabs and an Iranian) met in Kuwait City. They would not wait for the companies to reply. They raised the posted price of oil by 70 percent, to $5.11 a barrel, bringing it in line with the panicky spot market. The significance was twofold — the price increase itself, and the unilateral way it was imposed. The pretense of negotiating with companies was over. "This is a moment for which I have been waiting a long time," Yamani told a fellow delegate. "We are masters of our own commodity."
- The exporters argued consuming governments took 66 percent of retail oil prices in taxes, while they received only 9 percent. Iranian oil minister Amouzegar said the exporters were merely keying to market forces and would set prices unilaterally in the future. Piercy of Exxon learned about it from the newspapers.
- At the White House on October 17, Nixon told his senior advisers: "No one is more keenly aware of the stakes: oil and our strategic position." That same day in Kuwait City, the Arab oil ministers (the Iranian had left) gathered for an exclusively Arab conclave. Their subject: the oil weapon. "Now the atmosphere is more propitious than in 1967," declared the Kuwaiti oil minister.

### Embargo

- Despite Sadat's importuning, King Faisal was reluctant to take action against the US without more contact with Washington. He sent a letter to Nixon on October 16 warning that continued American support for Israel would make Saudi-American relations only "lukewarm."
- On October 17, Kissinger and Nixon received four Arab foreign ministers, led by Saudi Omar Saqqaf, whom Kissinger characterized as "gentle and wise." Discussions were cordial. Nixon pledged to "work within the framework of Resolution 242" to return Israel to 1967 borders. Saqqaf seemed to affirm Israel's right to exist within those borders. Nixon promised Kissinger as negotiator and assured Saqqaf that Kissinger, despite his Jewish origins, "was not subject to domestic, that is to say Jewish, pressures." Kissinger was writhing with embarrassment. Saqqaf deftly replied, "We are all Semites together." Saqqaf told reporters the talks had been "constructive and friendly."
- After the meetings, Kissinger told his staff he was surprised that there had been no mention of oil, and that it was unlikely the Arabs would use the oil weapon. But that was exactly what the Arab oil ministers in Kuwait City were contemplating. Early in 1973, Sadat had discussed the oil weapon in a "thinking aloud" speech. Experts from Egypt and other Arab countries had drawn up a plan for using oil, taking into account the growing US energy crisis.
- At the October 17 meeting, radical Iraq called on Arab states to nationalize all American business, withdraw all Arab funds from American banks, and institute a total oil embargo. The Algerian chairman dismissed this as impractical. Yamani, on instructions from his King, also resisted all-out economic warfare. The angry Iraqi delegates withdrew.
- Instead, the Arab ministers agreed to cut production 5 percent from September levels, with further 5 percent cuts each succeeding month until their objectives were met. Oil at previous levels would be maintained to "friendly states." A secret resolution recommended the US be "subjected to the most severe cuts" aiming at "the total halt of oil supplies to the United States from every individual country party to the resolution." Several countries immediately announced 10 percent rather than 5 percent cutbacks. The cutbacks were shrewder than a single-country export ban — they would reduce the absolute level of available supplies, maximize uncertainty, tension, and rivalry among importing countries, and split the industrial countries from the start.
- Events moved rapidly. On October 18, Nixon told his Cabinet that fighting might be prolonged and the Soviets had begun a massive resupply, so "we had to act to prevent the Soviets from tilting the military balance against Israel." On October 19, Nixon publicly proposed a $2.2 billion military aid package for Israel.
- The $2.2 billion aid package was designed so neither Egypt nor Israel ended up in a position of ascendancy, so both would have reason to negotiate. That same day (October 19), Libya announced it was embargoing all oil shipments to the United States.
- At two o'clock Saturday morning, October 20, Kissinger departed for Moscow to devise a cease-fire formula. On the plane, he learned stunning news: in retaliation for the Israeli aid proposal, Saudi Arabia had gone beyond rolling cutbacks — it would now cut off all shipments, every last barrel, to the United States. The other Arab states had done or were doing the same. The oil weapon was now fully in battle — "a weapon, in Kissinger's words, of political blackmail." The three-decade-old postwar petroleum order had died its final death.
- The embargo came as an almost complete surprise. "The possibility of an embargo didn't even enter my mind," said a senior Aramco executive. Despite two decades of discussion about the "oil weapon," the failed 1967 attempt, the threats during the Tehran negotiations, and the exceedingly tight market, neither the companies nor the US government had given serious thought to the prospect. What transformed the situation and galvanized the production cuts and embargo was the very public nature of the American resupply — the result of crosswinds at Lajes airfield in the Azores — and then the $2.2 billion aid package.
- Even the embargo was not the end of stunning events on October 20. In Moscow, Kissinger learned of the Saturday Night Massacre — Nixon had fired special prosecutor Archibald Cox. Attorney General Elliot Richardson and his chief deputy William Ruckelshaus resigned in protest. White House Chief of Staff Alexander Haig told Kissinger, "all hell has broken loose."

### The Third-Rate Burglary

- Throughout the war and the oil crisis, Nixon was preoccupied with Watergate. The unfolding of Watergate during the October War created a strange, surrealistic dimension. On October 9, the day Golda Meir signaled she wanted to fly to Washington to plead for aid, Nixon was working out the resignation of Vice-President Spiro Agnew. On October 12, the day officials realized Israel might lose the war, they were summoned to the White House for what Kissinger called an "eerie ceremony" in which Nixon introduced Gerald Ford as his new Vice-President.
- Effective control over American policy was lodged in the hands of Kissinger, who was now both Special Assistant for National Security and Secretary of State. His original base was Harvard's Center for International Affairs, housed in space borrowed from Harvard Semitic Museum, and his service to Nixon's great rival Nelson Rockefeller. Through the strange twists of Watergate, this former professor and Jewish refugee became the very embodiment of the legitimacy of the American government. His public personality expanded to fill the vacuum created by a discredited Presidency.
- Watergate had direct and major consequences for the Middle East and for oil. Sadat might never have gone to war had a strong President been able to open a dialogue between Egypt and Israel after the 1972 election. Watergate gave a lasting cast to the energy problems of the 1970s — the coincidence of the embargo and the Saturday Night Massacre fed conspiracy theories and obstructed rational responses. Some argued Kissinger had masterminded the crisis; some believed Nixon had deliberately encouraged the embargo to distract from Watergate. Illegal oil company campaign contributions, part of the loot extracted by the Committee to Reelect the President, flowed together in the public mind with the embargo, expanding the traditional distrust of the oil industry.

### Alert

- On October 21, the day after the Saturday Night Massacre, Yamani met with Aramco president Frank Jungers in Riyadh. Using computer data on exports and destinations, Yamani laid out the ground rules for the cutbacks and embargo. "Any deviations by the Aramco offtakers from the ground rules would be harshly dealt with." Yamani asked Jungers if he would be "surprised at the next move if this one didn't produce some results." "No," said Jungers. He guessed the subsequent move would be "complete nationalization of American interests if not a break in diplomatic relations." Yamani's final ominous comment: "The next step would not just be more of the same."
- In Moscow, Kissinger and the Russians completed a cease-fire plan, but implementation ran into serious snags — neither the Israelis nor Egyptians observed the cease-fire, and Egypt's Third Army faced capture or annihilation. Brezhnev sent a blunt, provocative letter to Nixon: the Soviet Union would not allow the Third Army to be destroyed. He demanded a joint American-Soviet force to separate the sides, or the Soviets would intervene unilaterally. "I shall say it straight," he menacingly wrote. Soviet airborne troops were on alert, ships in the Mediterranean were proceeding in a belligerent fashion, and neutron emissions from what might be nuclear weapons had been detected on a Soviet freighter passing through the Dardanelles.
- A half dozen senior national security officials were summoned to a late-night emergency meeting in the White House Situation Room. Nixon was not awakened — Haig told Kissinger the President was "too distraught." The officials concluded the risks had suddenly escalated; the US had to respond resolutely to Brezhnev's challenge. American forces were raised to DefCon 3, and in some cases even higher — the American military went on a worldwide nuclear alert in the early morning of October 25. The US and Soviet Union were squaring off directly, something that had not happened since the Cuban Missile Crisis. Miscalculation could lead to nuclear confrontation.
- But the following day, the fighting stopped, Egypt's Third Army was resupplied, and the cease-fire went into effect. The superpowers pulled back from their alerts. Two days later, Egyptian and Israeli military representatives met for direct talks for the first time in a quarter century. Both had been objectives of Sadat's gamble. The nuclear weapons were sheathed. But the Arabs continued to wield the oil weapon. The oil embargo remained in place, with consequences that would extend far beyond the October War.

## Chapter 30: "Bidding for Our Life"

- The embargo signaled a new era for world oil. Oil was now too important to be left to the oil men — it had become the province of presidents and premiers, of foreign and finance and energy ministers, of congressmen and parliamentarians. Kissinger, who by his own admission had known nothing about oil before 1973, would tell aides, "Don't talk to me about barrels of oil. They might as well be bottles of Coca Cola. I don't understand!" Yet once the oil weapon had been brought into play, this diplomatic acrobat would do more than anybody else to get the sword back into its scabbard.

### "The Loss"

- The "Arab oil embargo" had two elements: the rolling production cutbacks (5 percent initially, then additional 5 percent each month) affecting the entire market, and the total ban on exports to the US and the Netherlands (subsequently extended to Portugal, South Africa, and Rhodesia). In a bizarre twist, the embargo also extended to US military forces in the Eastern Hemisphere, including the Sixth Fleet — whose responsibilities included protecting some of the states imposing the embargo. Congress hurriedly made it a criminal act to discriminate against the Department of Defense.
- At the beginning of November, the Arab ministers increased the size of cuts. Available Arab oil in the first part of October had totaled 20.8 million bpd. In December, at the most severe point, it was 15.8 million bpd — a gross loss of 5 million bpd. America's spare capacity was gone. Other producers (led by Iran) increased output by 600,000 bpd. Iraq, whose proposal for total economic warfare had been rejected, sulked and actually increased production. Iraq's Saddam Hussein blasted Saudi Arabia and Kuwait as "reactionary ruling circles well known for their links with America." Net loss in December was 4.4 million bpd, or about 9 percent of the 50.8 million bpd "free world" total — amounting to 14 percent of internationally traded oil. With world consumption growing at 7.5 percent a year, the effects were amplified.
- Great uncertainty compounded the loss — contradictory information, massive disruption of supply channels, violent emotions. Would further cutbacks be imposed each month? Would new countries be embargoed? Would countries be shifted from the "neutral" to the "preferential" list? There was one other very large uncertainty: with per-barrel prices skyrocketing, the exporters could cut back on volumes and still increase their total income. They could sell less and earn more. They might decide to make the cuts permanent, meaning a chronic shortage, permanent fear, and even higher prices.

### Panic at the Pump

- The ingredients for panic prices: war, cutbacks, embargoes, shortages, desperate consumers, the specter of further cutbacks, and the possibility the Arabs would never restore production. Fear and uncertainty had a self-fulfilling effect — both companies and consumers frantically sought additional supplies not just for current use but for storage against future shortages. "We weren't bidding just for oil. We were bidding for our life."
- The posted price for Iranian oil per the October 16 agreement was $5.40 a barrel. In November, Nigerian oil sold for over $16. In mid-December, Iran held a major auction — bids came in over $17 a barrel, 600 percent greater than the pre-October 16 price. A Japanese trading company, inexperienced in buying oil and under pressure to assure Japan's supply, competing with eighty other companies, bid $22.60 a barrel (though the deal was never consummated). There were reports of even higher bids.
- E. F. Schumacher's pessimistic Limits to Growth outlook seemed vindicated. His timely publication of Small is Beautiful in 1973 made him a spokesman for those who challenged "the bigger is better" philosophy. "The party is over," he declared. "Whose party was it anyway?"
- The age of shortage was at hand. The prospect was gloomy: lost economic growth, recession, inflation, possible dislocation of the international monetary system. The US, the world's foremost superpower, had been thrown on the defensive by a handful of small nations. Western Europeans and Japanese were transported back to the bitter postwar years of deprivation and shortages.
- In Japan, the oil shortage was accompanied by a toilet paper shortage — housewives rushed out to hoard laundry detergent and toilet paper (in some cases, a two-year supply). The price of toilet paper would have quadrupled without government controls. Taxicab drivers staged angry demonstrations.
- In the United States, the shortfall struck at fundamental beliefs in the endless abundance of resources. A large part of the public did not even know, until October 1973, that the US imported any oil at all. Gasoline prices climbed by 40 percent. The shortage became vivid with the emergence of "gas lines." The allocation system, introduced just before the embargo, now perversely assured that gasoline could not be shifted from well-supplied areas to where it was needed. Motorists who had been content to drive until the gauge was on "empty" now hastened to "top off" their tanks with even a one-dollar purchase, lengthening lines further. Stations sprouted "Sorry, No Gas Today" signs. The experience would severely undermine Americans' confidence in the future.

### "Beef Prices"

- On November 7, 1973, Nixon made a major Presidential address on energy to an alarmed nation. He called for Project Independence — "Let us set as our national goal, in the spirit of Apollo, with the determination of the Manhattan Project, that by the end of this decade we will have developed the potential to meet our own energy needs without depending on any foreign energy source." His staff had told him the goal was impossible and silly to proclaim. Nixon overruled them — energy was now both a crisis and high politics.
- Nixon fired energy czar John Love and replaced him with Deputy Treasury Secretary William Simon. Nixon likened Simon's new post to Albert Speer's position as armaments overlord in the Third Reich — Simon was "somewhat discomfited by the comparison." The new energy czar found himself in never-ending Congressional hearings. Once, rushing to a hearing, Simon was walking backward to finish a conversation and cracked his head on his car, cutting his scalp. Though he needed stitches, the committee chairman would not postpone; Simon sat through five hours of interrogation with blood oozing from the gash. His wife gave up using any charge cards that carried her husband's name.
- Nixon resisted calls for gasoline rationing. He ordered rationing stamps printed and held in reserve. "Maybe that will shut them up." Aide Roy Ash counseled caution: "In a few months, I suspect, we will look back on the energy crisis somewhat like we now view beef prices — a continuing and routine governmental problem — but not a Presidential crisis." Nixon agreed: "absolutely right" and "makes great sense." But to the public, what had happened to gasoline prices far transcended beef. Their birthright as Americans seemed in jeopardy.
- Public opinion analyst Daniel Yankelovich warned of "incipient signs of panic" — people were "growing fearful that the country has run out of energy." Public confidence that "things are going well in the country" plummeted from 62 percent in May 1973 to 27 percent in late November 1973. "Because of Watergate, there was a general sense of paralysis," recalled Steven Bosworth of the State Department's Office of Fuels and Energy. "Congress was mesmerized by Watergate, the executive branch was mired in it, and the White House was circling the wagons."

### "Equal Misery"

- How was the shortfall to be allocated? The companies adopted a policy of "equal suffering" and "equal misery" — the same percentage of cutbacks from total supplies to all countries, by moving both Arab and non-Arab oil around the world. Non-Arab oil was diverted to embargoed or neutral countries; Arab oil went to the preferred lists. The five American majors ended up diverting about a third of their oil. Adjusting for different energy and oil growth rates, the loss over the embargo period was: Japan 17 percent, United States 18 percent, Western Europe 16 percent. The Federal Energy Administration later concluded that "it is difficult to imagine that any other allocation plan would have achieved a more equitable allocation of reduced supplies."
- The companies were caught in a vise: on one side, deadly serious pressure from Arab governments threatening to nationalize and throw them out; on the other, consuming governments demanding the oil their publics needed. "The only alternative was not to ship the oil at all," said Chevron's George Keller. "Obviously it was in the best interests of the United States to move 5, 6, 7 million barrels per day to our friends around the world rather than to have that cut off."
- Washington gave little direct guidance. Kissinger asked the companies "to take care of Holland," which had been particularly targeted by the Arabs. Japan felt a special vulnerability — little indigenous energy, highly dependent on American majors. A senior MITI bureaucrat warned the majors not to divert non-Arab oil from Japan to the US. The companies replied they would be happy to hand the whole thankless job over to governments. Japan backed off.
- The most turbulent reaction came from Britain. Though placed among "friendly nations" supposed to receive 100 percent of September supplies, Prime Minister Edward Heath summoned BP chairman Sir Eric Drake and Shell chairman Sir Frank McFadzean to Chequers and demanded special treatment — 100 percent of normal requirements. A confrontation between coal miners and Heath's government was brewing, threatening to cut coal supplies just as oil was short.
- Both chairmen pointed out they had been sucked into a vacuum from the failure of governments to plan. McFadzean noted Shell was 60 percent Dutch-owned, so even if he agreed with Heath, which he "most decidedly did not," it would not be possible to ride roughshod over Dutch interests. Drake, who had stood up to Mossadegh in Iran in 1951 and later to BP's autocratic chairman William Fraser, was certainly not going to give way to Edward Heath and allow him "to destroy my company." Having lived through one nationalization in Iran, Drake did not intend to be party to any more.
- Drake asked: "Are you asking me to do this as a shareholder or as a government? If you're telling me to do it as a government, then I must have it in writing. Then we can plead force majeure to the other governments." Heath lost his temper: "You know perfectly well that I can't put it in writing." "Then I won't do it," Drake replied with absolute firmness. After a few days of reflection, Heath gave up on his insistence for special treatment. The civil servants in Whitehall were more deft — they reminded companies that the British government decided who got North Sea exploration licenses, ensuring Britain received what they defined as "fair share" — and a bit more.

### A New World of Prices

- Amid the feverish spot-market bidding, OPEC oil ministers met in Tehran in late December 1973 to discuss the official price. The proposed range went from the OPEC Economic Commission's $23 a barrel down to Saudi Arabia's $8. Saudi Arabia feared a skyrocketing price could result in a depression. "If you went down," Yamani said of the industrial world, "we would go down." King Faisal also wanted to maintain the "political character" of the embargo — he did not want it to look like a money grab.
- Iran was by far the most aggressive. The Shah argued for $11.65 as the new posted price (meaning a $7 government take), based on what he called "a new concept" — the cost of alternative energy sources (liquids and gas from coal and shale oil). He cited an Arthur D. Little study. But Shell's chief Middle East adviser dismissed it: "The alternative source existed, in the volume required, only in economic theory, not in reality."
- After much hard discussion, the Shah's position was accepted. The new posted price would be $11.65. The price had been raised from $1.80 in 1970 to $2.18 in 1971 to $2.90 in mid-1973 to $5.12 in October 1973 — and now to $11.65. The two price increases since the war began constituted a fourfold increase. The Shah graciously said it was a price fixed out of "kindness and generosity."
- Nixon wrote a strong private letter asking that the price be reconsidered — "This drastic price increase is particularly unreasonable coming as it does when oil supplies are artificially restrained." The Shah's reply was brief and totally ungiving: "We also know that for us this source of wealth might be finished in thirty years."
- The Shah had found a new role as moralist for world oil: "Really oil is almost a noble product. We were almost careless to use oil for heating houses or even generating electricity. Why finish this noble product in, say, 30 years' time when thousands of billions of tons of coals remain in the ground." He lectured the industrial nations: "The era of their terrific progress and even more terrific income and wealth based on cheap oil is finished. They will have to find new sources of energy. Eventually they will have to tighten their belts." His haughty stance would cost him dearly only a few years later, when he desperately needed friends.

### Alliance Strained

- The embargo was a political act that took advantage of economic circumstances, and it had to be met with political action on three interrelated fronts: between Israel and its Arab neighbors; between America and its allies; and between the industrial countries and the Arab oil exporters.
- On the first front, Kissinger made himself the center of a vortex. "Shuttle diplomacy" became the hallmark of his tireless, dramatic, and virtuoso performance. Landmarks included an Egyptian-Israeli disengagement agreement in mid-January 1974, and a Syrian-Israeli disengagement at the end of May. Throughout, Kissinger had a particular partner in Sadat, who knew his own objectives. "The United States holds 99 percent of the cards in this game," Sadat publicly declared (though he privately admitted it was really only 60 percent — "but it sounds better if I say 99 percent"). Less than a month after the war, Sadat signaled to Kissinger that he was ready to begin a peace process.
- The oil embargo precipitated one of the gravest splits in the Western alliance since its foundation after World War II — the worst since Suez in 1956. Once the embargo began, the European allies, led by France, hastened to disassociate themselves from the United States and assume positions more agreeable to the Arabs.

### European Capitulation and the Netherlands Crisis

- The Arabs pressed Europeans to oppose the United States and support Arab Middle East policy. Yamani applied his personal touch: "We are extremely sorry for the inconvenience caused in Europe by the Arab oil cut," he said apologetically, while making clear exactly what was expected — distance from America and support for the Arab position.
- As Europeans shifted to "dialogue" and "cooperation" with Arab countries, senior American officials talked caustically about Europeans "being soft on OPEC and falling all over themselves in their haste to accommodate and appease." Europeans countered that the US was too confrontational. French President Georges Pompidou told Kissinger bluntly: "You only rely on the Arabs for about a tenth of your consumption. We are entirely dependent upon them."
- The French had long resented being excluded from Middle Eastern oil by "Anglo-Americans," especially since the postwar Red Line agreement renunciation. Suez in 1956 — when America undercut France and Britain — remained a deep wound. Prime Minister Edward Heath privately told the Americans, "I don't want to raise the issue of Suez but it's there for many people." Heath had been Anthony Eden's loyal whip during Suez.
- In mid-November 1973, the European Community passed a resolution supportive of the Arab position — described by one Arab official as "a kiss blown from afar — which is all very nice but we would prefer something warmer and closer." The resolution won Europeans a suspension of the December 5 percent cut. But the Arab oil ministers warned cuts would be imposed if Europeans did not keep "putting pressure on the United States or Israel."
- The Netherlands posed an awkward problem for the European Community. While most EC members were on the "friendly" list, the Netherlands was still embargoed. Other members were inclined to embargo transshipments to the Netherlands — violating a core EC principle of free commodity flow. The Netherlands reminded them, forcefully, that it was the major source of natural gas for Europe, including 40 percent of France's total supply and most of the gas used for heating and cooking in Paris. A quiet compromise emerged: an unspecified "common position" and expedited non-Arab supplies from international companies.

### Japan's Capitulation

- Japan was distressed to find itself on the "unfriendly" list. Forty-four percent of Japan's oil came from Arab Gulf states, and of all industrial nations it was the most dependent on oil — 77 percent of total energy versus 46 percent for the United States. Yamani spelled out Arab policy to Japan: "If you are hostile to us you get no oil. If you are neutral you get oil but not as much as before. If you are friendly you get the same as before."
- Before the embargo, a "resource faction" in Japanese government and business circles had pushed for reorientation toward the Middle East with little progress. Vice-Minister for Foreign Affairs Fumihiko Togo recalled: "before 1973, we could always buy the oil if only we had the money." After the crisis, the faction intensified efforts. On November 14, the same day Kissinger was in Tokyo trying to keep Japan allied, worried business leaders met privately with Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka to make a "direct request" for a major policy change.
- Days later, Arab exporters exempted European countries that had issued pro-Arab statements — tangible proof that policy changes were rewarded. Japanese emissaries sent on secret trips to the Middle East reported that Arabs regarded "neutrality" as insufficient, treating it as opposition. On November 22, Tokyo issued its own statement endorsing the Arab position.
- This represented Japan's first major split on foreign policy with the United States in the postwar era — a profound step since the U.S.-Japan alliance was the basis of Japanese foreign policy. Four days after the statement, Japan was exempted from December cutbacks. Tokyo sent a host of high-level representatives to the Middle East with economic assistance, loans, new projects, joint ventures, bilateral deals. The majors, through their allocations and cutbacks, had effectively told Japan they could not supply it as before — so Japan pursued its own security of supply. However, Japan refused Arab demands to break all diplomatic and economic relations with Israel. Those who pushed for such a break, argued Vice-Foreign Minister Togo, were suffering from "oil on the brain."

### The Scramble for Bilateral Deals

- Even as allies gave way to Arab demands, the US tried to promote a coordinated response among industrial countries. Washington feared bilateral state-to-state deals would create a rigid, permanently politicized oil market. But the rush was already on: "Bilateral Deals: Everybody's Doing It" headlined the Middle East Economic Survey in January 1974.
- The oil industry viewed with skepticism politicians scrambling for national supplies. Frank McFadzean of Shell marveled at "the spectacle of two senior Cabinet Ministers flying off with the melodrama normally associated with the relief of a beleaguered fortress, to sign a barter agreement involving a quantity of crude oil equal to less than four weeks of the country's requirements."
- Delegations and emissaries "descended on the Middle East like a latter day plague of near Biblical proportions" — most with little knowledge of the oil business. Kissinger feared these bilateral deals would undermine his Arab-Israeli peace negotiations. Competitive bidding based on panic, lack of information, mercantilism, sauve quipeut ("every man for himself") — all would make everyone worse off.

### The Washington Energy Conference and the Birth of the IEA

- The United States called for an energy conference in Washington in February 1974 to heal rifts, assuage fears about supply competition, and prevent oil from becoming a permanent source of Western division.
- Britain, despite being on the "friendly" list, found it bought them little — they still faced the same price increases. The oil shortage was magnified by a coal miners' confrontation with Heath's government that turned into a full-scale economic war. Electricity was interrupted, industry went on a three-day workweek, domestic hot water was in short supply, and BBC clergymen debated whether families should share bath water for the national weal. In what turned out to be Heath's last weeks in government, Britain was a supportive participant in the Washington Conference.
- Japan also supported a coordinated response, keen to mute what they saw as America's "tendency to become very confrontational." Germany wanted multilateral talks. France remained unreconstructed. Foreign Minister Michel Jobert opened a caucus of European Community participants in Washington with the bitter salutation: "Bonjour les traitres" ("Hello traitors").
- American officials hinted that the overall security relationship, including US troops in Europe, might be jeopardized by energy discord. Most conference participants agreed on developing consensus and common policies. The conference led to establishment of an emergency sharing program for the "next" crisis and the creation of the International Energy Agency (IEA) — charged with managing the program and harmonizing Western energy policies. Before 1974 was out, the IEA was set up in a leafy section of Paris's sixteenth arrondissement, in an annex to the OECD. One major industrial country refused to join — France. Foreign Minister Jobert called the IEA a "machine de guerre," an instrument of war.

### Sheathing the Oil Weapon

- When and how would the embargo end? No one knew — not even the Arabs. In late December 1973, Arab producers relaxed the embargo slightly as progress was made on the Arab-Israeli dispute. Kissinger called the embargo, by early January, "increasingly less appropriate."
- Kissinger visited King Faisal twice in Saudi Arabia. Walking through a tremendous hall where distinguished men in black robes and white headdresses sat against the walls, Kissinger — a Jewish refugee from Nazi persecution — "found himself reflecting in some wonder what strange twists of fate had caused a refugee from Nazi persecution to wind up in Arabia as the representative of American democracy."
- Faisal spoke in a gentle voice with elliptical comments "capable of many interpretations." He sat at Kissinger's right, looking straight ahead, "occasionally peeking from around his headdress to make sure I had understood the drift of some particular conundrum." Whether discussing the conspiracy of Jews and communists or the practical politics of ending the embargo, the King was apologetic but firm — the oil weapon was a joint Arab decision and its withdrawal must also be joint. His fundamental condition: Jerusalem must become an Arab Islamic city. When asked about the Wailing Wall, Faisal replied another wall could be built somewhere else "against which the Jews could wail."
- Washington turned to Sadat, who had become the chief advocate of ending the embargo he had championed. Like the war itself, Sadat said, the embargo had served its purpose and should end. Continuation could damage relations with Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, and a superpower could not afford to remain "under the gun" indefinitely.
- But Arab exporters were in no hurry to give up their trump card or appear to capitulate to American pressure. As the embargo dragged on, oil seeped back into the market and the cutoffs became less effective. The Saudis indicated the embargo could not end without movement on the Syrian front and tacit acquiescence of Syria's Hafez al-Assad, who held an effective veto because of his fury at Egyptian diplomatic progress.
- In mid-February 1974, Faisal met in Algiers with Sadat, Assad, and the president of Algeria. Sadat made clear the embargo had outlived its usefulness and might work against Arab interests. Faisal agreed to end it provided there was "constructive effort" toward Syrian-Israeli disengagement. Assad maintained a hard line for weeks, but ultimately could not resist the warning that the US peace effort required lifting the embargo. On March 18, 1974, the Arab oil ministers agreed to end the embargo. Syria and Libya dissented.

### Aftermath: The Oil Weapon's Impact

- After two decades of talk and failed attempts, the oil weapon had been used successfully — with impact "not merely convincing, but overwhelming, and far greater than even its proponents might have dared to expect." It recast alignments and geopolitics of the Middle East and the entire world, transformed relations between producers and consumers, and remade the international economy. The threat would remain.
- In May, Kissinger secured Syrian-Israeli disengagement. In June, Nixon visited Israel, Egypt, Syria, and Saudi Arabia. The embargo was history for the US (though still in place against the Netherlands).
- Nixon's behavior on the trip was bizarre. Sitting with the Israeli Cabinet in Tel Aviv, he announced he knew the best way to deal with terrorists, sprang to his feet, and with an imaginary submachine gun pretended to gun down the entire Cabinet, Chicago-style, making a "brrrrr" sound. The Israelis were "perplexed and a little concerned." In Damascus, he told Assad that the Israelis should be pushed back until they fell off the cliff, making strange chopping gestures. Assad would insist on recalling this exposition in subsequent meetings with Americans.
- Nixon's great moment was Egypt, where millions of enthusiastic Egyptians turned out to cheer — his last hurrah. The irony: the land of Nasser, master of anti-American crowds, now cheered the American president, while hostile crowds awaited Nixon at home. For Egyptians it was a celebration of Sadat's restoration of national prestige. For Nixon, it could have been a celebration of the embargo's end and his diplomacy, but he was in poor health, his leg swollen with phlebitis, spending free time listening to incriminating Oval Office tapes that would compel his resignation.

## Chapter 31: OPEC's Imperium

### The OPEC Building

- Times change, empires rise and fall. The modern office building on Vienna's Karl Lueger Ring, with a small bookstore on the ground floor, had customarily been called "the Texaco Building" in honor of its lead tenant. But by the mid-1970s it had abruptly become known as "the OPEC Building." The change symbolized a profound global upheaval: the suddenness with which oil-exporting countries had assumed the position formerly held by the international companies.
- OPEC ended up in Vienna only by accident. Originally established in Geneva, the Swiss doubted its significance and refused diplomatic status. The Austrians, eager for international prestige, were more accommodating — so in 1965 OPEC moved to Vienna. Its lodgment in the Texaco Building showed how little account had been taken of this "rather mysterious and peculiar organization" which, despite initial clamor, had fallen well short of its central political objective — "the assertion of 'sovereignty' by the oil exporters over their resources."
- Now, in the mid-1970s, all had changed. The international order was upside down. OPEC's members were courted, flattered, railed against, and denounced. Oil prices were at the heart of world commerce, and those who controlled them were regarded as the new masters of the global economy. OPEC's membership was virtually synonymous with all the world's petroleum exporters, excepting the Soviet Union. OPEC's members would determine if there was inflation or recession, would be the world's new bankers, and would seek a new international economic order — a wholesale redistribution of economic and political power.
- A former Secretary General of OPEC would look back on 1974-1978 as "OPEC's Golden Age." Yet the OPEC countries completed the acquisition of control over their own resources during these years, settling once and for all who owned their oil. But those years were dominated by a bitter battle not only with consumers but also within OPEC about the price — and that one question would dominate the economic policies and international politics of the entire decade.

### Oil and the World Economy

- The quadrupling of prices brought massive changes to every corner of the world economy. Combined petroleum earnings of oil exporters rose from $23 billion in 1972 to $140 billion by 1977. Exporters built up huge financial surpluses, and the fear that unspent tens of billions sitting idle in bank accounts could spell serious contraction created grave concern for the world's bankers.
- They need not have worried. The exporters, suddenly wealthy, embarked on a dizzying spending program: industrialization, infrastructure, subsidies, services, necessities, luxuries, weapons, waste, and corruption. Ports were clogged far beyond capacity, ships waited weeks to unload, vendors scrambled for rooms in overbooked hotels and elbowed into government ministry waiting rooms. Everything was for sale, and the oil producers now had the money to buy.
- Arms transactions became huge business. To Western industrial nations, securing access to oil became a strategic concern of the first order. Weapons sales were a way to enhance that security and gain influence. The 1973 events had demonstrated the region's volatility — deep rivalries, large ambitions, and the two superpowers had squared off in a nuclear alert over the Middle East.
- The proliferation of Datsun pickup trucks in Saudi Arabia was a sign of the times. "It is very expensive to maintain camels," said a Nissan executive, "it is cheaper to keep a Datsun." A Datsun cost $3,100 while a camel cost only $760, but at twelve cents a gallon for gasoline it was much cheaper to fuel a Datsun than feed a camel. Nissan became the number one vehicle purveyor to Saudi Arabia, and the Datsun pickup was the favorite among sheep-tending Bedouins whose fathers and grandfathers had been the camel-riding backbone of Ibn Saud's armies.
- The massive spending, combined with galloping inflation, ensured that OPEC's financial surpluses soon disappeared. In 1974, OPEC had a $67 billion surplus on balance of payments. By 1978, the surplus had turned into a $2 billion deficit.

### The "OPEC Tax" and Global Recession

- For the industrial West, oil rents flooding into exporter treasuries amounted to a huge withdrawal of purchasing power — the "OPEC tax." This tax sent industrial countries into deep recession. US gross national product plunged 6 percent between 1973 and 1975, while unemployment doubled to 9 percent. Japan's GNP declined in 1974 for the first time since World War II. Sobered Japanese students in Tokyo stopped chanting "Goddamn GNP" at demonstrations and instead found new virtue in hard work and the promise of lifetime employment.
- The price increases delivered a powerful inflationary shock to economies where inflation had already taken hold. While economic growth resumed in 1976, inflation became so embedded in the fabric of the West that it came to be seen as the intractable problem of the modern age.
- The group that suffered most were non-oil developing countries. The price shock was the most devastating blow to economic development in the 1970s — not only the same recessionary and inflationary shocks, but crippled balance of payments that constrained or prevented growth altogether. Many coped by borrowing, and OPEC surplus dollars were "recycled" through the banking system to them. A new category — the "fourth world" — was invented to cover the lower tier of developing countries knocked flat on their backs.
- The oil exporters' new wealth put them in an awkward position vis-a-vis the developing world, since they too proclaimed themselves the vanguard of the "South" fighting Northern "exploitation." Other developing countries initially cheered OPEC, but OPEC's new prices were a huge setback for them. The exporters' main response was to champion a broad "North-South dialogue" tying oil prices to other development issues, with the stated aim of global wealth redistribution.
- The Conference on International Economic Cooperation, meant to embody the North-South dialogue, convened in Paris in 1977. France promoted it as an alternative to American policies. Though it proceeded for two years absorbing much effort, there was little to show — participants could not even agree on a communique. What mattered for the developing world was not the high-minded rhetoric but the reality of depressed markets in the industrial world for their commodities.

### The Saudis Versus the Shah

- OPEC became an international spectacle of the first order in the mid-1970s. Oil talk — "differentials," "seasonal swings," "inventory build" — entered the parlance of policymakers, journalists, and financial speculators. Though usually described as a "cartel," OPEC was not one, properly speaking. Howard Page of Exxon observed in 1975: "You can call OPEC a club or an association but not, properly speaking, a cartel." He cited the Funk & Wagnall's definition — "a combination of producers to regulate the prices and the output of a commodity." OPEC set price but not output. There were no quotas or assigned production levels. The market was really dominated by "a somewhat unruly oligopoly." Most exporters produced at capacity; only Saudi Arabia set production to achieve price objectives.
- OPEC exporters responded to price criticism by noting that Western governments were taking more in tax per barrel than OPEC received in its sales price. In Western Europe in 1975, about 45 percent of what consumers paid went to their government, 35 percent to OPEC, 20 percent to shipping/refining/margins. In the US, the tax component was only 18 percent while OPEC's share was about 50 percent. In Japan, government took 28 percent, OPEC 45 percent. Consumer governments retorted that domestic taxes and the "OPEC tax" were strikingly different in macroeconomic consequences.
- The central concern from 1974 to 1978: would the price of oil go up or stay steady and be eroded by inflation? This was the focus of the running battle between Saudi Arabia and Iran — the two largest producers. In the 1960s they had competed over who would produce more; now they struggled over price and primacy.
- For the Shah, the December 1973 price increase was a great personal victory. He saw it as his moment and opportunity — seemingly endless revenues, as if by divine intervention, to fulfill his ambitions to create "Iran's Great Civilization." "One of the only things my husband likes in life," said the Empress, "is flying, driving, driving boats — speed!" The Shah applied his passion for speed to hurtle Iran into the twenty-first century, ignoring the agitation, disorientation, resentment, and unhappiness among those who did not share his obsession with modernity. Iran would become the world's fifth largest industrial power, a second Japan. "Iran will be one of the serious countries in the world," he boasted. "Everything you can dream of can be achieved here."
- Cut off from reality by oil money, the Shah became consumed by ambitions and dreams and began to believe all the imperial trappings. Who would dare disagree, counsel caution, or deliver bad news? He dismissed Western inflation as justifying still higher prices and discounted the notion that higher oil prices stoked inflation. "The day has passed when the big industrial countries can get away with political and economic pressure tactics," he told the US ambassador. Iran's more limited reserves, compared to Saudi Arabia's, argued for higher prices sooner rather than later. And there was the Shah's pride: "There are some people who thought — and perhaps some who still think — that I am a toy in the Americans' hands. Why would I accept to be a toy? There are reasons for our power which will make us stronger, so why would we be content to be someone else's catspaw?"

### Saudi Opposition to Price Increases

- The Saudis had never approved of the December 1973 price increase — too large, too dangerous to their own position. They feared the economic consequences and were alarmed at losing control over OPEC and the basic decisions about oil so central to the kingdom's future. Owing to their vast reserves, the Saudis had a decisive stake in long-term oil markets. Higher prices could trigger conservation and a shift to alternative fuels that would change and contract the long-term market, diminishing the value of their reserves.
- Saudi Arabia was large in territory but small in population — not much bigger than Hong Kong. Rapid oil revenue buildup could create social and political tensions, weakening ties that held the kingdom together. Nor did the Saudis want higher prices to interfere with Arab-Israeli conflict objectives. They worried about political stability in the industrial and developing world — economic difficulties in mid-1970s Europe seemed to be opening the door to communists, particularly in Italy, deeply unsettling to a Saudi government fearful of Soviet designs.
- The Saudis were also alarmed about Iran. The Shah was too short-sighted, too fired by ambition. Higher prices would give Iran more money and power, enabling more weapons purchases, shifting the strategic balance and encouraging the Shah to claim hegemony over the Gulf. In August 1975, the US ambassador reported from Riyadh that Yamani had said "the talk of eternal friendship between Iran and the United States was nauseating to him and other Saudis. They knew the Shah was a megalomaniac, that he was highly unstable mentally, and that if we didn't recognize this there must be something wrong with our powers of observation." Yamani sounded a warning: "If the Shah departs from the stage, we could also have a violent, anti-American regime in Teheran."
- The Saudis purposefully and forcefully pursued their line against further price increases at meeting after meeting. Their firmness at one point forced OPEC to accept two different prices — a lower one for Saudi Arabia and the UAE, and a higher one for the eleven other members. When others sought justification for price raises, the Saudis would push up production to weaken the market. But in doing so, they made a disconcerting discovery: their sustainable production capacity was not as high as assumed.

### Yamani: The Symbol of the New Age of Oil

- In all these Saudi maneuvers, the spotlight fell on one man — Ahmed Zaki Yamani. To the global oil industry, politicians, journalists, and the world at large, Yamani became the representative and symbol of the new age of oil. His visage, with large, limpid, seemingly unblinking brown eyes and clipped Van Dyke beard, became familiar the planet over. But the world sometimes confused his role and ascribed greater power than he had. He was the representative of Saudi Arabia, albeit enormously important — he could not dictate or solely determine policy, but he could shape it. His longevity augmented his power — he ended up being "there" longer than anyone else.
- Yamani was widely known as "Sheikh," though the title was an honorific assumed by prominent commoners. By background he was a Hijazi, an urban man from the worldly Red Sea coast, rather than a Nejdi from the desert principalities that had provided the original base of Ibn Saud's support. Born in Mecca in 1930, the year St. John Philby convinced King Ibn Saud to allow oil prospecting, Yamani grew up when camels still thronged the streets. He read at night either by oil lamp — "electreeks" — or at the mosque, where electricity had been hooked up.
- His grandfather and father were religious teachers and Islamic lawyers; his father had been grand mufti in the Dutch East Indies and Malaya. This combination of learning and piety shaped Yamani's outlook. After his father's return, the family house in Mecca became a meeting place for students: "Many of them were famous jurists and they would discuss the law with my father and argue cases. I started to join them and often after they left, my father and I would stay up for hours and he would teach me and he would criticize my arguments."
- Yamani studied at university in Cairo, then New York University Law School, followed by a year at Harvard Law School. He developed an intuitive grasp of the West and of how to communicate with Americans. Returning to Saudi Arabia, he set up the first law office in the country, advised government ministries, and wrote the contract for the 1957 concession with Arabian Oil, the Japanese consortium that broke in on the majors in the Middle East.
- Yamani's legal commentaries attracted the attention of Prince Faisal, second son of Ibn Saud, who invited Yamani to become his legal counselor. In 1962, when Faisal emerged triumphant from the power struggle with his brother Saud, one of his first acts was to fire the nationalist oil minister Abdullah Tariki. He appointed the thirty-two-year-old Yamani as successor, whose initial task was to end Tariki's confrontation with Aramco and begin with more subtlety and skill — driving toward the same objectives. "Give me the rantings and ravings of Tariki any day," an Aramco executive complained. "Yamani drives you to the wall with sweet reasonableness."
- By the 1973 embargo, Yamani had been oil minister for eleven years with considerable experience and superb negotiating talents. His voice was soft, forcing adversaries to strain to hear. He almost never lost his temper; the angrier he got, the more quiet he became. He went logically from point to point, dwelling on each long enough to draw out the essence. "It was all so simple and persuasive and so overwhelmingly obvious and irrefutable that only a maniac or a simpleton could disagree. It was a manner of presentation that was mesmerizingly irresistible to many, and absolutely infuriating to others."
- Yamani crafted his mystique: master of patience and of the unblinking stare, always fingering his worry beads, playing chess, pondering his opponent's position. He thought long-term: "In my public life, in my personal life, in everything I do I think long term. Once you start thinking short term, you are in trouble because short-term thinking is only a tactic for immediate benefit." He believed the Western world was afflicted by the curse of short-term thinking, "the inevitable result of democracy." He never gambled: "I can't bear gambling. Yes, I hate it. It rots the soul. I've never been a gambler. Never." In oil politics, "It's always a calculated risk. Oh, I calculate my risks well."
- Many thought him brilliant, a diplomat of high order. "He was a consummate strategist," said one who dealt with him for twenty-five years. "He never went directly to his goal, but he never lost sight of where he wanted to go." In the West he embodied the OPEC Imperium. Within OPEC and the Arab world, some hated him — resenting his prominence or regarding him as too close to the West. Iranian newspapers castigated him as a "stooge of capitalist circles, and a traitor not only to his own King and country but also to the Arab world and the Third World as a whole." The Iraqi oil minister declared Yamani was acting "in the service of imperialism and Zionism." To such rhetoric, the unflappable Yamani reacted with his enigmatic smile and unblinking stare.
- Kissinger commended Yamani in backhanded fashion: "I found him extraordinarily intelligent and well read; he could speak penetratingly on many subjects, including sociology and psychology. His watchful eyes and little Van Dyke beard made him look like a priggish young don playing at oil policy but not really meaning the apocalyptic message he was bringing... In his country at that time, barred by birth from the political leadership reserved for princes and by talent from an ordinary existence, he emerged in a position as essential as it was peripheral to the exercise of real political power within the Kingdom. He became the technician par excellence."
- Yamani was deeply devoted to King Faisal, who regarded him as a favored protege and rewarded him with extensive grants of real estate that skyrocketed during the oil boom, becoming the basis of his personal fortune. Yamani's close relationship with the King gave him carte blanche on oil policy, though always under Faisal's final control and within lines defined by the Royal Family, whose most prominent member on oil after the King was Prince Fahd.

### The Assassination of King Faisal

- In March 1975, Yamani accompanied the visiting Kuwaiti oil minister to an audience with King Faisal. A nephew of Faisal followed the party into the reception room, and as the Kuwaiti knelt before the King, the nephew stepped forward and fired several bullets into Faisal's head, killing him almost instantaneously. The murder was variously attributed to revenge (the nephew's brother had been killed a decade earlier leading a fundamentalist attack on a broadcasting station to protest television), the extreme left, mental derangement, and drugs (the nephew had been prosecuted for selling LSD in Colorado).
- In December 1975, the international terrorist "Carlos" — a fanatic Marxist from Venezuela — led five other terrorists in an attack on the OPEC ministerial meeting in Vienna's Karl Lueger Ring. Three people were killed in the first minutes. The terrorists took the oil ministers and aides hostage and embarked on a harrowing air journey — flying to Algiers, Tripoli, and back to Algiers — threatening to kill the ministers throughout. Two had been sentenced to death: Jamshid Amouzegar of Iran and Yamani, their number-one quarry. On the tense flights, Yamani spent the time playing with his worry beads and reciting Koran verses, convinced he would be a dead man. After forty-four hours, the ordeal ended in Algiers with the suspension of death sentences and release of everyone, including Yamani. Some believed a faction in one of the Arab governments had assisted the terrorists.
- After 1975, Yamani became obsessive about security. And after Faisal's assassination, he never had the same independence on oil. Faisal's successor was his half-brother Khalid, who had a heart condition and did not project himself as a strong leader. Fahd became Crown Prince and Deputy Prime Minister — the chief policymaker on oil and the person to whom Yamani now reported. To the outside world Yamani remained the number-one figure, but within Saudi Arabia it was the careful, cautious Prince Fahd who had the final say. Fahd made clear the opposition to higher prices was Saudi policy, not Yamani's alone. Hiking the price further would spell "economic disaster." In 1977, Fahd vigorously urged President Carter to put pressure on Iran and Venezuela to prevent further price increases.

### America's Strategy

- Whatever the internal OPEC rivalries, there was a general meeting of minds between Riyadh and Washington on oil prices. Through Nixon, Ford, and Carter administrations, the US consistently opposed higher prices. But Washington did not want to aggressively force prices down. "The only chance to bring oil prices down immediately would be massive political warfare against countries like Saudi Arabia and Iran to make them risk their political stability and maybe their security," Kissinger explained in 1975. There was even concern that exporters might suddenly slash prices, undermining expensive new developments like the North Sea, leading to IEA discussions about a "minimum safeguard price" to protect Western energy investment.
- Washington's central objective was stability — building stability into the price and letting inflation erode it. Before every OPEC meeting, the US dispatched emissaries worldwide, armed with statistics on inflation and energy use. At times the Saudis suspected the US was playing a trick, secretly colluding with the Shah to raise prices. Nixon, Ford, and Kissinger were reluctant to push too hard on the Shah, given strategic considerations.
- In an effort to cap prices, Washington flirted with the idea of going into the oil business in partnership with the Soviet Union. Kissinger pursued a "barrels-for-bushels" deal — Soviet oil for American wheat. A preliminary letter of understanding was signed in Moscow in October 1975. Senior Soviet officials came to Washington for intense negotiations. On a weekend break, Gulf Oil whisked the Russian delegation to Disney World. The head of the Soviet delegation explained that the Russians would love to sell their oil but the transaction had to be kept secret — they could not be seen as undercutting OPEC and Third World nationalism. There was also a pricing problem: Kissinger wanted American wheat valued at world prices but Russian oil at 12 percent below world prices. The Russians asked why the disparity — the Americans explained wheat was sold into an established market while Russian oil was entering a new one. Ultimately, the deal fell through. But the Soviet officials "did have a fabulous time at Disney World."
- The American commitment to stable prices put it on a collision course with Iran. When Ford criticized higher prices, the Shah shot back: "No one can dictate to us. No one can wave a finger at us, because we will wave a finger back." Iran was tied politically and economically to the US — government ministers, businessmen, and weapons merchants trouped to Tehran — yet the Shah continued to lecture the West on its weaknesses, and some in Washington questioned "exactly who was whose client."

### The "Blank Check" and the Shah's Shift

- At the beginning of the 1970s, Nixon and Kissinger had established a "blank check" policy — giving the Shah a free hand to buy any American weapons he wanted, even the most technologically advanced, so long as they were not nuclear. This was part of the "twin pillars strategy" for regional security after British withdrawal from the Gulf. Iran and Saudi Arabia were the two pillars, but Iran was clearly the "Big Pillar" — by the mid-1970s, Iran was responsible for fully half of total American arms sales abroad. The Defense Department was alarmed; Defense Secretary Schlesinger cautioned the Shah that Iran lacked the technical resources to assimilate so many complex weapons. "He fell in love with the F-15," said Schlesinger — though the Shah normally brushed aside such warnings, in this case he heeded and did not purchase the F-15.
- Treasury Secretary William Simon called the Shah "a nut." The Shah took strong exception; Simon apologized and explained he meant the Shah was "a nut on oil prices in the way one might say somebody was a nut about tennis or golf." The American ambassador was away from Tehran when this blew up; the Minister of Court replied: "Simon may be a good bond salesman, but he does not know a whole lot about oil." The Shah was reported to have said he knew English and understood "exactly what Mr. Simon meant."
- Despite the friction, a consensus held through Nixon and Ford administrations: Iran was an essential ally, and nothing should undercut the Shah's prestige. Nixon, Ford, and Kissinger had strategic and personal predilections for the Shah — he had not embargoed oil in 1973, and Iran could play a key geopolitical role. Kissinger told colleagues the Saudis were "pussy cats," but with the Shah he could talk geopolitics — Iran shared a border with the Soviet Union.
- The Shah worried about the new Carter Administration in 1977. Carter's policies on human rights and arms sales restrictions were directly threatening. But as Gary Sick of the NSC later wrote, "The United States had no visible strategic alternative to a close relationship with Iran."
- Relations were facilitated by the Shah's shift on oil prices. By the time Carter took office, the Shah was having second thoughts about pushing for higher prices. The freneticism, euphoria, and the oil boom itself were wrecking Iran's social fabric — chaos, waste, inflation, temptation, corruption, and deepening political and social tensions broadening opposition to the regime. Increasing numbers of subjects wanted no part of the Shah's Great Civilization.
- At the end of 1976, the Shah ruefully summed up: "We acquired money we could not spend." Money was not the remedy but the cause of many of Iran's ailments. Higher oil prices would not help. The Carter Administration launched a "price freeze offensive" as central US policy. After Secretary of State Cyrus Vance reassured the Shah about continued support in May 1977, the Iranian government surprised everyone — including its own officials — by calling for moderation on oil prices. The Shah privately told Treasury Secretary Blumenthal that Iran "does not want to be known as a price hawk." Had the number-one price hawk become a dove?
- In November 1977, the Shah came to Washington to meet Carter. At the very moment the Shah arrived at the White House, a battle erupted on the nearby Ellipse among anti- and pro-Shah demonstrators.

### The Shah-Carter Meeting and Price Stabilization

- Police broke up the demonstrators with tear gas. The fumes wafted over the South Lawn where Carter was greeting the Shah. Carter began blinking and rubbing his eyes; the Shah wiped away tears with a handkerchief. The footage was broadcast not only in America but in Iran, owing to new liberalization — giving Iranians a less-than-grand view of their monarch they had never before been permitted. That scene convinced some Iranians the US was about to disengage from the Shah. Why else, not understanding the American system, would Carter have "allowed" such demonstrations?
- In private meetings, Carter lobbied for both human rights and oil price stability. The Shah saw a trade: moderation on oil prices in exchange for continued arms flow and relief from human rights pressure. Carter stressed "the punishing impact of increased oil prices on the industrial economies." Contradicting what he had said since 1973, the Shah agreed to urge other OPEC countries to "give Western nations a break."
- Iran had now joined Saudi Arabia on the side of moderation. With those two countries representing 48 percent of OPEC production, they could dictate to the others and oil prices would be held in check. The battle between the Shah and the Saudis was ended — the Shah had been won over. Through the half-decade from 1974 to 1978, there were only two rather small OPEC-wide price increases: from $10.84 set at Tehran in December 1973 to $11.46 in 1975 and to $12.70 at the end of 1977.
- But inflation was increasing faster than anticipated, eroding the real price. By 1978, the oil price adjusted for inflation was about 10 percent below what it had been in 1974, immediately after the embargo. By restricting increases to two small ones, the real oil price had been lowered somewhat. Oil was not cheap, but neither had the price, as many feared, gone through the roof.

### Kuwait and "Our Friends": The End of Concessions

- If the exporters no longer needed to negotiate over price with anyone except each other, there were still the oil concessions — relics of the days when companies held sway and exporters were poor. The very existence of concessions was now said to be degrading. Mossadegh's nationalization in Iran (1951), Iraq's nationalization of IPC (1972) — while some concessions remained, the termination of the last great ones in Kuwait, Venezuela, and Saudi Arabia would mark the final demise of the concessional system that began with William Knox D'Arcy's bold commitment to Persia in 1901.
- The Kuwait Oil Company, established in 1934 by BP and Gulf, had been the arena for Major Frank Holmes and Ambassador Andrew Mellon's determination. Forty years later, in early 1974, Kuwait acquired 60 percent participation. In early March 1975, Kuwait announced it would take the last 40 percent from BP and Gulf with no special links maintained. "We will just say thank you very much and good bye," said oil minister Abdel Mattaleb Kazemi. "Oil is everything in Kuwait."
- James Lee of Gulf and John Sutcliffe of BP were summoned to Kuwait City. Sutcliffe pleaded: "There should be consideration for the old relationship." The Kuwaiti reply was emphatic: "No compensation was due." They were told firmly that Kuwait intended to take over 100 percent — a matter of sovereignty, not open to debate. The profit split had shifted "from the 50/50 split concept in the early 1960s to the present split of about 98 percent for the Government and 2 percent for the companies."
- BP negotiator P. I. Walters half-jokingly suggested the Kuwaitis invest their new oil wealth in BP shares rather than acquiring the physical assets. The Kuwaitis were not interested — at least not at that time. In December 1975, the two sides came to agreement on Kuwait's terms. Gulf and BP had asked $2 billion in compensation. The Kuwaitis laughed. The companies got $50 million.
- Herbert Goodman of Gulf Oil Trading Company was dispatched to put finishing touches on the new relationship. Goodman was one of the most experienced oil traders in the world — a former Foreign Service officer who had sold over a billion barrels in Japan and Korea in the 1960s. He recalled the glory days: "There was a respect for your credibility, clout, power. Why? It was trade following the flag — the enormous credibility and respect enjoyed by the United States. The American passport was truly a laissez-passer — a safeguard. Then that began to fade. I could feel it everywhere. It was the ebbing of American power — the Romans retreating from Hadrian's Wall."
- Goodman expected Gulf would get some preference reflecting a half-century relationship. But no — Gulf would be treated like any other customer, and would only get oil for its own refineries, not for third-party customers in Japan and Korea. "But those were the markets that Gulf had sweated blood to develop," Goodman protested. The Kuwaitis replied: "It was his blood that had been sweated. Those were their own markets, based upon their oil, and they would sell their oil in those markets."
- The Gulf men noticed how differently they were treated: "We would go from our hotel to the ministry, day after day, and wait. Sometimes, a junior person would come. Sometimes not." When Goodman tried to remind a Kuwaiti official of all Gulf had done for Kuwait, the Kuwaiti became very angry: "Whatever you did, you got paid for. You never did us any favors." Then he walked out. Gulf got a very small discount on oil for its own system, none on oil sold to others. "For the Kuwaitis, it was the overthrow of the colonial power," Goodman reflected. "There was this misunderstanding. Here was the conceit of the Americans that we were loved because we had done so much for these people. This was the American naivete... They saw it from a different point of view. They had always felt patronized. They remembered it."

### Venezuela: The Kitty Cat Died

- Venezuela had passed a "law of reversion" in 1971 stipulating all oil company concessions and assets would revert to Venezuela when concession terms ended, with restricted compensation. The first concessions would start expiring in 1983. Companies slowed investment, causing production to decline. "It was chicken and egg," recalled Robert Dolph of Creole (Exxon's subsidiary). "The policy was that there were no new areas to explore. So we were not feeding the kitty cat, and then they were complaining that the kitty cat is dying."
- By 1972, the government had effective administrative control over every phase of the industry and a 96 percent effective tax rate — nationalization's objectives without nationalization. The 1973 price increase strengthened nationalism and self-confidence, making 1983 too long to wait. Virtually all political factions agreed.
- Two sets of negotiations ensued: one with the international companies (Exxon, Shell, Gulf, and others), and one among Venezuelans themselves. The internal debate was fiercer: "The field had clearly split between those who advocated a violent confrontation with the foreign oil companies and those who preferred a nonviolent, negotiated settlement." Juan Pablo Perez Alfonzo, OPEC's cofounder, weighed in from his garden demanding immediate nationalization of not only oil but all foreign investment.
- The settlement proceeded with less rancor than expected, partly because of the companies' realism. Venezuela had been the source of a substantial part of their profits — at one point half of Exxon's entire global income. "We couldn't win," said Dolph of Creole. "Prices were strong; circumstances in the market were emboldening all the countries." Companies negotiated service contracts (fourteen to fifteen cents a barrel) and long-term supply deals. The first year after nationalization, Exxon signed with Venezuela what was considered the largest single oil supply contract ever — 900,000 barrels per day.
- The harder negotiation was between Venezuelan politicians and Venezuelan oil men. The key question: Would the nationalized industry be a political entity with its agenda set by politicians, or a business run by oil men with a longer time horizon? There was widespread fear of creating "another Pemex" — a bloated, politicized state-within-the-state. President Carlos Andres Perez opted for a "moderate" and pragmatic solution: Petroleos de Venezuela (PDVSA) was established as a state holding company — a buffer between politicians and oil men. Operating companies based on pre-nationalization organizations were created and eventually consolidated to three, each fully integrated down to its own gasoline stations. This quasi-competition would assure efficiency and prevent the growth of another bureaucratic state company. On the first day of 1976, the nationalization took effect. President Perez called it "an act of faith."

### Saudi Arabia: The Concession Surrendered

- What remained was the greatest concession of all — Aramco's in Saudi Arabia. From the bleak 1930s when King Ibn Saud wanted water more than oil, Aramco had grown into a vast enterprise. In June 1974, Saudi Arabia took 60 percent participation. But by year's end, the Saudis told the four Aramco companies — Exxon, Mobil, Texaco, and Chevron — that 60 percent was not enough. They wanted 100 percent. Anything less was humiliating in the new era of oil nationalism.
- The companies dug in — their number-one dictum was "never to give up the concession." It was the most valuable in the world. But even if that rule could not withstand the political pressures of the mid-1970s, the companies would try to make the best deal possible. Negotiations to determine ownership of fully one-third of the free world's oil reserves were arduous and nomadic. For a month in 1975, Aramco representatives encamped with Yamani in Beit Meri, a hill town above Beirut. Each morning, oil men walked from their hotel to an old monastery Yamani had converted into one of his homes. Then word came that a terrorist group might attack, and suddenly the quaint little street looked not quaint but dangerous. They promptly cleared out and thereafter trailed along with Yamani on his global peregrinations.
- Late one night in the spring of 1976, they reached agreement in Yamani's suite at the Al-Yamama Hotel in Riyadh. Forty-three years earlier, Standard of California had reluctantly agreed to make an up-front payment of $175,000 for the right to wildcat in the trackless desert. By 1976, proven reserves in that desert were estimated at 149 billion barrels — more than a quarter of total free world reserves. "It was truly the end of the era," said one of the Americans present at the Al-Yamama Hotel that night.
- Under the new arrangement, Saudi Arabia took ownership of all Aramco assets and rights within the country. Aramco could continue as the operator and provide services for twenty-one cents a barrel. It would market 80 percent of Saudi production. In 1980, Saudi Arabia paid compensation based on net book value. The sun had finally set on the great concessions. The oil producers had achieved their grand objective — they controlled their own oil. These nation-states had become synonymous with petroleum.
- There was one odd thing: the Saudis did not sign the agreement until 1990, fourteen years after it was agreed upon. "It was very practical," said a company negotiator. "They got what they wanted — full control — but they didn't want to disrupt Aramco." About 33 billion barrels and over $700 billion of business was conducted for fourteen years "in limbo."
- While companies retained links through supply contracts in Saudi Arabia, Venezuela, and Kuwait, those connections would weaken over time due to diversification by both sides. At the same time, a new relationship was emerging: instead of "concessionaires" with ownership rights, companies were becoming "contractors" with "production sharing" contracts — pioneered by Indonesia and Caltex in the late 1960s. The shift in terminology reflected an all-important political change: the sovereignty of the country was recognized by both parties. The lingering aura of a colonial past was banished — the companies were there merely as hired hands. By the mid-1970s, production sharing contracts were becoming common worldwide.

### The Changing Global Oil Industry

- Meanwhile, the amount of oil sold directly by exporters into the market — without the companies as middlemen — quintupled from 8 percent of total OPEC output in 1973 to 42 percent by 1979. The state-owned companies of oil-producing countries were moving downstream, beyond production, into the international oil business outside their own borders. In little more than half a decade, the global oil industry had taken on a completely new form under the OPEC Imperium. Even more dramatic changes were ahead.

## Chapter 32: The Adjustment

### The End of Cheap Oil and the Western Response

- Did the end of cheap oil mean the end of the road for Hydrocarbon Man? In the 1950s and 1960s, cheap and easy oil had fueled economic growth and promoted social peace. Now, expensive and insecure oil was going to constrain, stunt, or even eradicate economic growth. One of the great lessons of the interwar decades was how central economic growth was to the vitality of democratic institutions. After 1973, the industrial nations found their sovereignty diminished, their security threatened, and their foreign policies constrained. "The very substance of power in international politics seemed to have been transmuted by its oleaginous reaction with petroleum." The 1970s became a time of "rancor, tension, unease, and gritty pessimism."
- Yet Hydrocarbon Man would not easily surrender his postwar legacy. A massive adjustment began. The IEA turned out to be not the agent of confrontation the French had predicted, but an instrument for coordination — bringing Western energy policies into parallel. Emergency sharing procedures were worked out, along with targets for government-controlled strategic reserves of oil. The IEA also provided a forum for research on conventional and new energy sources.
- The central goal came down to changing what Kissinger described as the "objective conditions" from which oil power derived — the supply-demand balance and overall reliance on oil. Each major consuming country proceeded in its own characteristic way: Japan with a public-private consensus, France with dirigisme and state direction, the United States with its usual fractious political debate. But the elements were the same: alternative fuels, diversified oil sources, and conservation.

### Nations Respond: Japan

- After the initial panic, Japan began to marshal its responses. MITI made a "personal statement" by curtailing elevator service in its own headquarters. To reduce the need for air conditioning, Japan promoted the shoene rukku or "energy conservation look" — business suits with short-sleeve jackets. While the elevator service remained curtailed, the new suits, though advocated by Prime Minister Masayoshi Ohira himself, never caught on.
- Japan was committed to drastically altering its energy position, which since the early 1960s had been based on cheap Middle Eastern oil — no longer cheap or secure. Responses included conversion of electric generation and industrial production from oil to other fuels, acceleration of nuclear power development, expansion of coal and liquefied natural gas imports, and diversification of oil imports away from the Middle East toward the Pacific Rim. "Resource diplomacy" came to the fore in Japan's international relations.
- The most concentrated effort was the government-business drive to promote energy conservation in industry and reduce oil use. The campaign's success far exceeded expectations and was of key importance to Japan's renewed international competitiveness. "Both workers and business leaders were very apprehensive after 1973," recalled Naohiro Amaya, then Vice-Minister of MITI. "They feared for the survival of their companies, and so everybody worked together."
- In 1971, MITI had conducted a study on the need to shift from "energy-intensive" to "knowledge-intensive" industry. Heavy industries had not liked the study, which implied they were lame ducks. But the 1973 crisis provided the force to implement the strategy at breakneck speed. "Instead of using the resources in the ground, we would use the resources in our head," said Amaya. "The Japanese people are accustomed to crises like earthquakes and typhoons. The energy shock was a kind of earthquake, and so even though it was a great shock, we were prepared to adjust." He added: "In a way, it was a kind of blessing, because it forced the rapid change of Japanese industry."

### Nations Respond: France

- In France, the most senior energy official was Jean Blancard, an engineer from the elite Corps des Mines. Even as Paris pursued conciliatory bilateral policies toward oil producers, Blancard was arguing to President Pompidou: "The period from here on will be quite different — a transformation, not a crisis... It is not reasonable for such a country as ours to be hanging on the Arabs' decisions. We must pursue a policy of diversification of energy and try to decrease the need for oil — or at least not allow it to increase."
- Pompidou, seriously ill with swollen features from his treatment, convened his senior advisers in early 1974. Despite great pain during the long meeting, the discussion confirmed three basic planks of French energy policy: rapid development of nuclear power, a return to coal, and heavy emphasis on energy conservation — all designed to restore France's autonomy. Pompidou died less than a month later, but his successor Valery Giscard d'Estaing pushed ahead on all three. With a government system much more impervious to outside interveners like environmentalists, France would within a few years outstrip all other Western countries in its commitment to nuclear power.
- France also developed the most aggressive government policy on energy conservation. Inspectors would swoop down on banks, department stores, and offices to do "le check up" — measuring inside temperature with special thermometers. If the temperature exceeded the officially approved twenty-degree-centigrade level, fines would be levied on the building management.
- Perhaps the most striking aspect of France's conservation program was a ban on any advertising that "encouraged" energy consumption. Exxon's tiger was tamed in France — no longer in the tank, he was judiciously advising motorists to check their tires and tune their engines. Gasoline stations could not give away the usual trinkets — mugs, glasses, spoons, decals — as such gifts would encourage consumption. The only permitted giveaway: cheap tool kits, but only if they contained a brush for cleaning spark plugs to promote higher efficiency.
- The French national oil company Total tried putting up billboards showing green French countryside with the legend "This is France" signed "Total." The ad was banned. A stunned Total asked why. Jean Syrota of the Energy Conservation Agency explained: "Consumers look at this ad and say, 'Oil companies are wasting a great deal of money on such ads, therefore the companies must be rich, therefore there must not be any energy problem, therefore it is all right to waste energy.'"

### "Obscene Profits" and the Jackson Hearings

- In the halls of Congress, Senators and Congressmen held hearings on the energy crisis and the oil companies' role. The most dramatic were held by the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations, chaired by Senator Henry "Scoop" Jackson — a hard-headed Truman Democrat who, as he liked to say, had his head "screwed on straight." Nixon would fume in private at what he called "Scoop Jackson's demagoguery." A White House aide explained to the irate Nixon that "our troops in the Interior Committee have a major inferiority complex when it comes to Jackson, because, frankly, he Scoops the hell out of them."
- Jackson's hearings were one of the greatest political scoops of his career. Senior executives of the seven largest oil companies were lined up at one table and made to testify under oath. Flooded by television lights, they were subjected to withering questioning about operations and profits. The executives, whatever their skills at geology or chemical engineering, were no match for Jackson and the other Senators at political theater. "They came across as inept, insulated, self-satisfied, and out of touch."
- The timing was exquisite: oil companies were reporting huge profit increases while the embargo was still in effect. In an atmosphere of distrust and hostility, Jackson announced his subcommittee would find out if there was really an oil shortage. "The American people want to know if this so-called energy crisis is only a pretext; a cover to eliminate the major source of price competition — the independents, to raise prices, to repeal environmental laws, and to force adoption of new tax subsidies... Gentlemen, I am hopeful that we will receive the answers to these and other questions before we leave here today. If not, I can assure you we will get the answers one way or another in the days ahead."
- The company executives tried to defend themselves. The president of Gulf U.S. protested: "The contrivance theory is absolute nonsense... I know people are a bit mystified by the rapid turn of events." A Texaco vice-president declared: "We have not cheated or misled anyone." When an Exxon vice-president could not recall the amount of his company's 1973 dividend, Jackson scathingly called him "childish."
- The oil men were humiliated, sobered, and infuriated. Jackson's line, though "perhaps not quite up to Eugene O'Neill, nevertheless won thunderous applause across the country." The companies were guilty of making "obscene profits." "We didn't have a chance," complained Gulf's bloodied president. Jackson knew he spoke for many Americans — the two gasoline stations near his house were always closed by the time he headed home. He was outraged by what he saw as "the arrogance and greed of the oil companies" and proposed they be chartered by the Federal government. Jackson succeeded in turning "obscene profits" into a national catch phrase. When Exxon released its 1973 earnings — up 59 percent over 1972 — on the third day of hearings, chairman Kenneth Jamieson felt constrained to declare, "I am not embarrassed." Many thought otherwise.
- The oil companies became among the most unpopular institutions in America. Some Japanese publications ran articles about how American companies had planned the crisis to raise profits. A confidential planning document at one of the largest oil companies warned in 1976: "The future for private oil companies is much less certain. The trend for upstream operations to pass into government hands will continue, with companies filling a contractor role." In 1977, a senior Shell executive opined: "Paradoxically, the threat to the viability of an oil company may today come more from the importing than the exporting governments."
- The companies had been nationalized in producing nations, no longer owned the oil or set prices. Now consuming governments were hammering them too. The hallowed depletion allowance was sharply curtailed; so was the foreign tax credit, the "golden gimmick" used since WWII to facilitate oil development in Venezuela and the Middle East. There were continuing efforts to roll back oil prices, political pressure to keep down natural gas prices, and a movement for "divestiture" — breaking up integrated companies into separate firms for each segment. At one point, forty-five out of one hundred Senators voted in favor of divestiture. The industry called it "dismemberment."

### The Facts Behind "Obscene Profits"

- Profits of the largest oil companies had been almost perfectly flat for five years through 1972, despite explosive demand growth. Profits then rose from $6.9 billion in 1972 to $11.7 in 1973 to $16.4 billion in the banner year of 1974. Much of the increase came from foreign operations — as exporting countries pushed prices up, companies got a free ride on non-US equity oil they still owned, plus gains from buying oil at lower prices and selling at $11.65 after inventory. Their chemical operations had also done well, helped by a weak dollar.
- But profits dropped back to $11.5 billion in 1975, lower than 1973. Demand was down from recession, and exporting countries raised taxes to capture rents from the companies. Over the next few years, profits rose to $15 billion in 1978, which in real terms meant they were just about keeping up with inflation. Rates of return were, except for 1974, somewhat below the average rate for all American industry.
- Profits were concentrated in the upstream — crude oil and natural gas production. The value of reserves in the US and North Sea had increased with the oil price. The downstream — refineries, tankers, gasoline stations — had been built before 1973 on expectations of 7-8 percent annual oil demand growth. Actual demand was much lower, so downstream capacity was bloated far beyond requirements. A third of the tanker fleet was in surplus. This overcapacity, combined with loss of equity crude in the Middle East, made international oil companies question the rationale of the large downstream systems built in Europe in the 1950s-1960s for the disposal of Middle Eastern oil now taken away from them.

### The United States Energy Policy: "Chinese Water Torture"

- Despite strong consensus internationally through Nixon, Ford, and Carter Administrations on energy policy, no similar agreement existed domestically. Energy policy was marked by divisive, angry, bitter, confused debate about price controls and company practices. Nixon's resignation in August 1974 and Watergate had left a crippling crisis of confidence and a pervasive suspicion about the energy crisis itself.
- Oil and energy became the hottest cauldron in national politics. Nixon had imposed economy-wide price controls in August 1971; most expired by 1974, but not those on oil. The politics gave rise to "an awesome Rube Goldberg system of price controls, entitlements, and allocations that made the mandatory oil import program of the 1960s appear, by comparison, to have the simplicity of a haiku."
- The public wanted Washington to do "something" — return prices to the good old days while assuring adequate supplies. Markets were confused and distorted. "For every problem you solve, it seems you create two more," moaned one government regulator. Acquiring entitlements to crude supplies became a big business, leading to the return of hopelessly inefficient "tea kettle" refineries. "For the oil industry, the Federal Register became more important than the geologist's report." The costs were enormous — the Federal Energy Administration alone involved 200,000 respondents committing an estimated five million man-hours annually. Direct regulatory costs ran to several billion dollars in the mid-1970s.

### Ford's Grand Plan and Two Key Achievements

- In January 1975, President Ford proposed a grand ten-year plan to build 200 nuclear power plants, 250 major coal mines, 150 coal-fired power plants, 30 major oil refineries, and 20 major synthetic fuel plants. Vice-President Nelson Rockefeller — grandson of the man who personified the monolith of oil — championed an even grander $100 billion program to subsidize synthetic fuels. But opponents challenged the costs, and the Rockefeller initiatives came to naught.
- There were two highly significant achievements during the Nixon-Ford years. Congress gave a green light to the Alaskan oil pipeline (TAPS), which ended up costing ten billion dollars. TAPS — the Trans-Alaskan Pipeline — made possible what proved to be the single most important new contribution to American energy supply since Dad Joiner's discovery of the East Texas field in the 1930s.
- The other landmark was the 1975 fuel efficiency standards for the automobile industry. Average fuel efficiency would have to double over ten years, from 13 miles per gallon to 27.5 miles per gallon. Since one out of every seven barrels of oil used in the world daily was burned as motor fuel on America's roads, this change would have major impact on the world's oil balance. The legislation also established a strategic petroleum reserve — the same idea Eisenhower had proposed after the 1956 Suez crisis. In practice, the rate of fill proved fatally slow.

### Carter, Schlesinger, and the "Moral Equivalent of War"

- In 1977, Jimmy Carter became President, having campaigned as an outsider promising moral renewal. Energy had engaged his attention for years — as a former Navy submariner, he remembered Admiral Hyman Rickover's warning about exhausting nature's oil stock. He had promised a national energy policy within ninety days and was dedicated to keeping his word.
- He gave the job to James Schlesinger, a Ph.D. economist who combined powerful analytic intelligence with "intellectual zeal and moral fervor." Nixon had plucked Schlesinger from the Rand Corporation to head the Bureau of the Budget, then the Atomic Energy Commission, then the CIA, and then made him Secretary of Defense. On weekends, Schlesinger could be found bird-watching around Washington with binoculars. His tenure at Defense ended under Ford when he took exception to Kissinger's detente policy.
- Carter phoned Schlesinger after the Democratic Convention and invited him to Plains, Georgia. Schlesinger was close to Senator Henry Jackson — the single most important Senator on energy — and Carter's rival for the nomination. Jackson pressed Carter to make Schlesinger the energy champion. Carter was more than willing. "It was kind of convenient if the chairman of the Senate Energy Committee was a pal of your proto-energy secretary," Schlesinger noted.
- Carter read a late-1976 CIA report predicting future oil shortages and found it compelling. Schlesinger shared Carter's deep concern about foreign policy implications of a tight oil market. As Carter wrote in his memoirs, many Americans "deeply resented that the greatest nation on earth was being jerked around by a few desert states."
- In 1972, while at the Atomic Energy Commission, Schlesinger had expressed a then-heretical idea: that the US should promote energy conservation on grounds of national security, economic policy, and environmental improvement. "We can do somewhat better than automobiles that move at 10 miles to the gallon and badly insulated buildings that are simultaneously heated and cooled." By 1977, he was more convinced than ever that conservation should be central to energy policy. Unfortunately, "that premise was considerably more obvious to him than to many others."
- The Administration kept its energy program development secret, leaving no time to build consensus. Schlesinger asked Carter to relent on the ninety-day deadline. "I said 90 days," Carter firmly replied. "I made the pledge and I intend to keep it." Carter himself complained to Schlesinger: "Our basic & most difficult question is how to raise the price of scarce energy with minimum disruption of our economic system and greater equity in bearing the financial burden. I am not satisfied with your approach. It is extremely complicated." Then plaintively: "I can't understand it."
- The plan was unveiled in early April in a fireside Presidential address. On a TV interview the Sunday before, Schlesinger quoted William James — "the moral equivalent of war" — to capture the magnitude of the energy challenge. Carter was impressed and put it into his speech. He introduced his energy program as "the moral equivalent of war," and by that sobriquet it would often be known. Its detractors preferred the acronym: "Meow."
- The Carter program included a host of initiatives: introducing economic rationality into pricing, reducing the need for imported oil. Schlesinger's number-one priority was to let domestic oil under price controls rise to world market prices so consumers would react to correct price signals. The Carter program proposed ending price controls through a "crude oil equalization tax." Ironically, it had been the Republican Nixon who originally imposed price controls in 1971, and now a Democratic Administration was trying to lift them. Carter and Schlesinger also sought to extract the country from the straitjacket of natural gas price controls, put greater emphasis on conservation and coal, introduce competition into the electricity sector, and encourage alternative energy sources including solar power.
- Carter received a firsthand education in how special interests operate: liberals, conservatives, oil producers, consumer groups, automobile companies, pro- and anti-nuclear activists, coal producers, utility companies, environmentalists — all with conflicting agendas. To Schlesinger, the issue was clear: "a substantial long-run national problem." But he was unprepared for the storm of debate and the bitterness. "There are three kinds of lies — lies, damn lies, and energy lies," an old veteran at the Atomic Energy Commission had told him. Schlesinger later said: "I have a sort of World War II mentality. If the President says something is in the national interest, I had assumed he would get a more supportive response than we found. As Secretary of Defense, everyone not against you is with you. Here, on energy, you had interest groups against interest groups. You couldn't put a consensus together. It was distressing."
- Natural gas proved the most contentious issue — a decades-old theological struggle over whether prices should be controlled by government or set by the market. Schlesinger said of the Senate-House conferences: "I understand now what Hell is. Hell is endless and eternal sessions of the natural gas conference." A very intricate compromise was eventually arranged.
- A number of different categories for pricing purposes were created for a commodity that was composed of the same standard molecules of one carbon atom and four hydrogen atoms. Despite the bloody political battles and exhaustion of much political capital, the Carter Administration could claim important accomplishments. "Passage of the National Energy Act represents a watershed in that it starts the adjustment of our demands to the means available," Schlesinger told a London audience. But he ruefully observed: "The response was less close to William James' moral equivalent of war than to the political equivalent of the Chinese water torture."

### Boom Times: The Exploration Rush

- By end of 1978, post-embargo policies were just beginning to have their influence felt. But one reaction to the embargo was virtually instantaneous: the price hikes, expectation of future increases, expanded cash flows, and investor eagerness combined to ignite a frenetic global hunt for oil. "It's just wild," said Exxon's deputy exploration manager. What had been a depressed exploration business through 1972 was now running at capacity. The cost of everything — from semi-submersible drilling rigs to old-fashioned Oklahoma land crews — doubled from 1973 levels.
- The flow of investment was redirected in a very substantial way. The number-one commandment was to avoid nationalism in the Third World. Exploration in most OPEC countries was foreclosed by nationalization, and there was a strong presupposition that success in other developing countries would be seized. Companies redirected exploration spending to the industrial world: the United States (despite pessimism about its oil potential), Canada, and the British and Norwegian sectors of the North Sea. In 1975, Gulf undertook a complete global budget review — every investment dollar not nailed down was "quietly yanked out of the Third World and brought back to North America and the North Sea." By 1976, Royal Dutch/Shell was concentrating 80 percent of its worldwide non-US production expenditures in the North Sea. "After 1973 and nationalization, you had to go hunt your rabbits in a different field," recalled an Exxon executive.
- Oil companies also began to diversify into totally different businesses — reflecting the view that the business and political environment might grow "more and more narrow, more and more harsh, more and more constrained by government intervention and regulation." There was also a nagging fear that the days of oil itself might be numbered by geological depletion — between 1970 and 1976, proven American oil reserves dropped by 27 percent and gas reserves by 24 percent. Mobil bought the Montgomery Ward department store chain, Exxon went into office automation, ARCO into copper. But nothing aroused so much mirth and derision as Gulf's bid for Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus — seeming to prove that the new era of OPEC's imperium, high oil prices, confusion, bitter debates, and energy wars in Washington "really was a circus."

### New Supplies: Alaska and Mexico

- OPEC continued to dominate the world oil market throughout the 1970s — 65 percent of total "free world" oil production in 1973 and 62 percent in 1978. But its grip was beginning to loosen. The incentive of price and the motive of security were stimulating oil development outside OPEC. Three new oil provinces would have overwhelming influence: Alaska, Mexico, and the North Sea. Ironically, each had been identified before the 1973 price hike but not yet developed due to various mixtures of politics, economics, environmental opposition, technical obstacles, and the long leads required by major energy projects.
- With the emergency go-ahead on the Alaskan pipeline after the embargo, work proceeded rapidly. The steel pipe and tractors, purchased in 1968, had sat on the frozen banks of the Yukon River for five years, engines dutifully turned over on schedule. By 1977, the eight-hundred-mile pipeline was completed — some parts suspended on stilts above the tundra — and the first oil made the journey from the North Slope to the shipping port at Valdez. By 1978, over a million barrels per day were flowing. Within a few years, the flow would be two million barrels per day — a quarter of America's total crude oil production.
- In Mexico, Pemex had been the national oil company and embodiment of Mexican nationalism since the fiery 1930s nationalization. It devoted itself to supplying the domestic market, subject to a struggle for control between the government and the powerful oil workers' union. Pemex did relatively little to expand its reserve base; as the "Mexican economic miracle" grew, Mexico ceased being an exporter and actually became a minor oil importer, though effort went into disguising that fact.
- In 1972, Pemex launched a deep-drilling program in Tabasco's rolling savannas and struck an extraordinary structure called Reforma. The highly productive wells led to the region being dubbed "Little Kuwait," followed by further very large discoveries in the adjacent offshore Bay of Campeche. Mexico possessed world-class oil reserves.
- New President Jose Lopez Portillo, taking over in 1976 from the radical Echeverria, inherited Mexico's worst economic crisis since the Great Depression — the peso had collapsed, the economy stalled, and one out of every two Mexicans was under fifteen while 40 percent of the workforce was unemployed or underemployed. There were even rumors of a possible military coup.
- Lopez Portillo appointed his old friend Jorge Diaz Serrano to head Pemex. Unlike his predecessor (a bridge construction engineer), Diaz Serrano knew the oil industry — he had become a millionaire supplying services. Oil would provide Mexico with foreign earnings, remove the constraint on balance of payments, provide collateral for international borrowing, and put Mexico at the center of the new oil-based international economy. Lopez Portillo cautioned: "The capacity for monetary digestion is like that of a human body. You can't eat more than you can digest or you become ill." But his actions spoke louder — investment poured in, reserves were expanded rapidly, production surged from 500,000 barrels in 1972 to 830,000 in 1976 to 1.9 million barrels in 1980, almost a fourfold increase in less than a decade.
- Mexico went from being avoided by international lenders to becoming one of the most active borrowers. "Why the Bankers Suddenly Love Mexico" headlined Fortune. "Every Tom, Dick, and Harry in banking is knocking on their door," said the vice-chairman of Manufacturers Hanover Trust. One Mexican official was chosen "borrower of the year" in 1978 by a New York financial newsletter. Mexico had become a major new force in the world oil market, as it had not been since the 1920s, providing yet another alternative source of supply undermining OPEC's imperium.

### The North Sea: The Biggest Play of All

- For centuries, fishermen had the North Sea to themselves. By the mid-1970s, a helicopter view revealed floating drilling rigs, supply boats, platforms, pipe-laying barges — singly at first, then in such profusion as almost to crowd the sea. Here was the biggest new play for the world oil industry and its single greatest concentration of capital investment and effort. No major company dared to be left out, and many new players were drawn in — from Edinburgh investment trusts to Lord Thomson, the newspaper tycoon who owned the Times of London and was a partner of Armand Hammer.
- Ever since 1920, thousands of onshore wells in Western Europe had been drilled with disappointing results — total production never exceeded 250,000 barrels per day. The Suez crisis of 1956 boosted the search for secure European oil and gas. In 1959, Shell and Esso discovered the vast Groningen gas field in Holland, the largest then known outside the USSR. Realizing the North Sea's geology matched Holland's, companies began exploring adjacent waters. In 1965, Britain and Norway agreed to divide the North Sea right down the middle.
- Phillips Petroleum from Bartlesville, Oklahoma, began exploring in 1962 after its vice-chairman noticed a drilling derrick near Groningen during a Netherlands vacation. By 1969, after a string of dry holes — some thirty-two wells on the Norwegian shelf, not one commercial — Bartlesville's message was clear: "Don't drill any more wells." But Phillips had already paid for the rig Ocean Viking and could not sublease it. In the grand tradition stretching back to Colonel Drake, they decided on one more go. The weather was terrible — the rig broke from its anchors, and one night a capsize seemed so likely that emergency evacuation was initiated. But in November 1969, the Ocean Viking made a major find on Block 2/4 — the Ekofisk field, on the Norwegian side of the median line. The drilling superintendent examined the oil sample: "What the astronauts have done is great, but how about this?" It had a golden sheen, "almost transparent, but definitely almost like gold."
- Phillips's discovery set all companies to re-evaluating their data and stepping up activity. When asked what methods Phillips used to diagnose the geology, a senior Phillips executive replied: "Luck." Toward end of 1970, BP announced the discovery of oil in the Forties field on the British side, one hundred miles northwest of Ekofisk — a huge reservoir. Major strikes followed in 1971, including Shell and Exxon's discovery of the huge Brent field. The North Sea oil rush was on, and the 1973 crisis turned it into a roar.
- The venture was risky and dangerous. Drilling rigs had to work through water depths much greater than anything tried before, then drill another four miles under the seabed. "There's nothing quite as vile as the North Sea when she's in a temper," lamented one skipper. Weather could change three or four times a day; waves of fifty feet and winds of seventy miles an hour were not uncommon. Platforms — really small industrial cities set on man-made islands — had to stand on mud, quicksand, clay, and sand wave bottoms and withstand the fury of a "100-year wave" ninety feet high, as well as winds of 130 miles per hour.
- On June 18, 1975, British Secretary of State for Energy Anthony Wedgwood Benn turned a valve on an oil tanker in the Thames estuary. The first North Sea oil flowed ashore. Publicly, Benn enthusiastically declared June 18 should be a day of national celebration. Personally, he did not enjoy the inaugural at all — a leader of the Labour left with a passion for nationalization and inbred detestation of capitalism, especially as represented by the oil industry. He sourly noted in his diary that he had been forced to participate "in the company of a complete cross-section of the international capitalist and British Tory establishment." When he turned the valve, the oil "allegedly went on shore," he added with great suspicion.
- Benn played a leading role in replicating the traditional battle between governments and oil companies. Now that reserves had been proved and risks reduced, the British government wanted a larger share of the rents and more control. "Oil companies can jump over national boundaries to save on taxes more easily than a kangaroo pursued by a dingo can jump over a fence," complained Lord Balogh, Benn's Minister of State. The result was a special tax on oil revenues and the establishment of the British National Oil Corporation (BNOC) — with 51 percent participation in North Sea production, meant to be the national champion. One company head finally exploded: "I don't see any difference any more between those OPEC countries and Britain."
- Prime Minister Harold Wilson, puffing his pipe at 10 Downing Street in the summer of 1975, was ruminating on how Britain's oil production could grow to perhaps two and a half million barrels per day, transforming Britain's prospects and the balance of oil power. He was already thinking like the prime minister of an oil country. At the time, the Ford Administration was campaigning against higher oil prices. "We do have an interest in seeing that the price of oil doesn't fall too much," Wilson said. "If America wanted to really bring down the price, not many people here would necessarily agree." Wilson was sitting in the same room that Anthony Eden had used two decades earlier during the Suez crisis. Wilson confessed an ambition that might have shocked Eden: as leader of a newly emerging major oil power, Wilson genially said he hoped he might be chairman of OPEC by 1980.

### "The Crunch": Oil Price Forecasting and the Consensus of 1978

- One peculiar result of the 1973 price shock was the rise of oil price forecasting as a new line of work. Before 1973, it had not been necessary — prices changed in cents, not dollars, and were more or less flat. After 1973, oil price movements were decisive not only for energy industries but for a multitude of businesses from airlines to agricultural cooperatives, for governments, and for the international economy. "Birds do it, bees do it, even educated fleas do it" — everyone was in the forecasting business. Oil companies, governments, central banks, international organizations, brokerage houses, banks all did it.
- This forecasting was as much art as science. Judgments and assumptions governed predictions. Moreover, forecasting was much affected by the "community" in which it was done — a psychological and sociological phenomenon reflecting peer influence, the groping for certainty and mutual comfort in an uncertain world. The result was a strong tendency toward consensus, even when the consensus completely changed its tune every couple of years.
- By 1978, a clear consensus existed: while Alaska, Mexico, and the North Sea would together add six to seven million barrels per day by the early-to-mid 1980s, these new sources would serve only as a supplement, holding off and postponing but not decisively banishing the inevitable day of shortage and reckoning. Most forecasters agreed another oil crisis was highly probable a decade hence — in the second half of the 1980s — when demand would once again be at the very edge of available supply. The result would be an "energy gap," a shortage, resolved by another major price increase. There was considerable unanimity on this central theme, whether from the CIA, oil companies, Western governments, international agencies, or OPEC itself.
- The single most important assumption was the "Iron Law" — that there was an inevitably close relationship between economic growth rates and oil use. If the economy grew at 3-4 percent, oil demand would also grow at 3-4 percent. The facts of 1976-1978 seemed to confirm this: economic growth had rebounded, averaging 4.2 percent, and oil demand had grown at about 4 percent. The future picture was a projection of these current circumstances. The future effects of conservation were discounted. The stage was set for a repetition of 1973.
- Yamani, departing from his customary advocacy of price stability, began to argue for regular, small increases that would encourage conservation and alternative sources — much preferable to the wrenching increase everyone now expected. "From our own studies and from all the reliable studies I have read," he said in June 1978, "there are very strong indications that there will be a shortage of supply of oil sometime around the mid-1980s if not before... No matter what we do, that date is coming."
- It was also generally agreed that conditions did not point to any major price increase in the near term. That was a view based on economics; politics, however, was never easy to fit into models dealing with growth rates and elasticities of demand. And politics was not about to allow anyone the luxury of a long-term strategy.

### Carter's New Year's Eve Toast in Tehran

- On the last day of 1977, President Carter, en route from Warsaw to New Delhi, arrived in Tehran. He said he had asked Mrs. Carter where she wanted to spend New Year's Eve, and she had said with the Shah and his wife — so delightful a time the Carters had had when the royal couple visited Washington six weeks earlier. There were reasons of realpolitik behind the sentiment. Carter had been impressed by the Shah, who was taking steps toward liberalization and talking about human rights. Iran was a fulcrum country, essential to regional stability, critical in counterbalancing Soviet power, and central to the security of the world's oil supplies.
- Carter also wanted to show gratitude for the Shah's shift on human rights and oil prices, and was regretful and embarrassed about the tear gas incident at the White House. At a New Year's Eve banquet, Carter rose to offer a memorable toast: "Iran, because of the great leadership of the Shah, is an island of stability in one of the more troubled areas of the world. This is a great tribute to you, Your Majesty, and to the respect and the admiration and the love which your people give you." On that strong and hopeful note, the President and the Shah welcomed the momentous New Year of 1978.
- Not everyone saw the same island of stability. Shortly after Carter's visit, the president of one of the independent American oil companies active in Iran came back from Tehran with an urgent confidential message: "The Shah is in big trouble."

## Chapter 33: The Second Shock: The Great Panic

### The Newspaper Article That Triggered Revolution

- A week after Carter's departure from Iran, a Tehran newspaper published a savage attack on Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, an implacable opponent of the Shah living in exile in Iraq. The article, though anonymous, appeared to be the work of a regime official. Perhaps the Carter visit had bolstered flagging confidence. But the article was already in the works — exasperation was increasing with Khomeini's harsh attacks on the Shah's government, which were being circulated clandestinely on cassettes throughout Iran.
- Animosity between the royal house and the Shiite clergy dated back to Reza Shah's fierce battle for power with the Shiite clergy in the 1920s and 1930s — part of the larger struggle between secular and religious forces. But that newspaper article of January 7, 1978, triggered a wholly new stage in the struggle.

### Disillusion and Opposition

- It had become evident in the mid-1970s that Iran simply could not absorb the vast increase in oil revenues flooding in. The petrodollars, megalomaniacally misspent on extravagant modernization programs or lost to waste and corruption, were generating economic chaos and social and political tension throughout the nation. The rural populace poured from villages into already-overcrowded towns and cities; agricultural output was declining while food imports rose. Inflation had seized control of the country. A middle manager or civil servant in Tehran spent up to 70 percent of his salary on rent. Iran's infrastructure could not cope — the backward railway system was overwhelmed, Tehran's streets were jammed with traffic, the national electricity grid broke down. Parts of Tehran and other cities were regularly blacked out, sometimes for four or five hours a day — a disaster for industrial production and domestic life.
- Iranians from every sector of national life were losing patience with the Shah's regime and the pell-mell rush to modernization. Grasping for some certitude in the melee, they increasingly heeded the call of traditional Islam and of an ever more fervent fundamentalism. The beneficiary was Ayatollah Khomeini, whose religious rectitude and unyielding resistance made him the embodiment of opposition to the Shah and his regime, and indeed to the very character and times of Iran in the mid-1970s.
- Khomeini was born around 1900 in a small town 180 miles from Tehran, into a family of religious teachers. His father was killed by a government official a few months after his birth; his mother died when he was in his teens. He turned to religious studies and by the 1930s-1940s was a popular lecturer on Islamic philosophy and law, promulgating the concept of an Islamic Republic under the stern control of the clergy.
- Khomeini had regarded the Pahlavi regime as corrupt and illegitimate, but did not become politically active until about sixty. In 1962, he emerged as a leading figure in the opposition to the Shah's "White Revolution" reform program — opposing, among other things, the proposal that places in local assemblies no longer be restricted exclusively to male Moslems. When the government redistributed large estates including vast Shiite clergy holdings, Khomeini came forward as one of the most unyielding opponents, landing in jail more than once and eventually ending up in exile in Iraq. His hatred of the Shah was matched only by his detestation of the United States. His denunciations from exile were cast in the rhetoric of blood and vengeance; he seemed driven by unadulterated anger of extraordinary intensity, and he himself became the rallying point for the growing discontent.

### The Human Rights Dimension

- Another dimension of opposition had emerged. With Carter's election, human rights became a major issue in US foreign policy. The Shah's human rights record was not good — typical of much of the Third World, and better than some other countries in the region. A member of the International Commission of Jurists concluded in 1976 that the Shah was "way down the list of tyrants. He would not even make the A-list." Still, Savak, the Iranian secret police, was "brutal, quick, and particularly nasty in its torture; it was also callous, stupid, intrusive, pervasive, and arbitrary." None of this fit the image of the Great Civilization whose Shah was lecturing the industrial world on its character flaws. Thus, Iran's human rights record became more visible and much more reported upon, contributing to growing hostility both inside Iran and abroad.

### "Doing the 40-40"

- Khomeini's words took on new fury in late 1977 when his eldest son was murdered under mysterious circumstances — attributed to Savak. Then came the Tehran newspaper article of January 7, 1978. It ridiculed Khomeini, questioned his religious credentials, challenged his Iranian nationality, and accused him of various acts of immorality including authoring risque love sonnets as a young man. This journalistic assault set off riots in the holy city of Qom, Khomeini's spiritual home. Troops were called in and demonstrators killed.
- The disturbance in Qom ignited a new confrontation between the Moslem religious leadership and the government. The Shiite branch of Islam provided for a forty-day mourning period. By plan, the end of the forty-day period for the slain at Qom became the occasion for new demonstrations, more deaths, more mourning — and then after forty days, more demonstrations and still more deaths. One leader of this relentless cycle later called it "doing the 40-40." The riots and demonstrations spread across the country with further dramatic clashes, more killed, more martyrs.
- Attacks by police and army on critics of the regime only served to swell and broaden the ranks of those antagonistic to the Shah. The withdrawal of subsidies to the Shia religious establishment alienated the clergy further. Yet all through the first half of 1978, the opposition's significance was discounted. The Shah told the British ambassador the situation was serious but he was determined to press ahead with liberalization. His most implacable enemies were the mullahs, with their hold on the minds of the masses. "There could be no compromise with them. It was a straightforward confrontation and one side had to lose." The Shah made clear he could not imagine being on the losing side.
- In the US government, hardly anyone could imagine the Shah might fail. For Washington, any alternative was virtually unthinkable. He had sat on his throne for thirty-seven years, was courted throughout the world, was modernizing his country. Iran was one of the world's two great oil powers, with wealth far beyond anything it had known. The Shah was a critical ally, a regional policeman in a crucial area, the "Big Pillar." How could he possibly be toppled?
- American intelligence on Iran was constrained. As the US became more dependent on the Shah, there was less willingness to risk his ire by investigating the opposition he despised.
- There was not great demand among the "consumers" of intelligence for analyses of the Shah's stability — either thought unnecessary or the conclusions might be too unpalatable. "You couldn't give away intelligence on Iran," said one frustrated analyst. The intelligence community struggled throughout 1978 to assemble a National Intelligence Estimate but could never complete it. As late as September 28, 1978, the Defense Intelligence Agency's prognosis was that the Shah "is expected to remain actively in power over the next ten years."

### The Shah's Illness and the Escalating Crisis

- There were grisly signs of the fury against the Shah. Over two weeks in August 1978, half a dozen movie theaters were set afire by fundamentalists opposed to "sinful" movies. In mid-August, in Abadan, about five hundred people were crowded into a theater when someone locked the doors and incinerated the trapped moviegoers. In early September, bloody demonstrations took place in Tehran itself — the turning point. From then on, the Shah's government began to collapse as an effective ruling force.
- Something seemed wrong with the Shah himself. He appeared distant and more isolated. The British ambassador went to see him on September 16: "I was worried by the change in his appearance and manner. He looked shrunken; his face was yellow and he moved slowly. He seemed exhausted and drained of spirit." The Shah did have cancer — specifically leukemia, first diagnosed by French doctors in 1974. The seriousness was kept secret for several years from both the Shah and his wife. The British government and most certainly the Americans did not know. Had they been informed, calculations on many accounts might have been different. As time went on, the Shah began to feel the effects of the illness more and more and to fear its consequences — which might help explain the indecisiveness, strange detachment, malaise, and fatalism that seemed to take hold.

### "Like Snow in Water"

- As the political situation deteriorated, the Shah vacillated. He would not wage total war against the growing rebellion — "world public opinion" was watching too closely, and these were his people. But neither would he concede. He was befuddled by contradictory advice from the US government, and expressed his suspicion that the American CIA, British intelligence, and the BBC were conspiring against him.
- More of the country went on strike, including oil industry technicians. In early October 1978, at Iran's urging, Khomeini was expelled from Iraq (the Ba'thist regime in Baghdad had to worry about its own Shiite population). Denied refuge in Kuwait, Khomeini went to France and established himself in a suburb of Paris. The Iranian government may have thought: out of sight, out of mind. But it was mistaken — France provided Khomeini access to direct-dial international phone service that the Shah had installed in Tehran, greatly facilitating communication. The elderly, irate cleric proved himself a master of propaganda in front of the media that camped at his door.
- The Shah proceeded with liberalization — academic freedom, freedom of the press, freedom of assembly — but such Western-style rights were of little interest to a population rising against the monarch and the whole process of modernization. At the end of October, the Shah could only say, "We are melting away daily like snow in water." Strikes immobilized the economy and government; students, demonstrations, and riots went on unchecked.

### The Oil Industry in Chaos

- The main production area was known as "The Fields," located in the southeast, including Masjid-i-Suleiman where Anglo-Persian had made its original 1908 discovery. Seventy years later, operations were in the hands of the Oil Service Company of Iran (Osco), the descendant of the 1954 consortium. Staffed by expatriate oil men mostly from the member companies, Osco's headquarters was in Ahwaz. In October, striking Iranian laborers from The Fields moved into Osco's main headquarters, and by November a couple hundred were living in the corridors, eating and sleeping there. The Western oil men went about their jobs, carefully trying to avoid stepping on the workers. Meanwhile, impromptu prayer meetings in the courtyard grew from half a dozen to several hundred.
- Iran was the second-largest exporter after Saudi Arabia. Of 5.5 million barrels produced daily, about 4.5 million were exported. By early November, exports had been reduced to less than a million barrels per day, and thirty tankers were waiting in line at Kharg Island loading facilities — at a time when the international market's winter demand surge was beginning. Petroleum companies, responding to the general market softness, had been letting inventories fall.
- The head of the National Iranian Oil Company went south to The Fields to seek dialogue with the striking oil workers. He was mobbed by angry strikers, immediately decided to forgo negotiations, and fled the country. The Shah took a critical step: he installed a military government. But the general put in charge immediately suffered a heart attack and never asserted authority. The new government temporarily restored some order in the oil industry, and soldiers moved into Osco's headquarters in Ahwaz, coexisting uneasily with striking workers still camping in the corridors.

### US Policy in Disarray

- As events tumbled toward their conclusion, US policy was in confusion, disarray, and shock. During most of 1978, senior officials had been distracted by other developments — Camp David peace accords with Egypt and Israel, SALT negotiations with the Soviets, normalization of relations with China. American policy had been based on the premise that Iran was a reliable ally and the Big Pillar. Out of deference to the Shah, officials had kept their distance from his opponents, meaning they lacked channels to the emerging opposition. There was not even reporting to Washington on what Khomeini was actually saying on his famous tapes. Some insisted the unrest was a Soviet-orchestrated plot.
- The last months of 1978 saw a fierce bureaucratic battle over policy in Washington: How to bolster the Shah or assure continuity? How to support him without being so committed that relations with successors would be antagonistic? The indecision produced contradictory signals to Iran. "The United States never sent a clear, consistent signal," one senior official recalled. "Instead of oscillating back and forth between one course of action and the other and never deciding, we would have done better to have flipped a coin and then stuck to a policy." The cacophony from Washington confused the Shah and his senior officials, undermined their calculations, and "drastically weakened their resolve." No one in Washington knew how sick the Shah was.
- Efforts to construct an American position were complicated by a romantic and unrealistic view of Khomeini. A prominent professor wrote in the New York Times of Khomeini's tolerance, of how "his entourage of close advisers is uniformly composed of moderate, progressive individuals," and how Khomeini would provide "a desperately-needed model of humane governance for a third-world country." The American UN ambassador Andrew Young went even further: Khomeini would eventually be hailed as "a saint." An embarrassed Carter felt the need to make clear "that the United States is not in the canonization business."
- On November 9, Ambassador William Sullivan in Tehran sent a dramatic cable entitled "Thinking the Unthinkable" — perhaps the Shah would not survive; the US should begin to consider contingencies. Carter sent hand-written notes to his Secretary of State, National Security Adviser, Secretary of Defense, and Director of Central Intelligence to ask why he had not been previously informed of the situation. Sullivan concluded the US faced the situation in Iran "with no policy whatsoever."

### "Torrents of Blood"

- December 1978 was a month of mourning, processions, and self-flagellation in the Shiite creed. The high point was the holiday of Ashura, marking the martyrdom of the imam Hussein and symbolizing unremitting resistance to a tyrant. Khomeini promised it would be a month of vengeance and "torrents of blood." He called for new martyrs: "Let them kill five thousand, ten thousand, twenty thousand. We will prove that blood is more powerful than the sword." Huge demonstrations were held across the country, some truly awe-inspiring in size. The Army was crumbling away. "A dictator may survive by slaughtering his people, a king cannot act in such a way," the Shah said privately. And among his humiliations was a telephone prank: told that Senator Edward Kennedy was phoning from Washington, the Shah picked up — only to hear a quiet voice repeating: "Mohammed, abdicate. Mohammed, abdicate."
- A task force from Osco had begun preparing an evacuation plan for the twelve hundred expatriate oil men and their families in The Fields. The effort was not taken seriously until one afternoon George Link, an Exxon man who was Osco's general manager, had a car bomb thrown at him as he was being driven back to work after lunch. Link reflexively threw open his door and jumped out moments before the car exploded. Evacuation planning took on a new seriousness.
- Strikes once more gripped The Fields and Iranian production fell away rapidly. Paul Grimm, Osco's assistant general manager on loan from Texaco, was in direct confrontation with the workers. He bluntly warned some blue-collar expatriates who were joining the strikes that they would be dismissed. He was singled out as the man trying to break the walkout. In mid-December, as Grimm was driving to work, a shot was fired at him from a following car. He died instantly from a bullet in the back of his head. Evacuation of dependents now hurriedly began.
- By December 25, Christmas Day, Iranian petroleum exports had ceased altogether — a pivotal event in the world oil market. Spot prices in Europe surged 10 to 20 percent above official prices. The cutbacks deprived Iran of domestic oil supplies too — long lines formed in Tehran for gasoline and kerosene (the standard cooking fuel). Soldiers maintained order by firing shots into the air. Oil workers refused to provide petroleum products to the military, helping immobilize it. In an ironic reversal, an American tanker was diverted to Iran to supply badly needed fuel, but it was never able to unload because sufficiently secure arrangements could not be made.

### "I Am Feeling Tired": The Shah's Departure

- At the end of December, there was reluctant agreement in the ruling circles that a coalition government would be formed, the Shah would leave Iran ostensibly for medical treatment, and the Pahlavi dynasty appeared to be finished. So, virtually, was petroleum production in The Fields. In the week after Christmas, Osco decided to evacuate all Western employees. The expatriates assumed their exit was temporary — weeks or months at most. They were strictly limited to two suitcases. They left their houses intact. They faced a quandary similar to their predecessors who had been forced by Mossadegh to leave Abadan in 1951 — what to do with their dogs. Since they did not know how long they would be gone, they did what their predecessors had done: took their dogs out back and either shot them or clubbed them to death.
- They gathered at the airport at Ahwaz. Once again, the heirs of William D'Arcy Knox and George Reynolds were ignominiously leaving Iran. Unlike the "farewell to Abadan" in 1951, there were no honor guards, no bands, no singing of verses to "Colonel Bogey's March." Ahwaz had once been a very busy airport — now the oil industry was shut down, and the sky over the deserted airport was empty and silent and foreboding.
- On January 8, the British ambassador went to say farewell to the Shah. The monarchy that had survived all sorts of vicissitudes for almost half a century was at its end. The pomp of the celebration at Persepolis of the twenty-five hundredth anniversary of the Persian monarchy was gone. So was the power. Alexander the Great had captured Persepolis in 330 B.C. and burned the royal palace; now Khomeini was making a mockery of the self-proclaimed heir to Persepolis. "Like the Wizard of Oz, Mohammed Pahlavi was revealed to be, after all, but a mere mortal. The show was over."
- The Shah was calm and detached, speaking about events as though they had no relevance to him personally. The ambassador, despite all his years of self-discipline, found himself crying. The Shah said, "Never mind, I know how you feel." Then, in an odd gesture, he looked at his watch: "If it was up to me, I would leave — in ten minutes."
- At midday on January 16, the Shah appeared at Tehran airport. "I am feeling tired and need a rest," he said to a small group, maintaining the pathetic fiction that he was only going on vacation. He boarded his plane, carrying with his luggage a casket of Iranian soil, and left Tehran for the last time. His first stop was Egypt.
- With the Shah's departure, all of Tehran erupted into jubilation not seen since the Shah's own return in triumph in 1953. Car horns blared, headlights flashed, windshield wipers decorated with pictures of Khomeini swished back and forth. Newspapers were handed out with the unforgettable banner headline "The Shah Is Gone." Throughout the country, the great equestrian statues of his father and himself were pulled from their pedestals by wild crowds, and the Pahlavi dynasty crumbled into dust.

### Khomeini's Return and the End of the Pahlavi Dynasty

- On February 1, Khomeini arrived back in Tehran in a chartered Air France 747. Seats had been sold to Western reporters to finance the flight; Khomeini himself spent the trip resting on a carpet on the floor of first class. He brought with him a second government, a revolutionary council headed by Mehdi Bazargan, whose credentials as an opponent of the Shah were impeccable — in 1951, twenty-eight years earlier, Bazargan had been Mossadegh's choice to head the nationalized oil industry, had gone to the oil fields in person with stamps and a wooden sign reading "National Iranian Oil Company." He had served time in jail under the Shah.
- For a brief time, there were two rival governments in Tehran. But there could only be one. In the second week of February, fighting broke out at an air force base between "homafars" (non-commissioned officers sympathetic to the revolution) and troops of the Imperial Guard. The military support for the coalition government collapsed, and Bazargan was in. The American defense attache provided a succinct summary to Washington: "Army surrenders; Khomeini wins. Destroying all classified."

### The Last Man Out

- Not quite all oil men had departed from The Fields. About twenty stayed on to maintain Osco's legal presence. Among them was Jeremy Gilbert, an Irish mathematician turned petroleum engineer assigned by BP. Stricken with severe hepatitis, Gilbert was not allowed on the evacuation plane. He stayed in the hospital through the tumultuous days of January, hearing chanting and gunfire from his bed. On the day the Shah left, he heard the clangorous sounds of a giant celebration. His only contact with the outside world was the BBC and a huge arrangement of flowers from Osco.
- Very weak, Gilbert was mistaken by Iranians for an American. Nurses gathered outside his window to chant "Death to Americans." Another patient began beating him with crutches, ranting against Americans. Gilbert's actual Irish nationality posed another problem — Irish troops in Lebanon had recently gotten into a shooting match with Iraqis, so Gilbert was denied an Iraqi visa. He had to go on his knees before an agent at the Iraqi consulate and apologize for all the sins of the Irish.
- At the end of January, Gilbert made the trip out through Iraq. Iranian officials at the border waved him across; Iraqi guards detained him for hours suspecting he was a spy. The only taxi to Basra had left. "How do I get to Basra?" Gilbert asked. "You walk," a guard replied. Tired, weak, carrying two bags, he dragged himself along the dirt road until a van picked him up for a fee. His Iranian money was worthless — the driver chortled. Gilbert used his last dollars to get to the Basra airport. Broke, he remembered a new American Express card in his wallet and got a flight to Baghdad, then to London.
- Arriving late Friday at Heathrow, Gilbert phoned BP's personnel department to announce that the last Western oil man from The Fields was finally out. The personnel officer, distracted by weekend plans, misheard and thought the caller was phoning with news of the missing engineer: "Jerry Gilbert — we've been wondering where he was. Have you been in contact?" That was the final indignity. From the open pay phone at Heathrow, summoning whatever fragments of strength he had left, Gilbert loudly and abusively cursed not only the hapless personnel man but everyone connected with the world oil industry.

### Panic Begins

- The old regime was gone in Iran, the new one in power but struggling with bitter internal fights. From Iran, as if shaken by a violent earthquake, a giant tidal wave surged around the world. All were swept up in it; nothing and no one escaped. When the wave finally spent its fury two years later, the survivors would find themselves on totally new terrain. Everything was different; relations among all of them were altered. The wave would generate the Second Oil Shock, carrying prices from thirteen to thirty-four dollars a barrel, and bringing massive changes not only in the petroleum industry but in the world economy and global politics.
- The new oil shock passed through several stages. The first stretched from the end of December 1978 (when Iranian exports ceased) to autumn 1979. The loss of Iranian production was partly offset by increases elsewhere. Saudi Arabia pushed up production from its self-imposed ceiling of 8.5 million barrels per day to 10.5 by the end of 1978, lowering to 10.1 million in the first quarter of 1979 — still well above its 8.5 million ceiling. Other OPEC countries also boosted output. But overall, free world production in the critical first quarter of 1979 was about 2 million barrels per day below the last quarter of 1978.
- There was an actual shortage — but against world demand of 50 million barrels per day, the shortage was no more than 4 to 5 percent. Why should a 4-5 percent loss of supplies have resulted in a 150 percent increase in price? The answer was the panic, triggered by five circumstances:
- (1) The apparent continued growth of oil consumption and the signal it gave to the market. Demand had risen smartly from 1976 onward; the impact of conservation and non-OPEC oil was not yet clear, and it was assumed demand would continue to rise.
- (2) The disruption of contractual arrangements within the oil industry. Despite major upheavals, world oil had remained integrated through long-term contracts. The Iranian interruption hit companies unevenly, depending on their dependence on Iran, and led to disruptions of contractual flow. Hosts of new buyers hurtled into the marketplace, scrambling to secure supplies. Here was the real end of the classic integrated oil industry — links between upstream and downstream were finally severed. What had been the fringe, the spot market, became the center. What had been a somewhat disreputable activity, trading, became a central preoccupation.
- (3) The contradictory and conflicting policies of consumer governments. The IEA emergency sharing system was still in development, with many aspects untested. Actions by governments for domestic reasons were read as major international policies, adding stress and tension.
- (4) The upheaval presented oil exporters with the opportunity to capture additional, enormously large rents. Most, though not all, kept pushing the price up at every opportunity, and some manipulated supplies to further agitate the market.
- (5) The sheer power of emotion — uncertainty, anxiety, confusion, fear, pessimism. These sentiments fueled and governed actions during the panic. After the fact, when numbers were sorted out, such emotions seemed irrational. But at the time they were indubitably real. The whole international oil system seemed to have broken down. And what gave the emotions additional force was the conviction that a prophecy had been fulfilled: the oil crisis expected for the mid-1980s had arrived in 1979. This was not a temporary disruption, but the early arrival of a deeper crisis which would mean permanently high prices. Would the Iranian Revolution spread to Kuwait, Riyadh, Cairo, and beyond? Religious fundamentalism had caught the Western world by surprise, and one of its driving forces was obvious: a rejection of the West and the modern world. That recognition led to "an icy, pervasive fear."

### Panic Buying and Inventory Hoarding

- Buyers, gripped by panic and fearing a repetition of 1973, inadvertently made the shortage worse by building up inventories. The world oil industry maintains billions of barrels in inventories — stocks necessary for the smooth operations of the "machine" that extended from wellhead to gasoline station. A particular barrel could take ninety days to travel from a Gulf wellhead through refining and marketing to a gasoline station.
- Companies did not want to hold more inventories than needed. If prices were expected to fall, they reduced inventories; if prices were expected to rise, they bought more of today's cheaper barrels. In the panic of 1979-1980, companies bought well in excess of anticipated consumption — not only because of price but because they were not sure they could get any oil later. This extra buying, combined with hoarding, dizzily drove up the price. The panic of 1979-80 was self-fulfilling and ultimately self-defeating, prophecy on a truly colossal scale.
- Down the consumption chain, industrial users and utilities also furiously built inventories as insurance against rising prices and possible shortages. So did the motorist. Before 1979, the typical Western motorist drove with his tank one-quarter full. Suddenly, worried about gasoline shortages, he kept his tank three-quarters full. Almost overnight, upwards of a billion gallons of motor fuel were sucked out of gasoline station tanks by frightened motorists.
- The rush to build inventories by companies, reinforced by consumers, resulted in an additional three million barrels per day of "demand" above actual consumption. Added to the two million barrels per day of net lost supplies, the total shortfall was five million barrels per day — about 10 percent of consumption. The panic buying more than doubled the actual shortage and further fueled the panic. That was the mechanism that drove the price from thirteen to thirty-four dollars a barrel.

### Force Majeure: The Domino Effect

- The panic might have been contained if the shortfall had been distributed evenly. But BP, as a result of its historical position, was far more dependent on Iran than any other company — fully 40 percent of its supplies came from Iran. BP was "crude long" — a wholesaler selling much of its oil through long-term contracts to third parties including other majors like Exxon and independent refiners, particularly in Japan. Having lost Iranian supply, BP invoked force majeure and cut back on its buyers. It canceled its supply contract with Exxon altogether, while scrambling to buy oil elsewhere. Neither BP nor Shell were Aramco members, so they had no direct access to the increased Saudi production.
- The dominoes began to fall. Other companies, deprived of oil by BP's cutbacks, also invoked force majeure. In March, Exxon, faced with an April 1 renewal date for its contracts with Japanese buyers, announced it was going to phase out many of its third-party contracts. Exxon had been warning buyers since 1974 to diversify and "not to count on Exxon." Chairman Clifton Garvin explained: "The handwriting had been on the wall. Venezuela had been taken away from us. We no longer had the concession in Saudi Arabia. We couldn't see a role in being the middleman between the Saudis and the Japanese consumer." Exxon had already begun winding down third-party contracts, but in the crisis mood, its March 1979 message took on unexpected significance.
- Japan was hit hard. After the first crisis, it had carved a niche in Iran — by 1978, Iran supplied almost 20 percent of Japan's total oil needs. Now the majors could no longer be counted upon either. Japanese refineries could not go idle. The government ordered the Ginza lights dimmed as an energy-saving measure and urged Japanese buyers to go directly into the world marketplace. The formidable Japanese trading companies scoured the world for supplies. One trading house discovered that giving gloves as presents to secretaries was an excellent way to get in to see the right officials; to cultivate the Iraqi oil minister, this same house provided the services of a world-class acupuncturist.
- Other independent refiners from many nations joined the Japanese in the frantic quest. So did state oil companies like India's. Suddenly, where there had been relatively few buyers, now there were many — a highly desirable situation from the sellers' point of view. All the action moved to the spot markets, which had comprised only about 8 percent of total supplies as a balancing mechanism. But as buyers rushed in, prices were bid up and up. By late February 1979, spot prices were double official prices. People called it the "Rotterdam Market" after Europe's huge oil port, but in fact it was a global market, connected by a fevered network of telephones and telexes.
- Exporters also invoked force majeure, canceling contracts. One morning Shell received a telex from an exporting country announcing a contracted supply was no longer available due to force majeure. That same afternoon, Shell received another telex from the same country saying crude oil was available on a spot basis — miraculously the same volume that had just been cut off. The only difference? The price was 50 percent higher. Shell took the offer.

### Iranian Oil Returns — But the Panic Continues

- At the beginning of March 1979, far more rapidly than expected, Iranian exports began to return to the world market, albeit at much lower levels than before the Shah's fall. Spot prices began falling back toward official prices. This was the moment when order might have been reestablished. IEA member countries pledged to cut demand by 5 percent. But the panic had its own momentum. Who could be confident Iranian oil would remain available? Khomeini had asserted control, but The Fields were actually controlled by a radical leftist "Committee of 60" — militant white-collar workers functioning as a virtual government of their own, jailing oil administrators at will. Moreover, other OPEC countries had begun to announce cutbacks in their own output — with prices rising, it was more valuable to keep oil in the ground and sell it later.

### Leapfrog and Scramble

- At the end of March, OPEC met. Spot crude prices had risen by 30 percent, products by as much as 60 percent. OPEC decided members could add whatever surcharges and premiums "they deem justifiable in light of their own circumstances." What this really meant, as Yamani bluntly allowed, was a "free-for-all." The exporters were abandoning any notion of an official price structure. They would charge whatever the market would bear.
- Now there would be two games: "leapfrog" — producers vying with each other to raise prices; and "scramble" — a bruising competition for supply among anxious buyers. Companies that had been cut off, refiners, governments, traders, and of course the majors trampled one another in their rush to court the various exporters. None of this fevered activity brought forth any new supplies; all it did was intensify competition for existing supply and drive up the price. "Nobody controlled anything," said Shell's supply coordinator. "You just fought for it. At every level, you felt you had to buy now; whatever the price, it was good compared to what it would cost you tomorrow. You had to say 'yes' or you would lose out. That was the psychology of the buyer. Horrible as the terms might be from your point of view, they would be worse tomorrow."
- Only one exporter stood clearly in opposition to the surcharges, premiums, and rapid price increases — Saudi Arabia. Having fought further increases ever since the 1973 quadrupling, the Saudis now objected to the leapfrog because short-term winnings would be followed by large and perhaps ruinous losses. Oil would price itself out of its competitiveness in energy markets; Middle Eastern producers would again become the residual supplier, shunned on grounds of energy security.
- The Saudis issued what became known as the "Yamani Edict" — Saudi Arabia would keep to official prices with no surcharges. The four Aramco companies were required to sell at those official prices to both their own affiliates and third-party buyers. If Saudi Arabia found companies adding premiums, there would be hell to pay — they would risk having their access to Saudi oil cut off. Saudi Arabia was virtually alone among exporters in this position, with only the UAE as an ally. There was much behind-the-scenes pressure and outright imploring from Western nations.

### Saudi Production Cuts and Three Mile Island

- Yet in Q2 1979, the Saudis cut production back to the pre-crisis "ceiling" of 8.5 million barrels per day. Despite their insistence on keeping to official prices, that cutback helped send spot prices soaring. Multiple reasons were proffered: sending a conciliatory signal to Khomeini's new Islamic regime by making room for returning Iranian production; expressing dissatisfaction with the Camp David peace accords between Israel and Egypt (signed March 26); focusing on conservation of oil reserves and "the whole question of production in excess of actual revenue needs"; or simply assuming the crisis was easing. Whatever the reason, only Saudi Arabia had the kind of spare capacity that could quell the panic — the role once held by the United States.
- Hours after the latest OPEC meeting adjourned (early morning March 28), a pump failed and a valve malfunctioned at the Three Mile Island nuclear plant near Harrisburg, Pennsylvania. Hundreds of thousands of gallons of radioactive water poured into the reactor building. Days of near-panic followed. The event raised large doubts about nuclear power's future and threatened the Western assumption that nuclear would be a major line of response to the 1973 oil crisis. Did Three Mile Island mean the industrial world would find itself more dependent on oil than expected? The accident contributed to gloom, pessimism, and fatalism across the Western world.
- David Howell, British Secretary of State for Energy, declared: "Friends, we are living dangerously." Western governments' efforts to mobilize demand cutbacks were proving insufficient, but they were loath to invoke the IEA's emergency oil sharing system for fear of introducing more rigidity. Governments were torn between two contradictory objectives: obtaining low-priced oil and guaranteeing secure supplies at any price. Energy questions had become "short, short, short-run politics." Western governments became champions of aggressive worldwide acquisition hunts through companies and state-to-state deals, producing suspicion and finger-pointing among supposedly allied nations.

### The Return of Gas Lines in America

- For the American public, gas lines snaking for blocks around stations became the embodiment of the panic — the nightmare of 1973 had returned. There was a genuine shortage of gasoline: refineries geared to Iranian light crude couldn't produce as much gasoline from the heavier crudes they were forced to substitute. Inventories were low in California, and after news reports of spot shortages, all 12 million vehicles in the state seemed to show up at once.
- Emergency regulations made matters worse. Some states prohibited buying more than $5 of gasoline at a time, forcing motorists to return more frequently. Price controls limited the conservation response — decontrolled prices might have ended the lines quickly. The federal allocation system froze distribution patterns on a historical basis, denying the market flexibility to move supplies to match demand. Gasoline was in short supply in major urban areas but abundant in rural and vacation areas "where the only shortage was of tourists."
- The nation was rationing gasoline through the mechanism of gas lines themselves. And gas lines begat more gas lines: a typical car used seven-tenths of a gallon an hour idling in line. One estimate: America's motorists in spring and summer 1979 wasted 150,000 barrels of oil a day waiting in line to fill their tanks.
- Oil companies were once again public enemy number one. Charges flew thick and fast — companies withholding oil, tankers held offshore to drive up prices, deliberate hoarding. Clifton Garvin, chairman of Exxon, decided to "go public" to refute the accusations. A cool, measured chemical engineer and passionate bird watcher, Garvin appeared on the Phil Donahue Show — a first for the chief executive of the world's largest oil company. But whenever he explained the basic logistics of inventories, the interviewers' eyes glazed over. Garvin on the public mood: "The American is a funny person. He worships the result of things that are big, economies of scale, mass production, but he hates anything that is big and powerful, and the oil industry is seen as the biggest and most powerful industry." One day at his local Exxon station in Greenwich, Connecticut, the dealer offered to let Garvin skip to the front of the line. "I'm sitting right here," Garvin said firmly.

### Petroleum and the President — Carter's Crisis

- The gas lines marked the beginning of the end of Jimmy Carter's Presidency. Carter was both the Preacher (moral rehabilitation of post-Watergate America) and the Engineer (micro-managing the political machine). Energy and oil had been his number-one domestic focus, and now he confronted the very crisis he had warned against. By mid-March 1979, his chief White House energy adviser Eliot Cutler warned of "darts and arrows coming at us from all directions."
- In April, Carter delivered a major speech announcing decontrol of oil prices (infuriating liberals) coupled with a "windfall profits tax" on "excess" oil company earnings (infuriating conservatives). A special Presidential task force met repeatedly to find a solution to the gasoline shortage — the only quick fix was to get the Saudis to increase output again. In June, Carter sent the American ambassador to Riyadh with an official letter and a personal handwritten note imploring increased output. The ambassador met for hours with Prince Fahd, head of the Supreme Petroleum Council.
- Carter went to Vienna to sign SALT II with Brezhnev — normally a landmark achievement through three administrations. But it simply did not count. The only thing that mattered was the gas lines, and they were Carter's fault.

### "The Worst of Times"

- A survey by the American Automobile Association of 6,286 service stations showed 58% were closed Saturday June 23 and 70% closed Sunday June 24 — leaving Americans with very little gasoline on the first weekend of summer. Independent truckers conducted a rowdy, violent nationwide strike (three weeks running) to protest fuel shortages and rising prices. A hundred truckers snarled rush-hour traffic for thirty miles on the Long Island Expressway. Inflation was moving to unprecedented levels.
- Support grew for a huge "synthetic fuels" program to reduce dependence on imported oil. Three Mile Island had closed the door on nuclear. The alternative: produce several million barrels per day of synthetic fuels through hydrogenation of coal (as the Germans had done in WWII) and heating of shale rocks in the Rockies to 900 degrees Fahrenheit. Cost: tens of billions of dollars, years to implement, major environmental consequences, uncertain whether it would actually work at scale. Politically, the concept seemed increasingly irresistible.
- At the Tokyo economic summit (July 1979), Carter found the conference "harsh and acrimonious." German Chancellor Helmut Schmidt "got personally abusive toward me... He alleged that American interference in the Middle East trying to work for a peace treaty was what had caused the problems with oil all over the world." On Margaret Thatcher: Carter found her "a tough lady, highly opinionated, strong-willed, cannot admit that she doesn't know something."
- Stuart Eizenstat, chief White House domestic policy adviser, dispatched a grim memorandum from Tokyo: "Nothing else has so frustrated, confused, angered the American people — or so targeted their distress at you personally... In many respects, this would appear to be the worst of times. But I honestly believe that we can change this to a time of opportunity." Carter's approval rating had plummeted to 25%, matched only by Nixon's in his final days. He retreated to Camp David with a 107-page dissection of the national mind by pollster Patrick Caddell.
- In July, the Saudis pushed output from 8.5 to 9.5 million barrels per day, heeding the implorings from the US and responding to their own security assessment. But it was not a long-term solution and could not immediately cool the hot temper of the American public.
- Carter embraced the synthetic fuels plan: 2.5 million barrels per day by 1990, primarily from coal and shale oil (originally wanted 5 million bpd but was talked down). In his July "crisis of confidence" speech, though he did not use the word, it became known as Carter's "malaise" speech.
- Carter forced the resignations of five Cabinet members — including Treasury Secretary Michael Blumenthal and Health Secretary Joseph Califano. His political advisers Hamilton Jordan and Jody Powell had convinced him they were disloyal. Eizenstat argued strenuously against firing Califano and Blumenthal. Just before a Cabinet meeting, Carter told staff he wanted all Cabinet members to submit resignations; some staff tried to dissuade him, warning it could create a panic. Robert Strauss, walking in late and not knowing what had transpired, jokingly said everyone ought to resign. "Bob, shut up," whispered a colleague. "They had all just resigned." The aim was to bolster Presidential leadership; it had the opposite effect. The Washington Post's national editor muttered that "America's central government had just collapsed."

### The Cat-and-Mouse Dialectic

- Spot prices eased off slightly in summer 1979, but OPEC countries continued to cut output. Iraq extended its embargo to Egypt to punish Anwar Sadat for the Camp David accords. Nigeria, in the most dramatic use of the "oil weapon" since 1973, nationalized BP's extensive holdings in retaliation for alleged indirect sales to South Africa, then auctioned off its newly nationalized supply at higher prices.
- Buyers continued their quest to build up inventories and fill storage tanks to the brim, driven by fear and the assumption that demand was continuing to grow. This was a fatal miscalculation — a decline had already set in, reflecting conservation and an economic downturn, but the fall was almost imperceptible at first. Shell's supply coordinator: "Every negotiation with a producer government was a finger-biting exercise: there was one dominant thought in the mind of company presidents and negotiators alike — to hold on to term oil and limit the need for spot acquisition." A cat-and-mouse dialectic began, with contract terms and prices becoming "continuously worse."

### Information Failure and the Rise of the Traders

- As in most panics, information — or the lack of it — was the key. If timely, credible, widely accepted data had existed, companies would have recognized earlier that they were increasing stocks to unnecessarily high levels and that underlying demand was weakening. But there was not much in the way of such statistics, and what early indicators did exist were not given much attention. So the stock build continued unabated, as did rising prices.
- Price increases were not limited to OPEC. Britain's new state oil company BNOC raised prices on its desirable North Sea crudes and was for a moment even leading the market. "If BNOC, and by implication the British Government, were behaving like OPEC, who could expect OPEC to put an end to the oil price spiral?" With the exception of Saudi Arabia, OPEC countries lost no time catching up.
- The market was further churned by traders, for whom the volatility, disarray, and confusion was a heyday. Some were from established commodity trading houses, some had entered the business after 1973, and some were johnny-come-latelies whose only capital requirement was a telephone and a telex. They were everywhere, vying with traditional oil companies for ownership, as cargoes still on the high seas were sold and resold — one cargo fifty-six times over. A single cargo on a supertanker could be worth $50 million.
- The raison d'etre for the traders was the breakdown of the integrated systems of the majors. In the old days, oil stayed within a company's integrated channels or was swapped among companies. Now state oil companies accounted for larger and larger shares of total production, had no downstreams of their own, and sold to a wide spectrum of buyers. Traders exploited the enormous arbitrage between lower term-contract prices and higher, more volatile spot prices. "The trader could be in a superb position. All he had to do was manage to get himself a term contract of some sort. He could then turn around and sell it for eight dollars a barrel more on the spot market." How did the trader get his contract? "A ridiculously small commission to the appropriate parties. And sometimes the required brown envelopes would be passed."
- By summer and early fall 1979, the world oil market was in a state of anarchy whose global effects far exceeded those of the early 1930s (Dad Joiner's East Texas discovery) and the earliest days of the industry. While producers and traders swelled with money, consumers were forced to dip ever deeper into their own pockets. For the exultant exporters, "there was no limit, they thought, to what the market would bear." Some in the Western world feared what was at stake was "not only the price of the world's most important commodity, not only economic growth and the integrity of the world economy, but perhaps even the international order and world society."

### "The World Crisis" — Schlesinger's Farewell

- Among those leaving Carter's Cabinet that summer was James Schlesinger. Depressed by the unfolding situation in energy markets and international politics, Schlesinger gave a farewell speech invoking Winston Churchill's The World Crisis (his WWI history). Churchill had written of his efforts to convert the British Navy from coal to oil, despite the risk of depending on oil from Iran. Now, six decades later, "eerily and uncannily, that risk had become reality."
- Schlesinger warned: "Today we face a world crisis of vaster dimensions than Churchill described half a century ago — made more ominous by the problems of oil. There is little, if any, relief in prospect. Any major interruption — stemming from political decision, political instability, terrorist acts or major technical problems — would entail severe disruptions... The energy future is bleak and is likely to grow bleaker in the decade ahead." He would later say of himself, "I'm not a brooder," but "there was nothing more that he could do about the situation." With that foreboding valedictory, he departed public life. Very shortly after, "the pessimism reflected in his remarks, and the dark anxieties about what he saw as growing Western vulnerabilities and what others were now calling the decline of the West, were to take on yet more bizarre and devastating significance."

## Chapter 34: "We're Going Down"

### The Embassy Seizure — November 4, 1979

- Shortly after 3:00 a.m. Washington time, November 4, 1979, Elizabeth Ann Swift, the political officer in the US embassy in Tehran, got through by phone to the Operations Center on the seventh floor of the State Department. She reported that a large mob of young Iranians had broken into the embassy compound, surrounded the chancery building, and were forcing their way into other buildings. An hour and a half later, she reported the attackers had set fire to part of the embassy. Still another half hour later, some invaders had threatened to kill two unarmed Americans. The table and sofa blocking the door had been pulled aside. Swift continued in a professional, almost matter-of-fact way as the Americans were being tied. "We're going down" were her last words, before a young Iranian with a picture of Khomeini pinned to his shirt grabbed the phone. Swift and the other Americans, all blindfolded, were led into captivity. The line remained open for a long time, though no one was there. Then it went dead.
- Some 63 Americans — the skeleton staff remaining after the embassy was scaled down from 1,400 officials in the Shah's time — were taken hostage by a large, rowdy, violent band of zealots thereafter known as "students." Some were soon released, leaving 50 in captivity. The Iranian Hostage Crisis had begun, and the Second Oil Shock entered an even more dire geopolitical phase.

### The Shah as Pariah and the Trigger for the Hostage Crisis

- The specific grievance of the hostage takers focused on Mohammed Pahlavi and America's relation to him. His father, Reza Shah, had found exile in South Africa. But the son became a modern Flying Dutchman — he could find refuge in no port. He went to Egypt, Morocco, the Bahamas, Mexico, but no one wanted him. He was a reject, a pariah, and virtually no government wanted to risk the ire of the new Iran. All the courting, flattery, ingratiation, the respectful premiers and supplicating cabinet ministers — "it was as if none of that had ever happened."
- Cancer and related illnesses were ravaging the Shah's body. Remarkably, it was only at the end of September 1979, more than eight months after he left Iran, that senior American officials first learned the Shah was seriously ill. Only on October 18 did they discover it was cancer. Carter had adamantly refused to allow the Shah into the US for treatment. But after months of controversy, compounded by a vigorous campaign by Henry Kissinger, John McCloy, David Rockefeller, and others, the Shah was admitted. He arrived in New York October 23 and checked into the New York Hospital, Cornell Medical Center, under a pseudonym that happened to be the real name of US Undersecretary of State David Newsom. His presence was immediately known and widely reported.
- A few days later, Zbigniew Brzezinski attended the 25th anniversary of the Algerian revolution in Algiers, where he met with the new Iranian Prime Minister Mehdi Bazargan. Bazargan protested the Shah's admission to the US. The news of this meeting, combined with the Shah's arrival, alarmed Bazargan's theocratic rivals and young militant fundamentalists. The Shah's presence in the US stoked memories of 1953 — Mossadegh's fall, the Shah's flight to Rome, his triumphant return. It aroused fear that the US was about to stage another coup. And here was Bazargan trucking with Brzezinski, "one of the chief agents of the Great Satan," just a week and a half after the Shah's arrival. This provided the impetus and pretext for the embassy invasion.

### "Death to America" and the Hostage Crisis Unfolds

- The embassy seizure was perhaps originally intended as a sit-in, but it soon turned into an occupation and mass kidnapping, as well as a bizarre circus — vendors in front of the embassy sold revolutionary tape cassettes, shoes, sweatshirts, hats, and boiled sugar beets. The occupiers answered the embassy phone: "Nest of spies." Khomeini and his circle took advantage of the crisis to dispose of Bazargan, consolidate power, eliminate opponents, and put in place the elements of the theocratic regime. The hostage crisis would grind on for almost fifteen months — 444 days. Every day, Americans read about "America in Captivity." Each night, they were subjected to the televised spectacle of "America Held Hostage" with its repetitive chorus of "Death to America." (ABC, with its late-night hostage programs, finally found a way to compete against Johnny Carson and the Tonight Show.)
- The hostage crisis transmitted a powerful message: the shift of power in the world oil market in the 1970s was only part of a larger drama. The US and the West "seemed to say, were truly in decline, on the defensive, and, it appeared, unable to do anything to protect their interests." Carter: "They have us by the balls."
- Iran was not the only scene of unrest. In late November 1979, some seven hundred armed fundamentalists seized the Great Mosque in Mecca, intending it as the first stage of an uprising against the Saudi government. They were dislodged only with difficulty. The larger uprising never materialized, but it sent shock waves through the Islamic world. In early December, there was a Shia protest in al-Hasa, in the heart of the Saudi oil region. Then, in December, the Soviet Union invaded Afghanistan — the first large-scale use of Soviet military forces beyond the communist bloc since WWII. Russia "was still intent on fulfilling its century-and-a-half-old ambitions to drive toward the Gulf."
- President Carter responded in January 1980 with the Carter Doctrine: "An attempt by any outside force to gain control of the Persian Gulf region will be regarded as an assault on the vital interests of the United States of America, and such an assault will be repelled by any means necessary, including military force." This echoed Harry Truman's 1950 pledge to Ibn Saud and bore striking similarities to the Lansdowne Declaration of 1903, by which Britain had warned off Russia and Germany from the Persian Gulf.

### Carter's Fall and the Shah's Death

- Carter had earned great respect in the oil world in 1977 as the man who forced the Shah to bend on prices. He had been "the magician who had tamed the Shah." But now the Shah was an outcast, the Iranian Revolution had sparked the oil panic, and Carter's Presidency was held hostage by events in Iran. After the hostages were taken, the dying Shah quickly and apologetically left the US, spending his final hours before departure in pathetic isolation in a psychiatric ward, with barred windows, on an American Air Force base. He went to Panama and then back to Egypt, where he finally died in July 1980, "a year and a half after his flight from Tehran. No one really cared." Mohammed Pahlavi, son of an officer from the Cossack brigade, had become irrelevant to the hostage crisis, to the panic in the oil market, and to the international game of nations.
- Carter responded to the hostage taking by placing an embargo on Iranian oil imports and freezing Iranian assets. The Iranians counterattacked by prohibiting oil exports to any American firm. The freezing of assets hurt Iran; the oil import ban did not. But it necessitated a redistribution of supplies around the world, further disrupting supply channels and sending more frantic buyers into the spot market, bidding prices to new heights. Some cargoes went for $45/barrel; Iranians quoted $50 to worried Japanese trading companies. The dislocation amplified panic buying. As a major executive remarked four days after the hostage taking: "In this environment companies feel a need for higher stocks than previously considered normal." The inventory build was, in industry language, "supply protection" — in other words, insurance.
- The hostage crisis demonstrated the apparent weakness, "even nakedness," of the consuming countries, particularly the United States. It seemed to establish that world mastery really did lie in the hands of the oil exporters. But there were forces at work in the oil market even more powerful than governments — and now it was the turn of the exporters to make fatal miscalculations of their own.

### The Bazaar — Caracas OPEC Meeting, December 1979

- Rising oil prices were the object of constant attention by presidents and prime ministers — but also of intense dismay for the Saudi leaders. They were alarmed by their loss of control and the fact that power had passed to militants like Libya and Iran. They thought wildly rising prices threatened the world economy with recession, depression, or even ruin — thus threatening their own well-being. The days when Saudi Arabia's economic future was determined by the number of pilgrims coming to Mecca were long past; now the "rates" that mattered to Riyadh were world interest rates, exchange rates, inflation rates, growth rates. The Saudis also feared that price increases would destroy consumers' confidence in oil and stimulate long-lasting competition from alternative fuels — particularly threatening to a country sitting on reserves extending far into the twenty-first century.
- The Saudis responded with jawboning: Yamani became more of a hawk on conservation than almost any Western leader. They held down their own official prices, even if it meant leaving money on the table. They also sought to counteract rising prices by pushing production up. "We're losing control over everything," Yamani declared plaintively in mid-October 1979. "We feel so unhappy. We don't like to see it happening like this." Then came the hostage drama, and prices spiked again and again.
- At the Caracas OPEC meeting (late December 1979), OPEC's pricing structure was in total disarray: Saudi Arabia's official price was $18/barrel; others were as high as $28; spot prices were in the $40-$50 range. The Saudis announced a $6 increase to $24, hoping others would bring prices down into line. It didn't work — the Iranians immediately leapfrogged by another $5. Once again the sharpest fissure was between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
- In 1979, OPEC production was back up to 31 million barrels per day — even with the Iranian shutdown, 3 million bpd higher than 1978. Where was the extra oil going? Not into actual consumption, Yamani was sure, but into the inventories of companies fearful of future interruptions. "Political decisions cannot permanently negate the divine laws of supply and demand," Yamani explained. "Prices go up, and demand goes down, it's simple, it's ABC."
- At the Tamanaco hotel, Yamani moved into the top-floor Presidential suite and campaigned privately with other oil ministers. For eleven hours they argued in his suite. He warned that demand was already showing signs of weakening, that continuing leapfrogging would bring a "catastrophe in the world economy," and that they would eventually have to cut production to protect prices — then prices would collapse anyway. One oil minister said Yamani must be joking; another that he was obviously on drugs. There was no agreement whatsoever — indeed, there was no official price at all. "OPEC and the oil market," Yamani said dismissively, "had turned into a bazaar." He also had a warning for the other producers and a promise to consumers: "There will be a glut in the market. It is coming." Prices would fall.
- The other exporters ignored the admonition. "In the name of almighty God, there will be no surplus and prices will not fall," intoned the Iranian oil minister. Most exporters assumed demand was so inflexible they could dictate whatever prices they wanted. Immediately after the meeting, Libya, Algeria, and Nigeria raised prices once again.

### The "Miniglut" and the Failed Rescue Mission

- Caracas in late December 1979 was the moment when exporters lost touch with reality. Demand was indeed weakening, new supplies were being developed, inventories were being built up, spot prices were declining. And the Saudis continued their steady overproduction. Other producers continued to push up prices while some cut back on production — helping buoy prices. There was now talk of a "miniglut," but that was more than offset by a new "minipanic" as Washington sought a general embargo against Iran, accentuating nervousness.
- In April 1980, frustrated to the extreme by the hostage impasse, Carter mounted a military rescue operation. Eight helicopters were dispatched from the carrier Nimitz to a desolate spot dubbed Desert One in Iran, to rendezvous with six C-130s carrying assault teams. The squads were to retake the embassy, free the hostages, and get them to a secured airfield near Tehran. But things went awry: one helicopter dropped out for navigational problems, another for mechanical malfunction. Three Iranian vehicles, including a bus with forty-four people, passed close enough to observe the Americans. In a blinding sandstorm, one of the remaining helicopters collided with a C-130 and burst into flames, killing several servicemen. Only five helicopters remained; the mission required a minimum of six. It was aborted on direct orders of President Carter. The Iranians dispersed the hostages throughout Tehran.
- The general outlook was bleak. The "mini-glut" was expected to be over by spring 1981. OPEC's Long Range Strategy Committee planned for 10-15% annual price increases — meaning $60/barrel within five years. The CIA director, testifying five days after the failed rescue, warned: "Politically, the cardinal issue is how vicious the struggle for energy supplies will become." A Foreign Affairs article in summer 1980 was titled "Oil and the Decline of the West."
- OPEC met again in Algiers in June 1980. The Saudis, now joined by the Kuwaitis, again tried to end the bazaar — to no avail. The average oil price was $32/barrel, almost three times what it had been a year and a half earlier. Yamani, sitting in the coffee shop of the Algiers hotel, being shunned by the other delegates, unburdened himself to a friend: "They're too greedy, they're too greedy. They'll pay for it."
- The oil market was sagging under the distress Yamani had been predicting. Inventories were very high; a pronounced recession was emerging; both product prices and demand were falling; the inventory surplus was continuing to swell. Companies were even beginning to store oil in supertankers rather than sell it at a loss. Now it was the buyers' turn to walk away from contracts. In mid-September, a number of OPEC countries agreed to voluntarily cut back production by 10% to firm prices.

### OPEC's Twentieth Anniversary and the Outbreak of War

- The twentieth anniversary of OPEC was approaching. A grand celebration was being planned for a November summit in Baghdad, where OPEC had been founded in 1960. An official history was commissioned, a film made, 1,500 journalists invited. On the morning of September 22, 1980, OPEC ministers assembled at the Hapsburg Palace in Vienna to continue planning. But within minutes of the meeting's opening, it erupted into confusion, anger, and chaos — and was turned into a closed session. Something else had already been planned in Baghdad.

### The Second Battle of Qadisiyah: Iraq versus Iran

- On September 22, 1980, squadrons of Iraqi warplanes attacked a dozen targets in Iran without warning, and Iraqi troops began pushing into Iran along a broad front with heavy artillery. The outbreak of war shook the Persian Gulf yet again and threw the oil supply system into jeopardy, threatening a third oil shock.
- The war was sparked by a host of rivalries: ethnic, religious, political, economic, ideological, personal; a struggle for primacy in the Gulf; the insecurities of national cohesion; and the arbitrary way "nations" had been created and borders overlaid on the map of the defunct Ottoman Empire. Geography was decidedly at the heart of the conflict.
- The critical geographic issue was the Shatt-al-Arab, a meandering river and delta formed by the confluence of the Tigris and Euphrates with several Iranian rivers, serving as the boundary for 120 miles between the two countries. It was crucial to Iran as its avenue to the Gulf — the Abadan refinery was built on a mud flat in the river delta. It was critical to Iraq as virtually its only avenue to the high seas — Iraq's entire coastline was only twenty-six miles long, compared to Iran's fourteen hundred miles. A considerable part of both countries' oil infrastructure was concentrated around the Shatt-al-Arab.
- The Shah and the Ba'thists had sorted out their claims in an Algiers agreement in 1975, signed by Saddam Hussein. Iran got the better deal on sovereignty — Iraq gave up its forty-year insistence that the boundary was on the Iranian side, accepting the midpoint of the navigational channel instead. In return, the Shah cynically agreed to cut off his considerable aid to the Kurds (20% of Iraq's population), who were fighting the Ba'thists for autonomy in a region where much of Iraq's oil was found. The Shah's jettisoning of the Kurds was a major quid pro quo, perhaps a requisite for the Ba'thist regime's survival. Baghdad launched a decisive anti-Kurdish offensive just six hours after the Algiers communique. Three years later, in 1978, at the Shah's request, Iraq expelled Ayatollah Khomeini, who had been living in exile in Iraq for fourteen years — an act that "hardly turned out to be a favor at all."

### Saddam Hussein's Rise

- The Ba'th ("renaissance") movement grew out of an Arab Students Union formed by two Syrian intellectuals in 1930s Paris. It was militantly pan-Arabic, fervent in its denunciation of Western imperialism, all-embracing in ideology, contemptuous and hostile to opponents. It celebrated violence and absolutism. The party split into two branches — one took power in Syria, the other in Iraq — which became irreconcilable rivals despite their common origins.
- Saddam Hussein's father died just before his birth in 1937. The decisive influence on him was his uncle Khayr Allah Talfah, a fervent Sunni Arab nationalist who hated and despised European culture. For both uncle and nephew, the lodestar event was the pro-Nazi Rashid Ali coup of 1941, in which German planes attacked British forces in Iraq. Talfah participated in the coup; when it failed he was imprisoned for five years, leaving him with lasting bitterness and hatred that he communicated to his fatherless nephew. The Rashid Ali coup became a central myth of the Ba'thist movement.
- Saddam was shaped by the culture of his hometown Tikrit — remote from national life, oriented to the harsh desert. Tikrit's values of "suspicion, stealth, surprise, and the unalloyed use of force" were the ones Saddam absorbed. He was recruited into the Ba'th party as a teenager during the Suez crisis (1956). Shortly after joining, he reportedly carried out his first assassination — of a local political figure in Tikrit. In 1959, he was one of the assailants in the assassination attempt on Iraq's ruler Abdul Karim Kassem on Baghdad's main street. The attack failed; Hussein, wounded, fled to Egypt under a death sentence, not returning until 1963. He took charge of the Ba'th party's underground militia and became the strongman behind the Ba'thist regime that took power in 1968.
- He assumed the Presidency in 1979, replacing Ahmad Hasan al-Bakr (cousin of his uncle) — only in the course of a purge in which many Ba'thist party members were executed. To ensure the imprisoned Ba'thists provided appropriate confessions, Saddam took some of their families hostage. By 1979 he was known as a shaqawah — an implacable tough, "ruthless and emotionless when it came to those he considered as enemies, threats, obstacles to his objectives, or simply useful or convenient to run over."
- The new Iraqi regime was dominated by Tikritis, many related to Hussein. The government banned the use of names indicating clan, tribe, or locality. At the top sat members of Hussein's Talfah family and two other closely related families. His cousin and brother-in-law Adnan Khayr Alah Talfah was Minister of Defense. His cousin and son-in-law Hussein Kamil al-Majid became chief weapons buyer, responsible for nuclear and chemical weapons development.
- The influence of uncle Khayr Allah Talfah continued to be felt. In 1981, the government printing house distributed a pamphlet by Talfah titled Three Whom God Should Not Have Invented: Persians, Jews, and Flies.

### Khomeini vs. Hussein — The Road to War

- Khomeini held Hussein personally responsible for his troubles, ranking him among his preeminent enemies. When asked to list his enemies, Khomeini replied: "First, the Shah, then the American Satan, then Saddam Hussein and his infidel Ba'th Party." Khomeini's circle saw the Ba'thists as implacable enemies of their own creed and attacked Ba'thism as "the racist ideology of Arabism." Khomeini denounced Hussein as a "dwarf Pharaoh."
- Saddam had good reason to fear Khomeini's diatribes. Around half of Iraq's population was estimated to be Shia, while the Ba'thist regime was secular and based on the minority Arab Sunnis. Iraq was also the site of the holiest shrines of the Shia faith, and Shia agitation, fed from Iran, was growing. After an assassination attempt against his Deputy Prime Minister in April 1980, Hussein ordered the execution of the most prominent Shia ayatollah in Iraq and, for good measure, the ayatollah's sister. He denounced Khomeini as "Khomeini the rotten" and "a Shah dressed in religious garb."
- Iraq thought it saw its opportunity. Iran appeared disorganized and chaotic — "There is a government on every street corner in Iran." Iran's army was demoralized and in the grip of a bloody purge. Iraq could strike hard, topple Khomeini, end the Shiite revolutionary threat, assert sovereignty over the Shatt-al-Arab, and protect Iraq's oil position. There were even more enticing plums: Hussein could appeal to ethnic Arabs in Iran's Khuzistan (though less than half the population was of Arab descent) as their "liberator" and perhaps incorporate that territory, which the Iraqis called Arabistan. The prize was not merely fraternal reunification — 90% of Iran's oil reserves happened to be in Khuzistan. On top of all this, the Ba'thists could eradicate the wound of pride from the humiliating 1975 Algiers agreement. The Shah was gone; Hussein could assert Iraq's primacy, emerge as the new leader of the Arab world (with Egypt alienated by Camp David), and become one of the dominant oil powers. The opportunities were irresistible.
- Hussein billed the war as the "Second Battle of Qadisiyah" — the first having occurred in A.D. 636/637 near Najaf, when the Arabs defeated the Persians. That victory led to a further triumph in 642 celebrated as the "Victory of Victories," which sealed the doom of the Sassanid Persian Empire.

### Iraq's Blitzkrieg Fails — The Human Wave Assaults

- Hussein targeted the heart of the Iranian oil industry — Abadan and Ahwaz. He thought he could achieve all his objectives with a blitzkrieg of hard, sharp blows. In Vienna, at the disrupted OPEC meeting, the virtually universal assumption was that the war would be over in one or two weeks. But the Iraqi strategy proved a grave miscalculation: the Iranians withstood the first blow and struck back immediately at Iraqi targets. The assault actually enabled Khomeini to further consolidate his power, silence his critics, dispose of nonclerics in his government, and proceed with fashioning the Islamic Republic while mobilizing the population to resist.
- Iranians from virtually all political camps rushed to the common defense. The Arabs of Khuzistan showed no desire to be liberated by Iraq and did not welcome the Iraqis as "brothers." The Iraqis were unprepared for the "human wave" assaults — hundreds of thousands of young people, drawn by the Shiite vision of martyrdom, advanced on Iraqi positions in front of regular Iranian troops. Some arrived carrying their own coffins, exhorted by Khomeini that "the purest joy in Islam is to kill and be killed for God." They were given plastic keys to heaven to wear around their necks. Children were even used to clear minefields for the far more valuable tanks, and thousands of them died.

### The End of the Road — The Third Shock That Wasn't

- The war shook the oil market. On September 23, 1980, the second day of the war, Iraqi warplanes began a sustained assault against the Abadan refinery (the world's largest), proceeding over the next month to damage it severely. They also attacked every Iranian oil port and oil city. The Iranians counterattacked against Iraqi facilities, completely choking off Iraqi exports through the Gulf. Iran persuaded Syria (ruled by a rival Ba'thist party) to cut off Iraqi pipeline exports through Syria, leaving Iraq with only one limited pipeline through Turkey. Iranian exports were reduced, but Iraq's almost ceased — something Hussein had not counted on.
- In its initial stages, the Iran-Iraq war abruptly removed almost 4 million daily barrels — 15% of total OPEC output and 8% of free world demand. Spot prices jumped again. Arab light reached its highest price ever: $42/barrel. Was this the Third Shock? One reading of economic indicators pointed to a new shock; the other pointed in the opposite direction. Oil demand was certainly weakening — whether from recession (temporary) or conservation (lasting) was unclear. Economic contraction had already begun, compounded by a new resolve to fight inflation at all costs, even if it meant deep recession.
- Governments, working through the IEA, had learned the lessons of 1979 and concerted efforts to persuade companies not to buy in panic but to draw down inventories. The IEA message: things were manageable, this was not 1979, go easy, avoid "undesirable purchases." The message made more sense this time because since early 1979, companies had spent a great deal buying up supplies far in excess of demand. Those extra barrels had gone not into engines, furnaces, or power plants, but into storage. The Great Panic had turned into the Great Inventory Build, and when the war broke out, storage tanks around the world were brimming over, with supertankers chartered as additional floating storage.
- But the war reignited panic buying. "No matter what restraint we show," complained one refiner in November 1980, "there is still someone else out there who is willing to buy at higher prices and thereby pushes up the market." The all-important question was how companies would manage inventories. An American company executive: "Commercial firms can't afford such moves. Suggestions that we draw down inventories imply some knowledge of when the crisis will end. If I knew Iraq and Iran output would be back to prewar levels by July, sure I would draw down stocks." But he couldn't know.
- In December 1980, OPEC ministers met in Bali to discuss price. The Iranian oil minister had been captured by the Iraqis while touring the battlefield near Abadan — no one had bothered to tell him the area was in enemy hands. OPEC or no OPEC, Iraq would not free him. The Iranians were so angry they threatened to boycott all OPEC meetings. Indonesia's oil minister Dr. Subroto worked out a satisfactory compromise on seating (normally alphabetical, which would put Iran and Iraq next to each other): he inserted Indonesia between them. The Iranian delegation entered carrying a large portrait of their captured oil minister, which was placed in his designated chair. The conference concluded with another rise in OPEC prices, to a $36/barrel marker for all except the Saudis. A Third Shock was at hand — or so it seemed.

### The IEA Confrontation with Japan — D'Avignon's Threat

- At almost the same moment, energy ministers of the industrial nations gathered in Paris at the IEA. The mood was gloomy; the IEA's efforts to encourage inventory drawdown instead of panic buying were not meeting with great success. Japanese trading companies' frenetic purchasing had emerged as a particular sore subject. Near midnight, Count Etienne D'Avignon of Belgium, a forceful Commissioner of the European Community, lost his patience with the Japanese representative: "If you don't get your trading companies under control, you can forget about any more Toyotas and Sonys coming into Europe." The Japanese official paused: "You are a great international civil servant," he said at last. And he said no more.
- But MITI reinforced its "administrative guidance" to companies to go easy. By the end of 1980, the picture was becoming clearer: inventories remained very high, demand was continuing its precipitous fall, and market prices were weakening. It was becoming more and more uneconomic to hold on to stocks, creating a growing incentive to use inventories instead of buying additional oil.

### Saudi Overproduction and the Market Turns

- Not only was consumption declining, but supply from other sources was making up for the lost output from Iran and Iraq. The Saudis had been cranking out barrel after barrel to stifle the price surge. "We engineered the glut," Yamani once said, "and we want to see it in order to stabilize the price." Within days of the first battles, they pushed production up another 900,000 bpd, to the very limit of sustainable capacity — an increase equivalent to almost a quarter of the lost production from the two belligerents. Other OPEC producers also upped output, and even some oil from Iraq and Iran was coming back. Production from Mexico, Britain, Norway, Alaska, and other non-OPEC countries was continuing to increase. It was no longer just a "miniglut." Buyers were beginning to revolt against high prices. Non-OPEC producers cut their official prices to increase market share — their gain was OPEC's loss. OPEC's output in 1981 was 27% lower than 1979 output, the lowest it had been since 1970. Yamani's prophecy was at last coming true.

### The October 1981 Compromise and the End of Chapter 34

- OPEC was nearing the end of the road, though neither exporters, the industry, nor Western consuming countries had any idea of what lay ahead. Carter's Presidency had also ended: the hostages were not released until the very day he left office, succeeded by Ronald Reagan, whose buoyant confidence was more palatable to the electorate than Carter's "malaise."
- The oil market was responding to the phenomenal rise in prices over the 1970s and consumers' fears for the future. Yet the exporters were still unwilling to face up to the shifting "objective conditions" of the marketplace. They would not contemplate a price cut. Finally, in October 1981, they came to a new agreement: Saudi Arabia would raise its price from $32 to $34/barrel, while the others agreed to bring their price down from $36 to $34. Prices would be reunified. For the other producers, the compromise did mean a price cut. Saudi Arabia agreed, as part of the deal, to go back down to its old 8.5-million-barrel-per-day ceiling.
- Iraq and Iran remained locked in bitter battle. Yet even a war between two of the most important exporters could only retard, not cancel, the powerful forces set in motion by the two oil shocks. October 1981 represented the last time that the OPEC price would go up, at least for a decade. The "divine laws of supply and demand" were already in motion to drive prices down, "though not yet with the thunderous vengeance that was still to come. It was, as Yamani had said, as simple as ABC."

## Chapter 35: Just Another Commodity?

### The Greatest Boom of Them All

- None of the previous booms in an industry characterized by booms could rival the magnitude and madness of the fever at the end of the 1970s with the Second Oil Shock. It was the greatest boom of them all. With oil at $34/barrel, sums of money dwarfing anything ever before seen were involved. Oil companies plowed earnings back into new development, borrowed from banks, raised money from eager investors, leveraged themselves to the hilt. It was the golden age of the independent oil men — slapping backs, hiring drilling rigs, exploring at greater depths.
- To celebrate it all, at the very end of the 1970s, the television show Dallas went on the air, introducing the rapacious J.R. Ewing — replacing the lovable Clampetts of The Beverly Hillbillies — fashioning the image of the independent American oil man for years to come.
- In the US, the industry surged to a dizzy and unprecedented level of activity. Costs went out of control. Acreage, real estate in oil cities (Houston, Dallas, Denver), and drilling crew costs skyrocketed. Young geology graduates were wined, dined, and paid $50,000/year for their first job. Geologists with twenty years' experience quit the majors to put together deals, dreaming of becoming the next H.L. Hunt or J. Paul Getty. Doctors and dentists poured money into drilling funds, told their savings could be devastated by inflation and rising oil prices if they didn't have oil in their portfolios.

### The "Oil Mountain" and Exxon's Colony Shale Oil Project

- The industry was thought to be standing at the perilous edge of the "oil mountain" — supplies would begin precipitously falling away. Depletion combined with OPEC militancy would guarantee high and rising prices for an increasingly scarce commodity. Technology would have to create alternatives, setting a ceiling price for oil. This meant shale oil locked in the rock formations of the Western Slope of the Rockies in Colorado and Utah would finally be brought to market — exactly what Carter had proposed in 1979.
- Occidental, Unocal, and others were already working on shale oil technology. In 1980, Exxon hastily bought its way into the Colony Shale Oil Project on the Western Slope, spending fully a billion dollars on development, getting ready for the "new era" of energy. "Exxon had had a love affair with shale oil for a long time," recalled Clifton Garvin.
- But over the subsequent two years, the economic outlook changed quickly and drastically. In real terms, the oil price was going down; so was demand. Surplus production capacity was building. Colony Project cost estimates kept going up — "$6 or $8 billion for 50,000 barrels per day." One night Garvin told himself: "I can't spend shareholders' money that way." On May 2, 1982, Exxon announced tersely that it was terminating the Colony Project.
- The boom on Colorado's Western Slope ended literally in hours. The towns of Rifle, Battlement Mesa, and Parachute fell prey to the great tradition established at Pithole, Pennsylvania (1865-1866) — from dense forest to boom town of 15,000, to eerie ghost town. In Colorado, newly built homes were empty, apartments unrented, construction workers packed up and left, teenagers vandalized partly built homes and offices. "My business just died," said the owner of an office supply shop in Rifle. The boom to end all booms could not last.

### The Fundamentals — Recession, Conservation, and Non-OPEC Supply

- The US Federal Reserve responded to virulent inflation with exceedingly restrictive monetary policy — the prime rate reached 21.5% at one point. Tight money combined with the drain of spending power from oil price increases produced the deepest recession since the Great Depression, with two bottoms (1980 and the more severe 1982). The developing world, which was supposed to be a major source of new oil demand, instead went into steep economic decline — debt-laden, hit by recession in the industrial world — choking off their oil demand.
- Fundamental changes were taking place in the energy economy. Earlier fears of shortage (1920s, mid-1940s) had ended in surplus and glut because rising prices stimulated new technology and development of new areas. The pattern was now repeated at $34/barrel. Huge new developments were taking place outside OPEC: Mexico, Alaska, the North Sea all coincided with the Second Oil Shock. Egypt was also becoming a significant exporter. So were Malaysia, Angola, and China. Major innovations were improving exploration, production, and transportation technologies. The Alaskan pipeline's initial capacity of 1.7 million bpd was boosted to 2.1 million bpd with the addition of a chemical nicknamed "slickem" that reduced drag. Many things in exploration and production at $34/barrel that were not economical at $13 became viable. American oil production actually increased in the first half of the 1980s.
- The massive twentieth-century march toward higher dependence on oil within the total energy mix was reversed by higher prices, security considerations, and government policies. Coal staged a massive comeback in electricity generation and industry. Nuclear power made a rapid entry into electricity generation. In Japan, liquefied natural gas increased its share. Oil's share of the market for total energy in industrial countries declined from 53% in 1978 to 43% by 1985.
- Conservation had turned out to have massive impact. Energy conservation meant not deprivation but "greater efficiency and technological innovation." The 1975 legislation mandating a doubling of average fuel efficiency of new automobile fleets to 27.5 mpg by 1985 would reduce US oil consumption by 2 million bpd — just about equivalent to the 2 million bpd of additional production from Alaska. By 1985, the US was 25% more energy efficient and 32% more oil efficient than in 1973. If the US had stayed at 1973 efficiency levels, it would have used 13 million barrels of oil more than it actually did in 1985. Japan became 31% more energy efficient and 51% more oil efficient over the same period.
- By 1983, oil consumption in the noncommunist world was 45.7 million bpd — about 6 million bpd less than the 1979 high of 51.6 million. So while demand fell 6 million bpd between 1979 and 1983, non-OPEC production increased by 4 million bpd. On top of that, companies were eagerly disposing of the tremendous inventories built up in anticipation of demand that never materialized. Those three trends — the collapse in demand, the relentless buildup of non-OPEC supply, and the Great Inventory Dump — reduced the call on OPEC by about 13 million bpd, a fall of 43% from 1979 levels.

### Finally — The Cartel

- As late as 1977, OPEC had produced two-thirds of total free world crude. In 1982, for the first time, non-OPEC overtook OPEC production — and was still rising. Even Soviet oil exports to the West were substantially increasing. Much of the new oil, particularly from the North Sea, was sold on spot markets, making it very responsive to market conditions. Spot prices for a particular quality oil could be as much as $8/barrel lower than term contract prices — the difference between "a profit margin" and "formidable losses." Any buyer doing the simplest arithmetic was going to "go spot." New non-OPEC producers offered the most "market-responsive" (cheapest) prices to win market share.
- OPEC was confronted with an unpalatable choice: cut prices to regain markets, or cut production to maintain price. They did not want to reduce prices for fear of undermining their whole pricing structure and their newly acquired power and influence. They also feared that if they cut prices, industrial countries would raise excise and gasoline taxes, transferring oil rents from OPEC's treasuries to their own.
- In March 1982, OPEC (which had produced 31 million bpd in 1979) set an output limit of 18 million bpd, with individual quotas for each country except Saudi Arabia, which would adjust its production to support the system. OPEC had finally done what it had talked about — it had taken on the part played by the Texas Railroad Commission, turning itself into a true cartel, managing and allocating production as well as setting a price.
- New factors added to uncertainties: Iran was gaining the upper hand in the war with Iraq, becoming more belligerent toward Saudi Arabia and the Gulf states. In June 1982, Israel intervened in Lebanon. There was discussion of another embargo against the US as "punishment," but it was quickly scotched as irrelevant and dangerous in a distressed market. Meanwhile, King Khalid of Saudi Arabia died in June 1982 and was succeeded by Prince Fahd, who had already been the country's chief administrator and was the Royal Family's oil expert.
- By autumn 1982, the new quotas were already failing: demand was not recovering, non-OPEC production was still rising, and spot prices were plunging again. OPEC oil was still overabundant and overpriced.

### "Our Price Is Too High..." — The March 1983 London Meeting

- In 1983, competition mounted rapidly. The British North Sea sector alone was now producing more than Algeria, Libya, and Nigeria combined, with more coming on stream. Unofficial discounting and price cutting became the norm among OPEC countries. Saudi Arabia alone maintained the $34 marker — but buyers were forsaking Saudi Arabia in favor of discounted oil, even including the Aramco partners. Saudi production fell to its lowest level since 1970.
- Yamani offered a philosophical disquisition on the crisis: "Please excuse the comparison, but the history of the crisis is similar to that of a pregnant wife... The crisis started just like a normal pregnancy — with passion and joy. At this moment other members wanted us to raise the price of oil even higher despite our warnings... We were consumed with our moments of pleasure. But now the consequences had to be faced. Our price is too high in relation to the world market."
- By late February 1983, complete collapse seemed at hand. BNOC cut North Sea oil by $3 to $30/barrel — devastating to Nigeria, a country of 100 million whose economy was dangerously overdependent on oil. Nigerian oil competed directly with North Sea crudes, and Nigeria's normal buyers deserted the African country for cheaper North Sea oil. Nigeria virtually stopped exporting oil. "We are ready for a price war," Yahaya Dikko, the Nigerian oil minister, said firmly.
- In early March 1983, the oil ministers convened hurriedly at the Intercontinental Hotel at Hyde Park Corner, London — ironically the home court of their leading non-OPEC competitor, Great Britain. For twelve interminable, frustrating days they wrangled. OPEC slashed its prices by about 15% — from $34 to $29/barrel. It was the first time in OPEC's history that it had ever done such a thing. They also agreed on a 17.5-million-barrel-per-day quota for the whole group. OPEC had reset its price to meet the market — not a rising market price as in the past, but a falling one.
- One country had no official quota: Saudi Arabia. Yamani insisted the number would have been well below the 6 million bpd minimum acceptable to Riyadh. Instead, Saudi Arabia would "act as the swing producer to supply the balancing quantities to meet market requirements." For the first time, Saudi Arabia was explicitly charged with raising and lowering its output to balance the market and maintain the price. But OPEC's new system depended on twelve members not cheating and on Saudi Arabia's willingness and ability to play that pivotal role of swing producer.

### The Commodity Market — Oil's Transformation

- Behind OPEC's mutation into a true cartel was a far-reaching transformation of the oil industry itself. No longer would it be dominated by large, highly integrated companies. Instead, it would turn into a free-for-all, a clanging world of multitudinous buyers and sellers. Oil was becoming "just another commodity."
- Oil had always been a commodity — prices fluctuated wildly in the 1860s and 1870s. But the constant thrust toward integration had internalized price volatilities within the workings of a company, tying everything from the wellhead to the gasoline pump. Yamani warned: "Oil is not an ordinary commodity like tea or coffee. Oil is a strategic commodity. Oil is too important a commodity to be left to the vagaries of the spot or the futures markets, or any other type of speculative endeavor."
- But that was exactly what began to occur. Two forces drove the transformation: (1) The buildup of a huge surplus meant producers now had to worry about their access to markets, rather than consumers worrying about access to supplies. Buyers expected discounts, not security premiums. Security was hardly an issue anymore — what mattered was to be competitive in a glutted market. (2) The changing structure of the industry — exporting countries had assumed ownership of oil resources and international marketing, breaking the links that had tied their reserves to particular companies, refineries, and markets overseas. Companies, shorn of direct access to supplies, sought new resources elsewhere — but also had to find a new identity or become obsolete.
- Companies' focus shifted from long-term contracts to the spot market. Until the end of the 1970s, no more than 10% of internationally traded oil was found in spot markets — a fringe activity, a way to sop up excess refinery output. By the end of 1982, after the upheaval of the Second Oil Shock, more than half of internationally traded crude was either in the spot market or sold at prices keyed to spot.

### BP Leads the Way — Deintegration

- BP led the way into the new trading world, by no choice of its own. As a result of the upheaval in Iran and nationalization in Nigeria — on top of previous nationalizations in Kuwait, Iraq, and Libya — BP lost 40% of its supply. Desperately exposed, it went out into spot markets and began buying and trading oil on a larger and larger scale. The new BP could shop around for the cheapest crude, push efficiency throughout its operating units, and beat the competition. It became much more decentralized, with individual units responsible for their own profitability. The corporate culture changed from one dominated by the supply planner to one dominated by "traders and commercial people." BP's new chairman P.I. Walters: "It is nice to have some integration, obviously, but it is not something we would pay a premium for. We see ourselves as being much more opportunistic."
- Walters had long concluded that traditional integration, increasingly governed by computer models, did not make sense. The revelation came in June 1967, during the Six-Day War, when Aristotle Onassis abruptly canceled all chartering arrangements and offered BP his entire fleet at double rates. BP had until noon to decide. Walters realized "no computer program could help him now, only commercial judgment." He accepted Onassis's offer and returned to mowing his lawn. By Monday, tanker rates were four times what they had been on Friday. From that day, Walters became a campaigner for deintegrating BP's operations: "The proponents of further integration were moving in the wrong direction. They were handing over to machines what should be management judgments." He became famous for telling managers "there are no sacred cows in BP."

### The Aramco Partners Retreat and US Decontrol

- The four Aramco partners — Exxon, Mobil, Texaco, and Chevron — though somewhat cutting back, had continued taking large volumes of Saudi oil at "official prices" far above competitive crudes. The fundamental precept had always been to preserve access to Saudi oil. But in 1983-1984 they had to acknowledge the price for access was too high. George Keller, chairman of Chevron: "We couldn't keep pouring money down a hole. We had to back away, and ultimately we had to tell Yamani that we couldn't continue to do this." The Aramco links were not broken but significantly reduced. The alteration in the Aramco-Saudi Arabia commercial relationship was "one of the great symbols of how the oil industry was being transformed."
- The shift toward the commodity market was facilitated by the decontrol of US oil prices and the elimination of various controls. The US was no longer insulated from the world oil market — it was now tightly tied into the rest of the market. American output accounted for almost a quarter of total free world production, and one particular stream of American crude would become the new bellwether for the global industry.

### From Eggs to Oil — The Birth of NYMEX Crude Futures

- The emergence of West Texas Intermediate (WTI) as the benchmark reflected another momentous innovation: in 1983, the New York Mercantile Exchange (Nymex) introduced a futures contract in crude oil. This took place on the eighth floor of the World Trade Center, not in Vienna, Riyadh, or Houston.
- Futures markets allow buyers and sellers to minimize risk: a buyer acquires the right to buy at a specific future price (locking in costs), and a producer can sell forward (locking in revenue). Both are hedgers. "Liquidity" is provided by speculators hoping to profit from market psychology and supply-demand swings. Futures had existed for commodities like grain and pork bellies for years. In the 1970s, as the world economy became more volatile, futures emerged for gold, interest rates, currencies, and finally oil.
- The Nymex had not exactly enjoyed a distinguished career. Founded in 1872 (the same year Rockefeller launched "our plan" to take over the industry), it began as the Butter and Cheese Exchange for sixty-two New York City merchants. Eggs were added; it became the Butter, Cheese, and Egg Exchange, then the New York Mercantile Exchange. The Maine potato was the mainstay until the supply-demand balance changed and potato scandals hit (including the "mortifying failure of delivered stocks of potatoes to pass inspection"). The exchange abruptly terminated trading in Maine potatoes and was itself threatened with extinction.
- Just in time, the Nymex introduced a home heating oil contract, then gasoline futures (1981), and on March 30, 1983 — just two weeks after OPEC concluded its marathon London meeting — the exchange introduced futures in crude oil. "The juxtaposition was ironic, for the crude oil futures contract would resolutely undermine OPEC's price-setting powers."
- Floor traders took enthusiastically to crude futures. The initial reaction from established oil companies was "skepticism and outright hostility." A senior executive of one of the majors dismissed oil futures "as a way for dentists to lose money." But within a few years, most major oil companies, some exporting countries, and large financial houses were all participating. As volume built up astronomically, "Maine potatoes became a distant, quaint, and embarrassing memory."
- The evolution of price-setting: First it had been Standard Oil. Then the Texas Railroad Commission system and the majors. Then OPEC. Now price was being established every day, instantaneously, on the open market, in the interaction of floor traders on the Nymex with buyers and sellers glued to computer screens worldwide. "It was like the late-nineteenth-century oil exchanges of western Pennsylvania, but reborn with modern technology." The benchmark was WTI — a plentiful, easily traded crude stream and a good proxy for the world oil price. Two decades earlier, Arab light had supplanted Texas Gulf Coast oil as the world's marker crude. Now, in almost full circle, it was back to Texas. The price of WTI joined the gold price, interest rates, and the Dow Jones as among the most vital measures of the daily beat of the world economy.

### New Oil Wars: The Shootout at Value Gap

- With restructuring of global markets, the oil industry went through wholesale corporate reorganization. Deregulation removes protection and increases competitive pressure, typically resulting in consolidations, spinoffs, takeovers. Oil was completely deregulated by 1981. Overcapacity and weakening prices encouraged consolidation. Institutional investors (pension, mutual fund, money managers) — who controlled three-quarters of the stock of major American corporations — were becoming more aggressive, insisting on higher returns and unwilling to wait around for the long term. The oil industry was losing its luster after the boom.
- At the heart of the restructuring was the "value gap" — when a company's shares did not fully reflect what its oil and gas reserves would fetch. Companies with the greatest gap between stock price and asset value were most vulnerable. New management could enhance "shareholders' value" — and it could cost two or three times more to add a barrel by exploration than by buying another company's assets. The obvious implication: it was cheaper to "explore for oil on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange" — buy undervalued companies — than to explore under the topsoil of West Texas or the seabed of the Gulf of Mexico. Many companies had taken the huge cash flows from the two oil shocks and put them right back into exploration in the US, seeking secure alternatives to OPEC. The results were very disappointing — reserves were still declining, the expenditure proved inefficient and wasteful.
- The value gap facilitated a great upheaval — a series of corporate battles pitting company against company, with Wall Street warriors mixed in and sometimes in command. It was an entirely new kind of oil war.

### The Trigger — T. Boone Pickens

- The trigger for the upheaval was found in Amarillo, Texas — a town of 150,000 on the high, flat, dry Panhandle plateau. Oil and gas was the biggest business, run mostly by small independents. Cattle was another major business. So was nuclear weaponry — Amarillo was the nation's only center for final fabrication of nuclear bombs, producing four warheads a day.
- T. Boone Pickens, more than anyone else, detonated the explosions that remade the corporate landscape of oil. In the financial community, Pickens was widely applauded — he made things happen, enhanced shareholders' value. In the oil industry, while admired by some, he was loathed by others. He said he was pushing the industry "back to basics, fighting its self-indulgent waste." His adversaries said he was "merely a clever opportunist, with a gift for salesmanship, who wrapped old-fashioned greed in the mantle of shareholders' rights." Pickens saw the vulnerabilities of the oil industry on the backside of the Second Oil Shock earlier and with more clarity than most. On one level, his campaign "represented the revenge of the independent oil man on the hated majors."
- Born in 1928, Pickens grew up in the oil patch near Seminole, Oklahoma (site of one of the greatest Oklahoma discoveries). His father was a landman; his mother was in charge of gasoline rationing for three counties during WWII. He was "brash, self-confident, independent-minded, sharp-tongued, and outspoken." He did not readily accept the established order and "hated to lose." He went to work for Phillips after studying geology, but could not stand the bureaucracy. A boss told him: "If you're ever going to make it big with this company, you've got to learn to keep your mouth shut." In 1954, after three and a half years, he quit Phillips to become an independent, hustling around the oil states, using phone booths as offices, shaving in gas station restrooms.
- By 1964, Pickens had rolled up his various drilling deals into Mesa Petroleum. After Mesa went public, he became fascinated by the gap between stock value and the value of underlying oil and gas assets. He fastened his eyes on Hugoton Production — a sleepy but considerably larger company with extensive gas reserves in the nation's largest gas field in southwestern Kansas. Its stock price was much lower than what its reserves would have fetched. In 1969, he completed a hostile takeover of Hugoton and merged it into Mesa, creating a significant independent.
- Pickens was an inveterate trader, a veteran of futures long before most in the oil industry had even heard of them. His early speciality was cattle futures — at one point he took Mesa into the cattle-feeding business, making it the second-largest cattle feeder in the nation (the venture ended poorly). Even at the height of the oil wars of the mid-1980s, with billions at stake, Pickens would look out the window as his plane descended over the Texas range and start counting cattle to decide whether to go long or short on cattle futures. "It was sport."

### Pickens's Corporate Raids Begin

- Pickens had been an intense basketball then racketball player — speed, fast breaks, unexpected moves, quick reflexes, constant improvisation. That was the way he did business. "We used to crowd into Boone's office every Saturday morning, some of us sitting on the floor, and Boone would ask us how we were going to make money the next week." His style — game-planned, attentive to detail, but also highly improvisational — made him a tough rival for the big bureaucratic companies. His standard retort when hearing a competitor had done something he didn't like: "Tell them to go kiss a fat man's ass."
- By the early 1980s, Pickens was seeing the weaknesses: the US was a declining producer with increasingly poor prospects and disappointing discovery records. Stock prices of oil companies did not reflect the sale value of their proven reserves. It was Hugoton Production all over.
- His initial target (1982) was Cities Service — the nineteenth largest US oil company, thirty-eighth largest industrial corporation in the Fortune 500, three times the size of Mesa. But its stock sold for only a third of the appraised value of its oil and gas reserves. Mesa acquired a block of stock. Cities Service counter-tendered for Mesa. Gulf intervened with an offer for Cities at almost double its pre-brouhaha price, but then backed out. Finally, Armand Hammer's Occidental acquired all of Cities' stock. Mesa made a $30 million profit. That was the first move.

### Megamergers and the Boom Turns Sour

- Restructuring and megamergers were already spreading. Shell acquired Belridge (1979) for $3.6 billion — the largest corporate acquisition to that point. In 1981, Conoco escaped a Dome Petroleum takeover by falling into DuPont's arms for $7.8 billion. Mobil took a run at Marathon, which sold itself to US Steel for $5.9 billion (a way to diversify out of the disaster of the American steel industry). Mesa made a bid for General American, but Phillips picked it up for $1.1 billion.
- The global oil boom was turning sour. Exploration in the US fell away. Refinancings and bankruptcies among smaller companies jumped. Major companies started belt-tightening — cutbacks, hiring freezes, early retirements. Investors began forsaking the oil patch for the stock market; mutual funds and red-hot money managers were more interesting than oil, drilling programs, and geologists.

### The Mexican Weekend — Oil and the Global Financial Crisis

- Mexico had run up a huge international debt (over $84 billion by 1982) on the basis of its sudden emergence as a world oil power. Jesus Silva Herzog became Finance Minister in April 1982. To his shock, the country was on the edge of a grave economic crisis — the result of weakening oil prices, high interest rates, a severely overvalued peso, unrestrained government spending, and the drying up of markets for Mexico's non-oil exports. There was also immense capital flight. Mexico was unable to service its enormous debt.
- Silva Herzog began making secret Thursday-night trips from Mexico City to Washington to see Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker. He arranged a $900 million emergency loan, but it was dissipated in a week by capital flight. On August 12, 1982, he concluded improvisation would not work. Mexico could default — but that might cause the international financial system to collapse. The loan exposure of the nine largest American money center banks to Mexico was equivalent to 44% of their total capital.
- On August 13, Silva Herzog flew to Washington — the episode that became "the Mexican Weekend." He told Treasury Secretary Donald Regan: "We have to organize something, or otherwise there will be very serious international consequences." Regan: "You really have a problem." Silva Herzog: "No, Mr. Secretary, we have a problem." They worked nonstop through Sunday morning, assembling a multi-billion-dollar package of loans, credits, and advance purchases of Mexican oil for the Strategic Petroleum Reserve. Near 3:00 a.m. Sunday, negotiations nearly broke down when Silva Herzog discovered a $100 million service fee buried in the agreement. He was furious: "This is not a business transaction. Sorry, I cannot accept this." He called President Lopez Portillo, who said to terminate discussions and return to Mexico City. Later that day, the US Treasury rescinded the fee. The Mexican Weekend concluded with the first part of the emergency package in place. What was devised was a debt moratorium — politely called a "rollover." Mexico had, at least in part, defaulted.
- Silva Herzog reflected: "I thought of my father and the role he played in the oil expropriation... And now here I was in Mexico's worst crisis since the one of 1938, and it was also a crisis involving oil. We had just committed terrible mistakes on the basis of oil. But there had been this great mood of victory... We thought we were rich. We had oil."
- The Mexican debt drama brought home the reality that the global oil boom was over, and that "oil power" was less powerful than assumed. Oil could mean not only wealth but also weakness. The world oil crisis was now giving way to the international debt crisis — many world-class debtors would turn out to be oil nations.

### Penn Square and Continental Illinois — The Banking Fallout

- At the same time Mexico was teetering, Penn Square — a tiny go-go energy bank in an Oklahoma City shopping center — was on the edge of insolvency. Its senior energy lending officer liked to drink Amaretto and soda out of his Gucci loafers. Penn Square had generated a huge volume of questionable oil and gas loans, then sold some $2 billion worth "upstream" to major money center banks: Continental Illinois, Bank of America, Chase Manhattan. The loan portfolio Penn Square retained was worthless; regulators closed it down.
- But that was not the end. Continental Illinois — largest bank in the Midwest, seventh largest in the nation, the fastest-growing lender, winner of awards for management, its chairman named "Banker of the Year" — had been the most aggressive energy lender. As a competitor put it, Continental was "eating our lunch" in oil and gas loans. When oil prices weakened, Continental Illinois was "walking on nothing more solid than thin air." In 1984, it was hit by the largest bank run in history — all around the globe, banks and companies yanked their money. The Federal government intervened with a huge bailout: $5.5 billion of new capital, $8 billion in emergency loans, new management. Continental Illinois had, at least temporarily, been nationalized. With its collapse, energy lending "instantaneously went out of fashion."

### Dr. Drill — The Mukluk Wildcat

- Half of the undiscovered oil and gas in the US was thought to be in Alaska or adjacent waters. All eyes focused on Mukluk — a vast underground structure fourteen miles off the north coast of Alaska, sixty-five miles northwest of Prudhoe Bay. It was billed as "the most exciting prospect to come around for a generation." BP geologists said the odds were one in three instead of the normal one in eight. The effort to drill cost over $2 billion — companies had to build their own gravel island from which to drill in the frigid Arctic waters.
- In the first week of December 1983, "Dr. Drill spoke" — at eight thousand feet below the seabed, where the pay sands were supposed to begin, the drill had struck salt water. Mukluk was dry. Oil had once been trapped there, but either the structure was breached (a gigantic oil spill with no environmental gauging) or regional tilting caused it to migrate into the Prudhoe Bay structure. "We drilled in the right place," said the president of Sohio's production company. "We were simply 30 million years too late."
- Mukluk was not only the most expensive dry hole in history; it was also the turning point for exploration in the US. Betting so heavily on exploration was too risky and too expensive. Managements would face penalties for continuing to risk and lose money on such a scale. In the minds of many senior executives, Mukluk sent a bracing message: they ought to shift from exploring for oil to acquiring proven reserves — buying individual properties or entire companies. After Mukluk, they were much more in a buying mood.

### Family Matters — Getty Oil and Texaco

- Not only economics and geology drove restructuring — so did hatreds, resentments, and feuds inside families. A war among the Keck family heirs resulted in Mobil's acquiring Superior Oil ($5.7 billion). But the most prominent family troubles were at Getty Oil. J. Paul Getty had died in 1976, and by the 1980s Getty Oil was not replacing its reserves and its stock was selling at a very low price relative to its holdings. Gordon Getty, one of J. Paul's sons (more interested in composing music — a song cycle based on Emily Dickinson's poems — than in searching for oil), wondered where all the value had gone. That put him at odds with the professional managers running Getty.
- Two knocks came. First, from Pennzoil — a large independent run by Hugh Liedtke, an early partner of George Bush and friend of Boone Pickens. In some manner, Getty assented to the Pennzoil offer. The second knock came from Texaco, whose chairman appeared at the Pierre Hotel (once owned by the elder Getty) to make a counteroffer. Gordon Getty definitely accepted. So Texaco got Getty Oil for $10.2 billion. It also got sued by Pennzoil.

### The Death of a Major — Pickens Goes After Gulf Oil

- In July 1983, Mesa was committed to spending $300 million on an exploration program — fifty-one drilling rigs, five very expensive ones in the Gulf of Mexico. "Boys," Pickens announced at a board meeting, "this is it. We've got to figure out a way to make $300 million, and we've got to make it fast. We've lost too much money in the Gulf of Mexico. We can't drill our way out of this one. A field goal won't do it — we need a touchdown."
- Pickens' eyes fastened on Gulf Oil — one of the Seven Sisters, built by the Mellon family on the basis of Guffey and Galey's discovery at Spindletop in 1901, a major American institution and global company. It had firmly planted the American flag in Kuwait. The Mellons had long since stepped aside from active management; the family had fragmented and sold off much of its holdings. Gulf was the most vulnerable of the majors — its stock was selling at little more than a third of its appraised value.
- Pickens had a close-in view of Gulf management during the Cities Service struggle and decided it was "ineffective and indecisive," with a heavy bureaucratic structure that would be slow to respond. Gulf had suffered ten years of internal problems and deep splits — illegal political contributions (some tied to Watergate), controversial foreign payments, a purge of senior management and replacement by managers whose "appearance of probity was among their most important qualifications." The chairman who took over was nicknamed "Mr. Clean" and "the Boy Scout." Gulf was the only major oil company to place a nun on its board of directors. "These problems had meant six years of no decision... during a crucial time in the oil industry, during the OPEC turmoil, and at a time when everything was up in the air in the Far East, and we were losing our ass in Europe."
- Gulf's woes were long. In 1975, its Kuwait concession (a substantial part of earnings) had been nationalized. It lost a costly antitrust case on uranium marketing. Despite vast sums spent searching for politically secure oil in the US, domestic reserves were falling rapidly — declining 40% between 1978 and 1982. It was not well-positioned and had lost "a great deal of its old raison d'etre as a global company undertaking a massive international exploration and production effort. It had not yet found a new one."
- The new chairman, Jimmy Lee (successor to "Mr. Clean"), embodied the evolution of the major oil companies. He had worked in Gulf's Philadelphia refinery in the late 1940s, built refineries and marketing systems in the Philippines and Korea, headed the entire Far Eastern operation, was Gulf's man in Kuwait during the Middle Eastern battles, and ran Gulf's entire Eastern Hemisphere from London. Now he was back in Pittsburgh to rebuild the battered company. But he wouldn't have much time.

### The Battle for Gulf Oil

- In August 1983, Mesa started accumulating Gulf stock through numbered bank accounts with transfer codes known only to one or two people. In October, Mesa formed the Gulf Investors Group (GIG), providing financial clout for the offensive. GIG's objective was to push Gulf into transferring half its US oil and gas reserves into a royalty trust owned directly by stockholders (eliminating double taxation on dividends).
- Gulf initiated a counterattack targeting its 400,000 shareholders. But Gulf's senior management was sharply divided on how to proceed, making it seem indecisive — just as Pickens had predicted. In contrast, Pickens was "quick, flexible, continually improvising, and imaginative." He knew how to court institutional shareholders, play to the public, and handle the press. He presented himself as "the champion of shareholders, an authentic oil man, a populist, not a faceless bureaucrat from 'the good ol' boys club' of 'Big Oil.'"
- Gulf managed to squeak to victory in the proxy vote in December 1983, by a bare 52% to 48%. But it was only a reprieve. Pickens submitted a written proposal to spin off oil and gas reserves directly to shareholders; the board turned him down flat. He went to see the junk bond king Michael Milken at Drexel Burnham in Beverly Hills to explore raising money for an outright takeover bid.
- Jimmy Lee knew time was short. In late January 1984, he took a call from Robert O. Anderson, chairman of ARCO, who wanted to discuss things of "material interest." They met for dinner at the Brown Palace Hotel in Denver. Anderson wanted Gulf's foreign production — he believed the future of the major oil companies lay in overseas reserves and "the international circuit." He was willing to pay $62/share for Gulf (a big increase over its $41 pre-Pickens price). Lee replied by suggesting the two companies merge their US oil operations, which would have given Gulf half of ARCO's immensely valuable North Slope reserves. Anderson said "no thank you."
- Then Anderson called Lee again: "I think I should tell you that I had dinner last night in Denver with Boone Pickens. I told him that we were prepared to pay $62 a share for Gulf." Lee: "Thanks for telling me this," restraining his sarcasm. Anderson's objective in meeting Pickens was to understand what Pickens was trying to do and to ascertain that he would not block any deal. But Lee saw it differently — as soon as he hung up, he summoned his crisis team: "Bob Anderson has just cut our legs out from under us. For all practical purposes, we're in play."
- Anderson's second call ended whatever hopes Lee had that Gulf could remain independent. "The game was up." There had been a long-observed aversion among major oil companies against making hostile offers for one another. But Anderson's proposition, following Mobil's run at Marathon, made clear that the rule was no longer valid. Now there was a price on Gulf's head. Lee decided to go for the best price, telephoning CEOs of the other large companies with the same message: "We're vulnerable... If you're interested in taking a look, start doing your financials."
- Pickens played the next card, topping ARCO's $62 offer with a $65 tender offer. Lee: "I knew that $65 was a low ball. If someone's going to take your company, you might as well get the most you can."

### Chevron Wins Gulf — $13.2 Billion

- George Keller, chairman of Chevron (descended from Standard Oil Trust's western operations, headquartered in San Francisco), had already become interested in Gulf. Chevron had an admirable record of taking risks and finding oil, including in Saudi Arabia in the 1930s. But like other top executives, Keller had been shaken by the Mukluk failure: "After that, almost everybody decided to put more money into better bets."
- On New Year's Eve 1984, the chairman of Getty Oil had called Keller asking if Chevron would look at Getty. Keller's team analyzed Getty against other companies: Superior, Unocal, Sun — and Gulf. Getty was soon acquired by Texaco, but Chevron was still looking closely at Gulf. After Jimmy Lee's second phone call, Chevron frantically set about valuing Gulf. By March 3, they had a range: Gulf was worth $62/share at the most pessimistic end; at the most optimistic, $105 — anywhere from $10.2 to $17.3 billion. "It was a hell of a range," said Keller. Chevron's board authorized up to $78/share, with the actual proposal at Keller's discretion. "For God's sake, put a ceiling on it," begged Keller, unnerved by the thought of sole responsibility — "Every dollar higher on the stock means another $135 million."
- On March 5, the Gulf board met at its ornate Pittsburgh headquarters (virtually deserted, as most operations had moved to Houston). There were three serious offers: ARCO's ($72/share), Kohlberg Kravis Roberts' ($87.50/share, 56% cash, 44% securities — a leveraged buyout), and Chevron's (unknown amount). ARCO's was dismissed as too low. KKR's offer was more money in theory but riskier — Gulf's financial advisers (Merrill Lynch, Salomon Brothers) could not figure out what the "paper" would be worth, and the outside directors worried that accepting a management buyout could appear self-serving.
- Keller, waiting his turn, had an offer letter with just one blank spot — the price. He knew the two great risks: crude prices going down and interest rates going up. He picked up his pen and filled in $80/share — $13.2 billion, all cash. The reception from the Gulf board seemed chilly. He returned to the Chevron floor to await the decision.
- After seven hours of debate, the phone rang. It was Jimmy Lee. "Hello, George. You just bought yourself an oil company." All Keller could think was that he felt like someone who had bid on a house for the first time and discovered, to his shock, that he now owned it. It was a $13.2 billion house. That was the end of Gulf Oil — Spindletop, Guffey and Galey, the Mellons, Kuwait, Major Holmes — it was all over. It was history.
- Anderson (ARCO) was philosophical about losing: his absolute limit was $75. "At least if you like to lose a merger, you like to lose by a wide margin rather than by a narrow one. You hate to lose by a dollar a share." As far as Pickens was concerned, it was a great victory for stockholders — during his campaign, Gulf's stock price went from $41 to $80, and total market capitalization was raised from $6.8 billion to $13.2 billion, a $6.5 billion profit for Gulf stockholders. "That was $6.5 billion that would have never been made if Mesa and GIG hadn't come on the scene." His Gulf Investors Group made a $760 million profit, of which about $500 million went to Mesa — after tax, just about the $300 million Mesa had so desperately craved. Pickens was the highest-paid corporate executive in America that year ($18.6 million deferred bonus).
- Jimmy Lee's first reaction was relief. He set out to talk to employees around the country, but "over the next several days, exhaustion took over. So did sadness, and he sometimes broke into tears. 'I never had any intention but that Gulf would be here for ever and ever... It had been my whole life, my whole career. To think that it wasn't going to be there any more really got to me.'" Keller: "It was a good buy... We were able to acquire assets on a scale that would never be available otherwise." Why was Gulf in trouble? "It had ignored its solid existing position. It had decided it had to have one great big elephant. It was as though, instead of risking its future in the town in which it lived, it decided to go to Las Vegas. It missed everywhere."

### Shareholders' Value — Phillips, Unocal, ARCO, and Exxon

- Pickens was not yet through. In rapid fire, he made bids for both Phillips (Bartlesville, Oklahoma) and Unocal (Los Angeles). On Phillips, he was trailed by Carl Icahn, who had already bagged Trans World Airlines. Both companies successfully fought off the takeover attempts through the courts and by assuming a great deal of debt, buying back stock at much higher prices — increasing the payout to shareholders. Mesa made significant profits in both cases. After Unocal survived, its chairman Fred Hartley received a call from Armand Hammer of Occidental, who told him "he deserved a Nobel Prize for his valor."
- ARCO itself, seeing it might be vulnerable "to a Pickens, or to the Pickens," carried out a sort of self-acquisition — leveraging to buy back its stock at a higher price while sharply consolidating its activities and employment. Robert O. Anderson: "We were a sitting duck unless we got our share values up more closely to the values of our company."
- Royal Dutch/Shell paid $5.7 billion for the 31% of Shell Oil U.S.A. it did not already own. BP, disillusioned with Sohio's management (including the Mukluk fiasco), paid $7.6 billion for the rest of Sohio's shareholders to own the company completely and control the huge cash flow from Alaska.
- Exxon, at least until the beginning of the 1990s, stayed away from the high-visibility arena of mergers. It had been badly stung by its poor acquisitions record (Fortune once named two of its purchases among the five worst acquisitions of the 1970s). Clifton Garvin: Exxon had "a phobia about acquisition." Instead, Exxon spent $16 billion on share buy-backs between 1983 and mid-1990, guaranteeing stockholders a rising stock price and good yield, and ensuring nobody could claim Exxon shareholders were getting the short end of the stick. It also cut the number of its employees by 40%.
- Restructuring meant a smaller and more consolidated petroleum industry. Beginning geologists were no longer hired at $50,000/year — they were not being hired at all. The biggest losers were the people whose jobs were wiped out. "I thought I was working for a great social institution," said one executive whose job disappeared in Chevron's acquisition of Gulf. "I didn't think I was giving 25 years of my life, with all the costs for my family, for some pieces of paper." The great beneficiaries were the shareholders — all the mergers, acquisitions, recapitalizations, and stock buy-backs propelled well over $100 billion into the pockets of institutional and individual investors, pension funds, arbitrageurs. The shareholders did, eventually, win out.

### The New Security — 1985 Bonn Summit

- In May 1985, the seven major Western powers met in Bonn. The themes were free market politics, deregulation, and privatization. Reagan had been reelected by an enormous margin. Thatcher was well embarked on her reconstruction of British society. Even Mitterrand had jettisoned nationalization in favor of free markets. The Western world was in its third year of relatively vibrant economic growth — but this recovery was fundamentally different from previous ones: it was not being fueled by a rise in oil demand. The economies had adapted to high oil prices, and oil use was flat.
- The only serious energy question that leaders had grappled with recently was a divisive early-1980s battle over European plans to increase imports of Soviet gas. The Europeans wanted energy diversification and reduced dependence on oil, plus employment in engineering and steel. The Reagan Administration opposed the plan, fearing Soviet political leverage over Europe and hard currency earnings strengthening the Soviet economy and military. Washington banned export of American equipment, then sought to prohibit European equipment containing American technology — setting off "the most severe European-American conflict since the October War and the embargo in 1973." Margaret Thatcher personally called Reagan: "John Brown is going under, Ron." She flew to Scotland to be present when John Brown began exporting equipment in explicit defiance of the American ban. A compromise was finally reached: Europeans would restrict Soviet imports to 30% of total gas, and Norway's huge Troll field would be promoted as an alternative source within NATO.
- The 1985 Bonn summit issues revealed how the world had changed: they were "West-West" issues — protectionism, the dollar, accommodating Japan's economic challenge. Oil and energy, the preeminent "North-South" issue, was not on the table at all. Oil was available in abundance and was not a constraint on economic growth. Excess oil capacity exceeded demand by 10 million bpd (20% of the free world's consumption). The US, Germany, and Japan were putting significant amounts into strategic petroleum reserves — restoring the "security margin" absent during the 1970s.
- Iran and Iraq were breaking all the supposed "taboos" in their continuing conflict — attacking each other's cities, refineries, oil fields, and tankers, including tankers bearing the flags of other nations. But the bombing of a tanker, which earlier would have sent oil prices shooting up, could now just as easily cause the price to go down on spot and futures markets.
- For the first time since these summits had been instituted a decade earlier, the leaders issued a communique in which there was nothing about oil and energy. Not a single word. The omission itself was a powerful statement — the world economy had adjusted and accommodated itself to the upheavals of the 1970s. Oil did not seem to need any special tending; it was indeed "just another commodity." Half of the equation — secure oil supplies — appeared to be coming back into place. The other half, however, was not there. Oil was still not cheap — not yet.

## Chapter 36: The Good Sweating: How Low Can It Go?

### The Price Question

- The price of oil was balanced precariously in the mid-1980s. As the president of Esso Europe said in 1984: "Today, the price of oil is the chief variable in our equation and the greatest single source of uncertainty about the future." The answer would have a profound impact not only on oil companies but would determine the future vigor of "oil power" in world politics and mightily affect global economic prospects and the shifting balance of world economic and political strength.
- High prices would favor oil exporters — from Saudi Arabia to Libya to Mexico to the Soviet Union (which depended on oil, along with natural gas, for most of the hard currency it used to purchase Western technology). Low prices would favor the oil-importing countries — Germany, Japan. In between was the United States, with interests on both sides: the world's largest importer and consumer, yet also the world's second-largest producer, and a good part of its financial system had cast its fate with high oil prices.

### OPEC Quotas Fail — Cheating and Barter

- Despite becoming even more restrictive in 1984, OPEC's quota system was not working. Non-OPEC production continued to grow; coal, nuclear power, and natural gas were still taking markets away from oil; and conservation still shrinking demand. As revenues dwindled, quota cheating became more obvious. OPEC retained an international accounting firm to police the quotas — but the accountants had great difficulty gaining entree to some OPEC countries and were "completely denied entrance to key facilities." Various exporters turned to barter and countertrade — exchanging oil directly for weapons, planes, and industrial goods — which had the effect of increasing the oversupply.

### High or Low? — BNOC Abolished

- In the 1970s, BNOC (British National Oil Company) bought up to 1.3 million barrels/day from North Sea producers and resold it to refiners, giving it an important price-setting role. But with weakening prices, BNOC found itself buying at one price and selling at a lower one — a significant loss for BNOC and the British Treasury. Margaret Thatcher, who saw "no security reason to maintain BNOC," simply abolished it in the spring of 1985. The elimination of BNOC "removed one more important prop from the OPEC price; it was another victory for the market."
- In the oil industry, the general view was that while the price might sink a few dollars, it would recover and start rising toward the end of the 1980s or beginning of the 1990s. Yet weak demand, growing supply capacity, and the shift to the commodity market all pointed much more strongly in one direction — down. But how far?

### OPEC's Deepening Dilemma — Saudi Arabia's Impossible Position

- By the mid-1980s, OPEC faced a critical choice: cut price (but where would a falling price stop?), or continue propping up price — which would be holding up an umbrella under which non-OPEC oil, competing energy sources, and conservation would all flourish, guaranteeing OPEC a shrinking market share. Even as the Iran-Iraq War dragged on, exports from both belligerents were recovering. Nigeria adopted a "Nigeria first" policy aimed at maximizing exports.
- Saudi Arabia, as swing producer since 1983, was bearing disproportionate costs. The high point of Saudi earnings was $119 billion in 1981. By 1984, revenues had fallen to $36 billion, and would fall further to $26 billion in 1985. The country had embarked on a great spending and development program, now had to cut back dramatically, was running a large budget deficit, and its foreign reserves were being drawn down. The promulgation of the national budget was indefinitely postponed.
- The loss of market was reducing Saudi Arabia to a more marginal role on the world stage — at a time when the Iran-Iraq War was threatening the region and Khomeini continued his vendetta against Saudi Arabia. Yamani on Saudi television: "Crude oil is a political power and no one can deny that Arab political power in 1973 was based on oil and that its influence reached its peak in the Western world in 1979... At present we are suffering because of the weakness of Arab political power based on oil. These are elementary facts which are known even to the man in the street."
- The Saudis sent warning after warning: they would not continue to accept loss of market share, would not indefinitely tolerate quota violations and increased non-OPEC production, could not be counted on to be the swing producer. If need be, Saudi Arabia would flood the market. Were these warnings serious? Without a change, Saudi production might fall to a million barrels per day or less — and Saudi Arabia "would on the world stage almost cease being Saudi Arabia."

### Market Share — King Fahd's Letter and Production Collapse

- In June 1985, OPEC ministers congregated at Taif in Saudi Arabia. Yamani read them a letter from King Fahd sharply criticizing the cheating that had led "to a loss of markets for Saudi Arabia." The King: "If Member countries feel they have a free hand to act, then all should enjoy this situation and Saudi Arabia would certainly secure its own interests." The Nigerian oil minister hoped "this wise message had sunk in." But in the following weeks Saudi production sagged to as low as 2.2 million barrels per day — half its quota, little more than a fifth of what it had been producing half a decade earlier. Exports to the US, which had been 1.4 million bpd in 1979, slumped to a mere 26,000 bpd in June 1985 — "essentially nothing."
- At times, Saudi output fell below that of the British North Sea sector. "Here was the last outrage" — the Saudis were propping up the price so the British could produce more while Thatcher celebrated her indifference to whether oil prices were high or low. The Iraqis were also reconstructing export capacity and adding new pipelines through Saudi Arabia. Something had to give.

### The "Good Sweating" — Netback Deals

- A shade from the past: in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Rockefeller and his colleagues had instituted a "good sweating" against competitors by flooding the market and cutting prices. In the mid-1980s, circumstances were wholly different, yet not so different after all. "Once again, a 'good sweating' was at hand."
- The Saudis moved from a defense of price to a defense of volume — choosing an ingenious weapon: netback deals with the Aramco partners and other oil companies. Under these deals, Saudi Arabia would not charge a fixed price. Rather, it would be paid based on what the refined products earned in the marketplace. The refiner was guaranteed a predetermined profit off the top — say $2/barrel. No matter whether the final selling price of the products was $29 or $19 or $9, the refiner got his $2 and the Saudis got the rest. The refiner's profit was locked in, so he had no compulsion to strive for a higher price — he would simply want to move as much product as he could. "Increasing volume and reduced concern about the selling price would add up to a perfect recipe for falling prices."
- The Saudis were also careful not to be too confrontational — their aim was to regain their quota level, capping the volume covered by netback deals. They were aiming their new policy as much at other cheating OPEC members as at non-OPEC countries.
- As word circulated about the Saudi netback deals in late September/early October 1985, nervousness and anxiety rose. Other exporters started to follow suit out of pure competitive self-defense. For the long-suffering downstream part of the industry, netback deals were "a godsend, an opportunity at last to make money in refining, which had seemed almost beyond human ingenuity since the early 1970s."
- Most exporters expected no more than a drop to $18-$20/barrel, below which they thought North Sea production would not be economical. They were wrong — the tax rates in the North Sea were so high that in one field called Ninian, a drop from $20 to $10 would cost the companies only 85 cents; the British Treasury was taking most of the rents. Actual operating costs in Ninian were only $6/barrel. George Keller: "There is not much of a price floor."

### OPEC Declares War for Market Share — November/December 1985

- From the beginning of November 1985, the WTI futures price continued to climb, reaching its then-highest point ever — $31.75 on November 20, 1985 — belying the threat of a price collapse. Many thought the Saudis did not really mean what they were saying; it was merely an elaborate warning.
- A week and a half later, OPEC met. By its actions, Saudi Arabia had already declared a war for market share against the other OPEC countries. Now OPEC as a group announced its intention to battle non-OPEC to regain lost markets. The new formula: OPEC was no longer protecting price; its objective was to "secure and defend for OPEC a fair share in the world oil market consistent with the necessary income for member countries' development."
- When the communique was carried into a room of senior OPEC country planners, one said dismissively: "Oh, it's just another OPEC winter communique." Then the price began to collapse.

### The Third Oil Shock — Prices Plunge 70%

- WTI plummeted by 70% over the next few months — from its peak of $31.75 in late November 1985 to $10. Some Persian Gulf cargoes sold for around $6/barrel. The actual variation in OPEC output was marginal — 17.8 million bpd in early 1986 (only 9% above 1985, about the same level as the 1983 quota), and the additional production meant not much more than a 3% increase in total free world supply. But that, combined with the commitment to market share, was enough to drive prices to levels virtually unimaginable months earlier.
- It was the Third Oil Shock, but with all consequences running in the opposite direction. Now exporters were scrambling for markets rather than buyers for supplies. And buyers rather than sellers were playing leapfrog, each jumping over the other in pursuit of the lowest price. Security now had new dimensions: "security of demand" for the exporters — guaranteed access to markets. For consumers, it seemed all the concerns of the 1970s about security of supply were being made irrelevant. But would cheap imported oil undermine the energy security so laboriously rebuilt over the preceding thirteen years?
- Prices were also out of control. For the first time in memory, there was no price-setting structure at all — no official OPEC price, no standard. The market was victorious, at least for the time being. Price was set through thousands of individual transactions — net-back deals, spot deals, "spotback deals," barter deals, processing deals, "topping off" deals. OPEC countries were battling each other over customers. "Everybody gets tired of endless negotiations for each cargo or each quarter," said the head of the Iraq State Marketing Commission. "In the end, the lazy negotiator for the crude exporter simply gives across-the-board discounts... he undercuts all other OPEC barrels." It was not netbacks or any specific deal that caused the price collapse, but the fundamental fact that more oil was seeking markets than there were markets for oil, and the hand of the regulator (OPEC and Saudi Arabia) was removed.

### OPEC Division and the Non-OPEC "Dialogue"

- OPEC was bitterly divided. Iran, Algeria, and Libya wanted a new and much lower quota to restore price to $29/barrel. Saudi Arabia and Kuwait remained committed to regaining market share. Yamani told one of the major companies: "I never sold a barrel someone didn't want." Iran and Iraq were still locked in a death struggle, and Iran's hostility to the Arab exporters was unmitigated.
- Non-OPEC countries were suffering no less. Belatedly, they started a "dialogue" — Mexico, Egypt, Oman, Malaysia, and Angola attended an OPEC meeting as observers in spring 1986. Norway's conservative government had initially declared it would not negotiate with OPEC, but oil supplied 20% of government revenues and the budget couldn't be met. The ruling party fell and was replaced by its labor opposition, whose new prime minister immediately announced Norway would take steps to help stabilize the oil price. The new oil minister boarded Zaki Yamani's yacht in Venice for a cruise and a discussion of oil prices. Yet the dialogue between OPEC and non-OPEC yielded little of substance.

### "A Little Action" — Oil Companies Unprepared

- Many oil companies were unprepared for the crisis, having been convinced that OPEC would not do something so silly as to eradicate a large part of their own revenues. But planners at Shell in London, reading the fundamentals carefully, had geared up an "OCS" — an Oil Collapse Scenario. Shell insisted senior managers take it seriously, discuss their responses, and start taking prophylactic action. When the collapse struck, there was "an eerie calm and orderliness at Shell Centre on the south bank of the Thames. Managers there, as well as in the field, went about their jobs as though carrying out a civil defense emergency operation for which they had already practiced."
- In general, the industry responded with quick and massive cuts in expenditures. Particularly hard hit was exploration and production in the US — one of the highest-cost and most disappointing oil provinces. Companies had the most flexibility to respond in the US, where they didn't have to worry about jeopardizing long-negotiated arrangements with national governments.
- Consumers were jubilant. The fears of permanent shortage were laid to rest. "Gas wars" at filling stations were back, writ large as a global oil war. The irreducible minimum was established at Billy Jack Mason's Exxon station on the north side of Austin, Texas — a one-day promotion in early April 1986, sponsored by a local country music station: unleaded for zero cents a gallon. By nine o'clock, the line of cars stretched for six miles. Billy Jack's view on the future of prices: "That's overseas. Nothing we can do about that until the Arabs get the prices right."

### George Bush — From Oil Patch to Vice-Presidency

- George Bush, Vice-President and an adopted Texan, was preparing to leave on an overseas mission to the Middle East. As he later said: "They got a President of the United States that came out of the oil and gas industry, that knows it and knows it well." He knew the risk-taking, deal-making world of the independent oil men — "the backbone of exploration in the United States and who were the ones knocked flat on their backs by the price collapse."
- On graduating from Yale in 1948, Bush passed up Wall Street jobs (his father Prescott had been a partner at Brown Brothers, Harriman, before becoming Senator from Connecticut). He packed up his red 1947 Studebaker and set off for Texas — first Odessa, then Midland, "the oil capital of West Texas." He started as a trainee painting pumping equipment, then graduated to itinerant salesman, driving from rig to rig selling drill bits.
- Bush was part of what Fortune magazine called "the swarm of young Ivy Leaguers" who descended on Midland — creating "a most unlikely outpost of the working rich" and "a union between the cactus and the Ivy." He formed an independent oil company called Zapata (named after the film Viva Zapata!, with Marlon Brando, then playing in Midland). He mastered the skills of the independent oil man — combing courthouse records for mineral rights, arranging drilling rig crews, making the pilgrimage back East to round up investor money. He even closed a deal with Eugene Meyer, publisher of the Washington Post, in the back seat of Meyer's limousine near Union Station.
- The partners amicably split Zapata in two; Bush took the offshore oil services side, becoming one of the pioneers of offshore drilling and production in the Gulf of Mexico and around the world. He also served as part-time investor relations officer. By the mid-1960s, he had made sufficient money and turned to politics — Congressman from Houston, chairman of the Republican National Committee during Watergate, US envoy to China, head of the CIA, and then four years of unsuccessfully campaigning for the Republican nomination before Reagan chose him as running mate in 1980.
- Reagan's approach to energy was to make it a footnote — the crisis resulted from "regulation and the misguided policies of the United States government." He sped up Carter's decontrol. Rising oil prices, "Jimmy Carter's misfortune," had been transmuted into "Ronald Reagan's good fortune" — the inflation-adjusted price of oil actually started its long slide just around the time Reagan moved into the White House. The "free market" approach rested on a contradiction: a cartel (OPEC) was preventing a big fall in the price, thus providing the incentives for conservation and energy development in the US. But this contradiction remained latent until the price collapse of 1986.
- What was unleashed was "absolute competition," devastating to the American oil industry. Pink slips flew at an awesome rate; drilling rigs stacked up; the financial infrastructure of the Southwest was headed into an economic depression. If prices stayed down, US oil demand would shoot up, domestic production would plummet, and imports would flood in again. There were calls for an oil import tariff, but none came from the Reagan Administration. Another option: jawbone OPEC into getting its act together. Thus did George Bush's long official inattention to oil abruptly come to an end.

### "I Know I'm Correct" — Bush's Saudi Arabia Trip

- In early April 1986, Bush said he would "be selling very hard" to persuade the Saudis "of our own domestic interest and thus the interest of national security... I think it is essential that we talk about stability and that we not just have a continued free fall like a parachutist jumping out without a parachute." He ritualistically acknowledged the free market precept: "Our answer is market, market — let the market forces work." But then added: "I happen to believe, and always have, that a strong domestic U.S. industry is in the national security interests, vital interests of this country." Bush was clearly saying that market forces had gone too far. He was quickly and embarrassingly disavowed by the Reagan White House: "The way to address price stability is to let the free market work."
- Bush's first stop was Riyadh, where at a dinner with several ministers including Yamani, he commented that if prices remained too low, pressure for a tariff would build in Congress and it would be increasingly difficult to resist. The Saudis took his remark very seriously. In Dhahran, at a late-night session with King Fahd (lasting past 2:00 a.m.), the prime subject was Persian Gulf security and US weapons supplies — oil was mentioned only glancingly, but Fahd expressed his hope for "stability in the market." The King "felt Saudi Arabia was, in non-royal language, being given a bum rap."
- Bush stuck to his position despite domestic criticism. "I know I'm correct... Some things you're sure of. This I'm absolutely sure of — that low prices would cripple the domestic American energy industries, with serious consequences for the nation." At a breakfast with American businessmen in Dhahran: "There is some point at which the national security interest of the United States says, 'Hey, we must have a strong, viable domestic industry.'" A senior White House official disparagingly called it "not Administration policy." But Bush refused to retreat: "I don't know that I'm defending the [U.S. oil] industry. What I'm doing is defending a position that I feel very, very strongly... Whether that's a help politically or whether it proves a detriment politically I couldn't care less."
- The general view was that Bush was making an enormous political blunder. But the Washington Post editorial page said he was right: "A steadily increasing dependence on imported oil is, as the man suggests, not a happy prospect."
- The Saudis interpreted Bush's remarks as the VP saying that the price collapse was destabilizing and threatening US security — American petroleum imports would rise substantially, the US would be weakened militarily and strategically vis-a-vis the Soviet Union. The Bush mission, on top of the turmoil and other difficulties, provided reason for the Saudis to reconsider the fierce battle for market share. Moreover, the other exporters had finally learned that cheating had a cost.

### "Hara-Kiri" and $18 a Barrel — Finding the Right Price

- Alirio Parra, a senior official of Petroleos de Venezuela who had begun his career as an assistant to Juan Pablo Perez Alfonzo during the formation of OPEC, struggled to find historical context. He recalled a 1926 book, The United States Oil Policy, by John Ise: "The unfortunate features of the oil history of Pennsylvania have been repeated in the later history of almost every other producing region... the same instability, the same recurrent or chronic over-production, the same wide fluctuations in prices." Ise described the 1920s as a "spectacle of a vast overproduction of this limited natural resource, growing stocks, overflowing tanks, and declining prices." Oil producers were committing "hara-kiri" by producing so much oil. The remedy: "a reduction in the production." Though written sixty years earlier, the language and diagnosis sounded "all too familiar to Parra."
- Parra and others began working out a new pricing system that took into account the fact that oil and energy markets were competitive. They focused on $17-$19 a barrel — $11 less than the previous official price of $29. Correcting for inflation, $18 took oil prices back to where they had been in the mid-1970s, on the eve of the Second Oil Shock. It seemed to be the price at which oil was again competitive with other energy sources and with conservation — "the highest level that the exporters could attain and still achieve their goals of stimulating economic growth in the rest of the world and thus energy demand." An OPEC official: "Eighteen dollars is inconvenient for my country, but don't you think it's the best we can do?"
- In late May 1986, six oil ministers met in Taif. Yamani stated Saudi Arabia's position: "We want to see a correction in the trends in the market. Once we regain control of the market by increasing our share, we will be able to act accordingly. We want to regain our market power." The ministers confirmed their support for $17-$19 and agreed on the need for a new quota system. This "consensus" of $18 emerged "out of the wreckage of the old" through "a process of osmosis," said Parra.
- The Japanese, importing more than 99% of their oil, might have been expected to prefer the lowest possible price. But they did not — prices too low would undercut their large commitment to alternative energy sources, leading back to higher oil dependence and renewed vulnerability. Also, very low oil prices would swell Japan's already-huge trade surplus. Japan's industry and government believed in "reasonable prices" — which came out to about $18.
- The new US consensus: gains from falling oil prices (higher growth, lower inflation) would outweigh the losses (the Southwest, energy industries) — but only up to a point. The pain and dislocation at some level would cancel the benefits. That point fell somewhere between $15 and $18. The Reagan Administration was rooting for $18 — it would boost growth, restrain inflation, and be a price at which the domestic oil industry could scrape by.

### Revenue Pain and the End of the Market Share Strategy

- The market share strategy was, at least in the short term, a failure for OPEC. But who was hurt most? The Arab Gulf states (Saudi Arabia, Kuwait), which had greatly increased volumes, were least hurt: Kuwait's revenues down only 4%, Saudi Arabia's down 11%. The price hawks — Iran, Libya, Algeria (the most belligerent and hostile to the West) — were hit hardest: Iran's and Libya's oil earnings in H1 1986 were down 42% from 1985. Iran was the country most disadvantaged — its revenues were plummeting even as it was having to finance the war with Iraq, which had entered a more intense phase.
- The market share strategy was acknowledged as a failure. Yamani: "Not on your life. We all swing together or not at all. On this point, I am as stubborn as Mrs. Thatcher." Some exporters insisted Saudi Arabia resume its swing role; Yamani refused. In July 1986, Persian Gulf crudes were going for $7/barrel or less.
- By July, OPEC experts had worked out a detailed rationale: $17-$19 would lead to improved world economic outlook, stimulate oil demand, slow and arrest fuel substitution, and "will definitely discourage future developments of high cost oil." But if prices went any lower, exporters would face "strong protectionist measures in the major consuming countries, including the imposition of an oil imports tariff in both the U.S. and Japan."
- At the Geneva OPEC meeting (late July/early August 1986), Iran's oil minister Gholam Reza Aghazadeh appeared in Yamani's suite for a private discussion through an interpreter. His message so startled Yamani that he had the interpreter repeat it. Iran was willing to accept the temporary, voluntary quotas pushed by Yamani. Iran had backed down — its oil policy was more pragmatic than its foreign policy.
- The market share strategy was over. In announcing new quotas, OPEC insisted it would not carry the burden alone — non-OPEC would have to cooperate. Mexico would cut its output. Norway promised not to cut back but to reduce the growth of its output. The Soviet Union, which had stood aside (a senior Soviet energy official had derided the idea of cooperating with OPEC: "We are not a producer of bananas"), finally promised a 100,000-barrel-per-day cutback. The pledge was vague, but in the immediate turmoil, the symbolism was important.

### Playing It by Ear — Yamani at Harvard, Then Fired

- In September 1986, Harvard University was celebrating its 350th anniversary. From among the planet's five billion citizens, Harvard chose two people to give major speeches: Prince Charles, heir to the British throne, and Ahmed Zaki Yamani, the Saudi oil minister. A delegation from Harvard even flew to Geneva to personally extend the invitation.
- Prince Charles delivered a lively, entertaining speech. Yamani chose a very substantive, dense discourse filled with numbers to the second decimal place. He recalled his battles over price with the oil companies in the early 1970s and with his OPEC brethren in the late 1970s and early 1980s. He called for stability and recognition that oil was a "special commodity." He held out the hope of oil priced at $15/barrel with a gradual rise in both price and OPEC output. "It was a vision of a very orderly world. Did he really believe it?"
- When asked how oil policy was made inside Saudi Arabia, Yamani replied smoothly and without hesitation: "We play it by ear." The audience roared with laughter. Unbeknownst at the time, those words would be among the last of Yamani's official utterances.

### Yamani Fired

- A month later, in October, Yamani was in Geneva for the next stage of OPEC's reconstruction. The kingdom wanted not only to protect its quota and assure its volumes, but also to receive a higher price — the consensus $18, quite different from the $15 Yamani had talked about at Harvard. Yamani went so far as to suggest, semipublicly, that it was contradictory to try to pursue higher volume and higher price at the same time — which seemed to go explicitly against the policy King Fahd had enunciated.
- One evening, a week after the meeting, Yamani was back in Riyadh at dinner with friends when he received a phone call advising him to turn on the television news. An item at the end of the broadcast reported tersely that Ahmed Zaki Yamani had been "relieved" of his post as oil minister. That was the way he learned he had been fired. Yamani had been in the job twenty-four years — "a good, long run in any position anywhere. Still, it was an abrupt, embarrassing, and disconcerting end to a quarter-century career."
- The reasons for his firing were many and somewhat contradictory: he had embarrassed the Royal Family by failing to pursue their instructions vigorously and by criticizing them; he had made powerful enemies by opposing barter deals; his firing reflected the jettisoning of policies with which he had been associated; there was resentment of his arrogance, patronizing manner, high profile, and celebrity status outside the country. Yamani had been King Faisal's man, but Faisal had been dead for almost a dozen years; Fahd was King now and was the maker of oil policy. By 1986, Yamani had precious few allies, and many other ministers and advisers believed he had usurped their own authority. "And, when it came down to it, some said, King Fahd just plain didn't like Yamani."
- Perhaps in the long run it was the decline and then the precipitous collapse in the price of oil that led to Yamani's own downfall. There was also the specific matter of the Harvard speech — some in Riyadh had expected merely a few general words, not a seventeen-page speech that was not everyone's idea of an impromptu talk. Moreover, the policy it espoused was not exactly identical with the official policy of Saudi Arabia. And the "play it by ear" remark was interpreted in Riyadh as a tart criticism of the Saudi government. So Yamani was returned to private life — to manage his fortune, try to acquire a Swiss watchmaker, preside over his perfume factory in Taif, teach part-time at the Harvard Law School, and comment from time to time on world oil.

### Price Restored — The December 1986 Geneva Meeting

- The OPEC countries finally brought the "good sweating" to an end at a meeting in Geneva in December 1986. It was the first major OPEC meeting for the new Saudi oil minister, Hisham Nazir — among the initial generation of Saudi technocrats, just two years younger than Yamani, educated at UCLA, had been a deputy to Abdullah Tariki, then served many years as Minister of Planning. He was particularly alert to the links between oil and the national economy and to the overall revenue question. He carried no responsibility for the repudiated market share strategy.
- The exporters agreed to a "reference price" of $18/barrel, based on a composite of several different crudes. They also agreed to a quota that would support the price. No agreement was possible between Iran and Iraq on Iraq's quota — so the quota only applied to twelve countries; Iraq was outside it, free to do what it could. A "notional" quota of 1.5 million bpd was assigned to Iraq, bringing the total to 17.3 million bpd.
- To the surprise of many, the framework of agreement managed, with considerable reconstruction, to hold up through 1987, 1988, and 1989 — though with recurrent and sometimes intense pressure. The OPEC price was not exactly $18, but rather $15-$18. Prices were volatile, and at times the quota system seemed about to fall apart. But the producers, faced with the alternative, rallied. "After all, the OPEC countries themselves had felt the full brunt of the 'good sweating,' and they had had enough of it."
- The new oil prices completely wiped out the increases of the Second Oil Shock of 1979-81. The economic benefits to consumers were enormous. If the two oil price shocks of the 1970s constituted the "OPEC tax" — an immense transfer of wealth from consumers to producers — then the price collapse was the "OPEC tax cut," a transfer of $50 billion in 1986 alone back to the consuming countries. This tax cut stimulated and prolonged the economic growth that had begun four years earlier, while driving down inflation. In economic terms, the long crisis was certainly over.

### Iran Versus Iraq: The Tide Turns — The Tanker War and Cease-Fire

- Politically and strategically, the threat remained — the Iran-Iraq War, in its seventh year in 1987, broke through the barriers that had restricted it to the two belligerents and became internationalized for the first time, drawing in the other Arab Gulf states and the two superpowers. Iran had captured the Fao Peninsula, the southernmost extreme of Iraq bordering Kuwait — a potential gateway to the conquest of Basra. But the Iranians bogged down in marshy sands. Thereafter, the war turned against them. Iraqi successes in the air and its "tanker war" on Iranian shipping led to stepped-up Iranian attacks on third-country tankers. Iran zeroed in on Kuwait (which was assisting Iraq), launching at least five missile attacks directly on Kuwait itself.
- Kuwait asked the US to protect its shipping. Washington was jolted to learn that the Kuwaitis had also asked the Russians for protection. The potential significance of a Soviet approach caused the Kuwaiti request to "not linger" at the most senior levels of the Reagan Administration. To exclude the Russians, the US took on the whole job of reflagging — eleven Kuwaiti tankers were reflagged with the Stars and Stripes. US naval vessels were patrolling the Gulf. British and French naval units, along with ships from Italy, Belgium, and the Netherlands, also entered the Gulf. The Japanese, forbidden by their constitution from sending ships, chipped in by increasing the funds they provided to offset the cost of maintaining American forces in Japan and by investing in a precision locator system in the Strait of Hormuz.
- By spring 1988, Iraq was manifestly winning, making use of chemical weapons. Iran's ability and will to fight were fading. Its economy was in shambles. War weariness gripped the country; in one month, 140 Iraqi missiles fell on Tehran alone. Volunteers were no longer forthcoming.
- Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani — speaker of Parliament, deputy commander of the Army, nicknamed "Kuseh" (the Shark) — concluded it was time to seek an end to the war. He was a member of a wealthy pistachio-growing family, a Khomeini student and disciple since 1962. Iran was diplomatically and politically isolated, while Iraq was growing stronger.
- The American naval presence led to a major tragic confrontation: in early July 1988, the USS Vincennes, engaged in an exchange with Iranian warships, mistook an Iranian Airbus carrying 290 passengers for a hostile aircraft and shot it down. To the Iranian leadership, this was a sign that the US was preparing to bring its great power to bear in direct military confrontation with Iran. Iran could no longer afford to go against the United States.
- On July 17, 1988, Iran informed the United Nations of its willingness to countenance a cease-fire. "Taking this decision was more deadly than taking poison," Khomeini declared. "I submitted myself to God's will and drank this drink for his satisfaction." But vengeance was still his ambition: "God willing, we will empty our hearts' anguish at the appropriate time by taking revenge on the Al Saud and America." The Ayatollah would not live to see such a day; within a year, he would be dead.
- The cease-fire took effect August 20, 1988. Iraq immediately began symbolic oil shipments from its Gulf ports. Iran announced its intention to rebuild the great refinery at Abadan. One month short of eight years, the war ended in a stalemate favoring Iraq. As far as Baghdad was concerned, it had won the war and was now "the dominant political power in the Gulf, and one of the world's major oil powers." But the significance of the end of the war was much more far-reaching — it appeared that the threat to the free flow of Middle Eastern oil had been removed; the era of continuing crisis that had begun with the October War fifteen years earlier along the banks of the Suez Canal "finally seemed to be at an end."

### Reintegration and a New Era

- The end of the war pointed to a new era. The great contentious question of sovereignty had been resolved — the exporters owned the oil. But what came to matter over the 1980s was sure access to markets. The producing countries discovered that consumers had more flexibility and wider choices than had been imagined. "Security of demand" was no less important to them than "security of supply" was to consumers. Most exporters now wanted to establish themselves as reliable suppliers and that oil was a secure fuel. With socialism in bad repute and the North-South confrontation a fading memory, exporters could act more on economic than political concerns. Some were reopening the doors to exploration by private companies — doors that had been slammed shut in the 1970s.
- Others went further, following the logic of integration — state-owned companies of the exporters went downstream to acquire outlets. Petroleos de Venezuela built up a large refining and marketing system in the US and Western Europe. Kuwait turned itself into an integrated oil company, with refineries in Western Europe and thousands of gasoline stations operating under the brand name "Q-8." Kuwait did not stop there: in 1987, Margaret Thatcher reversed Winston Churchill's historic 1914 decision and sold off the government's 51% stake in British Petroleum. Kuwait thereupon snapped up 22% of BP — the very company that, along with Gulf, had developed and owned Kuwait's oil until 1975. The British government was infuriated and forced Kuwait to reduce its holdings to 10%.
- Saudi Arabia and Texaco (one of the original Aramco partners) announced a new joint venture — Saudi Arabia acquired a half interest in Texaco's refineries and gasoline stations in 33 states in the eastern and southern US. The transaction guaranteed the Saudis, if they wanted it, 600,000 barrels per day of sales in the US, compared to the trickle of 26,000 bpd they had fallen to in 1985. Such "reintegration" represented one effort to put greater long-term stability back into the industry and to manage the risks faced by producers and consumers.

### The Epilogue — Lessons Learned, Lessons Forgotten

- A few months after the cease-fire, George Bush, the former oil man, succeeded Ronald Reagan as President. With the astonishing disintegration of the barriers dividing the Soviet bloc from the Western democracies, unprecedented prospects for global peace appeared at hand. Oil would certainly remain a vital commodity in the economies of both industrialized and developing nations — and as a bargaining chip among producers and consumers, it would remain of paramount importance in the politics of world power.
- Yet out of the tumult of the 1970s and 1980s, important lessons had emerged. Consumers had learned that they could not regard oil, the fundament of their lives, so easily as a given. Producers had learned that they could not take their markets and customers for granted. The result was "a priority of economics over politics, an emphasis on cooperation over confrontation, or at least so it appeared." But would those critical lessons be recalled?
- At a discussion in New York City in the late spring of 1989, the oil minister from one of the major exporting countries spoke at length about the new realism of producers and consumers and the lessons learned by both. Afterwards, he was asked how long such lessons would be remembered. The question took him by surprise. He thought for a moment. "About three years, without reminding," he said. Within a year of that exchange, he himself was no longer minister. And a month later, his country was invaded.

